riety of materials, including polymers, liposomes and mesoporous materials. They are an important tool in modern science and technology, with numerous applications in various industries.','{\"pat_doc\": 16.0, \"pub_alt\": 14.0, \"pub_doc\": 42.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -135275.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0243e571f081656a8677694a7199ea7a','e73131830356703a23b1a11a711e48c5','e4f81d8ac891f1e1dbdd2332eaaa8fed','2023-09-05 22:16:53','2023-10-29 03:21:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Magnetic nanoparticles',24,'Magnetic nanoparticles are a class of nanoparticle that can be manipulated using magnetic fields. Such particles commonly consist of two components, a magnetic material, often iron, nickel and cobalt, and a chemical component that has functionality. While nanoparticles are smaller than 1 micrometer in diameter, the larger microbeads are 0.5â€“500 micrometer in diameter. Magnetic nanoparticle clusters that are composed of a number of individual magnetic nanoparticles are known as magnetic nanobeads with a diameter of 50â€“200 nanometers. Magnetic nanoparticle clusters are a basis for their further magnetic assembly into magnetic nanochains.','{\"pat_doc\": 1135.0, \"pub_alt\": 521.0, \"pub_doc\": 4699.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 137.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 35463096.0, \"pat_granted\": 349.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -8.6, \"pub_doc\": -35.6, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -2481846.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('026eeed653300cd0e5763a3c9ea04b67','ffe250fc447887b501aee1b30580085f','c15525a97e5927c0f087d514b050aed9','2023-09-08 09:37:37','2023-10-28 20:56:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Distillation',12,'Distillation is a process used to separate liquids with different boiling points. It involves heating a mixture of liquids to vaporize the components with lower boiling points, collecting the vapor, and then condensing it back into a liquid form. The process is widely used in industries such as petroleum refining, where crude oil is distilled to produce various fuels and other products. In addition, distillation is a common method used to purify water, create alcoholic beverages, and extract essential oils from plant materials. The efficiency of distillation depends on the difference in boiling points between the components being separated, with greater differences resulting in more effective separation.','{\"pat_doc\": 9790.0, \"pub_alt\": 493.0, \"pub_doc\": 7954.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 64.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 45017324.0, \"pat_granted\": 4459.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 349.4, \"pub_doc\": 1168.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.6, \"grant_fund\": -3503023.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('02b04f5ddc25f1df415585c30d28c3c2','3c2d35cb47d7e664ff6a420c7371c3f4','13d8c275545d800af0151763656e07e5','2023-09-05 19:14:04','2023-10-29 05:11:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Quantum dot',12,'Quantum dots â€“ also called semiconductor nanocrystals, are semiconductor particles a few nanometres in size, having optical and electronic properties that differ from those of larger particles as a result of quantum mechanics. They are a central topic in nanotechnology and materials science. When the quantum dots are illuminated by UV light, an electron in the quantum dot can be excited to a state of higher energy. In the case of a semiconducting quantum dot, this process corresponds to the transition of an electron from the valence band to the conductance band. The excited electron can drop back into the valence band releasing its energy as light. This light emission is illustrated in the figure on the right.','{\"pat_doc\": 5529.0, \"pub_alt\": 568.0, \"pub_doc\": 8451.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 131.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 103144701.0, \"pat_granted\": 2273.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 59.8, \"pub_doc\": 330.7, \"clinic_doc\": 1.1, \"grant_fund\": -9612731.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('02cd5a37d09eaff5e1c92ba6426fc3d1','b623d7ca57acae4c7c681109e883ff82','9b78c6ab99d1ce69ff59eddcd1444cfe','2023-09-04 18:43:50','2023-10-28 18:21:15','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Heart failure',24,'Heart failure, also known as congestive heart failure, is a syndrome, a group of signs and symptoms, caused by an impairment of the hearts blood pumping function. Symptoms typically include shortness of breath, excessive fatigue, and leg swelling. The shortness of breath may occur with exertion or while lying down, and may wake people up during the night. Chest pain, including angina, is not usually caused by heart failure, but may occur if the heart failure was caused by a heart attack. The severity of the heart failure is mainly decided based on ejection fraction and also measured by the severity of symptoms. Other conditions that may have symptoms similar to heart failure include obesity, kidney failure, liver disease, anemia, and thyroid disease. Common causes of heart failure include coronary artery disease, heart attack, high blood pressure, atrial fibrillation, valvular heart disease, excessive alcohol consumption, infection, and cardiomyopathy.','{\"pat_doc\": 2997.0, \"pub_alt\": 20133.0, \"pub_doc\": 46749.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1780.0, \"clinic_alt\": 886.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4207.0, \"grant_fund\": 780020823.0, \"pat_granted\": 819.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 60.6, \"pub_doc\": 1207.9, \"clinic_doc\": 749.7, \"grant_fund\": -131899850.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('02ea9d047a03b72bc16908b53c87c202','32fc867764b2c2323b6074823f18f91d','e11ca4e4a12f409964c63840550b841e','2023-09-08 02:44:51','2023-10-28 21:41:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Editing',36,'mRNA editing is the process by which the genetic information contained within the messenger RNA (mRNA) transcript is modified by the insertion, deletion, or substitution of nucleotides. This process is critical for the accurate transmission of genetic information from DNA to protein synthesis, as it allows for the generation of multiple mRNA isoforms from a single gene. The molecular machinery involved in mRNA editing is complex and involves specific enzymes such as adenosine deaminase acting on RNA (ADAR), which catalyzes the conversion of adenosine to inosine in the mRNA sequence. This process has been found to play a key role in regulating gene expression and is implicated in a number of disease states, including cancer and neurological disorders. By modulating mRNA editing, researchers hope to develop new strategies for the treatment of these conditions.','{\"pat_doc\": 15.0, \"pub_alt\": 274.0, \"pub_doc\": 146.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 8532062.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": -2.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -1088864.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('030133246933b900d1cd1cfdf4deca0f','5799fbde63662e16529cdc2465faa33f','eefb2660a8535eb1d304c9a60295324f','2023-09-08 14:51:25','2023-10-28 18:35:05','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Liposomes',12,'Liposomes are microscopic, spherical vesicles composed of a phospholipid bilayer that is able to encapsulate a variety of water-soluble substances. They are commonly used as drug delivery systems because the lipid bilayer gives them the ability to cross cell membranes and deliver their contents directly to the interior of cells. Liposomes can be prepared in a variety of sizes with different properties, which makes them a versatile tool in medical research and pharmaceuticals. Their biocompatibility and ability to encapsulate both hydrophilic and hydrophobic substances has caused them to become increasingly popular in the fields of drug delivery and cosmetics.','{\"pat_doc\": 778.0, \"pub_alt\": 501.0, \"pub_doc\": 3144.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 74.0, \"clinic_alt\": 108.0, \"clinic_doc\": 38.0, \"grant_fund\": 24093602.0, \"pat_granted\": 208.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 11.3, \"pub_doc\": 166.2, \"clinic_doc\": 8.1, \"grant_fund\": -13776868.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('035fcd98fdcb04f8e43a82dd4c2f951e','dbff1bacaaa4170742799b76b0d72aa1','e5dc1ab9b95fd144580ba449bdb1f286','2023-09-05 20:47:05','2023-10-29 04:21:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','CRISPR-Cas9',36,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 741.0, \"pub_alt\": 3609.0, \"pub_doc\": 5476.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 814.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 21.0, \"grant_fund\": 341525102.0, \"pat_granted\": 209.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.6, \"pub_doc\": 115.9, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -29971557.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0388672b9e8710b4d094b9fba86c9d8f','238b58270bac60d5acf4e26cc123d5f1','61eadfbcdffdebf7c01d9aa685edd597','2023-09-08 01:05:56','2023-10-28 11:35:31','Electronics','Components','Processing Devices','RISC-V',36,'RISC-V is an open standard instruction set architecture based on established reduced instruction set computer principles. Unlike most other ISA designs, RISC-V is provided under royalty-free open-source licenses. A number of companies are offering or have announced RISC-V hardware; open source operating systems with RISC-V support are available, and the instruction set is supported in several popular software toolchains. As a RISC architecture, the RISC-V ISA is a loadâ€“store architecture. Its floating-point instructions use IEEE 754 floating-point. Notable features of the RISC-V ISA include: instruction bit field locations chosen to simplify the use of multiplexers in a CPU, a design that is architecturally neutral, and a fixed location for the sign bit of immediate values to speed up sign extension. The instruction set is designed for a wide range of uses.','{\"pat_doc\": 485.0, \"pub_alt\": 247.0, \"pub_doc\": 1576.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 100.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 120126567.0, \"pat_granted\": 129.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 62.4, \"pub_doc\": 105.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 15384814.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('03bcfa823f40faa6614fd75f75e04c17','5421c4aba6fdcb923ad6893affebb649','ad96306f7a3e23d74408bb23ac8e0e9a','2023-09-08 09:55:35','2023-10-28 19:56:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Near-infrared imaging',24,'Near-infrared (NIR) imaging refers to a technique in which light in the near-infrared spectrum is used to create images of biological specimens. This technique is popular in the medical field, especially in cancer diagnosis and treatment. NIR light penetrates deeper into biological tissues than visible light and is absorbed by various molecules, including water, lipids, and proteins. By measuring the reflected or absorbed light, NIR imaging allows for the detection of abnormalities such as tumors. NIR imaging is non-invasive, fast, and does not require ionizing radiation, making it a safer alternative to other imaging techniques. It also has potential applications in areas such as agriculture, food, and environmental monitoring.','{\"pat_doc\": 70.0, \"pub_alt\": 876.0, \"pub_doc\": 260.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 24.0, \"grant_fund\": 1993714.0, \"pat_granted\": 25.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.8, \"pub_doc\": 0.6, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": -73702.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0437012162b8d2d4813aa0a1bfe71571','d86696ef8204e2fe630e53d5acb96743','0df45be154a854c136cea54f3239586e','2023-09-08 01:15:36','2023-10-28 15:31:15','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Hypoparathyroidism',36,'Hypoparathyroidism is decreased function of the parathyroid glands with underproduction of parathyroid hormone. This can lead to low levels of calcium in the blood, often causing cramping and twitching of muscles or tetany, and several other symptoms. It is a very rare disease. The condition can be inherited, but it is also encountered after thyroid or parathyroid gland surgery, and it can be caused by immune system-related damage as well as a number of rarer causes. The diagnosis is made with blood tests, and other investigations such as genetic testing depending on the results. The primary treatment of hypoparathyroidism is calcium and vitamin D supplementation. Calcium replacement or vitamin D can ameliorate the symptoms but can increase the risk of kidney stones and chronic kidney disease. Additionally, medications such as recombinant human parathyroid hormone or teriparatide may be given by injection to replace the missing hormone.','{\"pat_doc\": 102.0, \"pub_alt\": 362.0, \"pub_doc\": 1668.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 14.0, \"clinic_alt\": 60.0, \"clinic_doc\": 100.0, \"grant_fund\": 6599531.0, \"pat_granted\": 20.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.5, \"pub_doc\": 2.7, \"clinic_doc\": 13.5, \"grant_fund\": -516093.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('04710c03ab70e285372f0f1c217a5bff','b973f9a55a74403c41f6bfdbc9121654','b347f7200b8aff24464a347c263147e9','2023-09-04 19:13:14','2023-10-29 06:11:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Filtration',48,'Filtration is a physical separation process that separates solid matter and fluid from a mixture using a filter medium that has a complex structure through which only the fluid can pass. Solid particles that cannot pass through the filter medium are described as oversize and the fluid that passes through is called the filtrate. Oversize particles may form a filter cake on top of the filter and may also block the filter lattice, preventing the fluid phase from crossing the filter, known as blinding. The size of the largest particles that can successfully pass through a filter is called the effective pore size of that filter. The separation of solid and fluid is imperfect; solids will be contaminated with some fluid and filtrate will contain fine particles. Filtration occurs both in nature and in engineered systems; there are biological, geological, and industrial forms.','{\"pat_doc\": 241585.0, \"pub_alt\": 26339.0, \"pub_doc\": 156455.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5272.0, \"clinic_alt\": 592.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3744.0, \"grant_fund\": 1749219950.0, \"pat_granted\": 168484.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 315.7, \"pub_doc\": 2992.9, \"clinic_doc\": 373.4, \"grant_fund\": -100208796.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0527c5a5ab77696558f24b5080b7a975','224f79c7aefff29a3d4cd0f3806a209a','5439cfcadd881d98d0c7179fbcfec554','2023-09-08 02:01:45','2023-10-28 23:21:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Liquid Crystal Elastomers',36,'Liquid crystal elastomers (LCEs) are a class of materials that exhibit both the fluid-like properties of liquid crystals and the elasticity of an elastic solid. They are composed of polymeric chains that are cross-linked to form a three-dimensional network. The presence of liquid crystal domains allows these materials to exhibit several unusual properties, including reversible shape changes in response to external stimuli such as heat, light, or mechanical stress. This makes LCEs promising candidates for a range of applications, from soft robotics and actuators to biomedical devices and responsive materials.','{\"pat_doc\": 24.0, \"pub_alt\": 273.0, \"pub_doc\": 365.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 25.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 19525250.0, \"pat_granted\": 7.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 31.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2814310.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('052d1a3ab380642d8e821800148bc400','794ef6eb4705d90aa18415f5e5a2779f','7b7c2d14c4ce8d4f609c2918b205a47e','2023-09-08 09:38:47','2023-10-28 20:51:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Thermogravimetric Analysis',36,'Thermogravimetric analysis or thermal gravimetric analysis is a method of thermal analysis in which the mass of a sample is measured over time as the temperature changes. This measurement provides information about physical phenomena, such as phase transitions, absorption, adsorption and desorption; as well as chemical phenomena including chemisorptions, thermal decomposition, and solid-gas reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 502.0, \"pub_alt\": 423.0, \"pub_doc\": 16797.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 95.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 7827798.0, \"pat_granted\": 120.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 32.3, \"pub_doc\": 123.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -985255.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('056500f0e0bff15bb77df8a62b83fb08','7a50af118adfe006fb057aba1683daea','5ae657e8e871e94265b41c651880e213','2023-09-08 01:40:52','2023-10-29 00:01:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Coating technology',24,'Coating technology refers to the various processes used to apply a thin layer of material onto a surface to enhance or modify its properties. Coatings can be applied to a wide range of materials including metals, plastics, ceramics, and glass. Coatings can improve the surface properties of a material such as corrosion resistance, wear resistance, and thermal resistance. They can also be used to provide a decorative finish. Coating technology is extensively used in industries such as automotive, aerospace, construction, and electronics. There are several types of coating processes including thermal spraying, chemical vapor deposition, and electroplating. Advances in coating technology have enabled the development of high-performance coatings that can withstand extreme temperatures and harsh environments. Coating technology is an important field that helps to extend the life of materials and improve their performance.','{\"pat_doc\": 774.0, \"pub_alt\": 108.0, \"pub_doc\": 544.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 74.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 35221227.0, \"pat_granted\": 367.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.5, \"pub_doc\": 36.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.8, \"grant_fund\": 152974.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0569b75a04e9d2a76e223d86e2a1884b','b052bba7b488d052b6c520140b9a95f7','0f0001c9173ff0ef27a841bf7334c0a3','2023-09-07 23:32:11','2023-10-29 02:41:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Synthetic biology',24,'Synthetic biology is a multidisciplinary field of science that focuses on living systems and organisms, and it applies engineering principles to develop new biological parts, devices, and systems or to redesign existing systems found in nature. It is a branch of science that encompasses a broad range of methodologies from various disciplines, such as biotechnology, biomaterials, material science/engineering, genetic engineering, molecular biology, molecular engineering, systems biology, membrane science, biophysics, chemical and biological engineering, electrical and computer engineering, control engineering and evolutionary biology. It includes designing and constructing biological modules, biological systems, and biological machines or, re-design of existing biological systems for useful purposes. Additionally, it is the branch of science that focuses on the new abilities of engineering into existing organisms to redesign them for useful purposes.','{\"pat_doc\": 485.0, \"pub_alt\": 1082.0, \"pub_doc\": 3220.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 763.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 461611197.0, \"pat_granted\": 126.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 62.9, \"pub_doc\": 64.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -38172745.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0594d3f06b1f1d304ba3e14f060f33f3','ec9127faed503fab80aacc0c09e3bea4','1e154b56de35b3c06486dd7e904cade0','2023-09-05 22:15:33','2023-10-29 03:26:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Vaccines',24,'mRNA vaccines are a type of COVID-19 vaccine that provides immunity to the virus by introducing a small piece of messenger RNA (mRNA) into the body. This mRNA contains genetic instructions that direct cells to produce spike proteins, the same proteins that coat the surface of the coronavirus. Once the spike proteins are produced, the immune system recognizes them as foreign and develops antibodies to protect against future infections. mRNA vaccines are unique in that they do not contain weakened or dead virus particles, which makes them safer and easier to produce than traditional vaccines. They also have the potential to be rapidly developed and customized to address new variations of the virus. The two mRNA vaccines currently authorized for use in the United States are the Pfizer-BioNTech and Moderna vaccines.','{\"pat_doc\": 203.0, \"pub_alt\": 26339.0, \"pub_doc\": 2742.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 133.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1578.0, \"clinic_doc\": 81.0, \"grant_fund\": 83909479.0, \"pat_granted\": 16.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 39.4, \"pub_doc\": 427.8, \"clinic_doc\": 19.8, \"grant_fund\": 7035647.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('061f266a998fdd3b60088560937d329b','230eda4c55f24cadd07347f1a221f5ca','d9f345c5479253d7d74e62f81762d9a5','2023-09-05 21:57:22','2023-10-28 12:15:33','Electronics','Components','Storage Devices','Spintronics',48,'Spintronics, also known as spin electronics, is the study of the intrinsic spin of the electron and its associated magnetic moment, in addition to its fundamental electronic charge, in solid-state devices. The field of spintronics concerns spin-charge coupling in metallic systems; the analogous effects in insulators fall into the field of multiferroics. Spintronics fundamentally differs from traditional electronics in that, in addition to charge state, electron spins are used as a further degree of freedom, with implications in the efficiency of data storage and transfer. Spintronic systems are most often realised in dilute magnetic semiconductors and Heusler alloys and are of particular interest in the field of quantum computing and neuromorphic computing.','{\"pat_doc\": 189.0, \"pub_alt\": 491.0, \"pub_doc\": 6921.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 828.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 362810216.0, \"pat_granted\": 52.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.9, \"pub_doc\": 169.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5459749.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('06bd5a913086aa28a6dfdf3faa4c2c25','7894dc5316736cccc7857ade68b00def','5428f4cb6631add28ed91160f184e3d2','2023-09-04 18:49:56','2023-10-29 06:50:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Polymerase Chain Reaction',36,'The polymerase chain reaction is a method widely used to make millions to billions of copies of a specific DNA sample rapidly, allowing scientists amplify a very small sample of DNA sufficiently to enable detailed study. PCR was invented in 1983 by American biochemist Kary Mullis at Cetus Corporation; Mullis and biochemist Michael Smith, who had developed other essential ways of manipulating DNA, were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1993. PCR is fundamental to many of the procedures used in genetic testing and research, including analysis of ancient samples of DNA and identification of infectious agents. Using PCR, copies of very small amounts of DNA sequences are exponentially amplified in a series of cycles of temperature changes. PCR is now a common and often indispensable technique used in medical laboratory research for a broad variety of applications including biomedical research and criminal forensics. The majority of PCR methods rely on thermal cycling.','{\"pat_doc\": 3047.0, \"pub_alt\": 32701.0, \"pub_doc\": 56206.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 380.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1692.0, \"clinic_doc\": 944.0, \"grant_fund\": 60048740.0, \"pat_granted\": 1014.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 25.6, \"pub_doc\": -1022.4, \"clinic_doc\": 80.3, \"grant_fund\": -12358489.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('06f1d558e2414399f975ca270a56a4ab','2531f8a177fbfd014f79f1851c094d65','6dae4310435505307085d7f2c73a1787','2023-09-08 00:48:13','2023-10-28 11:40:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Bioelectronics',48,'Bioelectronics is a field of research in the convergence of biology and electronics.','{\"pat_doc\": 74.0, \"pub_alt\": 1022.0, \"pub_doc\": 1824.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 198.0, \"clinic_alt\": 8.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 124536409.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": 59.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": 7394410.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('06ff2472d9e1c00b250c2152a1e35d75','b3a328f05ef6249fe823d3c8f5701aaf','301cad2a0f77cdfc28e4f33b693d4618','2023-09-04 16:29:35','2023-10-29 07:16:15','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Magnetic Resonance Imaging',48,'Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) is a medical imaging technique that uses a strong magnetic field and radio waves to generate detailed images of the bodys internal structures. The process involves placing the patient in a machine that uses a powerful magnet to align the hydrogen atoms in their body. A short pulse of radio waves is then used to disrupt this alignment, causing the atoms to release energy that is detected by a scanner. The data collected is processed by a computer to produce detailed images of the target area. MRI is a non-invasive and highly precise diagnostic tool that can provide information about various conditions including tumors, infections, injuries, and abnormalities in organs and tissues. It is used in a wide range of medical applications, including neurology, cardiology, orthopedics, and oncology.','{\"pat_doc\": 10966.0, \"pub_alt\": 18424.0, \"pub_doc\": 103788.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3955.0, \"clinic_alt\": 824.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5536.0, \"grant_fund\": 2129054458.0, \"pat_granted\": 4281.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -32.4, \"pub_doc\": 760.2, \"clinic_doc\": 884.6, \"grant_fund\": -78449677.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('07e3195494991e6cac9191c7f72e1311','3ade3404fcd2fca0da04003e7692173a','556dd84c0895390f86a0e55de1ce00fb','2023-09-08 09:14:40','2023-10-28 21:16:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Fourier-transform infrared',24,'Fourier transform spectroscopy is a measurement technique whereby spectra are collected based on measurements of the coherence of a radiative source, using time-domain or space-domain measurements of the electromagnetic radiation or other type of radiation.','{\"pat_doc\": 33.0, \"pub_alt\": 2087.0, \"pub_doc\": 7722.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 27.0, \"clinic_alt\": 47.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 13244280.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.9, \"pub_doc\": 132.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": 254292.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0881b01a591f6ae2dbc745276650e276','9cb1fcb17b688427ac67a33166effbb2','5ed796512ab4425cf98a4d2c7cdf5653','2023-09-05 20:27:46','2023-10-28 18:01:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Hematopoietic Stem Cells',12,'Hematopoietic stem cells are the stem cells that give rise to other blood cells. This process is called haematopoiesis. In vertebrates, the very first definitive HSCs arise from the ventral endothelial wall of the embryonic aorta within the aorta-gonad-mesonephros region, through a process known as endothelial-to-hematopoietic transition. In adults, haematopoiesis occurs in the red bone marrow, in the core of most bones. The red bone marrow is derived from the layer of the embryo called the mesoderm. Haematopoiesis is the process by which all mature blood cells are produced. It must balance enormous production needs with the need to regulate the number of each blood cell type in the circulation. In vertebrates, the vast majority of hematopoiesis occurs in the bone marrow and is derived from a limited number of hematopoietic stem cells that are multipotent and capable of extensive self-renewal.','{\"pat_doc\": 386.0, \"pub_alt\": 1334.0, \"pub_doc\": 1248.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 108.0, \"clinic_alt\": 77.0, \"clinic_doc\": 189.0, \"grant_fund\": 63155977.0, \"pat_granted\": 97.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -13.9, \"pub_doc\": -37.5, \"clinic_doc\": 48.6, \"grant_fund\": -17355143.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('08b01592b5c891a32ec722b597cbb353','e1fcd3b18c69467f559b50097886167b','a2b94a39823e51d1e7bb659a1415d3c3','2023-09-08 00:31:20','2023-10-29 01:26:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Biocatalysis',36,'Biocatalysis refers to the use of living systems or their parts to speed up chemical reactions. In biocatalytic processes, natural catalysts, such as enzymes, perform chemical transformations on organic compounds. Both enzymes that have been more or less isolated and enzymes still residing inside living cells are employed for this task. Modern biotechnology, specifically directed evolution, has made the production of modified or non-natural enzymes possible. This has enabled the development of enzymes that can catalyze novel small molecule transformations that may be difficult or impossible using classical synthetic organic chemistry. Utilizing natural or modified enzymes to perform organic synthesis is termed chemoenzymatic synthesis; the reactions performed by the enzyme are classified as chemoenzymatic reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 467.0, \"pub_alt\": 743.0, \"pub_doc\": 2039.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 240.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 128600179.0, \"pat_granted\": 173.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 32.8, \"pub_doc\": 44.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 8603575.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('08ffb203e7616bd257de7ace3381afcc','d5e0c4320bf432eb18619675fba4a2d6','dc3eb969daa777d1268e99485984656d','2023-09-07 23:34:57','2023-10-28 17:16:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes',36,'Tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes are white blood cells that have left the bloodstream and migrated towards a tumor. They include T cells and B cells and are part of the larger category of â€˜tumor-infiltrating immune cells which consist of both mononuclear and polymorphonuclear immune cells, in variable proportions. Their abundance varies with tumor type and stage and in some cases relates to disease prognosis. TILs can often be found in the tumor stroma and within the tumor itself. Their functions can dynamically change throughout tumor progression and in response to anticancer therapy TILs are implicated in killing tumor cells. The presence of lymphocytes in tumors is often associated with better clinical outcomes.','{\"pat_doc\": 197.0, \"pub_alt\": 680.0, \"pub_doc\": 2860.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 83.0, \"clinic_alt\": 467.0, \"clinic_doc\": 93.0, \"grant_fund\": 29802587.0, \"pat_granted\": 19.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.9, \"pub_doc\": 39.6, \"clinic_doc\": 20.1, \"grant_fund\": -2417367.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('09511f9390bd05f967ef2bbfd2ecc157','c9c8d2e4c7e139d539bc510be3e5f7ac','e9be6c0a64d57a69a37703624e73b1fd','2023-09-08 01:22:43','2023-10-29 00:16:22','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','Cell Isolation',24,'Cell isolation is the process of separating individual living cells from a solid block of tissue or cell suspension. While some types of cell naturally exist in a separated form, other cell types that are found in solid tissue require specific techniques to separate them into individual cells. This may be performed by using enzymes to digest the proteins that binds these cells together within the extracellular matrix. After the matrix proteins have been digested, cells remain loosely bound together but can be gently separated mechanically. Following isolation, experiments can be performed on these single isolated cells including patch clamp electrophysiology, calcium fluorescence imaging, and immunocytochemistry.','{\"pat_doc\": 158.0, \"pub_alt\": 217.0, \"pub_doc\": 518.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 48.0, \"clinic_alt\": 5.0, \"clinic_doc\": 25.0, \"grant_fund\": 25150482.0, \"pat_granted\": 42.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -2.2, \"pub_doc\": 0.4, \"clinic_doc\": 4.9, \"grant_fund\": -1507208.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('09ce6048df2b74609a7a2e70e6bf6974','19f291b8d80548406a90803fc4e33614','a3e69530e54da2bd3284f3d40c81f2e9','2023-09-08 02:13:20','2023-10-28 22:56:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Microarray',36,'A protein microarray is a high-throughput method used to track the interactions and activities of proteins, and to determine their function, and determining function on a large scale. Its main advantage lies in the fact that large numbers of proteins can be tracked in parallel. The chip consists of a support surface such as a glass slide, nitrocellulose membrane, bead, or microtitre plate, to which an array of capture proteins is bound. Probe molecules, typically labeled with a fluorescent dye, are added to the array. Any reaction between the probe and the immobilised protein emits a fluorescent signal that is read by a laser scanner. Protein microarrays are rapid, automated, economical, and highly sensitive, consuming small quantities of samples and reagents. The concept and methodology of protein microarrays was first introduced and illustrated in antibody microarrays in 1983 in a scientific publication and a series of patents.','{\"pat_doc\": 27.0, \"pub_alt\": 2002.0, \"pub_doc\": 374.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 14.0, \"clinic_alt\": 15.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 10382146.0, \"pat_granted\": 10.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.4, \"pub_doc\": -10.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.6, \"grant_fund\": -222800.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0bb1502a0f4d065fb04abfb8dcac5e6d','3be40ed2b8c2e8e952c0d1e6215ce7bc','d884de485418948cbb2562e1d885751d','2023-09-08 02:06:23','2023-09-08 02:06:23','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Addison\'s Disease',12,'Addison\'s disease, also known as primary adrenal insufficiency, is a rare long-term endocrine disorder characterized by inadequate production of the steroid hormones cortisol and aldosterone by the two outer layers of the cells of the adrenal glands, causing adrenal insufficiency. Symptoms generally come on slowly and insidiously and may include abdominal pain and gastrointestinal abnormalities, weakness, and weight loss. Darkening of the skin in certain areas may also occur. Under certain circumstances, an adrenal crisis may occur with low blood pressure, vomiting, lower back pain, and loss of consciousness. Mood changes may also occur. Rapid onset of symptoms indicates acute adrenal failure, which is a clinical emergency. An adrenal crisis can be triggered by stress, such as from an injury, surgery, or infection. Addison\'s disease arises from problems with the adrenal gland such that not enough of the steroid hormone cortisol and possibly aldosterone are produced.','{\"pat_doc\": 11.0, \"pub_alt\": 1437.0, \"pub_doc\": 65.0, \"deals_num\": 1.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 3.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": 1.5, \"clinic_doc\": 2.8, \"grant_fund\": -203023.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.806}'),('0bd65ea1e87440623ba4f666810e8c89','ecb5eb0e681dab97bb1d5c09a929aa00','ad11810122ec68f63273a505f81c6d11','2023-09-08 00:01:07','2023-10-28 16:46:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Adeno-associated virus',36,'Adeno-associated viruses are small viruses that infect humans and some other primate species. They belong to the genus Dependoparvovirus, which in turn belongs to the family Parvoviridae. They are small replication-defective, nonenveloped viruses and have linear single-stranded DNA genome of approximately 4.8 kilobases. Several features make AAV an attractive candidate for creating viral vectors for gene therapy, and for the creation of isogenic human disease models. Gene therapy vectors using AAV can infect both dividing and quiescent cells and persist in an extrachromosomal state without integrating into the genome of the host cell. In the native virus, however, integration of virally carried genes into the host genome does occur. Integration can be important for certain applications, but can also have unwanted consequences. Recent human clinical trials using AAV for gene therapy in the retina have shown promise.','{\"pat_doc\": 4561.0, \"pub_alt\": 2540.0, \"pub_doc\": 3907.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 384.0, \"clinic_alt\": 500.0, \"clinic_doc\": 110.0, \"grant_fund\": 217147258.0, \"pat_granted\": 659.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 245.2, \"pub_doc\": 179.9, \"clinic_doc\": 23.4, \"grant_fund\": -12947659.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0c03db04a3b54c41564ba12d1b39aca6','9bb760bba4bbf8524e3eb2a7e4d37392','5bad126b4b19ef48ed380a8bafb56304','2023-09-08 09:50:54','2023-10-28 20:16:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Capillary Electrophoresis',12,'Capillary electrophoresis is a family of electrokinetic separation methods performed in submillimeter diameter capillaries and in micro- and nanofluidic channels. Very often, CE refers to capillary zone electrophoresis, but other electrophoretic techniques including capillary gel electrophoresis, capillary isoelectric focusing, capillary isotachophoresis and micellar electrokinetic chromatography belong also to this class of methods. In CE methods, analytes migrate through electrolyte solutions under the influence of an electric field. Analytes can be separated according to ionic mobility and/or partitioning into an alternate phase via non-covalent interactions. Additionally, analytes may be concentrated or \"focused\" by means of gradients in conductivity and pH.','{\"pat_doc\": 282.0, \"pub_alt\": 101.0, \"pub_doc\": 814.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 10.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 13.0, \"grant_fund\": 3583000.0, \"pat_granted\": 123.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.4, \"pub_doc\": -61.5, \"clinic_doc\": 3.8, \"grant_fund\": -1132051.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0c51a7ad01500526c76b20fc343d1cc1','5c2546ad4bcf61666dc6e1c3462112a1','63620f5d0220fdda22b46d43a342534f','2023-09-08 01:14:21','2023-10-29 00:26:20','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Phage Display',48,'Phage display is a laboratory technique for the study of proteinâ€“protein, proteinâ€“peptide, and proteinâ€“DNA interactions that uses bacteriophages to connect proteins with the genetic information that encodes them. In this technique, a gene encoding a protein of interest is inserted into a phage coat protein gene, causing the phage to \"display\" the protein on its outside while containing the gene for the protein on its inside, resulting in a connection between genotype and phenotype. These displaying phages can then be screened against other proteins, peptides or DNA sequences, in order to detect interaction between the displayed protein and those other molecules. In this way, large libraries of proteins can be screened and amplified in a process called in vitro selection, which is analogous to natural selection. The most common bacteriophages used in phage display are M13 and fd filamentous phage, though T4, T7, and Î» phage have also been used.','{\"pat_doc\": 701.0, \"pub_alt\": 1051.0, \"pub_doc\": 1844.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 247.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 108362547.0, \"pat_granted\": 253.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 23.5, \"pub_doc\": 24.6, \"clinic_doc\": -0.3, \"grant_fund\": -13328661.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0ca057c5edd469788fc98382f62b20f0','3be40ed2b8c2e8e952c0d1e6215ce7bc','d884de485418948cbb2562e1d885751d','2023-09-08 02:06:23','2023-09-08 02:06:23','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Addison\'s Disease',24,'Addison\'s disease, also known as primary adrenal insufficiency, is a rare long-term endocrine disorder characterized by inadequate production of the steroid hormones cortisol and aldosterone by the two outer layers of the cells of the adrenal glands, causing adrenal insufficiency. Symptoms generally come on slowly and insidiously and may include abdominal pain and gastrointestinal abnormalities, weakness, and weight loss. Darkening of the skin in certain areas may also occur. Under certain circumstances, an adrenal crisis may occur with low blood pressure, vomiting, lower back pain, and loss of consciousness. Mood changes may also occur. Rapid onset of symptoms indicates acute adrenal failure, which is a clinical emergency. An adrenal crisis can be triggered by stress, such as from an injury, surgery, or infection. Addison\'s disease arises from problems with the adrenal gland such that not enough of the steroid hormone cortisol and possibly aldosterone are produced.','{\"pat_doc\": 21.0, \"pub_alt\": 1437.0, \"pub_doc\": 131.0, \"deals_num\": 1.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 11.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 3.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": 1.5, \"clinic_doc\": 2.8, \"grant_fund\": -203023.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.806}'),('0ca50ab8ee5913ac924b9c0d6c2f155e','62d3bf1b81cd240eca1b17ec53a45aed','9d56006f7b0bfb85db66d228f98a19d9','2023-09-08 00:57:05','2023-10-29 00:51:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Polymeric nanoparticles',12,'Polymeric nanoparticles are microscopic particles made up of polymers that have numerous applications, especially in the field of drug delivery and biomedical engineering. These particles, ranging from 1 to 1000 nanometers in size, can be designed in such a way that it can encapsulate drugs or other therapeutic agents and deliver them to the targeted site in a controlled manner. With characteristics such as their small size, large surface area, and the ability to protect the encapsulated content from degradation, they provide an excellent alternative to traditional drug delivery techniques. Polymeric nanoparticles have potential applications in cancer treatment, gene therapy, and imaging, among others. They have the potential to revolutionize the way we treat diseases and offer the possibility of more effective, less invasive therapeutic options.','{\"pat_doc\": 104.0, \"pub_alt\": 230.0, \"pub_doc\": 738.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 20.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 2432274.0, \"pat_granted\": 22.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.6, \"pub_doc\": 37.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.2, \"grant_fund\": -3328898.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0cb19f51887c69f6c2a98792f3c49c5e','633e3e1c04bc9ee16dfcb222f957cce1','5ee4ac63831f6ebbfc5f216379d36d38','2023-09-08 08:27:45','2023-10-28 10:30:31','Electronics','Components','Other','Co-Packaged Optics',12,'Co-packaged optics is a term that refers to the integration of optical components within the silicon chip package, enabling high-speed computing to be achieved. This technology is expected to revolutionize the data center industry by enhancing speed and reducing power consumption. By eliminating fiber cabling and replacing it with on-board optical interconnects, co-packaged optics enables faster data transfer rates, better communication between processors, reduced data center infrastructure, and other significant benefits. An important aspect of this technology is that it leverages existing CMOS fabrication processes, ensuring compatibility with current manufacturing techniques. This new optical integration technology is set to push the capabilities of electronic data processing further than ever before, providing more efficient and faster data transfer speeds for data centers and beyond.','{\"pat_doc\": 24.0, \"pub_alt\": 2.0, \"pub_doc\": 48.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5998562.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.6, \"pub_doc\": 13.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2486201.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0cc9dbedf00fd62c742122918c99c206','3dd87ec4606ad304f7e661f044278af7','3fb1f33d12215e256dd98a72f66b746e','2023-09-08 01:32:52','2023-10-28 15:16:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Viral vector (gene) therapies','Oncolytic viruses',48,'An oncolytic virus is a virus that preferentially infects and kills cancer cells. As the infected cancer cells are destroyed by oncolysis, they release new infectious virus particles or virions to help destroy the remaining tumour. Oncolytic viruses are thought not only to cause direct destruction of the tumour cells, but also to stimulate host anti-tumour immune system responses. Oncolytic viruses also have the ability to affect the tumor micro-environment in multiple ways. The potential of viruses as anti-cancer agents was first realised in the early twentieth century, although coordinated research efforts did not begin until the 1960s. A number of viruses including adenovirus, reovirus, measles, herpes simplex, Newcastle disease virus, and vaccinia have been clinically tested as oncolytic agents. Most current oncolytic viruses are engineered for tumour selectivity, although there are naturally occurring examples such as reovirus and the senecavirus, resulting in clinical trials.','{\"pat_doc\": 682.0, \"pub_alt\": 756.0, \"pub_doc\": 1266.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 123.0, \"clinic_alt\": 130.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 50686791.0, \"pat_granted\": 81.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 26.2, \"pub_doc\": 4.4, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": -7924828.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0ceedadbf6da895e8fe3e1e942f080af','b44ddb1f06c55c8a655b7e35627c4216','eb670a907e9a4e83aa692353515a741c','2023-09-05 19:20:24','2023-10-29 05:06:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Emulsion',12,'An emulsion is a mixture of two or more liquids that are normally immiscible owing to liquid-liquid phase separation. Emulsions are part of a more general class of two-phase systems of matter called colloids. Although the terms colloid and emulsion are sometimes used interchangeably, emulsion should be used when both phases, dispersed and continuous, are liquids. In an emulsion, one liquid is dispersed in the other. Examples of emulsions include vinaigrettes, homogenized milk, liquid biomolecular condensates, and some cutting fluids for metal working. Two liquids can form different types of emulsions. As an example, oil and water can form, first, an oil-in-water emulsion, in which the oil is the dispersed phase, and water is the continuous phase. Second, they can form a water-in-oil emulsion, in which water is the dispersed phase and oil is the continuous phase. Multiple emulsions are also possible, including a \"water-in-oil-in-water\" emulsion and an \"oil-in-water-in-oil\" emulsion.','{\"pat_doc\": 17739.0, \"pub_alt\": 2443.0, \"pub_doc\": 10318.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 141.0, \"clinic_alt\": 588.0, \"clinic_doc\": 122.0, \"grant_fund\": 40961515.0, \"pat_granted\": 7037.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_doc\": 587.2, \"clinic_doc\": 18.4, \"grant_fund\": -8503567.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0d4588b108bd2a16891a23aa9c93ae26','05aa0de4a4917d54e102e40d1b76c9e1','fd6371fdffdf19bf1bf3ac9102b5acf9','2023-09-08 01:59:23','2023-10-28 23:31:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Autoclaving',24,'An autoclave is a machine used to carry out industrial and scientific processes requiring elevated temperature and pressure in relation to ambient pressure and/or temperature. Autoclaves are used before surgical procedures to perform sterilization and in the chemical industry to cure coatings and vulcanize rubber and for hydrothermal synthesis. Industrial autoclaves are used in industrial applications, especially in the manufacturing of composites. Many autoclaves are used to sterilize equipment and supplies by subjecting them to pressurized saturated steam at 121 Â°C for around 30-60 minutes at a pressure of 15 psi depending on the size of the load and the contents. The autoclave was invented by Charles Chamberland in 1879, although a precursor known as the steam digester was created by Denis Papin in 1679. The name comes from Greek auto-, ultimately meaning self, and Latin clavis meaning key, thus a self-locking device.','{\"pat_doc\": 328.0, \"pub_alt\": 74.0, \"pub_doc\": 496.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 2603418.0, \"pat_granted\": 145.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -12.2, \"pub_doc\": -9.9, \"clinic_doc\": 1.2, \"grant_fund\": 113571.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0d4a56151a4acc817597ac3af0f68fad','dc9a89b7d5132f4c1c6c291f4d309152','acf051d7127b574167932dffa9cd1c71','2023-09-08 02:48:54','2023-10-28 21:31:14','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Laboratory Information Management System',24,'A laboratory information management system, sometimes referred to as a laboratory information system or laboratory management system, is a software-based solution with features that support a modern laboratorys operations. Key features includeâ€”but are not limited toâ€”workflow and data tracking support, flexible architecture, and data exchange interfaces, which fully \"support its use in regulated environments\". The features and uses of a LIMS have evolved over the years from simple sample tracking to an enterprise resource planning tool that manages multiple aspects of laboratory informatics. There is no useful definition of the term \"LIMS\" as it is used to encompass a number of different laboratory informatics components. The spread and depth of these components is highly dependent on the LIMS implementation itself. All LIMSs have a workflow component and some summary data management facilities but beyond that there are significant differences in functionality.','{\"pat_doc\": 30.0, \"pub_alt\": 27.0, \"pub_doc\": 112.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 1870806.0, \"pat_granted\": 7.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 8.9, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": -5084945.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0d4d4d1dc4a12a5ea9c9daefd8dba2f0','074a886190f8a82396d29ea68958db61','e9ee3da8c5950eddf30d7e6a8d175388','2023-09-08 00:39:05','2023-10-29 01:16:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Protein Engineering',24,'Protein engineering is the process of developing useful or valuable proteins through the design and production of unnatural polypeptides, often by altering amino acid sequences found in nature. It is a young discipline, with much research taking place into the understanding of protein folding and recognition for protein design principles. It has been used to improve the function of many enzymes for industrial catalysis. It is also a product and services market, with an estimated value of $168 billion by 2017. There are two general strategies for protein engineering: rational protein design and directed evolution. These methods are not mutually exclusive; researchers will often apply both. In the future, more detailed knowledge of protein structure and function, and advances in high-throughput screening, may greatly expand the abilities of protein engineering.','{\"pat_doc\": 312.0, \"pub_alt\": 1207.0, \"pub_doc\": 1386.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 243.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 128298618.0, \"pat_granted\": 99.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.1, \"pub_doc\": 48.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -16048598.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0d6dfdcac4f0f2391da9d8b949ea4959','a966912b70494ff7ec5379fbffffe2e6','a3d7925fcedbb9a92b698d370be59c62','2023-09-08 00:18:16','2023-10-28 11:50:31','Electronics','Needs','Customer or Market Needs','Sustainable materials',24,'Sustainable materials are those that have been sourced and manufactured in a way that minimizes environmental impact, promotes social responsibility, and provides economic benefits to communities. These materials are typically renewable, recyclable, or biodegradable, and they ensure the longevity of our natural resources. Sustainable materials can include plant-based options like bamboo, organic cotton, and linen, as well as recycled materials such as plastic bottles or reclaimed wood. Using sustainable materials in various industries is an important step toward a more sustainable future, as it reduces waste, conserves energy, and supports a circular economy. As consumers, we can make a difference by choosing products made from sustainable materials and encouraging companies to prioritize sustainability in their sourcing and manufacturing practices.','{\"pat_doc\": 51.0, \"pub_alt\": 1001.0, \"pub_doc\": 1542.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 237.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 198219387.0, \"pat_granted\": 10.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_doc\": 189.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 19728859.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0d828b355e224eb4d34fc629ab96ddf8','42ee32d5802de92090c858e3452a50cf','d7426f446b19a6b58ca2ef44eac3e4b3','2023-09-08 01:12:46','2023-10-29 00:31:27','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','3D Cell Culture',36,'A 3D cell culture is an artificially created environment in which biological cells are permitted to grow or interact with their surroundings in all three dimensions. Unlike 2D environments, a 3D cell culture allows cells in vitro to grow in all directions, similar to how they would in vivo. These three-dimensional cultures are usually grown in bioreactors, small capsules in which the cells can grow into spheroids, or 3D cell colonies. Approximately 300 spheroids are usually cultured per bioreactor. 3D cell cultures can also be performed on microfluidic devices such as the OrganoplateÂ® to generate perfusable 3D tissues, and hanging drop devices to generate 3D spheroids.','{\"pat_doc\": 185.0, \"pub_alt\": 255.0, \"pub_doc\": 1253.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 148.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 43363529.0, \"pat_granted\": 56.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 5.8, \"pub_doc\": 19.4, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -5741441.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0ea07b57abb32c68e1b212db24814f1c','8b12860860c34fa4f49e9fadc6bbab1d','d471ba9d05b4186943ade5d1a2ae30dc','2023-09-04 18:21:24','2023-10-29 07:10:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Mass Spectrometry',36,'Mass Spectrometry is a powerful analytical technique used in chemistry, biochemistry, and other scientific fields to identify molecules based on their mass-to-charge ratio (m/z). The process involves ionizing a sample, then separating the resulting ions based on their mass-to-charge ratio using electromagnetic fields. The ions are then detected and analyzed to determine their individual masses and concentrations. Mass spectrometry is used in many applications, including characterizing the structure of unknown compounds, identifying proteins and peptides, and tracking the movement of isotopes within molecules. It has become a standard tool in many areas of research, including drug discovery, environmental analysis, and forensic science.','{\"pat_doc\": 11672.0, \"pub_alt\": 13857.0, \"pub_doc\": 95329.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4607.0, \"clinic_alt\": 146.0, \"clinic_doc\": 658.0, \"grant_fund\": 1878444736.0, \"pat_granted\": 3738.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 210.2, \"pub_doc\": 879.4, \"clinic_doc\": 100.8, \"grant_fund\": -169513024.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0ec6057784cbf528b60e530b29a0bd63','42dcab631334ddefd1aa257b8b5f1e8f','eefb2660a8535eb1d304c9a60295324f','2023-09-05 21:18:18','2023-10-29 04:01:40','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Liposomes',24,'A liposome is a small artificial vesicle, spherical in shape, having at least one lipid bilayer. Due to their hydrophobicity and/or hydrophilicity, biocompatibility, particle size and many other properties, liposomes can be used as drug delivery vehicles for administration of pharmaceutical drugs and nutrients, such as lipid nanoparticles in mRNA vaccines, and DNA vaccines. Liposomes can be prepared by disrupting biological membranes. Liposomes are most often composed of phospholipids, especially phosphatidylcholine, and cholesterol, but may also include other lipids, such as those found in egg and phosphatidylethanolamine, as long as they are compatible with lipid bilayer structure. A liposome design may employ surface ligands for attaching to unhealthy tissue. The major types of liposomes are the multilamellar vesicle, the small unilamellar liposome vesicle, the large unilamellar vesicle, and the cochleate vesicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 1552.0, \"pub_alt\": 501.0, \"pub_doc\": 6313.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 217.0, \"clinic_alt\": 108.0, \"clinic_doc\": 46.0, \"grant_fund\": 53400768.0, \"pat_granted\": 410.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 12.3, \"pub_doc\": 172.3, \"clinic_doc\": 8.1, \"grant_fund\": -13776868.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0ecb89543571e0a76a0e8799dea7b457','5ca1037faccf16f0f31845755f697cb1','a9ac8b399c3d26dbcd46f8f3ee6f5ae2','2023-09-08 09:09:41','2023-10-28 13:21:11','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Gynecologic Cancers',36,'Gynecologic oncology is a specialized field of medicine that focuses on cancers of the female reproductive system, including ovarian cancer, uterine cancer, vaginal cancer, cervical cancer, and vulvar cancer. As specialists, they have extensive training in the diagnosis and treatment of these cancers. In the United States, 82,000 women are diagnosed with gynecologic cancer annually. In 2013, an estimated 91,730 were diagnosed. There is low quality evidence which demonstrates women with gynaecological cancer receiving treatment from specialized centres benefit from longer survival than those managed in standard care. A meta analysis of three studies combining over 9000 women, suggested that specialist gynaecological cancer treatment centres may prolong the lives of women with ovarian cancer compared with general or community hospitals.','{\"pat_doc\": 6.0, \"pub_alt\": 156.0, \"pub_doc\": 862.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 28.0, \"clinic_alt\": 339.0, \"clinic_doc\": 63.0, \"grant_fund\": 13376650.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.0, \"pub_doc\": 5.4, \"clinic_doc\": 12.6, \"grant_fund\": -1132384.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0ef0447f25f8147f98538632d4959166','75926dafeed6c4c3d2dd27794c573c76','88cbe0424257da986f5d8f34f678784d','2023-09-08 00:55:46','2023-10-29 00:56:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Microencapsulation',36,'Microencapsulation is a process in which tiny particles or droplets are surrounded by a coating to give small capsules, with useful properties. In general, it is used to incorporate food ingredients, enzymes, cells or other materials on a micro metric scale. Microencapsulation can also be used to enclose solids, liquids, or gases inside a micrometric wall made of hard or soft soluble film, in order to reduce dosing frequency and prevent the degradation of pharmaceuticals. In its simplest form, a microcapsule is a small sphere comprising a near-uniform wall enclosing some material. The enclosed material in the microcapsule is referred to as the core, internal phase, or fill, whereas the wall is sometimes called a shell, coating, or membrane. Some materials like lipids and polymers, such as alginate, may be used as a mixture to trap the material of interest inside. Most microcapsules have pores with diameters between a few nanometers and a few micrometers.','{\"pat_doc\": 453.0, \"pub_alt\": 382.0, \"pub_doc\": 2231.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 90.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 15980878.0, \"pat_granted\": 151.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -18.0, \"pub_doc\": 33.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.4, \"grant_fund\": -2198383.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0f2822dc68158588792e3323e6e8ee3c','a4a5753db73052249bc74606e77f9c86','3bae6e0ea5ff6b484acb36d0b12b9eb0','2023-09-05 22:21:15','2023-10-29 03:16:16','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cryopreservation',12,'Cryopreservation or cryoconservation is a process where biological material - cells, tissues, or organs - are frozen to preserve the material for an extended period of time. At low temperatures any cell metabolism which might cause damage to the biological material in question is effectively stopped. Cryopreservation is an effective way to transport biological samples over long distances, store samples for prolonged periods of time, and create a bank of samples for users. Molecules, referred to as cryoprotective agents, are added to reduce the osmotic shock and physical stresses cells undergo in the freezing process. Some cryoprotective agents used in research are inspired by plants and animals in nature that have unique cold tolerance to survive harsh winters, including: trees, wood frogs, and tardigrades.','{\"pat_doc\": 839.0, \"pub_alt\": 439.0, \"pub_doc\": 1942.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 56.0, \"clinic_alt\": 14.0, \"clinic_doc\": 119.0, \"grant_fund\": 18534131.0, \"pat_granted\": 359.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 37.6, \"pub_doc\": 46.4, \"clinic_doc\": 29.8, \"grant_fund\": -15784626.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0f49cc08d865371f102ae6f62b4468b9','42dcab631334ddefd1aa257b8b5f1e8f','eefb2660a8535eb1d304c9a60295324f','2023-09-05 21:18:18','2023-10-29 04:01:40','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Liposomes',36,'A liposome is a small artificial vesicle, spherical in shape, having at least one lipid bilayer. Due to their hydrophobicity and/or hydrophilicity, biocompatibility, particle size and many other properties, liposomes can be used as drug delivery vehicles for administration of pharmaceutical drugs and nutrients, such as lipid nanoparticles in mRNA vaccines, and DNA vaccines. Liposomes can be prepared by disrupting biological membranes. Liposomes are most often composed of phospholipids, especially phosphatidylcholine, and cholesterol, but may also include other lipids, such as those found in egg and phosphatidylethanolamine, as long as they are compatible with lipid bilayer structure. A liposome design may employ surface ligands for attaching to unhealthy tissue. The major types of liposomes are the multilamellar vesicle, the small unilamellar liposome vesicle, the large unilamellar vesicle, and the cochleate vesicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 2368.0, \"pub_alt\": 590.0, \"pub_doc\": 9307.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 411.0, \"clinic_alt\": 108.0, \"clinic_doc\": 57.0, \"grant_fund\": 113084615.0, \"pat_granted\": 601.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 12.3, \"pub_doc\": 172.3, \"clinic_doc\": 8.1, \"grant_fund\": -13776868.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0f6f7bb7d11b96346c84907ee738e4b6','dbff1bacaaa4170742799b76b0d72aa1','e5dc1ab9b95fd144580ba449bdb1f286','2023-09-05 20:47:05','2023-10-29 04:21:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','CRISPR-Cas9',48,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 954.0, \"pub_alt\": 3609.0, \"pub_doc\": 7033.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1218.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 22.0, \"grant_fund\": 503974497.0, \"pat_granted\": 261.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.6, \"pub_doc\": 115.9, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -29971557.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0fdf715ad7ba7fa5032684903029f023','7d2130a3ffbe9bc530ccc4b006bedc33','a21d57b1520cb1a6af41c917959012e7','2023-09-05 20:52:48','2023-10-28 17:51:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','siRNA',48,'SiRNA (short interfering RNA) is a small double-stranded RNA molecule that can trigger the destruction of specific messenger RNA (mRNA) and thereby inhibit the expression of genes. SiRNA is involved in RNA interference, a natural process that regulates gene expression at the post-transcriptional level. Once inside the cell, siRNA is incorporated into the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), which separates the two strands of the siRNA molecule and guides the antisense strand to a complementary target mRNA. The RISC complex then cleaves the target mRNA, preventing its translation into proteins. SiRNA has become a powerful tool for investigating gene function and developing new therapeutics for various diseases. Its potential applications include treating viral infections, cancer, and genetic disorders, as well as controlling insect pests and enhancing crop yields.','{\"pat_doc\": 4053.0, \"pub_alt\": 585.0, \"pub_doc\": 22787.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1335.0, \"clinic_alt\": 109.0, \"clinic_doc\": 32.0, \"grant_fund\": 405137943.0, \"pat_granted\": 1147.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 99.5, \"pub_doc\": -402.5, \"clinic_doc\": 4.8, \"grant_fund\": -26868531.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('0fed5161a7452eb3bba413c8ed232a90','116c9f3326973bf53316f607199f9944','09c8640e20ae09de463871c1529a6589','2023-09-05 22:07:59','2023-10-29 03:36:14','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Fluorescence Microscopy',48,'A fluorescence microscope is an optical microscope that uses fluorescence instead of, or in addition to, scattering, reflection, and attenuation or absorption, to study the properties of organic or inorganic substances. \"Fluorescence microscope\" refers to any microscope that uses fluorescence to generate an image, whether it is a simple set up like an epifluorescence microscope or a more complicated design such as a confocal microscope, which uses optical sectioning to get better resolution of the fluorescence image.','{\"pat_doc\": 463.0, \"pub_alt\": 2153.0, \"pub_doc\": 12290.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1194.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 36.0, \"grant_fund\": 444947573.0, \"pat_granted\": 137.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.7, \"pub_doc\": -63.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.8, \"grant_fund\": -17544989.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('10f760d4caab2674012d63c0b7bace48','e1e875f09f9ac3cb516d1a52affa7c20','9ca5a3bb1439526aa869b8ae1a850da8','2024-01-18 11:38:52','2024-01-18 11:38:52','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Chromatography Detector',12,'In chemical analysis, chromatography is a laboratory technique for the separation of a mixture into its components. The mixture is dissolved in a fluid solvent (gas or liquid) called the mobile phase, which carries it through a system (a column, a capillary tube, a plate, or a sheet) on which a material called the stationary phase is fixed.','{\"pat_doc\": 20.0, \"pub_alt\": 2.0, \"pub_doc\": 2.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 9.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": -1.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 43088.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('114ade67100d42d171f97a011e13d84c','7e6303a93deff34a836da02c9ec9b121','b8d8729029b072a6d46a6e6415f7d63a','2023-09-20 19:21:20','2023-10-28 14:51:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Addisons Disease',12,'Addisons disease, also known as primary adrenal insufficiency, is a rare long-term endocrine disorder characterized by inadequate production of the steroid hormones cortisol and aldosterone by the two outer layers of the cells of the adrenal glands, causing adrenal insufficiency. Symptoms generally come on slowly and insidiously and may include abdominal pain and gastrointestinal abnormalities, weakness, and weight loss. Darkening of the skin in certain areas may also occur. Under certain circumstances, an adrenal crisis may occur with low blood pressure, vomiting, lower back pain, and loss of consciousness. Mood changes may also occur. Rapid onset of symptoms indicates acute adrenal failure, which is a clinical emergency. An adrenal crisis can be triggered by stress, such as from an injury, surgery, or infection. Addisons disease arises from problems with the adrenal gland such that not enough of the steroid hormone cortisol and possibly aldosterone are produced.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 3.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('117e4fa45ed013edaecc202bb42e5c97','c2aa8e8ff53300b96a4cd521696cbdbb','ba652e04894d8ad7c796a0f64375c740','2023-09-08 01:49:52','2023-10-28 23:56:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Suspension Culture',48,'A cell suspension or suspension culture is a type of cell culture in which single cells or small aggregates of cells are allowed to function and multiply in an agitated growth medium, thus forming a suspension. Suspension culture is one of the two classical types of cell culture, the other being adherent culture. The history of suspension cell culture closely aligns with the history of cell culture overall, but differs in maintenance methods and commercial applications. The cells themselves can either be derived from homogenized tissue or from heterogenous cell solutions. Suspension cell culture is commonly used to culture nonadhesive cell lines like hematopoietic cells, plant cells, and insect cells. While some cell lines are cultured in suspension, the majority of commercially available mammalian cell lines are adherent. Suspension cell cultures must be agitated to maintain cells in suspension, and may require specialized equipment and flasks.','{\"pat_doc\": 1211.0, \"pub_alt\": 278.0, \"pub_doc\": 1244.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 52.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 11982193.0, \"pat_granted\": 386.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.9, \"pub_doc\": -11.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -1405329.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('11ca0e5fc90374ca2955d81dc987b2c1','0b7aa8ee981ba0fe14ccf04dee81c1ad','62899d4dc41a7b9eb6091bb110aca523','2023-09-05 19:51:05','2023-10-29 04:55:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Tissue Engineering',48,'Tissue engineering is a biomedical engineering discipline that uses a combination of cells, engineering, materials methods, and suitable biochemical and physicochemical factors to restore, maintain, improve, or replace different types of biological tissues. Tissue engineering often involves the use of cells placed on tissue scaffolds in the formation of new viable tissue for a medical purpose but is not limited to applications involving cells and tissue scaffolds. While it was once categorized as a sub-field of biomaterials, having grown in scope and importance it can be considered as a field of its own. While most definitions of tissue engineering cover a broad range of applications, in practice the term is closely associated with applications that repair or replace portions of or whole tissues. Often, the tissues involved require certain mechanical and structural properties for proper functioning.','{\"pat_doc\": 3897.0, \"pub_alt\": 663.0, \"pub_doc\": 25919.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1721.0, \"clinic_alt\": 16.0, \"clinic_doc\": 81.0, \"grant_fund\": 718142197.0, \"pat_granted\": 1470.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.9, \"pub_doc\": 306.5, \"clinic_doc\": 10.5, \"grant_fund\": -54494104.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('126511c1f208cdb52b4aa684a92ca1c8','989e334c32437caa317127b884df7c33','704edc6299a6c2e6515a45403d655e47','2023-09-08 02:32:40','2023-10-28 10:55:31','Electronics','Components','Interface & Display Devices','MicroLED',36,'MicroLED is an emerging display technology that is similar to traditional LED displays, but with much smaller individual LEDs, or \"micro LEDs.\" The small size of these LEDs allows for higher resolution displays with better contrast and brightness compared to other types of displays like LCD or OLED. MicroLED is also more energy-efficient and can provide longer lifetimes than other technologies. While MicroLED displays have been around for a few years, they are still in the early stages of development with only a few consumer products in the market. However, it is expected that the technology will become more widely adopted in the coming years due to its many advantages over other display technologies.','{\"pat_doc\": 491.0, \"pub_alt\": 235.0, \"pub_doc\": 238.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 21.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 15395156.0, \"pat_granted\": 115.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 39.8, \"pub_doc\": 12.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 656986.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('12ba0c4ca124c620b96cbb878ed3772d','d006191764fe7b11e9181190cc8abcbe','5f9f631521aff2090e15184e37181d22','2023-09-04 19:03:56','2023-10-29 06:16:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Immunohistochemistry',48,'Immunohistochemistry is the most common application of immunostaining. It involves the process of selectively identifying antigens in cells of a tissue section by exploiting the principle of antibodies binding specifically to antigens in biological tissues. IHC takes its name from the roots \"immuno\", in reference to antibodies used in the procedure, and \"histo\", meaning tissue. Albert Coons conceptualized and first implemented the procedure in 1941. Visualising an antibody-antigen interaction can be accomplished in a number of ways, mainly either of the following: â€¢ Chromogenic immunohistochemistry, wherein an antibody is conjugated to an enzyme, such as peroxidase, that can catalyse a colour-producing reaction. â€¢ Immunofluorescence, where the antibody is tagged to a fluorophore, such as fluorescein or rhodamine. Immunohistochemical staining is widely used in the diagnosis of abnormal cells such as those found in cancerous tumors.','{\"pat_doc\": 679.0, \"pub_alt\": 28733.0, \"pub_doc\": 63246.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1587.0, \"clinic_alt\": 553.0, \"clinic_doc\": 863.0, \"grant_fund\": 465499696.0, \"pat_granted\": 240.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.1, \"pub_doc\": -408.2, \"clinic_doc\": 134.5, \"grant_fund\": -28858320.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('12ed8570078947d755d527e9f6b8568d','26139c734216125329350135b2f763ec','95dd984c9978fee8a3271496b2247ff4','2023-09-08 00:25:57','2023-10-29 01:41:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Sorting',12,'Cell sorting is the process through which a particular cell type is separated from others contained in a sample on the basis of its physical or biological properties, such as size, morphological parameters, viability and both extracellular and intracellular protein expression. The homogeneous cell population obtained after sorting can be used for a variety of applications including research, diagnosis, and therapy.','{\"pat_doc\": 305.0, \"pub_alt\": 686.0, \"pub_doc\": 911.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 67.0, \"clinic_alt\": 314.0, \"clinic_doc\": 31.0, \"grant_fund\": 34053669.0, \"pat_granted\": 122.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 39.0, \"pub_doc\": -33.8, \"clinic_doc\": 7.3, \"grant_fund\": -18215497.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('12f2e18d774d161d53127bb5968ccac7','4b77f13801e06ca4a3d587ee4f09a407','574dc8bedf464bfa6dcd368851dbebf9','2023-09-05 21:16:27','2023-10-29 04:06:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Transfection',24,'Transfection is the process of deliberately introducing naked or purified nucleic acids into eukaryotic cells. It may also refer to other methods and cell types, although other terms are often preferred: \"transformation\" is typically used to describe non-viral DNA transfer in bacteria and non-animal eukaryotic cells, including plant cells. In animal cells, transfection is the preferred term as transformation is also used to refer to progression to a cancerous state in these cells. Transduction is often used to describe virus-mediated gene transfer into eukaryotic cells. The word transfection is a portmanteau of trans- and infection. Genetic material, may be transfected. Transfection of animal cells typically involves opening transient pores or \"holes\" in the cell membrane to allow the uptake of material.','{\"pat_doc\": 1881.0, \"pub_alt\": 6193.0, \"pub_doc\": 7657.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 192.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1577.0, \"clinic_doc\": 28.0, \"grant_fund\": 42996768.0, \"pat_granted\": 554.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 70.6, \"pub_doc\": -483.2, \"clinic_doc\": 6.1, \"grant_fund\": -22113358.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('131e418fce27c280d4e9489ffdcf01e4','dfe596d300e59da2f75df75fd3120d54','a73d74823ba2a6c69ad94ff6d93ed919','2023-09-08 01:42:12','2023-10-28 15:06:14','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia',48,'Congenital adrenal hyperplasia is a group of autosomal recessive disorders characterized by impaired cortisol synthesis. It results from the deficiency of one of the five enzymes required for the synthesis of cortisol in the adrenal cortex. Most of these disorders involve excessive or deficient production of hormones such as glucocorticoids, mineralocorticoids, or sex steroids, and can alter development of primary or secondary sex characteristics in some affected infants, children, or adults. It is one of the most common autosomal recessive disorders in humans.','{\"pat_doc\": 178.0, \"pub_alt\": 119.0, \"pub_doc\": 1525.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 700.0, \"clinic_doc\": 74.0, \"grant_fund\": 4199049.0, \"pat_granted\": 23.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.4, \"pub_doc\": 1.7, \"clinic_doc\": 5.2, \"grant_fund\": -549349.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1342911d74f6c9bfa00ad242b38fda3d','666869b3162af8fad5a5b7d07b2312c9','f268e5ab79c5a1d38ab08daccf7ee951','2023-09-08 01:48:42','2023-10-28 11:10:33','Electronics','Components','Processing Devices','Neuromorphic Hardware',48,'Neuromorphic hardware is a type of computer hardware that is inspired by the workings of the human brain. Unlike traditional hardware that uses a Von Neumann architecture where the processing and memory are separate, neuromorphic hardware combines both processing and memory in a single unit. This results in a more efficient way of computing, where information is processed in parallel, similar to how neurons work in the brain. Neuromorphic hardware is often used in applications that require low power consumption and real-time processing, such as robotics and autonomous vehicles. The technology has the potential to create highly advanced and intelligent systems, but there are still challenges to overcome, such as developing effective programming models and scaling up the hardware for larger applications. Nonetheless, neuromorphic hardware is an exciting and promising area of research that has the potential to revolutionize computing as we know it.','{\"pat_doc\": 79.0, \"pub_alt\": 645.0, \"pub_doc\": 1005.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 66.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 229592558.0, \"pat_granted\": 30.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.9, \"pub_doc\": 33.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -50956752.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('142209332931400edc083c0868066f0f','4d2d0b15ee17780893b8c9e0ae59e835','005e837817c21a0393b99843cbfee450','2023-09-08 01:10:59','2023-10-28 15:36:18','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Acromegaly',24,'Acromegaly is a disorder that results in excess growth of certain parts of the human body. It is caused by excess growth hormone after the growth plates have closed. The initial symptom is typically enlargement of the hands and feet. There may also be an enlargement of the forehead, jaw, and nose. Other symptoms may include joint pain, thicker skin, deepening of the voice, headaches, and problems with vision. Complications of the disease may include type 2 diabetes, sleep apnea, and high blood pressure.','{\"pat_doc\": 51.0, \"pub_alt\": 367.0, \"pub_doc\": 1087.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 32.0, \"clinic_doc\": 68.0, \"grant_fund\": 1407203.0, \"pat_granted\": 14.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": -4.4, \"clinic_doc\": 10.7, \"grant_fund\": 169355.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1488e7bed11e6df64e5a9a6f27a2039a','90f1f351860541863718a68f1e2fe5b6','7a49c80d1b80fc15aa79d84c9b4afdbb','2023-09-05 22:29:10','2023-10-28 17:21:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Natural killer cells',36,'Natural killer cells, also known as NK cells or large granular lymphocytes, are a type of cytotoxic lymphocyte critical to the innate immune system that belong to the rapidly expanding family of known innate lymphoid cells and represent 5â€“20% of all circulating lymphocytes in humans. The role of NK cells is analogous to that of cytotoxic T cells in the vertebrate adaptive immune response. NK cells provide rapid responses to virus-infected cell and other intracellular pathogens acting at around 3 days after infection, and respond to tumor formation. Typically, immune cells detect the antigen presented on major histocompatibility complex on infected cell surfaces, triggering cytokine release, causing the death of the infected cell by lysis or apoptosis. NK cells are unique, however, as they have the ability to recognize and kill stressed cells in the absence of antibodies and MHC, allowing for a much faster immune reaction.','{\"pat_doc\": 1265.0, \"pub_alt\": 3387.0, \"pub_doc\": 3564.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 145.0, \"clinic_alt\": 200.0, \"clinic_doc\": 201.0, \"grant_fund\": 45075103.0, \"pat_granted\": 212.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 32.0, \"pub_doc\": 58.8, \"clinic_doc\": 29.4, \"grant_fund\": -4654238.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('15785bb014f089eff7688b1072c547e0','6272d8c4fefc516af912e39ce608f48b','f5961ebdecc3630bd05559901b09f90f','2023-09-08 01:50:58','2023-10-28 15:01:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Gene therapies (Non-viral)','Ribozyme',48,'Ribozymes are RNA molecules that have the ability to catalyze specific biochemical reactions, including RNA splicing in gene expression, similar to the action of protein enzymes. The 1982 discovery of ribozymes demonstrated that RNA can be both genetic material and a biological catalyst, and contributed to the RNA world hypothesis, which suggests that RNA may have been important in the evolution of prebiotic self-replicating systems. The most common activities of natural or in vitro evolved ribozymes are the cleavage of RNA and DNA and peptide bond formation. For example, the smallest ribozyme known can aminoacylate a GCCU-3 sequence in the presence of PheAMP. Within the ribosome, ribozymes function as part of the large subunit ribosomal RNA to link amino acids during protein synthesis. They also participate in a variety of RNA processing reactions, including RNA splicing, viral replication, and transfer RNA biosynthesis.','{\"pat_doc\": 441.0, \"pub_alt\": 1404.0, \"pub_doc\": 916.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 82.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 21600127.0, \"pat_granted\": 133.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 8.3, \"pub_doc\": -0.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.2, \"grant_fund\": -2009401.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('15e5b805ff95895c537494b549b9d672','4d2d0b15ee17780893b8c9e0ae59e835','005e837817c21a0393b99843cbfee450','2023-09-08 01:10:59','2023-10-28 15:36:19','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Acromegaly',48,'Acromegaly is a disorder that results in excess growth of certain parts of the human body. It is caused by excess growth hormone after the growth plates have closed. The initial symptom is typically enlargement of the hands and feet. There may also be an enlargement of the forehead, jaw, and nose. Other symptoms may include joint pain, thicker skin, deepening of the voice, headaches, and problems with vision. Complications of the disease may include type 2 diabetes, sleep apnea, and high blood pressure.','{\"pat_doc\": 100.0, \"pub_alt\": 367.0, \"pub_doc\": 2236.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 18.0, \"clinic_alt\": 32.0, \"clinic_doc\": 99.0, \"grant_fund\": 2519881.0, \"pat_granted\": 26.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": -4.4, \"clinic_doc\": 10.7, \"grant_fund\": 169355.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('161497f46271e92a82e92a84902d395e','e7461a8ad3be85a4a9927a05f09da738','74dfdb3be3d296db4e284e57c8999ab7','2023-09-08 02:05:14','2023-10-28 23:11:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Primary Cell Culture',48,'Primary cell culture is the ex vivo culture of cells freshly obtained from a multicellular organism, as opposed to the culture of immortalized cell lines. In general, primary cell cultures are considered more representative of in vivo tissues than cell lines, and this is recognized legally in some countries such as the UK. However, primary cells require adequate substrate and nutrient conditions to thrive and after a certain number of divisions they acquire a senescent phenotype, leading to irreversible cell cycle arrest. The generation of cell lines stems from these two reasons. Primary cells can become immortalized either spontaneously or by genetic modification, at which point they become cell lines which can be subcultured indefinitely. Because of their requirements for viability, primary cell cultures did not become widespread until the 2000s.','{\"pat_doc\": 163.0, \"pub_alt\": 151.0, \"pub_doc\": 683.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 102.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 15.0, \"grant_fund\": 44306923.0, \"pat_granted\": 49.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 9.5, \"pub_doc\": -8.7, \"clinic_doc\": 2.5, \"grant_fund\": -4026979.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('162398b9775ae3bbe09d7cf6179dc51e','7d2130a3ffbe9bc530ccc4b006bedc33','a21d57b1520cb1a6af41c917959012e7','2023-09-05 20:52:48','2023-10-28 17:51:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','siRNA',36,'SiRNA (short interfering RNA) is a small double-stranded RNA molecule that can trigger the destruction of specific messenger RNA (mRNA) and thereby inhibit the expression of genes. SiRNA is involved in RNA interference, a natural process that regulates gene expression at the post-transcriptional level. Once inside the cell, siRNA is incorporated into the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), which separates the two strands of the siRNA molecule and guides the antisense strand to a complementary target mRNA. The RISC complex then cleaves the target mRNA, preventing its translation into proteins. SiRNA has become a powerful tool for investigating gene function and developing new therapeutics for various diseases. Its potential applications include treating viral infections, cancer, and genetic disorders, as well as controlling insect pests and enhancing crop yields.','{\"pat_doc\": 3187.0, \"pub_alt\": 585.0, \"pub_doc\": 16611.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 841.0, \"clinic_alt\": 109.0, \"clinic_doc\": 30.0, \"grant_fund\": 271221143.0, \"pat_granted\": 884.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 99.5, \"pub_doc\": -402.5, \"clinic_doc\": 4.8, \"grant_fund\": -26868531.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('163766ba9f14753ee4c5f10c0ba69fc5','224f79c7aefff29a3d4cd0f3806a209a','5439cfcadd881d98d0c7179fbcfec554','2023-09-08 02:01:45','2023-10-28 23:21:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Liquid Crystal Elastomers',48,'Liquid crystal elastomers (LCEs) are a class of materials that exhibit both the fluid-like properties of liquid crystals and the elasticity of an elastic solid. They are composed of polymeric chains that are cross-linked to form a three-dimensional network. The presence of liquid crystal domains allows these materials to exhibit several unusual properties, including reversible shape changes in response to external stimuli such as heat, light, or mechanical stress. This makes LCEs promising candidates for a range of applications, from soft robotics and actuators to biomedical devices and responsive materials.','{\"pat_doc\": 32.0, \"pub_alt\": 273.0, \"pub_doc\": 428.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 33.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 21061150.0, \"pat_granted\": 12.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 31.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2814310.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('16dc5c198141136b1a6afda2aa484803','eee0d94d36c42e167a1a4be01f14392d','8c7694fa0bfc9847929f37bd7f31bd59','2023-09-04 19:48:49','2023-10-29 05:51:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','3D printing',12,'3D printing or additive manufacturing is the construction of a three-dimensional object from a CAD model or a digital 3D model. It can be done in a variety of processes in which material is deposited, joined or solidified under computer control, with the material being added together, typically layer by layer. In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping. As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology, whereby the term additive manufacturing can be used synonymously with 3D printing.','{\"pat_doc\": 9178.0, \"pub_alt\": 2627.0, \"pub_doc\": 9337.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 379.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 114.0, \"grant_fund\": 240443618.0, \"pat_granted\": 3939.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 434.0, \"pub_doc\": 1197.3, \"clinic_doc\": 23.8, \"grant_fund\": -8565739.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('16f40d970afa60ff5935e0a9f1273cc6','d702a8adc5dbea4b170f75415100b3b5','4aebb65d3ef171435ae3068e3a2c9f22','2023-09-04 18:33:18','2023-10-29 07:01:15','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Stem Cells',12,'Stem cells are undifferentiated cells that have the ability to differentiate into specialized cells and regenerate damaged tissues in the body. These cells have the potential to give rise to any cell type in the body, such as blood, bone, muscle, and nerve cells. Stem cells can be classified into embryonic, fetal, and adult stem cells based on their origin and potential to differentiate. Embryonic stem cells are obtained from early-stage embryos and can differentiate into any cell type, while fetal and adult stem cells are found in various tissues and have a more limited differentiation potential. Stem cell research shows promise for developing treatments for a range of diseases and conditions.','{\"pat_doc\": 6189.0, \"pub_alt\": 3006.0, \"pub_doc\": 18832.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1142.0, \"clinic_alt\": 531.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1551.0, \"grant_fund\": 581734272.0, \"pat_granted\": 1878.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 141.4, \"pub_doc\": -576.1, \"clinic_doc\": 354.8, \"grant_fund\": -242932791.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('176092840ac8db6f7964584b9f1cf4e9','1fccc88a9353a2b047cbe302f41187a4','e935f5dfeb3e4ae65d7860e4ea27b605','2023-09-05 20:23:19','2023-10-28 12:45:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Societal & Economic Disruptions','Post-COVID-19',24,'The concept of Post-COVID-19 refers to the scenario and circumstances following the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic. The world after COVID-19 is expected to be markedly different, with changes in the way people work, travel, socialize, and interact with each other. These changes may include a greater emphasis on remote work, increased use of technology for communication, more flexible working arrangements, significant shifts in consumer behavior, and a focus on public health and hygiene. The pandemic has also highlighted the importance of international cooperation and sustainable development, leading to the adoption of new policies aimed at creating a more resilient and equitable world. Ultimately, the post-COVID-19 era represents both an opportunity and a challenge for businesses, governments, and individuals to adapt and thrive in a rapidly changing world.','{\"pat_doc\": 30.0, \"pub_alt\": 24451.0, \"pub_doc\": 8693.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 161.0, \"clinic_alt\": 244.0, \"clinic_doc\": 264.0, \"grant_fund\": 33854723.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.4, \"pub_doc\": 1295.8, \"clinic_doc\": 64.2, \"grant_fund\": -5280894.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('17a8434fead2c4637eb105f9561b7a30','ce48dd19951bc72e32788762866aa8ba','9f4de602c8b4dc324f5081159f81d1f9','2023-09-08 10:02:32','2023-10-28 19:21:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Loss on Drying',36,'Loss on Drying (LOD) is a common analysis performed in the pharmaceutical, food, and cosmetics industries to quantify the amount of moisture content in a sample. It is a gravimetric analysis method that measures the weight lost by a sample when it is heated at a specific temperature. The difference between the initial weight of the sample and the weight after heating is recorded as LOD. This technique is useful in determining the stability and shelf life of products, as high moisture content can lead to microbial growth, chemical degradation, and decreased product quality. LOD is a critical parameter in product manufacturing, as it can affect the products physical and chemical properties, efficacy, and safety. Controlling the moisture content of a product is essential to ensure its stability and prevent spoilage, making LOD an important tool for quality control and assurance.','{\"pat_doc\": 30.0, \"pub_alt\": 10.0, \"pub_doc\": 232.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 1.4, \"clinic_doc\": -0.8, \"grant_fund\": -10651.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1805b711b1a99d3fe0744c6f585cd661','c24a789d6d92253253ff9f90dc646a7a','774a346d62790e44d654b1f21ecba973','2023-09-07 23:48:38','2023-10-29 02:26:21','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Single-Cell Analysis',36,'In the field of cellular biology, single-cell analysis is the study of genomics, transcriptomics, proteomics, metabolomics and cellâ€“cell interactions at the single cell level. The concept of single-cell analysis originated in the 1970s. Before the discovery of heterogeneity, single-cell analysis mainly referred to the analysis or manipulation of an individual cell in a bulk population of cells at a particular condition using optical or electronic microscope. To date, due to the heterogeneity seen in both eukaryotic and prokaryotic cell populations, analyzing a single cell makes it possible to discover mechanisms not seen when studying a bulk population of cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 126.0, \"pub_alt\": 920.0, \"pub_doc\": 1958.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 270.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 88174094.0, \"pat_granted\": 12.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.4, \"pub_doc\": 102.1, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": -19310396.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('186d2e8d917936a007a4c167cf6b7252','e73131830356703a23b1a11a711e48c5','e4f81d8ac891f1e1dbdd2332eaaa8fed','2023-09-05 22:16:53','2023-10-29 03:21:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Magnetic nanoparticles',12,'Magnetic nanoparticles are a class of nanoparticle that can be manipulated using magnetic fields. Such particles commonly consist of two components, a magnetic material, often iron, nickel and cobalt, and a chemical component that has functionality. While nanoparticles are smaller than 1 micrometer in diameter, the larger microbeads are 0.5â€“500 micrometer in diameter. Magnetic nanoparticle clusters that are composed of a number of individual magnetic nanoparticles are known as magnetic nanobeads with a diameter of 50â€“200 nanometers. Magnetic nanoparticle clusters are a basis for their further magnetic assembly into magnetic nanochains.','{\"pat_doc\": 473.0, \"pub_alt\": 142.0, \"pub_doc\": 2322.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 51.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 24694138.0, \"pat_granted\": 152.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -8.6, \"pub_doc\": -35.6, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -2481846.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('18c8a4c13bc6daa60f7d8ed86e9d28e3','82841277cc54621d2d6071e3ec919414','0b9a93bcbf56042557d5a41dd3db0243','2023-09-20 17:31:16','2023-10-28 13:01:19','Healthcare','Discovery & Development Technologies','Other','Waldo',24,'Telemanipulator, or waldo, is a device which, through electronic, hydraulic, or mechanical linkages, allows a hand-like mechanism to be controlled by a human operator.','{\"pat_doc\": 5.0, \"pub_alt\": 1322.0, \"pub_doc\": 736.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 56.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": 1452045.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.6, \"pub_doc\": 12.9, \"clinic_doc\": 2.4, \"grant_fund\": -590542.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('18d5845e0e1c2efd8b929aae8b913c90','02a38e6ea55a654be6d75d697c93ecfb','0af29b992be89a885d2b3986c5a61ac5','2023-09-08 10:03:52','2023-10-28 19:11:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Catalyst screening',48,'Catalyst screening can be defined as a process by which researchers test a large number of catalysts in order to identify the most effective one for a particular reaction. Catalysts are substances that speed up reactions without being consumed in the process. The screening process typically involves testing each catalyst under a variety of conditions such as temperature, pressure, and reaction time, to determine which catalyst is the most suitable for the reaction being studied. Catalyst screening is an important step in many research projects as it helps researchers to identify the catalysts that are most likely to be effective in a real-world scenario. It can also help to identify new catalysts that may be more effective than those that are currently being used in industry. By screening a large number of catalysts, researchers can quickly identify promising candidates for further study, ultimately leading to the development of more efficient catalysts for a wide range of applications.','{\"pat_doc\": 65.0, \"pub_alt\": 86.0, \"pub_doc\": 218.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 19.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4533375.0, \"pat_granted\": 43.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 7.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 219625.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('19069f6c6e3d2d536990b292fcd01b1a','2ef204f64673ee0cc4682daa8faf26bb','767ea62d04e7021f7b0e5dec58a48a8d','2023-09-08 10:56:51','2023-10-28 18:56:11','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Personalized Medicine',36,'Personalized medicine, also referred to as precision medicine, is a medical model that separates people into different groupsâ€”with medical decisions, practices, interventions and/or products being tailored to the individual patient based on their predicted response or risk of disease. The terms personalized medicine, precision medicine, stratified medicine and P4 medicine are used interchangeably to describe this concept though some authors and organisations use these expressions separately to indicate particular nuances. While the tailoring of treatment to patients dates back at least to the time of Hippocrates, the term has risen in usage in recent years given the growth of new diagnostic and informatics approaches that provide understanding of the molecular basis of disease, particularly genomics. This provides a clear evidence base on which to stratify related patients.','{\"pat_doc\": 360.0, \"pub_alt\": 664.0, \"pub_doc\": 7241.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 953.0, \"clinic_alt\": 592.0, \"clinic_doc\": 289.0, \"grant_fund\": 592471715.0, \"pat_granted\": 83.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.4, \"pub_doc\": 162.7, \"clinic_doc\": 61.2, \"grant_fund\": -59753219.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('191225fb57f7da663ed36e4b47a4b09a','e44792deacd6cf8232ea590a59b65829','ebccb11a63ab2a40e9dc38470854a837','2023-09-05 18:41:05','2023-10-29 05:46:09','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Differentiation',12,'Mechanisms of Development is a peer-reviewed scientific journal covering all aspects of developmental biology. It is the official journal of the International Society of Developmental Biologists and is published by Elsevier. The journal was established in 1972 as Cell Differentiation and was renamed Cell Differentiation and Development in 1988. It acquired its current name in December 1990. The editor-in-chief is D. Wilkinson. A separate section of the journal, Gene Expression Patterns, covers research on cloning and gene expression. In 2020 the journal became Cells & Development with the subtitle: Cell and Developmental Biology and their Quantitative Approaches.','{\"pat_doc\": 423.0, \"pub_alt\": 1147.0, \"pub_doc\": 4020.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 266.0, \"clinic_alt\": 437.0, \"clinic_doc\": 88.0, \"grant_fund\": 114158540.0, \"pat_granted\": 143.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.6, \"pub_doc\": 33.4, \"clinic_doc\": 21.2, \"grant_fund\": -58438151.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('193591f14b967dfa82165d2c17ad7981','629f564fa930d422fbfc8405c3bae6c0','72a385b9d786832dcc2c823f54ed4998','2023-09-05 20:39:21','2023-10-28 12:40:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Digital Twin',24,'A digital twin is a digital representation of an intended or actual real-world physical product, system, or process that serves as the effectively indistinguishable digital counterpart of it for practical purposes, such as simulation, integration, testing, monitoring, and maintenance. The digital twin has been intended from its initial introduction to be the underlying premise for Product Lifecycle Management and exists throughout the entire lifecycle of the physical entity it represents. Since information is granular, the digital twin representation is determined by the value-based use cases it is created to implement. The digital twin can and does often exist before there is a physical entity. The use of a digital twin in the creation phase allows the intended entitys entire lifecycle to be modeled and simulated. A digital twin of an existing entity may be used in real-time and regularly synchronized with the corresponding physical system.','{\"pat_doc\": 7192.0, \"pub_alt\": 767.0, \"pub_doc\": 11429.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1367.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 1785210668.0, \"pat_granted\": 1508.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1361.7, \"pub_doc\": 1705.1, \"clinic_doc\": 4.4, \"grant_fund\": 206480656.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('194f2126f1519756638af0e5ab9400a1','6df6cc21f2a3ec039f6f594cd9050b81','22c986a1ed138cca635623e24850cd2d','2023-09-08 02:47:18','2023-10-28 14:05:05','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel Drug Delivery','Progesterone supplementation',12,'Progesterone supplementation, also known as progesterone therapy, is a medical treatment that involves taking supplemental doses of progesterone hormone. Progesterone is naturally produced by the ovaries during a womans menstrual cycle and plays a crucial role in regulating the menstrual cycle and preparing the body for pregnancy. However, some women may have low levels of progesterone, resulting in irregular menstrual cycles or difficulty getting pregnant. Progesterone supplementation can help balance hormonal levels and increase the chances of conceiving and sustaining a pregnancy. It can be administered through various methods, such as pills, injections, or vaginal suppositories, and is usually prescribed by a healthcare professional based on the patients individual needs and medical history.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 13.0, \"pub_doc\": 49.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 18.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 3.4, \"grant_fund\": -80930.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1a0b4699ddb7406b1f82b2da13e7f9ee','164a36aa72f0d1ad31bba2a4ae14dad1','52e358453865c2f781ecea69256e441f','2023-09-08 02:22:34','2023-10-28 22:26:12','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Spectral Database',36,'A spectral database is a repository of spectral data that can be used for identification and characterization of chemical compounds. Spectral data includes information about the properties of light interacting with a sample, such as absorption, emission, and scattering. By comparing the spectral data of an unknown sample to that in a spectral database, researchers can identify the likely chemical composition of the sample. Spectral databases are crucial for many scientific fields, including chemistry, biology, and materials science. They are constantly being updated with new data and have become essential tools in modern research.','{\"pat_doc\": 77.0, \"pub_alt\": 96.0, \"pub_doc\": 287.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 27.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 11872148.0, \"pat_granted\": 26.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.1, \"pub_doc\": 3.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -1497510.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1a6388e8b35371559397d23319e80591','cb426d718331f51011984ab644408b3c','b10c3992ebb8f463a7fad145792de043','2023-09-08 09:16:19','2023-10-28 21:11:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Liquid Chromatography',24,'Liquid chromatography (LC) is a widely used separation technique to isolate, identify, and quantify various components within a mixture. It works on the principle of differential partitioning of sample components between a mobile phase (liquid) and stationary phase (solid or liquid). The sample is introduced into the mobile phase, which is pumped through the stationary phase packed inside a column. The interaction between sample components and stationary phase determines the retention time and separation of individual components. Various types of liquid chromatography, such as high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC), ultra-high-performance liquid chromatography (UHPLC), and size exclusion chromatography (SEC), are available to separate different types of analytes based on their physicochemical properties. LC is widely used in the pharmaceutical, biotechnology, food, and environmental testing industries due to its high resolution, accuracy, and sensitivity.','{\"pat_doc\": 8498.0, \"pub_alt\": 1833.0, \"pub_doc\": 33369.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 485.0, \"clinic_alt\": 68.0, \"clinic_doc\": 346.0, \"grant_fund\": 107491758.0, \"pat_granted\": 3173.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 443.5, \"pub_doc\": 370.3, \"clinic_doc\": 60.7, \"grant_fund\": -16962097.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1a9c0dbeb98fbf3376ec2297db1b5d56','75926dafeed6c4c3d2dd27794c573c76','88cbe0424257da986f5d8f34f678784d','2023-09-08 00:55:46','2023-10-29 00:56:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Microencapsulation',24,'Microencapsulation is a process in which tiny particles or droplets are surrounded by a coating to give small capsules, with useful properties. In general, it is used to incorporate food ingredients, enzymes, cells or other materials on a micro metric scale. Microencapsulation can also be used to enclose solids, liquids, or gases inside a micrometric wall made of hard or soft soluble film, in order to reduce dosing frequency and prevent the degradation of pharmaceuticals. In its simplest form, a microcapsule is a small sphere comprising a near-uniform wall enclosing some material. The enclosed material in the microcapsule is referred to as the core, internal phase, or fill, whereas the wall is sometimes called a shell, coating, or membrane. Some materials like lipids and polymers, such as alginate, may be used as a mixture to trap the material of interest inside. Most microcapsules have pores with diameters between a few nanometers and a few micrometers.','{\"pat_doc\": 276.0, \"pub_alt\": 382.0, \"pub_doc\": 1502.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 46.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 8391920.0, \"pat_granted\": 90.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -18.0, \"pub_doc\": 33.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.4, \"grant_fund\": -2198383.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1a9c389dc75917bffa6f81c51fe1252c','5c2546ad4bcf61666dc6e1c3462112a1','63620f5d0220fdda22b46d43a342534f','2023-09-08 01:14:21','2023-10-29 00:26:20','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Phage Display',36,'Phage display is a laboratory technique for the study of proteinâ€“protein, proteinâ€“peptide, and proteinâ€“DNA interactions that uses bacteriophages to connect proteins with the genetic information that encodes them. In this technique, a gene encoding a protein of interest is inserted into a phage coat protein gene, causing the phage to \"display\" the protein on its outside while containing the gene for the protein on its inside, resulting in a connection between genotype and phenotype. These displaying phages can then be screened against other proteins, peptides or DNA sequences, in order to detect interaction between the displayed protein and those other molecules. In this way, large libraries of proteins can be screened and amplified in a process called in vitro selection, which is analogous to natural selection. The most common bacteriophages used in phage display are M13 and fd filamentous phage, though T4, T7, and Î» phage have also been used.','{\"pat_doc\": 571.0, \"pub_alt\": 1051.0, \"pub_doc\": 1435.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 153.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 57336459.0, \"pat_granted\": 216.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 23.5, \"pub_doc\": 24.6, \"clinic_doc\": -0.3, \"grant_fund\": -13328661.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1ab09d473a0743df8aa08da22841c886','c42efb8fe2ca41dc7fd5d4dbb0848ed6','7e6689dbdfabd5b7cf95a105e9764132','2023-09-08 09:27:09','2023-10-28 21:01:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Gas Chromatography',24,'Gas chromatography is a common type of chromatography used in analytical chemistry for separating and analyzing compounds that can be vaporized without decomposition. Typical uses of GC include testing the purity of a particular substance, or separating the different components of a mixture. In preparative chromatography, GC can be used to prepare pure compounds from a mixture. Gas chromatography is also sometimes known as vapor-phase chromatography, or gasâ€“liquid partition chromatography. These alternative names, as well as their respective abbreviations, are frequently used in scientific literature. Gas chromatography is the process of separating compounds in a mixture by injecting a gaseous or liquid sample into a mobile phase, typically called the carrier gas, and passing the gas through a stationary phase. The mobile phase is usually an inert gas or an unreactive gas such as helium, argon, nitrogen or hydrogen.','{\"pat_doc\": 2842.0, \"pub_alt\": 4917.0, \"pub_doc\": 17515.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 227.0, \"clinic_alt\": 100.0, \"clinic_doc\": 83.0, \"grant_fund\": 46625691.0, \"pat_granted\": 1186.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 67.1, \"pub_doc\": 279.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.9, \"grant_fund\": -2716027.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1ac41c2a7b295413f800c564fb9f4322','af4c9bfdfefe7c5c014015d91cb309a6','df80b2fb86114e734e7660ea92fdd1fc','2023-09-08 00:08:07','2023-10-29 02:01:16','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Viral Vectors',24,'Viral vectors are tools commonly used by molecular biologists to deliver genetic material into cells. This process can be performed inside a living organism or in cell culture. Viruses have evolved specialized molecular mechanisms to efficiently transport their genomes inside the cells they infect. Delivery of genes or other genetic material by a vector is termed transduction and the infected cells are described as transduced. Molecular biologists first harnessed this machinery in the 1970s. Paul Berg used a modified SV40 virus containing DNA from the bacteriophage Î» to infect monkey kidney cells maintained in culture. In addition to their use in molecular biology research, viral vectors are used for gene therapy and the development of vaccines. Vectors can either integrate into a cells genome or transiently express a gene with non-integrative vectors.','{\"pat_doc\": 1973.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 1922.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 243.0, \"clinic_alt\": 58.0, \"clinic_doc\": 26.0, \"grant_fund\": 196604219.0, \"pat_granted\": 287.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 84.9, \"pub_doc\": -18.6, \"clinic_doc\": 4.4, \"grant_fund\": -2376931.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1b152c6ff677e3e815a5ef2bea0f7003','32fc867764b2c2323b6074823f18f91d','e11ca4e4a12f409964c63840550b841e','2023-09-08 02:44:51','2023-10-28 21:41:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Editing',12,'mRNA editing is the process by which the genetic information contained within the messenger RNA (mRNA) transcript is modified by the insertion, deletion, or substitution of nucleotides. This process is critical for the accurate transmission of genetic information from DNA to protein synthesis, as it allows for the generation of multiple mRNA isoforms from a single gene. The molecular machinery involved in mRNA editing is complex and involves specific enzymes such as adenosine deaminase acting on RNA (ADAR), which catalyzes the conversion of adenosine to inosine in the mRNA sequence. This process has been found to play a key role in regulating gene expression and is implicated in a number of disease states, including cancer and neurological disorders. By modulating mRNA editing, researchers hope to develop new strategies for the treatment of these conditions.','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_alt\": 48.0, \"pub_doc\": 44.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 908461.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": -2.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -1088864.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1ba7fa3befc991efc83926c635387e7b','c66db8e5795eca3126bf573522e8cf4e','e77dece162a0133e50d5b2357c40719f','2023-09-05 22:56:00','2023-10-29 02:51:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','RNA interference',36,'RNA interference is a biological process in which RNA molecules are involved in sequence-specific suppression of gene expression by double-stranded RNA, through translational or transcriptional repression. Historically, RNAi was known by other names, including co-suppression, post-transcriptional gene silencing, and quelling. The detailed study of each of these seemingly different processes elucidated that the identity of these phenomena were all actually RNAi. Andrew Fire and Craig C. Mello shared the 2006 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their work on RNAi in the nematode worm Caenorhabditis elegans, which they published in 1998. Since the discovery of RNAi and its regulatory potentials, it has become evident that RNAi has immense potential in suppression of desired genes. RNAi is now known as precise, efficient, stable and better than antisense therapy for gene suppression.','{\"pat_doc\": 1125.0, \"pub_alt\": 991.0, \"pub_doc\": 5500.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 265.0, \"clinic_alt\": 18.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 82609887.0, \"pat_granted\": 344.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.6, \"pub_doc\": -43.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": -14470471.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1bbc9e921837f113b320c1d305c1c99c','e5cdaf0403574f617436eb3c34f77c60','3889385fdc1bbeadad2bf5c86cbbd89a','2023-09-08 00:29:50','2023-10-29 01:31:13','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Electrochemical Biosensor',12,'An electrochemical biosensor is a device that uses the principles of electrochemistry to detect the presence of biological molecules. These biosensors typically consist of two main components - a biological recognition element, such as an enzyme or antibody, and a transducer that converts the interaction between the biological molecule and the recognition element into an electrical signal. The transducer typically consists of a working electrode, a reference electrode, and a counter electrode, which allow the movement of electrons between the recognition element and the surface of the electrode. The resulting electrical signal can then be measured and correlated to the concentration of the biological molecule of interest. Electrochemical biosensors are widely used in medical diagnostics, environmental monitoring, and food safety testing due to their high sensitivity, specificity, and ease of use.','{\"pat_doc\": 220.0, \"pub_alt\": 618.0, \"pub_doc\": 1062.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 16.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 4510143.0, \"pat_granted\": 71.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.7, \"pub_doc\": 147.8, \"clinic_doc\": 1.1, \"grant_fund\": -552123.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1c0b9bd7de934584fc1251ca2585b0ab','fff9e1e5499bae01aa4fb0b484f21e1e','6a1c4a31986c97cfddf4de1bf91188d1','2023-09-05 21:08:55','2023-10-28 12:35:32','Electronics','Devices','Connectivity','Wearable devices',36,'Wearable technology is any technology that is designed to be used while worn. Common types of wearable technology include smartwatches and smartglasses. Wearable electronic devices are often close to or on the surface of the skin, where they detect, analyze, and transmit information such as vital signs, and/or ambient data and which allow in some cases immediate biofeedback to the wearer. Wearable devices such as activity trackers are an example of the Internet of Things, since \"things\" such as electronics, software, sensors, and connectivity are effectors that enable objects to exchange data through the internet with a manufacturer, operator, and/or other connected devices, without requiring human intervention. Wearable technology offers a wide range of possible uses, from communication and entertainment to improving health and fitness, however, there are worries about privacy and security because wearable devices have the ability to collect personal data.','{\"pat_doc\": 2341.0, \"pub_alt\": 4130.0, \"pub_doc\": 9593.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 468.0, \"clinic_alt\": 525.0, \"clinic_doc\": 294.0, \"grant_fund\": 241969574.0, \"pat_granted\": 843.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 43.4, \"pub_doc\": 482.3, \"clinic_doc\": 56.6, \"grant_fund\": 2342060.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1c1c5872802b5e078d34ae240d24aa9f','014a9a76a066045b2a9bf86aedfb7d7c','9b98ef926c70dcba53c5447a923e9d23','2023-09-08 02:30:56','2023-10-28 22:06:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Sequencing',24,'Protein sequencing is the practical process of determining the amino acid sequence of all or part of a protein or peptide. This may serve to identify the protein or characterize its post-translational modifications. Typically, partial sequencing of a protein provides sufficient information to identify it with reference to databases of protein sequences derived from the conceptual translation of genes. The two major direct methods of protein sequencing are mass spectrometry and Edman degradation using a protein sequenator. Mass spectrometry methods are now the most widely used for protein sequencing and identification but Edman degradation remains a valuable tool for characterizing a proteins N-terminus.','{\"pat_doc\": 84.0, \"pub_alt\": 424.0, \"pub_doc\": 161.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 38.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 19467011.0, \"pat_granted\": 16.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.9, \"pub_doc\": 7.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": 2760440.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1c1f3c41915d31b99463f70f5905141c','51aee0cb27f70c84f894c07b0faada65','05f0a405c035c7fc807679b69158e068','2023-09-07 23:36:05','2023-10-28 17:11:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy',24,'Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is a condition in which muscle tissues of the heart become thickened without an obvious cause. The parts of the heart most commonly affected are the interventricular septum and the ventricles. This results in the heart being less able to pump blood effectively and also may cause electrical conduction problems. People who have HCM may have a range of symptoms. People may be asymptomatic, or may have fatigue, leg swelling, and shortness of breath. It may also result in chest pain or fainting. Symptoms may be worse when the person is dehydrated. Complications may include heart failure, an irregular heartbeat, and sudden cardiac death. HCM is most commonly inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern. It is often due to mutations in certain genes involved with making heart muscle proteins. Other inherited causes of left ventricular hypertrophy may include Fabry disease, Friedreichs ataxia, and certain medications such as tacrolimus.','{\"pat_doc\": 187.0, \"pub_alt\": 668.0, \"pub_doc\": 3179.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 97.0, \"clinic_alt\": 83.0, \"clinic_doc\": 142.0, \"grant_fund\": 28616745.0, \"pat_granted\": 35.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.4, \"pub_doc\": 133.8, \"clinic_doc\": 28.7, \"grant_fund\": -3954781.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1c32411ca82f4b76a20b6008f35797ec','60518e711e4b43d56a5bbd7732ffd16e','9d4e5b197da5f47c35976f2bf01251b9','2023-09-05 22:10:54','2023-10-29 03:31:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Personal Protective Equipment',48,'Personal protective equipment is protective clothing, helmets, goggles, or other garments or equipment designed to protect the wearers body from injury or infection. The hazards addressed by protective equipment include physical, electrical, heat, chemicals, biohazards, and airborne particulate matter. Protective equipment may be worn for job-related occupational safety and health purposes, as well as for sports and other recreational activities. Protective clothing is applied to traditional categories of clothing, and protective gear applies to items such as pads, guards, shields, or masks, and others. PPE suits can be similar in appearance to a cleanroom suit. The purpose of personal protective equipment is to reduce employee exposure to hazards when engineering controls and administrative controls are not feasible or effective to reduce these risks to acceptable levels. PPE is needed when there are hazards present.','{\"pat_doc\": 1296.0, \"pub_alt\": 13115.0, \"pub_doc\": 13088.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 505.0, \"clinic_alt\": 200.0, \"clinic_doc\": 254.0, \"grant_fund\": 178864142.0, \"pat_granted\": 225.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.6, \"pub_doc\": -446.8, \"clinic_doc\": -1.4, \"grant_fund\": -24125078.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1c49cbe9a4435c47e251430fcdf2d1f8','66370bcc1950b8300adc5378b5a9db5b','2cf8a6770a22256c603cf40927d188ef','2023-09-08 02:16:56','2023-10-28 22:41:13','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Non-viral Vector',24,'Non-viral vectors are genetic tools that aid in gene therapy that lack the viral genome and carry foreign genetic material that can be transferred into the cells. Instead of using an infectious pathogen, non-viral vectors use liposomes, nanoparticles, and chemical conjugates. Because non-viral vectors lack the viral genome, they are less immunogenic and safer than viral vectors. Non-viral vectors also allow the transfer of larger amounts of genetic material, providing possible benefits over the viral vector for genetic therapy applications. In addition, the simple design of non-viral vectors allows more economic and scalable production. Despite their advantages, non-viral vectors have lower transduction rates in cells than viral vectors.','{\"pat_doc\": 161.0, \"pub_alt\": 325.0, \"pub_doc\": 221.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 14.0, \"clinic_alt\": 29.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 4627036.0, \"pat_granted\": 16.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.8, \"pub_doc\": 0.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -408385.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1c8bd3adfb39c48ec7414e37a97e13f5','ab4b6025c38d1cab8fd476593532cb60','8c907d5d7b60b5604cad502b2ab3ea5b','2023-09-08 01:44:40','2023-10-28 11:20:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Societal & Economic Disruptions','Russia-Ukraine conflict',12,'The Russo-Ukrainian War is an ongoing international conflict between Russia, alongside Russian-backed separatists, and Ukraine, which began in February 2014. Following Ukraines Revolution of Dignity, Russia annexed Crimea from Ukraine and supported pro-Russian separatists fighting the Ukrainian military in the Donbas war. The first eight years of conflict also included naval incidents, cyberwarfare, and heightened political tensions. In February 2022, Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine. In early 2014, the Euromaidan protests led to the Revolution of Dignity and the ousting of Ukraines pro-Russian president Viktor Yanukovych. Shortly after, pro-Russian unrest erupted in eastern and southern Ukraine. Simultaneously, unmarked Russian troops moved into Ukraines Crimea and took over government buildings, strategic sites and infrastructure. Russia soon annexed Crimea after a highly-disputed referendum.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 4755.0, \"pub_doc\": 284.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 300611.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 93.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 113103.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1c9f7b06337e8625973c06061dd93511','8b3e02763472ad9cc815cfa5df7888cc','451ebb4679c1ff141207f279192eb1c8','2023-09-08 02:50:01','2023-10-28 21:26:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Bio-inspired material',12,'Bio-inspired materials refer to a class of materials inspired by natural designs and architectures found in living systems. These materials incorporate features such as self-assembly, hierarchical structure, and dynamic responsiveness. The idea behind bio-inspired materials is to take inspiration from nature to create advanced materials that have unique and valuable properties not found in conventional materials. Examples of such materials include self-healing polymers, super-strong spider silk-mimicking fibers, and high-performance ceramics based on the structure of seashells. Bio-inspired materials have the potential to lead to the development of new technologies and applications in fields such as medicine, construction, and robotics.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 189.0, \"pub_doc\": 49.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 12718728.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 4.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4564736.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1cb705e46d4ed616a6d602a22dfdc007','41d7ff0d462e6a3d557069a37ea17023','9c4ba206250041cf1644bb291a643634','2023-09-05 18:58:16','2023-10-29 05:25:05','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Next-Generation Sequencing',48,'Massive parallel sequencing or massively parallel sequencing is any of several high-throughput approaches to DNA sequencing using the concept of massively parallel processing; it is also called next-generation sequencing or second-generation sequencing. Some of these technologies emerged between 1993 and 1998 and have been commercially available since 2005. These technologies use miniaturized and parallelized platforms for sequencing of 1 million to 43 billion short reads per instrument run. Many NGS platforms differ in engineering configurations and sequencing chemistry. They share the technical paradigm of massive parallel sequencing via spatially separated, clonally amplified DNA templates or single DNA molecules in a flow cell. This design is very different from that of Sanger sequencingâ€”also known as capillary sequencing or first-generation sequencingâ€”which is based on electrophoretic separation of chain-termination products produced in individual sequencing reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 543.0, \"pub_alt\": 14265.0, \"pub_doc\": 26405.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1198.0, \"clinic_alt\": 77.0, \"clinic_doc\": 436.0, \"grant_fund\": 400868839.0, \"pat_granted\": 126.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.9, \"pub_doc\": 170.9, \"clinic_doc\": 72.6, \"grant_fund\": -38192044.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1ced2547bce485c12e8ce501fb690714','2ef204f64673ee0cc4682daa8faf26bb','767ea62d04e7021f7b0e5dec58a48a8d','2023-09-08 10:56:51','2023-10-28 18:56:11','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Personalized Medicine',12,'Personalized medicine, also referred to as precision medicine, is a medical model that separates people into different groupsâ€”with medical decisions, practices, interventions and/or products being tailored to the individual patient based on their predicted response or risk of disease. The terms personalized medicine, precision medicine, stratified medicine and P4 medicine are used interchangeably to describe this concept though some authors and organisations use these expressions separately to indicate particular nuances. While the tailoring of treatment to patients dates back at least to the time of Hippocrates, the term has risen in usage in recent years given the growth of new diagnostic and informatics approaches that provide understanding of the molecular basis of disease, particularly genomics. This provides a clear evidence base on which to stratify related patients.','{\"pat_doc\": 140.0, \"pub_alt\": 608.0, \"pub_doc\": 2547.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 213.0, \"clinic_alt\": 592.0, \"clinic_doc\": 231.0, \"grant_fund\": 134957089.0, \"pat_granted\": 38.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.4, \"pub_doc\": 162.7, \"clinic_doc\": 61.2, \"grant_fund\": -59753219.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1cf0280a0f1c8a4ba80e717e41397171','917192d39f4afc517e0a5df9df580afd','e5dc1ab9b95fd144580ba449bdb1f286','2023-09-05 20:46:53','2023-10-29 04:25:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','CRISPR-Cas9',12,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 275.0, \"pub_alt\": 993.0, \"pub_doc\": 1861.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 177.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 17.0, \"grant_fund\": 72055014.0, \"pat_granted\": 92.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.6, \"pub_doc\": 115.9, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -29971557.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1d468cde265a6eb6ea91b061f5f792b7','671b6a0797f6c4055d3d1b7f83353201','45aa22dbd0eeecd7a8f404b4dd4dc2cc','2023-09-08 02:41:52','2023-10-28 21:51:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Containment System',24,'A containment system is a structure or mechanism designed to isolate or control the spread of something potentially dangerous, such as disease, hazardous materials, or other substances. These systems come in various forms and sizes, depending on the nature of the threat and the environment they are used in. Examples can include sealed chambers, biosecurity measures, containment suits, or even something as simple as plastic barriers. The main goal of a containment system is to prevent the spread of the harmful agent to other areas or individuals, reducing the risk of harm and containing the situation until it can be properly addressed. They are particularly important in settings like laboratories, medical facilities, and industrial sites where potentially harmful materials or organisms may be present.','{\"pat_doc\": 592.0, \"pub_alt\": 26.0, \"pub_doc\": 144.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 1218552.0, \"pat_granted\": 243.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -9.9, \"pub_doc\": 1.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.5, \"grant_fund\": -3150370.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1d7eb16329453b4dcceee49809d18e57','8cc017d911f60e86f3530c8efab7f91a','7cfcc2197e33173ce522354c4a1177f6','2023-09-07 23:46:10','2023-10-29 02:31:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Green Hydrogen',24,'Green hydrogen is hydrogen generated from either renewable energy or low-carbon power. Green hydrogen has significantly lower carbon emissions than grey hydrogen, which is derived from fossil fuels without carbon capture. Green hydrogen may be used to decarbonize sectors that are hard to electrify, such as cement and iron production. Green hydrogen can be used to produce green ammonia, the main constituent of synthetic fertilizer. It can also be used for long-duration grid energy storage, and for long-duration seasonal energy storage. As of 2021, green hydrogen accounted for less than 0.04% of total hydrogen production. Its cost relative to hydrogen derived from fossil fuels is the main reason green hydrogen is in less demand.','{\"pat_doc\": 277.0, \"pub_alt\": 768.0, \"pub_doc\": 3035.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 418.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 465197755.0, \"pat_granted\": 73.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 63.1, \"pub_doc\": 594.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 22939710.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1d8c903e3a28ecf808ad5fbe88e7d431','0130bb7e16467c607ae66d5d6b5fe5d1','69904542b990c5c24086b0dfa8c698cf','2023-09-05 22:51:40','2023-10-29 03:01:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','High-Throughput Screening',24,'High-throughput screening is a method for scientific experimentation especially used in drug discovery and relevant to the fields of biology, materials science and chemistry. Using robotics, data processing/control software, liquid handling devices, and sensitive detectors, high-throughput screening allows a researcher to quickly conduct millions of chemical, genetic, or pharmacological tests. Through this process one can quickly recognize active compounds, antibodies, or genes that modulate a particular biomolecular pathway. The results of these experiments provide starting points for drug design and for understanding the noninteraction or role of a particular location.','{\"pat_doc\": 611.0, \"pub_alt\": 447.0, \"pub_doc\": 2933.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 280.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 11.0, \"grant_fund\": 263917207.0, \"pat_granted\": 196.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.8, \"pub_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -83628586.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1d91f230b1250357db1edb7cdc378cad','d006191764fe7b11e9181190cc8abcbe','5f9f631521aff2090e15184e37181d22','2023-09-04 19:03:56','2023-10-29 06:16:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Immunohistochemistry',24,'Immunohistochemistry is the most common application of immunostaining. It involves the process of selectively identifying antigens in cells of a tissue section by exploiting the principle of antibodies binding specifically to antigens in biological tissues. IHC takes its name from the roots \"immuno\", in reference to antibodies used in the procedure, and \"histo\", meaning tissue. Albert Coons conceptualized and first implemented the procedure in 1941. Visualising an antibody-antigen interaction can be accomplished in a number of ways, mainly either of the following: â€¢ Chromogenic immunohistochemistry, wherein an antibody is conjugated to an enzyme, such as peroxidase, that can catalyse a colour-producing reaction. â€¢ Immunofluorescence, where the antibody is tagged to a fluorophore, such as fluorescein or rhodamine. Immunohistochemical staining is widely used in the diagnosis of abnormal cells such as those found in cancerous tumors.','{\"pat_doc\": 379.0, \"pub_alt\": 28733.0, \"pub_doc\": 30861.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 650.0, \"clinic_alt\": 553.0, \"clinic_doc\": 653.0, \"grant_fund\": 173900871.0, \"pat_granted\": 127.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.1, \"pub_doc\": -408.2, \"clinic_doc\": 134.5, \"grant_fund\": -28858320.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1ddcd0dd330095062edc9e1de2bcf2ee','01807d836d93ed1511a8b58c90b6d398','3fcb9a9c61a418e177e61e3951321f26','2023-09-08 02:15:42','2023-10-28 22:46:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Controlled-release system',12,'A controlled-release system is a technology used in drug delivery, agriculture and other fields to release active ingredients evenly over a period of time. It involves encapsulating the active ingredient in a matrix that controls its release rate. This can increase the effectiveness of the ingredient and reduce the frequency of application. In drug delivery, it can improve patient compliance, reduce side effects and increase efficacy. In agriculture, it can reduce waste and environmental impact. Controlled-release systems can be designed using a variety of materials, including polymers, liposomes and mesoporous materials. They are an important tool in modern science and technology, with numerous applications in various industries.','{\"pat_doc\": 9.0, \"pub_alt\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": 26.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -135275.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1e08113f47913b06e5d2a9dec7652469','848c570f631dc66b6c71249b5532b80c','f53620dbd4935249cccf6fdb7d35b8cf','2023-09-04 19:36:20','2023-10-29 05:56:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Immunofluorescence',12,'Immunofluorescence is a technique used for light microscopy with a fluorescence microscope and is used primarily on biological samples. This technique uses the specificity of antibodies to their antigen to target fluorescent dyes to specific biomolecule targets within a cell, and therefore allows visualization of the distribution of the target molecule through the sample. The specific region an antibody recognizes on an antigen is called an epitope. There have been efforts in epitope mapping since many antibodies can bind the same epitope and levels of binding between antibodies that recognize the same epitope can vary. Additionally, the binding of the fluorophore to the antibody itself cannot interfere with the immunological specificity of the antibody or the binding capacity of its antigen. Immunofluorescence is a widely used example of immunostaining and is a specific example of immunohistochemistry.','{\"pat_doc\": 408.0, \"pub_alt\": 1409.0, \"pub_doc\": 10699.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 188.0, \"clinic_alt\": 392.0, \"clinic_doc\": 95.0, \"grant_fund\": 45533778.0, \"pat_granted\": 148.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 29.2, \"pub_doc\": 619.2, \"clinic_doc\": 22.2, \"grant_fund\": -6312911.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1e87fcf7dde4a7524a02249dcfc79d93','e73131830356703a23b1a11a711e48c5','e4f81d8ac891f1e1dbdd2332eaaa8fed','2023-09-05 22:16:53','2023-10-29 03:21:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Magnetic nanoparticles',36,'Magnetic nanoparticles are a class of nanoparticle that can be manipulated using magnetic fields. Such particles commonly consist of two components, a magnetic material, often iron, nickel and cobalt, and a chemical component that has functionality. While nanoparticles are smaller than 1 micrometer in diameter, the larger microbeads are 0.5â€“500 micrometer in diameter. Magnetic nanoparticle clusters that are composed of a number of individual magnetic nanoparticles are known as magnetic nanobeads with a diameter of 50â€“200 nanometers. Magnetic nanoparticle clusters are a basis for their further magnetic assembly into magnetic nanochains.','{\"pat_doc\": 1739.0, \"pub_alt\": 521.0, \"pub_doc\": 7108.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 249.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": 61910541.0, \"pat_granted\": 568.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -8.6, \"pub_doc\": -35.6, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -2481846.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1eace13327f03335b7fb49ff6af9cb68','b2cee85dff870540c318cdc9d046cdcd','c3c3761ddee3a08a11545145a56cc763','2023-09-05 21:43:53','2023-10-29 03:56:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Co-culture',12,'Co-culture refers to the interaction and exchange between two or more distinct cultures. This can occur through direct contact or through mediated channels, such as media or trade. The concept of co-culture recognizes that cultures do not exist in isolation but are rather constantly interacting and influencing one another. It is important to understand co-culture in order to appreciate cultural diversity and to build bridges between cultures. Co-culture can lead to cultural fusion, which is the blending of elements from different cultures to create a new, hybrid culture. This can be seen in the arts, cuisine, and fashion, among other areas. However, co-culture can also lead to conflict and tension, particularly when different cultures have contrasting beliefs or values. By recognizing the role of co-culture, individuals and societies can foster greater understanding and appreciation for diverse cultural perspectives.','{\"pat_doc\": 612.0, \"pub_alt\": 686.0, \"pub_doc\": 4289.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 266.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 51.0, \"grant_fund\": 99281033.0, \"pat_granted\": 222.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 54.4, \"pub_doc\": 183.5, \"clinic_doc\": 11.2, \"grant_fund\": -35120452.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1f01630c9e2c38c751afa166a157deb0','00deab06d5e60c8c68a35ce17a92c7a4','9910e15122e1c94e1e5ae9068add6ff3','2023-09-05 22:04:15','2023-10-29 03:41:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Genome Editing',24,'Genome editing, or genome engineering, or gene editing, is a type of genetic engineering in which DNA is inserted, deleted, modified or replaced in the genome of a living organism. Unlike early genetic engineering techniques that randomly inserts genetic material into a host genome, genome editing targets the insertions to site-specific locations. The basic mechanism involved in genetic manipulations through programmable nucleases is the recognition of target genomic loci and binding of effector DNA-binding domain, double-strand breaks in target DNA by the restriction endonucleases, and the repair of DSBs through homology-directed recombination or non-homologous end joining.','{\"pat_doc\": 1602.0, \"pub_alt\": 3578.0, \"pub_doc\": 5351.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 750.0, \"clinic_alt\": 54.0, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": 492410827.0, \"pat_granted\": 345.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 18.2, \"pub_doc\": 106.1, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -34230182.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1f01b2465eb1ffd07482b2108d284237','09e9ed6148f2e431ca17ead10dda844b','23bce1931f776364d9203491f1d59304','2023-09-05 22:01:13','2023-10-29 03:46:15','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Spectrophotometry',36,'Spectrophotometry is a branch of electromagnetic spectroscopy concerned with the quantitative measurement of the reflection or transmission properties of a material as a function of wavelength. Spectrophotometry uses photometers, known as spectrophotometers, that can measure the intensity of a light beam at different wavelengths. Although spectrophotometry is most commonly applied to ultraviolet, visible, and infrared radiation, modern spectrophotometers can interrogate wide swaths of the electromagnetic spectrum, including x-ray, ultraviolet, visible, infrared, and/or microwave wavelengths.','{\"pat_doc\": 812.0, \"pub_alt\": 835.0, \"pub_doc\": 8734.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 136.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 35.0, \"grant_fund\": 12532716.0, \"pat_granted\": 290.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.5, \"pub_doc\": 60.9, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": -1805233.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1f0556c0b5aff46487ea54cce80a0fed','eb2ca5cdbf466432efa3cad3dd594f1a','6725d42f932d0e446e761f0968e0172f','2023-09-08 02:04:06','2023-10-28 23:16:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','Cell Characterization',36,'Cell Characterization is the process of understanding the physical, chemical, and biological properties of a specific type of cell. It involves analyzing various aspects of the cell, such as morphology, size, and structure, as well as its function and behavior. Through this process, scientists can gain a deeper understanding of how cells function, how they interact with other cells, and how they respond to different environments or stimuli. Cell Characterization is an essential tool for researchers and scientists in a variety of fields, including cell biology, genetics, and immunology, as it allows for the development of new treatments and therapies for diseases and the discovery of new biological mechanisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 43.0, \"pub_alt\": 496.0, \"pub_doc\": 400.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 47.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 32635934.0, \"pat_granted\": 10.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 13.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -513209.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('1ff2304c9f586c36c5b7bac1003c0ae2','b2cee85dff870540c318cdc9d046cdcd','c3c3761ddee3a08a11545145a56cc763','2023-09-05 21:43:53','2023-10-29 03:56:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Co-culture',48,'Co-culture refers to the interaction and exchange between two or more distinct cultures. This can occur through direct contact or through mediated channels, such as media or trade. The concept of co-culture recognizes that cultures do not exist in isolation but are rather constantly interacting and influencing one another. It is important to understand co-culture in order to appreciate cultural diversity and to build bridges between cultures. Co-culture can lead to cultural fusion, which is the blending of elements from different cultures to create a new, hybrid culture. This can be seen in the arts, cuisine, and fashion, among other areas. However, co-culture can also lea