 state of higher energy. In the case of a semiconducting quantum dot, this process corresponds to the transition of an electron from the valence band to the conductance band. The excited electron can drop back into the valence band releasing its energy as light. This light emission is illustrated in the figure on the right.','{\"pat_doc\": 17443.0, \"pub_alt\": 568.0, \"pub_doc\": 24565.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 771.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 325100705.0, \"pat_granted\": 6755.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 59.8, \"pub_doc\": 330.7, \"clinic_doc\": 1.1, \"grant_fund\": -9612731.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('212b7326c941be228dbc98c4c2acd00a','4b77f13801e06ca4a3d587ee4f09a407','574dc8bedf464bfa6dcd368851dbebf9','2023-09-05 21:16:27','2023-10-29 04:06:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Transfection',48,'Transfection is the process of deliberately introducing naked or purified nucleic acids into eukaryotic cells. It may also refer to other methods and cell types, although other terms are often preferred: \"transformation\" is typically used to describe non-viral DNA transfer in bacteria and non-animal eukaryotic cells, including plant cells. In animal cells, transfection is the preferred term as transformation is also used to refer to progression to a cancerous state in these cells. Transduction is often used to describe virus-mediated gene transfer into eukaryotic cells. The word transfection is a portmanteau of trans- and infection. Genetic material, may be transfected. Transfection of animal cells typically involves opening transient pores or \"holes\" in the cell membrane to allow the uptake of material.','{\"pat_doc\": 3436.0, \"pub_alt\": 6193.0, \"pub_doc\": 17190.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 566.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1577.0, \"clinic_doc\": 35.0, \"grant_fund\": 174189697.0, \"pat_granted\": 1008.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 70.6, \"pub_doc\": -483.2, \"clinic_doc\": 6.1, \"grant_fund\": -22113358.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('21f94ada479426773a202f3ab0cfd984','4b77f13801e06ca4a3d587ee4f09a407','574dc8bedf464bfa6dcd368851dbebf9','2023-09-05 21:16:27','2023-10-29 04:06:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Transfection',36,'Transfection is the process of deliberately introducing naked or purified nucleic acids into eukaryotic cells. It may also refer to other methods and cell types, although other terms are often preferred: \"transformation\" is typically used to describe non-viral DNA transfer in bacteria and non-animal eukaryotic cells, including plant cells. In animal cells, transfection is the preferred term as transformation is also used to refer to progression to a cancerous state in these cells. Transduction is often used to describe virus-mediated gene transfer into eukaryotic cells. The word transfection is a portmanteau of trans- and infection. Genetic material, may be transfected. Transfection of animal cells typically involves opening transient pores or \"holes\" in the cell membrane to allow the uptake of material.','{\"pat_doc\": 2683.0, \"pub_alt\": 6193.0, \"pub_doc\": 12242.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 363.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1577.0, \"clinic_doc\": 33.0, \"grant_fund\": 91160573.0, \"pat_granted\": 786.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 70.6, \"pub_doc\": -483.2, \"clinic_doc\": 6.1, \"grant_fund\": -22113358.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('22017c74b1cacd607102cec5c510a55b','0bc5e22ada5efec34101dcd4f634e7a2','e77dece162a0133e50d5b2357c40719f','2023-09-05 22:55:17','2023-10-29 02:55:05','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','RNA interference',12,'RNA interference is a biological process in which RNA molecules are involved in sequence-specific suppression of gene expression by double-stranded RNA, through translational or transcriptional repression. Historically, RNAi was known by other names, including co-suppression, post-transcriptional gene silencing, and quelling. The detailed study of each of these seemingly different processes elucidated that the identity of these phenomena were all actually RNAi. Andrew Fire and Craig C. Mello shared the 2006 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their work on RNAi in the nematode worm Caenorhabditis elegans, which they published in 1998. Since the discovery of RNAi and its regulatory potentials, it has become evident that RNAi has immense potential in suppression of desired genes. RNAi is now known as precise, efficient, stable and better than antisense therapy for gene suppression.','{\"pat_doc\": 362.0, \"pub_alt\": 991.0, \"pub_doc\": 1684.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 53.0, \"clinic_alt\": 18.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 11697587.0, \"pat_granted\": 103.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.6, \"pub_doc\": -43.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": -14470471.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('220b6aab3ee654d889220514d9cdb62f','989e334c32437caa317127b884df7c33','704edc6299a6c2e6515a45403d655e47','2023-09-08 02:32:40','2023-10-28 10:55:31','Electronics','Components','Interface & Display Devices','MicroLED',12,'MicroLED is an emerging display technology that is similar to traditional LED displays, but with much smaller individual LEDs, or \"micro LEDs.\" The small size of these LEDs allows for higher resolution displays with better contrast and brightness compared to other types of displays like LCD or OLED. MicroLED is also more energy-efficient and can provide longer lifetimes than other technologies. While MicroLED displays have been around for a few years, they are still in the early stages of development with only a few consumer products in the market. However, it is expected that the technology will become more widely adopted in the coming years due to its many advantages over other display technologies.','{\"pat_doc\": 194.0, \"pub_alt\": 235.0, \"pub_doc\": 99.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2613166.0, \"pat_granted\": 37.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 39.8, \"pub_doc\": 12.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 656986.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('220ddbf5748450ed98c7f261e7407600','32fc867764b2c2323b6074823f18f91d','e11ca4e4a12f409964c63840550b841e','2023-09-08 02:44:51','2023-10-28 21:41:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Editing',24,'mRNA editing is the process by which the genetic information contained within the messenger RNA (mRNA) transcript is modified by the insertion, deletion, or substitution of nucleotides. This process is critical for the accurate transmission of genetic information from DNA to protein synthesis, as it allows for the generation of multiple mRNA isoforms from a single gene. The molecular machinery involved in mRNA editing is complex and involves specific enzymes such as adenosine deaminase acting on RNA (ADAR), which catalyzes the conversion of adenosine to inosine in the mRNA sequence. This process has been found to play a key role in regulating gene expression and is implicated in a number of disease states, including cancer and neurological disorders. By modulating mRNA editing, researchers hope to develop new strategies for the treatment of these conditions.','{\"pat_doc\": 9.0, \"pub_alt\": 274.0, \"pub_doc\": 92.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 3862640.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": -2.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -1088864.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('22949c90614ce808fe89f5e3469ebfe4','b7fe7c9d15ecc10608a0a70e65bacf5e','1c1aa7729e1e2fdd7a421fd9a7014e0a','2023-09-05 19:45:22','2023-10-28 12:50:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Augmented reality',48,'Augmented reality is an interactive experience that combines the real world and computer-generated content. The content can span multiple sensory modalities, including visual, auditory, haptic, somatosensory and olfactory. AR can be defined as a system that incorporates three basic features: a combination of real and virtual worlds, real-time interaction, and accurate 3D registration of virtual and real objects. The overlaid sensory information can be constructive, or destructive. This experience is seamlessly interwoven with the physical world such that it is perceived as an immersive aspect of the real environment. In this way, augmented reality alters ones ongoing perception of a real-world environment, whereas virtual reality completely replaces the users real-world environment with a simulated one. Augmented reality is largely synonymous with mixed reality. There is also overlap in terminology with extended reality and computer-mediated reality.','{\"pat_doc\": 29999.0, \"pub_alt\": 603.0, \"pub_doc\": 25196.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1891.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 226.0, \"grant_fund\": 844389937.0, \"pat_granted\": 9698.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 480.5, \"pub_doc\": 671.6, \"clinic_doc\": 35.2, \"grant_fund\": -13626091.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('22ba68c65a8e34e00b3e89d3a5bc6fe7','593e0b5980cd1f5c381a759416640c82','fac8fdaee075a0078ef0f1af1e190a56','2023-09-08 02:54:38','2023-10-28 10:40:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Neuromorphic Photonics',24,'Neuromorphic photonics is an area of research that seeks to combine the principles of neuroscience and photonics, a field of study that deals with light and its properties. Scientists working in the field aim to create artificial systems that can process information in a way that mimics the human brain, using light instead of electrical signals. By doing this, they hope to create more efficient and powerful computing systems that can tackle complex tasks such as image recognition and natural language processing with ease. Neuromorphic photonics is still in the early stages of development, but it has the potential to revolutionize the field of artificial intelligence and lead to a new generation of smart machines.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 63.0, \"pub_doc\": 50.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 25356.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -51400.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('22bf342f477639384b2f652cba1f4e60','090feb32dfbba21cb999b8efda702d3f','2774276ce5bfae5027508a164fb2fcb7','2023-09-08 02:36:18','2023-10-28 22:01:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Gene delivery vector',12,'A gene delivery vector is a vehicle used to transfer genetic material into cells. These vectors are commonly used in gene therapy and biotechnology applications to alter the expression of genes in cells. The most commonly used gene delivery vectors are viruses, which can infect cells and insert genetic material into the host cells genome. Retroviruses, adenoviruses, and adeno-associated viruses are some examples of viral vectors. Non-viral vectors, such as liposomes and naked DNA, can also be used to deliver genes, but are generally less efficient than viral vectors. Gene delivery vectors have immense potential in the treatment of genetic disorders, cancer, and other diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 30.0, \"pub_alt\": 363.0, \"pub_doc\": 64.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 12.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 1059595.0, \"pat_granted\": 7.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 5.7, \"pub_doc\": -4.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -650737.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2380dba546d5ccef49b12352909002fd','665bbf50f9c0e74f93301c0a8c98acec','f7f9ce80272ab55a46f45831f319f87c','2023-09-08 10:01:20','2023-10-28 19:26:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Turbidimetry',36,'Turbidimetry is the process of measuring the loss of intensity of transmitted light due to the scattering effect of particles suspended in it. Light is passed through a filter creating a light of known wavelength which is then passed through a cuvette containing a solution. A photoelectric cell collects the light which passes through the cuvette. A measurement is then given for the amount of absorbed light. Turbidimetry can be used in biology to find the number of cells in a solution. Turbidity-is an expression of optical look of a solution caused by radiation to the scattered and absorbed wavelength. Scattering of light is elastic so both incident and scattered radiation have same wavelength. A turbidometer measures the amount of radiation that passes through a fluid in forward direction,analogous to absorption spectrphotoometry.','{\"pat_doc\": 283.0, \"pub_alt\": 52.0, \"pub_doc\": 530.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 205867.0, \"pat_granted\": 85.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -10.5, \"pub_doc\": -8.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": -47175.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('23f22c5d6db369a206a7a56447f571b4','a50b8ea9f2c997ee8ae5e1323c17ab97','8ff2c0d27eb80a1a00a05bdcbea821c2','2023-09-08 02:07:31','2023-10-28 14:46:14','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Achondroplasia',48,'Achondroplasia is a genetic disorder with an autosomal dominant pattern of inheritance whose primary feature is dwarfism. In those with the condition, the arms and legs are short, while the torso is typically of normal length. Those affected have an average adult height of 131 centimetres for males and 123 centimetres for females. Other features can include an enlarged head and prominent forehead. Complications can include sleep apnea or recurrent ear infections. Achondroplasia includes short-limb skeletal dysplasia with severe combined immunodeficiency. Achondroplasia is caused by a mutation in the fibroblast growth factor receptor 3 gene that results in its protein being overactive. Achondroplasia results in impaired endochondral bone growth. The disorder has an autosomal dominant mode of inheritance, meaning only one mutated copy of the gene is required for the condition to occur.','{\"pat_doc\": 81.0, \"pub_alt\": 311.0, \"pub_doc\": 581.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 20.0, \"clinic_alt\": 125.0, \"clinic_doc\": 48.0, \"grant_fund\": 9418393.0, \"pat_granted\": 19.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.9, \"pub_doc\": 10.3, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": -1057396.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('242dcd2b569a0dc6ce50187260e76f6a','116c9f3326973bf53316f607199f9944','09c8640e20ae09de463871c1529a6589','2023-09-05 22:07:59','2023-10-29 03:36:14','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Fluorescence Microscopy',36,'A fluorescence microscope is an optical microscope that uses fluorescence instead of, or in addition to, scattering, reflection, and attenuation or absorption, to study the properties of organic or inorganic substances. \"Fluorescence microscope\" refers to any microscope that uses fluorescence to generate an image, whether it is a simple set up like an epifluorescence microscope or a more complicated design such as a confocal microscope, which uses optical sectioning to get better resolution of the fluorescence image.','{\"pat_doc\": 361.0, \"pub_alt\": 2153.0, \"pub_doc\": 9175.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 847.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 26.0, \"grant_fund\": 322094336.0, \"pat_granted\": 114.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.7, \"pub_doc\": -63.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.8, \"grant_fund\": -17544989.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2463fa7c70383a7d48392aa029b94d6b','30f5159f16b7a113dcbf47772afc4c96','0a44fd511d173aa7606e2fa180b97dbd','2023-09-08 02:14:34','2023-10-28 22:51:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Gene Circuits',24,'A gene circuit is a network of genes that work together to produce a certain outcome, such as the regulation of a specific biological process. These circuits function through gene expression, in which certain genes are turned on or off in response to environmental stimuli or cellular signals. The composition of the gene circuit can vary depending on the desired outcome, with different genes and regulatory elements influencing the behavior of the circuit. Gene circuits are important for understanding the complex processes that occur within cells and organisms, and have potential applications in fields such as synthetic biology and gene therapy.','{\"pat_doc\": 9.0, \"pub_alt\": 686.0, \"pub_doc\": 186.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 33.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 21845054.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 6.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2080968.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('24af6ebcbead1debcb0b76d8b5e9fbe6','f1df325e8a923b7c94ec1f46acdb203e','67ae7824162271af981ae2c6a606ee4e','2023-09-05 22:59:40','2023-10-28 12:00:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Memristor',48,'A memristor is a non-linear two-terminal electrical component relating electric charge and magnetic flux linkage. It was described and named in 1971 by Leon Chua, completing a theoretical quartet of fundamental electrical components which comprises also the resistor, capacitor and inductor. Chua and Kang later generalized the concept to memristive systems. Such a system comprises a circuit, of multiple conventional components, which mimics key properties of the ideal memristor component and is also commonly referred to as a memristor. Several such memristor system technologies have been developed, notably ReRAM. The identification of memristive properties in electronic devices has attracted controversy. Experimentally, the ideal memristor has yet to be demonstrated.','{\"pat_doc\": 2389.0, \"pub_alt\": 682.0, \"pub_doc\": 6532.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 201.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 81182825.0, \"pat_granted\": 788.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 108.5, \"pub_doc\": 242.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2583132.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('24b6712d65e4f349f2b9732b403b8ce0','3cd9bdd88ba7ae8b9d89cbab89c2b25b','461ca981d4ebaba8ec09f7fd419f33b2','2023-09-08 01:09:47','2023-10-29 00:36:23','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Solid dispersion',36,'Solid dispersion is a technique used in the pharmaceutical industry to improve the solubility and bioavailability of poorly water-soluble drugs. It involves the preparation of a solid mixture of a drug with a hydrophilic carrier, such as a polymer or a surfactant, where the drug is dispersed in a molecularly or colloidal form in the carrier matrix. The resulting system exhibits an increased surface area of the drug particles and facilitates the formation of supersaturated solutions upon dissolution in aqueous media, leading to enhanced drug absorption and better therapeutic efficacy. Solid dispersion offers several advantages over traditional formulations, including reduced drug doses, improved patient compliance, and lowered production costs. Despite its potential benefits, the design and optimization of solid dispersions require careful consideration of various factors, such as drug-carrier interactions, drug loading, and stability.','{\"pat_doc\": 1844.0, \"pub_alt\": 347.0, \"pub_doc\": 1591.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 21.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.0, \"grant_fund\": 2165932.0, \"pat_granted\": 453.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 29.1, \"pub_doc\": 19.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.9, \"grant_fund\": -1206355.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('251532daccf34d6f38739854013c5442','e5cdaf0403574f617436eb3c34f77c60','3889385fdc1bbeadad2bf5c86cbbd89a','2023-09-08 00:29:50','2023-10-29 01:31:13','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Electrochemical Biosensor',24,'An electrochemical biosensor is a device that uses the principles of electrochemistry to detect the presence of biological molecules. These biosensors typically consist of two main components - a biological recognition element, such as an enzyme or antibody, and a transducer that converts the interaction between the biological molecule and the recognition element into an electrical signal. The transducer typically consists of a working electrode, a reference electrode, and a counter electrode, which allow the movement of electrons between the recognition element and the surface of the electrode. The resulting electrical signal can then be measured and correlated to the concentration of the biological molecule of interest. Electrochemical biosensors are widely used in medical diagnostics, environmental monitoring, and food safety testing due to their high sensitivity, specificity, and ease of use.','{\"pat_doc\": 438.0, \"pub_alt\": 618.0, \"pub_doc\": 2035.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 50.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 7499823.0, \"pat_granted\": 148.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.7, \"pub_doc\": 147.8, \"clinic_doc\": 1.1, \"grant_fund\": -552123.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('251f865618717cc1d74fe222c0048246','3e296fb8632883059f895163006d1ec4','47c2be7d4757b7a89106ea7e007a13dc','2023-09-08 00:02:21','2023-10-29 02:11:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Fluorescence In Situ Hybridization',12,'Fluorescence in situ hybridization is a molecular cytogenetic technique that uses fluorescent probes that bind to only particular parts of a nucleic acid sequence with a high degree of sequence complementarity. It was developed by biomedical researchers in the early 1980s to detect and localize the presence or absence of specific DNA sequences on chromosomes. Fluorescence microscopy can be used to find out where the fluorescent probe is bound to the chromosomes. FISH is often used for finding specific features in DNA for use in genetic counseling, medicine, and species identification. FISH can also be used to detect and localize specific RNA targets in cells, circulating tumor cells, and tissue samples. In this context, it can help define the spatial-temporal patterns of gene expression within cells and tissues.','{\"pat_doc\": 65.0, \"pub_alt\": 217.0, \"pub_doc\": 1262.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 28.0, \"clinic_alt\": 50.0, \"clinic_doc\": 57.0, \"grant_fund\": 14858951.0, \"pat_granted\": 19.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.1, \"pub_doc\": -35.6, \"clinic_doc\": 12.4, \"grant_fund\": -136298.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2626da6032ed7e27fb34cd078d495239','2b6a132222106ddec0310c5473271c19','d16e559190b993e5f50fdc62d46eec9a','2023-09-08 09:58:57','2023-10-28 19:36:10','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Modification',48,'mRNA modification is a process that occurs after transcription but before translation. It refers to the chemical modifications of messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules in order to regulate their stability, localization, and translation efficiency. The most common type of mRNA modification is the addition of a 5â€™ cap, a modified guanine nucleotide, to the 5â€™ end of the mRNA molecule. This cap protects the mRNA from degradation and facilitates its translation. Another important mRNA modification is the addition of a poly(A) tail, a string of adenine nucleotides, to the 3â€™ end of the mRNA molecule. This tail also stabilizes the mRNA and enhances its translation. Other types of mRNA modifications include splicing, editing, and methylation, which can affect the sequence, structure, and function of the mRNA molecule. mRNA modification plays a critical role in gene expression regulation and is essential for cellular processes such as development, differentiation, and adaptation to environmental changes.','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_alt\": 251.0, \"pub_doc\": 503.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 65.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 44582418.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 16.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -6725984.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('262f9a11d277b8b0e86316fbdc708334','de3c47ca09e78512850cba5b26eb1590','85e7d38a1e770cd1c8c35e8a00e24e8d','2023-09-05 23:12:11','2023-10-29 02:46:12','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','X-ray Crystallography',12,'X-ray crystallography is the experimental science determining the atomic and molecular structure of a crystal, in which the crystalline structure causes a beam of incident X-rays to diffract into many specific directions. By measuring the angles and intensities of these diffracted beams, a crystallographer can produce a three-dimensional picture of the density of electrons within the crystal. From this electron density, the mean positions of the atoms in the crystal can be determined, as well as their chemical bonds, their crystallographic disorder, and various other information. Since many materials can form crystalsâ€”such as salts, metals, minerals, semiconductors, as well as various inorganic, organic, and biological moleculesâ€”X-ray crystallography has been fundamental in the development of many scientific fields.','{\"pat_doc\": 30.0, \"pub_alt\": 356.0, \"pub_doc\": 1596.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 112.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 165227273.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.7, \"pub_doc\": -59.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -3454168.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2642d14954a940e42ec35fe10d092b1e','7817ed2cad0c9306c26e32a11da07b14','191b41c4706125327318783808a1e02d','2023-09-07 23:52:24','2023-10-28 17:01:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Bioconjugates','Antibody Drug Conjugates',24,'Antibody-drug conjugates or ADCs are a class of biopharmaceutical drugs designed as a targeted therapy for treating cancer. Unlike chemotherapy, ADCs are intended to target and kill tumor cells while sparing healthy cells. As of 2019, some 56 pharmaceutical companies were developing ADCs. ADCs are complex molecules composed of an antibody linked to a biologically active cytotoxic payload or drug. Antibody-drug conjugates are an example of bioconjugates and immunoconjugates. ADCs combine the targeting properties of monoclonal antibodies with the cancer-killing capabilities of cytotoxic drugs, designed to discriminate between healthy and diseased tissue.','{\"pat_doc\": 822.0, \"pub_alt\": 337.0, \"pub_doc\": 277.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 6687623.0, \"pat_granted\": 167.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": 18.3, \"clinic_doc\": 2.1, \"grant_fund\": -1636318.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('265b1787d8c0e53e37866ac9ab3803bf','d5e0c4320bf432eb18619675fba4a2d6','dc3eb969daa777d1268e99485984656d','2023-09-07 23:34:57','2023-10-28 17:16:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes',24,'Tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes are white blood cells that have left the bloodstream and migrated towards a tumor. They include T cells and B cells and are part of the larger category of â€˜tumor-infiltrating immune cells which consist of both mononuclear and polymorphonuclear immune cells, in variable proportions. Their abundance varies with tumor type and stage and in some cases relates to disease prognosis. TILs can often be found in the tumor stroma and within the tumor itself. Their functions can dynamically change throughout tumor progression and in response to anticancer therapy TILs are implicated in killing tumor cells. The presence of lymphocytes in tumors is often associated with better clinical outcomes.','{\"pat_doc\": 147.0, \"pub_alt\": 680.0, \"pub_doc\": 1949.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 49.0, \"clinic_alt\": 467.0, \"clinic_doc\": 86.0, \"grant_fund\": 16108824.0, \"pat_granted\": 17.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.9, \"pub_doc\": 39.6, \"clinic_doc\": 20.1, \"grant_fund\": -2417367.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('268c42d556cf27cfb2f912ee1e942174','c42efb8fe2ca41dc7fd5d4dbb0848ed6','7e6689dbdfabd5b7cf95a105e9764132','2023-09-08 09:27:09','2023-10-28 21:01:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Gas Chromatography',12,'Gas chromatography is a common type of chromatography used in analytical chemistry for separating and analyzing compounds that can be vaporized without decomposition. Typical uses of GC include testing the purity of a particular substance, or separating the different components of a mixture. In preparative chromatography, GC can be used to prepare pure compounds from a mixture. Gas chromatography is also sometimes known as vapor-phase chromatography, or gasâ€“liquid partition chromatography. These alternative names, as well as their respective abbreviations, are frequently used in scientific literature. Gas chromatography is the process of separating compounds in a mixture by injecting a gaseous or liquid sample into a mobile phase, typically called the carrier gas, and passing the gas through a stationary phase. The mobile phase is usually an inert gas or an unreactive gas such as helium, argon, nitrogen or hydrogen.','{\"pat_doc\": 1287.0, \"pub_alt\": 2956.0, \"pub_doc\": 8738.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 75.0, \"clinic_alt\": 100.0, \"clinic_doc\": 66.0, \"grant_fund\": 19585569.0, \"pat_granted\": 546.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 67.1, \"pub_doc\": 279.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.9, \"grant_fund\": -2716027.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('26b66a31d8e5ad30e1b0c85714480bf8','97a64c193e09e440bbb1c8b928126797','4893d9f6d48ce8d1001500525173bb9e','2023-09-07 23:55:39','2023-10-29 02:21:16','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','Lipid Nanoparticles',36,'Lipid nanoparticles are nanoparticles composed of lipids. They are a novel pharmaceutical drug delivery system, and a novel pharmaceutical formulation. LNPs as a drug delivery vehicle were first approved in 2018 for the siRNA drug Onpattro. LNPs became more widely known in late 2020, as some COVID-19 vaccines that use RNA vaccine technology coat the fragile mRNA strands with PEGylated lipid nanoparticles as their delivery vehicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 1643.0, \"pub_alt\": 16312.0, \"pub_doc\": 3263.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 211.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1578.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 91274414.0, \"pat_granted\": 188.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 197.5, \"pub_doc\": 208.3, \"clinic_doc\": 3.7, \"grant_fund\": 10362532.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('26e20e3706787b0f11decc046b32134c','6ad6b984db7a5bd574d38199653cd677','9e26cf59e38dc5ee0cf30259ac7c92ca','2023-09-05 20:05:34','2023-10-29 04:46:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Microfluidics',12,'Microfluidics refers to a system that manipulates a small amount of fluids using small channels with sizes ten to hundreds micrometres. It is a multidisciplinary field that involves molecular analysis, biodefence, molecular biology, and microelectronics. It has practical applications in the design of systems that process low volumes of fluids to achieve multiplexing, automation, and high-throughput screening. Microfluidics emerged in the beginning of the 1980s and is used in the development of inkjet printheads, DNA chips, lab-on-a-chip technology, micro-propulsion, and micro-thermal technologies. Typically, micro means one of the following features: â€¢ Small volumes â€¢ Small size â€¢ Low energy consumption â€¢ Microdomain effects. Typically microfluidic systems transport, mix, separate, or otherwise process fluids. Various applications rely on passive fluid control using capillary forces, in the form of capillary flow modifying elements, akin to flow resistors and flow accelerators.','{\"pat_doc\": 359.0, \"pub_alt\": 762.0, \"pub_doc\": 2237.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 182.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 108747055.0, \"pat_granted\": 115.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 28.6, \"pub_doc\": 144.5, \"clinic_doc\": 2.3, \"grant_fund\": -40950330.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('278f2f5df444796c9261857b2b51ad6e','92b44ff8d1d0e8c4689c1026159f41bb','dd42ec1636f7ea17b4c2869a3e543827','2023-09-08 02:08:52','2023-10-28 11:00:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Quantum Internet',36,'Quantum networks form an important element of quantum computing and quantum communication systems. Quantum networks facilitate the transmission of information in the form of quantum bits, also called qubits, between physically separated quantum processors. A quantum processor is a small quantum computer being able to perform quantum logic gates on a certain number of qubits. Quantum networks work in a similar way to classical networks. The main difference is that quantum networking, like quantum computing, is better at solving certain problems, such as modeling quantum systems.','{\"pat_doc\": 12.0, \"pub_alt\": 652.0, \"pub_doc\": 404.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 116.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 93693098.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.5, \"pub_doc\": 18.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -4606738.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2790939ae94fd528128ccd52701a5f42','42ee32d5802de92090c858e3452a50cf','d7426f446b19a6b58ca2ef44eac3e4b3','2023-09-08 01:12:46','2023-10-29 00:31:27','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','3D Cell Culture',48,'A 3D cell culture is an artificially created environment in which biological cells are permitted to grow or interact with their surroundings in all three dimensions. Unlike 2D environments, a 3D cell culture allows cells in vitro to grow in all directions, similar to how they would in vivo. These three-dimensional cultures are usually grown in bioreactors, small capsules in which the cells can grow into spheroids, or 3D cell colonies. Approximately 300 spheroids are usually cultured per bioreactor. 3D cell cultures can also be performed on microfluidic devices such as the OrganoplateÂ® to generate perfusable 3D tissues, and hanging drop devices to generate 3D spheroids.','{\"pat_doc\": 240.0, \"pub_alt\": 327.0, \"pub_doc\": 1590.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 213.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 75369803.0, \"pat_granted\": 67.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 5.8, \"pub_doc\": 19.4, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -5741441.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('27a18c180097eedcf6daa2927fbcd9ae','18cad71c26158b8438ac86692a449576','7a95cc3a83815758eaf9c2eaa16704db','2023-09-05 21:55:52','2023-10-29 03:51:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Gene Editing',24,'Gene editing is the process of making specific changes to an organisms DNA using technologies such as CRISPR-Cas9. This technology allows scientists to make precise changes to DNA, including addition, deletion, or replacement of specific genes. It offers a powerful tool for disease research and treatment, as well as for increasing agricultural productivity and food security. Gene editing also raises ethical concerns, particularly in the area of human genome editing. While gene editing has enormous potential, it is important to consider the ethical implications and potential risks before using it in human clinical settings.','{\"pat_doc\": 3556.0, \"pub_alt\": 888.0, \"pub_doc\": 4545.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 718.0, \"clinic_alt\": 991.0, \"clinic_doc\": 24.0, \"grant_fund\": 434538631.0, \"pat_granted\": 876.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 332.4, \"pub_doc\": 204.6, \"clinic_doc\": 5.7, \"grant_fund\": -40539920.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('27c2eba8d292c75e0d637e1d3f0f7348','62d3bf1b81cd240eca1b17ec53a45aed','9d56006f7b0bfb85db66d228f98a19d9','2023-09-08 00:57:05','2023-10-29 00:51:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Polymeric nanoparticles',48,'Polymeric nanoparticles are microscopic particles made up of polymers that have numerous applications, especially in the field of drug delivery and biomedical engineering. These particles, ranging from 1 to 1000 nanometers in size, can be designed in such a way that it can encapsulate drugs or other therapeutic agents and deliver them to the targeted site in a controlled manner. With characteristics such as their small size, large surface area, and the ability to protect the encapsulated content from degradation, they provide an excellent alternative to traditional drug delivery techniques. Polymeric nanoparticles have potential applications in cancer treatment, gene therapy, and imaging, among others. They have the potential to revolutionize the way we treat diseases and offer the possibility of more effective, less invasive therapeutic options.','{\"pat_doc\": 396.0, \"pub_alt\": 1000.0, \"pub_doc\": 2841.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 146.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 29691320.0, \"pat_granted\": 86.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.6, \"pub_doc\": 37.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.2, \"grant_fund\": -3328898.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('27d9835fcefd26e85e53dfd3c15d6ab3','ae3fe7b4d0291ed05028397533f28114','3147652f436cfa0a26c21b17f2c50188','2023-09-05 21:59:53','2023-10-28 17:36:10','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','induced pluripotent stem cells',12,'Induced pluripotent stem cells are a type of pluripotent stem cell that can be generated directly from a somatic cell. The iPSC technology was pioneered by Shinya Yamanaka and Kazutoshi Takahashi in Kyoto, Japan, who together showed in 2006 that the introduction of four specific genes, collectively known as Yamanaka factors, encoding transcription factors could convert somatic cells into pluripotent stem cells. Shinya Yamanaka was awarded the 2012 Nobel Prize along with Sir John Gurdon \"for the discovery that mature cells can be reprogrammed to become pluripotent.\" Pluripotent stem cells hold promise in the field of regenerative medicine. Because they can propagate indefinitely, as well as give rise to every other cell type in the body, they represent a single source of cells that could be used to replace those lost to damage or disease. The most well-known type of pluripotent stem cell is the embryonic stem cell.','{\"pat_doc\": 394.0, \"pub_alt\": 2998.0,