al treatment that involves taking supplemental doses of progesterone hormone. Progesterone is naturally produced by the ovaries during a womans menstrual cycle and plays a crucial role in regulating the menstrual cycle and preparing the body for pregnancy. However, some women may have low levels of progesterone, resulting in irregular menstrual cycles or difficulty getting pregnant. Progesterone supplementation can help balance hormonal levels and increase the chances of conceiving and sustaining a pregnancy. It can be administered through various methods, such as pills, injections, or vaginal suppositories, and is usually prescribed by a healthcare professional based on the patients individual needs and medical history.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 73.0, \"pub_doc\": 131.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 38.0, \"grant_fund\": 696125.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 3.4, \"grant_fund\": -80930.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2ac83095090b8af8751c48d0a28b1c30','511fe46a46ed4b151dc1fca695ee35f6','3351a35ba591fc4123a3314384741e66','2023-09-08 01:54:20','2023-10-28 23:41:13','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Cationic polymers',48,'In chemistry, cationic polymerization is a type of chain growth polymerization in which a cationic initiator transfers charge to a monomer which then becomes reactive. This reactive monomer goes on to react similarly with other monomers to form a polymer. The types of monomers necessary for cationic polymerization are limited to alkenes with electron-donating substituents and heterocycles. Similar to anionic polymerization reactions, cationic polymerization reactions are very sensitive to the type of solvent used. Specifically, the ability of a solvent to form free ions will dictate the reactivity of the propagating cationic chain. Cationic polymerization is used in the production of polyisobutylene and poly.','{\"pat_doc\": 775.0, \"pub_alt\": 68.0, \"pub_doc\": 473.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 38.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 8818539.0, \"pat_granted\": 259.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -10.9, \"pub_doc\": -2.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 44316.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2acf8a54f7fadb40c9d3c25bf7cb6c36','f1d991da1c3d1f34a90384e385b676a5','4101f5b584ffd5355154925e914aabcc','2023-09-08 00:58:18','2023-10-29 00:46:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Mass Cytometry',24,'Mass cytometry is a mass spectrometry technique based on inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry and time of flight mass spectrometry used for the determination of the properties of cells. In this approach, antibodies are conjugated with isotopically pure elements, and these antibodies are used to label cellular proteins. Cells are nebulized and sent through an argon plasma, which ionizes the metal-conjugated antibodies. The metal signals are then analyzed by a time-of-flight mass spectrometer. The approach overcomes limitations of spectral overlap in flow cytometry by utilizing discrete isotopes as a reporter system instead of traditional fluorophores which have broad emission spectra.','{\"pat_doc\": 71.0, \"pub_alt\": 6207.0, \"pub_doc\": 1212.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 185.0, \"clinic_alt\": 53.0, \"clinic_doc\": 57.0, \"grant_fund\": 94226567.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.1, \"pub_doc\": 21.7, \"clinic_doc\": 15.1, \"grant_fund\": -21158977.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2ad4bbdc1557c4cc159a337ddb8243c6','ae3fe7b4d0291ed05028397533f28114','3147652f436cfa0a26c21b17f2c50188','2023-09-05 21:59:53','2023-10-28 17:36:10','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','induced pluripotent stem cells',48,'Induced pluripotent stem cells are a type of pluripotent stem cell that can be generated directly from a somatic cell. The iPSC technology was pioneered by Shinya Yamanaka and Kazutoshi Takahashi in Kyoto, Japan, who together showed in 2006 that the introduction of four specific genes, collectively known as Yamanaka factors, encoding transcription factors could convert somatic cells into pluripotent stem cells. Shinya Yamanaka was awarded the 2012 Nobel Prize along with Sir John Gurdon \"for the discovery that mature cells can be reprogrammed to become pluripotent.\" Pluripotent stem cells hold promise in the field of regenerative medicine. Because they can propagate indefinitely, as well as give rise to every other cell type in the body, they represent a single source of cells that could be used to replace those lost to damage or disease. The most well-known type of pluripotent stem cell is the embryonic stem cell.','{\"pat_doc\": 1479.0, \"pub_alt\": 2998.0, \"pub_doc\": 7706.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1162.0, \"clinic_alt\": 9.0, \"clinic_doc\": 66.0, \"grant_fund\": 651039566.0, \"pat_granted\": 366.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 34.5, \"pub_doc\": -32.8, \"clinic_doc\": 11.8, \"grant_fund\": -40706986.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2adddb86a0ca3ad394a6ad8082c7977a','123fff890be892fb84e8f950aecc8f54','e2436e9e1daec5dad6800e18965c31a2','2023-09-08 00:59:51','2023-10-28 16:01:19','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Monoclonal antibodies','Nanobodies',48,'Nanobodies are small antibody fragments with unique properties that offer promising potential for therapeutic and diagnostic applications. These fragments are derived from the immune system of camelids, such as camels and llamas, and consist of a single immunoglobulin domain that has a high affinity and specificity for its target. Nanobodies are much smaller and more stable than traditional antibodies, which allows them to penetrate deeper into tissues and reach difficult-to-access locations. Additionally, their small size and simplicity make it easier and cheaper to produce them at a large scale. Due to these advantages, nanobodies are being investigated for a variety of uses, including cancer therapy, imaging, and viral infections.','{\"pat_doc\": 438.0, \"pub_alt\": 1699.0, \"pub_doc\": 1535.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 315.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 172699247.0, \"pat_granted\": 94.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 40.8, \"pub_doc\": 70.3, \"clinic_doc\": 1.3, \"grant_fund\": -15354732.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2b74e6dfe986ed9a47bf467f31ae70bf','0a08029fe04824e466d5980ec8cdbf8b','a0ec7ffe04c046d0f8469b5de966ddfa','2023-09-04 18:53:15','2023-10-29 06:40:05','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Flow Cytometry',48,'Flow cytometry is a technique used to detect and measure physical and chemical characteristics of a population of cells or particles. In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument. The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components. Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths. Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer. Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials. Uses for flow cytometry include: â€¢ Cell counting â€¢ Cell sorting â€¢ Determining cell characteristics and function â€¢ Detecting microorganisms â€¢ Biomarker detection â€¢ Protein engineering detection â€¢ Diagnosis of health disorders such as blood cancers â€¢ Measuring genome size.','{\"pat_doc\": 2017.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 67644.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2556.0, \"clinic_alt\": 590.0, \"clinic_doc\": 864.0, \"grant_fund\": 741017990.0, \"pat_granted\": 652.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.1, \"pub_doc\": -433.8, \"clinic_doc\": 137.2, \"grant_fund\": -49967547.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2b84d8013ae6375cdcaa836ccecf277c','c9c8d2e4c7e139d539bc510be3e5f7ac','e9be6c0a64d57a69a37703624e73b1fd','2023-09-08 01:22:43','2023-10-29 00:16:22','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','Cell Isolation',12,'Cell isolation is the process of separating individual living cells from a solid block of tissue or cell suspension. While some types of cell naturally exist in a separated form, other cell types that are found in solid tissue require specific techniques to separate them into individual cells. This may be performed by using enzymes to digest the proteins that binds these cells together within the extracellular matrix. After the matrix proteins have been digested, cells remain loosely bound together but can be gently separated mechanically. Following isolation, experiments can be performed on these single isolated cells including patch clamp electrophysiology, calcium fluorescence imaging, and immunocytochemistry.','{\"pat_doc\": 72.0, \"pub_alt\": 217.0, \"pub_doc\": 252.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 23.0, \"clinic_alt\": 5.0, \"clinic_doc\": 20.0, \"grant_fund\": 8330485.0, \"pat_granted\": 22.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -2.2, \"pub_doc\": 0.4, \"clinic_doc\": 4.9, \"grant_fund\": -1507208.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2bab0e6c21dffd90c901c9b6d941ddad','2dd9d7ef89e93089944c052185d5b575','ce749f284f6019c4ac54019c71229b4d','2023-09-08 09:58:49','2023-10-28 19:41:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','digital droplet PCR',12,'Digital droplet PCR (ddPCR) is a highly sensitive and specific technique used for quantifying nucleic acids. ddPCR partitions a sample into thousands of droplets containing one or zero target molecules. The droplets are then subjected to PCR amplification and fluorescence analysis to determine which droplets contain the target molecule. This allows for highly precise quantification of the initial amount of target nucleic acid in the original sample, with a sensitivity of up to one copy per reaction. ddPCR has numerous applications in fields such as cancer research, infectious disease diagnosis, and genetic testing.','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_alt\": 13.0, \"pub_doc\": 136.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": 2368256.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": -2.8, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": -559015.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2bebc5e602110734ae806d3fd3b559d2','224d3dce630c1eacf85c0f88dd72e042','66dae1bd66572a9ac387868804da7fa9','2023-09-08 00:43:37','2023-10-28 16:11:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Monoclonal antibodies','Bispecific antibody',12,'A bispecific monoclonal antibody is an artificial protein that can simultaneously bind to two different types of antigen or two different epitopes on the same antigen. Naturally occurring antibodies typically only target one antigen. BsAbs can be manufactured in several structural formats. BsAbs can be designed to recruit and activate immune cells, to interfere with receptor signaling and inactivate signaling ligands, and to force association of protein complexes. BsAbs have been explored for cancer immunotherapy, drug delivery, and Alzeimers disease.','{\"pat_doc\": 1145.0, \"pub_alt\": 746.0, \"pub_doc\": 560.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 859.0, \"clinic_doc\": 208.0, \"grant_fund\": 59238077.0, \"pat_granted\": 188.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 160.2, \"pub_doc\": 80.4, \"clinic_doc\": 59.6, \"grant_fund\": 14897954.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2bf696edd8f26b3b762c5e37bf500a5f','09e9ed6148f2e431ca17ead10dda844b','23bce1931f776364d9203491f1d59304','2023-09-05 22:01:13','2023-10-29 03:46:15','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Spectrophotometry',24,'Spectrophotometry is a branch of electromagnetic spectroscopy concerned with the quantitative measurement of the reflection or transmission properties of a material as a function of wavelength. Spectrophotometry uses photometers, known as spectrophotometers, that can measure the intensity of a light beam at different wavelengths. Although spectrophotometry is most commonly applied to ultraviolet, visible, and infrared radiation, modern spectrophotometers can interrogate wide swaths of the electromagnetic spectrum, including x-ray, ultraviolet, visible, infrared, and/or microwave wavelengths.','{\"pat_doc\": 520.0, \"pub_alt\": 835.0, \"pub_doc\": 5888.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 72.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 29.0, \"grant_fund\": 6969361.0, \"pat_granted\": 193.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.5, \"pub_doc\": 60.9, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": -1805233.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2c033907004b3fa0a96264f408f46ce2','e1c03cd2dbe1db8089d68f8b8c8054b0','e21059dfa6307a406da37caf3abb3281','2023-09-08 09:10:54','2023-10-28 13:16:11','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Urothelial cancer',36,'Urothelial cancer is a type of cancer that develops in the urothelial cells, which line the urinary tract. It is also known as transitional cell carcinoma. This type of cancer can develop in the bladder, ureters, or renal pelvis. The majority of urothelial cancers are found in the bladder, and symptoms may include blood in the urine, painful urination, and frequent urination. Urothelial cancer can be treated with surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy, and the prognosis can vary depending on the stage of the cancer. Early detection and treatment can lead to a better outcome, so it is important to seek medical attention if any symptoms are present.','{\"pat_doc\": 206.0, \"pub_alt\": 762.0, \"pub_doc\": 1417.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 59.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1167.0, \"clinic_doc\": 259.0, \"grant_fund\": 10940950.0, \"pat_granted\": 44.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_doc\": -5.4, \"clinic_doc\": 57.4, \"grant_fund\": -606977.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2c0e532e7bf5adc00994a0440d7e3ff7','d26eb2bd1f18468fd4cd16acbcfe71a0','0de5062bb6f653f85fa36c9feb30d5e1','2023-09-08 01:30:22','2023-10-29 00:11:22','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Robotic Process Automation',12,'Robotic process automation is a form of business process automation that is based on software robots or artificial intelligence agents. It is sometimes referred to as software robotics. In traditional workflow automation tools, a software developer produces a list of actions to automate a task and interface to the back end system using internal application programming interfaces or dedicated scripting language. In contrast, RPA systems develop the action list by watching the user perform that task in the applications graphical user interface, and then perform the automation by repeating those tasks directly in the GUI. This can lower the barrier to the use of automation in products that might not otherwise feature APIs for this purpose. RPA tools have strong technical similarities to graphical user interface testing tools. These tools also automate interactions with the GUI, and often do so by repeating a set of demonstration actions performed by a user.','{\"pat_doc\": 409.0, \"pub_alt\": 119.0, \"pub_doc\": 389.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 395928.0, \"pat_granted\": 110.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 111.3, \"pub_doc\": 68.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -911088.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2c3aaf14acff182c95a0d3e21f679435','2ef204f64673ee0cc4682daa8faf26bb','767ea62d04e7021f7b0e5dec58a48a8d','2023-09-08 10:56:51','2023-10-28 18:56:11','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Personalized Medicine',48,'Personalized medicine, also referred to as precision medicine, is a medical model that separates people into different groupsâ€”with medical decisions, practices, interventions and/or products being tailored to the individual patient based on their predicted response or risk of disease. The terms personalized medicine, precision medicine, stratified medicine and P4 medicine are used interchangeably to describe this concept though some authors and organisations use these expressions separately to indicate particular nuances. While the tailoring of treatment to patients dates back at least to the time of Hippocrates, the term has risen in usage in recent years given the growth of new diagnostic and informatics approaches that provide understanding of the molecular basis of disease, particularly genomics. This provides a clear evidence base on which to stratify related patients.','{\"pat_doc\": 512.0, \"pub_alt\": 1841.0, \"pub_doc\": 9277.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1450.0, \"clinic_alt\": 592.0, \"clinic_doc\": 316.0, \"grant_fund\": 882851189.0, \"pat_granted\": 108.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.4, \"pub_doc\": 162.7, \"clinic_doc\": 61.2, \"grant_fund\": -59753219.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2c501e24142883a2683b42d4c2c1e7e0','230eda4c55f24cadd07347f1a221f5ca','d9f345c5479253d7d74e62f81762d9a5','2023-09-05 21:57:22','2023-10-28 12:15:33','Electronics','Components','Storage Devices','Spintronics',36,'Spintronics, also known as spin electronics, is the study of the intrinsic spin of the electron and its associated magnetic moment, in addition to its fundamental electronic charge, in solid-state devices. The field of spintronics concerns spin-charge coupling in metallic systems; the analogous effects in insulators fall into the field of multiferroics. Spintronics fundamentally differs from traditional electronics in that, in addition to charge state, electron spins are used as a further degree of freedom, with implications in the efficiency of data storage and transfer. Spintronic systems are most often realised in dilute magnetic semiconductors and Heusler alloys and are of particular interest in the field of quantum computing and neuromorphic computing.','{\"pat_doc\": 138.0, \"pub_alt\": 491.0, \"pub_doc\": 5460.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 569.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 276097862.0, \"pat_granted\": 41.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.9, \"pub_doc\": 169.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5459749.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2c6572a4c6f76b66b6f27a0c3fd58d6b','09e9ed6148f2e431ca17ead10dda844b','23bce1931f776364d9203491f1d59304','2023-09-05 22:01:13','2023-10-29 03:46:15','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Spectrophotometry',48,'Spectrophotometry is a branch of electromagnetic spectroscopy concerned with the quantitative measurement of the reflection or transmission properties of a material as a function of wavelength. Spectrophotometry uses photometers, known as spectrophotometers, that can measure the intensity of a light beam at different wavelengths. Although spectrophotometry is most commonly applied to ultraviolet, visible, and infrared radiation, modern spectrophotometers can interrogate wide swaths of the electromagnetic spectrum, including x-ray, ultraviolet, visible, infrared, and/or microwave wavelengths.','{\"pat_doc\": 1047.0, \"pub_alt\": 835.0, \"pub_doc\": 11503.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 205.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 50.0, \"grant_fund\": 21417383.0, \"pat_granted\": 364.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.5, \"pub_doc\": 60.9, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": -1805233.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2c77529fe8eb02031e2926ffc23feb5f','e1fe0660b514055c0dbf73bc14fd217a','ed9ba98e0c7216e9330cb415b46ee8cd','2023-09-07 23:50:12','2023-10-28 17:06:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Herpes simplex virus',36,'Herpes simplex virus 1 and 2, also known by their taxonomic names Human alphaherpesvirus 1 and Human alphaherpesvirus 2, are two members of the human Herpesviridae family, a set of viruses that produce viral infections in the majority of humans. Both HSV-1 and HSV-2 are very common and contagious. They can be spread when an infected person begins shedding the virus. As of 2016, about 67% of the world population under the age of 50 had HSV-1. In the United States, about 47.8% and 11.9% are estimated to have HSV-1 and HSV-2, respectively, though actual prevalence may be much higher. Because it can be transmitted through any intimate contact, it is one of the most common sexually transmitted infections.','{\"pat_doc\": 823.0, \"pub_alt\": 1973.0, \"pub_doc\": 4010.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 169.0, \"clinic_alt\": 635.0, \"clinic_doc\": 129.0, \"grant_fund\": 65994148.0, \"pat_granted\": 217.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.7, \"pub_doc\": 21.1, \"clinic_doc\": 20.7, \"grant_fund\": -10632542.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2cc5da60670fd99f534e427ba0658e83','633e3e1c04bc9ee16dfcb222f957cce1','5ee4ac63831f6ebbfc5f216379d36d38','2023-09-08 08:27:45','2023-10-28 10:30:32','Electronics','Components','Other','Co-Packaged Optics',48,'Co-packaged optics is a term that refers to the integration of optical components within the silicon chip package, enabling high-speed computing to be achieved. This technology is expected to revolutionize the data center industry by enhancing speed and reducing power consumption. By eliminating fiber cabling and replacing it with on-board optical interconnects, co-packaged optics enables faster data transfer rates, better communication between processors, reduced data center infrastructure, and other significant benefits. An important aspect of this technology is that it leverages existing CMOS fabrication processes, ensuring compatibility with current manufacturing techniques. This new optical integration technology is set to push the capabilities of electronic data processing further than ever before, providing more efficient and faster data transfer speeds for data centers and beyond.','{\"pat_doc\": 44.0, \"pub_alt\": 4.0, \"pub_doc\": 116.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 26944158.0, \"pat_granted\": 11.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.6, \"pub_doc\": 13.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2486201.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2cf15ad2d46864ed1a069dac8a5f0f3b','f1df325e8a923b7c94ec1f46acdb203e','67ae7824162271af981ae2c6a606ee4e','2023-09-05 22:59:40','2023-10-28 12:00:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Memristor',36,'A memristor is a non-linear two-terminal electrical component relating electric charge and magnetic flux linkage. It was described and named in 1971 by Leon Chua, completing a theoretical quartet of fundamental electrical components which comprises also the resistor, capacitor and inductor. Chua and Kang later generalized the concept to memristive systems. Such a system comprises a circuit, of multiple conventional components, which mimics key properties of the ideal memristor component and is also commonly referred to as a memristor. Several such memristor system technologies have been developed, notably ReRAM. The identification of memristive properties in electronic devices has attracted controversy. Experimentally, the ideal memristor has yet to be demonstrated.','{\"pat_doc\": 1929.0, \"pub_alt\": 481.0, \"pub_doc\": 5238.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 127.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 55560319.0, \"pat_granted\": 656.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 108.5, \"pub_doc\": 242.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2583132.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2d37805d5cf2c6316db91d93b90f0f06','3dc3dd5d2df2a0b127886fa91ef3f5d5','606edbb39b7dac4ec5ef367e4247cc8d','2023-09-08 09:54:26','2023-10-28 20:01:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Ion Chromatography',48,'Ion chromatography is a form of chromatography that separates ions and polar molecules based on their affinity to the ion exchanger. It works on almost any kind of charged moleculeâ€”including large proteins, small nucleotides, and amino acids. However, ion chromatography must be done in conditions that are one unit away from the isoelectric point of a protein. The two types of ion chromatography are anion-exchange and cation-exchange. Cation-exchange chromatography is used when the molecule of interest is positively charged. The molecule is positively charged because the pH for chromatography is less than the pI. In this type of chromatography, the stationary phase is negatively charged and positively charged molecules are loaded to be attracted to it. Anion-exchange chromatography is when the stationary phase is positively charged and negatively charged molecules are loaded to be attracted to it. It is often used in protein purification, water analysis, and quality control.','{\"pat_doc\": 4028.0, \"pub_alt\": 473.0, \"pub_doc\": 10006.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 304.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 12.0, \"grant_fund\": 66785173.0, \"pat_granted\": 1272.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.4, \"pub_doc\": -31.8, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": -6435445.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2dfd793392a80438cd08232676d38854','b7fe7c9d15ecc10608a0a70e65bacf5e','1c1aa7729e1e2fdd7a421fd9a7014e0a','2023-09-05 19:45:22','2023-10-28 12:50:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Augmented reality',12,'Augmented reality is an interactive experience that combines the real world and computer-generated content. The content can span multiple sensory modalities, including visual, auditory, haptic, somatosensory and olfactory. AR can be defined as a system that incorporates three basic features: a combination of real and virtual worlds, real-time interaction, and accurate 3D registration of virtual and real objects. The overlaid sensory information can be constructive, or destructive. This experience is seamlessly interwoven with the physical world such that it is perceived as an immersive aspect of the real environment. In this way, augmented reality alters ones ongoing perception of a real-world environment, whereas virtual reality completely replaces the users real-world environment with a simulated one. Augmented reality is largely synonymous with mixed reality. There is also overlap in terminology with extended reality and computer-mediated reality.','{\"pat_doc\": 8094.0, \"pub_alt\": 286.0, \"pub_doc\": 7028.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 224.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 135.0, \"grant_fund\": 155773356.0, \"pat_granted\": 2783.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 480.5, \"pub_doc\": 671.6, \"clinic_doc\": 35.2, \"grant_fund\": -13626091.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2e0db1a2cf2cbe691d5ee8d738ce254c','2189df4a2bc6ca2c1f680fee94f5b10c','41bec6af04474eb4358a3a371286538c','2023-09-07 23:37:46','2023-10-29 02:36:13','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Gene Silencing',24,'Gene silencing is the regulation of gene expression in a cell to prevent the expression of a certain gene. Gene silencing can occur during either transcription or translation and is often used in research. In particular, methods used to silence genes are being increasingly used to produce therapeutics to combat cancer and other diseases, such as infectious diseases and neurodegenerative disorders. Gene silencing is often considered the same as gene knockdown. When genes are silenced, their expression is reduced. In contrast, when genes are knocked out, they are completely erased from the organisms genome and, thus, have no expression. Gene silencing is considered a gene knockdown mechanism since the methods used to silence genes, such as RNAi, CRISPR, or siRNA, generally reduce the expression of a gene by at least 70% but do not eliminate it.','{\"pat_doc\": 520.0, \"pub_alt\": 591.0, \"pub_doc\": 3028.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 207.0, \"clinic_alt\": 16.0, \"clinic_doc\": 11.0, \"grant_fund\": 74976900.0, \"pat_granted\": 176.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 13.2, \"pub_doc\": -3.1, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": -9870496.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2e2af2357ba3568e4606a936d6410a38','b1f6b055bf7f576af1fda25a04ce64a1','d6145a42d41428a7d112c8f6aaaadaa8','2023-09-08 00:54:04','2023-10-29 01:01:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Digital Pathology',24,'Digital pathology is a sub-field of pathology that focuses on data management based on information generated from digitized specimen slides. Through the use of computer-based technology, digital pathology utilizes virtual microscopy. Glass slides are converted into digital slides that can be viewed, managed, shared and analyzed on a computer monitor. With the practice of Whole-Slide Imaging, which is another name for virtual microscopy, the field of digital pathology is growing and has applications in diagnostic medicine, with the goal of achieving efficient and cheaper diagnoses, prognosis, and prediction of diseases due to the success in machine learning and artificial intelligence in healthcare.','{\"pat_doc\": 339.0, \"pub_alt\": 896.0, \"pub_doc\": 1226.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 63.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 18.0, \"grant_fund\": 53500280.0, \"pat_granted\": 103.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 31.4, \"pub_doc\": 91.6, \"clinic_doc\": 5.1, \"grant_fund\": -15307360.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2e3eb341090a77553b9d437eb1e9631c','cef1c501111b2b4c4a7d99d59f4c45cc','61697279f5d40a0cf2ea206c3315fe94','2023-09-08 00:20:47','2023-10-28 16:31:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Chimeric antigen receptor T cells',12,'Chimeric antigen receptor (CAR) T cells, also known as CAR-T cells, are modified immune cells that are trained to seek and destroy cancer cells. CAR-T cells are created by extracting T cells, a type of white blood cell, from a patients blood and genetically engineering them to produce a special protein called a chimeric antigen receptor. This receptor allows the CAR-T cells to recognize and attack cancer cells that express specific markers on their surface. Once re-infused into the patients bloodstream, the CAR-T cells multiply and aggressively seek out and destroy cancer cells. CAR-T cell therapy has shown promising results in treating certain blood cancers, including leukemia and lymphoma, and is being studied for use in other types of cancer.','{\"pat_doc\": 90.0, \"pub_alt\": 172.0, \"pub_doc\": 200.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 32.0, \"clinic_doc\": 103.0, \"grant_fund\": 1772139.0, \"pat_granted\": 25.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -18.9, \"pub_doc\": 3.4, \"clinic_doc\": 24.6, \"grant_fund\": -2849426.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2ee499f34adda81881c6de29eafe2134','794ef6eb4705d90aa18415f5e5a2779f','7b7c2d14c4ce8d4f609c2918b205a47e','2023-09-08 09:38:47','2023-10-28 20:51:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Thermogravimetric Analysis',48,'Thermogravimetric analysis or thermal gravimetric analysis is a method of thermal analysis in which the mass of a sample is measured over time as the temperature changes. This measurement provides information about physical phenomena, such as phase transitions, absorption, adsorption and desorption; as well as chemical phenomena including chemisorptions, thermal decomposition, and solid-gas reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 605.0, \"pub_alt\": 423.0, \"pub_doc\": 22246.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 144.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 11738361.0, \"pat_granted\": 149.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 32.3, \"pub_doc\": 123.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -985255.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2efaeedcf6b560d9b4cc12ccd121fbb0','30f5159f16b7a113dcbf47772afc4c96','0a44fd511d173aa7606e2fa180b97dbd','2023-09-08 02:14:34','2023-10-28 22:51:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Gene Circuits',48,'A gene circuit is a network of genes that work together to produce a certain outcome, such as the regulation of a specific biological process. These circuits function through gene expression, in which certain genes are turned on or off in response to environmental stimuli or cellular signals. The composition of the gene circuit can vary depending on the desired outcome, with different genes and regulatory elements influencing the behavior of the circuit. Gene circuits are important for understanding the complex processes that occur within cells and organisms, and have potential applications in fields such as synthetic biology and gene therapy.','{\"pat_doc\": 19.0, \"pub_alt\": 686.0, \"pub_doc\": 348.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 68.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 70043672.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 6.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2080968.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2f8fdd51735a4019061ee3292ac3832c','d86696ef8204e2fe630e53d5acb96743','0df45be154a854c136cea54f3239586e','2023-09-08 01:15:35','2023-10-28 15:31:15','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Hypoparathyroidism',24,'Hypoparathyroidism is decreased function of the parathyroid glands with underproduction of parathyroid hormone. This can lead to low levels of calcium in the blood, often causing cramping and twitching of muscles or tetany, and several other symptoms. It is a very rare disease. The condition can be inherited, but it is also encountered after thyroid or parathyroid gland surgery, and it can be caused by immune system-related damage as well as a number of rarer causes. The diagnosis is made with blood tests, and other investigations such as genetic testing depending on the results. The primary treatment of hypoparathyroidism is calcium and vitamin D supplementation. Calcium replacement or vitamin D can ameliorate the symptoms but can increase the risk of kidney stones and chronic kidney disease. Additionally, medications such as recombinant human parathyroid hormone or teriparatide may be given by injection to replace the missing hormone.','{\"pat_doc\": 73.0, \"pub_alt\": 106.0, \"pub_doc\": 1087.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_alt\": 60.0, \"clinic_doc\": 87.0, \"grant_fund\": 3224378.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.5, \"pub_doc\": 2.7, \"clinic_doc\": 13.5, \"grant_fund\": -516093.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('2fc9cb6c864c713766775489b59c8173','7c86b2353e10d37f742b8e8282b894cd','87aeff98505d298c3f2a7150e8c8ae7d','2023-09-05 21:14:26','2023-10-29 04:11:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Mxene',24,'In materials science, MXenes are a class of two-dimensional inorganic compounds, that consist of atomically thin layers of transition metal carbides, nitrides, or carbonitrides. MXenes accept a variety of hydrophilic terminations. MXenes were first reported in 2012.','{\"pat_doc\": 2767.0, \"pub_alt\": 213.0, \"pub_doc\": 9028.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 98.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 34059626.0, \"pat_granted\": 908.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 348.8, \"pub_doc\": 1206.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 246192.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('303ba0873ad2eaded563caa76f9c5ed1','df68dc3c44b77575d9caaef9764342db','5cc2df341e20d3c3cf94910f9000682b','2023-09-08 08:32:17','2023-10-28 13:36:17','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Squamous cell carcinoma',24,'Squamous-cell carcinomas, also known as epidermoid carcinomas, comprise a number of different types of cancer that begin in squamous cells. These cells form on the surface of the skin, on the lining of hollow organs in the body, and on the lining of the respiratory and digestive tracts. Common types include: â€¢ cutaneous squamous-cell carcinoma: a type of skin cancer â€¢ squamous-cell carcinoma of the lung: a type of lung cancer â€¢ squamous-cell thyroid carcinoma: a type of thyroid cancer â€¢ esophageal squamous-cell carcinoma: a type of esophageal cancer â€¢ squamous-cell carcinoma of the vagina: a type of vaginal cancer. Despite sharing the name \"squamous-cell carcinoma\", the SCCs of different body sites can show differences in their presented symptoms, natural history, prognosis, and response to treatment.','{\"pat_doc\": 840.0, \"pub_alt\": 1142.0, \"pub_doc\": 22936.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 416.0, \"clinic_alt\": 717.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1822.0, \"grant_fund\": 117529488.0, \"pat_granted\": 210.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 29.4, \"pub_doc\": 69.4, \"clinic_doc\": 397.4, \"grant_fund\": -19576090.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3050b68720d74b7dd037b6ec8f477c9a','0bc5e22ada5efec34101dcd4f634e7a2','e77dece162a0133e50d5b2357c40719f','2023-09-05 22:55:17','2023-10-29 02:55:05','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','RNA interference',36,'RNA interference is a biological process in which RNA molecules are involved in sequence-specific suppression of gene expression by double-stranded RNA, through translational or transcriptional repression. Historically, RNAi was known by other names, including co-suppression, post-transcriptional gene silencing, and quelling. The detailed study of each of these seemingly different processes elucidated that the identity of these phenomena were all actually RNAi. Andrew Fire and Craig C. Mello shared the 2006 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their work on RNAi in the nematode worm Caenorhabditis elegans, which they published in 1998. Since the discovery of RNAi and its regulatory potentials, it has become evident that RNAi has immense potential in suppression of desired genes. RNAi is now known as precise, efficient, stable and better than antisense therapy for gene suppression.','{\"pat_doc\": 1125.0, \"pub_alt\": 991.0, \"pub_doc\": 5500.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 265.0, \"clinic_alt\": 18.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 82609887.0, \"pat_granted\": 344.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.6, \"pub_doc\": -43.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": -14470471.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('30ebf5b1b758fd943edcfdd85da0f2cf','66370bcc1950b8300adc5378b5a9db5b','2cf8a6770a22256c603cf40927d188ef','2023-09-08 02:16:56','2023-10-28 22:41:13','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Non-viral Vector',36,'Non-viral vectors are genetic tools that aid in gene therapy that lack the viral genome and carry foreign genetic material that can be transferred into the cells. Instead of using an infectious pathogen, non-viral vectors use liposomes, nanoparticles, and chemical conjugates. Because non-viral vectors lack the viral genome, they are less immunogenic and safer than viral vectors. Non-viral vectors also allow the transfer of larger amounts of genetic material, providing possible benefits over the viral vector for genetic therapy applications. In addition, the simple design of non-viral vectors allows more economic and scalable production. Despite their advantages, non-viral vectors have lower transduction rates in cells than viral vectors.','{\"pat_doc\": 203.0, \"pub_alt\": 325.0, \"pub_doc\": 332.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 24.0, \"clinic_alt\": 29.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 8165950.0, \"pat_granted\": 25.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.8, \"pub_doc\": 0.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -408385.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('30f601c11b501f329a80c4584fa433c9','5799fbde63662e16529cdc2465faa33f','eefb2660a8535eb1d304c9a60295324f','2023-09-08 14:51:25','2023-10-28 18:35:05','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Liposomes',36,'Liposomes are microscopic, spherical vesicles composed of a phospholipid bilayer that is able to encapsulate a variety of water-soluble substances. They are commonly used as drug delivery systems because the lipid bilayer gives them the ability to cross cell membranes and deliver their contents directly to the interior of cells. Liposomes can be prepared in a variety of sizes with different properties, which makes them a versatile tool in medical research and pharmaceuticals. Their biocompatibility and ability to encapsulate both hydrophilic and hydrophobic substances has caused them to become increasingly popular in the fields of drug delivery and cosmetics.','{\"pat_doc\": 2373.0, \"pub_alt\": 590.0, \"pub_doc\": 9296.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 411.0, \"clinic_alt\": 108.0, \"clinic_doc\": 57.0, \"grant_fund\": 113084615.0, \"pat_granted\": 601.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 11.3, \"pub_doc\": 166.2, \"clinic_doc\": 8.1, \"grant_fund\": -13776868.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('30f8799e1755cd409c6468756e7d0e2b','86828d3c6e58a58dd0ec1a5517969fd6','de33517ef25dd85cbe2dd8dc604a5426','2023-09-08 01:18:05','2023-10-28 15:26:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','biomolecular condensates',36,'Biomolecular condensates are non-membrane-bound, membraneless organelles that are formed by the reversible phase separation of proteins, nucleic acids, and other biomolecules. These condensates can be dynamic and can rapidly assemble and disassemble in response to cellular signals. They play a crucial role in many cellular processes, including DNA replication, transcription, and translation. Recent studies have shown that the formation of these condensates can also drive the assembly of large molecular complexes that are essential for cellular functions. Dysfunction of these condensates has been linked to various diseases, including neurodegenerative disorders. Understanding the principles underlying biomolecular condensate formation and dynamics is crucial for understanding cellular processes and developing new therapeutics.','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_alt\": 611.0, \"pub_doc\": 1004.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 108.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 60632316.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.9, \"pub_doc\": 89.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1255674.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3108184d71b8037719272a9fb5a477b8','665bbf50f9c0e74f93301c0a8c98acec','f7f9ce80272ab55a46f45831f319f87c','2023-09-08 10:01:20','2023-10-28 19:26:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Turbidimetry',48,'Turbidimetry is the process of measuring the loss of intensity of transmitted light due to the scattering effect of particles suspended in it. Light is passed through a filter creating a light of known wavelength which is then passed through a cuvette containing a solution. A photoelectric cell collects the light which passes through the cuvette. A measurement is then given for the amount of absorbed light. Turbidimetry can be used in biology to find the number of cells in a solution. Turbidity-is an expression of optical look of a solution caused by radiation to the scattered and absorbed wavelength. Scattering of light is elastic so both incident and scattered radiation have same wavelength. A turbidometer measures the amount of radiation that passes through a fluid in forward direction,analogous to absorption spectrphotoometry.','{\"pat_doc\": 399.0, \"pub_alt\": 97.0, \"pub_doc\": 715.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 9.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 494143.0, \"pat_granted\": 114.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -10.5, \"pub_doc\": -8.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": -47175.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('311d47556950e0f0acf8664b9236353b','86828d3c6e58a58dd0ec1a5517969fd6','de33517ef25dd85cbe2dd8dc604a5426','2023-09-08 01:18:05','2023-10-28 15:26:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','biomolecular condensates',12,'Biomolecular condensates are non-membrane-bound, membraneless organelles that are formed by the reversible phase separation of proteins, nucleic acids, and other biomolecules. These condensates can be dynamic and can rapidly assemble and disassemble in response to cellular signals. They play a crucial role in many cellular processes, including DNA replication, transcription, and translation. Recent studies have shown that the formation of these condensates can also drive the assembly of large molecular complexes that are essential for cellular functions. Dysfunction of these condensates has been linked to various diseases, including neurodegenerative disorders. Understanding the principles underlying biomolecular condensate formation and dynamics is crucial for understanding cellular processes and developing new therapeutics.','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_alt\": 611.0, \"pub_doc\": 448.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 41.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 20618724.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.9, \"pub_doc\": 89.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1255674.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('316d13ac20a4b6332b089b6be9d376ea','643c5418206cf3f26f9e4a26676606ed','9d0b9265fabb266bda4551314039c119','2023-09-04 18:47:48','2023-10-28 18:16:21','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Metabolism','Type 2 Diabetes',12,'Type 2 Diabetes is a chronic condition where the body becomes resistant to insulin or does not produce enough insulin to regulate blood sugar levels. Insulin is a hormone produced by the pancreas that helps the body to use glucose for energy. When glucose builds up in the blood, it can cause damage to organs and tissues over time. Risk factors for developing type 2 diabetes include obesity, physical inactivity, poor diet, and genetics. Symptoms of type 2 diabetes may include frequent urination, increased thirst, blurred vision, fatigue, and slow healing of wounds. Treatment typically involves lifestyle modifications, such as diet and exercise, as well as medications to help regulate blood sugar levels. Without proper management, type 2 diabetes can lead to complications such as heart disease, stroke, kidney disease, and nerve damage.','{\"pat_doc\": 788.0, \"pub_alt\": 3680.0, \"pub_doc\": 20714.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 549.0, \"clinic_alt\": 649.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3135.0, \"grant_fund\": 210423752.0, \"pat_granted\": 184.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 9.1, \"pub_doc\": 681.3, \"clinic_doc\": 645.5, \"grant_fund\": -142425510.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('31b265eb8af4cd19e71c6b7ab8899013','8b21dbe0cb1307d6f1256e0e5db60249','ccad4956fa80c9c27804d8a966399e00','2023-09-08 09:47:24','2023-10-28 20:31:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','High resolution mass spectrometry',48,'High resolution mass spectrometry (HRMS) is an advanced analytical technique that is used to determine the exact mass of atomic and molecular ions with very high accuracy. It is particularly useful in identifying unknown compounds, determining the composition of complex mixtures and characterizing the chemical structure of biomolecules such as peptides, proteins and nucleic acids. In HRMS, ions are first generated from a sample and then separated based on their mass-to-charge ratio using a mass spectrometer. The ions are then detected and their masses are measured using high resolution detectors. The high resolution of the technique enables the detection of very small mass differences, which can be used to differentiate between compounds with similar molecular weights. HRMS has revolutionized the field of analytical chemistry and has become an indispensable tool for many applications in areas such as pharmacology, environmental science, food analysis and forensics.','{\"pat_doc\": 174.0, \"pub_alt\": 1833.0, \"pub_doc\": 2145.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 158.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 50200609.0, \"pat_granted\": 61.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.4, \"pub_doc\": -17.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -1744859.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('31bb1b36fc196a224c4e2c078d3c1b47','eee0d94d36c42e167a1a4be01f14392d','8c7694fa0bfc9847929f37bd7f31bd59','2023-09-04 19:48:49','2023-10-29 05:51:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','3D printing',36,'3D printing or additive manufacturing is the construction of a three-dimensional object from a CAD model or a digital 3D model. It can be done in a variety of processes in which material is deposited, joined or solidified under computer control, with the material being added together, typically layer by layer. In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping. As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology, whereby the term additive manufacturing can be used synonymously with 3D printing.','{\"pat_doc\": 29407.0, \"pub_alt\": 2627.0, \"pub_doc\": 24714.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1896.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 200.0, \"grant_fund\": 763401819.0, \"pat_granted\": 13024.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 434.0, \"pub_doc\": 1197.3, \"clinic_doc\": 23.8, \"grant_fund\": -8565739.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('322a8ad5709693be5e8fc6a262ef258a','238b58270bac60d5acf4e26cc123d5f1','61eadfbcdffdebf7c01d9aa685edd597','2023-09-08 01:05:56','2023-10-28 11:35:31','Electronics','Components','Processing Devices','RISC-V',12,'RISC-V is an open standard instruction set architecture based on established reduced instruction set computer principles. Unlike most other ISA designs, RISC-V is provided under royalty-free open-source licenses. A number of companies are offering or have announced RISC-V hardware; open source operating systems with RISC-V support are available, and the instruction set is supported in several popular software toolchains. As a RISC architecture, the RISC-V ISA is a loadâ€“store architecture. Its floating-point instructions use IEEE 754 floating-point. Notable features of the RISC-V ISA include: instruction bit field locations chosen to simplify the use of multiplexers in a CPU, a design that is architecturally neutral, and a fixed location for the sign bit of immediate values to speed up sign extension. The instruction set is designed for a wide range of uses.','{\"pat_doc\": 224.0, \"pub_alt\": 247.0, \"pub_doc\": 603.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 44.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 66346838.0, \"pat_granted\": 55.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 62.4, \"pub_doc\": 105.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 15384814.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3318bb2f775863f617b93de69d81c2c9','2189df4a2bc6ca2c1f680fee94f5b10c','41bec6af04474eb4358a3a371286538c','2023-09-07 23:37:46','2023-10-29 02:36:13','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Gene Silencing',12,'Gene silencing is the regulation of gene expression in a cell to prevent the expression of a certain gene. Gene silencing can occur during either transcription or translation and is often used in research. In particular, methods used to silence genes are being increasingly used to produce therapeutics to combat cancer and other diseases, such as infectious diseases and neurodegenerative disorders. Gene silencing is often considered the same as gene knockdown. When genes are silenced, their expression is reduced. In contrast, when genes are knocked out, they are completely erased from the organisms genome and, thus, have no expression. Gene silencing is considered a gene knockdown mechanism since the methods used to silence genes, such as RNAi, CRISPR, or siRNA, generally reduce the expression of a gene by at least 70% but do not eliminate it.','{\"pat_doc\": 256.0, \"pub_alt\": 591.0, \"pub_doc\": 1460.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 76.0, \"clinic_alt\": 16.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 20649098.0, \"pat_granted\": 82.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 13.2, \"pub_doc\": -3.1, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": -9870496.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('33374002489ed368ad35217df53b528a','fad21049eb39f44584479b92c65f1f69','1d60e7deb149c3b68658f6de8ff089a9','2023-09-20 20:26:19','2023-10-28 15:56:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Cushings Syndrome',36,'Cushings syndrome is a collection of signs and symptoms due to prolonged exposure to glucocorticoids such as cortisol. Signs and symptoms may include high blood pressure, abdominal obesity but with thin arms and legs, reddish stretch marks, a round red face due to facial plethora, a fat lump between the shoulders, weak muscles, weak bones, acne, and fragile skin that heals poorly. Women may have more hair and irregular menstruation. Occasionally there may be changes in mood, headaches, and a chronic feeling of tiredness. Cushings syndrome is caused by either excessive cortisol-like medication, such as prednisone, or a tumor that either produces or results in the production of excessive cortisol by the adrenal glands. Cases due to a pituitary adenoma are known as Cushings disease, which is the second most common cause of Cushings syndrome after medication. A number of other tumors, often referred to as ectopic due to their placement outside the pituitary, may also cause Cushings.','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_alt\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 11.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": -1.4, \"clinic_doc\": -0.9, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('334b33d70360a90c1d71f2b53681acbd','0bc5e22ada5efec34101dcd4f634e7a2','e77dece162a0133e50d5b2357c40719f','2023-09-05 22:55:17','2023-10-29 02:55:05','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','RNA interference',48,'RNA interference is a biological process in which RNA molecules are involved in sequence-specific suppression of gene expression by double-stranded RNA, through translational or transcriptional repression. Historically, RNAi was known by other names, including co-suppression, post-transcriptional gene silencing, and quelling. The detailed study of each of these seemingly different processes elucidated that the identity of these phenomena were all actually RNAi. Andrew Fire and Craig C. Mello shared the 2006 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their work on RNAi in the nematode worm Caenorhabditis elegans, which they published in 1998. Since the discovery of RNAi and its regulatory potentials, it has become evident that RNAi has immense potential in suppression of desired genes. RNAi is now known as precise, efficient, stable and better than antisense therapy for gene suppression.','{\"pat_doc\": 1472.0, \"pub_alt\": 1214.0, \"pub_doc\": 7318.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 429.0, \"clinic_alt\": 18.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 137682729.0, \"pat_granted\": 454.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.6, \"pub_doc\": -43.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": -14470471.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3369b7e039340ca67183b9bc645730a2','525ddc02deb579259414604666af7d2e','e910bc33478f3cb83e3ef258c7d92a6c','2023-09-08 02:02:55','2023-10-28 14:55:06','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel therapies','Gonadotropin-Releasing-Hormone Agonist',36,'A gonadotropin-releasing hormone agonist is a type of medication which affects gonadotropins and sex hormones. They are used for a variety of indications including in fertility medicine and to lower sex hormone levels in the treatment of hormone-sensitive cancers such as prostate cancer and breast cancer, certain gynecological disorders like heavy periods and endometriosis, high testosterone levels in women, early puberty in children, as a part of transgender hormone therapy, and to delay puberty in transgender youth among other uses. It is also used in the suppression of spontaneous ovulation as part of controlled ovarian hyperstimulation, an essential component in in IVF. GnRH agonists are given by injections into fat, as implants placed into fat, and as nasal sprays.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 21.0, \"pub_doc\": 1.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('336e71a84aa521b30467aa754dd43732','12312c1c49930d5087ae7dcb6859710b','49f53d4e41fb1f785aeb36bddad58488','2023-09-08 10:40:37','2023-10-28 19:06:13','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Natural Language Processing',36,'Natural language processing is an interdisciplinary subfield of computer science and linguistics. It is primarily concerned with giving computers the ability to support and manipulate speech. It involves processing natural language datasets, such as text corpora or speech corpora, using either rule-based or probabilistic machine learning approaches. The goal is a computer capable of \"understanding\" the contents of documents, including the contextual nuances of the language within them. The technology can then accurately extract information and insights contained in the documents as well as categorize and organize the documents themselves. Challenges in natural language processing frequently involve speech recognition, natural-language understanding, and natural-language generation.','{\"pat_doc\": 11199.0, \"pub_alt\": 1330.0, \"pub_doc\": 28095.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1510.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 77.0, \"grant_fund\": 761050922.0, \"pat_granted\": 3181.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 771.9, \"pub_doc\": 1863.9, \"clinic_doc\": 17.1, \"grant_fund\": -13379287.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('33d46b2e5a782b58dc52a362dac92ca7','090feb32dfbba21cb999b8efda702d3f','2774276ce5bfae5027508a164fb2fcb7','2023-09-08 02:36:18','2023-10-28 22:01:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Gene delivery vector',24,'A gene delivery vector is a vehicle used to transfer genetic material into cells. These vectors are commonly used in gene therapy and biotechnology applications to alter the expression of genes in cells. The most commonly used gene delivery vectors are viruses, which can infect cells and insert genetic material into the host cells genome. Retroviruses, adenoviruses, and adeno-associated viruses are some examples of viral vectors. Non-viral vectors, such as liposomes and naked DNA, can also be used to deliver genes, but are generally less efficient than viral vectors. Gene delivery vectors have immense potential in the treatment of genetic disorders, cancer, and other diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 54.0, \"pub_alt\": 363.0, \"pub_doc\": 122.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 12.0, \"clinic_alt\": 12.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 8232684.0, \"pat_granted\": 14.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 5.7, \"pub_doc\": -4.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -650737.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('342d2d102c323deaf48a4de226e746ae','8cc017d911f60e86f3530c8efab7f91a','7cfcc2197e33173ce522354c4a1177f6','2023-09-07 23:46:10','2023-10-29 02:31:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Green Hydrogen',36,'Green hydrogen is hydrogen generated from either renewable energy or low-carbon power. Green hydrogen has significantly lower carbon emissions than grey hydrogen, which is derived from fossil fuels without carbon capture. Green hydrogen may be used to decarbonize sectors that are hard to electrify, such as cement and iron production. Green hydrogen can be used to produce green ammonia, the main constituent of synthetic fertilizer. It can also be used for long-duration grid energy storage, and for long-duration seasonal energy storage. As of 2021, green hydrogen accounted for less than 0.04% of total hydrogen production. Its cost relative to hydrogen derived from fossil fuels is the main reason green hydrogen is in less demand.','{\"pat_doc\": 293.0, \"pub_alt\": 768.0, \"pub_doc\": 3543.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 634.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 907606976.0, \"pat_granted\": 75.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 63.1, \"pub_doc\": 594.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 22939710.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3457447efbfd3a353f29a68689c10c32','55794ad69e12330a0b6d80e9fdb0988d','e612e4b67f9789306cf3914a627ea83c','2023-09-07 23:58:23','2023-10-29 02:16:16','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Metabolic Engineering',48,'Metabolic engineering is the practice of optimizing genetic and regulatory processes within cells to increase the cells production of a certain substance. These processes are chemical networks that use a series of biochemical reactions and enzymes that allow cells to convert raw materials into molecules necessary for the cells survival. Metabolic engineering specifically seeks to mathematically model these networks, calculate a yield of useful products, and pin point parts of the network that constrain the production of these products. Genetic engineering techniques can then be used to modify the network in order to relieve these constraints. Once again this modified network can be modeled to calculate the new product yield. The ultimate goal of metabolic engineering is to be able to use these organisms to produce valuable substances on an industrial scale in a cost-effective manner.','{\"pat_doc\": 855.0, \"pub_alt\": 260.0, \"pub_doc\": 4642.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 307.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 118716375.0, \"pat_granted\": 254.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 34.9, \"pub_doc\": 16.6, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -6039306.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('34c0b8af209e3ccf17c7602227e7a505','bec6c7cf3a4a7344b41e74da4cea341b','2483d5e44059b5dad528a46e9d77ee36','2023-09-08 00:50:32','2023-10-29 01:06:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','antisense oligonucleotides',36,'Antisense oligonucleotides (ASOs) are short single-stranded pieces of DNA or RNA that bind to specific target mRNA molecules to regulate gene expression. ASOs are designed to silence a particular gene by preventing the translation of mRNA into protein, which can be useful in treating genetic disorders caused by overexpression or abnormal splicing of certain genes. ASOs are made up of a sequence complementary to the target mRNA, and once bound, they can recruit cellular machinery to degrade the mRNA or block its translation. ASOs are a promising therapeutic strategy for a variety of diseases, including cancer, viral infections, and genetic disorders.','{\"pat_doc\": 1277.0, \"pub_alt\": 334.0, \"pub_doc\": 1427.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 166.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 89117343.0, \"pat_granted\": 232.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 12.5, \"pub_doc\": 28.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -4672412.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('34caf593cc30ef2aeab8338855af13c5','e1c03cd2dbe1db8089d68f8b8c8054b0','e21059dfa6307a406da37caf3abb3281','2023-09-08 09:10:54','2023-10-28 13:16:11','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Urothelial cancer',24,'Urothelial cancer is a type of cancer that develops in the urothelial cells, which line the urinary tract. It is also known as transitional cell carcinoma. This type of cancer can develop in the bladder, ureters, or renal pelvis. The majority of urothelial cancers are found in the bladder, and symptoms may include blood in the urine, painful urination, and frequent urination. Urothelial cancer can be treated with surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy, and the prognosis can vary depending on the stage of the cancer. Early detection and treatment can lead to a better outcome, so it is important to seek medical attention if any symptoms are present.','{\"pat_doc\": 150.0, \"pub_alt\": 704.0, \"pub_doc\": 951.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 33.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1167.0, \"clinic_doc\": 243.0, \"grant_fund\": 10060993.0, \"pat_granted\": 32.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_doc\": -5.4, \"clinic_doc\": 57.4, \"grant_fund\": -606977.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('35584fb9395f43cec19c8bde26342fab','e24808701d1b869f29beb5b17a6f3966','0a566310cdeaa23e7fc0d55380c35a91','2023-09-08 02:38:56','2023-10-28 14:11:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Gene therapies (Non-viral)','mRNA therapy',12,'mRNA (messenger RNA) therapy is a cutting-edge medical technique that harnesses the bodys own ability to produce essential proteins to better fight disease. The therapy involves injecting synthetic strands of mRNA into the body, which are then recognized by the bodys own cells as \"blueprints\" for specific proteins that are vital for health. These proteins are then produced by the bodys cells and can be used to combat a wide range of illnesses, from cancer to genetic disorders to viral infections like COVID-19. mRNA therapy has shown a lot of promise in clinical trials, with some treatments already approved for use in certain conditions. While the technology is still in its early stages, experts believe that mRNA therapy could revolutionize the way we treat diseases in the coming years.','{\"pat_doc\": 42.0, \"pub_alt\": 106.0, \"pub_doc\": 28.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 1548946.0, \"pat_granted\": 7.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.7, \"pub_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.4, \"grant_fund\": 71200.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('35620e9d2ce3e26ec9b8b32184d9d1f3','18cad71c26158b8438ac86692a449576','7a95cc3a83815758eaf9c2eaa16704db','2023-09-05 21:55:52','2023-10-29 03:51:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Gene Editing',36,'Gene editing is the process of making specific changes to an organisms DNA using technologies such as CRISPR-Cas9. This technology allows scientists to make precise changes to DNA, including addition, deletion, or replacement of specific genes. It offers a powerful tool for disease research and treatment, as well as for increasing agricultural productivity and food security. Gene editing also raises ethical concerns, particularly in the area of human genome editing. While gene editing has enormous potential, it is important to consider the ethical implications and potential risks before using it in human clinical settings.','{\"pat_doc\": 4860.0, \"pub_alt\": 3610.0, \"pub_doc\": 6475.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1153.0, \"clinic_alt\": 991.0, \"clinic_doc\": 25.0, \"grant_fund\": 728278905.0, \"pat_granted\": 1114.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 332.4, \"pub_doc\": 204.6, \"clinic_doc\": 5.7, \"grant_fund\": -40539920.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('35699c8f638efdcc2b3154b2f9435a9c','73178bcae12bbd288347bb8d8e293d45','9b201e2ee1a601e1d33b326135e74c79','2023-09-08 08:26:31','2023-10-28 10:35:32','Electronics','Devices','Other','4D printing',12,'4-dimensional printing uses the same techniques of 3D printing through computer-programmed deposition of material in successive layers to create a three-dimensional object. However, in 4D printing, the resulting 3D shape is able to morph into different forms in response to environmental stimulus, with the 4th dimension being the time-dependent shape change after the printing. It is therefore a type of programmable matter, wherein after the fabrication process, the printed product reacts with parameters within the environment and changes its form accordingly.','{\"pat_doc\": 100.0, \"pub_alt\": 211.0, \"pub_doc\": 429.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5299904.0, \"pat_granted\": 34.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 10.9, \"pub_doc\": 86.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 226691.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3576f17abf965c1e1df6f20e6675d5c2','643c5418206cf3f26f9e4a26676606ed','9d0b9265fabb266bda4551314039c119','2023-09-04 18:47:48','2023-10-28 18:16:21','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Metabolism','Type 2 Diabetes',48,'Type 2 Diabetes is a chronic condition where the body becomes resistant to insulin or does not produce enough insulin to regulate blood sugar levels. Insulin is a hormone produced by the pancreas that helps the body to use glucose for energy. When glucose builds up in the blood, it can cause damage to organs and tissues over time. Risk factors for developing type 2 diabetes include obesity, physical inactivity, poor diet, and genetics. Symptoms of type 2 diabetes may include frequent urination, increased thirst, blurred vision, fatigue, and slow healing of wounds. Treatment typically involves lifestyle modifications, such as diet and exercise, as well as medications to help regulate blood sugar levels. Without proper management, type 2 diabetes can lead to complications such as heart disease, stroke, kidney disease, and nerve damage.','{\"pat_doc\": 3363.0, \"pub_alt\": 12883.0, \"pub_doc\": 80515.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3113.0, \"clinic_alt\": 649.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6349.0, \"grant_fund\": 1693098473.0, \"pat_granted\": 697.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 9.1, \"pub_doc\": 681.3, \"clinic_doc\": 645.5, \"grant_fund\": -142425510.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('358ef1c12f8dff19e8ef55ee0f194b1a','70acbc1819a41cd643bd80877d3bc5a4','79f0607dd327b272b64831fef13948f0','2023-09-08 09:12:08','2023-10-28 13:11:13','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Oncogenic signalling',48,'Oncogenic signaling refers to the changes that occur within cells that lead to uncontrolled cell growth and proliferation, ultimately resulting in cancer. These changes are typically driven by mutations that occur in genes that are involved in regulating cell growth and division. When these mutations occur, the affected gene becomes altered in a way that enhances its ability to promote cell growth and proliferation. This can occur through various mechanisms, including the activation of signaling pathways that regulate cell growth and division, or the alteration of the proteins that control the cell cycle. Ultimately, oncogenic signaling is a complex and multifaceted phenomenon that involves multiple genetic and biochemical factors working together to promote the growth and spread of cancer cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 410.0, \"pub_doc\": 141.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 20.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4723719.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 2.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 250205.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('35971fc1aadc0edb31fe032abec01ebf','ad14e59d8d8e44865760de1a016459ca','15926313fb5354a8aa389bc294cbeab7','2023-09-05 20:43:37','2023-10-29 04:36:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein-Protein Interaction',48,'Proteinâ€“protein interactions are physical contacts of high specificity established between two or more protein molecules as a result of biochemical events steered by interactions that include electrostatic forces, hydrogen bonding and the hydrophobic effect. Many are physical contacts with molecular associations between chains that occur in a cell or in a living organism in a specific biomolecular context. Proteins rarely act alone as their functions tend to be regulated. Many molecular processes within a cell are carried out by molecular machines that are built from numerous protein components organized by their PPIs. These physiological interactions make up the so-called interactomics of the organism, while aberrant PPIs are the basis of multiple aggregation-related diseases, such as Creutzfeldtâ€“Jakob and Alzheimers diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 815.0, \"pub_alt\": 3033.0, \"pub_doc\": 19620.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1394.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 554330427.0, \"pat_granted\": 186.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.7, \"pub_doc\": 265.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.4, \"grant_fund\": -40776859.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('35a5279c9f11b3bb97ac0de6d71d7501','ec9127faed503fab80aacc0c09e3bea4','1e154b56de35b3c06486dd7e904cade0','2023-09-05 22:15:33','2023-10-29 03:26:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Vaccines',12,'mRNA vaccines are a type of COVID-19 vaccine that provides immunity to the virus by introducing a small piece of messenger RNA (mRNA) into the body. This mRNA contains genetic instructions that direct cells to produce spike proteins, the same proteins that coat the surface of the coronavirus. Once the spike proteins are produced, the immune system recognizes them as foreign and develops antibodies to protect against future infections. mRNA vaccines are unique in that they do not contain weakened or dead virus particles, which makes them safer and easier to produce than traditional vaccines. They also have the potential to be rapidly developed and customized to address new variations of the virus. The two mRNA vaccines currently authorized for use in the United States are the Pfizer-BioNTech and Moderna vaccines.','{\"pat_doc\": 133.0, \"pub_alt\": 13370.0, \"pub_doc\": 1189.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 53.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1578.0, \"clinic_doc\": 59.0, \"grant_fund\": 17540277.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 39.4, \"pub_doc\": 427.8, \"clinic_doc\": 19.8, \"grant_fund\": 7035647.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('35c8684602162a0ccf336e2864c6887d','e10a2a038e97b6bb75152e575137a4fb','77e5f6785bd7c9d4f3610b4ac830ad4e','2023-09-08 00:22:46','2023-10-28 16:26:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Electroporation',48,'Electroporation, or electropermeabilization, is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing chemicals, drugs, electrode arrays or DNA to be introduced into the cell. In microbiology, the process of electroporation is often used to transform bacteria, yeast, or plant protoplasts by introducing new coding DNA. If bacteria and plasmids are mixed together, the plasmids can be transferred into the bacteria after electroporation, though depending on what is being transferred, cell-penetrating peptides or CellSqueeze could also be used. Electroporation works by passing thousands of volts across suspended cells in an electroporation cuvette. Afterwards, the cells have to be handled carefully until they have had a chance to divide, producing new cells that contain reproduced plasmids.','{\"pat_doc\": 2338.0, \"pub_alt\": 1984.0, \"pub_doc\": 3808.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 351.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1151.0, \"clinic_doc\": 186.0, \"grant_fund\": 136514334.0, \"pat_granted\": 635.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 72.8, \"pub_doc\": -23.0, \"clinic_doc\": 21.4, \"grant_fund\": -13946036.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('36181d14e81567de8956fdba4408a8e9','b25c61978fbea0483d82d3d77115840d','13bed64c970494074ea74f12ff611354','2023-09-08 01:04:16','2023-10-28 15:46:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','PROTAC',48,'A proteolysis targeting chimera is a heterobifunctional molecule composed of two active domains and a linker, capable of removing specific unwanted proteins. Rather than acting as a conventional enzyme inhibitor, a PROTAC works by inducing selective intracellular proteolysis. PROTACs consist of two covalently linked protein-binding molecules: one capable of engaging an E3 ubiquitin ligase, and another that binds to a target protein meant for degradation. Recruitment of the E3 ligase to the target protein results in ubiquitination and subsequent degradation of the target protein via the proteasome. Because PROTACs need only to bind their targets with high selectivity, there are currently many efforts to retool previously ineffective inhibitor molecules as PROTACs for next-generation drugs.','{\"pat_doc\": 459.0, \"pub_alt\": 367.0, \"pub_doc\": 2052.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 301.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 13.0, \"grant_fund\": 127956453.0, \"pat_granted\": 67.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 50.7, \"pub_doc\": 127.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.5, \"grant_fund\": -9266726.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('362661dedb845915603ef946c8702430','1db9ef424bfbfaef3351c1c0c2bbb420','bb12623092a23c745c2bf47641f215ad','2023-09-08 09:57:46','2023-10-28 19:46:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Amino Acid Analysis',24,'Amino acid analysis is a common method used to determine the quantity and composition of amino acids in a protein or peptide sample. This technique involves acid hydrolysis of the protein or peptide, which breaks down the peptide bonds and releases the individual amino acids. The resulting mixture of amino acids is then separated and quantified using various analytical techniques such as high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) or gas chromatography (GC). This analysis provides valuable information about the composition and concentration of amino acids, which can be used to deduce the sequence of the peptide or identify the protein. This technique is widely used in research, industrial, and clinical settings for various applications such as protein characterization, quality control, and dietary analysis.','{\"pat_doc\": 24.0, \"pub_alt\": 57.0, \"pub_doc\": 255.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 35086.0, \"pat_granted\": 11.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": 3.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -90894.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3635459c7512669bf95f3707bdfc0f9d','9ac2c447720a37348ec3adf931d10093','10ca8f5850cbd8a1f9e8a6552dd0293d','2023-09-08 02:56:51','2023-10-28 13:46:12','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel therapies','Gonadotropin Stimulation',36,'Gonadotropin stimulation is a medical procedure that is used to increase the production of hormones that are responsible for regulating the reproductive system. The process involves administering a hormone called gonadotropin to the patient. This hormone stimulates the ovaries and testes to produce more eggs and sperm, respectively. Gonadotropin stimulation is commonly used in the treatment of infertility, as it can increase the chances of conceiving a child. The procedure is usually performed in conjunction with in vitro fertilization (IVF) or intrauterine insemination (IUI) to increase the chances of a successful pregnancy. However, gonadotropin stimulation is not without its risks and complications, which can include multiple pregnancies, ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome, and ectopic pregnancy. Patients undergoing this procedure should be carefully monitored by their healthcare provider to ensure their safety and well-being.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 278.0, \"pub_doc\": 114.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 21.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": -2.8, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3655ba77d8a9551a5dbbf0e62c1eb9a6','18cad71c26158b8438ac86692a449576','7a95cc3a83815758eaf9c2eaa16704db','2023-09-05 21:55:52','2023-10-29 03:51:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Gene Editing',48,'Gene editing is the process of making specific changes to an organisms DNA using technologies such as CRISPR-Cas9. This technology allows scientists to make precise changes to DNA, including addition, deletion, or replacement of specific genes. It offers a powerful tool for disease research and treatment, as well as for increasing agricultural productivity and food security. Gene editing also raises ethical concerns, particularly in the area of human genome editing. While gene editing has enormous potential, it is important to consider the ethical implications and potential risks before using it in human clinical settings.','{\"pat_doc\": 5806.0, \"pub_alt\": 3610.0, \"pub_doc\": 8212.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1606.0, \"clinic_alt\": 991.0, \"clinic_doc\": 27.0, \"grant_fund\": 1035541141.0, \"pat_granted\": 1247.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 332.4, \"pub_doc\": 204.6, \"clinic_doc\": 5.7, \"grant_fund\": -40539920.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('36914769a7f9144a811d06e00430a526','d006191764fe7b11e9181190cc8abcbe','5f9f631521aff2090e15184e37181d22','2023-09-04 19:03:56','2023-10-29 06:16:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Immunohistochemistry',36,'Immunohistochemistry is the most common application of immunostaining. It involves the process of selectively identifying antigens in cells of a tissue section by exploiting the principle of antibodies binding specifically to antigens in biological tissues. IHC takes its name from the roots \"immuno\", in reference to antibodies used in the procedure, and \"histo\", meaning tissue. Albert Coons conceptualized and first implemented the procedure in 1941. Visualising an antibody-antigen interaction can be accomplished in a number of ways, mainly either of the following: â€¢ Chromogenic immunohistochemistry, wherein an antibody is conjugated to an enzyme, such as peroxidase, that can catalyse a colour-producing reaction. â€¢ Immunofluorescence, where the antibody is tagged to a fluorophore, such as fluorescein or rhodamine. Immunohistochemical staining is widely used in the diagnosis of abnormal cells such as those found in cancerous tumors.','{\"pat_doc\": 533.0, \"pub_alt\": 28733.0, \"pub_doc\": 47184.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1120.0, \"clinic_alt\": 553.0, \"clinic_doc\": 777.0, \"grant_fund\": 319645373.0, \"pat_granted\": 184.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.1, \"pub_doc\": -408.2, \"clinic_doc\": 134.5, \"grant_fund\": -28858320.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3694cef5587a343995e287e3e167f9dc','dbff1bacaaa4170742799b76b0d72aa1','e5dc1ab9b95fd144580ba449bdb1f286','2023-09-05 20:47:05','2023-10-29 04:21:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','CRISPR-Cas9',12,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 275.0, \"pub_alt\": 993.0, \"pub_doc\": 1861.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 177.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 17.0, \"grant_fund\": 72055014.0, \"pat_granted\": 92.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.6, \"pub_doc\": 115.9, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -29971557.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('36eeae0410576d9d9df8809e6563cdcc','32fc867764b2c2323b6074823f18f91d','e11ca4e4a12f409964c63840550b841e','2023-09-08 02:44:51','2023-10-28 21:41:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Editing',48,'mRNA editing is the process by which the genetic information contained within the messenger RNA (mRNA) transcript is modified by the insertion, deletion, or substitution of nucleotides. This process is critical for the accurate transmission of genetic information from DNA to protein synthesis, as it allows for the generation of multiple mRNA isoforms from a single gene. The molecular machinery involved in mRNA editing is complex and involves specific enzymes such as adenosine deaminase acting on RNA (ADAR), which catalyzes the conversion of adenosine to inosine in the mRNA sequence. This process has been found to play a key role in regulating gene expression and is implicated in a number of disease states, including cancer and neurological disorders. By modulating mRNA editing, researchers hope to develop new strategies for the treatment of these conditions.','{\"pat_doc\": 20.0, \"pub_alt\": 274.0, \"pub_doc\": 197.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 23.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 12498324.0, \"pat_granted\": 7.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": -2.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -1088864.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('370994d530991dabc741b05402513226','3cd9bdd88ba7ae8b9d89cbab89c2b25b','461ca981d4ebaba8ec09f7fd419f33b2','2023-09-08 01:09:47','2023-10-29 00:36:23','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Solid dispersion',12,'Solid dispersion is a technique used in the pharmaceutical industry to improve the solubility and bioavailability of poorly water-soluble drugs. It involves the preparation of a solid mixture of a drug with a hydrophilic carrier, such as a polymer or a surfactant, where the drug is dispersed in a molecularly or colloidal form in the carrier matrix. The resulting system exhibits an increased surface area of the drug particles and facilitates the formation of supersaturated solutions upon dissolution in aqueous media, leading to enhanced drug absorption and better therapeutic efficacy. Solid dispersion offers several advantages over traditional formulations, including reduced drug doses, improved patient compliance, and lowered production costs. Despite its potential benefits, the design and optimization of solid dispersions require careful consideration of various factors, such as drug-carrier interactions, drug loading, and stability.','{\"pat_doc\": 598.0, \"pub_alt\": 347.0, \"pub_doc\": 554.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 1035516.0, \"pat_granted\": 136.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 29.1, \"pub_doc\": 19.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.9, \"grant_fund\": -1206355.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('376731d19c7bc66f31c1a99bca9b917c','99c7079af458b7e10d0e17de306286cf','7ec492ea6e0e56c5b381d422684157c5','2023-09-08 01:01:11','2023-09-08 01:01:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Cushing\'s Syndrome',12,'Cushing\'s syndrome is a collection of signs and symptoms due to prolonged exposure to glucocorticoids such as cortisol. Signs and symptoms may include high blood pressure, abdominal obesity but with thin arms and legs, reddish stretch marks, a round red face due to facial plethora, a fat lump between the shoulders, weak muscles, weak bones, acne, and fragile skin that heals poorly. Women may have more hair and irregular menstruation. Occasionally there may be changes in mood, headaches, and a chronic feeling of tiredness. Cushing\'s syndrome is caused by either excessive cortisol-like medication, such as prednisone, or a tumor that either produces or results in the production of excessive cortisol by the adrenal glands. Cases due to a pituitary adenoma are known as Cushing\'s disease, which is the second most common cause of Cushing\'s syndrome after medication. A number of other tumors, often referred to as ectopic due to their placement outside the pituitary, may also cause Cushing\'s.','{\"pat_doc\": 43.0, \"pub_alt\": 132.0, \"pub_doc\": 332.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 44.0, \"grant_fund\": 65106.0, \"pat_granted\": 19.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.3, \"pub_doc\": 41.6, \"clinic_doc\": 8.9, \"grant_fund\": -229023.8, \"capital_raised\": 215.348}'),('3773de498a7089d48db0282fe6eeac94','bec6c7cf3a4a7344b41e74da4cea341b','2483d5e44059b5dad528a46e9d77ee36','2023-09-08 00:50:32','2023-10-29 01:06:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','antisense oligonucleotides',48,'Antisense oligonucleotides (ASOs) are short single-stranded pieces of DNA or RNA that bind to specific target mRNA molecules to regulate gene expression. ASOs are designed to silence a particular gene by preventing the translation of mRNA into protein, which can be useful in treating genetic disorders caused by overexpression or abnormal splicing of certain genes. ASOs are made up of a sequence complementary to the target mRNA, and once bound, they can recruit cellular machinery to degrade the mRNA or block its translation. ASOs are a promising therapeutic strategy for a variety of diseases, including cancer, viral infections, and genetic disorders.','{\"pat_doc\": 1639.0, \"pub_alt\": 1072.0, \"pub_doc\": 1844.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 240.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 131301646.0, \"pat_granted\": 301.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 12.5, \"pub_doc\": 28.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -4672412.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('37e380e78236cdcd155dadc0a53d537f','4ed1727d16902077c7b79a9c262994fa','12a26d07df436f186302cbc8c800d6d6','2023-09-05 20:45:30','2023-10-29 04:31:13','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Electroencephalography',12,'Electroencephalography is a method to record an electrogram of the spontaneous electrical activity of the brain. The biosignals detected by EEG have been shown to represent the postsynaptic potentials of pyramidal neurons in the neocortex and allocortex. It is typically non-invasive, with the EEG electrodes placed along the scalp using the International 10â€“20 system, or variations of it. Electrocorticography, involving surgical placement of electrodes, is sometimes called \"intracranial EEG\". Clinical interpretation of EEG recordings is most often performed by visual inspection of the tracing or quantitative EEG analysis. Voltage fluctuations measured by the EEG bioamplifier and electrodes allow the evaluation of normal brain activity. As the electrical activity monitored by EEG originates in neurons in the underlying brain tissue, the recordings made by the electrodes on the surface of the scalp vary in accordance with their orientation and distance to the source of the activity.','{\"pat_doc\": 150.0, \"pub_alt\": 3156.0, \"pub_doc\": 4269.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 131.0, \"clinic_alt\": 122.0, \"clinic_doc\": 514.0, \"grant_fund\": 49040979.0, \"pat_granted\": 31.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 299.2, \"clinic_doc\": 125.2, \"grant_fund\": -19331779.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('382327ed740c172053b10d4ebaccd1fe','12312c1c49930d5087ae7dcb6859710b','49f53d4e41fb1f785aeb36bddad58488','2023-09-08 10:40:37','2023-10-28 19:06:13','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Natural Language Processing',12,'Natural language processing is an interdisciplinary subfield of computer science and linguistics. It is primarily concerned with giving computers the ability to support and manipulate speech. It involves processing natural language datasets, such as text corpora or speech corpora, using either rule-based or probabilistic machine learning approaches. The goal is a computer capable of \"understanding\" the contents of documents, including the contextual nuances of the language within them. The technology can then accurately extract information and insights contained in the documents as well as categorize and organize the documents themselves. Challenges in natural language processing frequently involve speech recognition, natural-language understanding, and natural-language generation.','{\"pat_doc\": 4347.0, \"pub_alt\": 1330.0, \"pub_doc\": 11101.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 344.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 58.0, \"grant_fund\": 204471117.0, \"pat_granted\": 1534.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 771.9, \"pub_doc\": 1863.9, \"clinic_doc\": 17.1, \"grant_fund\": -13379287.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('385c02b611ebd4111532fe7269144d1b','12c66b98c18d896674c2af1741421e5c','5a1910224c76b3f4bd205c2f98daf970','2023-09-08 01:57:43','2023-10-28 11:05:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Artificial General Intelligence',48,'An artificial general intelligence is a hypothetical type of intelligent agent. If realized, an AGI could learn to accomplish any intellectual task that human beings or animals can perform. Alternatively, AGI has been defined as an autonomous system that surpasses human capabilities in the majority of economically valuable tasks. Creating AGI is a primary goal of some artificial intelligence research and of companies such as OpenAI, DeepMind, and Anthropic. AGI is a common topic in science fiction and futures studies. The timeline for AGI development remains a subject of ongoing debate among researchers and experts. Some argue that it may be possible in years or decades, others maintain it might take a century or longer, and a minority believe it may never be achieved. Additionally, there is debate regarding whether modern large language models, such as GPT-4, are an early yet incomplete form of AGI or if new approaches are required.','{\"pat_doc\": 10.0, \"pub_alt\": 5136.0, \"pub_doc\": 663.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 22.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 8115196.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.8, \"pub_doc\": 35.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -520216.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3883be0188eecee6c58ad83183e3fc4b','5790a7bed485dce7c0fd1fac61020f51','f1911fd26254d1cbfba1808fbf1f3025','2023-09-08 01:53:10','2023-10-28 23:46:12','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Organ-on chip',36,'An organ-on-a-chip is a multi-channel 3-D microfluidic cell culture, integrated circuit that simulates the activities, mechanics and physiological response of an entire organ or an organ system. It constitutes the subject matter of significant biomedical engineering research, more precisely in bio-MEMS. The convergence of labs-on-chips and cell biology has permitted the study of human physiology in an organ-specific context. By acting as a more sophisticated in vitro approximation of complex tissues than standard cell culture, they provide the potential as an alternative to animal models for drug development and toxin testing. Although multiple publications claim to have translated organ functions onto this interface, the development of these microfluidic applications is still in its infancy. Organs-on-chips vary in design and approach between different researchers.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 1.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": -0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('38d812a359ce8b4cdd5cbe5648a064e8','7a50af118adfe006fb057aba1683daea','5ae657e8e871e94265b41c651880e213','2023-09-08 01:40:52','2023-10-29 00:01:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Coating technology',48,'Coating technology refers to the various processes used to apply a thin layer of material onto a surface to enhance or modify its properties. Coatings can be applied to a wide range of materials including metals, plastics, ceramics, and glass. Coatings can improve the surface properties of a material such as corrosion resistance, wear resistance, and thermal resistance. They can also be used to provide a decorative finish. Coating technology is extensively used in industries such as automotive, aerospace, construction, and electronics. There are several types of coating processes including thermal spraying, chemical vapor deposition, and electroplating. Advances in coating technology have enabled the development of high-performance coatings that can withstand extreme temperatures and harsh environments. Coating technology is an important field that helps to extend the life of materials and improve their performance.','{\"pat_doc\": 1453.0, \"pub_alt\": 294.0, \"pub_doc\": 926.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 193.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 68780340.0, \"pat_granted\": 672.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.5, \"pub_doc\": 36.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.8, \"grant_fund\": 152974.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('392e445e477c02237c9a8e846c9bc62c','92a972462fc449a3f071840dbe8b2742','392c6994beadcacc6139a1c22998f10f','2023-09-20 23:02:34','2023-10-28 18:26:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','spatial biology',24,'Spatial Biology is defined as the study of tissues within their own 2D or 3D context. It is the new frontier of molecular biology.\r\n\r\nConsider how GPS captures location coordinates within an area to create a map and track you within it. The same principle can be translated to spatial data on a cellular and molecular level.\r\n\r\nThrough this technology, we can help map the spatial architecture of a cell and how it talks to and interacts with its surroundings. Spatial biology is like being inside a tissue sample at a molecular level. It enables single-cell analysis. Through spatial biology tools, you are empowered to see things that are not possible by sequencing or any other technologies out there.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 407.0, \"pub_doc\": 119.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 16.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 13622731.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 26.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2600741.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('398dd39e336eaefed3b18cd9cba70327','33e3b46112ca032f374d6e6e96ae9ab3','96ff1b7975967b788c2beb91534beb0f','2023-09-05 20:50:48','2023-10-28 17:56:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Exosomes',12,'Exosomes are small membrane vesicles, typically with a diameter of 30-150 nm, that are secreted by many types of mammalian cells and are found in a variety of body fluids such as blood, urine, and breast milk. They are thought to play a role in intercellular communication and in some cases can transfer proteins, lipids, and genetic material between cells. Exosomes originate from the endosomal compartment of the cell and are formed by the inward budding of the membrane to create intraluminal vesicles. Once formed, the exosomes are released from the cell through fusion with the plasma membrane or phagocytosis by other cells. The content of exosomes can vary depending on the cell type and physiological conditions, and there is growing interest in their use as biomarkers for disease diagnosis and as potential therapeutic agents.','{\"pat_doc\": 1724.0, \"pub_alt\": 1205.0, \"pub_doc\": 4563.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 132.0, \"clinic_alt\": 97.0, \"clinic_doc\": 218.0, \"grant_fund\": 41859550.0, \"pat_granted\": 447.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 265.2, \"pub_doc\": 279.4, \"clinic_doc\": 55.8, \"grant_fund\": -46753820.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('39a0c561bdee0fa78f7e3bd524b83a6c','4823e60bd764349fc024f2fba11838f0','30640b686e5be896faa3d14ed6691346','2023-09-05 18:49:44','2023-10-29 05:35:06','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Biosensor',12,'A biosensor is an analytical device, used for the detection of a chemical substance, that combines a biological component with a physicochemical detector. The sensitive biological element, e.g. tissue, microorganisms, organelles, cell receptors, enzymes, antibodies, nucleic acids, etc., is a biologically derived material or biomimetic component that interacts with, binds with, or recognizes the analyte under study. The biologically sensitive elements can also be created by biological engineering. The transducer or the detector element, which transforms one signal into another one, works in a physicochemical way: optical, piezoelectric, electrochemical, electrochemiluminescence etc., resulting from the interaction of the analyte with the biological element, to easily measure and quantify. The biosensor reader device connects with the associated electronics or signal processors that are primarily responsible for the display of the results in a user-friendly way.','{\"pat_doc\": 2540.0, \"pub_alt\": 1506.0, \"pub_doc\": 9383.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 341.0, \"clinic_alt\": 12.0, \"clinic_doc\": 87.0, \"grant_fund\": 193119825.0, \"pat_granted\": 855.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 137.4, \"pub_doc\": 867.1, \"clinic_doc\": 19.0, \"grant_fund\": -13437491.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('39baeb1a8fec8e0ba4d52c013246b86d','dc9a89b7d5132f4c1c6c291f4d309152','acf051d7127b574167932dffa9cd1c71','2023-09-08 02:48:54','2023-10-28 21:31:14','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Laboratory Information Management System',12,'A laboratory information management system, sometimes referred to as a laboratory information system or laboratory management system, is a software-based solution with features that support a modern laboratorys operations. Key features includeâ€”but are not limited toâ€”workflow and data tracking support, flexible architecture, and data exchange interfaces, which fully \"support its use in regulated environments\". The features and uses of a LIMS have evolved over the years from simple sample tracking to an enterprise resource planning tool that manages multiple aspects of laboratory informatics. There is no useful definition of the term \"LIMS\" as it is used to encompass a number of different laboratory informatics components. The spread and depth of these components is highly dependent on the LIMS implementation itself. All LIMSs have a workflow component and some summary data management facilities but beyond that there are significant differences in functionality.','{\"pat_doc\": 12.0, \"pub_alt\": 27.0, \"pub_doc\": 55.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 297349.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 8.9, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": -5084945.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('39d892b4dd3736c5b447688d0d84d63a','3c24254d6c0d4e4249ab4b441e17dc83','abbcb6a1638f63a5747e204b798f4ec2','2023-09-08 00:41:06','2023-10-29 01:11:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','DNA Synthesis',48,'DNA synthesis is the natural or artificial creation of deoxyribonucleic acid molecules. DNA is a macromolecule made up of nucleotide units, which are linked by covalent bonds and hydrogen bonds, in a repeating structure. DNA synthesis occurs when these nucleotide units are joined to form DNA; this can occur artificially or naturally. Nucleotide units are made up of a nitrogenous base, pentose sugar and phosphate group. Each unit is joined when a covalent bond forms between its phosphate group and the pentose sugar of the next nucleotide, forming a sugar-phosphate backbone. DNA is a complementary, double stranded structure as specific base pairing occurs naturally when hydrogen bonds form between the nucleotide bases. There are several different definitions for DNA synthesis: it can refer to DNA replication - DNA biosynthesis, polymerase chain reaction - enzymatic DNA synthesis or gene synthesis - physically creating artificial gene sequences.','{\"pat_doc\": 634.0, \"pub_alt\": 1004.0, \"pub_doc\": 3485.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 298.0, \"clinic_alt\": 55.0, \"clinic_doc\": 72.0, \"grant_fund\": 159046406.0, \"pat_granted\": 165.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.0, \"pub_doc\": -7.9, \"clinic_doc\": 8.6, \"grant_fund\": -10466344.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('39d94a8c6be756861903a6df46f3490a','1edf5dbb1a5ebbaef987b8b78449add1','d55c8f5e392f4de211e65cb1cf025f9d','2023-09-08 01:07:08','2023-10-29 00:41:20','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Stability',36,'mRNA stability is the measure of how long a messenger RNA (mRNA) molecule lasts within a cell before it is degraded. This is important because the stability of mRNA affects the amount of protein that can be produced from that mRNA. If mRNA is stable, it can persist in the cell and continue to produce protein. However, if the mRNA is unstable, it will degrade quickly and less protein will be produced. mRNA stability is regulated by a number of factors including sequence motifs, RNA-binding proteins, and the presence of other molecules. Understanding how mRNA stability is regulated can provide insights into gene expression and can be helpful in developing new therapies for certain diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 28.0, \"pub_alt\": 1837.0, \"pub_doc\": 1499.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 128.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 80729163.0, \"pat_granted\": 9.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.1, \"pub_doc\": 58.5, \"clinic_doc\": -0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1054364.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('39dc2d7e57295ad7b9860642f0d5c5e0','5799fbde63662e16529cdc2465faa33f','eefb2660a8535eb1d304c9a60295324f','2023-09-08 14:51:25','2023-10-28 18:35:05','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Liposomes',24,'Liposomes are microscopic, spherical vesicles composed of a phospholipid bilayer that is able to encapsulate a variety of water-soluble substances. They are commonly used as drug delivery systems because the lipid bilayer gives them the ability to cross cell membranes and deliver their contents directly to the interior of cells. Liposomes can be prepared in a variety of sizes with different properties, which makes them a versatile tool in medical research and pharmaceuticals. Their biocompatibility and ability to encapsulate both hydrophilic and hydrophobic substances has caused them to become increasingly popular in the fields of drug delivery and cosmetics.','{\"pat_doc\": 1557.0, \"pub_alt\": 501.0, \"pub_doc\": 6304.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 217.0, \"clinic_alt\": 108.0, \"clinic_doc\": 46.0, \"grant_fund\": 53400768.0, \"pat_granted\": 412.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 11.3, \"pub_doc\": 166.2, \"clinic_doc\": 8.1, \"grant_fund\": -13776868.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3a1daa43cae5aff53dfc9ac011d3ff18','3826e17fd1b8b38d7108087bc8b07908','22c986a1ed138cca635623e24850cd2d','2023-09-08 02:47:26','2023-10-28 14:01:15','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel therapies','Progesterone supplementation',36,'Progesterone supplementation, also known as progesterone therapy, is a medical treatment that involves taking supplemental doses of progesterone hormone. Progesterone is naturally produced by the ovaries during a womans menstrual cycle and plays a crucial role in regulating the menstrual cycle and preparing the body for pregnancy. However, some women may have low levels of progesterone, resulting in irregular menstrual cycles or difficulty getting pregnant. Progesterone supplementation can help balance hormonal levels and increase the chances of conceiving and sustaining a pregnancy. It can be administered through various methods, such as pills, injections, or vaginal suppositories, and is usually prescribed by a healthcare professional based on the patients individual needs and medical history.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 73.0, \"pub_doc\": 131.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 38.0, \"grant_fund\": 696125.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 3.4, \"grant_fund\": -80930.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3ab39470400b8ffff9c493fad5d0ccbb','6272d8c4fefc516af912e39ce608f48b','f5961ebdecc3630bd05559901b09f90f','2023-09-08 01:50:58','2023-10-28 15:01:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Gene therapies (Non-viral)','Ribozyme',24,'Ribozymes are RNA molecules that have the ability to catalyze specific biochemical reactions, including RNA splicing in gene expression, similar to the action of protein enzymes. The 1982 discovery of ribozymes demonstrated that RNA can be both genetic material and a biological catalyst, and contributed to the RNA world hypothesis, which suggests that RNA may have been important in the evolution of prebiotic self-replicating systems. The most common activities of natural or in vitro evolved ribozymes are the cleavage of RNA and DNA and peptide bond formation. For example, the smallest ribozyme known can aminoacylate a GCCU-3 sequence in the presence of PheAMP. Within the ribosome, ribozymes function as part of the large subunit ribosomal RNA to link amino acids during protein synthesis. They also participate in a variety of RNA processing reactions, including RNA splicing, viral replication, and transfer RNA biosynthesis.','{\"pat_doc\": 243.0, \"pub_alt\": 286.0, \"pub_doc\": 449.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 31.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 6784491.0, \"pat_granted\": 73.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 8.3, \"pub_doc\": -0.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.2, \"grant_fund\": -2009401.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3ac0b66003d63724e84c1fd1192da132','3e296fb8632883059f895163006d1ec4','47c2be7d4757b7a89106ea7e007a13dc','2023-09-08 00:02:21','2023-10-29 02:11:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Fluorescence In Situ Hybridization',36,'Fluorescence in situ hybridization is a molecular cytogenetic technique that uses fluorescent probes that bind to only particular parts of a nucleic acid sequence with a high degree of sequence complementarity. It was developed by biomedical researchers in the early 1980s to detect and localize the presence or absence of specific DNA sequences on chromosomes. Fluorescence microscopy can be used to find out where the fluorescent probe is bound to the chromosomes. FISH is often used for finding specific features in DNA for use in genetic counseling, medicine, and species identification. FISH can also be used to detect and localize specific RNA targets in cells, circulating tumor cells, and tissue samples. In this context, it can help define the spatial-temporal patterns of gene expression within cells and tissues.','{\"pat_doc\": 184.0, \"pub_alt\": 1177.0, \"pub_doc\": 4106.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 117.0, \"clinic_alt\": 50.0, \"clinic_doc\": 77.0, \"grant_fund\": 61810260.0, \"pat_granted\": 51.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.1, \"pub_doc\": -35.6, \"clinic_doc\": 12.4, \"grant_fund\": -136298.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3ae73f4438b66077b7a817181d42362a','5790a7bed485dce7c0fd1fac61020f51','f1911fd26254d1cbfba1808fbf1f3025','2023-09-08 01:53:10','2023-10-28 23:46:12','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Organ-on chip',12,'An organ-on-a-chip is a multi-channel 3-D microfluidic cell culture, integrated circuit that simulates the activities, mechanics and physiological response of an entire organ or an organ system. It constitutes the subject matter of significant biomedical engineering research, more precisely in bio-MEMS. The convergence of labs-on-chips and cell biology has permitted the study of human physiology in an organ-specific context. By acting as a more sophisticated in vitro approximation of complex tissues than standard cell culture, they provide the potential as an alternative to animal models for drug development and toxin testing. Although multiple publications claim to have translated organ functions onto this interface, the development of these microfluidic applications is still in its infancy. Organs-on-chips vary in design and approach between different researchers.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": -0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3aea0592c001590f6c5730a8c25797e1','ecb5eb0e681dab97bb1d5c09a929aa00','ad11810122ec68f63273a505f81c6d11','2023-09-08 00:01:07','2023-10-28 16:46:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Adeno-associated virus',12,'Adeno-associated viruses are small viruses that infect humans and some other primate species. They belong to the genus Dependoparvovirus, which in turn belongs to the family Parvoviridae. They are small replication-defective, nonenveloped viruses and have linear single-stranded DNA genome of approximately 4.8 kilobases. Several features make AAV an attractive candidate for creating viral vectors for gene therapy, and for the creation of isogenic human disease models. Gene therapy vectors using AAV can infect both dividing and quiescent cells and persist in an extrachromosomal state without integrating into the genome of the host cell. In the native virus, however, integration of virally carried genes into the host genome does occur. Integration can be important for certain applications, but can also have unwanted consequences. Recent human clinical trials using AAV for gene therapy in the retina have shown promise.','{\"pat_doc\": 1636.0, \"pub_alt\": 2540.0, \"pub_doc\": 1481.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 78.0, \"clinic_alt\": 129.0, \"clinic_doc\": 84.0, \"grant_fund\": 55590068.0, \"pat_granted\": 256.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 245.2, \"pub_doc\": 179.9, \"clinic_doc\": 23.4, \"grant_fund\": -12947659.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3afa89e7103e9b56beec0eb03c6ab782','a4a5753db73052249bc74606e77f9c86','3bae6e0ea5ff6b484acb36d0b12b9eb0','2023-09-05 22:21:15','2023-10-29 03:16:16','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cryopreservation',36,'Cryopreservation or cryoconservation is a process where biological material - cells, tissues, or organs - are frozen to preserve the material for an extended period of time. At low temperatures any cell metabolism which might cause damage to the biological material in question is effectively stopped. Cryopreservation is an effective way to transport biological samples over long distances, store samples for prolonged periods of time, and create a bank of samples for users. Molecules, referred to as cryoprotective agents, are added to reduce the osmotic shock and physical stresses cells undergo in the freezing process. Some cryoprotective agents used in research are inspired by plants and animals in nature that have unique cold tolerance to survive harsh winters, including: trees, wood frogs, and tardigrades.','{\"pat_doc\": 2889.0, \"pub_alt\": 1278.0, \"pub_doc\": 5919.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 283.0, \"clinic_alt\": 14.0, \"clinic_doc\": 180.0, \"grant_fund\": 71654022.0, \"pat_granted\": 1305.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 37.6, \"pub_doc\": 46.4, \"clinic_doc\": 29.8, \"grant_fund\": -15784626.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3b4abeace0e3756fc08c87d4b572cfb1','8b3e02763472ad9cc815cfa5df7888cc','451ebb4679c1ff141207f279192eb1c8','2023-09-08 02:50:01','2023-10-28 21:26:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Bio-inspired material',36,'Bio-inspired materials refer to a class of materials inspired by natural designs and architectures found in living systems. These materials incorporate features such as self-assembly, hierarchical structure, and dynamic responsiveness. The idea behind bio-inspired materials is to take inspiration from nature to create advanced materials that have unique and valuable properties not found in conventional materials. Examples of such materials include self-healing polymers, super-strong spider silk-mimicking fibers, and high-performance ceramics based on the structure of seashells. Bio-inspired materials have the potential to lead to the development of new technologies and applications in fields such as medicine, construction, and robotics.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 189.0, \"pub_doc\": 139.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 38357123.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 4.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4564736.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3b623d74a02666201c4989441df7bf6d','cef1c501111b2b4c4a7d99d59f4c45cc','61697279f5d40a0cf2ea206c3315fe94','2023-09-08 00:20:47','2023-10-28 16:31:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Chimeric antigen receptor T cells',36,'Chimeric antigen receptor (CAR) T cells, also known as CAR-T cells, are modified immune cells that are trained to seek and destroy cancer cells. CAR-T cells are created by extracting T cells, a type of white blood cell, from a patients blood and genetically engineering them to produce a special protein called a chimeric antigen receptor. This receptor allows the CAR-T cells to recognize and attack cancer cells that express specific markers on their surface. Once re-infused into the patients bloodstream, the CAR-T cells multiply and aggressively seek out and destroy cancer cells. CAR-T cell therapy has shown promising results in treating certain blood cancers, including leukemia and lymphoma, and is being studied for use in other types of cancer.','{\"pat_doc\": 328.0, \"pub_alt\": 451.0, \"pub_doc\": 676.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 31.0, \"clinic_alt\": 32.0, \"clinic_doc\": 140.0, \"grant_fund\": 39446634.0, \"pat_granted\": 52.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -18.9, \"pub_doc\": 3.4, \"clinic_doc\": 24.6, \"grant_fund\": -2849426.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3ba66d98d69c2fb2f0fe9d6e4467a2da','f1c040e063712c5005b473ffb13588a1','cdaeb54e11180a1df70eb5bc5267c9f8','2023-09-08 09:46:18','2023-10-28 20:36:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Centrifugation',12,'Centrifugation is a mechanical process which involves the use of the centrifugal force to separate particles from a solution according to their size, shape, density, medium viscosity and rotor speed. The denser components of the mixture migrate away from the axis of the centrifuge, while the less dense components of the mixture migrate towards the axis. Chemists and biologists may increase the effective gravitational force of the test tube so that the precipitate will travel quickly and fully to the bottom of the tube. The remaining liquid that lies above the precipitate is called a supernatant or supernate. There is a correlation between the size and density of a particle and the rate that the particle separates from a heterogeneous mixture, when the only force applied is that of gravity. The larger the size and the larger the density of the particles, the faster they separate from the mixture.','{\"pat_doc\": 3705.0, \"pub_alt\": 363.0, \"pub_doc\": 2886.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 34.0, \"clinic_alt\": 29.0, \"clinic_doc\": 238.0, \"grant_fund\": 2903351.0, \"pat_granted\": 1816.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -24.6, \"pub_doc\": 42.5, \"clinic_doc\": 50.1, \"grant_fund\": -9080944.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3bb71bfecc65a30561b104eb9203a2f1','4efee97660391cd588fa5f748e6f0600','eaf48f12d2f6d964781bc23663490cdb','2023-09-08 10:49:43','2023-10-28 19:01:11','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Image Analysis',12,'Image analysis or imagery analysis is the extraction of meaningful information from images; mainly from digital images by means of digital image processing techniques. Image analysis tasks can be as simple as reading bar coded tags or as sophisticated as identifying a person from their face. Computers are indispensable for the analysis of large amounts of data, for tasks that require complex computation, or for the extraction of quantitative information. On the other hand, the human visual cortex is an excellent image analysis apparatus, especially for extracting higher-level information, and for many applications â€” including medicine, security, and remote sensing â€” human analysts still cannot be replaced by computers. For this reason, many important image analysis tools such as edge detectors and neural networks are inspired by human visual perception models.','{\"pat_doc\": 4042.0, \"pub_alt\": 773.0, \"pub_doc\": 7229.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 209.0, \"clinic_alt\": 18.0, \"clinic_doc\": 223.0, \"grant_fund\": 107572712.0, \"pat_granted\": 1336.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 297.4, \"pub_doc\": 418.9, \"clinic_doc\": 55.6, \"grant_fund\": -41339384.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3bced70705e906f2418689dbc6e2d21e','224d3dce630c1eacf85c0f88dd72e042','66dae1bd66572a9ac387868804da7fa9','2023-09-08 00:43:37','2023-10-28 16:11:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Monoclonal antibodies','Bispecific antibody',48,'A bispecific monoclonal antibody is an artificial protein that can simultaneously bind to two different types of antigen or two different epitopes on the same antigen. Naturally occurring antibodies typically only target one antigen. BsAbs can be manufactured in several structural formats. BsAbs can be designed to recruit and activate immune cells, to interfere with receptor signaling and inactivate signaling ligands, and to force association of protein complexes. BsAbs have been explored for cancer immunotherapy, drug delivery, and Alzeimers disease.','{\"pat_doc\": 3826.0, \"pub_alt\": 966.0, \"pub_doc\": 1826.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 65.0, \"clinic_alt\": 859.0, \"clinic_doc\": 238.0, \"grant_fund\": 89119415.0, \"pat_granted\": 625.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 160.2, \"pub_doc\": 80.4, \"clinic_doc\": 59.6, \"grant_fund\": 14897954.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3bfc3e9a32907a004b35ffad45621aac','00deab06d5e60c8c68a35ce17a92c7a4','9910e15122e1c94e1e5ae9068add6ff3','2023-09-05 22:04:15','2023-10-29 03:41:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Genome Editing',12,'Genome editing, or genome engineering, or gene editing, is a type of genetic engineering in which DNA is inserted, deleted, modified or replaced in the genome of a living organism. Unlike early genetic engineering techniques that randomly inserts genetic material into a host genome, genome editing targets the insertions to site-specific locations. The basic mechanism involved in genetic manipulations through programmable nucleases is the recognition of target genomic loci and binding of effector DNA-binding domain, double-strand breaks in target DNA by the restriction endonucleases, and the repair of DSBs through homology-directed recombination or non-homologous end joining.','{\"pat_doc\": 753.0, \"pub_alt\": 1334.0, \"pub_doc\": 2642.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 246.0, \"clinic_alt\": 13.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 183942570.0, \"pat_granted\": 183.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 18.2, \"pub_doc\": 106.1, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -34230182.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3c39d5f3355e92c1a24a6fcdc014dc0e','6ee75b4e6fefbd3534f1769a0b6e2972','e27f505c9d666365d5d09dc9decf7e50','2023-09-05 21:10:38','2023-10-28 12:30:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','6G',36,'6G technology is the next-generation wireless communication technology that is under development and expected to be commercialized by 2030. It is said to be 100 times faster than 5G with higher reliability, low latency and more secure communication. 6G will enable high-speed internet connectivity and high-resolution video streaming. It will also support the Internet of Things (IoT), artificial intelligence (AI), machine learning (ML), and virtual reality (VR) technologies. The development of 6G technology is still in the early stages with some countries having already started research on the technology. However, it is expected to bring significant changes to the way we live and work to enable new products and services that will drive innovation across different industries.','{\"pat_doc\": 6689.0, \"pub_alt\": 955.0, \"pub_doc\": 18574.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 899.0, \"clinic_alt\": 34.0, \"clinic_doc\": 256.0, \"grant_fund\": 1071003600.0, \"pat_granted\": 1724.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 485.2, \"pub_doc\": 1244.7, \"clinic_doc\": 33.1, \"grant_fund\": 83405037.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3cce9a94fb344a9ac8f896b70ffcf53f','46bdeb9160300133a73dc543b9ff12d8','e2208eebd283dcf9b3906ac407a5d224','2023-09-08 02:23:43','2023-10-28 14:31:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Gigantism',48,'Gigantism, also known as giantism, is a condition characterized by excessive growth and height significantly above average. In humans, this condition is caused by over-production of growth hormone in childhood, resulting in people up to 2.7 m in height. It is a rare disorder resulting from increased levels of growth hormone before the fusion of the growth plate which usually occurs at some point soon after puberty. This increase is most often due to abnormal tumor growths on the pituitary gland. Gigantism should not be confused with acromegaly, the adult form of the disorder, characterized by somatic enlargement specifically in the extremities and face.','{\"pat_doc\": 7.0, \"pub_alt\": 7410.0, \"pub_doc\": 451.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 20.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 5903696.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.9, \"pub_doc\": -6.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -404062.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3cd4b336d91392d1a775e3a3e7cb0b14','f90e9c061ea63f3d762a3d1141314989','30640b686e5be896faa3d14ed6691346','2023-09-05 18:55:23','2023-10-29 05:31:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Biosensor',36,'A biosensor is an analytical device, used for the detection of a chemical substance, that combines a biological component with a physicochemical detector. The sensitive biological element, e.g. tissue, microorganisms, organelles, cell receptors, enzymes, antibodies, nucleic acids, etc., is a biologically derived material or biomimetic component that interacts with, binds with, or recognizes the analyte under study. The biologically sensitive elements can also be created by biological engineering. The transducer or the detector element, which transforms one signal into another one, works in a physicochemical way: optical, piezoelectric, electrochemical, electrochemiluminescence etc., resulting from the interaction of the analyte with the biological element, to easily measure and quantify. The biosensor reader device connects with the associated electronics or signal processors that are primarily responsible for the display of the results in a user-friendly way.','{\"pat_doc\": 7686.0, \"pub_alt\": 3920.0, \"pub_doc\": 26404.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1614.0, \"clinic_alt\": 52.0, \"clinic_doc\": 141.0, \"grant_fund\": 751880011.0, \"pat_granted\": 2491.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 137.4, \"pub_doc\": 867.1, \"clinic_doc\": 19.0, \"grant_fund\": -13437491.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3d4aee428a090bc2f112da13f621c464','093421fa544b6541b1aa9445b0324876','c69cae5bf0730201ed4820a70e56cfc2','2023-09-08 09:08:02','2023-10-28 13:26:11','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Gastrointestinal Cancer',12,'Gastrointestinal cancer refers to malignant conditions of the gastrointestinal tract and accessory organs of digestion, including the esophagus, stomach, biliary system, pancreas, small intestine, large intestine, rectum and anus. The symptoms relate to the organ affected and can include obstruction, abnormal bleeding or other associated problems. The diagnosis often requires endoscopy, followed by biopsy of suspicious tissue. The treatment depends on the location of the tumor, as well as the type of cancer cell and whether it has invaded other tissues or spread elsewhere. These factors also determine the prognosis. Overall, the GI tract and the accessory organs of digestion are responsible for more cancers and more deaths from cancer than any other system in the body. There is significant geographic variation in the rates of different gastrointestinal cancers.','{\"pat_doc\": 53.0, \"pub_alt\": 1676.0, \"pub_doc\": 1170.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 19.0, \"clinic_alt\": 412.0, \"clinic_doc\": 192.0, \"grant_fund\": 6359221.0, \"pat_granted\": 7.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.9, \"pub_doc\": 83.2, \"clinic_doc\": 43.7, \"grant_fund\": -5165841.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3d5005b2542614c3d1b821e179b7f9a3','860562e383a8d17a8f172fa2f70cc8f9','aeef280b6e10fec919822406e149ebb2','2023-09-08 02:33:55','2023-10-28 14:16:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Lipid regulation',24,'Lipid regulation is the process of maintaining healthy levels of lipids in the body. Lipids are a type of molecule that includes fats, oils, and waxes. They are essential for many functions in the body, including providing energy and helping with the absorption of vitamins. However, too much or too little of certain types of lipids can lead to health problems. For example, high levels of cholesterol can increase the risk of heart disease, while low levels of essential fatty acids can lead to inflammation and other issues. Efficient lipid regulation requires a balanced diet and regular exercise, along with possible medication if needed.','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_alt\": 1137.0, \"pub_doc\": 131.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 19.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 8462199.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": 5.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.4, \"grant_fund\": 1008259.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3d79e5aa826b2b9dce78ea810e0375d3','6e9cf23bacc0f67b8c70385963421414','75c037afe780bd09b9ce614027c7464a','2023-09-08 01:52:03','2023-10-28 23:51:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Cell-Free System',12,'A cell-free system is an in vitro tool widely used to study biological reactions that happen within cells apart from a full cell system, thus reducing the complex interactions typically found when working in a whole cell. Subcellular fractions can be isolated by ultracentrifugation to provide molecular machinery that can be used in reactions in the absence of many of the other cellular components. Eukaryotic and prokaryotic cell internals have been used for creation of these simplified environments. These systems have enabled cell-free synthetic biology to emerge, providing control over what reaction is being examined, as well as its yield, and lessening the considerations otherwise invoked when working with more sensitive live cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 49.0, \"pub_alt\": 168.0, \"pub_doc\": 183.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 14.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 7417593.0, \"pat_granted\": 14.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.4, \"pub_doc\": 1.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 604452.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3db286e469fd2f478b5b7c51a671d446','46bdeb9160300133a73dc543b9ff12d8','e2208eebd283dcf9b3906ac407a5d224','2023-09-08 02:23:43','2023-10-28 14:31:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Gigantism',12,'Gigantism, also known as giantism, is a condition characterized by excessive growth and height significantly above average. In humans, this condition is caused by over-production of growth hormone in childhood, resulting in people up to 2.7 m in height. It is a rare disorder resulting from increased levels of growth hormone before the fusion of the growth plate which usually occurs at some point soon after puberty. This increase is most often due to abnormal tumor growths on the pituitary gland. Gigantism should not be confused with acromegaly, the adult form of the disorder, characterized by somatic enlargement specifically in the extremities and face.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 7410.0, \"pub_doc\": 103.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 544345.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.9, \"pub_doc\": -6.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -404062.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3e2dfa65b676167ddd8a9f7cc7c427e4','2dd9d7ef89e93089944c052185d5b575','ce749f284f6019c4ac54019c71229b4d','2023-09-08 09:58:49','2023-10-28 19:41:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','digital droplet PCR',24,'Digital droplet PCR (ddPCR) is a highly sensitive and specific technique used for quantifying nucleic acids. ddPCR partitions a sample into thousands of droplets containing one or zero target molecules. The droplets are then subjected to PCR amplification and fluorescence analysis to determine which droplets contain the target molecule. This allows for highly precise quantification of the initial amount of target nucleic acid in the original sample, with a sensitivity of up to one copy per reaction. ddPCR has numerous applications in fields such as cancer research, infectious disease diagnosis, and genetic testing.','{\"pat_doc\": 20.0, \"pub_alt\": 313.0, \"pub_doc\": 292.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 12.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 5503180.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": -2.8, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": -559015.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3e4241c3e05f9ec2d099c8d8e4995008','511fe46a46ed4b151dc1fca695ee35f6','3351a35ba591fc4123a3314384741e66','2023-09-08 01:54:20','2023-10-28 23:41:13','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Cationic polymers',12,'In chemistry, cationic polymerization is a type of chain growth polymerization in which a cationic initiator transfers charge to a monomer which then becomes reactive. This reactive monomer goes on to react similarly with other monomers to form a polymer. The types of monomers necessary for cationic polymerization are limited to alkenes with electron-donating substituents and heterocycles. Similar to anionic polymerization reactions, cationic polymerization reactions are very sensitive to the type of solvent used. Specifically, the ability of a solvent to form free ions will dictate the reactivity of the propagating cationic chain. Cationic polymerization is used in the production of polyisobutylene and poly.','{\"pat_doc\": 157.0, \"pub_alt\": 38.0, \"pub_doc\": 111.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 9.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1172361.0, \"pat_granted\": 55.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -10.9, \"pub_doc\": -2.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 44316.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3e774746a7f26c79a441c8064d3b170e','55794ad69e12330a0b6d80e9fdb0988d','e612e4b67f9789306cf3914a627ea83c','2023-09-07 23:58:23','2023-10-29 02:16:16','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Metabolic Engineering',24,'Metabolic engineering is the practice of optimizing genetic and regulatory processes within cells to increase the cells production of a certain substance. These processes are chemical networks that use a series of biochemical reactions and enzymes that allow cells to convert raw materials into molecules necessary for the cells survival. Metabolic engineering specifically seeks to mathematically model these networks, calculate a yield of useful products, and pin point parts of the network that constrain the production of these products. Genetic engineering techniques can then be used to modify the network in order to relieve these constraints. Once again this modified network can be modeled to calculate the new product yield. The ultimate goal of metabolic engineering is to be able to use these organisms to produce valuable substances on an industrial scale in a cost-effective manner.','{\"pat_doc\": 511.0, \"pub_alt\": 260.0, \"pub_doc\": 2376.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 114.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 40065440.0, \"pat_granted\": 157.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 34.9, \"pub_doc\": 16.6, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -6039306.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3ef0b5cbe81c1bb201540339a8fed2e2','fff9e1e5499bae01aa4fb0b484f21e1e','6a1c4a31986c97cfddf4de1bf91188d1','2023-09-05 21:08:55','2023-10-28 12:35:32','Electronics','Devices','Connectivity','Wearable devices',12,'Wearable technology is any technology that is designed to be used while worn. Common types of wearable technology include smartwatches and smartglasses. Wearable electronic devices are often close to or on the surface of the skin, where they detect, analyze, and transmit information such as vital signs, and/or ambient data and which allow in some cases immediate biofeedback to the wearer. Wearable devices such as activity trackers are an example of the Internet of Things, since \"things\" such as electronics, software, sensors, and connectivity are effectors that enable objects to exchange data through the internet with a manufacturer, operator, and/or other connected devices, without requiring human intervention. Wearable technology offers a wide range of possible uses, from communication and entertainment to improving health and fitness, however, there are worries about privacy and security because wearable devices have the ability to collect personal data.','{\"pat_doc\": 881.0, \"pub_alt\": 4130.0, \"pub_doc\": 3556.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 105.0, \"clinic_alt\": 525.0, \"clinic_doc\": 208.0, \"grant_fund\": 103943721.0, \"pat_granted\": 295.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 43.4, \"pub_doc\": 482.3, \"clinic_doc\": 56.6, \"grant_fund\": 2342060.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3f146c7fa160a8eea2ccd0f3a486fc5a','ad14e59d8d8e44865760de1a016459ca','15926313fb5354a8aa389bc294cbeab7','2023-09-05 20:43:37','2023-10-29 04:36:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein-Protein Interaction',24,'Proteinâ€“protein interactions are physical contacts of high specificity established between two or more protein molecules as a result of biochemical events steered by interactions that include electrostatic forces, hydrogen bonding and the hydrophobic effect. Many are physical contacts with molecular associations between chains that occur in a cell or in a living organism in a specific biomolecular context. Proteins rarely act alone as their functions tend to be regulated. Many molecular processes within a cell are carried out by molecular machines that are built from numerous protein components organized by their PPIs. These physiological interactions make up the so-called interactomics of the organism, while aberrant PPIs are the basis of multiple aggregation-related diseases, such as Creutzfeldtâ€“Jakob and Alzheimers diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 433.0, \"pub_alt\": 1359.0, \"pub_doc\": 10393.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 529.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.0, \"grant_fund\": 195050218.0, \"pat_granted\": 107.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.7, \"pub_doc\": 265.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.4, \"grant_fund\": -40776859.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('3f9730fdbf03b32fc8e0e25c231417cc','42ee32d5802de92090c858e3452a50cf','d7426f446b19a6b58ca2ef44eac3e4b3','2023-09-08 01:12:46','2023-10-29 00:31:27','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','3D Cell Culture',12,'A 3D cell culture is an artificially created environment in which biological cells are permitted to grow or interact with their surroundings in all three dimensions. Unlike 2D environments, a 3D cell culture allows cells in vitro to grow in all directions, similar to how they would in vivo. These three-dimensional cultures are usually grown in bioreactors, small capsules in which the cells can grow into spheroids, or 3D cell colonies. Approximately 300 spheroids are usually cultured per bioreactor. 3D cell cultures can also be performed on microfluidic devices such as the OrganoplateÂ® to generate perfusable 3D tissues, and hanging drop devices to generate 3D spheroids.','{\"pat_doc\": 70.0, \"pub_alt\": 255.0, \"pub_doc\": 405.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 38.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 13709173.0, \"pat_granted\": 16.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 5.8, \"pub_doc\": 19.4, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -5741441.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('40e664e18d9317435225aa7cbc408d56','b2cee85dff870540c318cdc9d046cdcd','c3c3761ddee3a08a11545145a56cc763','2023-09-05 21:43:53','2023-10-29 03:56:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Co-culture',36,'Co-culture refers to the interaction and exchange between two or more distinct cultures. This can occur through direct contact or through mediated channels, such as media or trade. The concept of co-culture recognizes that cultures do not exist in isolation but are rather constantly interacting and influencing one another. It is important to understand co-culture in order to appreciate cultural diversity and to build bridges between cultures. Co-culture can lead to cultural fusion, which is the blending of elements from different cultures to create a new, hybrid culture. This can be seen in the arts, cuisine, and fashion, among other areas. However, co-culture can also lead to conflict and tension, particularly when different cultures have contrasting beliefs or values. By recognizing the role of co-culture, individuals and societies can foster greater understanding and appreciation for diverse cultural perspectives.','{\"pat_doc\": 1844.0, \"pub_alt\": 1279.0, \"pub_doc\": 12754.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1174.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 73.0, \"grant_fund\": 394907223.0, \"pat_granted\": 631.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 54.4, \"pub_doc\": 183.5, \"clinic_doc\": 11.2, \"grant_fund\": -35120452.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('410430bcad78914a0682c04adb651033','4e9ebfbe4ac1ae58051339eff3ea0804','7358f1cae0370dbf5dda96c078758305','2023-09-08 11:07:58','2023-10-28 18:51:10','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Predictive Analytics',12,'Predictive analytics is a form of business analytics applying machine learning to generate a predictive model for certain business applications. As such, it encompasses a variety of statistical techniques from predictive modeling and machine learning that analyze current and historical facts to make predictions about future or otherwise unknown events. It represents a major subset of machine learning applications; in some contexts, it is synonymous with machine learning. In business, predictive models exploit patterns found in historical and transactional data to identify risks and opportunities. Models capture relationships among many factors to allow assessment of risk or potential associated with a particular set of conditions, guiding decision-making for candidate transactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 176.0, \"pub_alt\": 374.0, \"pub_doc\": 898.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 44.0, \"clinic_alt\": 15.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 46858462.0, \"pat_granted\": 36.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.6, \"pub_doc\": 64.5, \"clinic_doc\": 4.1, \"grant_fund\": -4049855.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('410789efccbcc8d04c2b5ef4aa88a514','629f564fa930d422fbfc8405c3bae6c0','72a385b9d786832dcc2c823f54ed4998','2023-09-05 20:39:21','2023-10-28 12:40:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Digital Twin',36,'A digital twin is a digital representation of an intended or actual real-world physical product, system, or process that serves as the effectively indistinguishable digital counterpart of it for practical purposes, such as simulation, integration, testing, monitoring, and maintenance. The digital twin has been intended from its initial introduction to be the underlying premise for Product Lifecycle Management and exists throughout the entire lifecycle of the physical entity it represents. Since information is granular, the digital twin representation is determined by the value-based use cases it is created to implement. The digital twin can and does often exist before there is a physical entity. The use of a digital twin in the creation phase allows the intended entitys entire lifecycle to be modeled and simulated. A digital twin of an existing entity may be used in real-time and regularly synchronized with the corresponding physical system.','{\"pat_doc\": 8384.0, \"pub_alt\": 767.0, \"pub_doc\": 14479.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1961.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 2420987170.0, \"pat_granted\": 1714.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1361.7, \"pub_doc\": 1705.1, \"clinic_doc\": 4.4, \"grant_fund\": 206480656.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('416cffb0b00805b579a8be758973ae23','19f291b8d80548406a90803fc4e33614','a3e69530e54da2bd3284f3d40c81f2e9','2023-09-08 02:13:20','2023-10-28 22:56:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Microarray',24,'A protein microarray is a high-throughput method used to track the interactions and activities of proteins, and to determine their function, and determining function on a large scale. Its main advantage lies in the fact that large numbers of proteins can be tracked in parallel. The chip consists of a support surface such as a glass slide, nitrocellulose membrane, bead, or microtitre plate, to which an array of capture proteins is bound. Probe molecules, typically labeled with a fluorescent dye, are added to the array. Any reaction between the probe and the immobilised protein emits a fluorescent signal that is read by a laser scanner. Protein microarrays are rapid, automated, economical, and highly sensitive, consuming small quantities of samples and reagents. The concept and methodology of protein microarrays was first introduced and illustrated in antibody microarrays in 1983 in a scientific publication and a series of patents.','{\"pat_doc\": 24.0, \"pub_alt\": 2002.0, \"pub_doc\": 224.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_alt\": 15.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 5648676.0, \"pat_granted\": 9.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.4, \"pub_doc\": -10.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.6, \"grant_fund\": -222800.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4174d83fc2251237d4364826287cdc4f','5e047db7e10164d6ec0e89c2fe69a4b9','589b84d604aa424bb142db78b62d89e3','2023-09-08 02:00:38','2023-10-28 23:26:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Electrophoresis',12,'Protein electrophoresis is a method for analysing the proteins in a fluid or an extract. The electrophoresis may be performed with a small volume of sample in a number of alternative ways with or without a supporting medium: SDS polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis, free-flow electrophoresis, electrofocusing, isotachophoresis, affinity electrophoresis, immunoelectrophoresis, counterelectrophoresis, and capillary electrophoresis. Each method has many variations with individual advantages and limitations. Gel electrophoresis is often performed in combination with electroblotting immunoblotting to give additional information about a specific protein. Because of practical limitations, protein electrophoresis is generally not suited as a preparative method.','{\"pat_doc\": 21.0, \"pub_alt\": 64.0, \"pub_doc\": 216.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 43.0, \"clinic_doc\": 18.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 3.1, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -94204.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4193319b658ba3424d4a87ab23a61930','fa64bf855faf8c0f2191aab2fb8e889c','1eb03b411e805213588194c37797ec5c','2023-09-05 21:42:31','2023-10-28 17:41:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Hypothyroidism',36,'Hypothyroidism is a disorder of the endocrine system in which the thyroid gland does not produce enough thyroid hormone. It can cause a number of symptoms, such as poor ability to tolerate cold, a feeling of tiredness, constipation, slow heart rate, depression, and weight gain. Occasionally there may be swelling of the front part of the neck due to goitre. Untreated cases of hypothyroidism during pregnancy can lead to delays in growth and intellectual development in the baby or congenital iodine deficiency syndrome. Worldwide, too little iodine in the diet is the most common cause of hypothyroidism. Hashimotos thyroiditis is the most common cause of hypothyroidism in countries with sufficient dietary iodine. Less common causes include previous treatment with radioactive iodine, injury to the hypothalamus or the anterior pituitary gland, certain medications, a lack of a functioning thyroid at birth, or previous thyroid surgery.','{\"pat_doc\": 175.0, \"pub_alt\": 1214.0, \"pub_doc\": 10491.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 98.0, \"clinic_alt\": 28.0, \"clinic_doc\": 612.0, \"grant_fund\": 17286831.0, \"pat_granted\": 21.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.4, \"pub_doc\": 201.3, \"clinic_doc\": 62.3, \"grant_fund\": -98143.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('41e11c0a457a317b6a8c1ce79d6fe2cc','00deab06d5e60c8c68a35ce17a92c7a4','9910e15122e1c94e1e5ae9068add6ff3','2023-09-05 22:04:15','2023-10-29 03:41:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Genome Editing',48,'Genome editing, or genome engineering, or gene editing, is a type of genetic engineering in which DNA is inserted, deleted, modified or replaced in the genome of a living organism. Unlike early genetic engineering techniques that randomly inserts genetic material into a host genome, genome editing targets the insertions to site-specific locations. The basic mechanism involved in genetic manipulations through programmable nucleases is the recognition of target genomic loci and binding of effector DNA-binding domain, double-strand breaks in target DNA by the restriction endonucleases, and the repair of DSBs through homology-directed recombination or non-homologous end joining.','{\"pat_doc\": 3140.0, \"pub_alt\": 3578.0, \"pub_doc\": 10377.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2137.0, \"clinic_alt\": 67.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.0, \"grant_fund\": 1092292589.0, \"pat_granted\": 578.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 18.2, \"pub_doc\": 106.1, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -34230182.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('420a4ddb81acb37fa92fca5fc05fda3c','3dc3dd5d2df2a0b127886fa91ef3f5d5','606edbb39b7dac4ec5ef367e4247cc8d','2023-09-08 09:54:26','2023-10-28 20:01:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Ion Chromatography',24,'Ion chromatography is a form of chromatography that separates ions and polar molecules based on their affinity to the ion exchanger. It works on almost any kind of charged moleculeâ€”including large proteins, small nucleotides, and amino acids. However, ion chromatography must be done in conditions that are one unit away from the isoelectric point of a protein. The two types of ion chromatography are anion-exchange and cation-exchange. Cation-exchange chromatography is used when the molecule of interest is positively charged. The molecule is positively charged because the pH for chromatography is less than the pI. In this type of chromatography, the stationary phase is negatively charged and positively charged molecules are loaded to be attracted to it. Anion-exchange chromatography is when the stationary phase is positively charged and negatively charged molecules are loaded to be attracted to it. It is often used in protein purification, water analysis, and quality control.','{\"pat_doc\": 2079.0, \"pub_alt\": 473.0, \"pub_doc\": 4929.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 89.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 20198492.0, \"pat_granted\": 668.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.4, \"pub_doc\": -31.8, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": -6435445.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('42302b0e92d24f90f5754dd8774a8695','525ddc02deb579259414604666af7d2e','e910bc33478f3cb83e3ef258c7d92a6c','2023-09-08 02:02:55','2023-10-28 14:55:06','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel therapies','Gonadotropin-Releasing-Hormone Agonist',24,'A gonadotropin-releasing hormone agonist is a type of medication which affects gonadotropins and sex hormones. They are used for a variety of indications including in fertility medicine and to lower sex hormone levels in the treatment of hormone-sensitive cancers such as prostate cancer and breast cancer, certain gynecological disorders like heavy periods and endometriosis, high testosterone levels in women, early puberty in children, as a part of transgender hormone therapy, and to delay puberty in transgender youth among other uses. It is also used in the suppression of spontaneous ovulation as part of controlled ovarian hyperstimulation, an essential component in in IVF. GnRH agonists are given by injections into fat, as implants placed into fat, and as nasal sprays.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 21.0, \"pub_doc\": 1.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('42716284b1174e87d45dff55365afb74','de3c47ca09e78512850cba5b26eb1590','85e7d38a1e770cd1c8c35e8a00e24e8d','2023-09-05 23:12:11','2023-10-29 02:46:12','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','X-ray Crystallography',24,'X-ray crystallography is the experimental science determining the atomic and molecular structure of a crystal, in which the crystalline structure causes a beam of incident X-rays to diffract into many specific directions. By measuring the angles and intensities of these diffracted beams, a crystallographer can produce a three-dimensional picture of the density of electrons within the crystal. From this electron density, the mean positions of the atoms in the crystal can be determined, as well as their chemical bonds, their crystallographic disorder, and various other information. Since many materials can form crystalsâ€”such as salts, metals, minerals, semiconductors, as well as various inorganic, organic, and biological moleculesâ€”X-ray crystallography has been fundamental in the development of many scientific fields.','{\"pat_doc\": 69.0, \"pub_alt\": 1051.0, \"pub_doc\": 3239.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 309.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 262169972.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.7, \"pub_doc\": -59.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -3454168.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('42e216fbd7591f711e623c7578b3763c','f6196df8d7ae9a4d7f729e93364e0bd8','f612c4461ae2b2296d600f221ca9683b','2023-09-08 00:23:58','2023-10-29 01:46:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Cryo-electron microscopy',48,'Cryo-electron microscopy (cryo-EM) is an imaging technique used to determine the three-dimensional structures of biological macromolecules at near-atomic resolution. It involves the rapid freezing of a sample and the use of an electron microscope to capture images of the frozen sample from multiple angles. These images are then combined and analyzed computationally to generate a high-resolution 3D model of the sample. Cryo-EM has revolutionized the field of structural biology, allowing researchers to study previously inaccessible proteins and complexes and providing new insights into biological processes such as protein folding, virus-host interactions, and drug binding. Its ability to work with relatively small samples, including single molecules, and its potential for automated imaging make cryo-EM a powerful tool for drug discovery and structural biology research.','{\"pat_doc\": 52.0, \"pub_alt\": 4035.0, \"pub_doc\": 3921.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 854.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 482487812.0, \"pat_granted\": 10.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_doc\": 58.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -19994930.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('433c2fd8a422e24916e8045dadd74c98','014a9a76a066045b2a9bf86aedfb7d7c','9b98ef926c70dcba53c5447a923e9d23','2023-09-08 02:30:56','2023-10-28 22:06:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Sequencing',36,'Protein sequencing is the practical process of determining the amino acid sequence of all or part of a protein or peptide. This may serve to identify the protein or characterize its post-translational modifications. Typically, partial sequencing of a protein provides sufficient information to identify it with reference to databases of protein sequences derived from the conceptual translation of genes. The two major direct methods of protein sequencing are mass spectrometry and Edman degradation using a protein sequenator. Mass spectrometry methods are now the most widely used for protein sequencing and identification but Edman degradation remains a valuable tool for characterizing a proteins N-terminus.','{\"pat_doc\": 129.0, \"pub_alt\": 424.0, \"pub_doc\": 219.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 51.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 21903624.0, \"pat_granted\": 20.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.9, \"pub_doc\": 7.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": 2760440.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('433ed13ae1579e9e50bbb0b697b446e3','3826e17fd1b8b38d7108087bc8b07908','22c986a1ed138cca635623e24850cd2d','2023-09-08 02:47:26','2023-10-28 14:01:15','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel therapies','Progesterone supplementation',12,'Progesterone supplementation, also known as progesterone therapy, is a medical treatment that involves taking supplemental doses of progesterone hormone. Progesterone is naturally produced by the ovaries during a womans menstrual cycle and plays a crucial role in regulating the menstrual cycle and preparing the body for pregnancy. However, some women may have low levels of progesterone, resulting in irregular menstrual cycles or difficulty getting pregnant. Progesterone supplementation can help balance hormonal levels and increase the chances of conceiving and sustaining a pregnancy. It can be administered through various methods, such as pills, injections, or vaginal suppositories, and is usually prescribed by a healthcare professional based on the patients individual needs and medical history.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 13.0, \"pub_doc\": 49.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 18.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 3.4, \"grant_fund\": -80930.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('43b51ca0642895aba3c9c885158fdddc','d702a8adc5dbea4b170f75415100b3b5','4aebb65d3ef171435ae3068e3a2c9f22','2023-09-04 18:33:18','2023-10-29 07:01:15','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Stem Cells',36,'Stem cells are undifferentiated cells that have the ability to differentiate into specialized cells and regenerate damaged tissues in the body. These cells have the potential to give rise to any cell type in the body, such as blood, bone, muscle, and nerve cells. Stem cells can be classified into embryonic, fetal, and adult stem cells based on their origin and potential to differentiate. Embryonic stem cells are obtained from early-stage embryos and can differentiate into any cell type, while fetal and adult stem cells are found in various tissues and have a more limited differentiation potential. Stem cell research shows promise for developing treatments for a range of diseases and conditions.','{\"pat_doc\": 19606.0, \"pub_alt\": 3957.0, \"pub_doc\": 60894.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5912.0, \"clinic_alt\": 531.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2323.0, \"grant_fund\": 2512184991.0, \"pat_granted\": 5813.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 141.4, \"pub_doc\": -576.1, \"clinic_doc\": 354.8, \"grant_fund\": -242932791.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('43c77f2ced4da9deb4179402b13e06d0','e1c03cd2dbe1db8089d68f8b8c8054b0','e21059dfa6307a406da37caf3abb3281','2023-09-08 09:10:54','2023-10-28 13:16:11','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Urothelial cancer',12,'Urothelial cancer is a type of cancer that develops in the urothelial cells, which line the urinary tract. It is also known as transitional cell carcinoma. This type of cancer can develop in the bladder, ureters, or renal pelvis. The majority of urothelial cancers are found in the bladder, and symptoms may include blood in the urine, painful urination, and frequent urination. Urothelial cancer can be treated with surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy, and the prognosis can vary depending on the stage of the cancer. Early detection and treatment can lead to a better outcome, so it is important to seek medical attention if any symptoms are present.','{\"pat_doc\": 74.0, \"pub_alt\": 444.0, \"pub_doc\": 467.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1167.0, \"clinic_doc\": 202.0, \"grant_fund\": 794213.0, \"pat_granted\": 16.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_doc\": -5.4, \"clinic_doc\": 57.4, \"grant_fund\": -606977.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('43c9f73ff9e62a3df3b9f5d02cda3922','ab4b6025c38d1cab8fd476593532cb60','8c907d5d7b60b5604cad502b2ab3ea5b','2023-09-08 01:44:40','2023-10-28 11:20:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Societal & Economic Disruptions','Russia-Ukraine conflict',48,'The Russo-Ukrainian War is an ongoing international conflict between Russia, alongside Russian-backed separatists, and Ukraine, which began in February 2014. Following Ukraines Revolution of Dignity, Russia annexed Crimea from Ukraine and supported pro-Russian separatists fighting the Ukrainian military in the Donbas war. The first eight years of conflict also included naval incidents, cyberwarfare, and heightened political tensions. In February 2022, Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine. In early 2014, the Euromaidan protests led to the Revolution of Dignity and the ousting of Ukraines pro-Russian president Viktor Yanukovych. Shortly after, pro-Russian unrest erupted in eastern and southern Ukraine. Simultaneously, unmarked Russian troops moved into Ukraines Crimea and took over government buildings, strategic sites and infrastructure. Russia soon annexed Crimea after a highly-disputed referendum.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 4755.0, \"pub_doc\": 382.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 529815.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 93.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 113103.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('43f91c51e18719b942252c14a3c184d5','e1e4825f9e69d0bff75f7b5f1728fa6c','de90a1c4d8531674dd30ee9b71846822','2023-09-08 02:18:06','2023-10-28 22:36:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Aseptic Technique',48,'Aseptic techniques are procedures followed by individual working in a area which is highly controlled with respect to its level of microbial count. The level of microbial count is controlled to eliminate their contamination in product, while processing aseptically in the working place like laminar air flow bench, unidirectional flow bench mainly used in pharmaceutical manufacturing of sterile drug products, and microbial testing labs. Aseptic techniques include the sterilization method of microbiological culture handling wire loops, which are required to hold over flame on a gas burner, before use in order to sterilize it. The growing procedures are adapted inside a critical area while handling sterile products or microbial culture. The sequential movement of material in and out of the critical area, sequential man movement and their dexterity of handling of the sterile product and the intervention methods altogether are called aseptic techniques.','{\"pat_doc\": 283.0, \"pub_alt\": 103.0, \"pub_doc\": 456.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 102.0, \"grant_fund\": 1084126.0, \"pat_granted\": 234.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -10.9, \"pub_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.6, \"grant_fund\": 112023.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('440a4c175eaae2294a5441eba45abd8f','1e66ed53f01f8188292c5c3609da476b','a58988e9b10205f335d6db1eeecb2311','2023-09-08 02:46:05','2023-10-28 21:36:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Expression System',12,'A Protein Expression System is a method used to produce proteins for scientific research, pharmaceutical development, and other applications. The system involves introducing DNA fragments encoding the desired protein sequence into a host cell, which then uses its own cellular machinery to produce the protein. Common hosts for protein expression include bacteria, yeast, and mammalian cells, with each system offering its own advantages and limitations. This method allows for the production of large quantities of a specific protein, aiding in the study of its function and potential therapeutic properties.','{\"pat_doc\": 55.0, \"pub_alt\": 79.0, \"pub_doc\": 52.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 10.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 3773595.0, \"pat_granted\": 16.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.7, \"pub_doc\": 3.2, \"clinic_doc\": -0.2, \"grant_fund\": -14107859.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('44131b77db73c3bdf3d9dbc0a6ee6e32','3cd9bdd88ba7ae8b9d89cbab89c2b25b','461ca981d4ebaba8ec09f7fd419f33b2','2023-09-08 01:09:47','2023-10-29 00:36:23','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Solid dispersion',48,'Solid dispersion is a technique used in the pharmaceutical industry to improve the solubility and bioavailability of poorly water-soluble drugs. It involves the preparation of a solid mixture of a drug with a hydrophilic carrier, such as a polymer or a surfactant, where the drug is dispersed in a molecularly or colloidal form in the carrier matrix. The resulting system exhibits an increased surface area of the drug particles and facilitates the formation of supersaturated solutions upon dissolution in aqueous media, leading to enhanced drug absorption and better therapeutic efficacy. Solid dispersion offers several advantages over traditional formulations, including reduced drug doses, improved patient compliance, and lowered production costs. Despite its potential benefits, the design and optimization of solid dispersions require careful consideration of various factors, such as drug-carrier interactions, drug loading, and stability.','{\"pat_doc\": 2343.0, \"pub_alt\": 347.0, \"pub_doc\": 2065.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 40.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 17.0, \"grant_fund\": 7518040.0, \"pat_granted\": 566.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 29.1, \"pub_doc\": 19.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.9, \"grant_fund\": -1206355.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('442d227f48c4c970250d5765a2f23afa','5ca1037faccf16f0f31845755f697cb1','a9ac8b399c3d26dbcd46f8f3ee6f5ae2','2023-09-08 09:09:41','2023-10-28 13:21:11','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Gynecologic Cancers',48,'Gynecologic oncology is a specialized field of medicine that focuses on cancers of the female reproductive system, including ovarian cancer, uterine cancer, vaginal cancer, cervical cancer, and vulvar cancer. As specialists, they have extensive training in the diagnosis and treatment of these cancers. In the United States, 82,000 women are diagnosed with gynecologic cancer annually. In 2013, an estimated 91,730 were diagnosed. There is low quality evidence which demonstrates women with gynaecological cancer receiving treatment from specialized centres benefit from longer survival than those managed in standard care. A meta analysis of three studies combining over 9000 women, suggested that specialist gynaecological cancer treatment centres may prolong the lives of women with ovarian cancer compared with general or community hospitals.','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_alt\": 288.0, \"pub_doc\": 1068.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 41.0, \"clinic_alt\": 339.0, \"clinic_doc\": 68.0, \"grant_fund\": 18716239.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.0, \"pub_doc\": 5.4, \"clinic_doc\": 12.6, \"grant_fund\": -1132384.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4442a9f491ba66c38c59d4e5707f60ac','66370bcc1950b8300adc5378b5a9db5b','2cf8a6770a22256c603cf40927d188ef','2023-09-08 02:16:56','2023-10-28 22:41:13','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Non-viral Vector',48,'Non-viral vectors are genetic tools that aid in gene therapy that lack the viral genome and carry foreign genetic material that can be transferred into the cells. Instead of using an infectious pathogen, non-viral vectors use liposomes, nanoparticles, and chemical conjugates. Because non-viral vectors lack the viral genome, they are less immunogenic and safer than viral vectors. Non-viral vectors also allow the transfer of larger amounts of genetic material, providing possible benefits over the viral vector for genetic therapy applications. In addition, the simple design of non-viral vectors allows more economic and scalable production. Despite their advantages, non-viral vectors have lower transduction rates in cells than viral vectors.','{\"pat_doc\": 248.0, \"pub_alt\": 325.0, \"pub_doc\": 430.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 35.0, \"clinic_alt\": 29.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 11797010.0, \"pat_granted\": 32.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.8, \"pub_doc\": 0.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -408385.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('446e424d52093fb5605c8e28363d9217','f47c085ebbd53aee312f00db0891448f','a2144b71351e9696db283cb552418a4f','2023-09-04 19:34:56','2023-10-29 06:01:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Monitoring System',24,'A monitoring system is a tool used to continuously track the status and performance of a particular process, network, or system. It helps detect and alert users of any abnormalities, errors, or threats in real-time, allowing them to quickly respond before any significant damage is done. The system collects data from various sources, such as sensors, servers, and applications, before analyzing and communicating the results to the user interface. This process enables operators to identify trends, isolate problems, and make informed decisions about necessary actions. In short, a monitoring system provides visibility, control, and optimization over a systems performance and security.','{\"pat_doc\": 56371.0, \"pub_alt\": 1928.0, \"pub_doc\": 21498.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 833.0, \"clinic_alt\": 428.0, \"clinic_doc\": 570.0, \"grant_fund\": 456409537.0, \"pat_granted\": 23107.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 794.4, \"pub_doc\": 681.4, \"clinic_doc\": 89.9, \"grant_fund\": -66984808.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('447b1c3b91575ce1b261d9480cecd2ba','1db9ef424bfbfaef3351c1c0c2bbb420','bb12623092a23c745c2bf47641f215ad','2023-09-08 09:57:46','2023-10-28 19:46:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Amino Acid Analysis',36,'Amino acid analysis is a common method used to determine the quantity and composition of amino acids in a protein or peptide sample. This technique involves acid hydrolysis of the protein or peptide, which breaks down the peptide bonds and releases the individual amino acids. The resulting mixture of amino acids is then separated and quantified using various analytical techniques such as high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) or gas chromatography (GC). This analysis provides valuable information about the composition and concentration of amino acids, which can be used to deduce the sequence of the peptide or identify the protein. This technique is widely used in research, industrial, and clinical settings for various applications such as protein characterization, quality control, and dietary analysis.','{\"pat_doc\": 38.0, \"pub_alt\": 57.0, \"pub_doc\": 393.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 449515.0, \"pat_granted\": 20.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": 3.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -90894.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('44beb9435cd6a17de120fb5b47e078e7','dbff1bacaaa4170742799b76b0d72aa1','e5dc1ab9b95fd144580ba449bdb1f286','2023-09-05 20:47:05','2023-10-29 04:21:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','CRISPR-Cas9',24,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 528.0, \"pub_alt\": 993.0, \"pub_doc\": 3792.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 460.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 20.0, \"grant_fund\": 192523840.0, \"pat_granted\": 151.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.6, \"pub_doc\": 115.9, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -29971557.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('44dd5c96538a023675b2a1ccc236f80f','00a65404eafa0410776576517426c1bf','c3708acc1ff6c957eeda159c8941d078','2023-09-08 02:55:47','2023-10-28 13:51:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Polymer-based Nanoparticles',36,'Polymer-based nanoparticles are tiny particles that are made from polymeric materials and have a diameter in the nanometer range. They are widely used in drug delivery, cancer therapy, imaging, and diagnostics, due to their unique and advantageous properties. Polymer-based nanoparticles offer several benefits, including controlled drug release, enhanced drug efficacy, and biocompatibility. They are also more stable and less toxic than traditional drug delivery vehicles such as liposomes. Polymer-based nanoparticles can be prepared using various fabrication methods such as emulsion polymerization, nanoprecipitation, and self-assembly. By manipulating the polymer chemistry and nanoparticle size, their properties can be tuned to optimize their performance for specific applications. Overall, polymer-based nanoparticles hold great promise for advancing medical technologies and improving patient outcomes.','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_alt\": 57.0, \"pub_doc\": 125.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 409375.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.6, \"pub_doc\": 4.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -69931.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('45045a2c7f6af4db381cb25d49327a60','86828d3c6e58a58dd0ec1a5517969fd6','de33517ef25dd85cbe2dd8dc604a5426','2023-09-08 01:18:05','2023-10-28 15:26:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','biomolecular condensates',24,'Biomolecular condensates are non-membrane-bound, membraneless organelles that are formed by the reversible phase separation of proteins, nucleic acids, and other biomolecules. These condensates can be dynamic and can rapidly assemble and disassemble in response to cellular signals. They play a crucial role in many cellular processes, including DNA replication, transcription, and translation. Recent studies have shown that the formation of these condensates can also drive the assembly of large molecular complexes that are essential for cellular functions. Dysfunction of these condensates has been linked to various diseases, including neurodegenerative disorders. Understanding the principles underlying biomolecular condensate formation and dynamics is crucial for understanding cellular processes and developing new therapeutics.','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_alt\": 611.0, \"pub_doc\": 730.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 82.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 44111910.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.9, \"pub_doc\": 89.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1255674.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('456096c6bc80841cf22f6f4c0fa7e94b','5f1ee7663407442aa2582d3efd1ad42b','5320de801f6c227388f87a0edfc49eb4','2023-09-04 19:25:15','2023-10-29 06:06:07','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Metabolomics',12,'Metabolomics is the scientific study of chemical processes involving metabolites, the small molecule substrates, intermediates, and products of cell metabolism. Specifically, metabolomics is the \"systematic study of the unique chemical fingerprints that specific cellular processes leave behind\", the study of their small-molecule metabolite profiles. The metabolome represents the complete set of metabolites in a biological cell, tissue, organ, or organism, which are the end products of cellular processes. Messenger RNA, gene expression data, and proteomic analyses reveal the set of gene products being produced in the cell, data that represents one aspect of cellular function. Conversely, metabolic profiling can give an instantaneous snapshot of the physiology of that cell, and thus, metabolomics provides a direct \"functional readout of the physiological state\" of an organism.','{\"pat_doc\": 42.0, \"pub_alt\": 5232.0, \"pub_doc\": 8339.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 459.0, \"clinic_alt\": 322.0, \"clinic_doc\": 575.0, \"grant_fund\": 280744879.0, \"pat_granted\": 9.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.2, \"pub_doc\": 1091.2, \"clinic_doc\": 144.0, \"grant_fund\": -118313386.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('45683b659d3e2546adf67ebcb52b2f6a','c3be1591926e87743c4c54d7028677c0','ef63c5da9830a0ea9737ee257244ed3a','2023-09-08 00:09:38','2023-10-28 16:36:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Lentivirus',12,'Lentivirus is a genus of retroviruses that cause chronic and deadly diseases characterized by long incubation periods, in humans and other mammalian species. The genus includes the human immunodeficiency virus, which causes AIDS. Lentiviruses are distributed worldwide, and are known to be hosted in apes, cows, goats, horses, cats, and sheep as well as several other mammals. Lentiviruses can integrate a significant amount of viral complementary DNA into the DNA of the host cell and can efficiently infect nondividing cells, so they are one of the most efficient methods of gene delivery. They can become endogenous, integrating their genome into the host germline genome, so that the virus is henceforth inherited by the hosts descendants.','{\"pat_doc\": 342.0, \"pub_alt\": 521.0, \"pub_doc\": 1276.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 30.0, \"clinic_alt\": 169.0, \"clinic_doc\": 37.0, \"grant_fund\": 15380867.0, \"pat_granted\": 104.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.0, \"pub_doc\": -93.8, \"clinic_doc\": 8.6, \"grant_fund\": -9867775.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('461d950afc39d44745d8611f42ab1eaa','9ae996f0d6bbaff7b400a3648677eeaf','f79d0c4233733c41a41b0769be4ec44f','2023-09-08 01:43:31','2023-10-28 11:25:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Heterogeneous Integration',48,'Heterogeneous Integration refers to the process of combining different types of materials, devices, components, or functions into a single system or package. It involves the use of various technologies to create complex systems that can perform multiple functions using different components integrated together. This process enables the creation of new products, systems, and services with improved features, performance, and flexibility. The main benefits of heterogeneous integration include reduced cost, improved system performance, and increased connectivity and functionality. This approach is widely used in the development of advanced microprocessors, wireless communication devices, sensors and actuators, and other high-tech products. By integrating various components with different functionalities, manufacturers can achieve compact, high-performance systems that meet the demands of modern applications.','{\"pat_doc\": 373.0, \"pub_alt\": 288.0, \"pub_doc\": 1192.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 161.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 165267588.0, \"pat_granted\": 106.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 24.9, \"pub_doc\": 44.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 9542163.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('46633f469dfa578189fc7d927bd9bd7c','e24808701d1b869f29beb5b17a6f3966','0a566310cdeaa23e7fc0d55380c35a91','2023-09-08 02:38:56','2023-10-28 14:11:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Gene therapies (Non-viral)','mRNA therapy',24,'mRNA (messenger RNA) therapy is a cutting-edge medical technique that harnesses the bodys own ability to produce essential proteins to better fight disease. The therapy involves injecting synthetic strands of mRNA into the body, which are then recognized by the bodys own cells as \"blueprints\" for specific proteins that are vital for health. These proteins are then produced by the bodys cells and can be used to combat a wide range of illnesses, from cancer to genetic disorders to viral infections like COVID-19. mRNA therapy has shown a lot of promise in clinical trials, with some treatments already approved for use in certain conditions. While the technology is still in its early stages, experts believe that mRNA therapy could revolutionize the way we treat diseases in the coming years.','{\"pat_doc\": 71.0, \"pub_alt\": 350.0, \"pub_doc\": 57.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 1548946.0, \"pat_granted\": 10.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.7, \"pub_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.4, \"grant_fund\": 71200.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('468b9839cdcecc15d2cbd28204eed5e9','b623d7ca57acae4c7c681109e883ff82','9b78c6ab99d1ce69ff59eddcd1444cfe','2023-09-04 18:43:50','2023-10-28 18:21:15','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Heart failure',12,'Heart failure, also known as congestive heart failure, is a syndrome, a group of signs and symptoms, caused by an impairment of the hearts blood pumping function. Symptoms typically include shortness of breath, excessive fatigue, and leg swelling. The shortness of breath may occur with exertion or while lying down, and may wake people up during the night. Chest pain, including angina, is not usually caused by heart failure, but may occur if the heart failure was caused by a heart attack. The severity of the heart failure is mainly decided based on ejection fraction and also measured by the severity of symptoms. Other conditions that may have symptoms similar to heart failure include obesity, kidney failure, liver disease, anemia, and thyroid disease. Common causes of heart failure include coronary artery disease, heart attack, high blood pressure, atrial fibrillation, valvular heart disease, excessive alcohol consumption, infection, and cardiomyopathy.','{\"pat_doc\": 1458.0, \"pub_alt\": 4976.0, \"pub_doc\": 22783.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 729.0, \"clinic_alt\": 886.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3298.0, \"grant_fund\": 297451465.0, \"pat_granted\": 389.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 60.6, \"pub_doc\": 1207.9, \"clinic_doc\": 749.7, \"grant_fund\": -131899850.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('46a2c99a2e059b07445a2cf6fb5c9596','8837382ad71ea14d648e72dffa07f350','a10d686867f23b1f3c14742bdf7326cc','2023-09-05 19:11:33','2023-10-29 05:16:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Biomaterial',24,'A biomaterial is a substance that has been engineered to interact with biological systems for a medical purpose, either a therapeutic or a diagnostic one. The corresponding field of study, called biomaterials science or biomaterials engineering, is about fifty years old. It has experienced steady and strong growth over its history, with many companies investing large amounts of money into the development of new products. Biomaterials science encompasses elements of medicine, biology, chemistry, tissue engineering and materials science. Note that a biomaterial is different from a biological material, such as bone, that is produced by a biological system. Additionally, care should be exercised in defining a biomaterial as biocompatible, since it is application-specific. A biomaterial that is biocompatible or suitable for one application may not be biocompatible in another.','{\"pat_doc\": 2249.0, \"pub_alt\": 1940.0, \"pub_doc\": 17203.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1415.0, \"clinic_alt\": 260.0, \"clinic_doc\": 257.0, \"grant_fund\": 607117659.0, \"pat_granted\": 659.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -44.8, \"pub_doc\": 588.5, \"clinic_doc\": 50.9, \"grant_fund\": -91915477.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('46d94066b551eb3c2f4d6198f3a32170','d4fdd9a1f4aa53cc01e7cbb316b38d68','a0401cb7a291257d3685c0a77fb2d841','2023-09-08 01:02:41','2023-10-28 15:51:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Retrovirus',48,'A retrovirus is a type of virus that inserts a DNA copy of its RNA genome into the DNA of a host cell that it invades, thus changing the genome of that cell. Once inside the host cells cytoplasm, the virus uses its own reverse transcriptase enzyme to produce DNA from its RNA genome, the reverse of the usual pattern, thus retro. The new DNA is then incorporated into the host cell genome by an integrase enzyme, at which point the retroviral DNA is referred to as a provirus. The host cell then treats the viral DNA as part of its own genome, transcribing and translating the viral genes along with the cells own genes, producing the proteins required to assemble new copies of the virus. Many retroviruses cause serious diseases in humans, other mammals, and birds. Retroviruses have many subfamilies in three basic groups. â€¢ Oncoretroviruses include human T-lymphotropic virus causing a type of leukemia in humans, and murine leukemia viruses in mice.','{\"pat_doc\": 546.0, \"pub_alt\": 3897.0, \"pub_doc\": 3157.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 330.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1310.0, \"clinic_doc\": 74.0, \"grant_fund\": 156801399.0, \"pat_granted\": 131.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.8, \"pub_doc\": 7.1, \"clinic_doc\": 15.6, \"grant_fund\": -9492771.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('47ac7d2a6f9931be3de8a8e91a340f59','e10a2a038e97b6bb75152e575137a4fb','77e5f6785bd7c9d4f3610b4ac830ad4e','2023-09-08 00:22:46','2023-10-28 16:26:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Electroporation',24,'Electroporation, or electropermeabilization, is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing chemicals, drugs, electrode arrays or DNA to be introduced into the cell. In microbiology, the process of electroporation is often used to transform bacteria, yeast, or plant protoplasts by introducing new coding DNA. If bacteria and plasmids are mixed together, the plasmids can be transferred into the bacteria after electroporation, though depending on what is being transferred, cell-penetrating peptides or CellSqueeze could also be used. Electroporation works by passing thousands of volts across suspended cells in an electroporation cuvette. Afterwards, the cells have to be handled carefully until they have had a chance to divide, producing new cells that contain reproduced plasmids.','{\"pat_doc\": 1335.0, \"pub_alt\": 688.0, \"pub_doc\": 1874.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 104.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1151.0, \"clinic_doc\": 125.0, \"grant_fund\": 39214481.0, \"pat_granted\": 369.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 72.8, \"pub_doc\": -23.0, \"clinic_doc\": 21.4, \"grant_fund\": -13946036.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('47f3465981f77a57a11236a082a0873a','ee19185ea91ee66a9b4ca70824b1b576','06752199a8f52b307494ef715b2504c5','2023-09-08 11:11:55','2023-10-28 18:46:09','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Biomarker Discovery',12,'Biomarker discovery is a medical term describing the process by which biomarkers are discovered. Many commonly used blood tests in medicine are biomarkers. There is interest in biomarker discovery on the part of the pharmaceutical industry; blood-test or other biomarkers could serve as intermediate markers of disease in clinical trials, and as possible drug targets.','{\"pat_doc\": 26.0, \"pub_alt\": 458.0, \"pub_doc\": 764.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 57.0, \"clinic_alt\": 309.0, \"clinic_doc\": 73.0, \"grant_fund\": 47280045.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": 37.9, \"clinic_doc\": 20.6, \"grant_fund\": -49263941.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('47fb04020d1a720e28c7893326ba5bbd','382772c54fc63869435b590e8d1111c4','43d3334d4623a18878a471a105e8c82e','2023-09-08 00:27:07','2023-10-28 16:21:14','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Pheochromocytoma',36,'Pheochromocytoma is a rare tumor of the adrenal medulla composed of chromaffin cells, also known as pheochromocytes. When a tumor composed of the same cells as a pheochromocytoma develops outside the adrenal gland, it is referred to as a paraganglioma. These neuroendocrine tumors typically release massive amounts of catecholamines, metanephrines, or methoxytyramine, which result in the most common symptoms, including hypertension, tachycardia, and diaphoresis. Rarely, some tumors may secrete little to no catecholamines, making diagnosis difficult. While tumors of the head and neck are parasympathetic, their sympathetic counterparts are predominantly located in the abdomen and pelvis, particularly concentrated at the organ of Zuckerkandl.','{\"pat_doc\": 43.0, \"pub_alt\": 288.0, \"pub_doc\": 2892.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 27.0, \"clinic_alt\": 312.0, \"clinic_doc\": 106.0, \"grant_fund\": 5490920.0, \"pat_granted\": 17.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.4, \"pub_doc\": 22.8, \"clinic_doc\": 17.8, \"grant_fund\": -4557007.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('481d8fb28f3a6db950257703dd337433','aedf0c478e49c48a393feff1fdcfaa4b','5b55c48790bb4cf3b5dc24f790e7d5a2','2023-09-05 21:32:03','2023-10-28 12:25:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Metaverse',36,'The Metaverse is a virtual reality space that contains multiple interconnected virtual worlds and augmented reality environments. It is a digital universe that enables users to create, experience, and interact with each other in various virtual environments. In the Metaverse, users can have a digital representation of themselves, or an avatar, who can move from one world to another. The concept of Metaverse is increasingly becoming popular as advancements in technology allow for more immersive and seamless experiences. It is used in various areas, including gaming, education, socialization, commerce, and even politics, to name a few. The Metaverse holds immense potential for revolutionizing how we interact with technology and each other.','{\"pat_doc\": 970.0, \"pub_alt\": 695.0, \"pub_doc\": 5936.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 142.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 76856260.0, \"pat_granted\": 275.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 259.5, \"pub_doc\": 1393.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.3, \"grant_fund\": 20484735.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('48572de0661aec618aeb5803c12bd897','860562e383a8d17a8f172fa2f70cc8f9','aeef280b6e10fec919822406e149ebb2','2023-09-08 02:33:55','2023-10-28 14:16:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Lipid regulation',12,'Lipid regulation is the process of maintaining healthy levels of lipids in the body. Lipids are a type of molecule that includes fats, oils, and waxes. They are essential for many functions in the body, including providing energy and helping with the absorption of vitamins. However, too much or too little of certain types of lipids can lead to health problems. For example, high levels of cholesterol can increase the risk of heart disease, while low levels of essential fatty acids can lead to inflammation and other issues. Efficient lipid regulation requires a balanced diet and regular exercise, along with possible medication if needed.','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_alt\": 28.0, \"pub_doc\": 64.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 3887983.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": 5.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.4, \"grant_fund\": 1008259.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('48803c390f0cccac8a1954d284ed40ea','e1fe0660b514055c0dbf73bc14fd217a','ed9ba98e0c7216e9330cb415b46ee8cd','2023-09-07 23:50:12','2023-10-28 17:06:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Herpes simplex virus',48,'Herpes simplex virus 1 and 2, also known by their taxonomic names Human alphaherpesvirus 1 and Human alphaherpesvirus 2, are two members of the human Herpesviridae family, a set of viruses that produce viral infections in the majority of humans. Both HSV-1 and HSV-2 are very common and contagious. They can be spread when an infected person begins shedding the virus. As of 2016, about 67% of the world population under the age of 50 had HSV-1. In the United States, about 47.8% and 11.9% are estimated to have HSV-1 and HSV-2, respectively, though actual prevalence may be much higher. Because it can be transmitted through any intimate contact, it is one of the most common sexually transmitted infections.','{\"pat_doc\": 1095.0, \"pub_alt\": 1973.0, \"pub_doc\": 5207.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 254.0, \"clinic_alt\": 635.0, \"clinic_doc\": 139.0, \"grant_fund\": 116346007.0, \"pat_granted\": 304.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.7, \"pub_doc\": 21.1, \"clinic_doc\": 20.7, \"grant_fund\": -10632542.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('48ab5177b633f9beabc13b0d0a2bb56c','6de9464f8e368a19a89261dd71c09017','641ccd99a014845dc487b6f5a217f8ff','2023-09-08 00:19:27','2023-10-29 01:56:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Nuclear Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy',24,'Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy, most commonly known as NMR spectroscopy or magnetic resonance spectroscopy, is a spectroscopic technique to observe local magnetic fields around atomic nuclei. This spectroscopy is based on the measurement of absorption of electromagnetic radiations in the radio frequency region from roughly 4 to 900 MHz. Absorption of radio waves in the presence of magnetic field is accompanied by a special type of nuclear transition, and for this reason, such type of spectroscopy is known as Nuclear Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy. The sample is placed in a magnetic field and the NMR signal is produced by excitation of the nuclei sample with radio waves into nuclear magnetic resonance, which is detected with sensitive radio receivers. The intramolecular magnetic field around an atom in a molecule changes the resonance frequency, thus giving access to details of the electronic structure of a molecule and its individual functional groups.','{\"pat_doc\": 61.0, \"pub_alt\": 745.0, \"pub_doc\": 2269.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 72.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 41821690.0, \"pat_granted\": 15.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.8, \"pub_doc\": 7.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.9, \"grant_fund\": -2653145.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('48bd2b1138304a47f087ee1ebe569ed8','b973f9a55a74403c41f6bfdbc9121654','b347f7200b8aff24464a347c263147e9','2023-09-04 19:13:14','2023-10-29 06:11:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Filtration',12,'Filtration is a physical separation process that separates solid matter and fluid from a mixture using a filter medium that has a complex structure through which only the fluid can pass. Solid particles that cannot pass through the filter medium are described as oversize and the fluid that passes through is called the filtrate. Oversize particles may form a filter cake on top of the filter and may also block the filter lattice, preventing the fluid phase from crossing the filter, known as blinding. The size of the largest particles that can successfully pass through a filter is called the effective pore size of that filter. The separation of solid and fluid is imperfect; solids will be contaminated with some fluid and filtrate will contain fine particles. Filtration occurs both in nature and in engineered systems; there are biological, geological, and industrial forms.','{\"pat_doc\": 54641.0, \"pub_alt\": 14658.0, \"pub_doc\": 42278.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 663.0, \"clinic_alt\": 592.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1873.0, \"grant_fund\": 261795069.0, \"pat_granted\": 37443.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 315.7, \"pub_doc\": 2992.9, \"clinic_doc\": 373.4, \"grant_fund\": -100208796.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('48c13da093e86680be157c411cdc5e25','926bd332c30fbfe2631a0f1af6fd3501','a8f010b8551aa704497c66b481f56011','2023-09-08 02:21:24','2023-10-28 14:36:11','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Autologous chondrocytes',36,'Autologous chondrocytes refer to a type of cellular therapy that involves using the patients own cartilage cells to repair damaged or degenerated cartilage tissue. This procedure is typically used in cases of chondral defects or osteoarthritis. The process involves extracting a sample of the patients cartilage cells and growing them in a laboratory setting. The cells are then re-implanted into the patients damaged joint, where they can help to regenerate new cartilage tissue. Autologous chondrocyte therapy is considered a promising approach for the treatment of cartilage defects, as it enables the use of the patients own cells and can lead to improved outcomes compared to other treatment options.','{\"pat_doc\": 2.0, \"pub_alt\": 27.0, \"pub_doc\": 56.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 1824372.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": -2.4, \"clinic_doc\": 1.7, \"grant_fund\": 108408.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('491525a599cb225b73794e34136789c5','ab4b6025c38d1cab8fd476593532cb60','8c907d5d7b60b5604cad502b2ab3ea5b','2023-09-08 01:44:40','2023-10-28 11:20:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Societal & Economic Disruptions','Russia-Ukraine conflict',24,'The Russo-Ukrainian War is an ongoing international conflict between Russia, alongside Russian-backed separatists, and Ukraine, which began in February 2014. Following Ukraines Revolution of Dignity, Russia annexed Crimea from Ukraine and supported pro-Russian separatists fighting the Ukrainian military in the Donbas war. The first eight years of conflict also included naval incidents, cyberwarfare, and heightened political tensions. In February 2022, Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine. In early 2014, the Euromaidan protests led to the Revolution of Dignity and the ousting of Ukraines pro-Russian president Viktor Yanukovych. Shortly after, pro-Russian unrest erupted in eastern and southern Ukraine. Simultaneously, unmarked Russian troops moved into Ukraines Crimea and took over government buildings, strategic sites and infrastructure. Russia soon annexed Crimea after a highly-disputed referendum.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 4755.0, \"pub_doc\": 377.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 529815.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 93.4