oodâ€“brain barrier may occur.','{\"pat_doc\": 6.0, \"pub_alt\": 26.0, \"pub_doc\": 128.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 9.0, \"clinic_alt\": 35.0, \"clinic_doc\": 26.0, \"grant_fund\": 4748192.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": -14.9, \"clinic_doc\": 6.2, \"grant_fund\": -2859987.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4b9b3142ae736152e6d94d2c484d0203','e1fe0660b514055c0dbf73bc14fd217a','ed9ba98e0c7216e9330cb415b46ee8cd','2023-09-07 23:50:12','2023-10-28 17:06:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Herpes simplex virus',12,'Herpes simplex virus 1 and 2, also known by their taxonomic names Human alphaherpesvirus 1 and Human alphaherpesvirus 2, are two members of the human Herpesviridae family, a set of viruses that produce viral infections in the majority of humans. Both HSV-1 and HSV-2 are very common and contagious. They can be spread when an infected person begins shedding the virus. As of 2016, about 67% of the world population under the age of 50 had HSV-1. In the United States, about 47.8% and 11.9% are estimated to have HSV-1 and HSV-2, respectively, though actual prevalence may be much higher. Because it can be transmitted through any intimate contact, it is one of the most common sexually transmitted infections.','{\"pat_doc\": 269.0, \"pub_alt\": 987.0, \"pub_doc\": 1287.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 53.0, \"clinic_alt\": 214.0, \"clinic_doc\": 82.0, \"grant_fund\": 18078171.0, \"pat_granted\": 75.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.7, \"pub_doc\": 21.1, \"clinic_doc\": 20.7, \"grant_fund\": -10632542.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4c278d9e2e8b5706b964dde9930407df','68e5caa32ed7e67484689ef37c744a39','8d40644b6dad0c0cd4481b73c097825b','2023-09-05 20:56:55','2023-10-29 04:16:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Bioreactor',36,'A bioreactor refers to any manufactured device or system that supports a biologically active environment. In one case, a bioreactor is a vessel in which a chemical process is carried out which involves organisms or biochemically active substances derived from such organisms. This process can either be aerobic or anaerobic. These bioreactors are commonly cylindrical, ranging in size from litres to cubic metres, and are often made of stainless steel. It may also refer to a device or system designed to grow cells or tissues in the context of cell culture. These devices are being developed for use in tissue engineering or biochemical/bioprocess engineering. On the basis of mode of operation, a bioreactor may be classified as batch, fed batch or continuous. An example of a continuous bioreactor is the chemostat. Organisms or biochemically active substances growing in bioreactors may be submerged in liquid medium or may be anchored to the surface of a solid medium.','{\"pat_doc\": 8841.0, \"pub_alt\": 4795.0, \"pub_doc\": 11974.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 893.0, \"clinic_alt\": 24.0, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": 386566749.0, \"pat_granted\": 3579.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 47.6, \"pub_doc\": 42.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -17747789.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4c6f5b25f7160e78d612a58d9e8214d2','d702a8adc5dbea4b170f75415100b3b5','4aebb65d3ef171435ae3068e3a2c9f22','2023-09-04 18:33:18','2023-10-29 07:01:15','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Stem Cells',24,'Stem cells are undifferentiated cells that have the ability to differentiate into specialized cells and regenerate damaged tissues in the body. These cells have the potential to give rise to any cell type in the body, such as blood, bone, muscle, and nerve cells. Stem cells can be classified into embryonic, fetal, and adult stem cells based on their origin and potential to differentiate. Embryonic stem cells are obtained from early-stage embryos and can differentiate into any cell type, while fetal and adult stem cells are found in various tissues and have a more limited differentiation potential. Stem cell research shows promise for developing treatments for a range of diseases and conditions.','{\"pat_doc\": 12943.0, \"pub_alt\": 3814.0, \"pub_doc\": 39549.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3369.0, \"clinic_alt\": 531.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1923.0, \"grant_fund\": 1443096486.0, \"pat_granted\": 3844.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 141.4, \"pub_doc\": -576.1, \"clinic_doc\": 354.8, \"grant_fund\": -242932791.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4c95020b74cc773e9d7fd4704d9b9cde','5e047db7e10164d6ec0e89c2fe69a4b9','589b84d604aa424bb142db78b62d89e3','2023-09-08 02:00:38','2023-10-28 23:26:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Electrophoresis',24,'Protein electrophoresis is a method for analysing the proteins in a fluid or an extract. The electrophoresis may be performed with a small volume of sample in a number of alternative ways with or without a supporting medium: SDS polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis, free-flow electrophoresis, electrofocusing, isotachophoresis, affinity electrophoresis, immunoelectrophoresis, counterelectrophoresis, and capillary electrophoresis. Each method has many variations with individual advantages and limitations. Gel electrophoresis is often performed in combination with electroblotting immunoblotting to give additional information about a specific protein. Because of practical limitations, protein electrophoresis is generally not suited as a preparative method.','{\"pat_doc\": 52.0, \"pub_alt\": 230.0, \"pub_doc\": 440.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 43.0, \"clinic_doc\": 24.0, \"grant_fund\": 869931.0, \"pat_granted\": 30.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 3.1, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -94204.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4c97a5d4843e7a65bf77fd32f3730dcf','bcec320c1d366012496fdc05b1162aad','3e072ff4f027f97184b7ecfb791122b7','2023-09-05 22:06:34','2023-10-28 17:26:11','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Bacteriophages',12,'A bacteriophage, also known informally as a phage, is a duplodnaviria virus that infects and replicates within bacteria and archaea. The term was derived from \"bacteria\" and the Greek Ï†Î±Î³Îµá¿–Î½, meaning \"to devour\". Bacteriophages are composed of proteins that encapsulate a DNA or RNA genome, and may have structures that are either simple or elaborate. Their genomes may encode as few as four genes and as many as hundreds of genes. Phages replicate within the bacterium following the injection of their genome into its cytoplasm. Bacteriophages are among the most common and diverse entities in the biosphere. Bacteriophages are ubiquitous viruses, found wherever bacteria exist. It is estimated there are more than 10Â³Â¹ bacteriophages on the planet, more than every other organism on Earth, including bacteria, combined.','{\"pat_doc\": 160.0, \"pub_alt\": 653.0, \"pub_doc\": 1323.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 68.0, \"clinic_alt\": 247.0, \"clinic_doc\": 18.0, \"grant_fund\": 20036989.0, \"pat_granted\": 28.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.4, \"pub_doc\": 69.6, \"clinic_doc\": 4.7, \"grant_fund\": -11975247.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4d7ddcef967202500db6a1db79273d55','01807d836d93ed1511a8b58c90b6d398','3fcb9a9c61a418e177e61e3951321f26','2023-09-08 02:15:42','2023-10-28 22:46:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Controlled-release system',36,'A controlled-release system is a technology used in drug delivery, agriculture and other fields to release active ingredients evenly over a period of time. It involves encapsulating the active ingredient in a matrix that controls its release rate. This can increase the effectiveness of the ingredient and reduce the frequency of application. In drug delivery, it can improve patient compliance, reduce side effects and increase efficacy. In agriculture, it can reduce waste and environmental impact. Controlled-release systems can be designed using a variety of materials, including polymers, liposomes and mesoporous materials. They are an important tool in modern science and technology, with numerous applications in various industries.','{\"pat_doc\": 25.0, \"pub_alt\": 14.0, \"pub_doc\": 59.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1352759.0, \"pat_granted\": 9.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -135275.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4de950d7f400b3a1f9b3a18612465e69','bec6c7cf3a4a7344b41e74da4cea341b','2483d5e44059b5dad528a46e9d77ee36','2023-09-08 00:50:32','2023-10-29 01:06:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','antisense oligonucleotides',12,'Antisense oligonucleotides (ASOs) are short single-stranded pieces of DNA or RNA that bind to specific target mRNA molecules to regulate gene expression. ASOs are designed to silence a particular gene by preventing the translation of mRNA into protein, which can be useful in treating genetic disorders caused by overexpression or abnormal splicing of certain genes. ASOs are made up of a sequence complementary to the target mRNA, and once bound, they can recruit cellular machinery to degrade the mRNA or block its translation. ASOs are a promising therapeutic strategy for a variety of diseases, including cancer, viral infections, and genetic disorders.','{\"pat_doc\": 401.0, \"pub_alt\": 334.0, \"pub_doc\": 500.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 58.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 27939065.0, \"pat_granted\": 66.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 12.5, \"pub_doc\": 28.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -4672412.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4e75c8effaee48fd6603bd94413ba00b','c66db8e5795eca3126bf573522e8cf4e','e77dece162a0133e50d5b2357c40719f','2023-09-05 22:56:00','2023-10-29 02:51:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','RNA interference',48,'RNA interference is a biological process in which RNA molecules are involved in sequence-specific suppression of gene expression by double-stranded RNA, through translational or transcriptional repression. Historically, RNAi was known by other names, including co-suppression, post-transcriptional gene silencing, and quelling. The detailed study of each of these seemingly different processes elucidated that the identity of these phenomena were all actually RNAi. Andrew Fire and Craig C. Mello shared the 2006 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their work on RNAi in the nematode worm Caenorhabditis elegans, which they published in 1998. Since the discovery of RNAi and its regulatory potentials, it has become evident that RNAi has immense potential in suppression of desired genes. RNAi is now known as precise, efficient, stable and better than antisense therapy for gene suppression.','{\"pat_doc\": 1472.0, \"pub_alt\": 1214.0, \"pub_doc\": 7318.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 429.0, \"clinic_alt\": 18.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 137682729.0, \"pat_granted\": 454.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.6, \"pub_doc\": -43.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": -14470471.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4e9f098d446f1bc8726509439338e777','2189df4a2bc6ca2c1f680fee94f5b10c','41bec6af04474eb4358a3a371286538c','2023-09-07 23:37:46','2023-10-29 02:36:13','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Gene Silencing',36,'Gene silencing is the regulation of gene expression in a cell to prevent the expression of a certain gene. Gene silencing can occur during either transcription or translation and is often used in research. In particular, methods used to silence genes are being increasingly used to produce therapeutics to combat cancer and other diseases, such as infectious diseases and neurodegenerative disorders. Gene silencing is often considered the same as gene knockdown. When genes are silenced, their expression is reduced. In contrast, when genes are knocked out, they are completely erased from the organisms genome and, thus, have no expression. Gene silencing is considered a gene knockdown mechanism since the methods used to silence genes, such as RNAi, CRISPR, or siRNA, generally reduce the expression of a gene by at least 70% but do not eliminate it.','{\"pat_doc\": 766.0, \"pub_alt\": 846.0, \"pub_doc\": 4642.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 333.0, \"clinic_alt\": 16.0, \"clinic_doc\": 13.0, \"grant_fund\": 127228306.0, \"pat_granted\": 265.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 13.2, \"pub_doc\": -3.1, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": -9870496.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4efb17ed8a92abe3db1718612398ff4d','3c24254d6c0d4e4249ab4b441e17dc83','abbcb6a1638f63a5747e204b798f4ec2','2023-09-08 00:41:06','2023-10-29 01:11:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','DNA Synthesis',24,'DNA synthesis is the natural or artificial creation of deoxyribonucleic acid molecules. DNA is a macromolecule made up of nucleotide units, which are linked by covalent bonds and hydrogen bonds, in a repeating structure. DNA synthesis occurs when these nucleotide units are joined to form DNA; this can occur artificially or naturally. Nucleotide units are made up of a nitrogenous base, pentose sugar and phosphate group. Each unit is joined when a covalent bond forms between its phosphate group and the pentose sugar of the next nucleotide, forming a sugar-phosphate backbone. DNA is a complementary, double stranded structure as specific base pairing occurs naturally when hydrogen bonds form between the nucleotide bases. There are several different definitions for DNA synthesis: it can refer to DNA replication - DNA biosynthesis, polymerase chain reaction - enzymatic DNA synthesis or gene synthesis - physically creating artificial gene sequences.','{\"pat_doc\": 330.0, \"pub_alt\": 590.0, \"pub_doc\": 1731.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 114.0, \"clinic_alt\": 55.0, \"clinic_doc\": 50.0, \"grant_fund\": 59152370.0, \"pat_granted\": 85.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.0, \"pub_doc\": -7.9, \"clinic_doc\": 8.6, \"grant_fund\": -10466344.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('4f4e1a7f1fe353b1d901438cea732557','ffe250fc447887b501aee1b30580085f','c15525a97e5927c0f087d514b050aed9','2023-09-08 09:37:37','2023-10-28 20:56:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Distillation',24,'Distillation is a process used to separate liquids with different boiling points. It involves heating a mixture of liquids to vaporize the components with lower boiling points, collecting the vapor, and then condensing it back into a liquid form. The process is widely used in industries such as petroleum refining, where crude oil is distilled to produce various fuels and other products. In addition, distillation is a common method used to purify water, create alcoholic beverages, and extract essential oils from plant materials. The efficiency of distillation depends on the difference in boiling points between the components being separated, with greater differences resulting in more effective separation.','{\"pat_doc\": 20993.0, \"pub_alt\": 493.0, \"pub_doc\": 14790.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 211.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 12.0, \"grant_fund\": 85300469.0, \"pat_granted\": 10089.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 349.4, \"pub_doc\": 1168.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.6, \"grant_fund\": -3503023.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('502ce4ea6172e6213b2d8f3c1fe524e9','e5cdaf0403574f617436eb3c34f77c60','3889385fdc1bbeadad2bf5c86cbbd89a','2023-09-08 00:29:50','2023-10-29 01:31:13','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Electrochemical Biosensor',36,'An electrochemical biosensor is a device that uses the principles of electrochemistry to detect the presence of biological molecules. These biosensors typically consist of two main components - a biological recognition element, such as an enzyme or antibody, and a transducer that converts the interaction between the biological molecule and the recognition element into an electrical signal. The transducer typically consists of a working electrode, a reference electrode, and a counter electrode, which allow the movement of electrons between the recognition element and the surface of the electrode. The resulting electrical signal can then be measured and correlated to the concentration of the biological molecule of interest. Electrochemical biosensors are widely used in medical diagnostics, environmental monitoring, and food safety testing due to their high sensitivity, specificity, and ease of use.','{\"pat_doc\": 627.0, \"pub_alt\": 618.0, \"pub_doc\": 2802.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 81.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 13651160.0, \"pat_granted\": 212.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.7, \"pub_doc\": 147.8, \"clinic_doc\": 1.1, \"grant_fund\": -552123.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('505f75bf3d6171ea40802190afea573c','b78f1ff4779c63394e7882c5ca767bf9','5f9f631521aff2090e15184e37181d22','2023-09-04 19:03:15','2023-10-29 06:20:05','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Immunohistochemistry',48,'Immunohistochemistry is the most common application of immunostaining. It involves the process of selectively identifying antigens in cells of a tissue section by exploiting the principle of antibodies binding specifically to antigens in biological tissues. IHC takes its name from the roots \"immuno\", in reference to antibodies used in the procedure, and \"histo\", meaning tissue. Albert Coons conceptualized and first implemented the procedure in 1941. Visualising an antibody-antigen interaction can be accomplished in a number of ways, mainly either of the following: â€¢ Chromogenic immunohistochemistry, wherein an antibody is conjugated to an enzyme, such as peroxidase, that can catalyse a colour-producing reaction. â€¢ Immunofluorescence, where the antibody is tagged to a fluorophore, such as fluorescein or rhodamine. Immunohistochemical staining is widely used in the diagnosis of abnormal cells such as those found in cancerous tumors.','{\"pat_doc\": 679.0, \"pub_alt\": 28733.0, \"pub_doc\": 63246.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1587.0, \"clinic_alt\": 553.0, \"clinic_doc\": 863.0, \"grant_fund\": 465499696.0, \"pat_granted\": 240.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.1, \"pub_doc\": -408.2, \"clinic_doc\": 134.5, \"grant_fund\": -28858320.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5072b71d22a9cad99031c084568e8607','511fe46a46ed4b151dc1fca695ee35f6','3351a35ba591fc4123a3314384741e66','2023-09-08 01:54:20','2023-10-28 23:41:13','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Cationic polymers',24,'In chemistry, cationic polymerization is a type of chain growth polymerization in which a cationic initiator transfers charge to a monomer which then becomes reactive. This reactive monomer goes on to react similarly with other monomers to form a polymer. The types of monomers necessary for cationic polymerization are limited to alkenes with electron-donating substituents and heterocycles. Similar to anionic polymerization reactions, cationic polymerization reactions are very sensitive to the type of solvent used. Specifically, the ability of a solvent to form free ions will dictate the reactivity of the propagating cationic chain. Cationic polymerization is used in the production of polyisobutylene and poly.','{\"pat_doc\": 367.0, \"pub_alt\": 38.0, \"pub_doc\": 233.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 20.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5785287.0, \"pat_granted\": 122.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -10.9, \"pub_doc\": -2.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 44316.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5077626f86a789880246d6cf203f5b7f','c2aa8e8ff53300b96a4cd521696cbdbb','ba652e04894d8ad7c796a0f64375c740','2023-09-08 01:49:52','2023-10-28 23:56:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Suspension Culture',36,'A cell suspension or suspension culture is a type of cell culture in which single cells or small aggregates of cells are allowed to function and multiply in an agitated growth medium, thus forming a suspension. Suspension culture is one of the two classical types of cell culture, the other being adherent culture. The history of suspension cell culture closely aligns with the history of cell culture overall, but differs in maintenance methods and commercial applications. The cells themselves can either be derived from homogenized tissue or from heterogenous cell solutions. Suspension cell culture is commonly used to culture nonadhesive cell lines like hematopoietic cells, plant cells, and insect cells. While some cell lines are cultured in suspension, the majority of commercially available mammalian cell lines are adherent. Suspension cell cultures must be agitated to maintain cells in suspension, and may require specialized equipment and flasks.','{\"pat_doc\": 928.0, \"pub_alt\": 278.0, \"pub_doc\": 928.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 32.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5587052.0, \"pat_granted\": 310.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.9, \"pub_doc\": -11.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -1405329.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('50818130322bd17006e7db54e6d589b0','00deab06d5e60c8c68a35ce17a92c7a4','9910e15122e1c94e1e5ae9068add6ff3','2023-09-05 22:04:15','2023-10-29 03:41:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Genome Editing',36,'Genome editing, or genome engineering, or gene editing, is a type of genetic engineering in which DNA is inserted, deleted, modified or replaced in the genome of a living organism. Unlike early genetic engineering techniques that randomly inserts genetic material into a host genome, genome editing targets the insertions to site-specific locations. The basic mechanism involved in genetic manipulations through programmable nucleases is the recognition of target genomic loci and binding of effector DNA-binding domain, double-strand breaks in target DNA by the restriction endonucleases, and the repair of DSBs through homology-directed recombination or non-homologous end joining.','{\"pat_doc\": 2446.0, \"pub_alt\": 3578.0, \"pub_doc\": 8103.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1414.0, \"clinic_alt\": 67.0, \"clinic_doc\": 13.0, \"grant_fund\": 790934574.0, \"pat_granted\": 493.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 18.2, \"pub_doc\": 106.1, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -34230182.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('50a29b9c211060f709e31609f9d8a393','7817ed2cad0c9306c26e32a11da07b14','191b41c4706125327318783808a1e02d','2023-09-07 23:52:24','2023-10-28 17:01:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Bioconjugates','Antibody Drug Conjugates',12,'Antibody-drug conjugates or ADCs are a class of biopharmaceutical drugs designed as a targeted therapy for treating cancer. Unlike chemotherapy, ADCs are intended to target and kill tumor cells while sparing healthy cells. As of 2019, some 56 pharmaceutical companies were developing ADCs. ADCs are complex molecules composed of an antibody linked to a biologically active cytotoxic payload or drug. Antibody-drug conjugates are an example of bioconjugates and immunoconjugates. ADCs combine the targeting properties of monoclonal antibodies with the cancer-killing capabilities of cytotoxic drugs, designed to discriminate between healthy and diseased tissue.','{\"pat_doc\": 429.0, \"pub_alt\": 337.0, \"pub_doc\": 178.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 888391.0, \"pat_granted\": 87.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": 18.3, \"clinic_doc\": 2.1, \"grant_fund\": -1636318.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('50d8f55b8acf13d9796be8a19cf2d27f','a7ad6a132b7a2b00d790b121db7d86dd','f1282be727c426b09902ece3b89742e1','2023-09-08 00:32:37','2023-10-28 16:16:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Dendrimers',24,'Dendrimers are highly ordered, branched polymeric molecules. Synonymous terms for dendrimer include arborols and cascade molecules. Typically, dendrimers are symmetric about the core, and often adopt a spherical three-dimensional morphology. The word dendron is also encountered frequently. A dendron usually contains a single chemically addressable group called the focal point or core. The difference between dendrons and dendrimers is illustrated in the top figure, but the terms are typically encountered interchangeably. The first dendrimers were made by divergent synthesis approaches by Fritz VÃ¶gtle in 1978, R.G. Denkewalter at Allied Corporation in 1981, Donald Tomalia at Dow Chemical in 1983 and in 1985, and by George R. Newkome in 1985. In 1990 a convergent synthetic approach was introduced by Craig Hawker and Jean FrÃ©chet. Dendrimer popularity then greatly increased, resulting in more than 5,000 scientific papers and patents by the year 2005.','{\"pat_doc\": 272.0, \"pub_alt\": 265.0, \"pub_doc\": 1421.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 43.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 10283135.0, \"pat_granted\": 72.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.3, \"pub_doc\": -12.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -1003737.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('50dd657427d3017eca4cedc61277cb8b','4703ee189b43ed759604065a8ab8bcd0','38375efab29a9add974615a48ca4c5ab','2023-09-08 02:24:52','2023-10-28 22:21:09','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Crystallography',24,'Protein crystallography is a technique used to determine the precise three-dimensional structure of proteins. It involves growing crystals of a protein of interest and using X-rays to deduce the position of each atom within the crystal lattice. The resulting structure can provide valuable insights into the function of the protein, including its interactions with other molecules and potential drug targets. Protein crystallography has played a crucial role in the fields of biology, biochemistry, and drug discovery, and continues to be an important tool for understanding the molecular basis of disease.','{\"pat_doc\": 6.0, \"pub_alt\": 76.0, \"pub_doc\": 124.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 24.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 8700159.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 2.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -4868876.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('50e0fff189a456ad7e2bcc1fe32d7332','00f5350f80c16146d1f1e5be0746e46e','e910bc33478f3cb83e3ef258c7d92a6c','2023-09-08 02:32:48','2023-10-28 14:21:12','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel Drug Delivery','Gonadotropin-Releasing-Hormone Agonist',12,'A gonadotropin-releasing hormone agonist is a type of medication which affects gonadotropins and sex hormones. They are used for a variety of indications including in fertility medicine and to lower sex hormone levels in the treatment of hormone-sensitive cancers such as prostate cancer and breast cancer, certain gynecological disorders like heavy periods and endometriosis, high testosterone levels in women, early puberty in children, as a part of transgender hormone therapy, and to delay puberty in transgender youth among other uses. It is also used in the suppression of spontaneous ovulation as part of controlled ovarian hyperstimulation, an essential component in in IVF. GnRH agonists are given by injections into fat, as implants placed into fat, and as nasal sprays.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5150509f49830b0eb960df30e14c2b5d','a7ad6a132b7a2b00d790b121db7d86dd','f1282be727c426b09902ece3b89742e1','2023-09-08 00:32:37','2023-10-28 16:16:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Dendrimers',12,'Dendrimers are highly ordered, branched polymeric molecules. Synonymous terms for dendrimer include arborols and cascade molecules. Typically, dendrimers are symmetric about the core, and often adopt a spherical three-dimensional morphology. The word dendron is also encountered frequently. A dendron usually contains a single chemically addressable group called the focal point or core. The difference between dendrons and dendrimers is illustrated in the top figure, but the terms are typically encountered interchangeably. The first dendrimers were made by divergent synthesis approaches by Fritz VÃ¶gtle in 1978, R.G. Denkewalter at Allied Corporation in 1981, Donald Tomalia at Dow Chemical in 1983 and in 1985, and by George R. Newkome in 1985. In 1990 a convergent synthetic approach was introduced by Craig Hawker and Jean FrÃ©chet. Dendrimer popularity then greatly increased, resulting in more than 5,000 scientific papers and patents by the year 2005.','{\"pat_doc\": 123.0, \"pub_alt\": 265.0, \"pub_doc\": 700.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 11.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 3585656.0, \"pat_granted\": 31.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.3, \"pub_doc\": -12.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -1003737.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5195693c90637435c5e5d90ee5ad76bd','ae3fe7b4d0291ed05028397533f28114','3147652f436cfa0a26c21b17f2c50188','2023-09-05 21:59:53','2023-10-28 17:36:10','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','induced pluripotent stem cells',36,'Induced pluripotent stem cells are a type of pluripotent stem cell that can be generated directly from a somatic cell. The iPSC technology was pioneered by Shinya Yamanaka and Kazutoshi Takahashi in Kyoto, Japan, who together showed in 2006 that the introduction of four specific genes, collectively known as Yamanaka factors, encoding transcription factors could convert somatic cells into pluripotent stem cells. Shinya Yamanaka was awarded the 2012 Nobel Prize along with Sir John Gurdon \"for the discovery that mature cells can be reprogrammed to become pluripotent.\" Pluripotent stem cells hold promise in the field of regenerative medicine. Because they can propagate indefinitely, as well as give rise to every other cell type in the body, they represent a single source of cells that could be used to replace those lost to damage or disease. The most well-known type of pluripotent stem cell is the embryonic stem cell.','{\"pat_doc\": 1170.0, \"pub_alt\": 2998.0, \"pub_doc\": 5888.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 858.0, \"clinic_alt\": 9.0, \"clinic_doc\": 58.0, \"grant_fund\": 436214875.0, \"pat_granted\": 279.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 34.5, \"pub_doc\": -32.8, \"clinic_doc\": 11.8, \"grant_fund\": -40706986.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('51d82176089e7826650fb6945665f718','241acd5defc6bb6b835e678e78fce56c','35f85abe435e1302c602406f943817c0','2023-09-08 02:20:19','2023-10-28 14:41:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Polyplexes',24,'Polyplexes are a class of nanocarriers used in gene therapy that enable delivery of therapeutic nucleic acids such as plasmids, siRNAs, and miRNAs. Their structure consists of a cationic polymer, usually polyethyleneimine (PEI), complexed with negatively charged nucleic acids to form a stable complex. The advantage of polyplexes is their ability to protect the nucleic acids from degradation and facilitate their passage into cells, ultimately leading to efficient gene expression. Additionally, the surface charge and size of polyplexes can be modified, allowing for targeted delivery and reduced toxicity. Polyplexes have shown great promise in preclinical studies, but their clinical translation is still limited due to challenges such as immune response and optimization of delivery parameters. Nonetheless, they continue to be an exciting field of study with potential for a variety of gene therapy applications.','{\"pat_doc\": 59.0, \"pub_alt\": 1037.0, \"pub_doc\": 238.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1646878.0, \"pat_granted\": 5.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 7.8, \"pub_doc\": 1.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -353261.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('51f16eb574481c85241739f431b089ae','7f22a30b9d31980762db19938046f3e9','5762d74cf97f0e57d03def69845fe3e1','2023-09-08 02:43:41','2023-10-28 21:46:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Enzyme Technology',48,'Enzyme Technology involves the use of enzymes to carry out specific chemical reactions, useful in various industries such as food, pharmaceuticals, and the environment. Enzymes are biocatalysts that facilitate chemical reactions without being consumed in the process. They are highly specific and can work under mild conditions, making them eco-friendly and efficient. Enzyme Technology includes the optimization of enzyme-catalyzed reactions, engineering of new enzymes, and production of enzymes through fermentation processes. The applications of enzyme technology are vast, including the production of biofuels, detergents, food additives, and medications. The use of enzyme technology can also lead to more sustainable processes, reduced waste, and decreased environmental impact in industries.','{\"pat_doc\": 135.0, \"pub_alt\": 97.0, \"pub_doc\": 158.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 20.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 20065242.0, \"pat_granted\": 34.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -7.1, \"pub_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -310772.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5206563f525d2be6ce894f57836b69dc','55794ad69e12330a0b6d80e9fdb0988d','e612e4b67f9789306cf3914a627ea83c','2023-09-07 23:58:23','2023-10-29 02:16:16','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Metabolic Engineering',36,'Metabolic engineering is the practice of optimizing genetic and regulatory processes within cells to increase the cells production of a certain substance. These processes are chemical networks that use a series of biochemical reactions and enzymes that allow cells to convert raw materials into molecules necessary for the cells survival. Metabolic engineering specifically seeks to mathematically model these networks, calculate a yield of useful products, and pin point parts of the network that constrain the production of these products. Genetic engineering techniques can then be used to modify the network in order to relieve these constraints. Once again this modified network can be modeled to calculate the new product yield. The ultimate goal of metabolic engineering is to be able to use these organisms to produce valuable substances on an industrial scale in a cost-effective manner.','{\"pat_doc\": 690.0, \"pub_alt\": 260.0, \"pub_doc\": 3528.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 214.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 93917516.0, \"pat_granted\": 213.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 34.9, \"pub_doc\": 16.6, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -6039306.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5235b3bfdae53ea549b49391904cb313','4d2d0b15ee17780893b8c9e0ae59e835','005e837817c21a0393b99843cbfee450','2023-09-08 01:10:59','2023-10-28 15:36:19','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Acromegaly',36,'Acromegaly is a disorder that results in excess growth of certain parts of the human body. It is caused by excess growth hormone after the growth plates have closed. The initial symptom is typically enlargement of the hands and feet. There may also be an enlargement of the forehead, jaw, and nose. Other symptoms may include joint pain, thicker skin, deepening of the voice, headaches, and problems with vision. Complications of the disease may include type 2 diabetes, sleep apnea, and high blood pressure.','{\"pat_doc\": 80.0, \"pub_alt\": 367.0, \"pub_doc\": 1658.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 10.0, \"clinic_alt\": 32.0, \"clinic_doc\": 82.0, \"grant_fund\": 2115377.0, \"pat_granted\": 19.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": -4.4, \"clinic_doc\": 10.7, \"grant_fund\": 169355.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('530eb59245bb551704daa22595c504e5','4823e60bd764349fc024f2fba11838f0','30640b686e5be896faa3d14ed6691346','2023-09-05 18:49:44','2023-10-29 05:35:06','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Biosensor',24,'A biosensor is an analytical device, used for the detection of a chemical substance, that combines a biological component with a physicochemical detector. The sensitive biological element, e.g. tissue, microorganisms, organelles, cell receptors, enzymes, antibodies, nucleic acids, etc., is a biologically derived material or biomimetic component that interacts with, binds with, or recognizes the analyte under study. The biologically sensitive elements can also be created by biological engineering. The transducer or the detector element, which transforms one signal into another one, works in a physicochemical way: optical, piezoelectric, electrochemical, electrochemiluminescence etc., resulting from the interaction of the analyte with the biological element, to easily measure and quantify. The biosensor reader device connects with the associated electronics or signal processors that are primarily responsible for the display of the results in a user-friendly way.','{\"pat_doc\": 5173.0, \"pub_alt\": 1506.0, \"pub_doc\": 18503.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 963.0, \"clinic_alt\": 52.0, \"clinic_doc\": 110.0, \"grant_fund\": 471849952.0, \"pat_granted\": 1736.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 137.4, \"pub_doc\": 867.1, \"clinic_doc\": 19.0, \"grant_fund\": -13437491.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('534683bf0a7c9aac1a69196711bada1e','8cc017d911f60e86f3530c8efab7f91a','7cfcc2197e33173ce522354c4a1177f6','2023-09-07 23:46:10','2023-10-29 02:31:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Green Hydrogen',12,'Green hydrogen is hydrogen generated from either renewable energy or low-carbon power. Green hydrogen has significantly lower carbon emissions than grey hydrogen, which is derived from fossil fuels without carbon capture. Green hydrogen may be used to decarbonize sectors that are hard to electrify, such as cement and iron production. Green hydrogen can be used to produce green ammonia, the main constituent of synthetic fertilizer. It can also be used for long-duration grid energy storage, and for long-duration seasonal energy storage. As of 2021, green hydrogen accounted for less than 0.04% of total hydrogen production. Its cost relative to hydrogen derived from fossil fuels is the main reason green hydrogen is in less demand.','{\"pat_doc\": 191.0, \"pub_alt\": 396.0, \"pub_doc\": 1946.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 190.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 277455561.0, \"pat_granted\": 51.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 63.1, \"pub_doc\": 594.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 22939710.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('53488f0f4695fba11d4818e69e39df08','df68dc3c44b77575d9caaef9764342db','5cc2df341e20d3c3cf94910f9000682b','2023-09-08 08:32:17','2023-10-28 13:36:17','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Squamous cell carcinoma',48,'Squamous-cell carcinomas, also known as epidermoid carcinomas, comprise a number of different types of cancer that begin in squamous cells. These cells form on the surface of the skin, on the lining of hollow organs in the body, and on the lining of the respiratory and digestive tracts. Common types include: â€¢ cutaneous squamous-cell carcinoma: a type of skin cancer â€¢ squamous-cell carcinoma of the lung: a type of lung cancer â€¢ squamous-cell thyroid carcinoma: a type of thyroid cancer â€¢ esophageal squamous-cell carcinoma: a type of esophageal cancer â€¢ squamous-cell carcinoma of the vagina: a type of vaginal cancer. Despite sharing the name \"squamous-cell carcinoma\", the SCCs of different body sites can show differences in their presented symptoms, natural history, prognosis, and response to treatment.','{\"pat_doc\": 1536.0, \"pub_alt\": 1142.0, \"pub_doc\": 45412.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1188.0, \"clinic_alt\": 717.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2268.0, \"grant_fund\": 325675378.0, \"pat_granted\": 380.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 29.4, \"pub_doc\": 69.4, \"clinic_doc\": 397.4, \"grant_fund\": -19576090.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('53ba9af4ea4c0c32cf8162eee96b49bc','7e6303a93deff34a836da02c9ec9b121','b8d8729029b072a6d46a6e6415f7d63a','2023-09-20 19:21:20','2023-10-28 14:51:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Addisons Disease',48,'Addisons disease, also known as primary adrenal insufficiency, is a rare long-term endocrine disorder characterized by inadequate production of the steroid hormones cortisol and aldosterone by the two outer layers of the cells of the adrenal glands, causing adrenal insufficiency. Symptoms generally come on slowly and insidiously and may include abdominal pain and gastrointestinal abnormalities, weakness, and weight loss. Darkening of the skin in certain areas may also occur. Under certain circumstances, an adrenal crisis may occur with low blood pressure, vomiting, lower back pain, and loss of consciousness. Mood changes may also occur. Rapid onset of symptoms indicates acute adrenal failure, which is a clinical emergency. An adrenal crisis can be triggered by stress, such as from an injury, surgery, or infection. Addisons disease arises from problems with the adrenal gland such that not enough of the steroid hormone cortisol and possibly aldosterone are produced.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 7.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5427e68e57f2062813f9d7459b5c9dc0','382772c54fc63869435b590e8d1111c4','43d3334d4623a18878a471a105e8c82e','2023-09-08 00:27:07','2023-10-28 16:21:14','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Pheochromocytoma',24,'Pheochromocytoma is a rare tumor of the adrenal medulla composed of chromaffin cells, also known as pheochromocytes. When a tumor composed of the same cells as a pheochromocytoma develops outside the adrenal gland, it is referred to as a paraganglioma. These neuroendocrine tumors typically release massive amounts of catecholamines, metanephrines, or methoxytyramine, which result in the most common symptoms, including hypertension, tachycardia, and diaphoresis. Rarely, some tumors may secrete little to no catecholamines, making diagnosis difficult. While tumors of the head and neck are parasympathetic, their sympathetic counterparts are predominantly located in the abdomen and pelvis, particularly concentrated at the organ of Zuckerkandl.','{\"pat_doc\": 25.0, \"pub_alt\": 288.0, \"pub_doc\": 1953.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 312.0, \"clinic_doc\": 92.0, \"grant_fund\": 2489455.0, \"pat_granted\": 7.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.4, \"pub_doc\": 22.8, \"clinic_doc\": 17.8, \"grant_fund\": -4557007.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('54b1e22ba7260180e4a73dcd0cbb8e2d','a7ad6a132b7a2b00d790b121db7d86dd','f1282be727c426b09902ece3b89742e1','2023-09-08 00:32:37','2023-10-28 16:16:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Dendrimers',48,'Dendrimers are highly ordered, branched polymeric molecules. Synonymous terms for dendrimer include arborols and cascade molecules. Typically, dendrimers are symmetric about the core, and often adopt a spherical three-dimensional morphology. The word dendron is also encountered frequently. A dendron usually contains a single chemically addressable group called the focal point or core. The difference between dendrons and dendrimers is illustrated in the top figure, but the terms are typically encountered interchangeably. The first dendrimers were made by divergent synthesis approaches by Fritz VÃ¶gtle in 1978, R.G. Denkewalter at Allied Corporation in 1981, Donald Tomalia at Dow Chemical in 1983 and in 1985, and by George R. Newkome in 1985. In 1990 a convergent synthetic approach was introduced by Craig Hawker and Jean FrÃ©chet. Dendrimer popularity then greatly increased, resulting in more than 5,000 scientific papers and patents by the year 2005.','{\"pat_doc\": 533.0, \"pub_alt\": 265.0, \"pub_doc\": 2935.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 122.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 24138635.0, \"pat_granted\": 141.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.3, \"pub_doc\": -12.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -1003737.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('555b28497b51d5ad45c9f4f073cde515','0130bb7e16467c607ae66d5d6b5fe5d1','69904542b990c5c24086b0dfa8c698cf','2023-09-05 22:51:40','2023-10-29 03:01:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','High-Throughput Screening',12,'High-throughput screening is a method for scientific experimentation especially used in drug discovery and relevant to the fields of biology, materials science and chemistry. Using robotics, data processing/control software, liquid handling devices, and sensitive detectors, high-throughput screening allows a researcher to quickly conduct millions of chemical, genetic, or pharmacological tests. Through this process one can quickly recognize active compounds, antibodies, or genes that modulate a particular biomolecular pathway. The results of these experiments provide starting points for drug design and for understanding the noninteraction or role of a particular location.','{\"pat_doc\": 303.0, \"pub_alt\": 350.0, \"pub_doc\": 1489.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 110.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 52620334.0, \"pat_granted\": 97.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.8, \"pub_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -83628586.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('555de3e411e38520da31b607639f1fa1','fa64bf855faf8c0f2191aab2fb8e889c','1eb03b411e805213588194c37797ec5c','2023-09-05 21:42:31','2023-10-28 17:41:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Hypothyroidism',12,'Hypothyroidism is a disorder of the endocrine system in which the thyroid gland does not produce enough thyroid hormone. It can cause a number of symptoms, such as poor ability to tolerate cold, a feeling of tiredness, constipation, slow heart rate, depression, and weight gain. Occasionally there may be swelling of the front part of the neck due to goitre. Untreated cases of hypothyroidism during pregnancy can lead to delays in growth and intellectual development in the baby or congenital iodine deficiency syndrome. Worldwide, too little iodine in the diet is the most common cause of hypothyroidism. Hashimotos thyroiditis is the most common cause of hypothyroidism in countries with sufficient dietary iodine. Less common causes include previous treatment with radioactive iodine, injury to the hypothalamus or the anterior pituitary gland, certain medications, a lack of a functioning thyroid at birth, or previous thyroid surgery.','{\"pat_doc\": 59.0, \"pub_alt\": 605.0, \"pub_doc\": 3619.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 18.0, \"clinic_alt\": 22.0, \"clinic_doc\": 310.0, \"grant_fund\": 3642886.0, \"pat_granted\": 7.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.4, \"pub_doc\": 201.3, \"clinic_doc\": 62.3, \"grant_fund\": -98143.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('55a3c024a04bf1aa31dfed3207f689f3','30f5159f16b7a113dcbf47772afc4c96','0a44fd511d173aa7606e2fa180b97dbd','2023-09-08 02:14:34','2023-10-28 22:51:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Gene Circuits',36,'A gene circuit is a network of genes that work together to produce a certain outcome, such as the regulation of a specific biological process. These circuits function through gene expression, in which certain genes are turned on or off in response to environmental stimuli or cellular signals. The composition of the gene circuit can vary depending on the desired outcome, with different genes and regulatory elements influencing the behavior of the circuit. Gene circuits are important for understanding the complex processes that occur within cells and organisms, and have potential applications in fields such as synthetic biology and gene therapy.','{\"pat_doc\": 13.0, \"pub_alt\": 686.0, \"pub_doc\": 277.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 51.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 59560333.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 6.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2080968.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('55a8c4d24ce4218741aea488791ae8c8','ee1ceea70d26f9efca309b5f07a6e479','77e5f6785bd7c9d4f3610b4ac830ad4e','2023-09-08 00:22:21','2023-10-29 01:51:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Electroporation',12,'Electroporation, or electropermeabilization, is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing chemicals, drugs, electrode arrays or DNA to be introduced into the cell. In microbiology, the process of electroporation is often used to transform bacteria, yeast, or plant protoplasts by introducing new coding DNA. If bacteria and plasmids are mixed together, the plasmids can be transferred into the bacteria after electroporation, though depending on what is being transferred, cell-penetrating peptides or CellSqueeze could also be used. Electroporation works by passing thousands of volts across suspended cells in an electroporation cuvette. Afterwards, the cells have to be handled carefully until they have had a chance to divide, producing new cells that contain reproduced plasmids.','{\"pat_doc\": 615.0, \"pub_alt\": 688.0, \"pub_doc\": 893.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 38.0, \"clinic_alt\": 473.0, \"clinic_doc\": 97.0, \"grant_fund\": 14861397.0, \"pat_granted\": 163.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 72.4, \"pub_doc\": -22.4, \"clinic_doc\": 21.4, \"grant_fund\": -13946036.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('55f82610234856df6e3fe3837c4e0e47','73178bcae12bbd288347bb8d8e293d45','9b201e2ee1a601e1d33b326135e74c79','2023-09-08 08:26:31','2023-10-28 10:35:32','Electronics','Devices','Other','4D printing',48,'4-dimensional printing uses the same techniques of 3D printing through computer-programmed deposition of material in successive layers to create a three-dimensional object. However, in 4D printing, the resulting 3D shape is able to morph into different forms in response to environmental stimulus, with the 4th dimension being the time-dependent shape change after the printing. It is therefore a type of programmable matter, wherein after the fabrication process, the printed product reacts with parameters within the environment and changes its form accordingly.','{\"pat_doc\": 419.0, \"pub_alt\": 240.0, \"pub_doc\": 1207.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 61.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 27554215.0, \"pat_granted\": 153.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 10.9, \"pub_doc\": 86.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 226691.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('56814ecb6bb996ba05d5735f7c9486f3','e24808701d1b869f29beb5b17a6f3966','0a566310cdeaa23e7fc0d55380c35a91','2023-09-08 02:38:56','2023-10-28 14:11:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Gene therapies (Non-viral)','mRNA therapy',48,'mRNA (messenger RNA) therapy is a cutting-edge medical technique that harnesses the bodys own ability to produce essential proteins to better fight disease. The therapy involves injecting synthetic strands of mRNA into the body, which are then recognized by the bodys own cells as \"blueprints\" for specific proteins that are vital for health. These proteins are then produced by the bodys cells and can be used to combat a wide range of illnesses, from cancer to genetic disorders to viral infections like COVID-19. mRNA therapy has shown a lot of promise in clinical trials, with some treatments already approved for use in certain conditions. While the technology is still in its early stages, experts believe that mRNA therapy could revolutionize the way we treat diseases in the coming years.','{\"pat_doc\": 131.0, \"pub_alt\": 350.0, \"pub_doc\": 86.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 9.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 3512149.0, \"pat_granted\": 20.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.7, \"pub_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.4, \"grant_fund\": 71200.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('56f7a3445832f29556a4107825ac2298','d0cc167aa82d70fd2bfffe86208ac337','870950b481f06063886edd5c24dd2f8a','2023-09-08 09:13:24','2023-10-28 13:06:13','Healthcare','Neuroscience','Other','Neuro-inflammation',48,'Neuroinflammation is inflammation of the nervous tissue. It may be initiated in response to a variety of cues, including infection, traumatic brain injury, toxic metabolites, or autoimmunity. In the central nervous system, including the brain and spinal cord, microglia are the resident innate immune cells that are activated in response to these cues. The CNS is typically an immunologically privileged site because peripheral immune cells are generally blocked by the bloodâ€“brain barrier, a specialized structure composed of astrocytes and endothelial cells. However, circulating peripheral immune cells may surpass a compromised BBB and encounter neurons and glial cells expressing major histocompatibility complex molecules, perpetuating the immune response. Although the response is initiated to protect the central nervous system from the infectious agent, the effect may be toxic and widespread inflammation as well as further migration of leukocytes through the bloodâ€“brain barrier may occur.','{\"pat_doc\": 32.0, \"pub_alt\": 602.0, \"pub_doc\": 617.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 54.0, \"clinic_alt\": 35.0, \"clinic_doc\": 42.0, \"grant_fund\": 36471200.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": -14.9, \"clinic_doc\": 6.2, \"grant_fund\": -2859987.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('572c81356ea9ead06595a1c8b64633c1','a7ad6a132b7a2b00d790b121db7d86dd','f1282be727c426b09902ece3b89742e1','2023-09-08 00:32:37','2023-10-28 16:16:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Dendrimers',36,'Dendrimers are highly ordered, branched polymeric molecules. Synonymous terms for dendrimer include arborols and cascade molecules. Typically, dendrimers are symmetric about the core, and often adopt a spherical three-dimensional morphology. The word dendron is also encountered frequently. A dendron usually contains a single chemically addressable group called the focal point or core. The difference between dendrons and dendrimers is illustrated in the top figure, but the terms are typically encountered interchangeably. The first dendrimers were made by divergent synthesis approaches by Fritz VÃ¶gtle in 1978, R.G. Denkewalter at Allied Corporation in 1981, Donald Tomalia at Dow Chemical in 1983 and in 1985, and by George R. Newkome in 1985. In 1990 a convergent synthetic approach was introduced by Craig Hawker and Jean FrÃ©chet. Dendrimer popularity then greatly increased, resulting in more than 5,000 scientific papers and patents by the year 2005.','{\"pat_doc\": 416.0, \"pub_alt\": 265.0, \"pub_doc\": 2217.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 76.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 17320475.0, \"pat_granted\": 112.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.3, \"pub_doc\": -12.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -1003737.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5817850e39da464dbee0444230e22e76','400032bc6a390bdea6fc89bda66806fe','5ca1ea433f162c5e837f4ddcc3c02253','2023-09-04 18:36:28','2023-10-29 06:56:10','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Chromatography',24,'In chemical analysis, chromatography is a laboratory technique for the separation of a mixture into its components. The mixture is dissolved in a fluid solvent (gas or liquid) called the mobile phase, which carries it through a system (a column, a capillary tube, a plate, or a sheet) on which a material called the stationary phase is fixed.','{\"pat_doc\": 23280.0, \"pub_alt\": 4918.0, \"pub_doc\": 63058.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1002.0, \"clinic_alt\": 100.0, \"clinic_doc\": 454.0, \"grant_fund\": 247361960.0, \"pat_granted\": 8991.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 570.9, \"pub_doc\": 561.6, \"clinic_doc\": 78.4, \"grant_fund\": -32028130.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('586b47312058ba78f98357a47abe2816','1728b9cb87efc77cfd614e3c4311a042','ee2727bc78203418d56b7f3bacf8d4dc','2023-09-08 01:47:28','2023-10-28 11:15:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Web 3.0',12,'Web 3.0, also known as the Semantic Web, refers to the evolution of the internet that aims to provide a more seamless and intelligent user experience. It is based on the idea of improving the way data is accessed and used, by creating a universal language for machines to understand and communicate with each other. This means that information on the web will be more interconnected, accessible, and easier to find. Web 3.0 aims to enable decentralization, personalization, and improved security on the internet. It has the potential to transform industries such as healthcare, finance, and education, by improving data sharing, privacy, and efficiency.','{\"pat_doc\": 11.0, \"pub_alt\": 338.0, \"pub_doc\": 329.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 9.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1748742.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.3, \"pub_doc\": 89.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 613675.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5876b84a92851bfe2e25d1ce48555972','a4a5753db73052249bc74606e77f9c86','3bae6e0ea5ff6b484acb36d0b12b9eb0','2023-09-05 22:21:15','2023-10-29 03:16:16','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cryopreservation',48,'Cryopreservation or cryoconservation is a process where biological material - cells, tissues, or organs - are frozen to preserve the material for an extended period of time. At low temperatures any cell metabolism which might cause damage to the biological material in question is effectively stopped. Cryopreservation is an effective way to transport biological samples over long distances, store samples for prolonged periods of time, and create a bank of samples for users. Molecules, referred to as cryoprotective agents, are added to reduce the osmotic shock and physical stresses cells undergo in the freezing process. Some cryoprotective agents used in research are inspired by plants and animals in nature that have unique cold tolerance to survive harsh winters, including: trees, wood frogs, and tardigrades.','{\"pat_doc\": 3668.0, \"pub_alt\": 1278.0, \"pub_doc\": 7690.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 444.0, \"clinic_alt\": 14.0, \"clinic_doc\": 204.0, \"grant_fund\": 142322984.0, \"pat_granted\": 1609.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 37.6, \"pub_doc\": 46.4, \"clinic_doc\": 29.8, \"grant_fund\": -15784626.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('58849c13b5bf470dea639642c4e6e025','6ad6b984db7a5bd574d38199653cd677','9e26cf59e38dc5ee0cf30259ac7c92ca','2023-09-05 20:05:34','2023-10-29 04:46:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Microfluidics',48,'Microfluidics refers to a system that manipulates a small amount of fluids using small channels with sizes ten to hundreds micrometres. It is a multidisciplinary field that involves molecular analysis, biodefence, molecular biology, and microelectronics. It has practical applications in the design of systems that process low volumes of fluids to achieve multiplexing, automation, and high-throughput screening. Microfluidics emerged in the beginning of the 1980s and is used in the development of inkjet printheads, DNA chips, lab-on-a-chip technology, micro-propulsion, and micro-thermal technologies. Typically, micro means one of the following features: â€¢ Small volumes â€¢ Small size â€¢ Low energy consumption â€¢ Microdomain effects. Typically microfluidic systems transport, mix, separate, or otherwise process fluids. Various applications rely on passive fluid control using capillary forces, in the form of capillary flow modifying elements, akin to flow resistors and flow accelerators.','{\"pat_doc\": 1374.0, \"pub_alt\": 762.0, \"pub_doc\": 8177.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1366.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 17.0, \"grant_fund\": 673897052.0, \"pat_granted\": 415.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 28.6, \"pub_doc\": 144.5, \"clinic_doc\": 2.3, \"grant_fund\": -40950330.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('58cf5b4943447377f841a1845f6e4d8b','30ab92573d44ab7bfab530de0c6c2f3b','834e427876f8944f329691ead9f0d4a1','2023-09-04 19:50:57','2023-10-28 18:06:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Coronary artery diseases',24,'Coronary artery diseases are a group of conditions that affect the blood vessels that supply the heart muscle with oxygen and nutrients. These diseases occur when there is a buildup of plaque, or fatty deposits, in the coronary arteries, which can narrow or block these vessels altogether. This can result in reduced blood flow to the heart, leading to chest pain (angina), shortness of breath, and even heart attacks. Risk factors for coronary artery disease include high blood pressure, high cholesterol, smoking, obesity, and an unhealthy diet. Treatment options for coronary artery disease include lifestyle changes such as exercise and diet modifications, medications, and in severe cases, surgery.','{\"pat_doc\": 21.0, \"pub_alt\": 339.0, \"pub_doc\": 401.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 11.0, \"clinic_alt\": 187.0, \"clinic_doc\": 49.0, \"grant_fund\": 2774033.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.7, \"pub_doc\": -4.9, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 134481.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('590002c2fec7ce58c89fb9e9eb45af81','123fff890be892fb84e8f950aecc8f54','e2436e9e1daec5dad6800e18965c31a2','2023-09-08 00:59:51','2023-10-28 16:01:19','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Monoclonal antibodies','Nanobodies',36,'Nanobodies are small antibody fragments with unique properties that offer promising potential for therapeutic and diagnostic applications. These fragments are derived from the immune system of camelids, such as camels and llamas, and consist of a single immunoglobulin domain that has a high affinity and specificity for its target. Nanobodies are much smaller and more stable than traditional antibodies, which allows them to penetrate deeper into tissues and reach difficult-to-access locations. Additionally, their small size and simplicity make it easier and cheaper to produce them at a large scale. Due to these advantages, nanobodies are being investigated for a variety of uses, including cancer therapy, imaging, and viral infections.','{\"pat_doc\": 386.0, \"pub_alt\": 1535.0, \"pub_doc\": 1298.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 219.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 114035395.0, \"pat_granted\": 80.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 40.8, \"pub_doc\": 70.3, \"clinic_doc\": 1.3, \"grant_fund\": -15354732.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5913b24722a63ea28918a3ac9d72e63c','1fccc88a9353a2b047cbe302f41187a4','e935f5dfeb3e4ae65d7860e4ea27b605','2023-09-05 20:23:19','2023-10-28 12:45:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Societal & Economic Disruptions','Post-COVID-19',12,'The concept of Post-COVID-19 refers to the scenario and circumstances following the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic. The world after COVID-19 is expected to be markedly different, with changes in the way people work, travel, socialize, and interact with each other. These changes may include a greater emphasis on remote work, increased use of technology for communication, more flexible working arrangements, significant shifts in consumer behavior, and a focus on public health and hygiene. The pandemic has also highlighted the importance of international cooperation and sustainable development, leading to the adoption of new policies aimed at creating a more resilient and equitable world. Ultimately, the post-COVID-19 era represents both an opportunity and a challenge for businesses, governments, and individuals to adapt and thrive in a rapidly changing world.','{\"pat_doc\": 18.0, \"pub_alt\": 7168.0, \"pub_doc\": 4516.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 43.0, \"clinic_alt\": 197.0, \"clinic_doc\": 205.0, \"grant_fund\": 7296582.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.4, \"pub_doc\": 1295.8, \"clinic_doc\": 64.2, \"grant_fund\": -5280894.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('593f27e5bd4f9121d91126a411e30687','7cdbaeda7c2e92f0a0d7bcfe3cd23472','e2d4dfcdd74fd300c5581dfc34bfe679','2023-09-05 22:19:06','2023-10-28 12:10:33','Electronics','Devices','Next Generation Computers','Brain-computer interfaces',36,'A brainâ€“computer interface, sometimes called a brainâ€“machine interface or smartbrain, is a direct communication pathway between the brains electrical activity and an external device, most commonly a computer or robotic limb. BCIs are often directed at researching, mapping, assisting, augmenting, or repairing human cognitive or sensory-motor functions. They are often conceptualized as a humanâ€“machine interface that skips the intermediary component of the physical movement of body parts, although they also raise the possibility of the erasure of the discreteness of brain and machine. Implementations of BCIs range from non-invasive and partially invasive to invasive, based on how close electrodes get to brain tissue.','{\"pat_doc\": 181.0, \"pub_alt\": 1231.0, \"pub_doc\": 1760.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 103.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 12.0, \"grant_fund\": 67203169.0, \"pat_granted\": 50.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 20.1, \"pub_doc\": 77.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -3687771.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('594ee1cb68460142e72878902a31e7d8','8a48608f902f6d6e18861f68c6c16aa1','afe94a7da70247bc6803357002649726','2023-09-08 11:13:41','2023-10-28 18:41:12','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Clinical Decision Support Systems',12,'Clinical decision support systems (CDSS) are computer programs designed to assist healthcare professionals in making clinical decisions by providing information and knowledge at the point of care. CDSS incorporate patient data and evidence-based guidelines to suggest potential diagnoses, recommend laboratory tests and treatment options, calculate medication doses and detect harmful drug interactions. CDSS can improve patient outcomes by enhancing the accuracy of diagnoses, preventing medical errors, and enabling clinicians to make more informed decisions based on relevant clinical evidence. Furthermore, CDSS can help reduce healthcare costs and improve efficiency by reducing unnecessary tests and treatments, and minimizing length of hospital stay. Overall, CDSS provide an important tool for healthcare professionals to provide high-quality patient care.','{\"pat_doc\": 7.0, \"pub_alt\": 543.0, \"pub_doc\": 399.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 10.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 23.0, \"grant_fund\": 3998154.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 46.6, \"clinic_doc\": 6.5, \"grant_fund\": -372976.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5991171a56829398e251d85e8f569ae1','fa50c7193d6065602454c2f7f0f8ac8f','089d2934c16e188b76ea22692ecca87c','2023-09-08 09:52:02','2023-10-28 20:11:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Affinity Chromatography',48,'Affinity chromatography is a method of separating a biomolecule from a mixture, based on a highly specific macromolecular binding interaction between the biomolecule and another substance. The specific type of binding interaction depends on the biomolecule of interest; antigen and antibody, enzyme and substrate, receptor and ligand, or protein and nucleic acid binding interactions are frequently exploited for isolation of various biomolecules. Affinity chromatography is useful for its high selectivity and resolution of separation, compared to other chromatographic methods.','{\"pat_doc\": 1648.0, \"pub_alt\": 356.0, \"pub_doc\": 2468.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 97.0, \"clinic_alt\": 8.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 15299494.0, \"pat_granted\": 550.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 7.8, \"pub_doc\": -45.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.5, \"grant_fund\": -1797705.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5994efe659bf0af760a303c2ca674b81','7817ed2cad0c9306c26e32a11da07b14','191b41c4706125327318783808a1e02d','2023-09-07 23:52:24','2023-10-28 17:01:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Bioconjugates','Antibody Drug Conjugates',48,'Antibody-drug conjugates or ADCs are a class of biopharmaceutical drugs designed as a targeted therapy for treating cancer. Unlike chemotherapy, ADCs are intended to target and kill tumor cells while sparing healthy cells. As of 2019, some 56 pharmaceutical companies were developing ADCs. ADCs are complex molecules composed of an antibody linked to a biologically active cytotoxic payload or drug. Antibody-drug conjugates are an example of bioconjugates and immunoconjugates. ADCs combine the targeting properties of monoclonal antibodies with the cancer-killing capabilities of cytotoxic drugs, designed to discriminate between healthy and diseased tissue.','{\"pat_doc\": 1662.0, \"pub_alt\": 337.0, \"pub_doc\": 505.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 33.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 19666853.0, \"pat_granted\": 319.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": 18.3, \"clinic_doc\": 2.1, \"grant_fund\": -1636318.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('599c7802fab55fb0bc4abe3b9614a377','51aee0cb27f70c84f894c07b0faada65','05f0a405c035c7fc807679b69158e068','2023-09-07 23:36:05','2023-10-28 17:11:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy',12,'Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is a condition in which muscle tissues of the heart become thickened without an obvious cause. The parts of the heart most commonly affected are the interventricular septum and the ventricles. This results in the heart being less able to pump blood effectively and also may cause electrical conduction problems. People who have HCM may have a range of symptoms. People may be asymptomatic, or may have fatigue, leg swelling, and shortness of breath. It may also result in chest pain or fainting. Symptoms may be worse when the person is dehydrated. Complications may include heart failure, an irregular heartbeat, and sudden cardiac death. HCM is most commonly inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern. It is often due to mutations in certain genes involved with making heart muscle proteins. Other inherited causes of left ventricular hypertrophy may include Fabry disease, Friedreichs ataxia, and certain medications such as tacrolimus.','{\"pat_doc\": 96.0, \"pub_alt\": 464.0, \"pub_doc\": 1630.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_alt\": 83.0, \"clinic_doc\": 112.0, \"grant_fund\": 9752500.0, \"pat_granted\": 22.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.4, \"pub_doc\": 133.8, \"clinic_doc\": 28.7, \"grant_fund\": -3954781.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('59cef546cb33e4dddd6d7ba518887a92','5ca1037faccf16f0f31845755f697cb1','a9ac8b399c3d26dbcd46f8f3ee6f5ae2','2023-09-08 09:09:41','2023-10-28 13:21:10','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Gynecologic Cancers',12,'Gynecologic oncology is a specialized field of medicine that focuses on cancers of the female reproductive system, including ovarian cancer, uterine cancer, vaginal cancer, cervical cancer, and vulvar cancer. As specialists, they have extensive training in the diagnosis and treatment of these cancers. In the United States, 82,000 women are diagnosed with gynecologic cancer annually. In 2013, an estimated 91,730 were diagnosed. There is low quality evidence which demonstrates women with gynaecological cancer receiving treatment from specialized centres benefit from longer survival than those managed in standard care. A meta analysis of three studies combining over 9000 women, suggested that specialist gynaecological cancer treatment centres may prolong the lives of women with ovarian cancer compared with general or community hospitals.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 70.0, \"pub_doc\": 258.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 339.0, \"clinic_doc\": 44.0, \"grant_fund\": 1351871.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.0, \"pub_doc\": 5.4, \"clinic_doc\": 12.6, \"grant_fund\": -1132384.5, \"capit