s in fields such as art, security, and medicine. A hologram is created by splitting a laser beam into two and directing one toward an object while the other heads straight onto a photographic plate or film. When the two beams meet, an interference pattern is formed that captures the objects unique features. This pattern can then be viewed, illuminating a hologram of the object that appears lifelike, with depth and dimension. Holography plays a significant role in virtual reality, data storage, and scientific research, among others.','{\"pat_doc\": 906.0, \"pub_alt\": 1635.0, \"pub_doc\": 5852.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 440.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 187010022.0, \"pat_granted\": 361.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -18.4, \"pub_doc\": 93.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": 8559104.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5b9959c744679c87de64c6b2276a7302','90f1f351860541863718a68f1e2fe5b6','7a49c80d1b80fc15aa79d84c9b4afdbb','2023-09-05 22:29:10','2023-10-28 17:21:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Natural killer cells',12,'Natural killer cells, also known as NK cells or large granular lymphocytes, are a type of cytotoxic lymphocyte critical to the innate immune system that belong to the rapidly expanding family of known innate lymphoid cells and represent 5â€“20% of all circulating lymphocytes in humans. The role of NK cells is analogous to that of cytotoxic T cells in the vertebrate adaptive immune response. NK cells provide rapid responses to virus-infected cell and other intracellular pathogens acting at around 3 days after infection, and respond to tumor formation. Typically, immune cells detect the antigen presented on major histocompatibility complex on infected cell surfaces, triggering cytokine release, causing the death of the infected cell by lysis or apoptosis. NK cells are unique, however, as they have the ability to recognize and kill stressed cells in the absence of antibodies and MHC, allowing for a much faster immune reaction.','{\"pat_doc\": 413.0, \"pub_alt\": 671.0, \"pub_doc\": 1166.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 32.0, \"clinic_alt\": 84.0, \"clinic_doc\": 124.0, \"grant_fund\": 6905984.0, \"pat_granted\": 89.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 32.0, \"pub_doc\": 58.8, \"clinic_doc\": 29.4, \"grant_fund\": -4654238.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5bc58e9e883d4df7d6ad90a3f808f328','ee19185ea91ee66a9b4ca70824b1b576','06752199a8f52b307494ef715b2504c5','2023-09-08 11:11:55','2023-10-28 18:46:09','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Biomarker Discovery',24,'Biomarker discovery is a medical term describing the process by which biomarkers are discovered. Many commonly used blood tests in medicine are biomarkers. There is interest in biomarker discovery on the part of the pharmaceutical industry; blood-test or other biomarkers could serve as intermediate markers of disease in clinical trials, and as possible drug targets.','{\"pat_doc\": 46.0, \"pub_alt\": 1311.0, \"pub_doc\": 1462.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 156.0, \"clinic_alt\": 309.0, \"clinic_doc\": 87.0, \"grant_fund\": 127875296.0, \"pat_granted\": 10.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": 37.9, \"clinic_doc\": 20.6, \"grant_fund\": -49263941.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5bff04055c24c62fc27e318bbd71dd1f','5a0a5b9065b639feb58f1b4e34dc9f7c','9c4ba206250041cf1644bb291a643634','2023-09-05 18:59:35','2023-10-29 05:21:13','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Next-Generation Sequencing',24,'Massive parallel sequencing or massively parallel sequencing is any of several high-throughput approaches to DNA sequencing using the concept of massively parallel processing; it is also called next-generation sequencing or second-generation sequencing. Some of these technologies emerged between 1993 and 1998 and have been commercially available since 2005. These technologies use miniaturized and parallelized platforms for sequencing of 1 million to 43 billion short reads per instrument run. Many NGS platforms differ in engineering configurations and sequencing chemistry. They share the technical paradigm of massive parallel sequencing via spatially separated, clonally amplified DNA templates or single DNA molecules in a flow cell. This design is very different from that of Sanger sequencingâ€”also known as capillary sequencing or first-generation sequencingâ€”which is based on electrophoretic separation of chain-termination products produced in individual sequencing reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 272.0, \"pub_alt\": 5565.0, \"pub_doc\": 13594.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 390.0, \"clinic_alt\": 58.0, \"clinic_doc\": 345.0, \"grant_fund\": 126089431.0, \"pat_granted\": 58.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.9, \"pub_doc\": 170.9, \"clinic_doc\": 72.6, \"grant_fund\": -38192044.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5c167ce8b43c9cdd5e33611814fa3d42','ffe250fc447887b501aee1b30580085f','c15525a97e5927c0f087d514b050aed9','2023-09-08 09:37:37','2023-10-28 20:56:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Distillation',36,'Distillation is a process used to separate liquids with different boiling points. It involves heating a mixture of liquids to vaporize the components with lower boiling points, collecting the vapor, and then condensing it back into a liquid form. The process is widely used in industries such as petroleum refining, where crude oil is distilled to produce various fuels and other products. In addition, distillation is a common method used to purify water, create alcoholic beverages, and extract essential oils from plant materials. The efficiency of distillation depends on the difference in boiling points between the components being separated, with greater differences resulting in more effective separation.','{\"pat_doc\": 31492.0, \"pub_alt\": 734.0, \"pub_doc\": 20449.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 347.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.0, \"grant_fund\": 131846036.0, \"pat_granted\": 15265.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 349.4, \"pub_doc\": 1168.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.6, \"grant_fund\": -3503023.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5c31b085ed926de063830a4d6f1fd96a','8b21dbe0cb1307d6f1256e0e5db60249','ccad4956fa80c9c27804d8a966399e00','2023-09-08 09:47:24','2023-10-28 20:31:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','High resolution mass spectrometry',24,'High resolution mass spectrometry (HRMS) is an advanced analytical technique that is used to determine the exact mass of atomic and molecular ions with very high accuracy. It is particularly useful in identifying unknown compounds, determining the composition of complex mixtures and characterizing the chemical structure of biomolecules such as peptides, proteins and nucleic acids. In HRMS, ions are first generated from a sample and then separated based on their mass-to-charge ratio using a mass spectrometer. The ions are then detected and their masses are measured using high resolution detectors. The high resolution of the technique enables the detection of very small mass differences, which can be used to differentiate between compounds with similar molecular weights. HRMS has revolutionized the field of analytical chemistry and has become an indispensable tool for many applications in areas such as pharmacology, environmental science, food analysis and forensics.','{\"pat_doc\": 93.0, \"pub_alt\": 1833.0, \"pub_doc\": 1046.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 55.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 21202169.0, \"pat_granted\": 31.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.4, \"pub_doc\": -17.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -1744859.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5c351b2232cc87848de9129f080f53de','1edf5dbb1a5ebbaef987b8b78449add1','d55c8f5e392f4de211e65cb1cf025f9d','2023-09-08 01:07:08','2023-10-29 00:41:20','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Stability',48,'mRNA stability is the measure of how long a messenger RNA (mRNA) molecule lasts within a cell before it is degraded. This is important because the stability of mRNA affects the amount of protein that can be produced from that mRNA. If mRNA is stable, it can persist in the cell and continue to produce protein. However, if the mRNA is unstable, it will degrade quickly and less protein will be produced. mRNA stability is regulated by a number of factors including sequence motifs, RNA-binding proteins, and the presence of other molecules. Understanding how mRNA stability is regulated can provide insights into gene expression and can be helpful in developing new therapies for certain diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 35.0, \"pub_alt\": 1837.0, \"pub_doc\": 1841.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 160.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 94428155.0, \"pat_granted\": 11.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.1, \"pub_doc\": 58.5, \"clinic_doc\": -0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1054364.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5c44913a3dc00a47c16842949a1f0922','dc9a89b7d5132f4c1c6c291f4d309152','acf051d7127b574167932dffa9cd1c71','2023-09-08 02:48:54','2023-10-28 21:31:14','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Laboratory Information Management System',36,'A laboratory information management system, sometimes referred to as a laboratory information system or laboratory management system, is a software-based solution with features that support a modern laboratorys operations. Key features includeâ€”but are not limited toâ€”workflow and data tracking support, flexible architecture, and data exchange interfaces, which fully \"support its use in regulated environments\". The features and uses of a LIMS have evolved over the years from simple sample tracking to an enterprise resource planning tool that manages multiple aspects of laboratory informatics. There is no useful definition of the term \"LIMS\" as it is used to encompass a number of different laboratory informatics components. The spread and depth of these components is highly dependent on the LIMS implementation itself. All LIMSs have a workflow component and some summary data management facilities but beyond that there are significant differences in functionality.','{\"pat_doc\": 48.0, \"pub_alt\": 112.0, \"pub_doc\": 152.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 16.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 20514256.0, \"pat_granted\": 11.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 8.9, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": -5084945.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5c658150cfd60ff225cf22bf8d30b7bc','6df6cc21f2a3ec039f6f594cd9050b81','22c986a1ed138cca635623e24850cd2d','2023-09-08 02:47:18','2023-10-28 14:05:05','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel Drug Delivery','Progesterone supplementation',24,'Progesterone supplementation, also known as progesterone therapy, is a medical treatment that involves taking supplemental doses of progesterone hormone. Progesterone is naturally produced by the ovaries during a womans menstrual cycle and plays a crucial role in regulating the menstrual cycle and preparing the body for pregnancy. However, some women may have low levels of progesterone, resulting in irregular menstrual cycles or difficulty getting pregnant. Progesterone supplementation can help balance hormonal levels and increase the chances of conceiving and sustaining a pregnancy. It can be administered through various methods, such as pills, injections, or vaginal suppositories, and is usually prescribed by a healthcare professional based on the patients individual needs and medical history.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 73.0, \"pub_doc\": 91.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 24.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 3.4, \"grant_fund\": -80930.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5cfd9dc518546a6379ef7bbb341ae8e6','53dc292182499fa33b7eec431b8b30ff','a0ec7ffe04c046d0f8469b5de966ddfa','2023-09-04 18:55:37','2023-10-29 06:31:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Flow Cytometry',48,'Flow cytometry is a technique used to detect and measure physical and chemical characteristics of a population of cells or particles. In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument. The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components. Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths. Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer. Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials. Uses for flow cytometry include: â€¢ Cell counting â€¢ Cell sorting â€¢ Determining cell characteristics and function â€¢ Detecting microorganisms â€¢ Biomarker detection â€¢ Protein engineering detection â€¢ Diagnosis of health disorders such as blood cancers â€¢ Measuring genome size.','{\"pat_doc\": 2017.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 67644.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2556.0, \"clinic_alt\": 590.0, \"clinic_doc\": 864.0, \"grant_fund\": 741017990.0, \"pat_granted\": 652.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.1, \"pub_doc\": -433.8, \"clinic_doc\": 137.2, \"grant_fund\": -49967547.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5d0c172c32065b838ab4f42ab8db7589','2531f8a177fbfd014f79f1851c094d65','6dae4310435505307085d7f2c73a1787','2023-09-08 00:48:13','2023-10-28 11:40:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Bioelectronics',24,'Bioelectronics is a field of research in the convergence of biology and electronics.','{\"pat_doc\": 44.0, \"pub_alt\": 1022.0, \"pub_doc\": 1031.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 105.0, \"clinic_alt\": 8.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 70945396.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": 59.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": 7394410.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5d432a6aa7304fa29f0fd7bbda358da1','e44792deacd6cf8232ea590a59b65829','ebccb11a63ab2a40e9dc38470854a837','2023-09-05 18:41:05','2023-10-29 05:46:09','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Differentiation',36,'Mechanisms of Development is a peer-reviewed scientific journal covering all aspects of developmental biology. It is the official journal of the International Society of Developmental Biologists and is published by Elsevier. The journal was established in 1972 as Cell Differentiation and was renamed Cell Differentiation and Development in 1988. It acquired its current name in December 1990. The editor-in-chief is D. Wilkinson. A separate section of the journal, Gene Expression Patterns, covers research on cloning and gene expression. In 2020 the journal became Cells & Development with the subtitle: Cell and Developmental Biology and their Quantitative Approaches.','{\"pat_doc\": 1190.0, \"pub_alt\": 1940.0, \"pub_doc\": 12320.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1354.0, \"clinic_alt\": 437.0, \"clinic_doc\": 136.0, \"grant_fund\": 500016823.0, \"pat_granted\": 365.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.6, \"pub_doc\": 33.4, \"clinic_doc\": 21.2, \"grant_fund\": -58438151.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5d90f00c614effcd0b3ec9b08249d3ef','75926dafeed6c4c3d2dd27794c573c76','88cbe0424257da986f5d8f34f678784d','2023-09-08 00:55:46','2023-10-29 00:56:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Microencapsulation',12,'Microencapsulation is a process in which tiny particles or droplets are surrounded by a coating to give small capsules, with useful properties. In general, it is used to incorporate food ingredients, enzymes, cells or other materials on a micro metric scale. Microencapsulation can also be used to enclose solids, liquids, or gases inside a micrometric wall made of hard or soft soluble film, in order to reduce dosing frequency and prevent the degradation of pharmaceuticals. In its simplest form, a microcapsule is a small sphere comprising a near-uniform wall enclosing some material. The enclosed material in the microcapsule is referred to as the core, internal phase, or fill, whereas the wall is sometimes called a shell, coating, or membrane. Some materials like lipids and polymers, such as alginate, may be used as a mixture to trap the material of interest inside. Most microcapsules have pores with diameters between a few nanometers and a few micrometers.','{\"pat_doc\": 120.0, \"pub_alt\": 24.0, \"pub_doc\": 735.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 12.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 2731106.0, \"pat_granted\": 43.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -18.0, \"pub_doc\": 33.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.4, \"grant_fund\": -2198383.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5de05fd8166c40003968b4784eed21eb','f6196df8d7ae9a4d7f729e93364e0bd8','f612c4461ae2b2296d600f221ca9683b','2023-09-08 00:23:58','2023-10-29 01:46:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Cryo-electron microscopy',36,'Cryo-electron microscopy (cryo-EM) is an imaging technique used to determine the three-dimensional structures of biological macromolecules at near-atomic resolution. It involves the rapid freezing of a sample and the use of an electron microscope to capture images of the frozen sample from multiple angles. These images are then combined and analyzed computationally to generate a high-resolution 3D model of the sample. Cryo-EM has revolutionized the field of structural biology, allowing researchers to study previously inaccessible proteins and complexes and providing new insights into biological processes such as protein folding, virus-host interactions, and drug binding. Its ability to work with relatively small samples, including single molecules, and its potential for automated imaging make cryo-EM a powerful tool for drug discovery and structural biology research.','{\"pat_doc\": 45.0, \"pub_alt\": 1845.0, \"pub_doc\": 3074.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 607.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 341600206.0, \"pat_granted\": 10.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_doc\": 58.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -19994930.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5e14bb93a4de226a0d48a56067148388','af4c9bfdfefe7c5c014015d91cb309a6','df80b2fb86114e734e7660ea92fdd1fc','2023-09-08 00:08:07','2023-10-29 02:01:16','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Viral Vectors',48,'Viral vectors are tools commonly used by molecular biologists to deliver genetic material into cells. This process can be performed inside a living organism or in cell culture. Viruses have evolved specialized molecular mechanisms to efficiently transport their genomes inside the cells they infect. Delivery of genes or other genetic material by a vector is termed transduction and the infected cells are described as transduced. Molecular biologists first harnessed this machinery in the 1970s. Paul Berg used a modified SV40 virus containing DNA from the bacteriophage Î» to infect monkey kidney cells maintained in culture. In addition to their use in molecular biology research, viral vectors are used for gene therapy and the development of vaccines. Vectors can either integrate into a cells genome or transiently express a gene with non-integrative vectors.','{\"pat_doc\": 3517.0, \"pub_alt\": 8518.0, \"pub_doc\": 3936.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 646.0, \"clinic_alt\": 75.0, \"clinic_doc\": 38.0, \"grant_fund\": 413772554.0, \"pat_granted\": 508.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 84.9, \"pub_doc\": -18.6, \"clinic_doc\": 4.4, \"grant_fund\": -2376931.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5e59ae73fedd81645c7beaa37d9ca866','bfef6514b60e4c25c2f8497aa216e34c','075f3ab037592e82b84202abe07674ba','2023-09-08 02:51:12','2023-10-28 10:45:33','Electronics','Devices','Next Generation Computers','Universal Quantum computer',48,'A quantum Turing machine or universal quantum computer is an abstract machine used to model the effects of a quantum computer. It provides a simple model that captures all of the power of quantum computationâ€”that is, any quantum algorithm can be expressed formally as a particular quantum Turing machine. However, the computationally equivalent quantum circuit is a more common model. Quantum Turing machines can be related to classical and probabilistic Turing machines in a framework based on transition matrices. That is, a matrix can be specified whose product with the matrix representing a classical or probabilistic machine provides the quantum probability matrix representing the quantum machine. This was shown by Lance Fortnow.','{\"pat_doc\": 5.0, \"pub_alt\": 180.0, \"pub_doc\": 172.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 29.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 40922157.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -8025713.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5e5f9e8211ad3effbb6c107ab66848b7','d3549b81bb39a9ac922f45ac120eb0cc','3da09264ab4cd2d03a36df24f5f30506','2023-09-08 09:48:28','2023-10-28 20:26:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry',12,'Inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry is a type of mass spectrometry that uses an inductively coupled plasma to ionize the sample. It atomizes the sample and creates atomic and small polyatomic ions, which are then detected. It is known and used for its ability to detect metals and several non-metals in liquid samples at very low concentrations. It can detect different isotopes of the same element, which makes it a versatile tool in isotopic labeling. Compared to atomic absorption spectroscopy, ICP-MS has greater speed, precision, and sensitivity. However, compared with other types of mass spectrometry, such as thermal ionization mass spectrometry and glow discharge mass spectrometry, ICP-MS introduces many interfering species: argon from the plasma, component gases of air that leak through the cone orifices, and contamination from glassware and the cones.','{\"pat_doc\": 112.0, \"pub_alt\": 1281.0, \"pub_doc\": 1431.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 16.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 5824282.0, \"pat_granted\": 28.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 10.7, \"pub_doc\": 21.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.6, \"grant_fund\": -270284.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5e6fcc73231fdd6ba6e9b9c6141547bb','4b77f13801e06ca4a3d587ee4f09a407','574dc8bedf464bfa6dcd368851dbebf9','2023-09-05 21:16:27','2023-10-29 04:06:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Transfection',12,'Transfection is the process of deliberately introducing naked or purified nucleic acids into eukaryotic cells. It may also refer to other methods and cell types, although other terms are often preferred: \"transformation\" is typically used to describe non-viral DNA transfer in bacteria and non-animal eukaryotic cells, including plant cells. In animal cells, transfection is the preferred term as transformation is also used to refer to progression to a cancerous state in these cells. Transduction is often used to describe virus-mediated gene transfer into eukaryotic cells. The word transfection is a portmanteau of trans- and infection. Genetic material, may be transfected. Transfection of animal cells typically involves opening transient pores or \"holes\" in the cell membrane to allow the uptake of material.','{\"pat_doc\": 943.0, \"pub_alt\": 6193.0, \"pub_doc\": 3470.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 75.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1577.0, \"clinic_doc\": 22.0, \"grant_fund\": 16560412.0, \"pat_granted\": 293.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 70.6, \"pub_doc\": -483.2, \"clinic_doc\": 6.1, \"grant_fund\": -22113358.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5e765cd1da8f3810667471617c4290ce','014a9a76a066045b2a9bf86aedfb7d7c','9b98ef926c70dcba53c5447a923e9d23','2023-09-08 02:30:56','2023-10-28 22:06:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Sequencing',48,'Protein sequencing is the practical process of determining the amino acid sequence of all or part of a protein or peptide. This may serve to identify the protein or characterize its post-translational modifications. Typically, partial sequencing of a protein provides sufficient information to identify it with reference to databases of protein sequences derived from the conceptual translation of genes. The two major direct methods of protein sequencing are mass spectrometry and Edman degradation using a protein sequenator. Mass spectrometry methods are now the most widely used for protein sequencing and identification but Edman degradation remains a valuable tool for characterizing a proteins N-terminus.','{\"pat_doc\": 171.0, \"pub_alt\": 424.0, \"pub_doc\": 279.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 64.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 24121937.0, \"pat_granted\": 26.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.9, \"pub_doc\": 7.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": 2760440.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5f02abc56c92c9a0c5c1fd35a96280cf','d893c2f2b521b2e83577694191a8eee4','8f14a9e350509c9aa1906cf48eaa7e87','2023-09-08 02:28:18','2023-10-28 22:11:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Water Purification System',36,'A water purification system is a device or process that removes impurities, contaminants, and other pollutants from water to make it safe for consumption. It typically involves several stages, such as sedimentation, filtration, disinfection, and sometimes reverse osmosis. These processes help to eliminate harmful bacteria, viruses, chemicals, and minerals while improving the taste and clarity of the water. Water purification systems may be utilized in households, hospitals, industries, and municipalities to ensure safe drinking water and maintain health and hygiene. The systems effectiveness depends on the quality of water being treated and the specific technology or technique used. Proper maintenance and regular monitoring are also critical to maintain its efficiency.','{\"pat_doc\": 2198.0, \"pub_alt\": 324.0, \"pub_doc\": 294.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 29.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 7094710.0, \"pat_granted\": 1279.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -46.1, \"pub_doc\": 9.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.4, \"grant_fund\": -471630.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5f0aa0df25bf7fc6c272438c27c47422','6ad6b984db7a5bd574d38199653cd677','9e26cf59e38dc5ee0cf30259ac7c92ca','2023-09-05 20:05:34','2023-10-29 04:46:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Microfluidics',36,'Microfluidics refers to a system that manipulates a small amount of fluids using small channels with sizes ten to hundreds micrometres. It is a multidisciplinary field that involves molecular analysis, biodefence, molecular biology, and microelectronics. It has practical applications in the design of systems that process low volumes of fluids to achieve multiplexing, automation, and high-throughput screening. Microfluidics emerged in the beginning of the 1980s and is used in the development of inkjet printheads, DNA chips, lab-on-a-chip technology, micro-propulsion, and micro-thermal technologies. Typically, micro means one of the following features: â€¢ Small volumes â€¢ Small size â€¢ Low energy consumption â€¢ Microdomain effects. Typically microfluidic systems transport, mix, separate, or otherwise process fluids. Various applications rely on passive fluid control using capillary forces, in the form of capillary flow modifying elements, akin to flow resistors and flow accelerators.','{\"pat_doc\": 1089.0, \"pub_alt\": 762.0, \"pub_doc\": 6350.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 949.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.0, \"grant_fund\": 439301014.0, \"pat_granted\": 344.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 28.6, \"pub_doc\": 144.5, \"clinic_doc\": 2.3, \"grant_fund\": -40950330.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5f18717988f8b3867a525a780e372e5e','4e9ebfbe4ac1ae58051339eff3ea0804','7358f1cae0370dbf5dda96c078758305','2023-09-08 11:07:58','2023-10-28 18:51:10','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Predictive Analytics',48,'Predictive analytics is a form of business analytics applying machine learning to generate a predictive model for certain business applications. As such, it encompasses a variety of statistical techniques from predictive modeling and machine learning that analyze current and historical facts to make predictions about future or otherwise unknown events. It represents a major subset of machine learning applications; in some contexts, it is synonymous with machine learning. In business, predictive models exploit patterns found in historical and transactional data to identify risks and opportunities. Models capture relationships among many factors to allow assessment of risk or potential associated with a particular set of conditions, guiding decision-making for candidate transactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 576.0, \"pub_alt\": 587.0, \"pub_doc\": 3185.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 398.0, \"clinic_alt\": 85.0, \"clinic_doc\": 31.0, \"grant_fund\": 199060398.0, \"pat_granted\": 172.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.6, \"pub_doc\": 64.5, \"clinic_doc\": 4.1, \"grant_fund\": -4049855.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5f4e7f84745915df3ac5439ef80db5bb','0bc5e22ada5efec34101dcd4f634e7a2','e77dece162a0133e50d5b2357c40719f','2023-09-05 22:55:17','2023-10-29 02:55:05','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','RNA interference',24,'RNA interference is a biological process in which RNA molecules are involved in sequence-specific suppression of gene expression by double-stranded RNA, through translational or transcriptional repression. Historically, RNAi was known by other names, including co-suppression, post-transcriptional gene silencing, and quelling. The detailed study of each of these seemingly different processes elucidated that the identity of these phenomena were all actually RNAi. Andrew Fire and Craig C. Mello shared the 2006 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their work on RNAi in the nematode worm Caenorhabditis elegans, which they published in 1998. Since the discovery of RNAi and its regulatory potentials, it has become evident that RNAi has immense potential in suppression of desired genes. RNAi is now known as precise, efficient, stable and better than antisense therapy for gene suppression.','{\"pat_doc\": 754.0, \"pub_alt\": 991.0, \"pub_doc\": 3577.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 153.0, \"clinic_alt\": 18.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 39864264.0, \"pat_granted\": 219.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.6, \"pub_doc\": -43.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": -14470471.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5f67b73f3b7a6eafccb91d3fd2a9ba8c','00f5350f80c16146d1f1e5be0746e46e','e910bc33478f3cb83e3ef258c7d92a6c','2023-09-08 02:32:48','2023-10-28 14:21:12','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel Drug Delivery','Gonadotropin-Releasing-Hormone Agonist',24,'A gonadotropin-releasing hormone agonist is a type of medication which affects gonadotropins and sex hormones. They are used for a variety of indications including in fertility medicine and to lower sex hormone levels in the treatment of hormone-sensitive cancers such as prostate cancer and breast cancer, certain gynecological disorders like heavy periods and endometriosis, high testosterone levels in women, early puberty in children, as a part of transgender hormone therapy, and to delay puberty in transgender youth among other uses. It is also used in the suppression of spontaneous ovulation as part of controlled ovarian hyperstimulation, an essential component in in IVF. GnRH agonists are given by injections into fat, as implants placed into fat, and as nasal sprays.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 21.0, \"pub_doc\": 1.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5f780f1717f2fd1fd72ae57564fb4d45','6de9464f8e368a19a89261dd71c09017','641ccd99a014845dc487b6f5a217f8ff','2023-09-08 00:19:27','2023-10-29 01:56:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Nuclear Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy',12,'Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy, most commonly known as NMR spectroscopy or magnetic resonance spectroscopy, is a spectroscopic technique to observe local magnetic fields around atomic nuclei. This spectroscopy is based on the measurement of absorption of electromagnetic radiations in the radio frequency region from roughly 4 to 900 MHz. Absorption of radio waves in the presence of magnetic field is accompanied by a special type of nuclear transition, and for this reason, such type of spectroscopy is known as Nuclear Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy. The sample is placed in a magnetic field and the NMR signal is produced by excitation of the nuclei sample with radio waves into nuclear magnetic resonance, which is detected with sensitive radio receivers. The intramolecular magnetic field around an atom in a molecule changes the resonance frequency, thus giving access to details of the electronic structure of a molecule and its individual functional groups.','{\"pat_doc\": 29.0, \"pub_alt\": 201.0, \"pub_doc\": 1149.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 24.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 14354018.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.8, \"pub_doc\": 7.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.9, \"grant_fund\": -2653145.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5f912c2b31710f00aaf451a9cc4e7978','ffe250fc447887b501aee1b30580085f','c15525a97e5927c0f087d514b050aed9','2023-09-08 09:37:37','2023-10-28 20:56:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Distillation',48,'Distillation is a process used to separate liquids with different boiling points. It involves heating a mixture of liquids to vaporize the components with lower boiling points, collecting the vapor, and then condensing it back into a liquid form. The process is widely used in industries such as petroleum refining, where crude oil is distilled to produce various fuels and other products. In addition, distillation is a common method used to purify water, create alcoholic beverages, and extract essential oils from plant materials. The efficiency of distillation depends on the difference in boiling points between the components being separated, with greater differences resulting in more effective separation.','{\"pat_doc\": 40352.0, \"pub_alt\": 734.0, \"pub_doc\": 24900.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 507.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 186452630.0, \"pat_granted\": 19370.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 349.4, \"pub_doc\": 1168.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.6, \"grant_fund\": -3503023.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5f93fe48ea93e67a46594db9f0abdfd2','c808cb9a80255cfef7c8736a22f3fd7d','586771bdb6aa5a69c62ea062df64fb52','2023-09-07 21:05:13','2023-10-28 11:55:31','Electronics','Components','Other','2D Materials',24,'2-Dimensional materials are a class of nanomaterials defined by their property of being merely one or two atoms thick. Graphene is at this time the material most commonly associated with 2-D materials.','{\"pat_doc\": 96.0, \"pub_alt\": 668.0, \"pub_doc\": 5109.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 458.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 268329701.0, \"pat_granted\": 20.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.3, \"pub_doc\": 184.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5014990.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5fbc5aa042aefaf7e2f27a9f7bf45a3d','b25c61978fbea0483d82d3d77115840d','13bed64c970494074ea74f12ff611354','2023-09-08 01:04:15','2023-10-28 15:46:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','PROTAC',12,'A proteolysis targeting chimera is a heterobifunctional molecule composed of two active domains and a linker, capable of removing specific unwanted proteins. Rather than acting as a conventional enzyme inhibitor, a PROTAC works by inducing selective intracellular proteolysis. PROTACs consist of two covalently linked protein-binding molecules: one capable of engaging an E3 ubiquitin ligase, and another that binds to a target protein meant for degradation. Recruitment of the E3 ligase to the target protein results in ubiquitination and subsequent degradation of the target protein via the proteasome. Because PROTACs need only to bind their targets with high selectivity, there are currently many efforts to retool previously ineffective inhibitor molecules as PROTACs for next-generation drugs.','{\"pat_doc\": 188.0, \"pub_alt\": 310.0, \"pub_doc\": 717.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 53.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 14451253.0, \"pat_granted\": 34.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 50.7, \"pub_doc\": 127.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.5, \"grant_fund\": -9266726.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5fd95ebad9b6305569ff66e49ec14210','19f291b8d80548406a90803fc4e33614','a3e69530e54da2bd3284f3d40c81f2e9','2023-09-08 02:13:20','2023-10-28 22:56:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Microarray',48,'A protein microarray is a high-throughput method used to track the interactions and activities of proteins, and to determine their function, and determining function on a large scale. Its main advantage lies in the fact that large numbers of proteins can be tracked in parallel. The chip consists of a support surface such as a glass slide, nitrocellulose membrane, bead, or microtitre plate, to which an array of capture proteins is bound. Probe molecules, typically labeled with a fluorescent dye, are added to the array. Any reaction between the probe and the immobilised protein emits a fluorescent signal that is read by a laser scanner. Protein microarrays are rapid, automated, economical, and highly sensitive, consuming small quantities of samples and reagents. The concept and methodology of protein microarrays was first introduced and illustrated in antibody microarrays in 1983 in a scientific publication and a series of patents.','{\"pat_doc\": 32.0, \"pub_alt\": 2002.0, \"pub_doc\": 500.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 19.0, \"clinic_alt\": 15.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 11790450.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.4, \"pub_doc\": -10.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.6, \"grant_fund\": -222800.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('5fff3db2a42aac71c0392125ca843643','2815d363c4afb5dbd132a1ef2ad77edd','6476dd0e621a6ae9d97f588345914b91','2023-09-08 02:29:21','2023-10-28 14:26:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','McCune-Albright Syndrome',24,'McCuneâ€“Albright syndrome is a complex genetic disorder affecting the bone, skin and endocrine systems. It is a mosaic disease arising from somatic activating mutations in GNAS, which encodes the alpha-subunit of the Gâ‚› heterotrimeric G protein. It was first described in 1937 by American pediatrician Donovan James McCune and American endocrinologist Fuller Albright.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 11.0, \"pub_doc\": 115.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 1089214.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": -0.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": 27877.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6028e7bf8798a04f6edc360d5511b15c','c3be1591926e87743c4c54d7028677c0','ef63c5da9830a0ea9737ee257244ed3a','2023-09-08 00:09:38','2023-10-28 16:36:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Lentivirus',48,'Lentivirus is a genus of retroviruses that cause chronic and deadly diseases characterized by long incubation periods, in humans and other mammalian species. The genus includes the human immunodeficiency virus, which causes AIDS. Lentiviruses are distributed worldwide, and are known to be hosted in apes, cows, goats, horses, cats, and sheep as well as several other mammals. Lentiviruses can integrate a significant amount of viral complementary DNA into the DNA of the host cell and can efficiently infect nondividing cells, so they are one of the most efficient methods of gene delivery. They can become endogenous, integrating their genome into the host germline genome, so that the virus is henceforth inherited by the hosts descendants.','{\"pat_doc\": 1416.0, \"pub_alt\": 2501.0, \"pub_doc\": 5732.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 248.0, \"clinic_alt\": 169.0, \"clinic_doc\": 56.0, \"grant_fund\": 106356293.0, \"pat_granted\": 410.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.0, \"pub_doc\": -93.8, \"clinic_doc\": 8.6, \"grant_fund\": -9867775.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6033a35ec157ff648523d84d3d131a7b','53dc292182499fa33b7eec431b8b30ff','a0ec7ffe04c046d0f8469b5de966ddfa','2023-09-04 18:55:37','2023-10-29 06:31:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Flow Cytometry',36,'Flow cytometry is a technique used to detect and measure physical and chemical characteristics of a population of cells or particles. In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument. The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components. Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths. Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer. Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials. Uses for flow cytometry include: â€¢ Cell counting â€¢ Cell sorting â€¢ Determining cell characteristics and function â€¢ Detecting microorganisms â€¢ Biomarker detection â€¢ Protein engineering detection â€¢ Diagnosis of health disorders such as blood cancers â€¢ Measuring genome size.','{\"pat_doc\": 1558.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 50469.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1677.0, \"clinic_alt\": 590.0, \"clinic_doc\": 766.0, \"grant_fund\": 478554038.0, \"pat_granted\": 510.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.1, \"pub_doc\": -433.8, \"clinic_doc\": 137.2, \"grant_fund\": -49967547.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('60688070c5ad6def6265eb06af11c335','0a08029fe04824e466d5980ec8cdbf8b','a0ec7ffe04c046d0f8469b5de966ddfa','2023-09-04 18:53:14','2023-10-29 06:40:05','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Flow Cytometry',24,'Flow cytometry is a technique used to detect and measure physical and chemical characteristics of a population of cells or particles. In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument. The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components. Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths. Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer. Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials. Uses for flow cytometry include: â€¢ Cell counting â€¢ Cell sorting â€¢ Determining cell characteristics and function â€¢ Detecting microorganisms â€¢ Biomarker detection â€¢ Protein engineering detection â€¢ Diagnosis of health disorders such as blood cancers â€¢ Measuring genome size.','{\"pat_doc\": 1084.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 33213.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 907.0, \"clinic_alt\": 590.0, \"clinic_doc\": 661.0, \"grant_fund\": 266196486.0, \"pat_granted\": 347.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raise