tures and characterizing the chemical structure of biomolecules such as peptides, proteins and nucleic acids. In HRMS, ions are first generated from a sample and then separated based on their mass-to-charge ratio using a mass spectrometer. The ions are then detected and their masses are measured using high resolution detectors. The high resolution of the technique enables the detection of very small mass differences, which can be used to differentiate between compounds with similar molecular weights. HRMS has revolutionized the field of analytical chemistry and has become an indispensable tool for many applications in areas such as pharmacology, environmental science, food analysis and forensics.','{\"pat_doc\": 140.0, \"pub_alt\": 1833.0, \"pub_doc\": 1592.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 114.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 37472471.0, \"pat_granted\": 49.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.4, \"pub_doc\": -17.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -1744859.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6115c0419affe3f2711c8fd00c17bf66','093421fa544b6541b1aa9445b0324876','c69cae5bf0730201ed4820a70e56cfc2','2023-09-08 09:08:02','2023-10-28 13:26:11','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Gastrointestinal Cancer',36,'Gastrointestinal cancer refers to malignant conditions of the gastrointestinal tract and accessory organs of digestion, including the esophagus, stomach, biliary system, pancreas, small intestine, large intestine, rectum and anus. The symptoms relate to the organ affected and can include obstruction, abnormal bleeding or other associated problems. The diagnosis often requires endoscopy, followed by biopsy of suspicious tissue. The treatment depends on the location of the tumor, as well as the type of cancer cell and whether it has invaded other tissues or spread elsewhere. These factors also determine the prognosis. Overall, the GI tract and the accessory organs of digestion are responsible for more cancers and more deaths from cancer than any other system in the body. There is significant geographic variation in the rates of different gastrointestinal cancers.','{\"pat_doc\": 177.0, \"pub_alt\": 1676.0, \"pub_doc\": 3290.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 162.0, \"clinic_alt\": 412.0, \"clinic_doc\": 306.0, \"grant_fund\": 41248763.0, \"pat_granted\": 31.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.9, \"pub_doc\": 83.2, \"clinic_doc\": 43.7, \"grant_fund\": -5165841.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('61da72ecd770afa23a16612a1ff939ab','a966912b70494ff7ec5379fbffffe2e6','a3d7925fcedbb9a92b698d370be59c62','2023-09-08 00:18:16','2023-10-28 11:50:31','Electronics','Needs','Customer or Market Needs','Sustainable materials',48,'Sustainable materials are those that have been sourced and manufactured in a way that minimizes environmental impact, promotes social responsibility, and provides economic benefits to communities. These materials are typically renewable, recyclable, or biodegradable, and they ensure the longevity of our natural resources. Sustainable materials can include plant-based options like bamboo, organic cotton, and linen, as well as recycled materials such as plastic bottles or reclaimed wood. Using sustainable materials in various industries is an important step toward a more sustainable future, as it reduces waste, conserves energy, and supports a circular economy. As consumers, we can make a difference by choosing products made from sustainable materials and encouraging companies to prioritize sustainability in their sourcing and manufacturing practices.','{\"pat_doc\": 82.0, \"pub_alt\": 1001.0, \"pub_doc\": 2359.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 444.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 304429154.0, \"pat_granted\": 15.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_doc\": 189.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 19728859.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6232124a9b70d53353b7e1be46b30d41','26139c734216125329350135b2f763ec','95dd984c9978fee8a3271496b2247ff4','2023-09-08 00:25:57','2023-10-29 01:41:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Sorting',48,'Cell sorting is the process through which a particular cell type is separated from others contained in a sample on the basis of its physical or biological properties, such as size, morphological parameters, viability and both extracellular and intracellular protein expression. The homogeneous cell population obtained after sorting can be used for a variety of applications including research, diagnosis, and therapy.','{\"pat_doc\": 970.0, \"pub_alt\": 822.0, \"pub_doc\": 3800.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 454.0, \"clinic_alt\": 314.0, \"clinic_doc\": 53.0, \"grant_fund\": 238009433.0, \"pat_granted\": 394.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 39.0, \"pub_doc\": -33.8, \"clinic_doc\": 7.3, \"grant_fund\": -18215497.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6251c752a62d846cf96db2189320ba1d','b3a328f05ef6249fe823d3c8f5701aaf','301cad2a0f77cdfc28e4f33b693d4618','2023-09-04 16:29:35','2023-10-29 07:16:15','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Magnetic Resonance Imaging',36,'Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) is a medical imaging technique that uses a strong magnetic field and radio waves to generate detailed images of the bodys internal structures. The process involves placing the patient in a machine that uses a powerful magnet to align the hydrogen atoms in their body. A short pulse of radio waves is then used to disrupt this alignment, causing the atoms to release energy that is detected by a scanner. The data collected is processed by a computer to produce detailed images of the target area. MRI is a non-invasive and highly precise diagnostic tool that can provide information about various conditions including tumors, infections, injuries, and abnormalities in organs and tissues. It is used in a wide range of medical applications, including neurology, cardiology, orthopedics, and oncology.','{\"pat_doc\": 8213.0, \"pub_alt\": 18424.0, \"pub_doc\": 80049.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2760.0, \"clinic_alt\": 688.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4877.0, \"grant_fund\": 1474670546.0, \"pat_granted\": 3214.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -32.4, \"pub_doc\": 760.2, \"clinic_doc\": 884.6, \"grant_fund\": -78449677.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6286b5d3bbd1d21a91aa2e1698e10b49','2ef204f64673ee0cc4682daa8faf26bb','767ea62d04e7021f7b0e5dec58a48a8d','2023-09-08 10:56:51','2023-10-28 18:56:11','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Personalized Medicine',24,'Personalized medicine, also referred to as precision medicine, is a medical model that separates people into different groupsâ€”with medical decisions, practices, interventions and/or products being tailored to the individual patient based on their predicted response or risk of disease. The terms personalized medicine, precision medicine, stratified medicine and P4 medicine are used interchangeably to describe this concept though some authors and organisations use these expressions separately to indicate particular nuances. While the tailoring of treatment to patients dates back at least to the time of Hippocrates, the term has risen in usage in recent years given the growth of new diagnostic and informatics approaches that provide understanding of the molecular basis of disease, particularly genomics. This provides a clear evidence base on which to stratify related patients.','{\"pat_doc\": 251.0, \"pub_alt\": 664.0, \"pub_doc\": 4941.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 556.0, \"clinic_alt\": 592.0, \"clinic_doc\": 260.0, \"grant_fund\": 298081883.0, \"pat_granted\": 54.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.4, \"pub_doc\": 162.7, \"clinic_doc\": 61.2, \"grant_fund\": -59753219.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6295fca2b8799cfb4572667e1953c7fc','a0128a060f00fc2880c25d9fe5536900','beb557d6f3a8f418565f2d30cdebe10e','2023-09-08 01:20:42','2023-10-28 15:21:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','natural killer T cells',48,'Natural Killer T cells are a type of lymphocytes that bridge the adaptive and innate immune systems. They have the ability to recognize and respond to a broad range of antigens presented on the surface of many different cell types, including cancer cells, and are important in regulating immune responses. These cells differentiate from the thymus and are characterized by the co-expression of T cell receptors and NK cell receptors. The interaction of these receptors allows them to respond quickly to pathogens and induces the rapid secretion of cytokines and other effector molecules. Natural Killer T cells play a vital role in controlling immune responses and have been implicated in various autoimmune diseases. Recent studies on the modulation of Natural Killer T cell responses provide new insights into the development of immunotherapeutic strategies for infectious and inflammatory diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 50.0, \"pub_alt\": 282.0, \"pub_doc\": 450.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 26.0, \"clinic_alt\": 37.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 9947231.0, \"pat_granted\": 15.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.0, \"pub_doc\": -0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.9, \"grant_fund\": -984070.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('629fd72eeaeb2362de02acca6d2753ac','bcec320c1d366012496fdc05b1162aad','3e072ff4f027f97184b7ecfb791122b7','2023-09-05 22:06:34','2023-10-28 17:26:11','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Bacteriophages',48,'A bacteriophage, also known informally as a phage, is a duplodnaviria virus that infects and replicates within bacteria and archaea. The term was derived from \"bacteria\" and the Greek Ï†Î±Î³Îµá¿–Î½, meaning \"to devour\". Bacteriophages are composed of proteins that encapsulate a DNA or RNA genome, and may have structures that are either simple or elaborate. Their genomes may encode as few as four genes and as many as hundreds of genes. Phages replicate within the bacterium following the injection of their genome into its cytoplasm. Bacteriophages are among the most common and diverse entities in the biosphere. Bacteriophages are ubiquitous viruses, found wherever bacteria exist. It is estimated there are more than 10Â³Â¹ bacteriophages on the planet, more than every other organism on Earth, including bacteria, combined.','{\"pat_doc\": 704.0, \"pub_alt\": 1165.0, \"pub_doc\": 5082.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 480.0, \"clinic_alt\": 247.0, \"clinic_doc\": 31.0, \"grant_fund\": 165226816.0, \"pat_granted\": 124.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.4, \"pub_doc\": 69.6, \"clinic_doc\": 4.7, \"grant_fund\": -11975247.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('62b246ada764bc84a538284653e28ffc','989e334c32437caa317127b884df7c33','704edc6299a6c2e6515a45403d655e47','2023-09-08 02:32:40','2023-10-28 10:55:31','Electronics','Components','Interface & Display Devices','MicroLED',48,'MicroLED is an emerging display technology that is similar to traditional LED displays, but with much smaller individual LEDs, or \"micro LEDs.\" The small size of these LEDs allows for higher resolution displays with better contrast and brightness compared to other types of displays like LCD or OLED. MicroLED is also more energy-efficient and can provide longer lifetimes than other technologies. While MicroLED displays have been around for a few years, they are still in the early stages of development with only a few consumer products in the market. However, it is expected that the technology will become more widely adopted in the coming years due to its many advantages over other display technologies.','{\"pat_doc\": 574.0, \"pub_alt\": 235.0, \"pub_doc\": 292.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 31.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 17619646.0, \"pat_granted\": 141.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 39.8, \"pub_doc\": 12.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 656986.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('62c2b41e3af92f629ee82a8f4e1a4f2b','3dc3dd5d2df2a0b127886fa91ef3f5d5','606edbb39b7dac4ec5ef367e4247cc8d','2023-09-08 09:54:26','2023-10-28 20:01:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Ion Chromatography',36,'Ion chromatography is a form of chromatography that separates ions and polar molecules based on their affinity to the ion exchanger. It works on almost any kind of charged moleculeâ€”including large proteins, small nucleotides, and amino acids. However, ion chromatography must be done in conditions that are one unit away from the isoelectric point of a protein. The two types of ion chromatography are anion-exchange and cation-exchange. Cation-exchange chromatography is used when the molecule of interest is positively charged. The molecule is positively charged because the pH for chromatography is less than the pI. In this type of chromatography, the stationary phase is negatively charged and positively charged molecules are loaded to be attracted to it. Anion-exchange chromatography is when the stationary phase is positively charged and negatively charged molecules are loaded to be attracted to it. It is often used in protein purification, water analysis, and quality control.','{\"pat_doc\": 3066.0, \"pub_alt\": 473.0, \"pub_doc\": 7465.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 202.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 11.0, \"grant_fund\": 41952034.0, \"pat_granted\": 1008.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.4, \"pub_doc\": -31.8, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": -6435445.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('632efb05c74352f489d459cbb6e51563','d9d824a70a843cb14f452ee5dfe90190','1c2b4adda3013a6c23af8f23b2fc3d3e','2023-09-08 00:45:08','2023-10-28 11:45:31','Electronics','Devices','Immersive Experience','head-mounted display',12,'A head-mounted display is a display device, worn on the head or as part of a helmet, that has a small display optic in front of one or each eye. An HMD has many uses including gaming, aviation, engineering, and medicine. Virtual reality headsets are HMDs combined with IMUs. There is also an optical head-mounted display, which is a wearable display that can reflect projected images and allows a user to see through it.','{\"pat_doc\": 2167.0, \"pub_alt\": 266.0, \"pub_doc\": 722.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 47.0, \"grant_fund\": 3254162.0, \"pat_granted\": 769.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 37.6, \"pub_doc\": 37.6, \"clinic_doc\": 11.9, \"grant_fund\": -2029094.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('638e3ab5f2250a4f48670754da0812a4','7f22a30b9d31980762db19938046f3e9','5762d74cf97f0e57d03def69845fe3e1','2023-09-08 02:43:41','2023-10-28 21:46:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Enzyme Technology',36,'Enzyme Technology involves the use of enzymes to carry out specific chemical reactions, useful in various industries such as food, pharmaceuticals, and the environment. Enzymes are biocatalysts that facilitate chemical reactions without being consumed in the process. They are highly specific and can work under mild conditions, making them eco-friendly and efficient. Enzyme Technology includes the optimization of enzyme-catalyzed reactions, engineering of new enzymes, and production of enzymes through fermentation processes. The applications of enzyme technology are vast, including the production of biofuels, detergents, food additives, and medications. The use of enzyme technology can also lead to more sustainable processes, reduced waste, and decreased environmental impact in industries.','{\"pat_doc\": 91.0, \"pub_alt\": 97.0, \"pub_doc\": 135.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 18910662.0, \"pat_granted\": 27.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -7.1, \"pub_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -310772.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('63f9e8eb4490244e6e7a03fffa0b1f77','dd3b10037cd066e53410e9747f800fec','9bd82f68388cbaa629adeec1747d02c9','2023-09-04 19:22:50','2023-10-28 12:55:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','5g',12,'5G refers to the fifth generation of mobile networks and is the successor to 4G. It represents a significant improvement in terms of speed, latency, and capacity, enabling faster download and upload speeds, quicker response times, and the ability to connect more devices to the network simultaneously. The new network technology uses higher frequency radio waves and advanced antenna technology to transmit and receive data more efficiently. The increased bandwidth of 5G networks will enhance the capabilities of emerging technologies such as virtual and augmented reality, driverless vehicles, and Internet of Things (IoT) devices. The deployment of 5G networks is currently underway worldwide, and it is expected to have a significant impact on the way we communicate and access information in the years to come.','{\"pat_doc\": 19145.0, \"pub_alt\": 866.0, \"pub_doc\": 16364.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 476.0, \"clinic_alt\": 59.0, \"clinic_doc\": 514.0, \"grant_fund\": 669269678.0, \"pat_granted\": 7100.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1603.5, \"pub_doc\": 859.7, \"clinic_doc\": 107.3, \"grant_fund\": -2206973786.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('643ea3efea1b83fbca4d1950bec0c232','adc255a75abbc6dc9e8c5d454e86dad3','da6fc92b2753b0e9a72b21f2c514a42d','2023-09-08 00:04:14','2023-10-29 02:06:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Smart material',48,'Smart materials, also called intelligent or responsive materials, are designed materials that have one or more properties that can be significantly changed in a controlled fashion by external stimuli, such as stress, moisture, electric or magnetic fields, light, temperature, pH, or chemical compounds. Smart materials are the basis of many applications, including sensors and actuators, or artificial muscles, particularly as electroactive polymers. Terms used to describe smart materials include shape memory material and shape memory technology.','{\"pat_doc\": 193.0, \"pub_alt\": 490.0, \"pub_doc\": 11613.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 399.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 196972386.0, \"pat_granted\": 72.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -2.5, \"pub_doc\": 844.3, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -20872158.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('643f0ecbdec35e534ebc8345a795801a','ee1ceea70d26f9efca309b5f07a6e479','77e5f6785bd7c9d4f3610b4ac830ad4e','2023-09-08 00:22:21','2023-10-29 01:51:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Electroporation',36,'Electroporation, or electropermeabilization, is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing chemicals, drugs, electrode arrays or DNA to be introduced into the cell. In microbiology, the process of electroporation is often used to transform bacteria, yeast, or plant protoplasts by introducing new coding DNA. If bacteria and plasmids are mixed together, the plasmids can be transferred into the bacteria after electroporation, though depending on what is being transferred, cell-penetrating peptides or CellSqueeze could also be used. Electroporation works by passing thousands of volts across suspended cells in an electroporation cuvette. Afterwards, the cells have to be handled carefully until they have had a chance to divide, producing new cells that contain reproduced plasmids.','{\"pat_doc\": 1916.0, \"pub_alt\": 1984.0, \"pub_doc\": 2827.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 218.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1151.0, \"clinic_doc\": 164.0, \"grant_fund\": 80965440.0, \"pat_granted\": 534.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 72.4, \"pub_doc\": -22.4, \"clinic_doc\": 21.4, \"grant_fund\": -13946036.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('647c37b27f351157137ab00e1fc42f88','8445e498b5c8e24b28f8fe85d68e76af','33b4678f6b096b9a11757bc96a56f980','2023-09-08 01:16:53','2023-10-29 00:21:18','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Directed Evolution',12,'Directed evolution is a method used in protein engineering that mimics the process of natural selection to steer proteins or nucleic acids toward a user-defined goal. It consists of subjecting a gene to iterative rounds of mutagenesis, selection and amplification. It can be performed in vivo, or in vitro. Directed evolution is used both for protein engineering as an alternative to rationally designing modified proteins, as well as for experimental evolution studies of fundamental evolutionary principles in a controlled, laboratory environment.','{\"pat_doc\": 178.0, \"pub_alt\": 278.0, \"pub_doc\": 458.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 68.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 34803967.0, \"pat_granted\": 50.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 25.3, \"pub_doc\": 7.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -10443235.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('648889908542f85cc240378fef001491','917192d39f4afc517e0a5df9df580afd','e5dc1ab9b95fd144580ba449bdb1f286','2023-09-05 20:46:53','2023-10-29 04:25:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','CRISPR-Cas9',36,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 741.0, \"pub_alt\": 3609.0, \"pub_doc\": 5476.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 814.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 21.0, \"grant_fund\": 341525102.0, \"pat_granted\": 209.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.6, \"pub_doc\": 115.9, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -29971557.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('648d995f73748671b03a2011139abbf4','51aee0cb27f70c84f894c07b0faada65','05f0a405c035c7fc807679b69158e068','2023-09-07 23:36:05','2023-10-28 17:11:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy',48,'Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is a condition in which muscle tissues of the heart become thickened without an obvious cause. The parts of the heart most commonly affected are the interventricular septum and the ventricles. This results in the heart being less able to pump blood effectively and also may cause electrical conduction problems. People who have HCM may have a range of symptoms. People may be asymptomatic, or may have fatigue, leg swelling, and shortness of breath. It may also result in chest pain or fainting. Symptoms may be worse when the person is dehydrated. Complications may include heart failure, an irregular heartbeat, and sudden cardiac death. HCM is most commonly inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern. It is often due to mutations in certain genes involved with making heart muscle proteins. Other inherited causes of left ventricular hypertrophy may include Fabry disease, Friedreichs ataxia, and certain medications such as tacrolimus.','{\"pat_doc\": 298.0, \"pub_alt\": 668.0, \"pub_doc\": 5938.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 198.0, \"clinic_alt\": 126.0, \"clinic_doc\": 179.0, \"grant_fund\": 70964268.0, \"pat_granted\": 56.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.4, \"pub_doc\": 133.8, \"clinic_doc\": 28.7, \"grant_fund\": -3954781.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('649e610e92b6bf62438570c020ecffda','f82670ab57400d3e832f9efb4a5573a4','2e3f377d891e03c5b7a4ddf257a19dc5','2023-09-08 01:35:27','2023-10-28 15:11:17','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','DNA origami',36,'DNA origami is the nanoscale folding of DNA to create arbitrary two- and three-dimensional shapes at the nanoscale. The specificity of the interactions between complementary base pairs make DNA a useful construction material, through design of its base sequences. DNA is a well-understood material that is suitable for creating scaffolds that hold other molecules in place or to create structures all on its own. DNA origami was the cover story of Nature on March 16, 2006. Since then, DNA origami has progressed past an art form and has found a number of applications from drug delivery systems to uses as circuitry in plasmonic devices; however, most commercial applications remain in a concept or testing phase.','{\"pat_doc\": 102.0, \"pub_alt\": 581.0, \"pub_doc\": 924.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 120.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 116225689.0, \"pat_granted\": 25.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.1, \"pub_doc\": 26.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1724661.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('64b2525d355e4416ba216e111a64b925','c24a789d6d92253253ff9f90dc646a7a','774a346d62790e44d654b1f21ecba973','2023-09-07 23:48:38','2023-10-29 02:26:21','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Single-Cell Analysis',12,'In the field of cellular biology, single-cell analysis is the study of genomics, transcriptomics, proteomics, metabolomics and cellâ€“cell interactions at the single cell level. The concept of single-cell analysis originated in the 1970s. Before the discovery of heterogeneity, single-cell analysis mainly referred to the analysis or manipulation of an individual cell in a bulk population of cells at a particular condition using optical or electronic microscope. To date, due to the heterogeneity seen in both eukaryotic and prokaryotic cell populations, analyzing a single cell makes it possible to discover mechanisms not seen when studying a bulk population of cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 39.0, \"pub_alt\": 500.0, \"pub_doc\": 784.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 38.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 17292804.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.4, \"pub_doc\": 102.1, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": -19310396.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('64d3df3e14476f67b222b63037fe02e3','123fff890be892fb84e8f950aecc8f54','e2436e9e1daec5dad6800e18965c31a2','2023-09-08 00:59:51','2023-10-28 16:01:19','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Monoclonal antibodies','Nanobodies',24,'Nanobodies are small antibody fragments with unique properties that offer promising potential for therapeutic and diagnostic applications. These fragments are derived from the immune system of camelids, such as camels and llamas, and consist of a single immunoglobulin domain that has a high affinity and specificity for its target. Nanobodies are much smaller and more stable than traditional antibodies, which allows them to penetrate deeper into tissues and reach difficult-to-access locations. Additionally, their small size and simplicity make it easier and cheaper to produce them at a large scale. Due to these advantages, nanobodies are being investigated for a variety of uses, including cancer therapy, imaging, and viral infections.','{\"pat_doc\": 303.0, \"pub_alt\": 780.0, \"pub_doc\": 895.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 122.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 50944489.0, \"pat_granted\": 61.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 40.8, \"pub_doc\": 70.3, \"clinic_doc\": 1.3, \"grant_fund\": -15354732.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('66145dcbba5895edcd8f03d73bbf5220','2b6a132222106ddec0310c5473271c19','d16e559190b993e5f50fdc62d46eec9a','2023-09-08 09:58:57','2023-10-28 19:36:10','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Modification',36,'mRNA modification is a process that occurs after transcription but before translation. It refers to the chemical modifications of messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules in order to regulate their stability, localization, and translation efficiency. The most common type of mRNA modification is the addition of a 5â€™ cap, a modified guanine nucleotide, to the 5â€™ end of the mRNA molecule. This cap protects the mRNA from degradation and facilitates its translation. Another important mRNA modification is the addition of a poly(A) tail, a string of adenine nucleotides, to the 3â€™ end of the mRNA molecule. This tail also stabilizes the mRNA and enhances its translation. Other types of mRNA modifications include splicing, editing, and methylation, which can affect the sequence, structure, and function of the mRNA molecule. mRNA modification plays a critical role in gene expression regulation and is essential for cellular processes such as development, differentiation, and adaptation to environmental changes.','{\"pat_doc\": 7.0, \"pub_alt\": 182.0, \"pub_doc\": 416.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 36.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 22687650.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 16.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -6725984.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('662550ebc134e06f4ed7aefc5a216fd5','665bbf50f9c0e74f93301c0a8c98acec','f7f9ce80272ab55a46f45831f319f87c','2023-09-08 10:01:20','2023-10-28 19:26:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Turbidimetry',24,'Turbidimetry is the process of measuring the loss of intensity of transmitted light due to the scattering effect of particles suspended in it. Light is passed through a filter creating a light of known wavelength which is then passed through a cuvette containing a solution. A photoelectric cell collects the light which passes through the cuvette. A measurement is then given for the amount of absorbed light. Turbidimetry can be used in biology to find the number of cells in a solution. Turbidity-is an expression of optical look of a solution caused by radiation to the scattered and absorbed wavelength. Scattering of light is elastic so both incident and scattered radiation have same wavelength. A turbidometer measures the amount of radiation that passes through a fluid in forward direction,analogous to absorption spectrphotoometry.','{\"pat_doc\": 178.0, \"pub_alt\": 52.0, \"pub_doc\": 343.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 149735.0, \"pat_granted\": 62.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -10.5, \"pub_doc\": -8.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": -47175.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6634877b9bd3ff97683b30166a07c131','b052bba7b488d052b6c520140b9a95f7','0f0001c9173ff0ef27a841bf7334c0a3','2023-09-07 23:32:11','2023-10-29 02:41:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Synthetic biology',48,'Synthetic biology is a multidisciplinary field of science that focuses on living systems and organisms, and it applies engineering principles to develop new biological parts, devices, and systems or to redesign existing systems found in nature. It is a branch of science that encompasses a broad range of methodologies from various disciplines, such as biotechnology, biomaterials, material science/engineering, genetic engineering, molecular biology, molecular engineering, systems biology, membrane science, biophysics, chemical and biological engineering, electrical and computer engineering, control engineering and evolutionary biology. It includes designing and constructing biological modules, biological systems, and biological machines or, re-design of existing biological systems for useful purposes. Additionally, it is the branch of science that focuses on the new abilities of engineering into existing organisms to redesign them for useful purposes.','{\"pat_doc\": 705.0, \"pub_alt\": 1696.0, \"pub_doc\": 6196.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1718.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 1121607807.0, \"pat_granted\": 173.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 62.9, \"pub_doc\": 64.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -38172745.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6648167fa596b3e409f33e39e9a419ee','e44792deacd6cf8232ea590a59b65829','ebccb11a63ab2a40e9dc38470854a837','2023-09-05 18:41:05','2023-10-29 05:46:09','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Differentiation',48,'Mechanisms of Development is a peer-reviewed scientific journal covering all aspects of developmental biology. It is the official journal of the International Society of Developmental Biologists and is published by Elsevier. The journal was established in 1972 as Cell Differentiation and was renamed Cell Differentiation and Development in 1988. It acquired its current name in December 1990. The editor-in-chief is D. Wilkinson. A separate section of the journal, Gene Expression Patterns, covers research on cloning and gene expression. In 2020 the journal became Cells & Development with the subtitle: Cell and Developmental Biology and their Quantitative Approaches.','{\"pat_doc\": 1570.0, \"pub_alt\": 1940.0, \"pub_doc\": 16212.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2063.0, \"clinic_alt\": 437.0, \"clinic_doc\": 154.0, \"grant_fund\": 796800511.0, \"pat_granted\": 484.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.6, \"pub_doc\": 33.4, \"clinic_doc\": 21.2, \"grant_fund\": -58438151.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('664e55cd9aae60d53fccc409295b7e07','241acd5defc6bb6b835e678e78fce56c','35f85abe435e1302c602406f943817c0','2023-09-08 02:20:19','2023-10-28 14:41:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Polyplexes',48,'Polyplexes are a class of nanocarriers used in gene therapy that enable delivery of therapeutic nucleic acids such as plasmids, siRNAs, and miRNAs. Their structure consists of a cationic polymer, usually polyethyleneimine (PEI), complexed with negatively charged nucleic acids to form a stable complex. The advantage of polyplexes is their ability to protect the nucleic acids from degradation and facilitate their passage into cells, ultimately leading to efficient gene expression. Additionally, the surface charge and size of polyplexes can be modified, allowing for targeted delivery and reduced toxicity. Polyplexes have shown great promise in preclinical studies, but their clinical translation is still limited due to challenges such as immune response and optimization of delivery parameters. Nonetheless, they continue to be an exciting field of study with potential for a variety of gene therapy applications.','{\"pat_doc\": 90.0, \"pub_alt\": 1037.0, \"pub_doc\": 468.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 14.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5757191.0, \"pat_granted\": 10.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 7.8, \"pub_doc\": 1.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -353261.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('669dada5b42f9e239bb8e7df2be57c54','33e3b46112ca032f374d6e6e96ae9ab3','96ff1b7975967b788c2beb91534beb0f','2023-09-05 20:50:48','2023-10-28 17:56:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Exosomes',36,'Exosomes are small membrane vesicles, typically with a diameter of 30-150 nm, that are secreted by many types of mammalian cells and are found in a variety of body fluids such as blood, urine, and breast milk. They are thought to play a role in intercellular communication and in some cases can transfer proteins, lipids, and genetic material between cells. Exosomes originate from the endosomal compartment of the cell and are formed by the inward budding of the membrane to create intraluminal vesicles. Once formed, the exosomes are released from the cell through fusion with the plasma membrane or phagocytosis by other cells. The content of exosomes can vary depending on the cell type and physiological conditions, and there is growing interest in their use as biomarkers for disease diagnosis and as potential therapeutic agents.','{\"pat_doc\": 4830.0, \"pub_alt\": 18945.0, \"pub_doc\": 13658.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 925.0, \"clinic_alt\": 219.0, \"clinic_doc\": 327.0, \"grant_fund\": 259144348.0, \"pat_granted\": 1135.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 265.2, \"pub_doc\": 279.4, \"clinic_doc\": 55.8, \"grant_fund\": -46753820.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('66a4b1f50e6b8ed3d0930f0f4d82d365','3cf46267ec47fde029e918d250b335a1','c26c7529dcbe3665be368505da21babe','2023-09-08 02:53:34','2023-10-28 13:56:10','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Nanobots',36,'Nanoid robotics, or for short, nanorobotics or nanobotics, is an emerging technology field creating machines or robots whose components are at or near the scale of a nanometer. More specifically, nanorobotics refers to the nanotechnology engineering discipline of designing and building nanorobots with devices ranging in size from 0.1 to 10 micrometres and constructed of nanoscale or molecular components. The terms nanobot, nanoid, nanite, nanomachine and nanomite have also been used to describe such devices currently under research and development. Nanomachines are largely in the research and development phase, but some primitive molecular machines and nanomotors have been tested. An example is a sensor having a switch approximately 1.5 nanometers across, able to count specific molecules in the chemical sample. The first useful applications of nanomachines may be in nanomedicine. For example, biological machines could be used to identify and destroy cancer cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 9.0, \"pub_alt\": 265.0, \"pub_doc\": 117.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1714584.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 11.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -619816.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('66b7b2c37a4cb0950ff89abd832fe5e0','8b34441cb6296c1404d0a6501ee553ff','eecaf00b18ce2e327917c5c42d883f43','2023-09-05 18:42:49','2023-10-29 05:41:10','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Raman Spectroscopy',24,'Raman spectroscopy is a spectroscopic technique typically used to determine vibrational modes of molecules, although rotational and other low-frequency modes of systems may also be observed. Raman spectroscopy is commonly used in chemistry to provide a structural fingerprint by which molecules can be identified. Raman spectroscopy relies upon inelastic scattering of photons, known as Raman scattering. A source of monochromatic light, usually from a laser in the visible, near infrared, or near ultraviolet range is used, although X-rays can also be used. The laser light interacts with molecular vibrations, phonons or other excitations in the system, resulting in the energy of the laser photons being shifted up or down. The shift in energy gives information about the vibrational modes in the system. Infrared spectroscopy typically yields similar yet complementary information. Typically, a sample is illuminated with a laser beam.','{\"pat_doc\": 1283.0, \"pub_alt\": 1807.0, \"pub_doc\": 19236.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 485.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 63.0, \"grant_fund\": 135108467.0, \"pat_granted\": 347.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -8.3, \"pub_doc\": 257.9, \"clinic_doc\": 14.3, \"grant_fund\": -11262983.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('66cebe7d570079195e05e22275289382','e1fcd3b18c69467f559b50097886167b','a2b94a39823e51d1e7bb659a1415d3c3','2023-09-08 00:31:20','2023-10-29 01:26:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Biocatalysis',12,'Biocatalysis refers to the use of living systems or their parts to speed up chemical reactions. In biocatalytic processes, natural catalysts, such as enzymes, perform chemical transformations on organic compounds. Both enzymes that have been more or less isolated and enzymes still residing inside living cells are employed for this task. Modern biotechnology, specifically directed evolution, has made the production of modified or non-natural enzymes possible. This has enabled the development of enzymes that can catalyze novel small molecule transformations that may be difficult or impossible using classical synthetic organic chemistry. Utilizing natural or modified enzymes to perform organic synthesis is termed chemoenzymatic synthesis; the reactions performed by the enzyme are classified as chemoenzymatic reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 213.0, \"pub_alt\": 234.0, \"pub_doc\": 707.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 64.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 46363990.0, \"pat_granted\": 70.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 32.8, \"pub_doc\": 44.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 8603575.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('66d4c80082d6e788d38201dd0262d5fb','6272d8c4fefc516af912e39ce608f48b','f5961ebdecc3630bd05559901b09f90f','2023-09-08 01:50:58','2023-10-28 15:01:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Gene therapies (Non-viral)','Ribozyme',12,'Ribozymes are RNA molecules that have the ability to catalyze specific biochemical reactions, including RNA splicing in gene expression, similar to the action of protein enzymes. The 1982 discovery of ribozymes demonstrated that RNA can be both genetic material and a biological catalyst, and contributed to the RNA world hypothesis, which suggests that RNA may have been important in the evolution of prebiotic self-replicating systems. The most common activities of natural or in vitro evolved ribozymes are the cleavage of RNA and DNA and peptide bond formation. For example, the smallest ribozyme known can aminoacylate a GCCU-3 sequence in the presence of PheAMP. Within the ribosome, ribozymes function as part of the large subunit ribosomal RNA to link amino acids during protein synthesis. They also participate in a variety of RNA processing reactions, including RNA splicing, viral replication, and transfer RNA biosynthesis.','{\"pat_doc\": 126.0, \"pub_alt\": 148.0, \"pub_doc\": 213.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 11.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 3191516.0, \"pat_granted\": 35.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 8.3, \"pub_doc\": -0.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.2, \"grant_fund\": -2009401.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('66e1702c8ec11f312c7d71205f35e13e','4e9ebfbe4ac1ae58051339eff3ea0804','7358f1cae0370dbf5dda96c078758305','2023-09-08 11:07:58','2023-10-28 18:51:10','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Predictive Analytics',36,'Predictive analytics is a form of business analytics applying machine learning to generate a predictive model for certain business applications. As such, it encompasses a variety of statistical techniques from predictive modeling and machine learning that analyze current and historical facts to make predictions about future or otherwise unknown events. It represents a major subset of machine learning applications; in some contexts, it is synonymous with machine learning. In business, predictive models exploit patterns found in historical and transactional data to identify risks and opportunities. Models capture relationships among many factors to allow assessment of risk or potential associated with a particular set of conditions, guiding decision-making for candidate transactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 456.0, \"pub_alt\": 587.0, \"pub_doc\": 2502.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 266.0, \"clinic_alt\": 23.0, \"clinic_doc\": 27.0, \"grant_fund\": 142746190.0, \"pat_granted\": 134.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.6, \"pub_doc\": 64.5, \"clinic_doc\": 4.1, \"grant_fund\": -4049855.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('66edac168a70c1f547894413f15c1d88','7e6303a93deff34a836da02c9ec9b121','b8d8729029b072a6d46a6e6415f7d63a','2023-09-20 19:21:20','2023-10-28 14:51:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Addisons Disease',24,'Addisons disease, also known as primary adrenal insufficiency, is a rare long-term endocrine disorder characterized by inadequate production of the steroid hormones cortisol and aldosterone by the two outer layers of the cells of the adrenal glands, causing adrenal insufficiency. Symptoms generally come on slowly and insidiously and may include abdominal pain and gastrointestinal abnormalities, weakness, and weight loss. Darkening of the skin in certain areas may also occur. Under certain circumstances, an adrenal crisis may occur with low blood pressure, vomiting, lower back pain, and loss of consciousness. Mood changes may also occur. Rapid onset of symptoms indicates acute adrenal failure, which is a clinical emergency. An adrenal crisis can be triggered by stress, such as from an injury, surgery, or infection. Addisons disease arises from problems with the adrenal gland such that not enough of the steroid hormone cortisol and possibly aldosterone are produced.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 3.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('670f4ae3821fbe403c6f121ccfa42d3c','f6196df8d7ae9a4d7f729e93364e0bd8','f612c4461ae2b2296d600f221ca9683b','2023-09-08 00:23:57','2023-10-29 01:46:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Cryo-electron microscopy',12,'Cryo-electron microscopy (cryo-EM) is an imaging technique used to determine the three-dimensional structures of biological macromolecules at near-atomic resolution. It involves the rapid freezing of a sample and the use of an electron microscope to capture images of the frozen sample from multiple angles. These images are then combined and analyzed computationally to generate a high-resolution 3D model of the sample. Cryo-EM has revolutionized the field of structural biology, allowing researchers to study previously inaccessible proteins and complexes and providing new insights into biological processes such as protein folding, virus-host interactions, and drug binding. Its ability to work with relatively small samples, including single molecules, and its potential for automated imaging make cryo-EM a powerful tool for drug discovery and structural biology research.','{\"pat_doc\": 19.0, \"pub_alt\": 1845.0, \"pub_doc\": 1017.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 127.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 74938649.0, \"pat_granted\": 5.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_doc\": 58.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -19994930.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6769c99f4cbaa6d5633d375f5d4f3c6f','70acbc1819a41cd643bd80877d3bc5a4','79f0607dd327b272b64831fef13948f0','2023-09-08 09:12:08','2023-10-28 13:11:13','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Oncogenic signalling',12,'Oncogenic signaling refers to the changes that occur within cells that lead to uncontrolled cell growth and proliferation, ultimately resulting in cancer. These changes are typically driven by mutations that occur in genes that are involved in regulating cell growth and division. When these mutations occur, the affected gene becomes altered in a way that enhances its ability to promote cell growth and proliferation. This can occur through various mechanisms, including the activation of signaling pathways that regulate cell growth and division, or the alteration of the proteins that control the cell cycle. Ultimately, oncogenic signaling is a complex and multifaceted phenomenon that involves multiple genetic and biochemical factors working together to promote the growth and spread of cancer cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 410.0, \"pub_doc\": 37.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 415828.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 2.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 250205.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('67751cc1d69a1197f4d1fa0c9b8603c7','2815d363c4afb5dbd132a1ef2ad77edd','6476dd0e621a6ae9d97f588345914b91','2023-09-08 02:29:21','2023-10-28 14:26:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','McCune-Albright Syndrome',36,'McCuneâ€“Albright syndrome is a complex genetic disorder affecting the bone, skin and endocrine systems. It is a mosaic disease arising from somatic activating mutations in GNAS, which encodes the alpha-subunit of the Gâ‚› heterotrimeric G protein. It was first described in 1937 by American pediatrician Donovan James McCune and American endocrinologist Fuller Albright.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 70.0, \"pub_doc\": 159.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 3755507.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": -0.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": 27877.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('677cfdb614f3013ae7a8ab28cbd39b00','164a36aa72f0d1ad31bba2a4ae14dad1','52e358453865c2f781ecea69256e441f','2023-09-08 02:22:34','2023-10-28 22:26:12','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Spectral Database',48,'A spectral database is a repository of spectral data that can be used for identification and characterization of chemical compounds. Spectral data includes information about the properties of light interacting with a sample, such as absorption, emission, and scattering. By comparing the spectral data of an unknown sample to that in a spectral database, researchers can identify the likely chemical composition of the sample. Spectral databases are crucial for many scientific fields, including chemistry, biology, and materials science. They are constantly being updated with new data and have become essential tools in modern research.','{\"pat_doc\": 101.0, \"pub_alt\": 192.0, \"pub_doc\": 369.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 16630019.0, \"pat_granted\": 31.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.1, \"pub_doc\": 3.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -1497510.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('67c56dce2713781660b76203e698bbb0','b2deca51e58703d27137669b972e2778','782fafb2d5b336b1996d7a1bfb56f465','2023-09-08 09:53:17','2023-10-28 20:06:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Mass spectrometry imaging',24,'Mass spectrometry imaging is a technique used in mass spectrometry to visualize the spatial distribution of molecules, as biomarkers, metabolites, peptides or proteins by their molecular masses. After collecting a mass spectrum at one spot, the sample is moved to reach another region, and so on, until the entire sample is scanned. By choosing a peak in the resulting spectra that corresponds to the compound of interest, the MS data is used to map its distribution across the sample. This results in pictures of the spatially resolved distribution of a compound pixel by pixel. Each data set contains a veritable gallery of pictures because any peak in each spectrum can be spatially mapped. Despite the fact that MSI has been generally considered a qualitative method, the signal generated by this technique is proportional to the relative abundance of the analyte. Therefore, quantification is possible, when its challenges are overcome.','{\"pat_doc\": 85.0, \"pub_alt\": 481.0, \"pub_doc\": 999.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 81.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 32121781.0, \"pat_granted\": 26.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 30.5, \"clinic_doc\": -0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2225201.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('67f7e22bf51c1841f612bd239b1657f4','8b3e02763472ad9cc815cfa5df7888cc','451ebb4679c1ff141207f279192eb1c8','2023-09-08 02:50:01','2023-10-28 21:26:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Bio-inspired material',24,'Bio-inspired materials refer to a class of materials inspired by natural designs and architectures found in living systems. These materials incorporate features such as self-assembly, hierarchical structure, and dynamic responsiveness. The idea behind bio-inspired materials is to take inspiration from nature to create advanced materials that have unique and valuable properties not found in conventional materials. Examples of such materials include self-healing polymers, super-strong spider silk-mimicking fibers, and high-performance ceramics based on the structure of seashells. Bio-inspired materials have the potential to lead to the development of new technologies and applications in fields such as medicine, construction, and robotics.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 189.0, \"pub_doc\": 101.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 25.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 31040517.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 4.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4564736.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('686db74e9147bef1fa26919d88c33a51','94a11929f6fb7d9d93e190ab5230cb23','2874f833fd4f69190438aa7cb5f052b5','2023-09-05 20:19:29','2023-10-29 04:41:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Blockchain technology',36,'Blockchain technology is a distributed ledger technology that allows for secure, transparent and irreversible peer-to-peer transactions without the need for intermediaries. It is based on a decentralized network of nodes that validate transactions and add them to the blockchain, a public ledger of all transactions. Blockchain technology is essentially a digital ledger that records and stores data in a secure and transparent way. This makes it useful for a variety of applications, such as cryptocurrency, supply chain management, voting systems, and more. The technologys key features include decentralization, transparency, immutability, and security. Overall, blockchain technology has the potential to revolutionize multiple industries and enable new business models.','{\"pat_doc\": 3354.0, \"pub_alt\": 1120.0, \"pub_doc\": 16472.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 205.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 100859919.0, \"pat_granted\": 868.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 306.0, \"pub_doc\": 1055.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -4560710.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6964cf8a1b3640e7077fff7623f811f6','7894dc5316736cccc7857ade68b00def','5428f4cb6631add28ed91160f184e3d2','2023-09-04 18:49:56','2023-10-29 06:50:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Polymerase Chain Reaction',12,'The polymerase chain reaction is a method widely used to make millions to billions of copies of a specific DNA sample rapidly, allowing scientists amplify a very small sample of DNA sufficiently to enable detailed study. PCR was invented in 1983 by American biochemist Kary Mullis at Cetus Corporation; Mullis and biochemist Michael Smith, who had developed other essential ways of manipulating DNA, were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1993. PCR is fundamental to many of the procedures used in genetic testing and research, including analysis of ancient samples of DNA and identification of infectious agents. Using PCR, copies of very small amounts of DNA sequences are exponentially amplified in a series of cycles of temperature changes. PCR is now a common and often indispensable technique used in medical laboratory research for a broad variety of applications including biomedical research and criminal forensics. The majority of PCR methods rely on thermal cycling.','{\"pat_doc\": 969.0, \"pub_alt\": 6193.0, \"pub_doc\": 16202.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 67.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1692.0, \"clinic_doc\": 488.0, \"grant_fund\": 13156566.0, \"pat_granted\": 304.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 25.6, \"pub_doc\": -1022.4, \"clinic_doc\": 80.3, \"grant_fund\": -12358489.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('69669ec91683f81392d40af010f020af','68e5caa32ed7e67484689ef37c744a39','8d40644b6dad0c0cd4481b73c097825b','2023-09-05 20:56:55','2023-10-29 04:16:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Bioreactor',48,'A bioreactor refers to any manufactured device or system that supports a biologically active environment. In one case, a bioreactor is a vessel in which a chemical process is carried out which involves organisms or biochemically active substances derived from such organisms. This process can either be aerobic or anaerobic. These bioreactors are commonly cylindrical, ranging in size from litres to cubic metres, and are often made of stainless steel. It may also refer to a device or system designed to grow cells or tissues in the context of cell culture. These devices are being developed for use in tissue engineering or biochemical/bioprocess engineering. On the basis of mode of operation, a bioreactor may be classified as batch, fed batch or continuous. An example of a continuous bioreactor is the chemostat. Organisms or biochemically active substances growing in bioreactors may be submerged in liquid medium or may be anchored to the surface of a solid medium.','{\"pat_doc\": 11436.0, \"pub_alt\": 4795.0, \"pub_doc\": 15730.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1273.0, \"clinic_alt\": 24.0, \"clinic_doc\": 11.0, \"grant_fund\": 559946971.0, \"pat_granted\": 4643.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 47.6, \"pub_doc\": 42.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -17747789.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6987502c3ba6709b79ee986fd8ab033e','26139c734216125329350135b2f763ec','95dd984c9978fee8a3271496b2247ff4','2023-09-08 00:25:57','2023-10-29 01:41:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Sorting',36,'Cell sorting is the process through which a particular cell type is separated from others contained in a sample on the basis of its physical or biological properties, such as size, morphological parameters, viability and both extracellular and intracellular protein expression. The homogeneous cell population obtained after sorting can be used for a variety of applications including research, diagnosis, and therapy.','{\"pat_doc\": 774.0, \"pub_alt\": 822.0, \"pub_doc\": 2779.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 306.0, \"clinic_alt\": 314.0, \"clinic_doc\": 46.0, \"grant_fund\": 149633751.0, \"pat_granted\": 317.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 39.0, \"pub_doc\": -33.8, \"clinic_doc\": 7.3, \"grant_fund\": -18215497.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('69cc75fadfa7dc54f414916214edc76a','e1e4825f9e69d0bff75f7b5f1728fa6c','de90a1c4d8531674dd30ee9b71846822','2023-09-08 02:18:06','2023-10-28 22:36:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Aseptic Technique',24,'Aseptic techniques are procedures followed by individual working in a area which is highly controlled with respect to its level of microbial count. The level of microbial count is controlled to eliminate their contamination in product, while processing aseptically in the working place like laminar air flow bench, unidirectional flow bench mainly used in pharmaceutical manufacturing of sterile drug products, and microbial testing labs. Aseptic techniques include the sterilization method of microbiological culture handling wire loops, which are required to hold over flame on a gas burner, before use in order to sterilize it. The growing procedures are adapted inside a critical area while handling sterile products or microbial culture. The sequential movement of material in and out of the critical area, sequential man movement and their dexterity of handling of the sterile product and the intervention methods altogether are called aseptic techniques.','{\"pat_doc\": 117.0, \"pub_alt\": 98.0, \"pub_doc\": 252.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 63.0, \"grant_fund\": 745435.0, \"pat_granted\": 100.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -10.9, \"pub_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.6, \"grant_fund\": 112023.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('69d7d50f8287efddad32789c4ebedb14','8f5e65940c2b32c65f99c25d9fea77ca','e9ee3da8c5950eddf30d7e6a8d175388','2023-09-08 00:36:35','2023-10-29 01:20:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Engineering',36,'Protein engineering is the process of developing useful or valuable proteins through the design and production of unnatural polypeptides, often by altering amino acid sequences found in nature. It is a young discipline, with much research taking place into the understanding of protein folding and recognition for protein design principles. It has been used to improve the function of many enzymes for industrial catalysis. It is also a product and services market, with an estimated value of $168 billion by 2017. There are two general strategies for protein engineering: rational protein design and directed evolution. These methods are not mutually exclusive; researchers will often apply both. In the future, more detailed knowledge of protein structure and function, and advances in high-throughput screening, may greatly expand the abilities of protein engineering.','{\"pat_doc\": 429.0, \"pub_alt\": 1312.0, \"pub_doc\": 1996.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 432.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 254484564.0, \"pat_granted\": 135.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.1, \"pub_doc\": 48.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -16048598.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('69f3f5efb65b12d71d88de91e5975d2f','e10a2a038e97b6bb75152e575137a4fb','77e5f6785bd7c9d4f3610b4ac830ad4e','2023-09-08 00:22:46','2023-10-28 16:26:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Electroporation',12,'Electroporation, or electropermeabilization, is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing chemicals, drugs, electrode arrays or DNA to be introduced into the cell. In microbiology, the process of electroporation is often used to transform bacteria, yeast, or plant protoplasts by introducing new coding DNA. If bacteria and plasmids are mixed together, the plasmids can be transferred into the bacteria after electroporation, though depending on what is being transferred, cell-penetrating peptides or CellSqueeze could also be used. Electroporation works by passing thousands of volts across suspended cells in an electroporation cuvette. Afterwards, the cells have to be handled carefully until they have had a chance to divide, producing new cells that contain reproduced plasmids.','{\"pat_doc\": 615.0, \"pub_alt\": 688.0, \"pub_doc\": 895.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 38.0, \"clinic_alt\": 473.0, \"clinic_doc\": 97.0, \"grant_fund\": 14861397.0, \"pat_granted\": 163.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 72.8, \"pub_doc\": -23.0, \"clinic_doc\": 21.4, \"grant_fund\": -13946036.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6ad10ecfc4a663e45674cd27e350f752','fa64bf855faf8c0f2191aab2fb8e889c','1eb03b411e805213588194c37797ec5c','2023-09-05 21:42:31','2023-10-28 17:41:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Hypothyroidism',24,'Hypothyroidism is a disorder of the endocrine system in which the thyroid gland does not produce enough thyroid hormone. It can cause a number of symptoms, such as poor ability to tolerate cold, a feeling of tiredness, constipation, slow heart rate, depression, and weight gain. Occasionally there may be swelling of the front part of the neck due to goitre. Untreated cases of hypothyroidism during pregnancy can lead to delays in growth and intellectual development in the baby or congenital iodine deficiency syndrome. Worldwide, too little iodine in the diet is the most common cause of hypothyroidism. Hashimotos thyroiditis is the most common cause of hypothyroidism in countries with sufficient dietary iodine. Less common causes include previous treatment with radioactive iodine, injury to the hypothalamus or the anterior pituitary gland, certain medications, a lack of a functioning thyroid at birth, or previous thyroid surgery.','{\"pat_doc\": 118.0, \"pub_alt\": 1214.0, \"pub_doc\": 7043.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 59.0, \"clinic_alt\": 22.0, \"clinic_doc\": 465.0, \"grant_fund\": 11733422.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.4, \"pub_doc\": 201.3, \"clinic_doc\": 62.3, \"grant_fund\": -98143.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6af41d8269b788aeaab506c7423bbc1c','bcba00ed6e680440a1ab86723a027c98','9c021c3d61d0f8b13421b316b3cb4987','2023-09-05 22:27:22','2023-10-29 03:11:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','DNA Sequencing',24,'DNA sequencing is the process of determining the nucleic acid sequence â€“ the order of nucleotides in DNA. It includes any method or technology that is used to determine the order of the four bases: adenine, guanine, cytosine, and thymine. The advent of rapid DNA sequencing methods has greatly accelerated biological and medical research and discovery. Knowledge of DNA sequences has become indispensable for basic biological research, DNA Genographic Projects and in numerous applied fields such as medical diagnosis, biotechnology, forensic biology, virology and biological systematics. Comparing healthy and mutated DNA sequences can diagnose different diseases including various cancers, characterize antibody repertoire, and can be used to guide patient treatment. Having a quick way to sequence DNA allows for faster and more individualized medical care to be administered, and for more organisms to be identified and cataloged.','{\"pat_doc\": 591.0, \"pub_alt\": 6178.0, \"pub_doc\": 5702.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 372.0, \"clinic_alt\": 59.0, \"clinic_doc\": 148.0, \"grant_fund\": 212482026.0, \"pat_granted\": 204.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -8.7, \"pub_doc\": -57.5, \"clinic_doc\": 29.0, \"grant_fund\": -30361904.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6b66caf90f3f5183fdfbb8ffbf9484a4','c4e49c5cbafa19cbaf0a14bd5ddcb651','0b71467e6421c543859a81713b7406ad','2023-09-08 09:43:15','2023-10-28 20:41:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','sample preparation',12,'In analytical chemistry, sample preparation refers to the ways in which a sample is treated prior to its analyses. Preparation is a very important step in most analytical techniques, because the techniques are often not responsive to the analyte in its in-situ form, or the results are distorted by interfering species. Sample preparation may involve dissolution, extraction, reaction with some chemical species, pulverizing, treatment with a chelating agent, masking, filtering, dilution, sub-sampling or many other techniques. Treatment is done to prepare the sample into a form ready for analysis by specified analytical equipment. Sample preparation could involve: crushing and dissolution, chemical digestion with acid or alkali, sample extraction, sample clean up and sample pre-concentration.','{\"pat_doc\": 2446.0, \"pub_alt\": 343.0, \"pub_doc\": 3764.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 131.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 40.0, \"grant_fund\": 54708497.0, \"pat_granted\": 1133.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 189.7, \"pub_doc\": 74.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.5, \"grant_fund\": -48834204.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6bec99