e individual amino acids. The resulting mixture of amino acids is then separated and quantified using various analytical techniques such as high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) or gas chromatography (GC). This analysis provides valuable information about the composition and concentration of amino acids, which can be used to deduce the sequence of the peptide or identify the protein. This technique is widely used in research, industrial, and clinical settings for various applications such as protein characterization, quality control, and dietary analysis.','{\"pat_doc\": 52.0, \"pub_alt\": 213.0, \"pub_doc\": 509.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 22.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 626049.0, \"pat_granted\": 26.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": 3.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -90894.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6bfda2ebef8650bb43527f767f0e1313','233fd598fd0386ae12fee35e82334037','bd1c38b04e309caf5a996a81284254cb','2023-09-04 19:01:17','2023-10-29 06:26:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Nanomaterial',24,'Nanomaterials describe, in principle, materials of which a single unit is sized between 1 and 100 nm. Nanomaterials research takes a materials science-based approach to nanotechnology, leveraging advances in materials metrology and synthesis which have been developed in support of microfabrication research. Materials with structure at the nanoscale often have unique optical, electronic, thermo-physical or mechanical properties. Nanomaterials are slowly becoming commercialized and beginning to emerge as commodities.','{\"pat_doc\": 3328.0, \"pub_alt\": 504.0, \"pub_doc\": 35792.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1410.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 11.0, \"grant_fund\": 526989472.0, \"pat_granted\": 1001.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 290.2, \"pub_doc\": 1878.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.8, \"grant_fund\": -70327657.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6c1bc870d3242af74933956192744041','bcba00ed6e680440a1ab86723a027c98','9c021c3d61d0f8b13421b316b3cb4987','2023-09-05 22:27:22','2023-10-29 03:11:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','DNA Sequencing',48,'DNA sequencing is the process of determining the nucleic acid sequence â€“ the order of nucleotides in DNA. It includes any method or technology that is used to determine the order of the four bases: adenine, guanine, cytosine, and thymine. The advent of rapid DNA sequencing methods has greatly accelerated biological and medical research and discovery. Knowledge of DNA sequences has become indispensable for basic biological research, DNA Genographic Projects and in numerous applied fields such as medical diagnosis, biotechnology, forensic biology, virology and biological systematics. Comparing healthy and mutated DNA sequences can diagnose different diseases including various cancers, characterize antibody repertoire, and can be used to guide patient treatment. Having a quick way to sequence DNA allows for faster and more individualized medical care to be administered, and for more organisms to be identified and cataloged.','{\"pat_doc\": 1209.0, \"pub_alt\": 6178.0, \"pub_doc\": 11585.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1032.0, \"clinic_alt\": 61.0, \"clinic_doc\": 198.0, \"grant_fund\": 526046764.0, \"pat_granted\": 421.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -8.7, \"pub_doc\": -57.5, \"clinic_doc\": 29.0, \"grant_fund\": -30361904.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6c2c980893a782182e89cb4f8ba8d305','df68dc3c44b77575d9caaef9764342db','5cc2df341e20d3c3cf94910f9000682b','2023-09-08 08:32:17','2023-10-28 13:36:17','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Squamous cell carcinoma',36,'Squamous-cell carcinomas, also known as epidermoid carcinomas, comprise a number of different types of cancer that begin in squamous cells. These cells form on the surface of the skin, on the lining of hollow organs in the body, and on the lining of the respiratory and digestive tracts. Common types include: â€¢ cutaneous squamous-cell carcinoma: a type of skin cancer â€¢ squamous-cell carcinoma of the lung: a type of lung cancer â€¢ squamous-cell thyroid carcinoma: a type of thyroid cancer â€¢ esophageal squamous-cell carcinoma: a type of esophageal cancer â€¢ squamous-cell carcinoma of the vagina: a type of vaginal cancer. Despite sharing the name \"squamous-cell carcinoma\", the SCCs of different body sites can show differences in their presented symptoms, natural history, prognosis, and response to treatment.','{\"pat_doc\": 1214.0, \"pub_alt\": 1142.0, \"pub_doc\": 34114.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 759.0, \"clinic_alt\": 717.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2056.0, \"grant_fund\": 227339660.0, \"pat_granted\": 299.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 29.4, \"pub_doc\": 69.4, \"clinic_doc\": 397.4, \"grant_fund\": -19576090.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6c7de3fa67accfd5d72929d31addb410','7d75075a107a397f768de4a8ce5a4861','75614694863f46e81b896a0f2f0af650','2023-09-08 02:25:57','2023-10-28 22:16:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','29Si NMR',12,'29Si NMR (Nuclear Magnetic Resonance) spectroscopy is a technique used to study the chemical composition and structure of silicon-containing compounds. Specifically, it detects the magnetic properties of the 29Si isotope present in the sample, which can be used to determine factors such as the chemical environment, bonding, and symmetry of the silicon atoms. This technique can provide valuable insights into the nature of materials ranging from ceramics to pharmaceuticals and is frequently utilized in fields such as materials science, geochemistry, and solid-state chemistry. By analyzing the various 29Si NMR signals obtained, researchers can gain a deeper understanding of the chemical properties of the sample and the factors underlying its behavior.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 9.0, \"pub_doc\": 79.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 1.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -10985.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6cab2b2679df792b7d74e6f721363c0a','0a067dac7f4a167516bf9ae7db80387b','05ecfec6f6dadbdbb84f6f314d1e344e','2023-09-08 09:06:23','2023-10-28 13:31:15','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Non-small cell lung cancer',48,'Non-small-cell lung carcinoma is any type of epithelial lung cancer other than small-cell lung carcinoma. NSCLC accounts for about 85% of all lung cancers. As a class, NSCLCs are relatively insensitive to chemotherapy, compared to small-cell carcinoma. When possible, they are primarily treated by surgical resection with curative intent, although chemotherapy has been used increasingly both preoperatively and postoperatively.','{\"pat_doc\": 2469.0, \"pub_alt\": 1405.0, \"pub_doc\": 31367.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 776.0, \"clinic_alt\": 822.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3678.0, \"grant_fund\": 302075457.0, \"pat_granted\": 609.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 34.7, \"pub_doc\": 157.7, \"clinic_doc\": 620.8, \"grant_fund\": -18325526.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6d6c78308947a20127915a1a372f3620','b1f6b055bf7f576af1fda25a04ce64a1','d6145a42d41428a7d112c8f6aaaadaa8','2023-09-08 00:54:04','2023-10-29 01:01:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Digital Pathology',36,'Digital pathology is a sub-field of pathology that focuses on data management based on information generated from digitized specimen slides. Through the use of computer-based technology, digital pathology utilizes virtual microscopy. Glass slides are converted into digital slides that can be viewed, managed, shared and analyzed on a computer monitor. With the practice of Whole-Slide Imaging, which is another name for virtual microscopy, the field of digital pathology is growing and has applications in diagnostic medicine, with the goal of achieving efficient and cheaper diagnoses, prognosis, and prediction of diseases due to the success in machine learning and artificial intelligence in healthcare.','{\"pat_doc\": 452.0, \"pub_alt\": 896.0, \"pub_doc\": 1729.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 108.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 19.0, \"grant_fund\": 116848299.0, \"pat_granted\": 132.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 31.4, \"pub_doc\": 91.6, \"clinic_doc\": 5.1, \"grant_fund\": -15307360.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6d778708de7cb67e148a564728c317de','938382e729311744061a6779d6023f38','41fcc042c592c420a4959d0a8d491f70','2023-09-08 01:56:00','2023-10-28 23:36:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Purification',36,'Protein purification is a series of processes intended to isolate one or a few proteins from a complex mixture, usually cells, tissues or whole organisms. Protein purification is vital for the specification of the function, structure and interactions of the protein of interest. The purification process may separate the protein and non-protein parts of the mixture, and finally separate the desired protein from all other proteins. Ideally, to study a protein of interest, it must be separated from other components of the cell so that contaminants wont interfere in the examination of the protein of interests structure and function. Separation of one protein from all others is typically the most laborious aspect of protein purification. Separation steps usually exploit differences in protein size, physico-chemical properties, binding affinity and biological activity. The pure result may be termed protein isolate.','{\"pat_doc\": 893.0, \"pub_alt\": 356.0, \"pub_doc\": 558.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 88.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 32748741.0, \"pat_granted\": 408.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 5.2, \"pub_doc\": -6.6, \"clinic_doc\": -0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2889090.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6e09e92a47ce3335c533085f1d4c046d','92a972462fc449a3f071840dbe8b2742','392c6994beadcacc6139a1c22998f10f','2023-09-20 23:02:34','2023-10-28 18:26:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','spatial biology',12,'Spatial Biology is defined as the study of tissues within their own 2D or 3D context. It is the new frontier of molecular biology.\r\n\r\nConsider how GPS captures location coordinates within an area to create a map and track you within it. The same principle can be translated to spatial data on a cellular and molecular level.\r\n\r\nThrough this technology, we can help map the spatial architecture of a cell and how it talks to and interacts with its surroundings. Spatial biology is like being inside a tissue sample at a molecular level. It enables single-cell analysis. Through spatial biology tools, you are empowered to see things that are not possible by sequencing or any other technologies out there.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 407.0, \"pub_doc\": 84.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 11.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 8238772.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 26.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2600741.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6ea0e64e4ff4f57f8e385872bc1e1171','1edf5dbb1a5ebbaef987b8b78449add1','d55c8f5e392f4de211e65cb1cf025f9d','2023-09-08 01:07:08','2023-10-29 00:41:20','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Stability',24,'mRNA stability is the measure of how long a messenger RNA (mRNA) molecule lasts within a cell before it is degraded. This is important because the stability of mRNA affects the amount of protein that can be produced from that mRNA. If mRNA is stable, it can persist in the cell and continue to produce protein. However, if the mRNA is unstable, it will degrade quickly and less protein will be produced. mRNA stability is regulated by a number of factors including sequence motifs, RNA-binding proteins, and the presence of other molecules. Understanding how mRNA stability is regulated can provide insights into gene expression and can be helpful in developing new therapies for certain diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 24.0, \"pub_alt\": 1837.0, \"pub_doc\": 1032.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 78.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 46151926.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.1, \"pub_doc\": 58.5, \"clinic_doc\": -0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1054364.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6f60c353a4492f86b9e1763d720c9db1','d3549b81bb39a9ac922f45ac120eb0cc','3da09264ab4cd2d03a36df24f5f30506','2023-09-08 09:48:28','2023-10-28 20:26:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry',48,'Inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry is a type of mass spectrometry that uses an inductively coupled plasma to ionize the sample. It atomizes the sample and creates atomic and small polyatomic ions, which are then detected. It is known and used for its ability to detect metals and several non-metals in liquid samples at very low concentrations. It can detect different isotopes of the same element, which makes it a versatile tool in isotopic labeling. Compared to atomic absorption spectroscopy, ICP-MS has greater speed, precision, and sensitivity. However, compared with other types of mass spectrometry, such as thermal ionization mass spectrometry and glow discharge mass spectrometry, ICP-MS introduces many interfering species: argon from the plasma, component gases of air that leak through the cone orifices, and contamination from glassware and the cones.','{\"pat_doc\": 387.0, \"pub_alt\": 1281.0, \"pub_doc\": 5632.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 132.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.0, \"grant_fund\": 30814492.0, \"pat_granted\": 94.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 10.7, \"pub_doc\": 21.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.6, \"grant_fund\": -270284.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('6ffb6e5c90e7877fdcac76157d61a566','ec9127faed503fab80aacc0c09e3bea4','1e154b56de35b3c06486dd7e904cade0','2023-09-05 22:15:33','2023-10-29 03:26:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Vaccines',48,'mRNA vaccines are a type of COVID-19 vaccine that provides immunity to the virus by introducing a small piece of messenger RNA (mRNA) into the body. This mRNA contains genetic instructions that direct cells to produce spike proteins, the same proteins that coat the surface of the coronavirus. Once the spike proteins are produced, the immune system recognizes them as foreign and develops antibodies to protect against future infections. mRNA vaccines are unique in that they do not contain weakened or dead virus particles, which makes them safer and easier to produce than traditional vaccines. They also have the potential to be rapidly developed and customized to address new variations of the virus. The two mRNA vaccines currently authorized for use in the United States are the Pfizer-BioNTech and Moderna vaccines.','{\"pat_doc\": 246.0, \"pub_alt\": 26339.0, \"pub_doc\": 3500.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 174.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1578.0, \"clinic_doc\": 82.0, \"grant_fund\": 128751131.0, \"pat_granted\": 21.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 39.4, \"pub_doc\": 427.8, \"clinic_doc\": 19.8, \"grant_fund\": 7035647.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('705193b82dedb70a70ec9a5ba465398c','3ac2ba09e7b52bbe721ad2f6f07c0d4c','efc072896d951f3550e7d73c38f3d42e','2023-09-08 09:56:42','2023-10-28 19:51:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Microscale thermophoresis',24,'Microscale thermophoresis is a technology for the interaction analysis of biomolecules. Microscale thermophoresis is the directed movement of particles in a microscopic temperature gradient. Any change of the hydration shell of biomolecules due to changes in their structure/conformation results in a relative change of the movement along the temperature gradient and is used to determine binding affinities. MST allows measurement of interactions directly in solution without the need of immobilization to a surface.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 170.0, \"pub_doc\": 378.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 14.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2329836.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -485048.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('70599c1971a040ce83066f7867ae9848','0aa43655311231d22f19c9a7f97c3577','69904542b990c5c24086b0dfa8c698cf','2023-09-05 22:50:45','2023-10-29 03:05:06','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','High-Throughput Screening',12,'High-throughput screening is a method for scientific experimentation especially used in drug discovery and relevant to the fields of biology, materials science and chemistry. Using robotics, data processing/control software, liquid handling devices, and sensitive detectors, high-throughput screening allows a researcher to quickly conduct millions of chemical, genetic, or pharmacological tests. Through this process one can quickly recognize active compounds, antibodies, or genes that modulate a particular biomolecular pathway. The results of these experiments provide starting points for drug design and for understanding the noninteraction or role of a particular location.','{\"pat_doc\": 303.0, \"pub_alt\": 350.0, \"pub_doc\": 1489.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 110.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 52620334.0, \"pat_granted\": 97.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.8, \"pub_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -83628586.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('70c746c2d52326cc64b0175cfec16b9d','de3c47ca09e78512850cba5b26eb1590','85e7d38a1e770cd1c8c35e8a00e24e8d','2023-09-05 23:12:11','2023-10-29 02:46:12','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','X-ray Crystallography',36,'X-ray crystallography is the experimental science determining the atomic and molecular structure of a crystal, in which the crystalline structure causes a beam of incident X-rays to diffract into many specific directions. By measuring the angles and intensities of these diffracted beams, a crystallographer can produce a three-dimensional picture of the density of electrons within the crystal. From this electron density, the mean positions of the atoms in the crystal can be determined, as well as their chemical bonds, their crystallographic disorder, and various other information. Since many materials can form crystalsâ€”such as salts, metals, minerals, semiconductors, as well as various inorganic, organic, and biological moleculesâ€”X-ray crystallography has been fundamental in the development of many scientific fields.','{\"pat_doc\": 92.0, \"pub_alt\": 1727.0, \"pub_doc\": 4947.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 626.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 411205014.0, \"pat_granted\": 16.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.7, \"pub_doc\": -59.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -3454168.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('70dfb2b7434fb512f59cc705d4dc2d13','b25c61978fbea0483d82d3d77115840d','13bed64c970494074ea74f12ff611354','2023-09-08 01:04:16','2023-10-28 15:46:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','PROTAC',36,'A proteolysis targeting chimera is a heterobifunctional molecule composed of two active domains and a linker, capable of removing specific unwanted proteins. Rather than acting as a conventional enzyme inhibitor, a PROTAC works by inducing selective intracellular proteolysis. PROTACs consist of two covalently linked protein-binding molecules: one capable of engaging an E3 ubiquitin ligase, and another that binds to a target protein meant for degradation. Recruitment of the E3 ligase to the target protein results in ubiquitination and subsequent degradation of the target protein via the proteasome. Because PROTACs need only to bind their targets with high selectivity, there are currently many efforts to retool previously ineffective inhibitor molecules as PROTACs for next-generation drugs.','{\"pat_doc\": 412.0, \"pub_alt\": 327.0, \"pub_doc\": 1698.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 234.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 86487984.0, \"pat_granted\": 60.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 50.7, \"pub_doc\": 127.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.5, \"grant_fund\": -9266726.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('70e9303041c79f0f2e96e832b844609f','e1e875f09f9ac3cb516d1a52affa7c20','9ca5a3bb1439526aa869b8ae1a850da8','2024-01-18 11:38:52','2024-01-18 11:38:52','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Chromatography Detector',24,'In chemical analysis, chromatography is a laboratory technique for the separation of a mixture into its components. The mixture is dissolved in a fluid solvent (gas or liquid) called the mobile phase, which carries it through a system (a column, a capillary tube, a plate, or a sheet) on which a material called the stationary phase is fixed.','{\"pat_doc\": 48.0, \"pub_alt\": 2.0, \"pub_doc\": 7.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 430882.0, \"pat_granted\": 25.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": -1.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 43088.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('711f4110d474b03fb16642f62340c3fe','b052bba7b488d052b6c520140b9a95f7','0f0001c9173ff0ef27a841bf7334c0a3','2023-09-07 23:32:11','2023-10-29 02:41:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Synthetic biology',36,'Synthetic biology is a multidisciplinary field of science that focuses on living systems and organisms, and it applies engineering principles to develop new biological parts, devices, and systems or to redesign existing systems found in nature. It is a branch of science that encompasses a broad range of methodologies from various disciplines, such as biotechnology, biomaterials, material science/engineering, genetic engineering, molecular biology, molecular engineering, systems biology, membrane science, biophysics, chemical and biological engineering, electrical and computer engineering, control engineering and evolutionary biology. It includes designing and constructing biological modules, biological systems, and biological machines or, re-design of existing biological systems for useful purposes. Additionally, it is the branch of science that focuses on the new abilities of engineering into existing organisms to redesign them for useful purposes.','{\"pat_doc\": 624.0, \"pub_alt\": 1696.0, \"pub_doc\": 4754.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1234.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 819397167.0, \"pat_granted\": 154.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 62.9, \"pub_doc\": 64.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -38172745.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('71481f570bf51b5203e26deb35c95a90','f90e9c061ea63f3d762a3d1141314989','30640b686e5be896faa3d14ed6691346','2023-09-05 18:55:23','2023-10-29 05:31:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Biosensor',24,'A biosensor is an analytical device, used for the detection of a chemical substance, that combines a biological component with a physicochemical detector. The sensitive biological element, e.g. tissue, microorganisms, organelles, cell receptors, enzymes, antibodies, nucleic acids, etc., is a biologically derived material or biomimetic component that interacts with, binds with, or recognizes the analyte under study. The biologically sensitive elements can also be created by biological engineering. The transducer or the detector element, which transforms one signal into another one, works in a physicochemical way: optical, piezoelectric, electrochemical, electrochemiluminescence etc., resulting from the interaction of the analyte with the biological element, to easily measure and quantify. The biosensor reader device connects with the associated electronics or signal processors that are primarily responsible for the display of the results in a user-friendly way.','{\"pat_doc\": 5173.0, \"pub_alt\": 1506.0, \"pub_doc\": 18503.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 963.0, \"clinic_alt\": 52.0, \"clinic_doc\": 110.0, \"grant_fund\": 471849952.0, \"pat_granted\": 1736.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 137.4, \"pub_doc\": 867.1, \"clinic_doc\": 19.0, \"grant_fund\": -13437491.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('71660ae0b9c8b6c5d3183983a2996836','a966912b70494ff7ec5379fbffffe2e6','a3d7925fcedbb9a92b698d370be59c62','2023-09-08 00:18:16','2023-10-28 11:50:31','Electronics','Needs','Customer or Market Needs','Sustainable materials',12,'Sustainable materials are those that have been sourced and manufactured in a way that minimizes environmental impact, promotes social responsibility, and provides economic benefits to communities. These materials are typically renewable, recyclable, or biodegradable, and they ensure the longevity of our natural resources. Sustainable materials can include plant-based options like bamboo, organic cotton, and linen, as well as recycled materials such as plastic bottles or reclaimed wood. Using sustainable materials in various industries is an important step toward a more sustainable future, as it reduces waste, conserves energy, and supports a circular economy. As consumers, we can make a difference by choosing products made from sustainable materials and encouraging companies to prioritize sustainability in their sourcing and manufacturing practices.','{\"pat_doc\": 25.0, \"pub_alt\": 191.0, \"pub_doc\": 897.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 93.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 115346963.0, \"pat_granted\": 5.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_doc\": 189.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 19728859.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7167cc2a28ab37bfff44068f3545a6a1','f75d09446940f86ed08ebd34eebf7374','aa6c75c69a90f2c711a2a5e31bb1c990','2023-09-08 01:34:12','2023-10-29 00:06:22','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','mRNA sequencing',48,'mRNA sequencing refers to the process of analyzing the transcriptome of an organism by sequencing the messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules that are expressed in a given sample. mRNA is synthesized from DNA and contains the information required to make proteins, which are the building blocks of the cell. By sequencing the mRNA, researchers can identify which genes are being expressed in a specific tissue or cell type, and can also measure the abundance of each transcript. This information can be used to gain insights into the biological processes that are occurring in the organism, and can also be used to identify genes that are dysregulated in diseases such as cancer. mRNA sequencing has become a widely used technique for studying gene expression, and new methods are continually being developed to improve the accuracy and speed of this process.','{\"pat_doc\": 29.0, \"pub_alt\": 8858.0, \"pub_doc\": 1245.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 68.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 22916526.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.5, \"pub_doc\": 43.3, \"clinic_doc\": 1.2, \"grant_fund\": -1315097.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('71a5f07d6bc1c7828bda6bafa6c032a2','4ed1727d16902077c7b79a9c262994fa','12a26d07df436f186302cbc8c800d6d6','2023-09-05 20:45:30','2023-10-29 04:31:13','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Electroencephalography',48,'Electroencephalography is a method to record an electrogram of the spontaneous electrical activity of the brain. The biosignals detected by EEG have been shown to represent the postsynaptic potentials of pyramidal neurons in the neocortex and allocortex. It is typically non-invasive, with the EEG electrodes placed along the scalp using the International 10â€“20 system, or variations of it. Electrocorticography, involving surgical placement of electrodes, is sometimes called \"intracranial EEG\". Clinical interpretation of EEG recordings is most often performed by visual inspection of the tracing or quantitative EEG analysis. Voltage fluctuations measured by the EEG bioamplifier and electrodes allow the evaluation of normal brain activity. As the electrical activity monitored by EEG originates in neurons in the underlying brain tissue, the recordings made by the electrodes on the surface of the scalp vary in accordance with their orientation and distance to the source of the activity.','{\"pat_doc\": 622.0, \"pub_alt\": 5051.0, \"pub_doc\": 15984.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 894.0, \"clinic_alt\": 122.0, \"clinic_doc\": 846.0, \"grant_fund\": 318060954.0, \"pat_granted\": 130.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 299.2, \"clinic_doc\": 125.2, \"grant_fund\": -19331779.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('71e6340b41522806b9a81ffea8db6af8','99c7079af458b7e10d0e17de306286cf','7ec492ea6e0e56c5b381d422684157c5','2023-09-08 01:01:11','2023-09-08 01:01:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Cushing\'s Syndrome',24,'Cushing\'s syndrome is a collection of signs and symptoms due to prolonged exposure to glucocorticoids such as cortisol. Signs and symptoms may include high blood pressure, abdominal obesity but with thin arms and legs, reddish stretch marks, a round red face due to facial plethora, a fat lump between the shoulders, weak muscles, weak bones, acne, and fragile skin that heals poorly. Women may have more hair and irregular menstruation. Occasionally there may be changes in mood, headaches, and a chronic feeling of tiredness. Cushing\'s syndrome is caused by either excessive cortisol-like medication, such as prednisone, or a tumor that either produces or results in the production of excessive cortisol by the adrenal glands. Cases due to a pituitary adenoma are known as Cushing\'s disease, which is the second most common cause of Cushing\'s syndrome after medication. A number of other tumors, often referred to as ectopic due to their placement outside the pituitary, may also cause Cushing\'s.','{\"pat_doc\": 99.0, \"pub_alt\": 563.0, \"pub_doc\": 604.0, \"deals_num\": 4.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 53.0, \"grant_fund\": 806744.0, \"pat_granted\": 38.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 4.0, \"capital_raised\": 2154.17429357}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.3, \"pub_doc\": 41.6, \"clinic_doc\": 8.9, \"grant_fund\": -229023.8, \"capital_raised\": 215.348}'),('720271be94248a10b3c0d47f6cf107f9','de565fc9dd512d5b484b35f776f4545e','5428f4cb6631add28ed91160f184e3d2','2023-09-04 18:50:59','2023-10-29 06:46:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Polymerase Chain Reaction',12,'The polymerase chain reaction is a method widely used to make millions to billions of copies of a specific DNA sample rapidly, allowing scientists amplify a very small sample of DNA sufficiently to enable detailed study. PCR was invented in 1983 by American biochemist Kary Mullis at Cetus Corporation; Mullis and biochemist Michael Smith, who had developed other essential ways of manipulating DNA, were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1993. PCR is fundamental to many of the procedures used in genetic testing and research, including analysis of ancient samples of DNA and identification of infectious agents. Using PCR, copies of very small amounts of DNA sequences are exponentially amplified in a series of cycles of temperature changes. PCR is now a common and often indispensable technique used in medical laboratory research for a broad variety of applications including biomedical research and criminal forensics. The majority of PCR methods rely on thermal cycling.','{\"pat_doc\": 969.0, \"pub_alt\": 6193.0, \"pub_doc\": 16202.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 67.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1692.0, \"clinic_doc\": 488.0, \"grant_fund\": 13156566.0, \"pat_granted\": 304.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 25.6, \"pub_doc\": -1022.4, \"clinic_doc\": 80.3, \"grant_fund\": -12358489.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7204a002c683294eed9d8dfdaaed2741','b973f9a55a74403c41f6bfdbc9121654','b347f7200b8aff24464a347c263147e9','2023-09-04 19:13:14','2023-10-29 06:11:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Filtration',36,'Filtration is a physical separation process that separates solid matter and fluid from a mixture using a filter medium that has a complex structure through which only the fluid can pass. Solid particles that cannot pass through the filter medium are described as oversize and the fluid that passes through is called the filtrate. Oversize particles may form a filter cake on top of the filter and may also block the filter lattice, preventing the fluid phase from crossing the filter, known as blinding. The size of the largest particles that can successfully pass through a filter is called the effective pore size of that filter. The separation of solid and fluid is imperfect; solids will be contaminated with some fluid and filtrate will contain fine particles. Filtration occurs both in nature and in engineered systems; there are biological, geological, and industrial forms.','{\"pat_doc\": 188825.0, \"pub_alt\": 26339.0, \"pub_doc\": 122941.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3524.0, \"clinic_alt\": 592.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3105.0, \"grant_fund\": 1198454208.0, \"pat_granted\": 133298.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 315.7, \"pub_doc\": 2992.9, \"clinic_doc\": 373.4, \"grant_fund\": -100208796.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7273bd05aa4ecde0dfde6c2122052e60','ae3fe7b4d0291ed05028397533f28114','3147652f436cfa0a26c21b17f2c50188','2023-09-05 21:59:53','2023-10-28 17:36:10','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','induced pluripotent stem cells',24,'Induced pluripotent stem cells are a type of pluripotent stem cell that can be generated directly from a somatic cell. The iPSC technology was pioneered by Shinya Yamanaka and Kazutoshi Takahashi in Kyoto, Japan, who together showed in 2006 that the introduction of four specific genes, collectively known as Yamanaka factors, encoding transcription factors could convert somatic cells into pluripotent stem cells. Shinya Yamanaka was awarded the 2012 Nobel Prize along with Sir John Gurdon \"for the discovery that mature cells can be reprogrammed to become pluripotent.\" Pluripotent stem cells hold promise in the field of regenerative medicine. Because they can propagate indefinitely, as well as give rise to every other cell type in the body, they represent a single source of cells that could be used to replace those lost to damage or disease. The most well-known type of pluripotent stem cell is the embryonic stem cell.','{\"pat_doc\": 827.0, \"pub_alt\": 2998.0, \"pub_doc\": 3735.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 550.0, \"clinic_alt\": 9.0, \"clinic_doc\": 52.0, \"grant_fund\": 236371237.0, \"pat_granted\": 176.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 34.5, \"pub_doc\": -32.8, \"clinic_doc\": 11.8, \"grant_fund\": -40706986.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('73399ba7563186f284ab352ef3a11505','de565fc9dd512d5b484b35f776f4545e','5428f4cb6631add28ed91160f184e3d2','2023-09-04 18:50:59','2023-10-29 06:46:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Polymerase Chain Reaction',48,'The polymerase chain reaction is a method widely used to make millions to billions of copies of a specific DNA sample rapidly, allowing scientists amplify a very small sample of DNA sufficiently to enable detailed study. PCR was invented in 1983 by American biochemist Kary Mullis at Cetus Corporation; Mullis and biochemist Michael Smith, who had developed other essential ways of manipulating DNA, were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1993. PCR is fundamental to many of the procedures used in genetic testing and research, including analysis of ancient samples of DNA and identification of infectious agents. Using PCR, copies of very small amounts of DNA sequences are exponentially amplified in a series of cycles of temperature changes. PCR is now a common and often indispensable technique used in medical laboratory research for a broad variety of applications including biomedical research and criminal forensics. The majority of PCR methods rely on thermal cycling.','{\"pat_doc\": 3966.0, \"pub_alt\": 32701.0, \"pub_doc\": 75414.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 605.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1692.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1161.0, \"grant_fund\": 109561078.0, \"pat_granted\": 1298.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 25.6, \"pub_doc\": -1022.4, \"clinic_doc\": 80.3, \"grant_fund\": -12358489.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7396f19978492af6893c0e893a5df971','62d3bf1b81cd240eca1b17ec53a45aed','9d56006f7b0bfb85db66d228f98a19d9','2023-09-08 00:57:05','2023-10-29 00:51:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Polymeric nanoparticles',24,'Polymeric nanoparticles are microscopic particles made up of polymers that have numerous applications, especially in the field of drug delivery and biomedical engineering. These particles, ranging from 1 to 1000 nanometers in size, can be designed in such a way that it can encapsulate drugs or other therapeutic agents and deliver them to the targeted site in a controlled manner. With characteristics such as their small size, large surface area, and the ability to protect the encapsulated content from degradation, they provide an excellent alternative to traditional drug delivery techniques. Polymeric nanoparticles have potential applications in cancer treatment, gene therapy, and imaging, among others. They have the potential to revolutionize the way we treat diseases and offer the possibility of more effective, less invasive therapeutic options.','{\"pat_doc\": 187.0, \"pub_alt\": 1000.0, \"pub_doc\": 1501.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 57.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 7885478.0, \"pat_granted\": 35.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.6, \"pub_doc\": 37.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.2, \"grant_fund\": -3328898.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('74258514e62e95b0b1b76cbf85a4fd32','02a38e6ea55a654be6d75d697c93ecfb','0af29b992be89a885d2b3986c5a61ac5','2023-09-08 10:03:52','2023-10-28 19:11:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Catalyst screening',24,'Catalyst screening can be defined as a process by which researchers test a large number of catalysts in order to identify the most effective one for a particular reaction. Catalysts are substances that speed up reactions without being consumed in the process. The screening process typically involves testing each catalyst under a variety of conditions such as temperature, pressure, and reaction time, to determine which catalyst is the most suitable for the reaction being studied. Catalyst screening is an important step in many research projects as it helps researchers to identify the catalysts that are most likely to be effective in a real-world scenario. It can also help to identify new catalysts that may be more effective than those that are currently being used in industry. By screening a large number of catalysts, researchers can quickly identify promising candidates for further study, ultimately leading to the development of more efficient catalysts for a wide range of applications.','{\"pat_doc\": 32.0, \"pub_alt\": 86.0, \"pub_doc\": 124.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2559657.0, \"pat_granted\": 19.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 7.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 219625.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('74abcfb4a2e03e328ddbfa4e2bf88107','8b34441cb6296c1404d0a6501ee553ff','eecaf00b18ce2e327917c5c42d883f43','2023-09-05 18:42:49','2023-10-29 05:41:10','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Raman Spectroscopy',48,'Raman spectroscopy is a spectroscopic technique typically used to determine vibrational modes of molecules, although rotational and other low-frequency modes of systems may also be observed. Raman spectroscopy is commonly used in chemistry to provide a structural fingerprint by which molecules can be identified. Raman spectroscopy relies upon inelastic scattering of photons, known as Raman scattering. A source of monochromatic light, usually from a laser in the visible, near infrared, or near ultraviolet range is used, although X-rays can also be used. The laser light interacts with molecular vibrations, phonons or other excitations in the system, resulting in the energy of the laser photons being shifted up or down. The shift in energy gives information about the vibrational modes in the system. Infrared spectroscopy typically yields similar yet complementary information. Typically, a sample is illuminated with a laser beam.','{\"pat_doc\": 2603.0, \"pub_alt\": 3241.0, \"pub_doc\": 37519.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1332.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 79.0, \"grant_fund\": 310418233.0, \"pat_granted\": 767.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -8.3, \"pub_doc\": 257.9, \"clinic_doc\": 14.3, \"grant_fund\": -11262983.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('74b5903b9ac952e3c4da6ff0560cbf42','ecb5eb0e681dab97bb1d5c09a929aa00','ad11810122ec68f63273a505f81c6d11','2023-09-08 00:01:07','2023-10-28 16:46:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Adeno-associated virus',24,'Adeno-associated viruses are small viruses that infect humans and some other primate species. They belong to the genus Dependoparvovirus, which in turn belongs to the family Parvoviridae. They are small replication-defective, nonenveloped viruses and have linear single-stranded DNA genome of approximately 4.8 kilobases. Several features make AAV an attractive candidate for creating viral vectors for gene therapy, and for the creation of isogenic human disease models. Gene therapy vectors using AAV can infect both dividing and quiescent cells and persist in an extrachromosomal state without integrating into the genome of the host cell. In the native virus, however, integration of virally carried genes into the host genome does occur. Integration can be important for certain applications, but can also have unwanted consequences. Recent human clinical trials using AAV for gene therapy in the retina have shown promise.','{\"pat_doc\": 3309.0, \"pub_alt\": 2540.0, \"pub_doc\": 2773.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 196.0, \"clinic_alt\": 500.0, \"clinic_doc\": 97.0, \"grant_fund\": 117750687.0, \"pat_granted\": 478.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 245.2, \"pub_doc\": 179.9, \"clinic_doc\": 23.4, \"grant_fund\": -12947659.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('74b73716e8baf9448035dab24469994e','5f1ee7663407442aa2582d3efd1ad42b','5320de801f6c227388f87a0edfc49eb4','2023-09-04 19:25:15','2023-10-29 06:06:07','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Metabolomics',24,'Metabolomics is the scientific study of chemical processes involving metabolites, the small molecule substrates, intermediates, and products of cell metabolism. Specifically, metabolomics is the \"systematic study of the unique chemical fingerprints that specific cellular processes leave behind\", the study of their small-molecule metabolite profiles. The metabolome represents the complete set of metabolites in a biological cell, tissue, organ, or organism, which are the end products of cellular processes. Messenger RNA, gene expression data, and proteomic analyses reveal the set of gene products being produced in the cell, data that represents one aspect of cellular function. Conversely, metabolic profiling can give an instantaneous snapshot of the physiology of that cell, and thus, metabolomics provides a direct \"functional readout of the physiological state\" of an organism.','{\"pat_doc\": 84.0, \"pub_alt\": 5232.0, \"pub_doc\": 15849.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1097.0, \"clinic_alt\": 322.0, \"clinic_doc\": 730.0, \"grant_fund\": 575900993.0, \"pat_granted\": 17.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.2, \"pub_doc\": 1091.2, \"clinic_doc\": 144.0, \"grant_fund\": -118313386.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7507e07ea582b59f141f15f93116c98b','6ee75b4e6fefbd3534f1769a0b6e2972','e27f505c9d666365d5d09dc9decf7e50','2023-09-05 21:10:38','2023-10-28 12:30:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','6G',24,'6G technology is the next-generation wireless communication technology that is under development and expected to be commercialized by 2030. It is said to be 100 times faster than 5G with higher reliability, low latency and more secure communication. 6G will enable high-speed internet connectivity and high-resolution video streaming. It will also support the Internet of Things (IoT), artificial intelligence (AI), machine learning (ML), and virtual reality (VR) technologies. The development of 6G technology is still in the early stages with some countries having already started research on the technology. However, it is expected to bring significant changes to the way we live and work to enable new products and services that will drive innovation across different industries.','{\"pat_doc\": 4970.0, \"pub_alt\": 955.0, \"pub_doc\": 13621.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 674.0, \"clinic_alt\": 34.0, \"clinic_doc\": 206.0, \"grant_fund\": 648306728.0, \"pat_granted\": 1141.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 485.2, \"pub_doc\": 1244.7, \"clinic_doc\": 33.1, \"grant_fund\": 83405037.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('753521bca9697e7a57616a167c4489e3','6ee75b4e6fefbd3534f1769a0b6e2972','e27f505c9d666365d5d09dc9decf7e50','2023-09-05 21:10:38','2023-10-28 12:30:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','6G',48,'6G technology is the next-generation wireless communication technology that is under development and expected to be commercialized by 2030. It is said to be 100 times faster than 5G with higher reliability, low latency and more secure communication. 6G will enable high-speed internet connectivity and high-resolution video streaming. It will also support the Internet of Things (IoT), artificial intelligence (AI), machine learning (ML), and virtual reality (VR) technologies. The development of 6G technology is still in the early stages with some countries having already started research on the technology. However, it is expected to bring significant changes to the way we live and work to enable new products and services that will drive innovation across different industries.','{\"pat_doc\": 8038.0, \"pub_alt\": 10557.0, \"pub_doc\": 22149.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1039.0, \"clinic_alt\": 34.0, \"clinic_doc\": 305.0, \"grant_fund\": 1145151723.0, \"pat_granted\": 2120.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 485.2, \"pub_doc\": 1244.7, \"clinic_doc\": 33.1, \"grant_fund\": 83405037.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('766705bb9868ef755aaa1b2af91d631c','7e6303a93deff34a836da02c9ec9b121','b8d8729029b072a6d46a6e6415f7d63a','2023-09-20 19:21:20','2023-10-28 14:51:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Addisons Disease',36,'Addisons disease, also known as primary adrenal insufficiency, is a rare long-term endocrine disorder characterized by inadequate production of the steroid hormones cortisol and aldosterone by the two outer layers of the cells of the adrenal glands, causing adrenal insufficiency. Symptoms generally come on slowly and insidiously and may include abdominal pain and gastrointestinal abnormalities, weakness, and weight loss. Darkening of the skin in certain areas may also occur. Under certain circumstances, an adrenal crisis may occur with low blood pressure, vomiting, lower back pain, and loss of consciousness. Mood changes may also occur. Rapid onset of symptoms indicates acute adrenal failure, which is a clinical emergency. An adrenal crisis can be triggered by stress, such as from an injury, surgery, or infection. Addisons disease arises from problems with the adrenal gland such that not enough of the steroid hormone cortisol and possibly aldosterone are produced.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 5.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('76cd20041a834374567800846e92abea','8f5e65940c2b32c65f99c25d9fea77ca','e9ee3da8c5950eddf30d7e6a8d175388','2023-09-08 00:36:35','2023-10-29 01:20:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Engineering',12,'Protein engineering is the process of developing useful or valuable proteins through the design and production of unnatural polypeptides, often by altering amino acid sequences found in nature. It is a young discipline, with much research taking place into the understanding of protein folding and recognition for protein design principles. It has been used to improve the function of many enzymes for industrial catalysis. It is also a product and services market, with an estimated value of $168 billion by 2017. There are two general strategies for protein engineering: rational protein design and directed evolution. These methods are not mutually exclusive; researchers will often apply both. In the future, more detailed knowledge of protein structure and function, and advances in high-throughput screening, may greatly expand the abilities of protein engineering.','{\"pat_doc\": 163.0, \"pub_alt\": 1207.0, \"pub_doc\": 713.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 91.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 66491002.0, \"pat_granted\": 41.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.1, \"pub_doc\": 48.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -16048598.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('76ec649f5628176bfe29dfd3913469d9','bf8b4feb522a72f79560c81cf6dc8720','62899d4dc41a7b9eb6091bb110aca523','2023-09-05 19:55:00','2023-10-29 04:51:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','Tissue Engineering',48,'Tissue engineering is a biomedical engineering discipline that uses a combination of cells, engineering, materials methods, and suitable biochemical and physicochemical factors to restore, maintain, improve, or replace different types of biological tissues. Tissue engineering often involves the use of cells placed on tissue scaffolds in the formation of new viable tissue for a medical purpose but is not limited to applications involving cells and tissue scaffolds. While it was once categorized as a sub-field of biomaterials, having grown in scope and importance it can be considered as a field of its own. While most definitions of tissue engineering cover a broad range of applications, in practice the term is closely associated with applications that repair or replace portions of or whole tissues. Often, the tissues involved require certain mechanical and structural properties for proper functioning.','{\"pat_doc\": 3897.0, \"pub_alt\": 663.0, \"pub_doc\": 25919.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1721.0, \"clinic_alt\": 16.0, \"clinic_doc\": 81.0, \"grant_fund\": 718142197.0, \"pat_granted\": 1470.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.9, \"pub_doc\": 306.5, \"clinic_doc\": 10.5, \"grant_fund\": -54494104.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('76f4054875aeb201804d0aa68639a985','2531f8a177fbfd014f79f1851c094d65','6dae4310435505307085d7f2c73a1787','2023-09-08 00:48:13','2023-10-28 11:40:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Bioelectronics',36,'Bioelectronics is a field of research in the convergence of biology and electronics.','{\"pat_doc\": 59.0, \"pub_alt\": 1022.0, \"pub_doc\": 1454.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 157.0, \"clinic_alt\": 8.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 107855740.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": 59.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": 7394410.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('77071a485de4f8d05fd27bb9ca500433','938382e729311744061a6779d6023f38','41fcc042c592c420a4959d0a8d491f70','2023-09-08 01:56:00','2023-10-28 23:36:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Purification',24,'Protein purification is a series of processes intended to isolate one or a few proteins from a complex mixture, usually cells, tissues or whole organisms. Protein purification is vital for the specification of the function, structure and interactions of the protein of interest. The purification process may separate the protein and non-protein parts of the mixture, and finally separate the desired protein from all other proteins. Ideally, to study a protein of interest, it must be separated from other components of the cell so that contaminants wont interfere in the examination of the protein of interests structure and function. Separation of one protein from all others is typically the most laborious aspect of protein purification. Separation steps usually exploit differences in protein size, physico-chemical properties, binding affinity and biological activity. The pure result may be termed protein isolate.','{\"pat_doc\": 591.0, \"pub_alt\": 155.0, \"pub_doc\": 371.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 42.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 16256172.0, \"pat_granted\": 270.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 5.2, \"pub_doc\": -6.6, \"clinic_doc\": -0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2889090.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('772804e8fdd0d422129fca5ad126fba6','230eda4c55f24cadd07347f1a221f5ca','d9f345c5479253d7d74e62f81762d9a5','2023-09-05 21:57:22','2023-10-28 12:15:33','Electronics','Components','Storage Devices','Spintronics',24,'Spintronics, also known as spin electronics, is the study of the intrinsic spin of the electron and its associated magnetic moment, in addition to its fundamental electronic charge, in solid-state devices. The field of spintronics concerns spin-charge coupling in metallic systems; the analogous effects in insulators fall into the field of multiferroics. Spintronics fundamentally differs from traditional electronics in that, in addition to charge state, electron spins are used as a further degree of freedom, with implications in the efficiency of data storage and transfer. Spintronic systems are most often realised in dilute magnetic semiconductors and Heusler alloys and are of particular interest in the field of quantum computing and neuromorphic computing.','{\"pat_doc\": 99.0, \"pub_alt\": 335.0, \"pub_doc\": 3760.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 325.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 192681008.0, \"pat_granted\": 27.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.9, \"pub_doc\": 169.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5459749.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('777361b6ddd9ecf7d95321ffa02168c9','dfe596d300e59da2f75df75fd3120d54','a73d74823ba2a6c69ad94ff6d93ed919','2023-09-08 01:42:12','2023-10-28 15:06:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia',36,'Congenital adrenal hyperplasia is a group of autosomal recessive disorders characterized by impaired cortisol synthesis. It results from the deficiency of one of the five enzymes required for the synthesis of cortisol in the adrenal cortex. Most of these disorders involve excessive or deficient production of hormones such as glucocorticoids, mineralocorticoids, or sex steroids, and can alter development of primary or secondary sex characteristics in some affected infants, children, or adults. It is one of the most common autosomal recessive disorders in humans.','{\"pat_doc\": 146.0, \"pub_alt\": 119.0, \"pub_doc\": 1144.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 10.0, \"clinic_alt\": 700.0, \"clinic_doc\": 57.0, \"grant_fund\": 1274915.0, \"pat_granted\": 18.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.4, \"pub_doc\": 1.7, \"clinic_doc\": 5.2, \"grant_fund\": -549349.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('77747d864cffddf81b0140cbe24d254c','97a64c193e09e440bbb1c8b928126797','4893d9f6d48ce8d1001500525173bb9e','2023-09-07 23:55:39','2023-10-29 02:21:16','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','Lipid Nanoparticles',12,'Lipid nanoparticles are nanoparticles composed of lipids. They are a novel pharmaceutical drug delivery system, and a novel pharmaceutical formulation. LNPs as a drug delivery vehicle were first approved in 2018 for the siRNA drug Onpattro. LNPs became more widely known in late 2020, as some COVID-19 vaccines that use RNA vaccine technology coat the fragile mRNA strands with PEGylated lipid nanoparticles as their delivery vehicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 757.0, \"pub_alt\": 6178.0, \"pub_doc\": 1284.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 78.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1578.0, \"clinic_doc\": 13.0, \"grant_fund\": 46614547.0, \"pat_granted\": 85.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 197.5, \"pub_doc\": 208.3, \"clinic_doc\": 3.7, \"grant_fund\": 10362532.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7798afed115462c9019c6622bb502cbe','d5e0c4320bf432eb18619675fba4a2d6','dc3eb969daa777d1268e99485984656d','2023-09-07 23:34:57','2023-10-28 17:16:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes',48,'Tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes are white blood cells that have left the bloodstream and migrated towards a tumor. They include T cells and B cells and are part of the larger category of â€˜tumor-infiltrating immune cells which consist of both mononuclear and polymorphonuclear immune cells, in variable proportions. Their abundance varies with tumor type and stage and in some cases relates to disease prognosis. TILs can often be found in the tumor stroma and within the tumor itself. Their functions can dynamically change throughout tumor progression and in response to anticancer therapy TILs are implicated in killing tumor cells. The presence of lymphocytes in tumors is often associated with better clinical outcomes.','{\"pat_doc\": 223.0, \"pub_alt\": 680.0, \"pub_doc\": 3698.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 119.0, \"clinic_alt\": 467.0, \"clinic_doc\": 103.0, \"grant_fund\": 43169209.0, \"pat_granted\": 21.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.9, \"pub_doc\": 39.6, \"clinic_doc\": 20.1, \"grant_fund\": -2417367.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('77c411827f890fae1b4914906e364a15','02a38e6ea55a654be6d75d697c93ecfb','0af29b992be89a885d2b3986c5a61ac5','2023-09-08 10:03:52','2023-10-28 19:11:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Catalyst screening',12,'Catalyst screening can be defined as a process by which researchers test a large number of catalysts in order to identify the most effective one for a particular reaction. Catalysts are substances that speed up reactions without being consumed in the process. The screening process typically involves testing each catalyst under a variety of conditions such as temperature, pressure, and reaction time, to determine which catalyst is the most suitable for the reaction being studied. Catalyst screening is an important step in many research projects as it helps researchers to identify the catalysts that are most likely to be effective in a real-world scenario. It can also help to identify new catalysts that may be more effective than those that are currently being used in industry. By screening a large number of catalysts, researchers can quickly identify promising candidates for further study, ultimately leading to the development of more efficient catalysts for a wide range of applications.','{\"pat_doc\": 16.0, \"pub_alt\": 86.0, \"pub_doc\": 69.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1506663.0, \"pat_granted\": 9.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 7.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 219625.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('77cf9e68f0dbfc6329938e27dfaa4f1f','5799fbde63662e16529cdc2465faa33f','eefb2660a8535eb1d304c9a60295324f','2023-09-08 14:51:25','2023-10-28 18:35:05','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Liposomes',48,'Liposomes are microscopic, spherical vesicles composed of a phospholipid bilayer that is able to encapsulate a variety of water-soluble substances. They are commonly used as drug delivery systems because the lipid bilayer gives them the ability to cross cell membranes and deliver their contents directly to the interior of cells. Liposomes can be prepared in a variety of sizes with different properties, which makes them a versatile tool in medical research and pharmaceuticals. Their biocompatibility and ability to encapsulate both hydrophilic and hydrophobic substances has caused them to become increasingly popular in the fields of drug delivery and cosmetics.','{\"pat_doc\": 3101.0, \"pub_alt\": 590.0, \"pub_doc\": 11942.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 611.0, \"clinic_alt\": 108.0, \"clinic_doc\": 67.0, \"grant_fund\": 172975550.0, \"pat_granted\": 795.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 11.3, \"pub_doc\": 166.2, \"clinic_doc\": 8.1, \"grant_fund\": -13776868.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('77f5d342d0e36e198517dbd5d64d1669','8445e498b5c8e24b28f8fe85d68e76af','33b4678f6b096b9a11757bc96a56f980','2023-09-08 01:16:53','2023-10-29 00:21:18','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Directed Evolution',36,'Directed evolution is a method used in protein engineering that mimics the process of natural selection to steer proteins or nucleic acids toward a user-defined goal. It consists of subjecting a gene to iterative rounds of mutagenesis, selection and amplification. It can be performed in vivo, or in vitro. Directed evolution is used both for protein engineering as an alternative to rationally designing modified proteins, as well as for experimental evolution studies of fundamental evolutionary principles in a controlled, laboratory environment.','{\"pat_doc\": 429.0, \"pub_alt\": 901.0, \"pub_doc\": 1421.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 302.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 129263670.0, \"pat_granted\": 139.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 25.3, \"pub_doc\": 7.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -10443235.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('78b6bf372db26f0cb02a6516c666daf5','7894dc5316736cccc7857ade68b00def','5428f4cb6631add28ed91160f184e3d2','2023-09-04 18:49:56','2023-10-29 06:50:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Polymerase Chain Reaction',24,'The polymerase chain reaction is a method widely used to make millions to billions of copies of a specific DNA sample rapidly, allowing scientists amplify a very small sample of DNA sufficiently to enable detailed study. PCR was invented in 1983 by American biochemist Kary Mullis at Cetus Corporation; Mullis and biochemist Michael Smith, who had developed other essential ways of manipulating DNA, were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1993. PCR is fundamental to many of the procedures used in genetic testing and research, including analysis of ancient samples of DNA and identification of infectious agents. Using PCR, copies of very small amounts of DNA sequences are exponentially amplified in a series of cycles of temperature changes. PCR is now a common and often indispensable technique used in medical laboratory research for a broad variety of applications including biomedical research and criminal forensics. The majority of PCR methods rely on thermal cycling.','{\"pat_doc\": 2061.0, \"pub_alt\": 7175.0, \"pub_doc\": 35601.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 179.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1692.0, \"clinic_doc\": 711.0, \"grant_fund\": 29343864.0, \"pat_granted\": 691.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 25.6, \"pub_doc\": -1022.4, \"clinic_doc\": 80.3, \"grant_fund\": -12358489.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7918859dd32ed7a1e2488b78bb7726f0','241acd5defc6bb6b835e678e78fce56c','35f85abe435e1302c602406f943817c0','2023-09-08 02:20:19','2023-10-28 14:41:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Polyplexes',36,'Polyplexes are a class of nanocarriers used in gene therapy that enable delivery of therapeutic nucleic acids such as plasmids, siRNAs, and miRNAs. Their structure consists of a cationic polymer, usually polyethyleneimine (PEI), complexed with negatively charged nucleic acids to form a stable complex. The advantage of polyplexes is their ability to protect the nucleic acids from degradation and facilitate their passage into cells, ultimately leading to efficient gene expression. Additionally, the surface charge and size of polyplexes can be modified, allowing for targeted delivery and reduced toxicity. Polyplexes have shown great promise in preclinical studies, but their clinical translation is still limited due to challenges such as immune response and optimization of delivery parameters. Nonetheless, they continue to be an exciting field of study with potential for a variety of gene therapy applications.','{\"pat_doc\": 80.0, \"pub_alt\": 1037.0, \"pub_doc\": 350.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 11.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5166606.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 7.8, \"pub_doc\": 1.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -353261.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('793df9208694306dd40f1117a25e6cfb','ee19185ea91ee66a9b4ca70824b1b576','06752199a8f52b307494ef715b2504c5','2023-09-08 11:11:55','2023-10-28 18:46:09','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Biomarker Discovery',36,'Biomarker discovery is a medical term describing the process by which biomarkers are discovered. Many commonly used blood tests in medicine are biomarkers. There is interest in biomarker discovery on the part of the pharmaceutical industry; blood-test or other biomarkers could serve as intermediate markers of disease in clinical trials, and as possible drug targets.','{\"pat_doc\": 63.0, \"pub_alt\": 1311.0, \"pub_doc\": 2150.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 267.0, \"clinic_alt\": 309.0, \"clinic_doc\": 93.0, \"grant_fund\": 239189465.0, \"pat_granted\": 12.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": 37.9, \"clinic_doc\": 20.6, \"grant_fund\": -49263941.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('79506d0de56ac9970dfc1658216c7422','86bfc1d6ea6ada0972bb4ebd56d88ad7','8f2884ac2f89f569ae690ad0aa820ccc','2023-09-08 01:08:24','2023-10-28 15:41:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Tumor-associated antigens',24,'Tumor-associated antigens (TAAs) are proteins that are present in cancer cells but not in normal cells or are expressed at higher levels in tumors than in healthy tissues. These antigens may be recognized by the immune system as foreign and trigger an immune response against the cancer cells. TAAs are being studied for their potential use in cancer vaccines and immunotherapy. However, many TAAs are also present in normal tissues, which can lead to side effects when targeted by cancer treatments. Therefore, the specificity of TAAs and their potential impact on healthy tissues must be carefully evaluated before their use in clinical settings.','{\"pat_doc\": 166.0, \"pub_alt\": 279.0, \"pub_doc\": 581.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 24.0, \"clinic_alt\": 504.0, \"clinic_doc\": 29.0, \"grant_fund\": 11412244.0, \"pat_granted\": 28.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.6, \"pub_doc\": 27.2, \"clinic_doc\": 6.4, \"grant_fund\": -3038596.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('79604357917ca3957101a42f0cb31ad9','7cad47d8fa337e04fde87c8076f4adfe','25cc485513e0e2921857b91eeab511ae','2023-09-08 08:31:01','2023-10-28 13:41:15','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Colorectal cancer',36,'Colorectal cancer, also known as bowel cancer, colon cancer, or rectal cancer, is the development of cancer from the colon or rectum. Signs and symptoms may include blood in the stool, a change in bowel movements, weight loss, and fatigue. Most colorectal cancers are due to old age and lifestyle factors, with only a small number of cases due to underlying genetic disorders. Risk factors include diet, obesity, smoking, and lack of physical activity. Dietary factors that increase the risk include red meat, processed meat, and alcohol. Another risk factor is inflammatory bowel disease, which includes Crohns disease and ulcerative colitis. Some of the inherited genetic disorders that can cause colorectal cancer include familial adenomatous polyposis and hereditary non-polyposis colon cancer; however, these represent less than 5% of cases. It typically starts as a benign tumor, often in the form of a polyp, which over time becomes cancerous.','{\"pat_doc\": 4045.0, \"pub_alt\": 7747.0, \"pub_doc\": 45529.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1534.0, \"clinic_alt\": 699.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3342.0, \"grant_fund\": 662578576.0, \"pat_granted\": 1074.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 91.4, \"pub_doc\": 499.3, \"clinic_doc\": 542.0, \"grant_fund\": -69281414.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7985250f593782a76af108ad6a2289db','7a50af118adfe006fb057aba1683daea','5ae657e8e871e94265b41c651880e213','2023-09-08 01:40:52','2023-10-29 00:01:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Coating technology',12,'Coating technology refers to the various processes used to apply a thin layer of material onto a surface to enhance or modify its properties. Coatings can be applied to a wide range of materials including metals, plastics, ceramics, and glass. Coatings can improve the surface properties of a material such as corrosion resistance, wear resistance, and thermal resistance. They can also be used to provide a decorative finish. Coating technology is extensively used in industries such as automotive, aerospace, construction, and electronics. There are several types of coating processes including thermal spraying, chemical vapor deposition, and electroplating. Advances in coating technology have enabled the development of high-performance coatings that can withstand extreme temperatures and harsh environments. Coating technology is an important field that helps to extend the life of materials and improve their performance.','{\"pat_doc\": 348.0, \"pub_alt\": 24.0, \"pub_doc\": 282.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 25.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 18354633.0, \"pat_granted\": 156.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.5, \"pub_doc\": 36.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.8, \"grant_fund\": 152974.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('79861885b87532106c12b34d116c8e87','97a64c193e09e440bbb1c8b928126797','4893d9f6d48ce8d1001500525173bb9e','2023-09-07 23:55:39','2023-10-29 02:21:16','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','Lipid Nanoparticles',48,'Lipid nanoparticles are nanoparticles composed of lipids. They are a novel pharmaceutical drug delivery system, and a novel pharmaceutical formulation. LNPs as a drug delivery vehicle were first approved in 2018 for the siRNA drug Onpattro. LNPs became more widely known in late 2020, as some COVID-19 vaccines that use RNA vaccine technology coat the fragile mRNA strands with PEGylated lipid nanoparticles as their delivery vehicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 1839.0, \"pub_alt\": 16312.0, \"pub_doc\": 3903.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 273.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1578.0, \"clinic_doc\": 17.0, \"grant_fund\": 107603694.0, \"pat_granted\": 219.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 197.5, \"pub_doc\": 208.3, \"clinic_doc\": 3.7, \"grant_fund\": 10362532.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('79e13c9a8a667e08708ceb968a1e9a82','7d75075a107a397f768de4a8ce5a4861','75614694863f46e81b896a0f2f0af650','2023-09-08 02:25:57','2023-10-28 22:16:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','29Si NMR',24,'29Si NMR (Nuclear Magnetic Resonance) spectroscopy is a technique used to study the chemical composition and structure of silicon-containing compounds. Specifically, it detects the magnetic properties of the 29Si isotope present in the sample, which can be used to determine factors such as the chemical environment, bonding, and symmetry of the silicon atoms. This technique can provide valuable insights into the nature of materials ranging from ceramics to pharmaceuticals and is frequently utilized in fields such as materials science, geochemistry, and solid-state chemistry. By analyzing the various 29Si NMR signals obtained, researchers can gain a deeper understanding of the chemical properties of the sample and the factors underlying its behavior.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 9.0, \"pub_doc\": 160.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 1.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -10985.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7abde4bda98789d056f88e75ab8d5488','8a48608f902f6d6e18861f68c6c16aa1','afe94a7da70247bc6803357002649726','2023-09-08 11:13:41','2023-10-28 18:41:12','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Clinical Decision Support Systems',24,'Clinical decision support systems (CDSS) are computer programs designed to assist healthcare professionals in making clinical decisions by providing information and knowledge at the point of care. CDSS incorporate patient data and evidence-based guidelines to suggest potential diagnoses, recommend laboratory tests and treatment options, calculate medication doses and detect harmful drug interactions. CDSS can improve patient outcomes by enhancing the accuracy of diagnoses, preventing medical errors, and enabling clinicians to make more informed decisions based on relevant clinical evidence. Furthermore, CDSS can help reduce healthcare costs and improve efficiency by reducing unnecessary tests and treatments, and minimizing length of hospital stay. Overall, CDSS provide an important tool for healthcare professionals to provide high-quality patient care.','{\"pat_doc\": 11.0, \"pub_alt\": 543.0, \"pub_doc\": 803.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 26.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 29.0, \"grant_fund\": 13000620.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 46.6, \"clinic_doc\": 6.5, \"grant_fund\": -372976.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7b4ced56a8ab7a748bcd3a13c8ca7da8','e73131830356703a23b1a11a711e48c5','e4f81d8ac891f1e1dbdd2332eaaa8fed','2023-09-05 22:16:53','2023-10-29 03:21:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Magnetic nanoparticles',48,'Magnetic nanoparticles are a class of nanoparticle that can be manipulated using magnetic fields. Such particles commonly consist of two components, a magnetic material, often iron, nickel and cobalt, and a chemical component that has functionality. While nanoparticles are smaller than 1 micrometer in diameter, the larger microbeads are 0.5â€“500 micrometer in diameter. Magnetic nanoparticle clusters that are composed of a number of individual magnetic nanoparticles are known as magnetic nanobeads with a diameter of 50â€“200 nanometers. Magnetic nanoparticle clusters are a basis for their further magnetic assembly into magnetic nanochains.','{\"pat_doc\": 2260.0, \"pub_alt\": 521.0, \"pub_doc\": 9538.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 415.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": 89651339.0, \"pat_granted\": 742.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -8.6, \"pub_doc\": -35.6, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -2481846.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7b579e0b8830dd12eb50d0d3fa8ac1d9','bfef6514b60e4c25c2f8497aa216e34c','075f3ab037592e82b84202abe07674ba','2023-09-08 02:51:12','2023-10-28 10:45:32','Electronics','Devices','Next Generation Computers','Universal Quantum computer',36,'A quantum Turing machine or universal quantum computer is an abstract machine used to model the effects of a quantum computer. It provides a simple model that captures all of the power of quantum computationâ€”that is, any quantum algorithm can be expressed formally as a particular quantum Turing machine. However, the computationally equivalent quantum circuit is a more common model. Quantum Turing machines can be related to classical and probabilistic Turing machines in a framework based on transition matrices. That is, a matrix can be specified whose product with the matrix representing a classical or probabilistic machine provides the quantum probability matrix representing the quantum machine. This was shown by Lance Fortnow.','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_alt\": 180.0, \"pub_doc\": 132.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 16.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 8335175.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -8025713.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7bca4c9fbc7d4578d945df1bc219e097','2dd9d7ef89e93089944c052185d5b575','ce749f284f6019c4ac54019c71229b4d','2023-09-08 09:58:49','2023-10-28 19:41:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','digital droplet PCR',48,'Digital droplet PCR (ddPCR) is a highly sensitive and specific technique used for quantifying nucleic acids. ddPCR partitions a sample into thousands of droplets containing one or zero target molecules. The droplets are then subjected to PCR amplification and fluorescence analysis to determine which droplets contain the target molecule. This allows for highly precise quantification of the initial amount of target nucleic acid in the original sample, with a sensitivity of up to one copy per reaction. ddPCR has numerous applications in fields such as cancer research, infectious disease diagnosis, and genetic testing.','{\"pat_doc\": 37.0, \"pub_alt\": 313.0, \"pub_doc\": 600.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 34.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 18.0, \"grant_fund\": 12729659.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": -2.8, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": -559015.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7bd0181ed19259d3437891ca881233d5','8fbcc1f9eedaac7f718565fe8c77f942','db8b9e3ac816571bb88d6adb6207c374','2023-09-08 10:03:44','2023-10-28 19:16:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Microbiological assay',36,'Microbiological assay is a type of analytical technique used in biochemistry and microbiology to determine the concentration of a particular substance by measuring the growth response of microorganisms to varying levels of the substance. In this assay, a known quantity of a microorganism is inoculated into a series of test tubes containing different concentrations of the substance being tested. The growth response of the microorganism is then measured and compared to a set of standard concentrations of the substance to determine the relative concentration in the sample being tested. Microbiological assays are widely used in the pharmaceutical industry to determine the potency of drugs and antibiotics, and in the food industry to measure the nutritional value of food products.','{\"pat_doc\": 45.0, \"pub_alt\": 80.0, \"pub_doc\": 221.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 20.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 5377978.0, \"pat_granted\": 34.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.0, \"pub_doc\": -7.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.4, \"grant_fund\": -3518570.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7c0748a2d2088cd37b4d44158363adbe','233fd598fd0386ae12fee35e82334037','bd1c38b04e309caf5a996a81284254cb','2023-09-04 19:01:17','2023-10-29 06:26:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Nanomaterial',12,'Nanomaterials describe, in principle, materials of which a single unit is sized between 1 and 100 nm. Nanomaterials research takes a materials science-based approach to nanotechnology, leveraging advances in materials metrology and synthesis which have been developed in support of microfabrication research. Materials with structure at the nanoscale often have unique optical, electronic, thermo-physical or mechanical properties. Nanomaterials are slowly becoming commercialized and beginning to emerge as commodities.','{\"pat_doc\": 1992.0, \"pub_alt\": 504.0, \"pub_doc\": 18469.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 476.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 276252671.0, \"pat_granted\": 615.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 290.2, \"pub_doc\": 1878.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.8, \"grant_fund\": -70327657.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7c1e3c711df78c98e8523ad94622fe69','593e0b5980cd1f5c381a759416640c82','fac8fdaee075a0078ef0f1af1e190a56','2023-09-08 02:54:38','2023-10-28 10:40:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Neuromorphic Photonics',36,'Neuromorphic photonics is an area of research that seeks to combine the principles of neuroscience and photonics, a field of study that deals with light and its properties. Scientists working in the field aim to create artificial systems that can process information in a way that mimics the human brain, using light instead of electrical signals. By doing this, they hope to create more efficient and powerful computing systems that can tackle complex tasks such as image recognition and natural language processing with ease. Neuromorphic photonics is still in the early stages of development, but it has the potential to revolutionize the field of artificial intelligence and lead to a new generation of smart machines.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 134.0, \"pub_doc\": 78.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 190047.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -51400.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7c3be1e2423840deb1b5f97846bc2c2d','6de9464f8e368a19a89261dd71c09017','641ccd99a014845dc487b6f5a217f8ff','2023-09-08 00:19:27','2023-10-29 01:56:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Nuclear Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy',48,'Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy, most commonly known as NMR spectroscopy or magnetic resonance spectroscopy, is a spectroscopic technique to observe local magnetic fields around atomic nuclei. This spectroscopy is based on the measurement of absorption of electromagnetic radiations in the radio frequency region from roughly 4 to 900 MHz. Absorption of radio waves in the presence of magnetic field is accompanied by a special type of nuclear transition, and for this reason, such type of spectroscopy is known as Nuclear Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy. The sample is placed in a magnetic field and the NMR signal is produced by excitation of the nuclei sample with radio waves into nuclear magnetic resonance, which is detected with sensitive radio receivers. The intramolecular magnetic field around an atom in a molecule changes the resonance frequency, thus giving access to details of the electronic structure of a molecule and its individual functional groups.','{\"pat_doc\": 146.0, \"pub_alt\": 745.0, \"pub_doc\": 4591.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 213.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 13.0, \"grant_fund\": 115171666.0, \"pat_granted\": 44.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.8, \"pub_doc\": 7.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.9, \"grant_fund\": -2653145.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7cfb9e9e8f5d0d584652f11acfd0bdef','30ab92573d44ab7bfab530de0c6c2f3b','834e427876f8944f329691ead9f0d4a1','2023-09-04 19:50:57','2023-10-28 18:06:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Coronary artery diseases',12,'Coronary artery diseases are a group of conditions that affect the blood vessels that supply the heart muscle with oxygen and nutrients. These diseases occur when there is a buildup of plaque, or fatty deposits, in the coronary arteries, which can narrow or block these vessels altogether. This can result in reduced blood flow to the heart, leading to chest pain (angina), shortness of breath, and even heart attacks. Risk factors for coronary artery disease include high blood pressure, high cholesterol, smoking, obesity, and an unhealthy diet. Treatment options for coronary artery disease include lifestyle changes such as exercise and diet modifications, medications, and in severe cases, surgery.','{\"pat_doc\": 10.0, \"pub_alt\": 76.0, \"pub_doc\": 192.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 187.0, \"clinic_doc\": 40.0, \"grant_fund\": 1060913.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.7, \"pub_doc\": -4.9, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 134481.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7d3c05712a7262729b210f9e0ab65f64','b6bd0e112ac4b84a4babc4781241a61c','eaab7bb973ab23e8de7a128f3cda6817','2023-09-08 00:05:29','2023-10-28 16:41:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Mesenchymal stromal cells',12,'Mesenchymal stem cells also known as mesenchymal stromal cells or medicinal signaling cells are multipotent stromal cells that can differentiate into a variety of cell types, including osteoblasts, chondrocytes, myocytes and adipocytes.','{\"pat_doc\": 70.0, \"pub_alt\": 452.0, \"pub_doc\": 1087.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 33.0, \"clinic_alt\": 61.0, \"clinic_doc\": 112.0, \"grant_fund\": 9717847.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": -47.2, \"clinic_doc\": 30.5, \"grant_fund\": -5473780.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7d6b7d61822b95e06420211f41afb69f','e8e3ae6a8794d6acab5085e68542cec5','c89ffe68cd3a23332175ee5b50bcf229','2023-09-05 21:41:00','2023-10-28 12:20:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Quantum computing',24,'A quantum computer is a computer that exploits quantum mechanical phenomena. At small scales, physical matter exhibits properties of both particles and waves, and quantum computing leverages this behavior, specifically quantum superposition and entanglement, using specialized hardware that supports the preparation and manipulation of quantum states. Classical physics cannot explain the operation of these quantum devices, and a scalable quantum computer could perform some calculations exponentially faster than any modern \"classical\" computer. In particular, a large-scale quantum computer could break widely used encryption schemes and aid physicists in performing physical simulations; however, the current state of the art is largely experimental and impractical, with several obstacles to useful applications. Moreover, scalable quantum computers do not hold promise for many practical tasks, and for many important tasks quantum speedups are proven impossible.','{\"pat_doc\": 2500.0, \"pub_alt\": 1038.0, \"pub_doc\": 6937.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1025.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 838001722.0, \"pat_granted\": 688.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 329.1, \"pub_doc\": 695.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": 9235870.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7d7fd4b2a43a5334d2609c0b69dbd815','d0cc167aa82d70fd2bfffe86208ac337','870950b481f06063886edd5c24dd2f8a','2023-09-08 09:13:24','2023-10-28 13:06:13','Healthcare','Neuroscience','Other','Neuro-inflammation',36,'Neuroinflammation is inflammation of the nervous tissue. It may be initiated in response to a variety of cues, including infection, traumatic brain injury, toxic metabolites, or autoimmunity. In the central nervous system, including the brain and spinal cord, microglia are the resident innate immune cells that are activated in response to these cues. The CNS is typically an immunologically privileged site because peripheral immune cells are generally blocked by the bloodâ€“brain barrier, a specialized structure composed of astrocytes and endothelial cells. However, circulating peripheral immune cells may surpass a compromised BBB and encounter neurons and glial cells expressing major histocompatibility complex molecules, perpetuating the immune response. Although the response is initiated to protect the central nervous system from the infectious agent, the effect may be toxic and widespread inflammation as well as further migration of leukocytes through the bloodâ€“brain barrier may occur.','{\"pat_doc\": 25.0, \"pub_alt\": 602.0, \"pub_doc\": 445.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 31.0, \"clinic_alt\": 35.0, \"clinic_doc\": 37.0, \"grant_fund\": 20676931.0, \"pat_granted\": 7.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": -14.9, \"clinic_doc\": 6.2, \"grant_fund\": -2859987.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7dc67b2228175a200e9e527f6cf779c9','00a65404eafa0410776576517426c1bf','c3708acc1ff6c957eeda159c8941d078','2023-09-08 02:55:47','2023-10-28 13:51:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Polymer-based Nanoparticles',48,'Polymer-based nanoparticles are tiny particles that are made from polymeric materials and have a diameter in the nanometer range. They are widely used in drug delivery, cancer therapy, imaging, and diagnostics, due to their unique and advantageous properties. Polymer-based nanoparticles offer several benefits, including controlled drug release, enhanced drug efficacy, and biocompatibility. They are also more stable and less toxic than traditional drug delivery vehicles such as liposomes. Polymer-based nanoparticles can be prepared using various fabrication methods such as emulsion polymerization, nanoprecipitation, and self-assembly. By manipulating the polymer chemistry and nanoparticle size, their properties can be tuned to optimize their performance for specific applications. Overall, polymer-based nanoparticles hold great promise for advancing medical technologies and improving patient outcomes.','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_alt\": 57.0, \"pub_doc\": 155.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 506021.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.6, \"pub_doc\": 4.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -69931.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7e2a41625e16958a43e52208477ed6e2','b663e797baa447591490dab433b724b6','e5dc1ab9b95fd144580ba449bdb1f286','2023-09-05 22:04:26','2023-10-28 17:31:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Gene therapies (Non-viral)','CRISPR-Cas9',36,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 745.0, \"pub_alt\": 3610.0, \"pub_doc\": 5470.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 814.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 21.0, \"grant_fund\": 341525102.0, \"pat_granted\": 210.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.8, \"pub_doc\": 114.2, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -29971557.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7e747fe2f5011fae542d2d6904cf1f10','8cc017d911f60e86f3530c8efab7f91a','7cfcc2197e33173ce522354c4a1177f6','2023-09-07 23:46:10','2023-10-29 02:31:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Green Hydrogen',48,'Green hydrogen is hydrogen generated from either renewable energy or low-carbon power. Green hydrogen has significantly lower carbon emissions than grey hydrogen, which is derived from fossil fuels without carbon capture. Green hydrogen may be used to decarbonize sectors that are hard to electrify, such as cement and iron production. Green hydrogen can be used to produce green ammonia, the main constituent of synthetic fertilizer. It can also be used for long-duration grid energy storage, and for long-duration seasonal energy storage. As of 2021, green hydrogen accounted for less than 0.04% of total hydrogen production. Its cost relative to hydrogen derived from fossil fuels is the main reason green hydrogen is in less demand.','{\"pat_doc\": 297.0, \"pub_alt\": 768.0, \"pub_doc\": 3701.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 688.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1023707825.0, \"pat_granted\": 76.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 63.1, \"pub_doc\": 594.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 22939710.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7e8170ca96b00bbcbafdaa1b41efb436','e1fe0660b514055c0dbf73bc14fd217a','ed9ba98e0c7216e9330cb415b46ee8cd','2023-09-07 23:50:12','2023-10-28 17:06:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Herpes simplex virus',24,'Herpes simplex virus 1 and 2, also known by their taxonomic names Human alphaherpesvirus 1 and Human alphaherpesvirus 2, are two members of the human Herpesviridae family, a set of viruses that produce viral infections in the majority of humans. Both HSV-1 and HSV-2 are very common and contagious. They can be spread when an infected person begins shedding the virus. As of 2016, about 67% of the world population under the age of 50 had HSV-1. In the United States, about 47.8% and 11.9% are estimated to have HSV-1 and HSV-2, respectively, though actual prevalence may be much higher. Because it can be transmitted through any intimate contact, it is one of the most common sexually transmitted infections.','{\"pat_doc\": 584.0, \"pub_alt\": 1973.0, \"pub_doc\": 2619.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 113.0, \"clinic_alt\": 214.0, \"clinic_doc\": 101.0, \"grant_fund\": 37283980.0, \"pat_granted\": 152.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.7, \"pub_doc\": 21.1, \"clinic_doc\": 20.7, \"grant_fund\": -10632542.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7e980c0a014fc5c7cf32d494ffbe912d','bfef6514b60e4c25c2f8497aa216e34c','075f3ab037592e82b84202abe07674ba','2023-09-08 02:51:12','2023-10-28 10:45:32','Electronics','Devices','Next Generation Computers','Universal Quantum computer',24,'A quantum Turing machine or universal quantum computer is an abstract machine used to model the effects of a quantum computer. It provides a simple model that captures all of the power of quantum computationâ€”that is, any quantum algorithm can be expressed formally as a particular quantum Turing machine. However, the computationally equivalent quantum circuit is a more common model. Quantum Turing machines can be related to classical and probabilistic Turing machines in a framework based on transition matrices. That is, a matrix can be specified whose product with the matrix representing a classical or probabilistic machine provides the quantum probability matrix representing the quantum machine. This was shown by Lance Fortnow.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 134.0, \"pub_doc\": 92.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 12.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 8180867.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -8025713.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7f7c77111d405732150050f46cb0dc88','75926dafeed6c4c3d2dd27794c573c76','88cbe0424257da986f5d8f34f678784d','2023-09-08 00:55:46','2023-10-29 00:56:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Microencapsulation',48,'Microencapsulation is a process in which tiny particles or droplets are surrounded by a coating to give small capsules, with useful properties. In general, it is used to incorporate food ingredients, enzymes, cells or other materials on a micro metric scale. Microencapsulation can also be used to enclose solids, liquids, or gases inside a micrometric wall made of hard or soft soluble film, in order to reduce dosing frequency and prevent the degradation of pharmaceuticals. In its simplest form, a microcapsule is a small sphere comprising a near-uniform wall enclosing some material. The enclosed material in the microcapsule is referred to as the core, internal phase, or fill, whereas the wall is sometimes called a shell, coating, or membrane. Some materials like lipids and polymers, such as alginate, may be used as a mixture to trap the material of interest inside. Most microcapsules have pores with diameters between a few nanometers and a few micrometers.','{\"pat_doc\": 626.0, \"pub_alt\": 382.0, \"pub_doc\": 2867.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 132.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 25397215.0, \"pat_granted\": 201.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -18.0, \"pub_doc\": 33.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.4, \"grant_fund\": -2198383.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7f95b0ba27731281e8ebb5b6f2671f33','12dcedeb603ee2f3832d8525115bfc64','4893d9f6d48ce8d1001500525173bb9e','2023-09-07 23:56:32','2023-10-28 16:51:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Lipid Nanoparticles',36,'Lipid nanoparticles are nanoparticles composed of lipids. They are a novel pharmaceutical drug delivery system, and a novel pharmaceutical formulation. LNPs as a drug delivery vehicle were first approved in 2018 for the siRNA drug Onpattro. LNPs became more widely known in late 2020, as some COVID-19 vaccines that use RNA vaccine technology coat the fragile mRNA strands with PEGylated lipid nanoparticles as their delivery vehicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 1643.0, \"pub_alt\": 16312.0, \"pub_doc\": 3267.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 211.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1578.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 91274414.0, \"pat_granted\": 188.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 197.2, \"pub_doc\": 208.7, \"clinic_doc\": 3.7, \"grant_fund\": 10362532.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('7ff74ea978bce7cf516212de009e2504','3dd87ec4606ad304f7e661f044278af7','3fb1f33d12215e256dd98a72f66b746e','2023-09-08 01:32:52','2023-10-28 15:16:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Viral vector (gene) therapies','Oncolytic viruses',36,'An oncolytic virus is a virus that preferentially infects and kills cancer cells. As the infected cancer cells are destroyed by oncolysis, they release new infectious virus particles or virions to help destroy the remaining tumour. Oncolytic viruses are thought not only to cause direct destruction of the tumour cells, but also to stimulate host anti-tumour immune system responses. Oncolytic viruses also have the ability to affect the tumor micro-environment in multiple ways. The potential of viruses as anti-cancer agents was first realised in the early twentieth century, although coordinated research efforts did not begin until the 1960s. A number of viruses including adenovirus, reovirus, measles, herpes simplex, Newcastle disease virus, and vaccinia have been clinically tested as oncolytic agents. Most current oncolytic viruses are engineered for tumour selectivity, although there are naturally occurring examples such as reovirus and the senecavirus, resulting in clinical trials.','{\"pat_doc\": 554.0, \"pub_alt\": 756.0, \"pub_doc\": 966.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 83.0, \"clinic_alt\": 130.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 24519175.0, \"pat_granted\": 67.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 26.2, \"pub_doc\": 4.4, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": -7924828.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('802a3c43817a0f4787f0ebdd4e7610ee','f47c085ebbd53aee312f00db0891448f','a2144b71351e9696db283cb552418a4f','2023-09-04 19:34:56','2023-10-29 06:01:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Monitoring System',36,'A monitoring system is a tool used to continuously track the status and performance of a particular process, network, or system. It helps detect and alert users of any abnormalities, errors, or threats in real-time, allowing them to quickly respond before any significant damage is done. The system collects data from various sources, such as sensors, servers, and applications, before analyzing and communicating the results to the user interface. This process enables operators to identify trends, isolate problems, and make informed decisions about necessary actions. In short, a monitoring system provides visibility, control, and optimization over a systems performance and security.','{\"pat_doc\": 84770.0, \"pub_alt\": 1928.0, \"pub_doc\": 31637.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1490.0, \"clinic_alt\": 428.0, \"clinic_doc\": 701.0, \"grant_fund\": 763611021.0, \"pat_granted\": 35169.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 794.4, \"pub_doc\": 681.4, \"clinic_doc\": 89.9, \"grant_fund\": -66984808.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8100c5e397de385873c7c04546602275','382772c54fc63869435b590e8d1111c4','43d3334d4623a18878a471a105e8c82e','2023-09-08 00:27:07','2023-10-28 16:21:14','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Pheochromocytoma',48,'Pheochromocytoma is a rare tumor of the adrenal medulla composed of chromaffin cells, also known as pheochromocytes. When a tumor composed of the same cells as a pheochromocytoma develops outside the adrenal gland, it is referred to as a paraganglioma. These neuroendocrine tumors typically release massive amounts of catecholamines, metanephrines, or methoxytyramine, which result in the most common symptoms, including hypertension, tachycardia, and diaphoresis. Rarely, some tumors may secrete little to no catecholamines, making diagnosis difficult. While tumors of the head and neck are parasympathetic, their sympathetic counterparts are predominantly located in the abdomen and pelvis, particularly concentrated at the organ of Zuckerkandl.','{\"pat_doc\": 58.0, \"pub_alt\": 288.0, \"pub_doc\": 3840.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_alt\": 312.0, \"clinic_doc\": 120.0, \"grant_fund\": 21163213.0, \"pat_granted\": 22.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.4, \"pub_doc\": 22.8, \"clinic_doc\": 17.8, \"grant_fund\": -4557007.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('82198cfd2e1d4cd5a764d39b58a3ff1c','bcba00ed6e680440a1ab86723a027c98','9c021c3d61d0f8b13421b316b3cb4987','2023-09-05 22:27:22','2023-10-29 03:11:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','DNA Sequencing',36,'DNA sequencing is the process of determining the nucleic acid sequence â€“ the order of nucleotides in DNA. It includes any method or technology that is used to determine the order of the four bases: adenine, guanine, cytosine, and thymine. The advent of rapid DNA sequencing methods has greatly accelerated biological and medical research and discovery. Knowledge of DNA sequences has become indispensable for basic biological research, DNA Genographic Projects and in numerous applied fields such as medical diagnosis, biotechnology, forensic biology, virology and biological systematics. Comparing healthy and mutated DNA sequences can diagnose different diseases including various cancers, characterize antibody repertoire, and can be used to guide patient treatment. Having a quick way to sequence DNA allows for faster and more individualized medical care to be administered, and for more organisms to be identified and cataloged.','{\"pat_doc\": 907.0, \"pub_alt\": 6178.0, \"pub_doc\": 8645.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 680.0, \"clinic_alt\": 61.0, \"clinic_doc\": 169.0, \"grant_fund\": 360920532.0, \"pat_granted\": 314.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -8.7, \"pub_doc\": -57.5, \"clinic_doc\": 29.0, \"grant_fund\": -30361904.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('821d3b0e27a61da3ed5c442c098697a5','d9d824a70a843cb14f452ee5dfe90190','1c2b4adda3013a6c23af8f23b2fc3d3e','2023-09-08 00:45:08','2023-10-28 11:45:32','Electronics','Devices','Immersive Experience','head-mounted display',24,'A head-mounted display is a display device, worn on the head or as part of a helmet, that has a small display optic in front of one or each eye. An HMD has many uses including gaming, aviation, engineering, and medicine. Virtual reality headsets are HMDs combined with IMUs. There is also an optical head-mounted display, which is a wearable display that can reflect projected images and allows a user to see through it.','{\"pat_doc\": 4213.0, \"pub_alt\": 597.0, \"pub_doc\": 1447.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 36.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 62.0, \"grant_fund\": 5682112.0, \"pat_granted\": 1546.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 37.6, \"pub_doc\": 37.6, \"clinic_doc\": 11.9, \"grant_fund\": -2029094.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('825edc5076aa927a3bf89a0ef0cc7b7f','e1fcd3b18c69467f559b50097886167b','a2b94a39823e51d1e7bb659a1415d3c3','2023-09-08 00:31:20','2023-10-29 01:26:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Biocatalysis',24,'Biocatalysis refers to the use of living systems or their parts to speed up chemical reactions. In biocatalytic processes, natural catalysts, such as enzymes, perform chemical transformations on organic compounds. Both enzymes that have been more or less isolated and enzymes still residing inside living cells are employed for this task. Modern biotechnology, specifically directed evolution, has made the production of modified or non-natural enzymes possible. This has enabled the development of enzymes that can catalyze novel small molecule transformations that may be difficult or impossible using classical synthetic organic chemistry. Utilizing natural or modified enzymes to perform organic synthesis is termed chemoenzymatic synthesis; the reactions performed by the enzyme are classified as chemoenzymatic reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 345.0, \"pub_alt\": 266.0, \"pub_doc\": 1407.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 148.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 86901043.0, \"pat_granted\": 131.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 32.8, \"pub_doc\": 44.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 8603575.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('82cfd04944694f7246f8bd8faf870e98','5421c4aba6fdcb923ad6893affebb649','ad96306f7a3e23d74408bb23ac8e0e9a','2023-09-08 09:55:35','2023-10-28 19:56:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Near-infrared imaging',36,'Near-infrared (NIR) imaging refers to a technique in which light in the near-infrared spectrum is used to create images of biological specimens. This technique is popular in the medical field, especially in cancer diagnosis and treatment. NIR light penetrates deeper into biological tissues than visible light and is absorbed by various molecules, including water, lipids, and proteins. By measuring the reflected or absorbed light, NIR imaging allows for the detection of abnormalities such as tumors. NIR imaging is non-invasive, fast, and does not require ionizing radiation, making it a safer alternative to other imaging techniques. It also has potential applications in areas such as agriculture, food, and environmental monitoring.','{\"pat_doc\": 109.0, \"pub_alt\": 876.0, \"pub_doc\": 393.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 9.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 28.0, \"grant_fund\": 3842430.0, \"pat_granted\": 35.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.8, \"pub_doc\": 0.6, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": -73702.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('82d20ebf9f387ddbb36245db66140574','68e5caa32ed7e67484689ef37c744a39','8d40644b6dad0c0cd4481b73c097825b','2023-09-05 20:56:55','2023-10-29 04:16:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Bioreactor',24,'A bioreactor refers to any manufactured device or system that supports a biologically active environment. In one case, a bioreactor is a vessel in which a chemical process is carried out which involves organisms or biochemically active substances derived from such organisms. This process can either be aerobic or anaerobic. These bioreactors are commonly cylindrical, ranging in size from litres to cubic metres, and are often made of stainless steel. It may also refer to a device or system designed to grow cells or tissues in the context of cell culture. These devices are being developed for use in tissue engineering or biochemical/bioprocess engineering. On the basis of mode of operation, a bioreactor may be classified as batch, fed batch or continuous. An example of a continuous bioreactor is the chemostat. Organisms or biochemically active substances growing in bioreactors may be submerged in liquid medium or may be anchored to the surface of a solid medium.','{\"pat_doc\": 5895.0, \"pub_alt\": 2313.0, \"pub_doc\": 7931.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 536.0, \"clinic_alt\": 24.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 266521105.0, \"pat_granted\": 2449.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 47.6, \"pub_doc\": 42.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -17747789.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('838838666c41b7da695d440d260dbb06','1fccc88a9353a2b047cbe302f41187a4','e935f5dfeb3e4ae65d7860e4ea27b605','2023-09-05 20:23:19','2023-10-28 12:45:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Societal & Economic Disruptions','Post-COVID-19',48,'The concept of Post-COVID-19 refers to the scenario and circumstances following the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic. The world after COVID-19 is expected to be markedly different, with changes in the way people work, travel, socialize, and interact with each other. These changes may include a greater emphasis on remote work, increased use of technology for communication, more flexible working arrangements, significant shifts in consumer behavior, and a focus on public health and hygiene. The pandemic has also highlighted the importance of international cooperation and sustainable development, leading to the adoption of new policies aimed at creating a more resilient and equitable world. Ultimately, the post-COVID-19 era represents both an opportunity and a challenge for businesses, governments, and individuals to adapt and thrive in a rapidly changing world.','{\"pat_doc\": 32.0, \"pub_alt\": 24451.0, \"pub_doc\": 12082.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 368.0, \"clinic_alt\": 244.0, \"clinic_doc\": 290.0, \"grant_fund\": 88900074.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.4, \"pub_doc\": 1295.8, \"clinic_doc\": 64.2, \"grant_fund\": -5280894.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8399a0cafb4941a3f3bbaf199a2d5518','bcba00ed6e680440a1ab86723a027c98','9c021c3d61d0f8b13421b316b3cb4987','2023-09-05 22:27:22','2023-10-29 03:11:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','DNA Sequencing',12,'DNA sequencing is the process of determining the nucleic acid sequence â€“ the order of nucleotides in DNA. It includes any method or technology that is used to determine the order of the four bases: adenine, guanine, cytosine, and thymine. The advent of rapid DNA sequencing methods has greatly accelerated biological and medical research and discovery. Knowledge of DNA sequences has become indispensable for basic biological research, DNA Genographic Projects and in numerous applied fields such as medical diagnosis, biotechnology, forensic biology, virology and biological systematics. Comparing healthy and mutated DNA sequences can diagnose different diseases including various cancers, characterize antibody repertoire, and can be used to guide patient treatment. Having a quick way to sequence DNA allows for faster and more individualized medical care to be administered, and for more organisms to be identified and cataloged.','{\"pat_doc\": 272.0, \"pub_alt\": 6178.0, \"pub_doc\": 2743.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 127.0, \"clinic_alt\": 59.0, \"clinic_doc\": 125.0, \"grant_fund\": 63858065.0, \"pat_granted\": 94.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -8.7, \"pub_doc\": -57.5, \"clinic_doc\": 29.0, \"grant_fund\": -30361904.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('839a9f8e785e8e215ccce53d1647418b','e8e3ae6a8794d6acab5085e68542cec5','c89ffe68cd3a23332175ee5b50bcf229','2023-09-05 21:41:00','2023-10-28 12:20:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Quantum computing',12,'A quantum computer is a computer that exploits quantum mechanical phenomena. At small scales, physical matter exhibits properties of both particles and waves, and quantum computing leverages this behavior, specifically quantum superposition and entanglement, using specialized hardware that supports the preparation and manipulation of quantum states. Classical physics cannot explain the operation of these quantum devices, and a scalable quantum computer could perform some calculations exponentially faster than any modern \"classical\" computer. In particular, a large-scale quantum computer could break widely used encryption schemes and aid physicists in performing physical simulations; however, the current state of the art is largely experimental and impractical, with several obstacles to useful applications. Moreover, scalable quantum computers do not hold promise for many practical tasks, and for many important tasks quantum speedups are proven impossible.','{\"pat_doc\": 1415.0, \"pub_alt\": 1038.0, \"pub_doc\": 3818.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 379.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 408414926.0, \"pat_granted\": 423.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 329.1, \"pub_doc\": 695.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": 9235870.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('83ba64f3b4de05d7d86cf76206e2aebd','90f1f351860541863718a68f1e2fe5b6','7a49c80d1b80fc15aa79d84c9b4afdbb','2023-09-05 22:29:10','2023-10-28 17:21:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Natural killer cells',24,'Natural killer cells, also known as NK cells or large granular lymphocytes, are a type of cytotoxic lymphocyte critical to the innate immune system that belong to the rapidly expanding family of known innate lymphoid cells and represent 5â€“20% of all circulating lymphocytes in humans. The role of NK cells is analogous to that of cytotoxic T cells in the vertebrate adaptive immune response. NK cells provide rapid responses to virus-infected cell and other intracellular pathogens acting at around 3 days after infection, and respond to tumor formation. Typically, immune cells detect the antigen presented on major histocompatibility complex on infected cell surfaces, triggering cytokine release, causing the death of the infected cell by lysis or apoptosis. NK cells are unique, however, as they have the ability to recognize and kill stressed cells in the absence of antibodies and MHC, allowing for a much faster immune reaction.','{\"pat_doc\": 846.0, \"pub_alt\": 1026.0, \"pub_doc\": 2425.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 78.0, \"clinic_alt\": 200.0, \"clinic_doc\": 167.0, \"grant_fund\": 20430799.0, \"pat_granted\": 154.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 32.0, \"pub_doc\": 58.8, \"clinic_doc\": 29.4, \"grant_fund\": -4654238.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('83bd53b476520c866a590867965ff9a4','c24a789d6d92253253ff9f90dc646a7a','774a346d62790e44d654b1f21ecba973','2023-09-07 23:48:38','2023-10-29 02:26:21','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Single-Cell Analysis',24,'In the field of cellular biology, single-cell analysis is the study of genomics, transcriptomics, proteomics, metabolomics and cellâ€“cell interactions at the single cell level. The concept of single-cell analysis originated in the 1970s. Before the discovery of heterogeneity, single-cell analysis mainly referred to the analysis or manipulation of an individual cell in a bulk population of cells at a particular condition using optical or electronic microscope. To date, due to the heterogeneity seen in both eukaryotic and prokaryotic cell populations, analyzing a single cell makes it possible to discover mechanisms not seen when studying a bulk population of cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 86.0, \"pub_alt\": 770.0, \"pub_doc\": 1418.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 143.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 47005646.0, \"pat_granted\": 5.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.4, \"pub_doc\": 102.1, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": -19310396.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('83d83dbfab8aa36b0b7f91470724ac56','3c51150cb4d6d0c2bbf77b25519de393','6de0c721cf3eb4c836d007670b4c702d','2023-09-08 00:28:32','2023-10-29 01:36:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Live Cell Imaging',36,'Live cell imaging is the study of living cells using time-lapse microscopy. It is used by scientists to obtain a better understanding of biological function through the study of cellular dynamics. Live cell imaging was pioneered in first decade of the 21th century. One of the first time-lapse microcinematographic films of cells ever made was made by Julius Ries, showing the fertilization and development of the sea urchin egg. Since then, several microscopy methods have been developed which allow researchers to study living cells in greater detail with less effort. A newer type of imaging utilizing quantum dots have been used as they are shown to be more stable. The development of holotomographic microscopy has disregarded phototoxicity and other staining-derived disadvantages by implementing digital staining based on cells refractive index.','{\"pat_doc\": 54.0, \"pub_alt\": 371.0, \"pub_doc\": 1165.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 294.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 135099758.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.4, \"pub_doc\": -16.3, \"clinic_doc\": -0.2, \"grant_fund\": -12558862.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('845fdafb53aab9ea16122f315ac5bafc','e1e875f09f9ac3cb516d1a52affa7c20','9ca5a3bb1439526aa869b8ae1a850da8','2024-01-18 11:38:52','2024-01-18 11:38:52','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Chromatography Detector',48,'In chemical analysis, chromatography is a laboratory technique for the separation of a mixture into its components. The mixture is dissolved in a fluid solvent (gas or liquid) called the mobile phase, which carries it through a system (a column, a capillary tube, a plate, or a sheet) on which a material called the stationary phase is fixed.','{\"pat_doc\": 88.0, \"pub_alt\": 2.0, \"pub_doc\": 16.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 430882.0, \"pat_granted\": 51.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": -1.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 43088.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8473dc863df2b2b95ef56670fa02d34b','adc255a75abbc6dc9e8c5d454e86dad3','da6fc92b2753b0e9a72b21f2c514a42d','2023-09-08 00:04:14','2023-10-29 02:06:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Smart material',36,'Smart materials, also called intelligent or responsive materials, are designed materials that have one or more properties that can be significantly changed in a controlled fashion by external stimuli, such as stress, moisture, electric or magnetic fields, light, temperature, pH, or chemical compounds. Smart materials are the basis of many applications, including sensors and actuators, or artificial muscles, particularly as electroactive polymers. Terms used to describe smart materials include shape memory material and shape memory technology.','{\"pat_doc\": 149.0, \"pub_alt\": 394.0, \"pub_doc\": 10738.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 264.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 110398278.0, \"pat_granted\": 55.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -2.5, \"pub_doc\": 844.3, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -20872158.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8491e5dbc66b7d624bda270ff26a4e24','047522bba3b34e3fc4e040441987ea79','f7fd5614f8eb7d0dc72ab27f1dc2ffa2','2023-09-08 01:19:33','2023-10-28 11:30:33','Electronics','Components','Transfer Devices','Optical interconnect',12,'In integrated circuits, optical interconnects refers to any system of transmitting signals from one part of an integrated circuit to another using light. Optical interconnects have been the topic of study due to the high latency and power consumption incurred by conventional metal interconnects in transmitting electrical signals over long distances, such as in interconnects classed as global interconnects. The International Technology Roadmap for Semiconductors has highlighted interconnect scaling as a problem for the semiconductor industry. In electrical interconnects, nonlinear signals are transmitted by copper wires conventionally, and these electrical wires all have resistance and capacitance which severely limits the rise time of signals when the dimension of the wires are scaled down. Optical solution are used to transmit signals through long distances to substitute interconnection between dies within the integrated circuit package.','{\"pat_doc\": 215.0, \"pub_alt\": 238.0, \"pub_doc\": 286.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 16.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 15492141.0, \"pat_granted\": 58.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 24.2, \"pub_doc\": -0.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -665738.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('851d2c50315fe9d421717ab9a44c6233','cb426d718331f51011984ab644408b3c','b10c3992ebb8f463a7fad145792de043','2023-09-08 09:16:19','2023-10-28 21:11:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Liquid Chromatography',12,'Liquid chromatography (LC) is a widely used separation technique to isolate, identify, and quantify various components within a mixture. It works on the principle of differential partitioning of sample components between a mobile phase (liquid) and stationary phase (solid or liquid). The sample is introduced into the mobile phase, which is pumped through the stationary phase packed inside a column. The interaction between sample components and stationary phase determines the retention time and separation of individual components. Various types of liquid chromatography, such as high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC), ultra-high-performance liquid chromatography (UHPLC), and size exclusion chromatography (SEC), are available to separate different types of analytes based on their physicochemical properties. LC is widely used in the pharmaceutical, biotechnology, food, and environmental testing industries due to its high resolution, accuracy, and sensitivity.','{\"pat_doc\": 4245.0, \"pub_alt\": 1833.0, \"pub_doc\": 16530.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 183.0, \"clinic_alt\": 68.0, \"clinic_doc\": 277.0, \"grant_fund\": 42790521.0, \"pat_granted\": 1591.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 443.5, \"pub_doc\": 370.3, \"clinic_doc\": 60.7, \"grant_fund\": -16962097.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('85b31b4941ab398632755520bed576f3','9d996765d8494cce256222ac0a94a875','c98801edf863685348c2c0b17f91ca87','2023-09-07 23:53:35','2023-10-28 16:56:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Hyperthyroidism',12,'Hyperthyroidism is the condition that occurs due to excessive production of thyroid hormones by the thyroid gland. Thyrotoxicosis is the condition that occurs due to excessive thyroid hormone of any cause and therefore includes hyperthyroidism. Some, however, use the terms interchangeably. Signs and symptoms vary between people and may include irritability, muscle weakness, sleeping problems, a fast heartbeat, heat intolerance, diarrhea, enlargement of the thyroid, hand tremor, and weight loss. Symptoms are typically less severe in the elderly and during pregnancy. An uncommon but life-threatening complication is thyroid storm in which an event such as an infection results in worsening symptoms such as confusion and a high temperature; this often results in death. The opposite is hypothyroidism, when the thyroid gland does not make enough thyroid hormone. Graves disease is the cause of about 50% to 80% of the cases of hyperthyroidism in the United States.','{\"pat_doc\": 25.0, \"pub_alt\": 362.0, \"pub_doc\": 1494.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 22.0, \"clinic_doc\": 105.0, \"grant_fund\": 79500.0, \"pat_granted\": 11.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -7.0, \"pub_doc\": 88.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": -513561.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('85b9fbb8fef27c5ea9cf3e891787d873','794ef6eb4705d90aa18415f5e5a2779f','7b7c2d14c4ce8d4f609c2918b205a47e','2023-09-08 09:38:47','2023-10-28 20:51:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Thermogravimetric Analysis',24,'Thermogravimetric analysis or thermal gravimetric analysis is a method of thermal analysis in which the mass of a sample is measured over time as the temperature changes. This measurement provides information about physical phenomena, such as phase transitions, absorption, adsorption and desorption; as well as chemical phenomena including chemisorptions, thermal decomposition, and solid-gas reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 369.0, \"pub_alt\": 423.0, \"pub_doc\": 11375.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 38.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 3043763.0, \"pat_granted\": 90.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 32.3, \"pub_doc\": 123.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -985255.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('85d9073aa0d5b7a0befa39b1ef0dc67c','c9c8d2e4c7e139d539bc510be3e5f7ac','e9be6c0a64d57a69a37703624e73b1fd','2023-09-08 01:22:43','2023-10-29 00:16:22','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','Cell Isolation',48,'Cell isolation is the process of separating individual living cells from a solid block of tissue or cell suspension. While some types of cell naturally exist in a separated form, other cell types that are found in solid tissue require specific techniques to separate them into individual cells. This may be performed by using enzymes to digest the proteins that binds these cells together within the extracellular matrix. After the matrix proteins have been digested, cells remain loosely bound together but can be gently separated mechanically. Following isolation, experiments can be performed on these single isolated cells including patch clamp electrophysiology, calcium fluorescence imaging, and immunocytochemistry.','{\"pat_doc\": 308.0, \"pub_alt\": 217.0, \"pub_doc\": 1032.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 141.0, \"clinic_alt\": 5.0, \"clinic_doc\": 35.0, \"grant_fund\": 55220106.0, \"pat_granted\": 100.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -2.2, \"pub_doc\": 0.4, \"clinic_doc\": 4.9, \"grant_fund\": -1507208.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('866e857b3431a8160e35e2a83ff75227','d893c2f2b521b2e83577694191a8eee4','8f14a9e350509c9aa1906cf48eaa7e87','2023-09-08 02:28:18','2023-10-28 22:11:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Water Purification System',12,'A water purification system is a device or process that removes impurities, contaminants, and other pollutants from water to make it safe for consumption. It typically involves several stages, such as sedimentation, filtration, disinfection, and sometimes reverse osmosis. These processes help to eliminate harmful bacteria, viruses, chemicals, and minerals while improving the taste and clarity of the water. Water purification systems may be utilized in households, hospitals, industries, and municipalities to ensure safe drinking water and maintain health and hygiene. The systems effectiveness depends on the quality of water being treated and the specific technology or technique used. Proper maintenance and regular monitoring are also critical to maintain its efficiency.','{\"pat_doc\": 576.0, \"pub_alt\": 324.0, \"pub_doc\": 90.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 1559878.0, \"pat_granted\": 309.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -46.1, \"pub_doc\": 9.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.4, \"grant_fund\": -471630.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('869bdadb8f75e07ea88019b32a04629e','dfe596d300e59da2f75df75fd3120d54','a73d74823ba2a6c69ad94ff6d93ed919','2023-09-08 01:42:12','2023-10-28 15:06:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia',24,'Congenital adrenal hyperplasia is a group of autosomal recessive disorders characterized by impaired cortisol synthesis. It results from the deficiency of one of the five enzymes required for the synthesis of cortisol in the adrenal cortex. Most of these disorders involve excessive or deficient production of hormones such as glucocorticoids, mineralocorticoids, or sex steroids, and can alter development of primary or secondary sex characteristics in some affected infants, children, or adults. It is one of the most common autosomal recessive disorders in humans.','{\"pat_doc\": 105.0, \"pub_alt\": 74.0, \"pub_doc\": 746.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 9.0, \"clinic_alt\": 700.0, \"clinic_doc\": 47.0, \"grant_fund\": 1274915.0, \"pat_granted\": 9.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.4, \"pub_doc\": 1.7, \"clinic_doc\": 5.2, \"grant_fund\": -549349.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('86df61beaf8a1e5cb24c57ae6a4100ac','8fbcc1f9eedaac7f718565fe8c77f942','db8b9e3ac816571bb88d6adb6207c374','2023-09-08 10:03:44','2023-10-28 19:16:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Microbiological assay',48,'Microbiological assay is a type of analytical technique used in biochemistry and microbiology to determine the concentration of a particular substance by measuring the growth response of microorganisms to varying levels of the substance. In this assay, a known quantity of a microorganism is inoculated into a series of test tubes containing different concentrations of the substance being tested. The growth response of the microorganism is then measured and compared to a set of standard concentrations of the substance to determine the relative concentration in the sample being tested. Microbiological assays are widely used in the pharmaceutical industry to determine the potency of drugs and antibiotics, and in the food industry to measure the nutritional value of food products.','{\"pat_doc\": 52.0, \"pub_alt\": 80.0, \"pub_doc\": 312.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 32.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 19735604.0, \"pat_granted\": 39.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.0, \"pub_doc\": -7.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.4, \"grant_fund\": -3518570.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8740e9291bd99de41a42a9418f0759db','b7fe7c9d15ecc10608a0a70e65bacf5e','1c1aa7729e1e2fdd7a421fd9a7014e0a','2023-09-05 19:45:22','2023-10-28 12:50:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Augmented reality',36,'Augmented reality is an interactive experience that combines the real world and computer-generated content. The content can span multiple sensory modalities, including visual, auditory, haptic, somatosensory and olfactory. AR can be defined as a system that incorporates three basic features: a combination of real and virtual worlds, real-time interaction, and accurate 3D registration of virtual and real objects. The overlaid sensory information can be constructive, or destructive. This experience is seamlessly interwoven with the physical world such that it is perceived as an immersive aspect of the real environment. In this way, augmented reality alters ones ongoing perception of a real-world environment, whereas virtual reality completely replaces the users real-world environment with a simulated one. Augmented reality is largely synonymous with mixed reality. There is also overlap in terminology with extended reality and computer-mediated reality.','{\"pat_doc\": 23407.0, \"pub_alt\": 603.0, \"pub_doc\": 20169.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1276.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 200.0, \"grant_fund\": 616153250.0, \"pat_granted\": 7819.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 480.5, \"pub_doc\": 671.6, \"clinic_doc\": 35.2, \"grant_fund\": -13626091.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('88769438831736c9f8ac795c0cf0ea78','7286b6dd5e6f51fb279c0a6a82e528d2','4cfacc6752b10fbede9acf0bca84032d','2023-09-08 02:52:18','2023-10-28 21:21:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Line Culture',36,'Cell line culture refers to the process of growing and propagating cells in vitro, outside the organism from which they were derived. The cells are typically obtained from tissues or organs and are cultured in a laboratory using specialized techniques and growth media. Cell line cultures are used extensively in research, drug development, and biomedical applications to study cell behavior, cell function, and disease processes, among other things. They are an important tool for understanding the mechanisms of diseases and for developing new drugs and therapies. In addition, they offer a reliable and reproducible model system that is easily manipulated, making them an attractive option for a wide range of applications. Overall, cell line culture has revolutionized scientific research and is a critical tool in advancing medical knowledge and treatments.','{\"pat_doc\": 16.0, \"pub_alt\": 15.0, \"pub_doc\": 123.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 12.0, \"clinic_alt\": 4.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 1480527.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -149953.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('888d2a6aee031ecbe1ce1bb19066ff13','b6bd0e112ac4b84a4babc4781241a61c','eaab7bb973ab23e8de7a128f3cda6817','2023-09-08 00:05:29','2023-10-28 16:41:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Mesenchymal stromal cells',36,'Mesenchymal stem cells also known as mesenchymal stromal cells or medicinal signaling cells are multipotent stromal cells that can differentiate into a variety of cell types, including osteoblasts, chondrocytes, myocytes and adipocytes.','{\"pat_doc\": 224.0, \"pub_alt\": 495.0, \"pub_doc\": 3572.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 145.0, \"clinic_alt\": 190.0, \"clinic_doc\": 170.0, \"grant_fund\": 43834039.0, \"pat_granted\": 26.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": -47.2, \"clinic_doc\": 30.5, \"grant_fund\": -5473780.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('88939a207bc43a22927f468ff1572e14','402437da63ba33a83221799ab29cf95b','d511e8881547550871faef764cbfed18','2023-09-08 02:40:12','2023-10-28 21:56:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Sterilization Technique',36,'Sterilization technique involves the process of eliminating all forms of microorganisms and pathogens from a surface or object. This technique is used in medical facilities or laboratories to avoid the spread of infections or diseases. There are several sterilization methods, such as chemical sterilization, radiation sterilization, and physical sterilization. Chemical sterilization procedures involve the use of gases or liquids to get rid of bacteria or other microorganisms. Radiation sterilization involves the utilization of ionizing radiation to destroy pathogens, whereas physical sterilization involves the use of heat, pressure, or filtration to eliminate bacteria or other microorganisms. These sterilization techniques are essential in maintaining a sterile environment, which is crucial in medical facilities that perform surgeries or other sensitive procedures.','{\"pat_doc\": 63.0, \"pub_alt\": 506.0, \"pub_doc\": 186.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 9.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 1583809.0, \"pat_granted\": 41.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -5.0, \"pub_doc\": 3.3, \"clinic_doc\": -0.7, \"grant_fund\": 247564.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('88d253a79a56ea3a2f790e16a32cd325','94a11929f6fb7d9d93e190ab5230cb23','2874f833fd4f69190438aa7cb5f052b5','2023-09-05 20:19:29','2023-10-29 04:41:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Blockchain technology',12,'Blockchain technology is a distributed ledger technology that allows for secure, transparent and irreversible peer-to-peer transactions without the need for intermediaries. It is based on a decentralized network of nodes that validate transactions and add them to the blockchain, a public ledger of all transactions. Blockchain technology is essentially a digital ledger that records and stores data in a secure and transparent way. This makes it useful for a variety of applications, such as cryptocurrency, supply chain management, voting systems, and more. The technologys key features include decentralization, transparency, immutability, and security. Overall, blockchain technology has the potential to revolutionize multiple industries and enable new business models.','{\"pat_doc\": 1577.0, \"pub_alt\": 986.0, \"pub_doc\": 6511.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 34.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 23116312.0, \"pat_granted\": 609.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 306.0, \"pub_doc\": 1055.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -4560710.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('88d9bb3668f4921c9b478f3b0c023a1a','eee0d94d36c42e167a1a4be01f14392d','8c7694fa0bfc9847929f37bd7f31bd59','2023-09-04 19:48:49','2023-10-29 05:51:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','3D printing',24,'3D printing or additive manufacturing is the construction of a three-dimensional object from a CAD model or a digital 3D model. It can be done in a variety of processes in which material is deposited, joined or solidified under computer control, with the material being added together, typically layer by layer. In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping. As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology, whereby the term additive manufacturing can be used synonymously with 3D printing.','{\"pat_doc\": 19748.0, \"pub_alt\": 2627.0, \"pub_doc\": 17603.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1132.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 165.0, \"grant_fund\": 488051999.0, \"pat_granted\": 8881.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 434.0, \"pub_doc\": 1197.3, \"clinic_doc\": 23.8, \"grant_fund\": -8565739.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8904ca9bd2e870274cd20775c701c640','e8e3ae6a8794d6acab5085e68542cec5','c89ffe68cd3a23332175ee5b50bcf229','2023-09-05 21:41:00','2023-10-28 12:20:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Quantum computing',48,'A quantum computer is a computer that exploits quantum mechanical phenomena. At small scales, physical matter exhibits properties of both particles and waves, and quantum computing leverages this behavior, specifically quantum superposition and entanglement, using specialized hardware that supports the preparation and manipulation of quantum states. Classical physics cannot explain the operation of these quantum devices, and a scalable quantum computer could perform some calculations exponentially faster than any modern \"classical\" computer. In particular, a large-scale quantum computer could break widely used encryption schemes and aid physicists in performing physical simulations; however, the current state of the art is largely experimental and impractical, with several obstacles to useful applications. Moreover, scalable quantum computers do not hold promise for many practical tasks, and for many important tasks quantum speedups are proven impossible.','{\"pat_doc\": 3671.0, \"pub_alt\": 1038.0, \"pub_doc\": 11075.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2169.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 1581342055.0, \"pat_granted\": 967.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 329.1, \"pub_doc\": 695.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": 9235870.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('890503612ebd58b3d0e85f7bf794bd7b','33e3b46112ca032f374d6e6e96ae9ab3','96ff1b7975967b788c2beb91534beb0f','2023-09-05 20:50:48','2023-10-28 17:56:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Exosomes',24,'Exosomes are small membrane vesicles, typically with a diameter of 30-150 nm, that are secreted by many types of mammalian cells and are found in a variety of body fluids such as blood, urine, and breast milk. They are thought to play a role in intercellular communication and in some cases can transfer proteins, lipids, and genetic material between cells. Exosomes originate from the endosomal compartment of the cell and are formed by the inward budding of the membrane to create intraluminal vesicles. Once formed, the exosomes are released from the cell through fusion with the plasma membrane or phagocytosis by other cells. The content of exosomes can vary depending on the cell type and physiological conditions, and there is growing interest in their use as biomarkers for disease diagnosis and as potential therapeutic agents.','{\"pat_doc\": 3445.0, \"pub_alt\": 18945.0, \"pub_doc\": 9279.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 508.0, \"clinic_alt\": 97.0, \"clinic_doc\": 283.0, \"grant_fund\": 130000531.0, \"pat_granted\": 831.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 265.2, \"pub_doc\": 279.4, \"clinic_doc\": 55.8, \"grant_fund\": -46753820.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('893b628a7d3df31871e5a4e5561a2807','9ae996f0d6bbaff7b400a3648677eeaf','f79d0c4233733c41a41b0769be4ec44f','2023-09-08 01:43:30','2023-10-28 11:25:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Heterogeneous Integration',24,'Heterogeneous Integration refers to the process of combining different types of materials, devices, components, or functions into a single system or package. It involves the use of various technologies to create complex systems that can perform multiple functions using different components integrated together. This process enables the creation of new products, systems, and services with improved features, performance, and flexibility. The main benefits of heterogeneous integration include reduced cost, improved system performance, and increased connectivity and functionality. This approach is widely used in the development of advanced microprocessors, wireless communication devices, sensors and actuators, and other high-tech products. By integrating various components with different functionalities, manufacturers can achieve compact, high-performance systems that meet the demands of modern applications.','{\"pat_doc\": 249.0, \"pub_alt\": 288.0, \"pub_doc\": 673.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 103.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 106890808.0, \"pat_granted\": 70.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 24.9, \"pub_doc\": 44.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 9542163.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('89a143eacc728d2da07abeef0e26f958','7817ed2cad0c9306c26e32a11da07b14','191b41c4706125327318783808a1e02d','2023-09-07 23:52:24','2023-10-28 17:01:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Bioconjugates','Antibody Drug Conjugates',36,'Antibody-drug conjugates or ADCs are a class of biopharmaceutical drugs designed as a targeted therapy for treating cancer. Unlike chemotherapy, ADCs are intended to target and kill tumor cells while sparing healthy cells. As of 2019, some 56 pharmaceutical companies were developing ADCs. ADCs are complex molecules composed of an antibody linked to a biologically active cytotoxic payload or drug. Antibody-drug conjugates are an example of bioconjugates and immunoconjugates. ADCs combine the targeting properties of monoclonal antibodies with the cancer-killing capabilities of cytotoxic drugs, designed to discriminate between healthy and diseased tissue.','{\"pat_doc\": 1240.0, \"pub_alt\": 337.0, \"pub_doc\": 394.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 25.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 13742673.0, \"pat_granted\": 241.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": 18.3, \"clinic_doc\": 2.1, \"grant_fund\": -1636318.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8a3d443fa84d2a9e5992bfd5c536b618','9d996765d8494cce256222ac0a94a875','c98801edf863685348c2c0b17f91ca87','2023-09-07 23:53:35','2023-10-28 16:56:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Hyperthyroidism',48,'Hyperthyroidism is the condition that occurs due to excessive production of thyroid hormones by the thyroid gland. Thyrotoxicosis is the condition that occurs due to excessive thyroid hormone of any cause and therefore includes hyperthyroidism. Some, however, use the terms interchangeably. Signs and symptoms vary between people and may include irritability, muscle weakness, sleeping problems, a fast heartbeat, heat intolerance, diarrhea, enlargement of the thyroid, hand tremor, and weight loss. Symptoms are typically less severe in the elderly and during pregnancy. An uncommon but life-threatening complication is thyroid storm in which an event such as an infection results in worsening symptoms such as confusion and a high temperature; this often results in death. The opposite is hypothyroidism, when the thyroid gland does not make enough thyroid hormone. Graves disease is the cause of about 50% to 80% of the cases of hyperthyroidism in the United States.','{\"pat_doc\": 162.0, \"pub_alt\": 1393.0, \"pub_doc\": 5534.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 53.0, \"clinic_alt\": 28.0, \"clinic_doc\": 288.0, \"grant_fund\": 6710614.0, \"pat_granted\": 72.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -7.0, \"pub_doc\": 88.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": -513561.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8a6ca58dc1fbc8081e3c5f43f3918088','666869b3162af8fad5a5b7d07b2312c9','f268e5ab79c5a1d38ab08daccf7ee951','2023-09-08 01:48:42','2023-10-28 11:10:32','Electronics','Components','Processing Devices','Neuromorphic Hardware',24,'Neuromorphic hardware is a type of computer hardware that is inspired by the workings of the human brain. Unlike traditional hardware that uses a Von Neumann architecture where the processing and memory are separate, neuromorphic hardware combines both processing and memory in a single unit. This results in a more efficient way of computing, where information is processed in parallel, similar to how neurons work in the brain. Neuromorphic hardware is often used in applications that require low power consumption and real-time processing, such as robotics and autonomous vehicles. The technology has the potential to create highly advanced and intelligent systems, but there are still challenges to overcome, such as developing effective programming models and scaling up the hardware for larger applications. Nonetheless, neuromorphic hardware is an exciting and promising area of research that has the potential to revolutionize computing as we know it.','{\"pat_doc\": 52.0, \"pub_alt\": 645.0, \"pub_doc\": 570.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 35.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 30986191.0, \"pat_granted\": 16.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.9, \"pub_doc\": 33.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -50956752.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8a926251a0ef2ab3e69e87ecfe1a48c8','ad14e59d8d8e44865760de1a016459ca','15926313fb5354a8aa389bc294cbeab7','2023-09-05 20:43:37','2023-10-29 04:36:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein-Protein Interaction',36,'Proteinâ€“protein interactions are physical contacts of high specificity established between two or more protein molecules as a result of biochemical events steered by interactions that include electrostatic forces, hydrogen bonding and the hydrophobic effect. Many are physical contacts with molecular associations between chains that occur in a cell or in a living organism in a specific biomolecular context. Proteins rarely act alone as their functions tend to be regulated. Many molecular processes within a cell are carried out by molecular machines that are built from numerous protein components organized by their PPIs. These physiological interactions make up the so-called interactomics of the organism, while aberrant PPIs are the basis of multiple aggregation-related diseases, such as Creutzfeldtâ€“Jakob and Alzheimers diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 656.0, \"pub_alt\": 1773.0, \"pub_doc\": 15372.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 961.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 15.0, \"grant_fund\": 367883432.0, \"pat_granted\": 151.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.7, \"pub_doc\": 265.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.4, \"grant_fund\": -40776859.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8ad25d40783605614d3566bf1cf56a13','671b6a0797f6c4055d3d1b7f83353201','45aa22dbd0eeecd7a8f404b4dd4dc2cc','2023-09-08 02:41:52','2023-10-28 21:51:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Containment System',36,'A containment system is a structure or mechanism designed to isolate or control the spread of something potentially dangerous, such as disease, hazardous materials, or other substances. These systems come in various forms and sizes, depending on the nature of the threat and the environment they are used in. Examples can include sealed chambers, biosecurity measures, containment suits, or even something as simple as plastic barriers. The main goal of a containment system is to prevent the spread of the harmful agent to other areas or individuals, reducing the risk of harm and containing the situation until it can be properly addressed. They are particularly important in settings like laboratories, medical facilities, and industrial sites where potentially harmful materials or organisms may be present.','{\"pat_doc\": 893.0, \"pub_alt\": 33.0, \"pub_doc\": 224.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 12.0, \"clinic_alt\": 11.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 18733057.0, \"pat_granted\": 374.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -9.9, \"pub_doc\": 1.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.5, \"grant_fund\": -3150370.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8ae2407452f4d6bc92f8164a1446d9c1','3c2d35cb47d7e664ff6a420c7371c3f4','13d8c275545d800af0151763656e07e5','2023-09-05 19:14:04','2023-10-29 05:11:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Quantum dot',48,'Quantum dots â€“ also called semiconductor nanocrystals, are semiconductor particles a few nanometres in size, having optical and electronic properties that differ from those of larger particles as a result of quantum mechanics. They are a central topic in nanotechnology and materials science. When the quantum dots are illuminated by UV light, an electron in the quantum dot can be excited to a state of higher energy. In the case of a semiconducting quantum dot, this process corresponds to the transition of an electron from the valence band to the conductance band. The excited electron can drop back into the valence band releasing its energy as light. This light emission is illustrated in the figure on the right.','{\"pat_doc\": 22862.0, \"pub_alt\": 2664.0, \"pub_doc\": 32157.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1282.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 462203312.0, \"pat_granted\": 8482.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 59.8, \"pub_doc\": 330.7, \"clinic_doc\": 1.1, \"grant_fund\": -9612731.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8b003e6fcc5be9c932098bcb19b04aa8','9d996765d8494cce256222ac0a94a875','c98801edf863685348c2c0b17f91ca87','2023-09-07 23:53:35','2023-10-28 16:56:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Hyperthyroidism',24,'Hyperthyroidism is the condition that occurs due to excessive production of thyroid hormones by the thyroid gland. Thyrotoxicosis is the condition that occurs due to excessive thyroid hormone of any cause and therefore includes hyperthyroidism. Some, however, use the terms interchangeably. Signs and symptoms vary between people and may include irritability, muscle weakness, sleeping problems, a fast heartbeat, heat intolerance, diarrhea, enlargement of the thyroid, hand tremor, and weight loss. Symptoms are typically less severe in the elderly and during pregnancy. An uncommon but life-threatening complication is thyroid storm in which an event such as an infection results in worsening symptoms such as confusion and a high temperature; this often results in death. The opposite is hypothyroidism, when the thyroid gland does not make enough thyroid hormone. Graves disease is the cause of about 50% to 80% of the cases of hyperthyroidism in the United States.','{\"pat_doc\": 71.0, \"pub_alt\": 1393.0, \"pub_doc\": 2930.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 22.0, \"clinic_doc\": 175.0, \"grant_fund\": 1800294.0, \"pat_granted\": 28.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -7.0, \"pub_doc\": 88.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": -513561.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8b0edfd07a186b1f0a32ca1cc8194e63','19f291b8d80548406a90803fc4e33614','a3e69530e54da2bd3284f3d40c81f2e9','2023-09-08 02:13:20','2023-10-28 22:56:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Microarray',12,'A protein microarray is a high-throughput method used to track the interactions and activities of proteins, and to determine their function, and determining function on a large scale. Its main advantage lies in the fact that large numbers of proteins can be tracked in parallel. The chip consists of a support surface such as a glass slide, nitrocellulose membrane, bead, or microtitre plate, to which an array of capture proteins is bound. Probe molecules, typically labeled with a fluorescent dye, are added to the array. Any reaction between the probe and the immobilised protein emits a fluorescent signal that is read by a laser scanner. Protein microarrays are rapid, automated, economical, and highly sensitive, consuming small quantities of samples and reagents. The concept and methodology of protein microarrays was first introduced and illustrated in antibody microarrays in 1983 in a scientific publication and a series of patents.','{\"pat_doc\": 9.0, \"pub_alt\": 13.0, \"pub_doc\": 101.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 15.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 540849.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.4, \"pub_doc\": -10.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.6, \"grant_fund\": -222800.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8ba1e396d558d9f6bd4201463d25f56e','9be33f727d7b72fef24f5c1785693e63','968e5d71e0d0c5dc526e2a9156a8d9aa','2023-09-08 10:00:06','2023-10-28 19:31:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','supercritical fluid chromatography',36,'Supercritical fluid chromatography is a form of normal phase chromatography that uses a supercritical fluid such as carbon dioxide as the mobile phase. It is used for the analysis and purification of low to moderate molecular weight, thermally labile molecules and can also be used for the separation of chiral compounds. Principles are similar to those of high performance liquid chromatography, however SFC typically utilizes carbon dioxide as the mobile phase; therefore the entire chromatographic flow path must be pressurized. Because the supercritical phase represents a state in which liquid and gas properties converge, supercritical fluid chromatography is sometimes called convergence chromatography.','{\"pat_doc\": 157.0, \"pub_alt\": 270.0, \"pub_doc\": 449.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 16.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 2469703.0, \"pat_granted\": 74.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.0, \"pub_doc\": -10.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": -373175.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8bcca6e7cc369987d74346fec76aeb80','7cad47d8fa337e04fde87c8076f4adfe','25cc485513e0e2921857b91eeab511ae','2023-09-08 08:31:01','2023-10-28 13:41:15','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Colorectal cancer',12,'Colorectal cancer, also known as bowel cancer, colon cancer, or rectal cancer, is the development of cancer from the colon or rectum. Signs and symptoms may include blood in the stool, a change in bowel movements, weight loss, and fatigue. Most colorectal cancers are due to old age and lifestyle factors, with only a small number of cases due to underlying genetic disorders. Risk factors include diet, obesity, smoking, and lack of physical activity. Dietary factors that increase the risk include red meat, processed meat, and alcohol. Another risk factor is inflammatory bowel disease, which includes Crohns disease and ulcerative colitis. Some of the inherited genetic disorders that can cause colorectal cancer include familial adenomatous polyposis and hereditary non-polyposis colon cancer; however, these represent less than 5% of cases. It typically starts as a benign tumor, often in the form of a polyp, which over time becomes cancerous.','{\"pat_doc\": 1358.0, \"pub_alt\": 3750.0, \"pub_doc\": 15437.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 315.0, \"clinic_alt\": 699.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2244.0, \"grant_fund\": 154391370.0, \"pat_granted\": 384.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 91.4, \"pub_doc\": 499.3, \"clinic_doc\": 542.0, \"grant_fund\": -69281414.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8c20ab934021a51bf4cb5dc80421021d','86bfc1d6ea6ada0972bb4ebd56d88ad7','8f2884ac2f89f569ae690ad0aa820ccc','2023-09-08 01:08:24','2023-10-28 15:41:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Tumor-associated antigens',12,'Tumor-associated antigens (TAAs) are proteins that are present in cancer cells but not in normal cells or are expressed at higher levels in tumors than in healthy tissues. These antigens may be recognized by the immune system as foreign and trigger an immune response against the cancer cells. TAAs are being studied for their potential use in cancer vaccines and immunotherapy. However, many TAAs are also present in normal tissues, which can lead to side effects when targeted by cancer treatments. Therefore, the specificity of TAAs and their potential impact on healthy tissues must be carefully evaluated before their use in clinical settings.','{\"pat_doc\": 75.0, \"pub_alt\": 279.0, \"pub_doc\": 294.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 13.0, \"clinic_alt\": 504.0, \"clinic_doc\": 24.0, \"grant_fund\": 6568187.0, \"pat_granted\": 14.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.6, \"pub_doc\": 27.2, \"clinic_doc\": 6.4, \"grant_fund\": -3038596.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8ca271c056ce33349382e64f70702088','e7461a8ad3be85a4a9927a05f09da738','74dfdb3be3d296db4e284e57c8999ab7','2023-09-08 02:05:14','2023-10-28 23:11:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Primary Cell Culture',36,'Primary cell culture is the ex vivo culture of cells freshly obtained from a multicellular organism, as opposed to the culture of immortalized cell lines. In general, primary cell cultures are considered more representative of in vivo tissues than cell lines, and this is recognized legally in some countries such as the UK. However, primary cells require adequate substrate and nutrient conditions to thrive and after a certain number of divisions they acquire a senescent phenotype, leading to irreversible cell cycle arrest. The generation of cell lines stems from these two reasons. Primary cells can become immortalized either spontaneously or by genetic modification, at which point they become cell lines which can be subcultured indefinitely. Because of their requirements for viability, primary cell cultures did not become widespread until the 2000s.','{\"pat_doc\": 136.0, \"pub_alt\": 151.0, \"pub_doc\": 505.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 72.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.0, \"grant_fund\": 25435258.0, \"pat_granted\": 45.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 9.5, \"pub_doc\": -8.7, \"clinic_doc\": 2.5, \"grant_fund\": -4026979.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8d23aa1b87f5de590d18f51d6a733418','1e66ed53f01f8188292c5c3609da476b','a58988e9b10205f335d6db1eeecb2311','2023-09-08 02:46:06','2023-10-28 21:36:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Expression System',48,'A Protein Expression System is a method used to produce proteins for scientific research, pharmaceutical development, and other applications. The system involves introducing DNA fragments encoding the desired protein sequence into a host cell, which then uses its own cellular machinery to produce the protein. Common hosts for protein expression include bacteria, yeast, and mammalian cells, with each system offering its own advantages and limitations. This method allows for the production of large quantities of a specific protein, aiding in the study of its function and potential therapeutic properties.','{\"pat_doc\": 221.0, \"pub_alt\": 315.0, \"pub_doc\": 208.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 80.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 71921427.0, \"pat_granted\": 58.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.7, \"pub_doc\": 3.2, \"clinic_doc\": -0.2, \"grant_fund\": -14107859.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8d9eaaee58a2e0950bb0e0e6f1be945f','96a98502ddc2632768ff7919ec246022','d471ba9d05b4186943ade5d1a2ae30dc','2023-09-04 18:23:33','2023-10-29 07:06:12','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Mass Spectrometry',36,'Mass Spectrometry is a powerful analytical technique used in chemistry, biochemistry, and other scientific fields to identify molecules based on their mass-to-charge ratio (m/z). The process involves ionizing a sample, then separating the resulting ions based on their mass-to-charge ratio using electromagnetic fields. The ions are then detected and analyzed to determine their individual masses and concentrations. Mass spectrometry is used in many applications, including characterizing the structure of unknown compounds, identifying proteins and peptides, and tracking the movement of isotopes within molecules. It has become a standard tool in many areas of research, including drug discovery, environmental analysis, and forensic science.','{\"pat_doc\": 11672.0, \"pub_alt\": 13857.0, \"pub_doc\": 95329.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4607.0, \"clinic_alt\": 146.0, \"clinic_doc\": 658.0, \"grant_fund\": 1878444736.0, \"pat_granted\": 3738.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 210.2, \"pub_doc\": 879.4, \"clinic_doc\": 100.8, \"grant_fund\": -169513024.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8dd29fef0b7e4b5ac11a601d869000e1','6ee75b4e6fefbd3534f1769a0b6e2972','e27f505c9d666365d5d09dc9decf7e50','2023-09-05 21:10:38','2023-10-28 12:30:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','6G',12,'6G technology is the next-generation wireless communication technology that is under development and expected to be commercialized by 2030. It is said to be 100 times faster than 5G with higher reliability, low latency and more secure communication. 6G will enable high-speed internet connectivity and high-resolution video streaming. It will also support the Internet of Things (IoT), artificial intelligence (AI), machine learning (ML), and virtual reality (VR) technologies. The development of 6G technology is still in the early stages with some countries having already started research on the technology. However, it is expected to bring significant changes to the way we live and work to enable new products and services that will drive innovation across different industries.','{\"pat_doc\": 2824.0, \"pub_alt\": 955.0, \"pub_doc\": 7252.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 256.0, \"clinic_alt\": 34.0, \"clinic_doc\": 161.0, \"grant_fund\": 415442444.0, \"pat_granted\": 556.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 485.2, \"pub_doc\": 1244.7, \"clinic_doc\": 33.1, \"grant_fund\": 83405037.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8dd53a5f3e46bc39ea34a3c8243850bc','047522bba3b34e3fc4e040441987ea79','f7fd5614f8eb7d0dc72ab27f1dc2ffa2','2023-09-08 01:19:33','2023-10-28 11:30:33','Electronics','Components','Transfer Devices','Optical interconnect',36,'In integrated circuits, optical interconnects refers to any system of transmitting signals from one part of an integrated circuit to another using light. Optical interconnects have been the topic of study due to the high latency and power consumption incurred by conventional metal interconnects in transmitting electrical signals over long distances, such as in interconnects classed as global interconnects. The International Technology Roadmap for Semiconductors has highlighted interconnect scaling as a problem for the semiconductor industry. In electrical interconnects, nonlinear signals are transmitted by copper wires conventionally, and these electrical wires all have resistance and capacitance which severely limits the rise time of signals when the dimension of the wires are scaled down. Optical solution are used to transmit signals through long distances to substitute interconnection between dies within the integrated circuit package.','{\"pat_doc\": 558.0, \"pub_alt\": 238.0, \"pub_doc\": 829.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 62.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 34065884.0, \"pat_granted\": 163.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 24.2, \"pub_doc\": -0.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -665738.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8eb854d55a7c13116185e489ac7f428b','3cf46267ec47fde029e918d250b335a1','c26c7529dcbe3665be368505da21babe','2023-09-08 02:53:34','2023-10-28 13:56:10','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Nanobots',12,'Nanoid robotics, or for short, nanorobotics or nanobotics, is an emerging technology field creating machines or robots whose components are at or near the scale of a nanometer. More specifically, nanorobotics refers to the nanotechnology engineering discipline of designing and building nanorobots with devices ranging in size from 0.1 to 10 micrometres and constructed of nanoscale or molecular components. The terms nanobot, nanoid, nanite, nanomachine and nanomite have also been used to describe such devices currently under research and development. Nanomachines are largely in the research and development phase, but some primitive molecular machines and nanomotors have been tested. An example is a sensor having a switch approximately 1.5 nanometers across, able to count specific molecules in the chemical sample. The first useful applications of nanomachines may be in nanomedicine. For example, biological machines could be used to identify and destroy cancer cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 81.0, \"pub_doc\": 56.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 911879.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 11.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -619816.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8ed0349c4fb09e99deabda52c36b1b9b','68e5caa32ed7e67484689ef37c744a39','8d40644b6dad0c0cd4481b73c097825b','2023-09-05 20:56:55','2023-10-29 04:16:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Bioreactor',12,'A bioreactor refers to any manufactured device or system that supports a biologically active environment. In one case, a bioreactor is a vessel in which a chemical process is carried out which involves organisms or biochemically active substances derived from such organisms. This process can either be aerobic or anaerobic. These bioreactors are commonly cylindrical, ranging in size from litres to cubic metres, and are often made of stainless steel. It may also refer to a device or system designed to grow cells or tissues in the context of cell culture. These devices are being developed for use in tissue engineering or biochemical/bioprocess engineering. On the basis of mode of operation, a bioreactor may be classified as batch, fed batch or continuous. An example of a continuous bioreactor is the chemostat. Organisms or biochemically active substances growing in bioreactors may be submerged in liquid medium or may be anchored to the surface of a solid medium.','{\"pat_doc\": 2656.0, \"pub_alt\": 488.0, \"pub_doc\": 3900.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 174.0, \"clinic_alt\": 24.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 98093657.0, \"pat_granted\": 1008.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 47.6, \"pub_doc\": 42.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -17747789.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8ee8a510471e858c5c1552b113bc3d32','69a17d20e0dd95936b11c342f374274e','21412fd8c571a6c3727e6a6906b7c1a8','2023-09-08 02:19:08','2023-10-28 22:31:10','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Synthesis',12,'mRNA synthesis, also known as transcription, is a process that occurs in the nucleus of a cell whereby DNA is copied into a single strand of messenger RNA (mRNA). This process involves the separation of the two strands of DNA and the synthesizing of an mRNA strand using one of the DNA strands as a template. The mRNA formed during transcription will carry a genetic message from the DNA to the ribosome, where it will be translated into a protein. This process is a critical step in gene expression and the regulation of cellular processes. Defects in mRNA synthesis can lead to genetic disorders, developmental abnormalities, and diseases, making it an important area of study for geneticists and molecular biologists.','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_alt\": 714.0, \"pub_doc\": 61.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 610588.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.1, \"pub_doc\": 2.4, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -2023051.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8f0144b01482d522d863b68025584a56','2b6a132222106ddec0310c5473271c19','d16e559190b993e5f50fdc62d46eec9a','2023-09-08 09:58:57','2023-10-28 19:36:09','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Modification',24,'mRNA modification is a process that occurs after transcription but before translation. It refers to the chemical modifications of messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules in order to regulate their stability, localization, and translation efficiency. The most common type of mRNA modification is the addition of a 5â€™ cap, a modified guanine nucleotide, to the 5â€™ end of the mRNA molecule. This cap protects the mRNA from degradation and facilitates its translation. Another important mRNA modification is the addition of a poly(A) tail, a string of adenine nucleotides, to the 3â€™ end of the mRNA molecule. This tail also stabilizes the mRNA and enhances its translation. Other types of mRNA modifications include splicing, editing, and methylation, which can affect the sequence, structure, and function of the mRNA molecule. mRNA modification plays a critical role in gene expression regulation and is essential for cellular processes such as development, differentiation, and adaptation to environmental changes.','{\"pat_doc\": 6.0, \"pub_alt\": 182.0, \"pub_doc\": 289.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 24.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 7172376.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 16.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -6725984.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('8f0c669a5a6f51e4db168581e840edf2','074a886190f8a82396d29ea68958db61','e9ee3da8c5950eddf30d7e6a8d175388','2023-09-08 00:39:05','2023-10-29 01:16:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Protein Engineering',48,'Protein engineering is the process of developing useful or valuable proteins through the design and production of unnatural polypeptides, often by altering amino acid sequences found in nature. It is a young discipline, with much research taking place into the understanding of protein folding and recognition for protein design principles. It has been used to improve the function of many enzymes for industrial catalysis. It is also a product and services market, with an estimated value of $168 billion by 2017. There are two general strategies for protein engineering: rational protein design and directed evolution. These methods are not mutually exclusive; researchers will often apply both. In the future, more detailed knowledge of protein structure and function, and advances in high-throughput screening, may greatly expand the abilities of protein engineering.','{\"pat_doc\": 529.0, \"pub_alt\": 1312.0, \"pub_doc\": 2569.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 600.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 353011452.0, \"pat_granted\": 169.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.1, \"pub_doc\": 48.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -16048598.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9062fc7b2e84f01682326718d65bd2e8','c4e49c5cbafa19cbaf0a14bd5ddcb651','0b71467e6421c543859a81713b7406ad','2023-09-08 09:43:15','2023-10-28 20:41:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','sample preparation',48,'In analytical chemistry, sample preparation refers to the ways in which a sample is treated prior to its analyses. Preparation is a very important step in most analytical techniques, because the techniques are often not responsive to the analyte in its in-situ form, or the results are distorted by interfering species. Sample preparation may involve dissolution, extraction, reaction with some chemical species, pulverizing, treatment with a chelating agent, masking, filtering, dilution, sub-sampling or many other techniques. Treatment is done to prepare the sample into a form ready for analysis by specified analytical equipment. Sample preparation could involve: crushing and dissolution, chemical digestion with acid or alkali, sample extraction, sample clean up and sample pre-concentration.','{\"pat_doc\": 9363.0, \"pub_alt\": 3919.0, \"pub_doc\": 14634.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1136.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 71.0, \"grant_fund\": 459733183.0, \"pat_granted\": 4362.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 189.7, \"pub_doc\": 74.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.5, \"grant_fund\": -48834204.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('91bfa82d2c4049863216fa176c05a9b2','6272d8c4fefc516af912e39ce608f48b','f5961ebdecc3630bd05559901b09f90f','2023-09-08 01:50:58','2023-10-28 15:01:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Gene therapies (Non-viral)','Ribozyme',36,'Ribozymes are RNA molecules that have the ability to catalyze specific biochemical reactions, including RNA splicing in gene expression, similar to the action of protein enzymes. The 1982 discovery of ribozymes demonstrated that RNA can be both genetic material and a biological catalyst, and contributed to the RNA world hypothesis, which suggests that RNA may have been important in the evolution of prebiotic self-replicating systems. The most common activities of natural or in vitro evolved ribozymes are the cleavage of RNA and DNA and peptide bond formation. For example, the smallest ribozyme known can aminoacylate a GCCU-3 sequence in the presence of PheAMP. Within the ribosome, ribozymes function as part of the large subunit ribosomal RNA to link amino acids during protein synthesis. They also participate in a variety of RNA processing reactions, including RNA splicing, viral replication, and transfer RNA biosynthesis.','{\"pat_doc\": 334.0, \"pub_alt\": 1404.0, \"pub_doc\": 711.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 59.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 12377176.0, \"pat_granted\": 103.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 8.3, \"pub_doc\": -0.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.2, \"grant_fund\": -2009401.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9214be95fc37fbb6660271163f225ad2','1e66ed53f01f8188292c5c3609da476b','a58988e9b10205f335d6db1eeecb2311','2023-09-08 02:46:05','2023-10-28 21:36:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Expression System',24,'A Protein Expression System is a method used to produce proteins for scientific research, pharmaceutical development, and other applications. The system involves introducing DNA fragments encoding the desired protein sequence into a host cell, which then uses its own cellular machinery to produce the protein. Common hosts for protein expression include bacteria, yeast, and mammalian cells, with each system offering its own advantages and limitations. This method allows for the production of large quantities of a specific protein, aiding in the study of its function and potential therapeutic properties.','{\"pat_doc\": 111.0, \"pub_alt\": 79.0, \"pub_doc\": 111.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 21.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 15430409.0, \"pat_granted\": 26.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.7, \"pub_doc\": 3.2, \"clinic_doc\": -0.2, \"grant_fund\": -14107859.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('923bce45971fb15137c98bad2c5106bb','7d9363772a465cde721c0298e8b025e2','7bdb69262d8e22c117d34100c1831a78','2023-09-08 02:12:10','2023-10-28 23:01:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Organotypic Culture',36,'Organotypic culture is a method of growing cells in a three-dimensional structure that mimics the natural organization of tissues and organs. This type of culture system creates an environment that more closely resembles the in vivo conditions of the cells being examined, allowing for more accurate experimental results. In an organotypic culture, the cells are grown on a natural or synthetic scaffold that enables them to self-assemble into tissue-like structures. This provides an opportunity to study cell-to-cell interactions and analyze the development and behavior of tissue-specific functions. Organotypic cultures have been used in various fields, including cancer research, drug development, and regenerative medicine. They are a valuable tool for investigating complex biological processes and identifying potential therapeutic targets.','{\"pat_doc\": 10.0, \"pub_alt\": 225.0, \"pub_doc\": 339.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 44.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 25731563.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 5.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -1146973.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('92df795dd827b0daf6463a2c6eaf6a60','e8e3ae6a8794d6acab5085e68542cec5','c89ffe68cd3a23332175ee5b50bcf229','2023-09-05 21:41:00','2023-10-28 12:20:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Quantum computing',36,'A quantum computer is a computer that exploits quantum mechanical phenomena. At small scales, physical matter exhibits properties of both particles and waves, and quantum computing leverages this behavior, specifically quantum superposition and entanglement, using specialized hardware that supports the preparation and manipulation of quantum states. Classical physics cannot explain the operation of these quantum devices, and a scalable quantum computer could perform some calculations exponentially faster than any modern \"classical\" computer. In particular, a large-scale quantum computer could break widely used encryption schemes and aid physicists in performing physical simulations; however, the current state of the art is largely experimental and impractical, with several obstacles to useful applications. Moreover, scalable quantum computers do not hold promise for many practical tasks, and for many important tasks quantum speedups are proven impossible.','{\"pat_doc\": 3237.0, \"pub_alt\": 1038.0, \"pub_doc\": 9336.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1593.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 1171775785.0, \"pat_granted\": 875.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 329.1, \"pub_doc\": 695.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": 9235870.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('932af0a18b8ef9aea304015c228fb7db','a50b8ea9f2c997ee8ae5e1323c17ab97','8ff2c0d27eb80a1a00a05bdcbea821c2','2023-09-08 02:07:31','2023-10-28 14:46:14','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Achondroplasia',36,'Achondroplasia is a genetic disorder with an autosomal dominant pattern of inheritance whose primary feature is dwarfism. In those with the condition, the arms and legs are short, while the torso is typically of normal length. Those affected have an average adult height of 131 centimetres for males and 123 centimetres for females. Other features can include an enlarged head and prominent forehead. Complications can include sleep apnea or recurrent ear infections. Achondroplasia includes short-limb skeletal dysplasia with severe combined immunodeficiency. Achondroplasia is caused by a mutation in the fibroblast growth factor receptor 3 gene that results in its protein being overactive. Achondroplasia results in impaired endochondral bone growth. The disorder has an autosomal dominant mode of inheritance, meaning only one mutated copy of the gene is required for the condition to occur.','{\"pat_doc\": 71.0, \"pub_alt\": 71.0, \"pub_doc\": 468.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 125.0, \"clinic_doc\": 45.0, \"grant_fund\": 5456510.0, \"pat_granted\": 16.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.9, \"pub_doc\": 10.3, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": -1057396.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('932b0dba46e92a60b38975ca7ab11cf2','fad21049eb39f44584479b92c65f1f69','1d60e7deb149c3b68658f6de8ff089a9','2023-09-20 20:26:19','2023-10-28 15:56:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Cushings Syndrome',24,'Cushings syndrome is a collection of signs and symptoms due to prolonged exposure to glucocorticoids such as cortisol. Signs and symptoms may include high blood pressure, abdominal obesity but with thin arms and legs, reddish stretch marks, a round red face due to facial plethora, a fat lump between the shoulders, weak muscles, weak bones, acne, and fragile skin that heals poorly. Women may have more hair and irregular menstruation. Occasionally there may be changes in mood, headaches, and a chronic feeling of tiredness. Cushings syndrome is caused by either excessive cortisol-like medication, such as prednisone, or a tumor that either produces or results in the production of excessive cortisol by the adrenal glands. Cases due to a pituitary adenoma are known as Cushings disease, which is the second most common cause of Cushings syndrome after medication. A number of other tumors, often referred to as ectopic due to their placement outside the pituitary, may also cause Cushings.','{\"pat_doc\": 2.0, \"pub_alt\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 9.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": -1.4, \"clinic_doc\": -0.9, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('93d77cdf469086655d60deda8837df1d','46bdeb9160300133a73dc543b9ff12d8','e2208eebd283dcf9b3906ac407a5d224','2023-09-08 02:23:43','2023-10-28 14:31:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Gigantism',24,'Gigantism, also known as giantism, is a condition characterized by excessive growth and height significantly above average. In humans, this condition is caused by over-production of growth hormone in childhood, resulting in people up to 2.7 m in height. It is a rare disorder resulting from increased levels of growth hormone before the fusion of the growth plate which usually occurs at some point soon after puberty. This increase is most often due to abnormal tumor growths on the pituitary gland. Gigantism should not be confused with acromegaly, the adult form of the disorder, characterized by somatic enlargement specifically in the extremities and face.','{\"pat_doc\": 2.0, \"pub_alt\": 7410.0, \"pub_doc\": 207.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 788343.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.9, \"pub_doc\": -6.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -404062.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('940563a49bdda44eb7e5f7ce1a749bd9','8b21dbe0cb1307d6f1256e0e5db60249','ccad4956fa80c9c27804d8a966399e00','2023-09-08 09:47:24','2023-10-28 20:31:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','High resolution mass spectrometry',12,'High resolution mass spectrometry (HRMS) is an advanced analytical technique that is used to determine the exact mass of atomic and molecular ions with very high accuracy. It is particularly useful in identifying unknown compounds, determining the composition of complex mixtures and characterizing the chemical structure of biomolecules such as peptides, proteins and nucleic acids. In HRMS, ions are first generated from a sample and then separated based on their mass-to-charge ratio using a mass spectrometer. The ions are then detected and their masses are measured using high resolution detectors. The high resolution of the technique enables the detection of very small mass differences, which can be used to differentiate between compounds with similar molecular weights. HRMS has revolutionized the field of analytical chemistry and has become an indispensable tool for many applications in areas such as pharmacology, environmental science, food analysis and forensics.','{\"pat_doc\": 45.0, \"pub_alt\": 1833.0, \"pub_doc\": 491.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 22.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 7901978.0, \"pat_granted\": 16.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.4, \"pub_doc\": -17.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -1744859.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('944715bf55c1d759123edef85407a64a','f75d09446940f86ed08ebd34eebf7374','aa6c75c69a90f2c711a2a5e31bb1c990','2023-09-08 01:34:12','2023-10-29 00:06:22','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','mRNA sequencing',12,'mRNA sequencing refers to the process of analyzing the transcriptome of an organism by sequencing the messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules that are expressed in a given sample. mRNA is synthesized from DNA and contains the information required to make proteins, which are the building blocks of the cell. By sequencing the mRNA, researchers can identify which genes are being expressed in a specific tissue or cell type, and can also measure the abundance of each transcript. This information can be used to gain insights into the biological processes that are occurring in the organism, and can also be used to identify genes that are dysregulated in diseases such as cancer. mRNA sequencing has become a widely used technique for studying gene expression, and new methods are continually being developed to improve the accuracy and speed of this process.','{\"pat_doc\": 11.0, \"pub_alt\": 128.0, \"pub_doc\": 367.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 20.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 4503319.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.5, \"pub_doc\": 43.3, \"clinic_doc\": 1.2, \"grant_fund\": -1315097.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9460e9f7aad21abfe2d2d9782ad646b3','12c66b98c18d896674c2af1741421e5c','5a1910224c76b3f4bd205c2f98daf970','2023-09-08 01:57:43','2023-10-28 11:05:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Artificial General Intelligence',24,'An artificial general intelligence is a hypothetical type of intelligent agent. If realized, an AGI could learn to accomplish any intellectual task that human beings or animals can perform. Alternatively, AGI has been defined as an autonomous system that surpasses human capabilities in the majority of economically valuable tasks. Creating AGI is a primary goal of some artificial intelligence research and of companies such as OpenAI, DeepMind, and Anthropic. AGI is a common topic in science fiction and futures studies. The timeline for AGI development remains a subject of ongoing debate among researchers and experts. Some argue that it may be possible in years or decades, others maintain it might take a century or longer, and a minority believe it may never be achieved. Additionally, there is debate regarding whether modern large language models, such as GPT-4, are an early yet incomplete form of AGI or if new approaches are required.','{\"pat_doc\": 7.0, \"pub_alt\": 5136.0, \"pub_doc\": 393.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1819151.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.8, \"pub_doc\": 35.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -520216.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('94a06856687cf04f941a6769d721686e','6e9cf23bacc0f67b8c70385963421414','75c037afe780bd09b9ce614027c7464a','2023-09-08 01:52:03','2023-10-28 23:51:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Cell-Free System',24,'A cell-free system is an in vitro tool widely used to study biological reactions that happen within cells apart from a full cell system, thus reducing the complex interactions typically found when working in a whole cell. Subcellular fractions can be isolated by ultracentrifugation to provide molecular machinery that can be used in reactions in the absence of many of the other cellular components. Eukaryotic and prokaryotic cell internals have been used for creation of these simplified environments. These systems have enabled cell-free synthetic biology to emerge, providing control over what reaction is being examined, as well as its yield, and lessening the considerations otherwise invoked when working with more sensitive live cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 101.0, \"pub_alt\": 168.0, \"pub_doc\": 365.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 37.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 21452831.0, \"pat_granted\": 26.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.4, \"pub_doc\": 1.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 604452.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('94ab95f51f4feff9c75f818169380dc3','2dd9d7ef89e93089944c052185d5b575','ce749f284f6019c4ac54019c71229b4d','2023-09-08 09:58:49','2023-10-28 19:41:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','digital droplet PCR',36,'Digital droplet PCR (ddPCR) is a highly sensitive and specific technique used for quantifying nucleic acids. ddPCR partitions a sample into thousands of droplets containing one or zero target molecules. The droplets are then subjected to PCR amplification and fluorescence analysis to determine which droplets contain the target molecule. This allows for highly precise quantification of the initial amount of target nucleic acid in the original sample, with a sensitivity of up to one copy per reaction. ddPCR has numerous applications in fields such as cancer research, infectious disease diagnosis, and genetic testing.','{\"pat_doc\": 27.0, \"pub_alt\": 313.0, \"pub_doc\": 458.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 21.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 8427974.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": -2.8, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": -559015.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('95091d715f9e5ecd15fdb78fdd15bedc','3ade3404fcd2fca0da04003e7692173a','556dd84c0895390f86a0e55de1ce00fb','2023-09-08 09:14:40','2023-10-28 21:16:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Fourier-transform infrared',36,'Fourier transform spectroscopy is a measurement technique whereby spectra are collected based on measurements of the coherence of a radiative source, using time-domain or space-domain measurements of the electromagnetic radiation or other type of radiation.','{\"pat_doc\": 41.0, \"pub_alt\": 2087.0, \"pub_doc\": 11497.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 55.0, \"clinic_alt\": 47.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 17796759.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.9, \"pub_doc\": 132.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": 254292.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('95101992f45c983b1981210e6a3b1b8c','de565fc9dd512d5b484b35f776f4545e','5428f4cb6631add28ed91160f184e3d2','2023-09-04 18:50:59','2023-10-29 06:46:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Polymerase Chain Reaction',36,'The polymerase chain reaction is a method widely used to make millions to billions of copies of a specific DNA sample rapidly, allowing scientists amplify a very small sample of DNA sufficiently to enable detailed study. PCR was invented in 1983 by American biochemist Kary Mullis at Cetus Corporation; Mullis and biochemist Michael Smith, who had developed other essential ways of manipulating DNA, were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1993. PCR is fundamental to many of the procedures used in genetic testing and research, including analysis of ancient samples of DNA and identification of infectious agents. Using PCR, copies of very small amounts of DNA sequences are exponentially amplified in a series of cycles of temperature changes. PCR is now a common and often indispensable technique used in medical laboratory research for a broad variety of applications including biomedical research and criminal forensics. The majority of PCR methods rely on thermal cycling.','{\"pat_doc\": 3047.0, \"pub_alt\": 32701.0, \"pub_doc\": 56206.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 380.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1692.0, \"clinic_doc\": 944.0, \"grant_fund\": 60048740.0, \"pat_granted\": 1014.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 25.6, \"pub_doc\": -1022.4, \"clinic_doc\": 80.3, \"grant_fund\": -12358489.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('95a81a9266a13df9780f3cf9754240a9','c3be1591926e87743c4c54d7028677c0','ef63c5da9830a0ea9737ee257244ed3a','2023-09-08 00:09:38','2023-10-28 16:36:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Lentivirus',36,'Lentivirus is a genus of retroviruses that cause chronic and deadly diseases characterized by long incubation periods, in humans and other mammalian species. The genus includes the human immunodeficiency virus, which causes AIDS. Lentiviruses are distributed worldwide, and are known to be hosted in apes, cows, goats, horses, cats, and sheep as well as several other mammals. Lentiviruses can integrate a significant amount of viral complementary DNA into the DNA of the host cell and can efficiently infect nondividing cells, so they are one of the most efficient methods of gene delivery. They can become endogenous, integrating their genome into the host germline genome, so that the virus is henceforth inherited by the hosts descendants.','{\"pat_doc\": 1103.0, \"pub_alt\": 2501.0, \"pub_doc\": 4177.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 146.0, \"clinic_alt\": 169.0, \"clinic_doc\": 47.0, \"grant_fund\": 67089007.0, \"pat_granted\": 319.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.0, \"pub_doc\": -93.8, \"clinic_doc\": 8.6, \"grant_fund\": -9867775.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('95be2d234c45e269f0fff463fd212408','8c579df990726481d707857fe85bab54','f0c1b8c703203eb82e320beebf070142','2023-09-04 19:39:15','2023-10-28 18:11:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','CRISPR',48,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 10517.0, \"pub_alt\": 3610.0, \"pub_doc\": 38048.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6697.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1068.0, \"clinic_doc\": 91.0, \"grant_fund\": 3389433680.0, \"pat_granted\": 2329.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 422.3, \"pub_doc\": 715.2, \"clinic_doc\": 17.3, \"grant_fund\": -192193900.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('960891df54429e5f3115a000cd357771','7d9363772a465cde721c0298e8b025e2','7bdb69262d8e22c117d34100c1831a78','2023-09-08 02:12:10','2023-10-28 23:01:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Organotypic Culture',48,'Organotypic culture is a method of growing cells in a three-dimensional structure that mimics the natural organization of tissues and organs. This type of culture system creates an environment that more closely resembles the in vivo conditions of the cells being examined, allowing for more accurate experimental results. In an organotypic culture, the cells are grown on a natural or synthetic scaffold that enables them to self-assemble into tissue-like structures. This provides an opportunity to study cell-to-cell interactions and analyze the development and behavior of tissue-specific functions. Organotypic cultures have been used in various fields, including cancer research, drug development, and regenerative medicine. They are a valuable tool for investigating complex biological processes and identifying potential therapeutic targets.','{\"pat_doc\": 15.0, \"pub_alt\": 356.0, \"pub_doc\": 442.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 76.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 36238793.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 5.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -1146973.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('961cfa0aa1408e69b3ca23c929b43104','dc11d80fc0114b8dfe9fa719a1d68ad7','a0ec7ffe04c046d0f8469b5de966ddfa','2023-09-04 18:54:26','2023-10-29 06:35:05','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Flow Cytometry',24,'Flow cytometry is a technique used to detect and measure physical and chemical characteristics of a population of cells or particles. In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument. The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components. Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths. Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer. Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials. Uses for flow cytometry include: â€¢ Cell counting â€¢ Cell sorting â€¢ Determining cell characteristics and function â€¢ Detecting microorganisms â€¢ Biomarker detection â€¢ Protein engineering detection â€¢ Diagnosis of health disorders such as blood cancers â€¢ Measuring genome size.','{\"pat_doc\": 1084.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 33213.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 907.0, \"clinic_alt\": 590.0, \"clinic_doc\": 661.0, \"grant_fund\": 266196486.0, \"pat_granted\": 347.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.1, \"pub_doc\": -433.8, \"clinic_doc\": 137.2, \"grant_fund\": -49967547.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9623e5fb788b9e160717ae30794c6f6c','3dd87ec4606ad304f7e661f044278af7','3fb1f33d12215e256dd98a72f66b746e','2023-09-08 01:32:52','2023-10-28 15:16:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Viral vector (gene) therapies','Oncolytic viruses',12,'An oncolytic virus is a virus that preferentially infects and kills cancer cells. As the infected cancer cells are destroyed by oncolysis, they release new infectious virus particles or virions to help destroy the remaining tumour. Oncolytic viruses are thought not only to cause direct destruction of the tumour cells, but also to stimulate host anti-tumour immune system responses. Oncolytic viruses also have the ability to affect the tumor micro-environment in multiple ways. The potential of viruses as anti-cancer agents was first realised in the early twentieth century, although coordinated research efforts did not begin until the 1960s. A number of viruses including adenovirus, reovirus, measles, herpes simplex, Newcastle disease virus, and vaccinia have been clinically tested as oncolytic agents. Most current oncolytic viruses are engineered for tumour selectivity, although there are naturally occurring examples such as reovirus and the senecavirus, resulting in clinical trials.','{\"pat_doc\": 195.0, \"pub_alt\": 330.0, \"pub_doc\": 320.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 14.0, \"clinic_alt\": 130.0, \"clinic_doc\": 13.0, \"grant_fund\": 2764159.0, \"pat_granted\": 30.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 26.2, \"pub_doc\": 4.4, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": -7924828.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('96d2632cce879aa1df73f5475b0055c3','7894dc5316736cccc7857ade68b00def','5428f4cb6631add28ed91160f184e3d2','2023-09-04 18:49:56','2023-10-29 06:50:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Polymerase Chain Reaction',48,'The polymerase chain reaction is a method widely used to make millions to billions of copies of a specific DNA sample rapidly, allowing scientists amplify a very small sample of DNA sufficiently to enable detailed study. PCR was invented in 1983 by American biochemist Kary Mullis at Cetus Corporation; Mullis and biochemist Michael Smith, who had developed other essential ways of manipulating DNA, were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1993. PCR is fundamental to many of the procedures used in genetic testing and research, including analysis of ancient samples of DNA and identification of infectious agents. Using PCR, copies of very small amounts of DNA sequences are exponentially amplified in a series of cycles of temperature changes. PCR is now a common and often indispensable technique used in medical laboratory research for a broad variety of applications including biomedical research and criminal forensics. The majority of PCR methods rely on thermal cycling.','{\"pat_doc\": 3966.0, \"pub_alt\": 32701.0, \"pub_doc\": 75414.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 605.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1692.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1161.0, \"grant_fund\": 109561078.0, \"pat_granted\": 1298.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 25.6, \"pub_doc\": -1022.4, \"clinic_doc\": 80.3, \"grant_fund\": -12358489.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('96e4b1234bece3e810c37f29c4902b5c','164a36aa72f0d1ad31bba2a4ae14dad1','52e358453865c2f781ecea69256e441f','2023-09-08 02:22:34','2023-10-28 22:26:12','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Spectral Database',12,'A spectral database is a repository of spectral data that can be used for identification and characterization of chemical compounds. Spectral data includes information about the properties of light interacting with a sample, such as absorption, emission, and scattering. By comparing the spectral data of an unknown sample to that in a spectral database, researchers can identify the likely chemical composition of the sample. Spectral databases are crucial for many scientific fields, including chemistry, biology, and materials science. They are constantly being updated with new data and have become essential tools in modern research.','{\"pat_doc\": 23.0, \"pub_alt\": 56.0, \"pub_doc\": 97.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 1620803.0, \"pat_granted\": 7.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.1, \"pub_doc\": 3.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -1497510.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('96f6e3756f3347aa59035aea423b14f5','21d871363877cc98d16111d220b3c6ab','aa4364cfb922eeea74c84893f0cb9469','2023-09-08 09:40:12','2023-10-28 20:46:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Surface Plasmon Resonance',36,'Surface plasmon resonance is a phenomenon that occurs where electrons in a thin metal sheet become excited by light that is directed to the sheet with a particular angle of incidence, and then travel parallel to the sheet. Assuming a constant light source wavelength and that the metal sheet is thin, the angle of incidence that triggers SPR is related to the refractive index of the material and even a small change in the refractive index will cause SPR to not be observed. This makes SPR a possible technique for detecting particular substances and SPR biosensors have been developed to detect various important biomarkers.','{\"pat_doc\": 1155.0, \"pub_alt\": 2771.0, \"pub_doc\": 11076.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 266.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 85934049.0, \"pat_granted\": 385.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.7, \"pub_doc\": 132.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.9, \"grant_fund\": -19685515.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9714d74382df4e7495da3d0954e86e4a','b2deca51e58703d27137669b972e2778','782fafb2d5b336b1996d7a1bfb56f465','2023-09-08 09:53:17','2023-10-28 20:06:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Mass spectrometry imaging',36,'Mass spectrometry imaging is a technique used in mass spectrometry to visualize the spatial distribution of molecules, as biomarkers, metabolites, peptides or proteins by their molecular masses. After collecting a mass spectrum at one spot, the sample is moved to reach another region, and so on, until the entire sample is scanned. By choosing a peak in the resulting spectra that corresponds to the compound of interest, the MS data is used to map its distribution across the sample. This results in pictures of the spatially resolved distribution of a compound pixel by pixel. Each data set contains a veritable gallery of pictures because any peak in each spectrum can be spatially mapped. Despite the fact that MSI has been generally considered a qualitative method, the signal generated by this technique is proportional to the relative abundance of the analyte. Therefore, quantification is possible, when its challenges are overcome.','{\"pat_doc\": 129.0, \"pub_alt\": 481.0, \"pub_doc\": 1494.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 112.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 50369329.0, \"pat_granted\": 42.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 30.5, \"clinic_doc\": -0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2225201.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9756069dac8902fff7579a568adc9096','96a98502ddc2632768ff7919ec246022','d471ba9d05b4186943ade5d1a2ae30dc','2023-09-04 18:23:33','2023-10-29 07:06:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Mass Spectrometry',12,'Mass Spectrometry is a powerful analytical technique used in chemistry, biochemistry, and other scientific fields to identify molecules based on their mass-to-charge ratio (m/z). The process involves ionizing a sample, then separating the resulting ions based on their mass-to-charge ratio using electromagnetic fields. The ions are then detected and analyzed to determine their individual masses and concentrations. Mass spectrometry is used in many applications, including characterizing the structure of unknown compounds, identifying proteins and peptides, and tracking the movement of isotopes within molecules. It has become a standard tool in many areas of research, including drug discovery, environmental analysis, and forensic science.','{\"pat_doc\": 3936.0, \"pub_alt\": 3571.0, \"pub_doc\": 32260.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 943.0, \"clinic_alt\": 146.0, \"clinic_doc\": 435.0, \"grant_fund\": 418515424.0, \"pat_granted\": 1337.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 210.2, \"pub_doc\": 879.4, \"clinic_doc\": 100.8, \"grant_fund\": -169513024.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('975d2d6f738a4f1ab6ecb9820cb74cdb','ce48dd19951bc72e32788762866aa8ba','9f4de602c8b4dc324f5081159f81d1f9','2023-09-08 10:02:32','2023-10-28 19:21:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Loss on Drying',24,'Loss on Drying (LOD) is a common analysis performed in the pharmaceutical, food, and cosmetics industries to quantify the amount of moisture content in a sample. It is a gravimetric analysis method that measures the weight lost by a sample when it is heated at a specific temperature. The difference between the initial weight of the sample and the weight after heating is recorded as LOD. This technique is useful in determining the stability and shelf life of products, as high moisture content can lead to microbial growth, chemical degradation, and decreased product quality. LOD is a critical parameter in product manufacturing, as it can affect the products physical and chemical properties, efficacy, and safety. Controlling the moisture content of a product is essential to ensure its stability and prevent spoilage, making LOD an important tool for quality control and assurance.','{\"pat_doc\": 21.0, \"pub_alt\": 8.0, \"pub_doc\": 153.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 5.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 1.4, \"clinic_doc\": -0.8, \"grant_fund\": -10651.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('978b80262c1d598118b89509f178d7a0','94a11929f6fb7d9d93e190ab5230cb23','2874f833fd4f69190438aa7cb5f052b5','2023-09-05 20:19:29','2023-10-29 04:41:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Blockchain technology',48,'Blockchain technology is a distributed ledger technology that allows for secure, transparent and irreversible peer-to-peer transactions without the need for intermediaries. It is based on a decentralized network of nodes that validate transactions and add them to the blockchain, a public ledger of all transactions. Blockchain technology is essentially a digital ledger that records and stores data in a secure and transparent way. This makes it useful for a variety of applications, such as cryptocurrency, supply chain management, voting systems, and more. The technologys key features include decentralization, transparency, immutability, and security. Overall, blockchain technology has the potential to revolutionize multiple industries and enable new business models.','{\"pat_doc\": 3906.0, \"pub_alt\": 1120.0, \"pub_doc\": 19828.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 321.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 139350818.0, \"pat_granted\": 930.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 306.0, \"pub_doc\": 1055.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -4560710.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('979541b77401694124ccab0ae4cb9969','e24808701d1b869f29beb5b17a6f3966','0a566310cdeaa23e7fc0d55380c35a91','2023-09-08 02:38:56','2023-10-28 14:11:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Gene therapies (Non-viral)','mRNA therapy',36,'mRNA (messenger RNA) therapy is a cutting-edge medical technique that harnesses the bodys own ability to produce essential proteins to better fight disease. The therapy involves injecting synthetic strands of mRNA into the body, which are then recognized by the bodys own cells as \"blueprints\" for specific proteins that are vital for health. These proteins are then produced by the bodys cells and can be used to combat a wide range of illnesses, from cancer to genetic disorders to viral infections like COVID-19. mRNA therapy has shown a lot of promise in clinical trials, with some treatments already approved for use in certain conditions. While the technology is still in its early stages, experts believe that mRNA therapy could revolutionize the way we treat diseases in the coming years.','{\"pat_doc\": 97.0, \"pub_alt\": 350.0, \"pub_doc\": 74.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 2526332.0, \"pat_granted\": 15.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.7, \"pub_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.4, \"grant_fund\": 71200.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('97c8d0003f43809a91c55473b2ca9840','a0128a060f00fc2880c25d9fe5536900','beb557d6f3a8f418565f2d30cdebe10e','2023-09-08 01:20:42','2023-10-28 15:21:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','natural killer T cells',24,'Natural Killer T cells are a type of lymphocytes that bridge the adaptive and innate immune systems. They have the ability to recognize and respond to a broad range of antigens presented on the surface of many different cell types, including cancer cells, and are important in regulating immune responses. These cells differentiate from the thymus and are characterized by the co-expression of T cell receptors and NK cell receptors. The interaction of these receptors allows them to respond quickly to pathogens and induces the rapid secretion of cytokines and other effector molecules. Natural Killer T cells play a vital role in controlling immune responses and have been implicated in various autoimmune diseases. Recent studies on the modulation of Natural Killer T cell responses provide new insights into the development of immunotherapeutic strategies for infectious and inflammatory diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 24.0, \"pub_alt\": 282.0, \"pub_doc\": 214.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_alt\": 37.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 2312015.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.0, \"pub_doc\": -0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.9, \"grant_fund\": -984070.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('97d066de8ee8f61ecbca26a6ebc9a3cd','629f564fa930d422fbfc8405c3bae6c0','72a385b9d786832dcc2c823f54ed4998','2023-09-05 20:39:21','2023-10-28 12:40:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Digital Twin',48,'A digital twin is a digital representation of an intended or actual real-world physical product, system, or process that serves as the effectively indistinguishable digital counterpart of it for practical purposes, such as simulation, integration, testing, monitoring, and maintenance. The digital twin has been intended from its initial introduction to be the underlying premise for Product Lifecycle Management and exists throughout the entire lifecycle of the physical entity it represents. Since information is granular, the digital twin representation is determined by the value-based use cases it is created to implement. The digital twin can and does often exist before there is a physical entity. The use of a digital twin in the creation phase allows the intended entitys entire lifecycle to be modeled and simulated. A digital twin of an existing entity may be used in real-time and regularly synchronized with the corresponding physical system.','{\"pat_doc\": 8875.0, \"pub_alt\": 767.0, \"pub_doc\": 16023.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2379.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 2814221855.0, \"pat_granted\": 1766.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1361.7, \"pub_doc\": 1705.1, \"clinic_doc\": 4.4, \"grant_fund\": 206480656.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('97f5c5559a2f209ce85010410fd75f25','633e3e1c04bc9ee16dfcb222f957cce1','5ee4ac63831f6ebbfc5f216379d36d38','2023-09-08 08:27:45','2023-10-28 10:30:32','Electronics','Components','Other','Co-Packaged Optics',36,'Co-packaged optics is a term that refers to the integration of optical components within the silicon chip package, enabling high-speed computing to be achieved. This technology is expected to revolutionize the data center industry by enhancing speed and reducing power consumption. By eliminating fiber cabling and replacing it with on-board optical interconnects, co-packaged optics enables faster data transfer rates, better communication between processors, reduced data center infrastructure, and other significant benefits. An important aspect of this technology is that it leverages existing CMOS fabrication processes, ensuring compatibility with current manufacturing techniques. This new optical integration technology is set to push the capabilities of electronic data processing further than ever before, providing more efficient and faster data transfer speeds for data centers and beyond.','{\"pat_doc\": 41.0, \"pub_alt\": 4.0, \"pub_doc\": 106.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 13738132.0, \"pat_granted\": 11.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.6, \"pub_doc\": 13.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2486201.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9914a672e2e1182da5c4c16ad03371da','11ceddbe2884cfa304852a2ce17a1058','2483d5e44059b5dad528a46e9d77ee36','2023-09-08 00:49:58','2023-10-28 16:06:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','antisense oligonucleotides',36,'Antisense oligonucleotides (ASOs) are short single-stranded pieces of DNA or RNA that bind to specific target mRNA molecules to regulate gene expression. ASOs are designed to silence a particular gene by preventing the translation of mRNA into protein, which can be useful in treating genetic disorders caused by overexpression or abnormal splicing of certain genes. ASOs are made up of a sequence complementary to the target mRNA, and once bound, they can recruit cellular machinery to degrade the mRNA or block its translation. ASOs are a promising therapeutic strategy for a variety of diseases, including cancer, viral infections, and genetic disorders.','{\"pat_doc\": 1278.0, \"pub_alt\": 334.0, \"pub_doc\": 1427.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 166.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 89117343.0, \"pat_granted\": 232.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 12.1, \"pub_doc\": 27.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -4641956.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('995660a900c7ff68e21e096a7c31adb4','224d3dce630c1eacf85c0f88dd72e042','66dae1bd66572a9ac387868804da7fa9','2023-09-08 00:43:37','2023-10-28 16:11:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Monoclonal antibodies','Bispecific antibody',36,'A bispecific monoclonal antibody is an artificial protein that can simultaneously bind to two different types of antigen or two different epitopes on the same antigen. Naturally occurring antibodies typically only target one antigen. BsAbs can be manufactured in several structural formats. BsAbs can be designed to recruit and activate immune cells, to interfere with receptor signaling and inactivate signaling ligands, and to force association of protein complexes. BsAbs have been explored for cancer immunotherapy, drug delivery, and Alzeimers disease.','{\"pat_doc\": 3133.0, \"pub_alt\": 746.0, \"pub_doc\": 1494.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 48.0, \"clinic_alt\": 859.0, \"clinic_doc\": 227.0, \"grant_fund\": 79069997.0, \"pat_granted\": 507.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 160.2, \"pub_doc\": 80.4, \"clinic_doc\": 59.6, \"grant_fund\": 14897954.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('997276786f7f42821a4b1d498270c565','0a08029fe04824e466d5980ec8cdbf8b','a0ec7ffe04c046d0f8469b5de966ddfa','2023-09-04 18:53:15','2023-10-29 06:40:05','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Flow Cytometry',36,'Flow cytometry is a technique used to detect and measure physical and chemical characteristics of a population of cells or particles. In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument. The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components. Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths. Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer. Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials. Uses for flow cytometry include: â€¢ Cell counting â€¢ Cell sorting â€¢ Determining cell characteristics and function â€¢ Detecting microorganisms â€¢ Biomarker detection â€¢ Protein engineering detection â€¢ Diagnosis of health disorders such as blood cancers â€¢ Measuring genome size.','{\"pat_doc\": 1558.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 50469.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1677.0, \"clinic_alt\": 590.0, \"clinic_doc\": 766.0, \"grant_fund\": 478554038.0, \"pat_granted\": 510.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.1, \"pub_doc\": -433.8, \"clinic_doc\": 137.2, \"grant_fund\": -49967547.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('997b643b4f3a879da62a93029f98975b','4ed1727d16902077c7b79a9c262994fa','12a26d07df436f186302cbc8c800d6d6','2023-09-05 20:45:30','2023-10-29 04:31:13','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Electroencephalography',24,'Electroencephalography is a method to record an electrogram of the spontaneous electrical activity of the brain. The biosignals detected by EEG have been shown to represent the postsynaptic potentials of pyramidal neurons in the neocortex and allocortex. It is typically non-invasive, with the EEG electrodes placed along the scalp using the International 10â€“20 system, or variations of it. Electrocorticography, involving surgical placement of electrodes, is sometimes called \"intracranial EEG\". Clinical interpretation of EEG recordings is most often performed by visual inspection of the tracing or quantitative EEG analysis. Voltage fluctuations measured by the EEG bioamplifier and electrodes allow the evaluation of normal brain activity. As the electrical activity monitored by EEG originates in neurons in the underlying brain tissue, the recordings made by the electrodes on the surface of the scalp vary in accordance with their orientation and distance to the source of the activity.','{\"pat_doc\": 301.0, \"pub_alt\": 5051.0, \"pub_doc\": 8603.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 363.0, \"clinic_alt\": 122.0, \"clinic_doc\": 639.0, \"grant_fund\": 107011763.0, \"pat_granted\": 68.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 299.2, \"clinic_doc\": 125.2, \"grant_fund\": -19331779.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('998db63f3233a4d42d70033713eaaf32','402437da63ba33a83221799ab29cf95b','d511e8881547550871faef764cbfed18','2023-09-08 02:40:12','2023-10-28 21:56:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Sterilization Technique',48,'Sterilization technique involves the process of eliminating all forms of microorganisms and pathogens from a surface or object. This technique is used in medical facilities or laboratories to avoid the spread of infections or diseases. There are several sterilization methods, such as chemical sterilization, radiation sterilization, and physical sterilization. Chemical sterilization procedures involve the use of gases or liquids to get rid of bacteria or other microorganisms. Radiation sterilization involves the utilization of ionizing radiation to destroy pathogens, whereas physical sterilization involves the use of heat, pressure, or filtration to eliminate bacteria or other microorganisms. These sterilization techniques are essential in maintaining a sterile environment, which is crucial in medical facilities that perform surgeries or other sensitive procedures.','{\"pat_doc\": 90.0, \"pub_alt\": 506.0, \"pub_doc\": 239.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 14.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 2282004.0, \"pat_granted\": 55.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -5.0, \"pub_doc\": 3.3, \"clinic_doc\": -0.7, \"grant_fund\": 247564.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('99df6b03c633f2a52226366f14f06546','42dcab631334ddefd1aa257b8b5f1e8f','eefb2660a8535eb1d304c9a60295324f','2023-09-05 21:18:18','2023-10-29 04:01:40','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Liposomes',48,'A liposome is a small artificial vesicle, spherical in shape, having at least one lipid bilayer. Due to their hydrophobicity and/or hydrophilicity, biocompatibility, particle size and many other properties, liposomes can be used as drug delivery vehicles for administration of pharmaceutical drugs and nutrients, such as lipid nanoparticles in mRNA vaccines, and DNA vaccines. Liposomes can be prepared by disrupting biological membranes. Liposomes are most often composed of phospholipids, especially phosphatidylcholine, and cholesterol, but may also include other lipids, such as those found in egg and phosphatidylethanolamine, as long as they are compatible with lipid bilayer structure. A liposome design may employ surface ligands for attaching to unhealthy tissue. The major types of liposomes are the multilamellar vesicle, the small unilamellar liposome vesicle, the large unilamellar vesicle, and the cochleate vesicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 3091.0, \"pub_alt\": 590.0, \"pub_doc\": 11947.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 611.0, \"clinic_alt\": 108.0, \"clinic_doc\": 67.0, \"grant_fund\": 172975550.0, \"pat_granted\": 793.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 12.3, \"pub_doc\": 172.3, \"clinic_doc\": 8.1, \"grant_fund\": -13776868.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9a741df1fdb26cf3f3173cacce77ac3c','12c66b98c18d896674c2af1741421e5c','5a1910224c76b3f4bd205c2f98daf970','2023-09-08 01:57:43','2023-10-28 11:05:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Artificial General Intelligence',12,'An artificial general intelligence is a hypothetical type of intelligent agent. If realized, an AGI could learn to accomplish any intellectual task that human beings or animals can perform. Alternatively, AGI has been defined as an autonomous system that surpasses human capabilities in the majority of economically valuable tasks. Creating AGI is a primary goal of some artificial intelligence research and of companies such as OpenAI, DeepMind, and Anthropic. AGI is a common topic in science fiction and futures studies. The timeline for AGI development remains a subject of ongoing debate among researchers and experts. Some argue that it may be possible in years or decades, others maintain it might take a century or longer, and a minority believe it may never be achieved. Additionally, there is debate regarding whether modern large language models, such as GPT-4, are an early yet incomplete form of AGI or if new approaches are required.','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_alt\": 5136.0, \"pub_doc\": 240.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1344960.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.8, \"pub_doc\": 35.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -520216.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9b37b72d0a0b1c16889929b11e8f394f','5f1ee7663407442aa2582d3efd1ad42b','5320de801f6c227388f87a0edfc49eb4','2023-09-04 19:25:15','2023-10-29 06:06:07','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Metabolomics',36,'Metabolomics is the scientific study of chemical processes involving metabolites, the small molecule substrates, intermediates, and products of cell metabolism. Specifically, metabolomics is the \"systematic study of the unique chemical fingerprints that specific cellular processes leave behind\", the study of their small-molecule metabolite profiles. The metabolome represents the complete set of metabolites in a biological cell, tissue, organ, or organism, which are the end products of cellular processes. Messenger RNA, gene expression data, and proteomic analyses reveal the set of gene products being produced in the cell, data that represents one aspect of cellular function. Conversely, metabolic profiling can give an instantaneous snapshot of the physiology of that cell, and thus, metabolomics provides a direct \"functional readout of the physiological state\" of an organism.','{\"pat_doc\": 117.0, \"pub_alt\": 5232.0, \"pub_doc\": 22194.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1807.0, \"clinic_alt\": 322.0, \"clinic_doc\": 855.0, \"grant_fund\": 1043571376.0, \"pat_granted\": 29.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.2, \"pub_doc\": 1091.2, \"clinic_doc\": 144.0, \"grant_fund\": -118313386.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9b407213babb1b641fbf761959db7eac','05aa0de4a4917d54e102e40d1b76c9e1','fd6371fdffdf19bf1bf3ac9102b5acf9','2023-09-08 01:59:23','2023-10-28 23:31:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Autoclaving',48,'An autoclave is a machine used to carry out industrial and scientific processes requiring elevated temperature and pressure in relation to ambient pressure and/or temperature. Autoclaves are used before surgical procedures to perform sterilization and in the chemical industry to cure coatings and vulcanize rubber and for hydrothermal synthesis. Industrial autoclaves are used in industrial applications, especially in the manufacturing of composites. Many autoclaves are used to sterilize equipment and supplies by subjecting them to pressurized saturated steam at 121 Â°C for around 30-60 minutes at a pressure of 15 psi depending on the size of the load and the contents. The autoclave was invented by Charles Chamberland in 1879, although a precursor known as the steam digester was created by Denis Papin in 1679. The name comes from Greek auto-, ultimately meaning self, and Latin clavis meaning key, thus a self-locking device.','{\"pat_doc\": 694.0, \"pub_alt\": 174.0, \"pub_doc\": 1029.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 13.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 3709312.0, \"pat_granted\": 299.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -12.2, \"pub_doc\": -9.9, \"clinic_doc\": 1.2, \"grant_fund\": 113571.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9b43622e9535c9d18e73bc3fcc876beb','093421fa544b6541b1aa9445b0324876','c69cae5bf0730201ed4820a70e56cfc2','2023-09-08 09:08:02','2023-10-28 13:26:11','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Gastrointestinal Cancer',24,'Gastrointestinal cancer refers to malignant conditions of the gastrointestinal tract and accessory organs of digestion, including the esophagus, stomach, biliary system, pancreas, small intestine, large intestine, rectum and anus. The symptoms relate to the organ affected and can include obstruction, abnormal bleeding or other associated problems. The diagnosis often requires endoscopy, followed by biopsy of suspicious tissue. The treatment depends on the location of the tumor, as well as the type of cancer cell and whether it has invaded other tissues or spread elsewhere. These factors also determine the prognosis. Overall, the GI tract and the accessory organs of digestion are responsible for more cancers and more deaths from cancer than any other system in the body. There is significant geographic variation in the rates of different gastrointestinal cancers.','{\"pat_doc\": 113.0, \"pub_alt\": 1676.0, \"pub_doc\": 2301.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 94.0, \"clinic_alt\": 412.0, \"clinic_doc\": 253.0, \"grant_fund\": 17450115.0, \"pat_granted\": 17.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.9, \"pub_doc\": 83.2, \"clinic_doc\": 43.7, \"grant_fund\": -5165841.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9bc65cdc0a03471c3ee6168e7e5c8bee','d893c2f2b521b2e83577694191a8eee4','8f14a9e350509c9aa1906cf48eaa7e87','2023-09-08 02:28:18','2023-10-28 22:11:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Water Purification System',24,'A water purification system is a device or process that removes impurities, contaminants, and other pollutants from water to make it safe for consumption. It typically involves several stages, such as sedimentation, filtration, disinfection, and sometimes reverse osmosis. These processes help to eliminate harmful bacteria, viruses, chemicals, and minerals while improving the taste and clarity of the water. Water purification systems may be utilized in households, hospitals, industries, and municipalities to ensure safe drinking water and maintain health and hygiene. The systems effectiveness depends on the quality of water being treated and the specific technology or technique used. Proper maintenance and regular monitoring are also critical to maintain its efficiency.','{\"pat_doc\": 1422.0, \"pub_alt\": 324.0, \"pub_doc\": 191.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 16.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 3860512.0, \"pat_granted\": 818.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -46.1, \"pub_doc\": 9.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.4, \"grant_fund\": -471630.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9bc86f26fff5e8273c67342cce884c29','1edf5dbb1a5ebbaef987b8b78449add1','d55c8f5e392f4de211e65cb1cf025f9d','2023-09-08 01:07:08','2023-10-29 00:41:20','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Stability',12,'mRNA stability is the measure of how long a messenger RNA (mRNA) molecule lasts within a cell before it is degraded. This is important because the stability of mRNA affects the amount of protein that can be produced from that mRNA. If mRNA is stable, it can persist in the cell and continue to produce protein. However, if the mRNA is unstable, it will degrade quickly and less protein will be produced. mRNA stability is regulated by a number of factors including sequence motifs, RNA-binding proteins, and the presence of other molecules. Understanding how mRNA stability is regulated can provide insights into gene expression and can be helpful in developing new therapies for certain diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 16.0, \"pub_alt\": 1837.0, \"pub_doc\": 523.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 32.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 20032964.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.1, \"pub_doc\": 58.5, \"clinic_doc\": -0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1054364.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9c0649231974ca23a4a6283e8594e049','df68dc3c44b77575d9caaef9764342db','5cc2df341e20d3c3cf94910f9000682b','2023-09-08 08:32:17','2023-10-28 13:36:17','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Squamous cell carcinoma',12,'Squamous-cell carcinomas, also known as epidermoid carcinomas, comprise a number of different types of cancer that begin in squamous cells. These cells form on the surface of the skin, on the lining of hollow organs in the body, and on the lining of the respiratory and digestive tracts. Common types include: â€¢ cutaneous squamous-cell carcinoma: a type of skin cancer â€¢ squamous-cell carcinoma of the lung: a type of lung cancer â€¢ squamous-cell thyroid carcinoma: a type of thyroid cancer â€¢ esophageal squamous-cell carcinoma: a type of esophageal cancer â€¢ squamous-cell carcinoma of the vagina: a type of vaginal cancer. Despite sharing the name \"squamous-cell carcinoma\", the SCCs of different body sites can show differences in their presented symptoms, natural history, prognosis, and response to treatment.','{\"pat_doc\": 397.0, \"pub_alt\": 1142.0, \"pub_doc\": 11415.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 152.0, \"clinic_alt\": 717.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1511.0, \"grant_fund\": 45763466.0, \"pat_granted\": 103.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 29.4, \"pub_doc\": 69.4, \"clinic_doc\": 397.4, \"grant_fund\": -19576090.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9c312f5de5c65affe606d11f4d836ad4','12312c1c49930d5087ae7dcb6859710b','49f53d4e41fb1f785aeb36bddad58488','2023-09-08 10:40:37','2023-10-28 19:06:13','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Natural Language Processing',24,'Natural language processing is an interdisciplinary subfield of computer science and linguistics. It is primarily concerned with giving computers the ability to support and manipulate speech. It involves processing natural language datasets, such as text corpora or speech corpora, using either rule-based or probabilistic machine learning approaches. The goal is a computer capable of \"understanding\" the contents of documents, including the contextual nuances of the language within them. The technology can then accurately extract information and insights contained in the documents as well as categorize and organize the documents themselves. Challenges in natural language processing frequently involve speech recognition, natural-language understanding, and natural-language generation.','{\"pat_doc\": 8070.0, \"pub_alt\": 1330.0, \"pub_doc\": 20408.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 914.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 72.0, \"grant_fund\": 481913452.0, \"pat_granted\": 2482.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 771.9, \"pub_doc\": 1863.9, \"clinic_doc\": 17.1, \"grant_fund\": -13379287.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9c59ef21302ce577f60efb45bfaea546','cb426d718331f51011984ab644408b3c','b10c3992ebb8f463a7fad145792de043','2023-09-08 09:16:19','2023-10-28 21:11:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Liquid Chromatography',48,'Liquid chromatography (LC) is a widely used separation technique to isolate, identify, and quantify various components within a mixture. It works on the principle of differential partitioning of sample components between a mobile phase (liquid) and stationary phase (solid or liquid). The sample is introduced into the mobile phase, which is pumped through the stationary phase packed inside a column. The interaction between sample components and stationary phase determines the retention time and separation of individual components. Various types of liquid chromatography, such as high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC), ultra-high-performance liquid chromatography (UHPLC), and size exclusion chromatography (SEC), are available to separate different types of analytes based on their physicochemical properties. LC is widely used in the pharmaceutical, biotechnology, food, and environmental testing industries due to its high resolution, accuracy, and sensitivity.','{\"pat_doc\": 15139.0, \"pub_alt\": 1833.0, \"pub_doc\": 64927.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1358.0, \"clinic_alt\": 68.0, \"clinic_doc\": 481.0, \"grant_fund\": 282168197.0, \"pat_granted\": 5323.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 443.5, \"pub_doc\": 370.3, \"clinic_doc\": 60.7, \"grant_fund\": -16962097.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9c5a951e0c61f983682ab551999a339e','86828d3c6e58a58dd0ec1a5517969fd6','de33517ef25dd85cbe2dd8dc604a5426','2023-09-08 01:18:05','2023-10-28 15:26:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','biomolecular condensates',48,'Biomolecular condensates are non-membrane-bound, membraneless organelles that are formed by the reversible phase separation of proteins, nucleic acids, and other biomolecules. These condensates can be dynamic and can rapidly assemble and disassemble in response to cellular signals. They play a crucial role in many cellular processes, including DNA replication, transcription, and translation. Recent studies have shown that the formation of these condensates can also drive the assembly of large molecular complexes that are essential for cellular functions. Dysfunction of these condensates has been linked to various diseases, including neurodegenerative disorders. Understanding the principles underlying biomolecular condensate formation and dynamics is crucial for understanding cellular processes and developing new therapeutics.','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_alt\": 611.0, \"pub_doc\": 1155.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 127.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 79389717.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.9, \"pub_doc\": 89.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1255674.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9c5b0d7b3667cf20440dea5a4753a3ae','2f412f6d08233ef2ee97b503f7c210fd','bc432a22793de3677b1dacfb29fc2326','2023-09-08 09:49:36','2023-10-28 20:21:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','SDS-PAGE',12,'SDS-PAGE is a discontinuous electrophoretic system developed by Ulrich K. Laemmli which is commonly used as a method to separate proteins with molecular masses between 5 and 250 kDa. The combined use of sodium dodecyl sulfate and polyacrylamide gel eliminates the influence of structure and charge, and proteins are separated by differences in their size. At least up to 2012, the publication describing it was the most frequently cited paper by a single author, and the second most cited overall.','{\"pat_doc\": 72.0, \"pub_alt\": 40.0, \"pub_doc\": 1338.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 594828.0, \"pat_granted\": 25.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.7, \"pub_doc\": -42.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": -1973486.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9c696f034f84b4450ee783b8cf702ab8','9be33f727d7b72fef24f5c1785693e63','968e5d71e0d0c5dc526e2a9156a8d9aa','2023-09-08 10:00:06','2023-10-28 19:31:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','supercritical fluid chromatography',12,'Supercritical fluid chromatography is a form of normal phase chromatography that uses a supercritical fluid such as carbon dioxide as the mobile phase. It is used for the analysis and purification of low to moderate molecular weight, thermally labile molecules and can also be used for the separation of chiral compounds. Principles are similar to those of high performance liquid chromatography, however SFC typically utilizes carbon dioxide as the mobile phase; therefore the entire chromatographic flow path must be pressurized. Because the supercritical phase represents a state in which liquid and gas properties converge, supercritical fluid chromatography is sometimes called convergence chromatography.','{\"pat_doc\": 45.0, \"pub_alt\": 270.0, \"pub_doc\": 131.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 361869.0, \"pat_granted\": 25.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.0, \"pub_doc\": -10.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": -373175.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9c93a81072123d6d828e42029b0ffc63','e7461a8ad3be85a4a9927a05f09da738','74dfdb3be3d296db4e284e57c8999ab7','2023-09-08 02:05:14','2023-10-28 23:11:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Primary Cell Culture',24,'Primary cell culture is the ex vivo culture of cells freshly obtained from a multicellular organism, as opposed to the culture of immortalized cell lines. In general, primary cell cultures are considered more representative of in vivo tissues than cell lines, and this is recognized legally in some countries such as the UK. However, primary cells require adequate substrate and nutrient conditions to thrive and after a certain number of divisions they acquire a senescent phenotype, leading to irreversible cell cycle arrest. The generation of cell lines stems from these two reasons. Primary cells can become immortalized either spontaneously or by genetic modification, at which point they become cell lines which can be subcultured indefinitely. Because of their requirements for viability, primary cell cultures did not become widespread until the 2000s.','{\"pat_doc\": 99.0, \"pub_alt\": 151.0, \"pub_doc\": 324.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 44.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 12.0, \"grant_fund\": 14171947.0, \"pat_granted\": 35.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 9.5, \"pub_doc\": -8.7, \"clinic_doc\": 2.5, \"grant_fund\": -4026979.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9ccdb49b1205cd96e531dfa612be12ea','f1df325e8a923b7c94ec1f46acdb203e','67ae7824162271af981ae2c6a606ee4e','2023-09-05 22:59:40','2023-10-28 12:00:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Memristor',24,'A memristor is a non-linear two-terminal electrical component relating electric charge and magnetic flux linkage. It was described and named in 1971 by Leon Chua, completing a theoretical quartet of fundamental electrical components which comprises also the resistor, capacitor and inductor. Chua and Kang later generalized the concept to memristive systems. Such a system comprises a circuit, of multiple conventional components, which mimics key properties of the ideal memristor component and is also commonly referred to as a memristor. Several such memristor system technologies have been developed, notably ReRAM. The identification of memristive properties in electronic devices has attracted controversy. Experimentally, the ideal memristor has yet to be demonstrated.','{\"pat_doc\": 1440.0, \"pub_alt\": 481.0, \"pub_doc\": 3833.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 77.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 40284467.0, \"pat_granted\": 515.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 108.5, \"pub_doc\": 242.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2583132.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9d570923458c7fed17586fe82abbd8ed','41d7ff0d462e6a3d557069a37ea17023','9c4ba206250041cf1644bb291a643634','2023-09-05 18:58:16','2023-10-29 05:25:05','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Next-Generation Sequencing',24,'Massive parallel sequencing or massively parallel sequencing is any of several high-throughput approaches to DNA sequencing using the concept of massively parallel processing; it is also called next-generation sequencing or second-generation sequencing. Some of these technologies emerged between 1993 and 1998 and have been commercially available since 2005. These technologies use miniaturized and parallelized platforms for sequencing of 1 million to 43 billion short reads per instrument run. Many NGS platforms differ in engineering configurations and sequencing chemistry. They share the technical paradigm of massive parallel sequencing via spatially separated, clonally amplified DNA templates or single DNA molecules in a flow cell. This design is very different from that of Sanger sequencingâ€”also known as capillary sequencing or first-generation sequencingâ€”which is based on electrophoretic separation of chain-termination products produced in individual sequencing reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 272.0, \"pub_alt\": 5565.0, \"pub_doc\": 13594.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 390.0, \"clinic_alt\": 58.0, \"clinic_doc\": 345.0, \"grant_fund\": 126089431.0, \"pat_granted\": 58.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.9, \"pub_doc\": 170.9, \"clinic_doc\": 72.6, \"grant_fund\": -38192044.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9d77f600c5bf6694394dc26bc0c857e3','224f79c7aefff29a3d4cd0f3806a209a','5439cfcadd881d98d0c7179fbcfec554','2023-09-08 02:01:45','2023-10-28 23:21:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Liquid Crystal Elastomers',12,'Liquid crystal elastomers (LCEs) are a class of materials that exhibit both the fluid-like properties of liquid crystals and the elasticity of an elastic solid. They are composed of polymeric chains that are cross-linked to form a three-dimensional network. The presence of liquid crystal domains allows these materials to exhibit several unusual properties, including reversible shape changes in response to external stimuli such as heat, light, or mechanical stress. This makes LCEs promising candidates for a range of applications, from soft robotics and actuators to biomedical devices and responsive materials.','{\"pat_doc\": 11.0, \"pub_alt\": 273.0, \"pub_doc\": 162.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 11455909.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 31.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2814310.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9d8a68af0f4368ba81ae40b63c6b7ced','b1f6b055bf7f576af1fda25a04ce64a1','d6145a42d41428a7d112c8f6aaaadaa8','2023-09-08 00:54:04','2023-10-29 01:01:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Digital Pathology',12,'Digital pathology is a sub-field of pathology that focuses on data management based on information generated from digitized specimen slides. Through the use of computer-based technology, digital pathology utilizes virtual microscopy. Glass slides are converted into digital slides that can be viewed, managed, shared and analyzed on a computer monitor. With the practice of Whole-Slide Imaging, which is another name for virtual microscopy, the field of digital pathology is growing and has applications in diagnostic medicine, with the goal of achieving efficient and cheaper diagnoses, prognosis, and prediction of diseases due to the success in machine learning and artificial intelligence in healthcare.','{\"pat_doc\": 179.0, \"pub_alt\": 896.0, \"pub_doc\": 653.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 25.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 17.0, \"grant_fund\": 13422412.0, \"pat_granted\": 55.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 31.4, \"pub_doc\": 91.6, \"clinic_doc\": 5.1, \"grant_fund\": -15307360.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9ddd3878b425215511f2151b4c865df5','92a972462fc449a3f071840dbe8b2742','392c6994beadcacc6139a1c22998f10f','2023-09-20 23:02:34','2023-10-28 18:26:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','spatial biology',36,'Spatial Biology is defined as the study of tissues within their own 2D or 3D context. It is the new frontier of molecular biology.\r\n\r\nConsider how GPS captures location coordinates within an area to create a map and track you within it. The same principle can be translated to spatial data on a cellular and molecular level.\r\n\r\nThrough this technology, we can help map the spatial architecture of a cell and how it talks to and interacts with its surroundings. Spatial biology is like being inside a tissue sample at a molecular level. It enables single-cell analysis. Through spatial biology tools, you are empowered to see things that are not possible by sequencing or any other technologies out there.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 407.0, \"pub_doc\": 134.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 18.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 16065885.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 26.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2600741.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9e1338a1b8f3123833ce712f2760ee20','f75d09446940f86ed08ebd34eebf7374','aa6c75c69a90f2c711a2a5e31bb1c990','2023-09-08 01:34:12','2023-10-29 00:06:22','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','mRNA sequencing',24,'mRNA sequencing refers to the process of analyzing the transcriptome of an organism by sequencing the messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules that are expressed in a given sample. mRNA is synthesized from DNA and contains the information required to make proteins, which are the building blocks of the cell. By sequencing the mRNA, researchers can identify which genes are being expressed in a specific tissue or cell type, and can also measure the abundance of each transcript. This information can be used to gain insights into the biological processes that are occurring in the organism, and can also be used to identify genes that are dysregulated in diseases such as cancer. mRNA sequencing has become a widely used technique for studying gene expression, and new methods are continually being developed to improve the accuracy and speed of this process.','{\"pat_doc\": 21.0, \"pub_alt\": 315.0, \"pub_doc\": 716.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 33.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 7867444.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.5, \"pub_doc\": 43.3, \"clinic_doc\": 1.2, \"grant_fund\": -1315097.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9e72c138ffdc9b3c7cf035001f6a03e8','c808cb9a80255cfef7c8736a22f3fd7d','586771bdb6aa5a69c62ea062df64fb52','2023-09-07 21:05:13','2023-10-28 11:55:32','Electronics','Components','Other','2D Materials',36,'2-Dimensional materials are a class of nanomaterials defined by their property of being merely one or two atoms thick. Graphene is at this time the material most commonly associated with 2-D materials.','{\"pat_doc\": 148.0, \"pub_alt\": 668.0, \"pub_doc\": 7479.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 720.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 464347218.0, \"pat_granted\": 36.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.3, \"pub_doc\": 184.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5014990.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9ea6d7cdff9e152e7900f3fc84a03411','7cad47d8fa337e04fde87c8076f4adfe','25cc485513e0e2921857b91eeab511ae','2023-09-08 08:31:01','2023-10-28 13:41:15','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Colorectal cancer',24,'Colorectal cancer, also known as bowel cancer, colon cancer, or rectal cancer, is the development of cancer from the colon or rectum. Signs and symptoms may include blood in the stool, a change in bowel movements, weight loss, and fatigue. Most colorectal cancers are due to old age and lifestyle factors, with only a small number of cases due to underlying genetic disorders. Risk factors include diet, obesity, smoking, and lack of physical activity. Dietary factors that increase the risk include red meat, processed meat, and alcohol. Another risk factor is inflammatory bowel disease, which includes Crohns disease and ulcerative colitis. Some of the inherited genetic disorders that can cause colorectal cancer include familial adenomatous polyposis and hereditary non-polyposis colon cancer; however, these represent less than 5% of cases. It typically starts as a benign tumor, often in the form of a polyp, which over time becomes cancerous.','{\"pat_doc\": 2776.0, \"pub_alt\": 7747.0, \"pub_doc\": 30797.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 879.0, \"clinic_alt\": 699.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2830.0, \"grant_fund\": 368525789.0, \"pat_granted\": 765.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 91.4, \"pub_doc\": 499.3, \"clinic_doc\": 542.0, \"grant_fund\": -69281414.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9eb42ddfc69111e8e42f358f59bfe18b','1728b9cb87efc77cfd614e3c4311a042','ee2727bc78203418d56b7f3bacf8d4dc','2023-09-08 01:47:28','2023-10-28 11:15:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Web 3.0',48,'Web 3.0, also known as the Semantic Web, refers to the evolution of the internet that aims to provide a more seamless and intelligent user experience. It is based on the idea of improving the way data is accessed and used, by creating a universal language for machines to understand and communicate with each other. This means that information on the web will be more interconnected, accessible, and easier to find. Web 3.0 aims to enable decentralization, personalization, and improved security on the internet. It has the potential to transform industries such as healthcare, finance, and education, by improving data sharing, privacy, and efficiency.','{\"pat_doc\": 17.0, \"pub_alt\": 338.0, \"pub_doc\": 631.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 24.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 3411251.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.3, \"pub_doc\": 89.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 613675.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('9eb74db445411fba34816bf4585f3246','dd3b10037cd066e53410e9747f800fec','9bd82f68388cbaa629adeec1747d02c9','2023-09-04 19:22:50','2023-10-28 12:55:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','5g',24,'5G refers to the fifth generation of mobile networks and is the successor to 4G. It represents a significant improvement in terms of speed, latency, and capacity, enabling faster download and upload speeds, quicker response times, and the ability to connect more devices to the network simultaneously. The new network technology uses higher frequency radio waves and advanced antenna technology to transmit and receive data more efficiently. The increased bandwidth of 5G networks will enhance the capabilities of emerging technologies such as virtual and augmented reality, driverless vehicles, and Internet of Things (IoT) devices. The deployment of 5G networks is currently underway worldwide, and it is expected to have a significant impact on the way we communicate and access information in the years to come.','{\"pat_doc\": 41242.0, \"pub_alt\": 866.0, \"pub_doc\": 33954.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1454.0, \"clinic_alt\": 61.0, \"clinic_doc\": 671.0, \"grant_fund\": 1176732211.0, \"pat_granted\": 16718.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1603.5, \"pub_doc\": 859.7, \"clinic_doc\": 107.3, \"grant_fund\": -2206973786.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a016d65485a613e53f0d5fca89e9b29f','4703ee189b43ed759604065a8ab8bcd0','38375efab29a9add974615a48ca4c5ab','2023-09-08 02:24:52','2023-10-28 22:21:09','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Crystallography',36,'Protein crystallography is a technique used to determine the precise three-dimensional structure of proteins. It involves growing crystals of a protein of interest and using X-rays to deduce the position of each atom within the crystal lattice. The resulting structure can provide valuable insights into the function of the protein, including its interactions with other molecules and potential drug targets. Protein crystallography has played a crucial role in the fields of biology, biochemistry, and drug discovery, and continues to be an important tool for understanding the molecular basis of disease.','{\"pat_doc\": 9.0, \"pub_alt\": 76.0, \"pub_doc\": 193.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 50.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 16779838.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 2.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -4868876.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a05cc61c4a72f603badcbd937af5ae4c','633e3e1c04bc9ee16dfcb222f957cce1','5ee4ac63831f6ebbfc5f216379d36d38','2023-09-08 08:27:45','2023-10-28 10:30:32','Electronics','Components','Other','Co-Packaged Optics',24,'Co-packaged optics is a term that refers to the integration of optical components within the silicon chip package, enabling high-speed computing to be achieved. This technology is expected to revolutionize the data center industry by enhancing speed and reducing power consumption. By eliminating fiber cabling and replacing it with on-board optical interconnects, co-packaged optics enables faster data transfer rates, better communication between processors, reduced data center infrastructure, and other significant benefits. An important aspect of this technology is that it leverages existing CMOS fabrication processes, ensuring compatibility with current manufacturing techniques. This new optical integration technology is set to push the capabilities of electronic data processing further than ever before, providing more efficient and faster data transfer speeds for data centers and beyond.','{\"pat_doc\": 34.0, \"pub_alt\": 2.0, \"pub_doc\": 88.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 8248536.0, \"pat_granted\": 9.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.6, \"pub_doc\": 13.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2486201.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a05efec94f1ba5df2c336c0cef43d37a','8445e498b5c8e24b28f8fe85d68e76af','33b4678f6b096b9a11757bc96a56f980','2023-09-08 01:16:53','2023-10-29 00:21:18','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Directed Evolution',48,'Directed evolution is a method used in protein engineering that mimics the process of natural selection to steer proteins or nucleic acids toward a user-defined goal. It consists of subjecting a gene to iterative rounds of mutagenesis, selection and amplification. It can be performed in vivo, or in vitro. Directed evolution is used both for protein engineering as an alternative to rationally designing modified proteins, as well as for experimental evolution studies of fundamental evolutionary principles in a controlled, laboratory environment.','{\"pat_doc\": 535.0, \"pub_alt\": 901.0, \"pub_doc\": 1854.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 444.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 196504667.0, \"pat_granted\": 169.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 25.3, \"pub_doc\": 7.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -10443235.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a08b782c674a6339fb6424d9fc3a56e1','99c7079af458b7e10d0e17de306286cf','7ec492ea6e0e56c5b381d422684157c5','2023-09-08 01:01:12','2023-09-08 01:01:12','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Cushing\'s Syndrome',36,'Cushing\'s syndrome is a collection of signs and symptoms due to prolonged exposure to glucocorticoids such as cortisol. Signs and symptoms may include high blood pressure, abdominal obesity but with thin arms and legs, reddish stretch marks, a round red face due to facial plethora, a fat lump between the shoulders, weak muscles, weak bones, acne, and fragile skin that heals poorly. Women may have more hair and irregular menstruation. Occasionally there may be changes in mood, headaches, and a chronic feeling of tiredness. Cushing\'s syndrome is caused by either excessive cortisol-like medication, such as prednisone, or a tumor that either produces or results in the production of excessive cortisol by the adrenal glands. Cases due to a pituitary adenoma are known as Cushing\'s disease, which is the second most common cause of Cushing\'s syndrome after medication. A number of other tumors, often referred to as ectopic due to their placement outside the pituitary, may also cause Cushing\'s.','{\"pat_doc\": 155.0, \"pub_alt\": 563.0, \"pub_doc\": 847.0, \"deals_num\": 5.0, \"grant_doc\": 10.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 66.0, \"grant_fund\": 1424796.0, \"pat_granted\": 57.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 4.0, \"capital_raised\": 2154.86746457}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.3, \"pub_doc\": 41.6, \"clinic_doc\": 8.9, \"grant_fund\": -229023.8, \"capital_raised\": 215.348}'),('a0984e8d8b2dad063a450ff172120bd1','26139c734216125329350135b2f763ec','95dd984c9978fee8a3271496b2247ff4','2023-09-08 00:25:57','2023-10-29 01:41:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Sorting',24,'Cell sorting is the process through which a particular cell type is separated from others contained in a sample on the basis of its physical or biological properties, such as size, morphological parameters, viability and both extracellular and intracellular protein expression. The homogeneous cell population obtained after sorting can be used for a variety of applications including research, diagnosis, and therapy.','{\"pat_doc\": 571.0, \"pub_alt\": 822.0, \"pub_doc\": 1841.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 165.0, \"clinic_alt\": 314.0, \"clinic_doc\": 39.0, \"grant_fund\": 82249242.0, \"pat_granted\": 231.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 39.0, \"pub_doc\": -33.8, \"clinic_doc\": 7.3, \"grant_fund\": -18215497.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a0ee9e4dbcd3f9fb41c3408392f96923','af4c9bfdfefe7c5c014015d91cb309a6','df80b2fb86114e734e7660ea92fdd1fc','2023-09-08 00:08:07','2023-10-29 02:01:16','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Viral Vectors',12,'Viral vectors are tools commonly used by molecular biologists to deliver genetic material into cells. This process can be performed inside a living organism or in cell culture. Viruses have evolved specialized molecular mechanisms to efficiently transport their genomes inside the cells they infect. Delivery of genes or other genetic material by a vector is termed transduction and the infected cells are described as transduced. Molecular biologists first harnessed this machinery in the 1970s. Paul Berg used a modified SV40 virus containing DNA from the bacteriophage Î» to infect monkey kidney cells maintained in culture. In addition to their use in molecular biology research, viral vectors are used for gene therapy and the development of vaccines. Vectors can either integrate into a cells genome or transiently express a gene with non-integrative vectors.','{\"pat_doc\": 941.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 926.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 102.0, \"clinic_alt\": 58.0, \"clinic_doc\": 19.0, \"grant_fund\": 107071117.0, \"pat_granted\": 146.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 84.9, \"pub_doc\": -18.6, \"clinic_doc\": 4.4, \"grant_fund\": -2376931.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a0f5751d3bdcfcdc6f721b7f393ca941','9d996765d8494cce256222ac0a94a875','c98801edf863685348c2c0b17f91ca87','2023-09-07 23:53:35','2023-10-28 16:56:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Hyperthyroidism',36,'Hyperthyroidism is the condition that occurs due to excessive production of thyroid hormones by the thyroid gland. Thyrotoxicosis is the condition that occurs due to excessive thyroid hormone of any cause and therefore includes hyperthyroidism. Some, however, use the terms interchangeably. Signs and symptoms vary between people and may include irritability, muscle weakness, sleeping problems, a fast heartbeat, heat intolerance, diarrhea, enlargement of the thyroid, hand tremor, and weight loss. Symptoms are typically less severe in the elderly and during pregnancy. An uncommon but life-threatening complication is thyroid storm in which an event such as an infection results in worsening symptoms such as confusion and a high temperature; this often results in death. The opposite is hypothyroidism, when the thyroid gland does not make enough thyroid hormone. Graves disease is the cause of about 50% to 80% of the cases of hyperthyroidism in the United States.','{\"pat_doc\": 112.0, \"pub_alt\": 1393.0, \"pub_doc\": 4317.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 32.0, \"clinic_alt\": 28.0, \"clinic_doc\": 232.0, \"grant_fund\": 5618321.0, \"pat_granted\": 48.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -7.0, \"pub_doc\": 88.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": -513561.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a13383af323d4198f4add920d6103c40','224d3dce630c1eacf85c0f88dd72e042','66dae1bd66572a9ac387868804da7fa9','2023-09-08 00:43:37','2023-10-28 16:11:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Monoclonal antibodies','Bispecific antibody',24,'A bispecific monoclonal antibody is an artificial protein that can simultaneously bind to two different types of antigen or two different epitopes on the same antigen. Naturally occurring antibodies typically only target one antigen. BsAbs can be manufactured in several structural formats. BsAbs can be designed to recruit and activate immune cells, to interfere with receptor signaling and inactivate signaling ligands, and to force association of protein complexes. BsAbs have been explored for cancer immunotherapy, drug delivery, and Alzeimers disease.','{\"pat_doc\": 2262.0, \"pub_alt\": 746.0, \"pub_doc\": 1087.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 33.0, \"clinic_alt\": 859.0, \"clinic_doc\": 220.0, \"grant_fund\": 69860820.0, \"pat_granted\": 359.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 160.2, \"pub_doc\": 80.4, \"clinic_doc\": 59.6, \"grant_fund\": 14897954.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a1b0c7581aa27622bcf57c9260d225e9','11ceddbe2884cfa304852a2ce17a1058','2483d5e44059b5dad528a46e9d77ee36','2023-09-08 00:49:58','2023-10-28 16:06:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','antisense oligonucleotides',48,'Antisense oligonucleotides (ASOs) are short single-stranded pieces of DNA or RNA that bind to specific target mRNA molecules to regulate gene expression. ASOs are designed to silence a particular gene by preventing the translation of mRNA into protein, which can be useful in treating genetic disorders caused by overexpression or abnormal splicing of certain genes. ASOs are made up of a sequence complementary to the target mRNA, and once bound, they can recruit cellular machinery to degrade the mRNA or block its translation. ASOs are a promising therapeutic strategy for a variety of diseases, including cancer, viral infections, and genetic disorders.','{\"pat_doc\": 1641.0, \"pub_alt\": 1072.0, \"pub_doc\": 1847.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 240.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 131301646.0, \"pat_granted\": 301.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 12.1, \"pub_doc\": 27.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -4641956.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a35236fc7cf1ed7e7f0460bd78e41902','ab4b6025c38d1cab8fd476593532cb60','8c907d5d7b60b5604cad502b2ab3ea5b','2023-09-08 01:44:40','2023-10-28 11:20:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Societal & Economic Disruptions','Russia-Ukraine conflict',36,'The Russo-Ukrainian War is an ongoing international conflict between Russia, alongside Russian-backed separatists, and Ukraine, which began in February 2014. Following Ukraines Revolution of Dignity, Russia annexed Crimea from Ukraine and supported pro-Russian separatists fighting the Ukrainian military in the Donbas war. The first eight years of conflict also included naval incidents, cyberwarfare, and heightened political tensions. In February 2022, Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine. In early 2014, the Euromaidan protests led to the Revolution of Dignity and the ousting of Ukraines pro-Russian president Viktor Yanukovych. Shortly after, pro-Russian unrest erupted in eastern and southern Ukraine. Simultaneously, unmarked Russian troops moved into Ukraines Crimea and took over government buildings, strategic sites and infrastructure. Russia soon annexed Crimea after a highly-disputed referendum.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 4755.0, \"pub_doc\": 379.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 529815.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 93.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 113103.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a36fbfd2a1a3e7a8cff3ecf0b47c1fce','d86696ef8204e2fe630e53d5acb96743','0df45be154a854c136cea54f3239586e','2023-09-08 01:15:36','2023-10-28 15:31:15','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Hypoparathyroidism',48,'Hypoparathyroidism is decreased function of the parathyroid glands with underproduction of parathyroid hormone. This can lead to low levels of calcium in the blood, often causing cramping and twitching of muscles or tetany, and several other symptoms. It is a very rare disease. The condition can be inherited, but it is also encountered after thyroid or parathyroid gland surgery, and it can be caused by immune system-related damage as well as a number of rarer causes. The diagnosis is made with blood tests, and other investigations such as genetic testing depending on the results. The primary treatment of hypoparathyroidism is calcium and vitamin D supplementation. Calcium replacement or vitamin D can ameliorate the symptoms but can increase the risk of kidney stones and chronic kidney disease. Additionally, medications such as recombinant human parathyroid hormone or teriparatide may be given by injection to replace the missing hormone.','{\"pat_doc\": 121.0, \"pub_alt\": 362.0, \"pub_doc\": 2209.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 19.0, \"clinic_alt\": 60.0, \"clinic_doc\": 127.0, \"grant_fund\": 9244081.0, \"pat_granted\": 23.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.5, \"pub_doc\": 2.7, \"clinic_doc\": 13.5, \"grant_fund\": -516093.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a40e766680ef781ac1de5588764a3f22','fa50c7193d6065602454c2f7f0f8ac8f','089d2934c16e188b76ea22692ecca87c','2023-09-08 09:52:02','2023-10-28 20:11:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Affinity Chromatography',36,'Affinity chromatography is a method of separating a biomolecule from a mixture, based on a highly specific macromolecular binding interaction between the biomolecule and another substance. The specific type of binding interaction depends on the biomolecule of interest; antigen and antibody, enzyme and substrate, receptor and ligand, or protein and nucleic acid binding interactions are frequently exploited for isolation of various biomolecules. Affinity chromatography is useful for its high selectivity and resolution of separation, compared to other chromatographic methods.','{\"pat_doc\": 1273.0, \"pub_alt\": 356.0, \"pub_doc\": 1792.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 64.0, \"clinic_alt\": 8.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 7755372.0, \"pat_granted\": 414.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 7.8, \"pub_doc\": -45.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.5, \"grant_fund\": -1797705.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a41b6793b4c91407fb3b8ee7d3635b24','5421c4aba6fdcb923ad6893affebb649','ad96306f7a3e23d74408bb23ac8e0e9a','2023-09-08 09:55:35','2023-10-28 19:56:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Near-infrared imaging',12,'Near-infrared (NIR) imaging refers to a technique in which light in the near-infrared spectrum is used to create images of biological specimens. This technique is popular in the medical field, especially in cancer diagnosis and treatment. NIR light penetrates deeper into biological tissues than visible light and is absorbed by various molecules, including water, lipids, and proteins. By measuring the reflected or absorbed light, NIR imaging allows for the detection of abnormalities such as tumors. NIR imaging is non-invasive, fast, and does not require ionizing radiation, making it a safer alternative to other imaging techniques. It also has potential applications in areas such as agriculture, food, and environmental monitoring.','{\"pat_doc\": 22.0, \"pub_alt\": 388.0, \"pub_doc\": 127.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 20.0, \"grant_fund\": 1966821.0, \"pat_granted\": 9.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.8, \"pub_doc\": 0.6, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": -73702.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a462c37841a616cb344870cd028bfadc','d26eb2bd1f18468fd4cd16acbcfe71a0','0de5062bb6f653f85fa36c9feb30d5e1','2023-09-08 01:30:22','2023-10-29 00:11:22','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Robotic Process Automation',36,'Robotic process automation is a form of business process automation that is based on software robots or artificial intelligence agents. It is sometimes referred to as software robotics. In traditional workflow automation tools, a software developer produces a list of actions to automate a task and interface to the back end system using internal application programming interfaces or dedicated scripting language. In contrast, RPA systems develop the action list by watching the user perform that task in the applications graphical user interface, and then perform the automation by repeating those tasks directly in the GUI. This can lower the barrier to the use of automation in products that might not otherwise feature APIs for this purpose. RPA tools have strong technical similarities to graphical user interface testing tools. These tools also automate interactions with the GUI, and often do so by repeating a set of demonstration actions performed by a user.','{\"pat_doc\": 1077.0, \"pub_alt\": 119.0, \"pub_doc\": 936.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 25.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 3532954.0, \"pat_granted\": 230.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 111.3, \"pub_doc\": 68.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -911088.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a47815a5a251010f98faf21520717662','40a0355ede62ff4272058fe5b25b12bf','eefb2660a8535eb1d304c9a60295324f','2023-09-05 21:19:43','2023-10-28 17:46:11','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Liposomes',36,'A liposome is a small artificial vesicle, spherical in shape, having at least one lipid bilayer. Due to their hydrophobicity and/or hydrophilicity, biocompatibility, particle size and many other properties, liposomes can be used as drug delivery vehicles for administration of pharmaceutical drugs and nutrients, such as lipid nanoparticles in mRNA vaccines, and DNA vaccines. Liposomes can be prepared by disrupting biological membranes. Liposomes are most often composed of phospholipids, especially phosphatidylcholine, and cholesterol, but may also include other lipids, such as those found in egg and phosphatidylethanolamine, as long as they are compatible with lipid bilayer structure. A liposome design may employ surface ligands for attaching to unhealthy tissue. The major types of liposomes are the multilamellar vesicle, the small unilamellar liposome vesicle, the large unilamellar vesicle, and the cochleate vesicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 2373.0, \"pub_alt\": 590.0, \"pub_doc\": 9296.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 411.0, \"clinic_alt\": 108.0, \"clinic_doc\": 57.0, \"grant_fund\": 113084615.0, \"pat_granted\": 601.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 11.3, \"pub_doc\": 166.2, \"clinic_doc\": 8.1, \"grant_fund\": -13776868.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a5c4134038679dbeb66ef57e4ccb1a27','593e0b5980cd1f5c381a759416640c82','fac8fdaee075a0078ef0f1af1e190a56','2023-09-08 02:54:38','2023-10-28 10:40:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Neuromorphic Photonics',48,'Neuromorphic photonics is an area of research that seeks to combine the principles of neuroscience and photonics, a field of study that deals with light and its properties. Scientists working in the field aim to create artificial systems that can process information in a way that mimics the human brain, using light instead of electrical signals. By doing this, they hope to create more efficient and powerful computing systems that can tackle complex tasks such as image recognition and natural language processing with ease. Neuromorphic photonics is still in the early stages of development, but it has the potential to revolutionize the field of artificial intelligence and lead to a new generation of smart machines.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 134.0, \"pub_doc\": 96.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 314937.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -51400.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a5e5ed59dffa4dfc2e07837386a83c29','f1c040e063712c5005b473ffb13588a1','cdaeb54e11180a1df70eb5bc5267c9f8','2023-09-08 09:46:18','2023-10-28 20:36:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Centrifugation',36,'Centrifugation is a mechanical process which involves the use of the centrifugal force to separate particles from a solution according to their size, shape, density, medium viscosity and rotor speed. The denser components of the mixture migrate away from the axis of the centrifuge, while the less dense components of the mixture migrate towards the axis. Chemists and biologists may increase the effective gravitational force of the test tube so that the precipitate will travel quickly and fully to the bottom of the tube. The remaining liquid that lies above the precipitate is called a supernatant or supernate. There is a correlation between the size and density of a particle and the rate that the particle separates from a heterogeneous mixture, when the only force applied is that of gravity. The larger the size and the larger the density of the particles, the faster they separate from the mixture.','{\"pat_doc\": 12227.0, \"pub_alt\": 488.0, \"pub_doc\": 8784.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 299.0, \"clinic_alt\": 45.0, \"clinic_doc\": 400.0, \"grant_fund\": 49379456.0, \"pat_granted\": 6304.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -24.6, \"pub_doc\": 42.5, \"clinic_doc\": 50.1, \"grant_fund\": -9080944.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a5fb718ca543f6d71ba102f12248c754','3826e17fd1b8b38d7108087bc8b07908','22c986a1ed138cca635623e24850cd2d','2023-09-08 02:47:26','2023-10-28 14:01:15','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel therapies','Progesterone supplementation',24,'Progesterone supplementation, also known as progesterone therapy, is a medical treatment that involves taking supplemental doses of progesterone hormone. Progesterone is naturally produced by the ovaries during a womans menstrual cycle and plays a crucial role in regulating the menstrual cycle and preparing the body for pregnancy. However, some women may have low levels of progesterone, resulting in irregular menstrual cycles or difficulty getting pregnant. Progesterone supplementation can help balance hormonal levels and increase the chances of conceiving and sustaining a pregnancy. It can be administered through various methods, such as pills, injections, or vaginal suppositories, and is usually prescribed by a healthcare professional based on the patients individual needs and medical history.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 73.0, \"pub_doc\": 91.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 24.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 3.4, \"grant_fund\": -80930.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a64bfc7acf7f1fa336bf8ece84b507c7','2189df4a2bc6ca2c1f680fee94f5b10c','41bec6af04474eb4358a3a371286538c','2023-09-07 23:37:46','2023-10-29 02:36:13','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Gene Silencing',48,'Gene silencing is the regulation of gene expression in a cell to prevent the expression of a certain gene. Gene silencing can occur during either transcription or translation and is often used in research. In particular, methods used to silence genes are being increasingly used to produce therapeutics to combat cancer and other diseases, such as infectious diseases and neurodegenerative disorders. Gene silencing is often considered the same as gene knockdown. When genes are silenced, their expression is reduced. In contrast, when genes are knocked out, they are completely erased from the organisms genome and, thus, have no expression. Gene silencing is considered a gene knockdown mechanism since the methods used to silence genes, such as RNAi, CRISPR, or siRNA, generally reduce the expression of a gene by at least 70% but do not eliminate it.','{\"pat_doc\": 984.0, \"pub_alt\": 846.0, \"pub_doc\": 6097.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 498.0, \"clinic_alt\": 16.0, \"clinic_doc\": 17.0, \"grant_fund\": 181471191.0, \"pat_granted\": 331.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 13.2, \"pub_doc\": -3.1, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": -9870496.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a698f2436c345c0893d8d57a7f2647ff','4823e60bd764349fc024f2fba11838f0','30640b686e5be896faa3d14ed6691346','2023-09-05 18:49:44','2023-10-29 05:35:06','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Biosensor',36,'A biosensor is an analytical device, used for the detection of a chemical substance, that combines a biological component with a physicochemical detector. The sensitive biological element, e.g. tissue, microorganisms, organelles, cell receptors, enzymes, antibodies, nucleic acids, etc., is a biologically derived material or biomimetic component that interacts with, binds with, or recognizes the analyte under study. The biologically sensitive elements can also be created by biological engineering. The transducer or the detector element, which transforms one signal into another one, works in a physicochemical way: optical, piezoelectric, electrochemical, electrochemiluminescence etc., resulting from the interaction of the analyte with the biological element, to easily measure and quantify. The biosensor reader device connects with the associated electronics or signal processors that are primarily responsible for the display of the results in a user-friendly way.','{\"pat_doc\": 7686.0, \"pub_alt\": 3920.0, \"pub_doc\": 26404.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1614.0, \"clinic_alt\": 52.0, \"clinic_doc\": 141.0, \"grant_fund\": 751880011.0, \"pat_granted\": 2491.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 137.4, \"pub_doc\": 867.1, \"clinic_doc\": 19.0, \"grant_fund\": -13437491.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a6fb2286122151d1ec306bb6d4467aa6','fa50c7193d6065602454c2f7f0f8ac8f','089d2934c16e188b76ea22692ecca87c','2023-09-08 09:52:02','2023-10-28 20:11:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Affinity Chromatography',24,'Affinity chromatography is a method of separating a biomolecule from a mixture, based on a highly specific macromolecular binding interaction between the biomolecule and another substance. The specific type of binding interaction depends on the biomolecule of interest; antigen and antibody, enzyme and substrate, receptor and ligand, or protein and nucleic acid binding interactions are frequently exploited for isolation of various biomolecules. Affinity chromatography is useful for its high selectivity and resolution of separation, compared to other chromatographic methods.','{\"pat_doc\": 843.0, \"pub_alt\": 155.0, \"pub_doc\": 1160.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 35.0, \"clinic_alt\": 8.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 3697427.0, \"pat_granted\": 264.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 7.8, \"pub_doc\": -45.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.5, \"grant_fund\": -1797705.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a7c019642f7f1f376f11fe555fdffedd','d0cc167aa82d70fd2bfffe86208ac337','870950b481f06063886edd5c24dd2f8a','2023-09-08 09:13:24','2023-10-28 13:06:13','Healthcare','Neuroscience','Other','Neuro-inflammation',24,'Neuroinflammation is inflammation of the nervous tissue. It may be initiated in response to a variety of cues, including infection, traumatic brain injury, toxic metabolites, or autoimmunity. In the central nervous system, including the brain and spinal cord, microglia are the resident innate immune cells that are activated in response to these cues. The CNS is typically an immunologically privileged site because peripheral immune cells are generally blocked by the bloodâ€“brain barrier, a specialized structure composed of astrocytes and endothelial cells. However, circulating peripheral immune cells may surpass a compromised BBB and encounter neurons and glial cells expressing major histocompatibility complex molecules, perpetuating the immune response. Although the response is initiated to protect the central nervous system from the infectious agent, the effect may be toxic and widespread inflammation as well as further migration of leukocytes through the bloodâ€“brain barrier may occur.','{\"pat_doc\": 16.0, \"pub_alt\": 602.0, \"pub_doc\": 278.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 22.0, \"clinic_alt\": 35.0, \"clinic_doc\": 31.0, \"grant_fund\": 14981741.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": -14.9, \"clinic_doc\": 6.2, \"grant_fund\": -2859987.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a819288b12842c94fb176b3c8dc74930','fff9e1e5499bae01aa4fb0b484f21e1e','6a1c4a31986c97cfddf4de1bf91188d1','2023-09-05 21:08:55','2023-10-28 12:35:32','Electronics','Devices','Connectivity','Wearable devices',48,'Wearable technology is any technology that is designed to be used while worn. Common types of wearable technology include smartwatches and smartglasses. Wearable electronic devices are often close to or on the surface of the skin, where they detect, analyze, and transmit information such as vital signs, and/or ambient data and which allow in some cases immediate biofeedback to the wearer. Wearable devices such as activity trackers are an example of the Internet of Things, since \"things\" such as electronics, software, sensors, and connectivity are effectors that enable objects to exchange data through the internet with a manufacturer, operator, and/or other connected devices, without requiring human intervention. Wearable technology offers a wide range of possible uses, from communication and entertainment to improving health and fitness, however, there are worries about privacy and security because wearable devices have the ability to collect personal data.','{\"pat_doc\": 3094.0, \"pub_alt\": 4130.0, \"pub_doc\": 11807.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 629.0, \"clinic_alt\": 525.0, \"clinic_doc\": 320.0, \"grant_fund\": 329473544.0, \"pat_granted\": 1100.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 43.4, \"pub_doc\": 482.3, \"clinic_doc\": 56.6, \"grant_fund\": 2342060.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a82d24a87a4ef9b09c28d23b0f3c9e6e','0130bb7e16467c607ae66d5d6b5fe5d1','69904542b990c5c24086b0dfa8c698cf','2023-09-05 22:51:40','2023-10-29 03:01:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','High-Throughput Screening',48,'High-throughput screening is a method for scientific experimentation especially used in drug discovery and relevant to the fields of biology, materials science and chemistry. Using robotics, data processing/control software, liquid handling devices, and sensitive detectors, high-throughput screening allows a researcher to quickly conduct millions of chemical, genetic, or pharmacological tests. Through this process one can quickly recognize active compounds, antibodies, or genes that modulate a particular biomolecular pathway. The results of these experiments provide starting points for drug design and for understanding the noninteraction or role of a particular location.','{\"pat_doc\": 1072.0, \"pub_alt\": 1213.0, \"pub_doc\": 5758.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 713.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.0, \"grant_fund\": 734054113.0, \"pat_granted\": 340.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.8, \"pub_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -83628586.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a89cee71d2591b67587372b9a80fc0d5','b1f6b055bf7f576af1fda25a04ce64a1','d6145a42d41428a7d112c8f6aaaadaa8','2023-09-08 00:54:04','2023-10-29 01:01:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Digital Pathology',48,'Digital pathology is a sub-field of pathology that focuses on data management based on information generated from digitized specimen slides. Through the use of computer-based technology, digital pathology utilizes virtual microscopy. Glass slides are converted into digital slides that can be viewed, managed, shared and analyzed on a computer monitor. With the practice of Whole-Slide Imaging, which is another name for virtual microscopy, the field of digital pathology is growing and has applications in diagnostic medicine, with the goal of achieving efficient and cheaper diagnoses, prognosis, and prediction of diseases due to the success in machine learning and artificial intelligence in healthcare.','{\"pat_doc\": 542.0, \"pub_alt\": 896.0, \"pub_doc\": 2100.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 157.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 19.0, \"grant_fund\": 173538529.0, \"pat_granted\": 155.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 31.4, \"pub_doc\": 91.6, \"clinic_doc\": 5.1, \"grant_fund\": -15307360.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a8a646fc8cffd36980fe17c5ad55d781','fa50c7193d6065602454c2f7f0f8ac8f','089d2934c16e188b76ea22692ecca87c','2023-09-08 09:52:02','2023-10-28 20:11:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Affinity Chromatography',12,'Affinity chromatography is a method of separating a biomolecule from a mixture, based on a highly specific macromolecular binding interaction between the biomolecule and another substance. The specific type of binding interaction depends on the biomolecule of interest; antigen and antibody, enzyme and substrate, receptor and ligand, or protein and nucleic acid binding interactions are frequently exploited for isolation of various biomolecules. Affinity chromatography is useful for its high selectivity and resolution of separation, compared to other chromatographic methods.','{\"pat_doc\": 395.0, \"pub_alt\": 155.0, \"pub_doc\": 525.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 12.0, \"clinic_alt\": 8.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 2507916.0, \"pat_granted\": 125.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 7.8, \"pub_doc\": -45.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.5, \"grant_fund\": -1797705.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a8c7fc49f1e817cfa6a38aace1902962','1db9ef424bfbfaef3351c1c0c2bbb420','bb12623092a23c745c2bf47641f215ad','2023-09-08 09:57:46','2023-10-28 19:46:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Amino Acid Analysis',12,'Amino acid analysis is a common method used to determine the quantity and composition of amino acids in a protein or peptide sample. This technique involves acid hydrolysis of the protein or peptide, which breaks down the peptide bonds and releases the individual amino acids. The resulting mixture of amino acids is then separated and quantified using various analytical techniques such as high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) or gas chromatography (GC). This analysis provides valuable information about the composition and concentration of amino acids, which can be used to deduce the sequence of the peptide or identify the protein. This technique is widely used in research, industrial, and clinical settings for various applications such as protein characterization, quality control, and dietary analysis.','{\"pat_doc\": 15.0, \"pub_alt\": 25.0, \"pub_doc\": 135.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": 3.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -90894.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a9612b028c869ae4ce95da41579c236c','5f1ee7663407442aa2582d3efd1ad42b','5320de801f6c227388f87a0edfc49eb4','2023-09-04 19:25:15','2023-10-29 06:06:07','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Metabolomics',48,'Metabolomics is the scientific study of chemical processes involving metabolites, the small molecule substrates, intermediates, and products of cell metabolism. Specifically, metabolomics is the \"systematic study of the unique chemical fingerprints that specific cellular processes leave behind\", the study of their small-molecule metabolite profiles. The metabolome represents the complete set of metabolites in a biological cell, tissue, organ, or organism, which are the end products of cellular processes. Messenger RNA, gene expression data, and proteomic analyses reveal the set of gene products being produced in the cell, data that represents one aspect of cellular function. Conversely, metabolic profiling can give an instantaneous snapshot of the physiology of that cell, and thus, metabolomics provides a direct \"functional readout of the physiological state\" of an organism.','{\"pat_doc\": 148.0, \"pub_alt\": 5232.0, \"pub_doc\": 27284.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2614.0, \"clinic_alt\": 322.0, \"clinic_doc\": 960.0, \"grant_fund\": 1661189455.0, \"pat_granted\": 40.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.2, \"pub_doc\": 1091.2, \"clinic_doc\": 144.0, \"grant_fund\": -118313386.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a96a06922eaf461918b353f295d2443f','b5180881c0acd170e35e7e2628346b44','6f23015b34810fffb37ea505c3bdbd67','2023-09-05 19:31:51','2023-10-29 05:01:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Culture',24,'Cell culture or tissue culture is the process by which cells are grown under controlled conditions, generally outside of their natural environment. The term \"tissue culture\" was coined by American pathologist Montrose Thomas Burrows. This technique is also called micropropagation. After the cells of interest have been isolated from living tissue, they can subsequently be maintained under carefully controlled conditions. They need to be kept at body temperature in an incubator. These conditions vary for each cell type, but generally consist of a suitable vessel with a substrate or rich medium that supplies the essential nutrients, growth factors, hormones, and gases, and regulates the physio-chemical environment. Most cells require a surface or an artificial substrate to form an adherent culture as a monolayer, whereas others can be grown free floating in a medium as a suspension culture.','{\"pat_doc\": 12256.0, \"pub_alt\": 6747.0, \"pub_doc\": 14391.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1546.0, \"clinic_alt\": 504.0, \"clinic_doc\": 237.0, \"grant_fund\": 505857447.0, \"pat_granted\": 4832.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 342.7, \"pub_doc\": -154.3, \"clinic_doc\": 41.7, \"grant_fund\": -133904294.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a9a14d8c0ea25c1a11fbd3a822491cc9','11ceddbe2884cfa304852a2ce17a1058','2483d5e44059b5dad528a46e9d77ee36','2023-09-08 00:49:58','2023-10-28 16:06:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','antisense oligonucleotides',12,'Antisense oligonucleotides (ASOs) are short single-stranded pieces of DNA or RNA that bind to specific target mRNA molecules to regulate gene expression. ASOs are designed to silence a particular gene by preventing the translation of mRNA into protein, which can be useful in treating genetic disorders caused by overexpression or abnormal splicing of certain genes. ASOs are made up of a sequence complementary to the target mRNA, and once bound, they can recruit cellular machinery to degrade the mRNA or block its translation. ASOs are a promising therapeutic strategy for a variety of diseases, including cancer, viral infections, and genetic disorders.','{\"pat_doc\": 401.0, \"pub_alt\": 334.0, \"pub_doc\": 500.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 58.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 27939065.0, \"pat_granted\": 66.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 12.1, \"pub_doc\": 27.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -4641956.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a9ad88eac8cbea69e88db1675ee04d1b','42dcab631334ddefd1aa257b8b5f1e8f','eefb2660a8535eb1d304c9a60295324f','2023-09-05 21:18:18','2023-10-29 04:01:40','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Liposomes',12,'A liposome is a small artificial vesicle, spherical in shape, having at least one lipid bilayer. Due to their hydrophobicity and/or hydrophilicity, biocompatibility, particle size and many other properties, liposomes can be used as drug delivery vehicles for administration of pharmaceutical drugs and nutrients, such as lipid nanoparticles in mRNA vaccines, and DNA vaccines. Liposomes can be prepared by disrupting biological membranes. Liposomes are most often composed of phospholipids, especially phosphatidylcholine, and cholesterol, but may also include other lipids, such as those found in egg and phosphatidylethanolamine, as long as they are compatible with lipid bilayer structure. A liposome design may employ surface ligands for attaching to unhealthy tissue. The major types of liposomes are the multilamellar vesicle, the small unilamellar liposome vesicle, the large unilamellar vesicle, and the cochleate vesicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 778.0, \"pub_alt\": 501.0, \"pub_doc\": 3162.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 74.0, \"clinic_alt\": 108.0, \"clinic_doc\": 38.0, \"grant_fund\": 24093602.0, \"pat_granted\": 208.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 12.3, \"pub_doc\": 172.3, \"clinic_doc\": 8.1, \"grant_fund\": -13776868.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a9c8ffe1af1e109c3d0a6cc5cb265466','d5e0c4320bf432eb18619675fba4a2d6','dc3eb969daa777d1268e99485984656d','2023-09-07 23:34:57','2023-10-28 17:16:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes',12,'Tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes are white blood cells that have left the bloodstream and migrated towards a tumor. They include T cells and B cells and are part of the larger category of â€˜tumor-infiltrating immune cells which consist of both mononuclear and polymorphonuclear immune cells, in variable proportions. Their abundance varies with tumor type and stage and in some cases relates to disease prognosis. TILs can often be found in the tumor stroma and within the tumor itself. Their functions can dynamically change throughout tumor progression and in response to anticancer therapy TILs are implicated in killing tumor cells. The presence of lymphocytes in tumors is often associated with better clinical outcomes.','{\"pat_doc\": 90.0, \"pub_alt\": 680.0, \"pub_doc\": 936.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 20.0, \"clinic_alt\": 467.0, \"clinic_doc\": 76.0, \"grant_fund\": 6755565.0, \"pat_granted\": 11.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.9, \"pub_doc\": 39.6, \"clinic_doc\": 20.1, \"grant_fund\": -2417367.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('a9cb0b36ba7496237916f2a309d6d9f5','9ac2c447720a37348ec3adf931d10093','10ca8f5850cbd8a1f9e8a6552dd0293d','2023-09-08 02:56:51','2023-10-28 13:46:12','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel therapies','Gonadotropin Stimulation',24,'Gonadotropin stimulation is a medical procedure that is used to increase the production of hormones that are responsible for regulating the reproductive system. The process involves administering a hormone called gonadotropin to the patient. This hormone stimulates the ovaries and testes to produce more eggs and sperm, respectively. Gonadotropin stimulation is commonly used in the treatment of infertility, as it can increase the chances of conceiving a child. The procedure is usually performed in conjunction with in vitro fertilization (IVF) or intrauterine insemination (IUI) to increase the chances of a successful pregnancy. However, gonadotropin stimulation is not without its risks and complications, which can include multiple pregnancies, ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome, and ectopic pregnancy. Patients undergoing this procedure should be carefully monitored by their healthcare provider to ensure their safety and well-being.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 278.0, \"pub_doc\": 72.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": -2.8, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('aa293707a764aa1be862f28986788464','3be40ed2b8c2e8e952c0d1e6215ce7bc','d884de485418948cbb2562e1d885751d','2023-09-08 02:06:23','2023-09-08 02:06:23','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Addison\'s Disease',36,'Addison\'s disease, also known as primary adrenal insufficiency, is a rare long-term endocrine disorder characterized by inadequate production of the steroid hormones cortisol and aldosterone by the two outer layers of the cells of the adrenal glands, causing adrenal insufficiency. Symptoms generally come on slowly and insidiously and may include abdominal pain and gastrointestinal abnormalities, weakness, and weight loss. Darkening of the skin in certain areas may also occur. Under certain circumstances, an adrenal crisis may occur with low blood pressure, vomiting, lower back pain, and loss of consciousness. Mood changes may also occur. Rapid onset of symptoms indicates acute adrenal failure, which is a clinical emergency. An adrenal crisis can be triggered by stress, such as from an injury, surgery, or infection. Addison\'s disease arises from problems with the adrenal gland such that not enough of the steroid hormone cortisol and possibly aldosterone are produced.','{\"pat_doc\": 29.0, \"pub_alt\": 1437.0, \"pub_doc\": 200.0, \"deals_num\": 3.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 12.0, \"grant_fund\": 1372726.0, \"pat_granted\": 5.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 1.0, \"capital_raised\": 3.945}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": 1.5, \"clinic_doc\": 2.8, \"grant_fund\": -203023.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.806}'),('aa55966851d4bdf6142aaa8951fbf19b','69a17d20e0dd95936b11c342f374274e','21412fd8c571a6c3727e6a6906b7c1a8','2023-09-08 02:19:08','2023-10-28 22:31:10','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Synthesis',48,'mRNA synthesis, also known as transcription, is a process that occurs in the nucleus of a cell whereby DNA is copied into a single strand of messenger RNA (mRNA). This process involves the separation of the two strands of DNA and the synthesizing of an mRNA strand using one of the DNA strands as a template. The mRNA formed during transcription will carry a genetic message from the DNA to the ribosome, where it will be translated into a protein. This process is a critical step in gene expression and the regulation of cellular processes. Defects in mRNA synthesis can lead to genetic disorders, developmental abnormalities, and diseases, making it an important area of study for geneticists and molecular biologists.','{\"pat_doc\": 9.0, \"pub_alt\": 755.0, \"pub_doc\": 244.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 28.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 17120411.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.1, \"pub_doc\": 2.4, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -2023051.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('aa63055c468b8bab442eba1f380ef149','b7fe7c9d15ecc10608a0a70e65bacf5e','1c1aa7729e1e2fdd7a421fd9a7014e0a','2023-09-05 19:45:22','2023-10-28 12:50:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Augmented reality',24,'Augmented reality is an interactive experience that combines the real world and computer-generated content. The content can span multiple sensory modalities, including visual, auditory, haptic, somatosensory and olfactory. AR can be defined as a system that incorporates three basic features: a combination of real and virtual worlds, real-time interaction, and accurate 3D registration of virtual and real objects. The overlaid sensory information can be constructive, or destructive. This experience is seamlessly interwoven with the physical world such that it is perceived as an immersive aspect of the real environment. In this way, augmented reality alters ones ongoing perception of a real-world environment, whereas virtual reality completely replaces the users real-world environment with a simulated one. Augmented reality is largely synonymous with mixed reality. There is also overlap in terminology with extended reality and computer-mediated reality.','{\"pat_doc\": 15900.0, \"pub_alt\": 451.0, \"pub_doc\": 13955.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 744.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 180.0, \"grant_fund\": 426527843.0, \"pat_granted\": 5325.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 480.5, \"pub_doc\": 671.6, \"clinic_doc\": 35.2, \"grant_fund\": -13626091.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('aa6fb1878881db373deb8f256148c00a','b6bd0e112ac4b84a4babc4781241a61c','eaab7bb973ab23e8de7a128f3cda6817','2023-09-08 00:05:29','2023-10-28 16:41:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Mesenchymal stromal cells',48,'Mesenchymal stem cells also known as mesenchymal stromal cells or medicinal signaling cells are multipotent stromal cells that can differentiate into a variety of cell types, including osteoblasts, chondrocytes, myocytes and adipocytes.','{\"pat_doc\": 280.0, \"pub_alt\": 495.0, \"pub_doc\": 4770.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 208.0, \"clinic_alt\": 945.0, \"clinic_doc\": 185.0, \"grant_fund\": 73435968.0, \"pat_granted\": 37.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": -47.2, \"clinic_doc\": 30.5, \"grant_fund\": -5473780.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('aa8438cffb63134c2b0af0a4d84815ea','9cb1fcb17b688427ac67a33166effbb2','5ed796512ab4425cf98a4d2c7cdf5653','2023-09-05 20:27:46','2023-10-28 18:01:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Hematopoietic Stem Cells',48,'Hematopoietic stem cells are the stem cells that give rise to other blood cells. This process is called haematopoiesis. In vertebrates, the very first definitive HSCs arise from the ventral endothelial wall of the embryonic aorta within the aorta-gonad-mesonephros region, through a process known as endothelial-to-hematopoietic transition. In adults, haematopoiesis occurs in the red bone marrow, in the core of most bones. The red bone marrow is derived from the layer of the embryo called the mesoderm. Haematopoiesis is the process by which all mature blood cells are produced. It must balance enormous production needs with the need to regulate the number of each blood cell type in the circulation. In vertebrates, the vast majority of hematopoiesis occurs in the bone marrow and is derived from a limited number of hematopoietic stem cells that are multipotent and capable of extensive self-renewal.','{\"pat_doc\": 1765.0, \"pub_alt\": 1334.0, \"pub_doc\": 5561.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 773.0, \"clinic_alt\": 164.0, \"clinic_doc\": 290.0, \"grant_fund\": 381919423.0, \"pat_granted\": 409.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -13.9, \"pub_doc\": -37.5, \"clinic_doc\": 48.6, \"grant_fund\": -17355143.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('aa84e29ddf5d678f7d0b5fc14942aee5','05aa0de4a4917d54e102e40d1b76c9e1','fd6371fdffdf19bf1bf3ac9102b5acf9','2023-09-08 01:59:23','2023-10-28 23:31:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Autoclaving',36,'An autoclave is a machine used to carry out industrial and scientific processes requiring elevated temperature and pressure in relation to ambient pressure and/or temperature. Autoclaves are used before surgical procedures to perform sterilization and in the chemical industry to cure coatings and vulcanize rubber and for hydrothermal synthesis. Industrial autoclaves are used in industrial applications, especially in the manufacturing of composites. Many autoclaves are used to sterilize equipment and supplies by subjecting them to pressurized saturated steam at 121 Â°C for around 30-60 minutes at a pressure of 15 psi depending on the size of the load and the contents. The autoclave was invented by Charles Chamberland in 1879, although a precursor known as the steam digester was created by Denis Papin in 1679. The name comes from Greek auto-, ultimately meaning self, and Latin clavis meaning key, thus a self-locking device.','{\"pat_doc\": 518.0, \"pub_alt\": 174.0, \"pub_doc\": 750.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 2728412.0, \"pat_granted\": 234.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -12.2, \"pub_doc\": -9.9, \"clinic_doc\": 1.2, \"grant_fund\": 113571.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('aaae678094cfe5623b76ef36b3a2e739','794ef6eb4705d90aa18415f5e5a2779f','7b7c2d14c4ce8d4f609c2918b205a47e','2023-09-08 09:38:47','2023-10-28 20:51:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Thermogravimetric Analysis',12,'Thermogravimetric analysis or thermal gravimetric analysis is a method of thermal analysis in which the mass of a sample is measured over time as the temperature changes. This measurement provides information about physical phenomena, such as phase transitions, absorption, adsorption and desorption; as well as chemical phenomena including chemisorptions, thermal decomposition, and solid-gas reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 198.0, \"pub_alt\": 423.0, \"pub_doc\": 5815.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 13.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1809701.0, \"pat_granted\": 49.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 32.3, \"pub_doc\": 123.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -985255.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ab0744ab677adf2d36bbd2e179cee5dd','dc9a89b7d5132f4c1c6c291f4d309152','acf051d7127b574167932dffa9cd1c71','2023-09-08 02:48:54','2023-10-28 21:31:14','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Laboratory Information Management System',48,'A laboratory information management system, sometimes referred to as a laboratory information system or laboratory management system, is a software-based solution with features that support a modern laboratorys operations. Key features includeâ€”but are not limited toâ€”workflow and data tracking support, flexible architecture, and data exchange interfaces, which fully \"support its use in regulated environments\". The features and uses of a LIMS have evolved over the years from simple sample tracking to an enterprise resource planning tool that manages multiple aspects of laboratory informatics. There is no useful definition of the term \"LIMS\" as it is used to encompass a number of different laboratory informatics components. The spread and depth of these components is highly dependent on the LIMS implementation itself. All LIMSs have a workflow component and some summary data management facilities but beyond that there are significant differences in functionality.','{\"pat_doc\": 60.0, \"pub_alt\": 112.0, \"pub_doc\": 183.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 22.0, \"clinic_alt\": 189.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 32071425.0, \"pat_granted\": 14.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 8.9, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": -5084945.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ab4c229db1295a72fa7679b0e1b517a3','643c5418206cf3f26f9e4a26676606ed','9d0b9265fabb266bda4551314039c119','2023-09-04 18:47:48','2023-10-28 18:16:21','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Metabolism','Type 2 Diabetes',36,'Type 2 Diabetes is a chronic condition where the body becomes resistant to insulin or does not produce enough insulin to regulate blood sugar levels. Insulin is a hormone produced by the pancreas that helps the body to use glucose for energy. When glucose builds up in the blood, it can cause damage to organs and tissues over time. Risk factors for developing type 2 diabetes include obesity, physical inactivity, poor diet, and genetics. Symptoms of type 2 diabetes may include frequent urination, increased thirst, blurred vision, fatigue, and slow healing of wounds. Treatment typically involves lifestyle modifications, such as diet and exercise, as well as medications to help regulate blood sugar levels. Without proper management, type 2 diabetes can lead to complications such as heart disease, stroke, kidney disease, and nerve damage.','{\"pat_doc\": 2599.0, \"pub_alt\": 12883.0, \"pub_doc\": 61827.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2118.0, \"clinic_alt\": 649.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5322.0, \"grant_fund\": 1065772997.0, \"pat_granted\": 559.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 9.1, \"pub_doc\": 681.3, \"clinic_doc\": 645.5, \"grant_fund\": -142425510.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ab6621ee8e858f3ab5dccb2d379c3371','1728b9cb87efc77cfd614e3c4311a042','ee2727bc78203418d56b7f3bacf8d4dc','2023-09-08 01:47:28','2023-10-28 11:15:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Web 3.0',36,'Web 3.0, also known as the Semantic Web, refers to the evolution of the internet that aims to provide a more seamless and intelligent user experience. It is based on the idea of improving the way data is accessed and used, by creating a universal language for machines to understand and communicate with each other. This means that information on the web will be more interconnected, accessible, and easier to find. Web 3.0 aims to enable decentralization, personalization, and improved security on the internet. It has the potential to transform industries such as healthcare, finance, and education, by improving data sharing, privacy, and efficiency.','{\"pat_doc\": 16.0, \"pub_alt\": 338.0, \"pub_doc\": 572.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 19.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 3381127.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.3, \"pub_doc\": 89.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 613675.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('abae588e26f6985bf3b14e1b343e9c66','aedf0c478e49c48a393feff1fdcfaa4b','5b55c48790bb4cf3b5dc24f790e7d5a2','2023-09-05 21:32:03','2023-10-28 12:25:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Metaverse',48,'The Metaverse is a virtual reality space that contains multiple interconnected virtual worlds and augmented reality environments. It is a digital universe that enables users to create, experience, and interact with each other in various virtual environments. In the Metaverse, users can have a digital representation of themselves, or an avatar, who can move from one world to another. The concept of Metaverse is increasingly becoming popular as advancements in technology allow for more immersive and seamless experiences. It is used in various areas, including gaming, education, socialization, commerce, and even politics, to name a few. The Metaverse holds immense potential for revolutionizing how we interact with technology and each other.','{\"pat_doc\": 977.0, \"pub_alt\": 695.0, \"pub_doc\": 5960.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 148.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 77065439.0, \"pat_granted\": 279.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 259.5, \"pub_doc\": 1393.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.3, \"grant_fund\": 20484735.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('abf9ecd15e0b406ec4f92aa6371e9342','7cad47d8fa337e04fde87c8076f4adfe','25cc485513e0e2921857b91eeab511ae','2023-09-08 08:31:01','2023-10-28 13:41:15','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Colorectal cancer',48,'Colorectal cancer, also known as bowel cancer, colon cancer, or rectal cancer, is the development of cancer from the colon or rectum. Signs and symptoms may include blood in the stool, a change in bowel movements, weight loss, and fatigue. Most colorectal cancers are due to old age and lifestyle factors, with only a small number of cases due to underlying genetic disorders. Risk factors include diet, obesity, smoking, and lack of physical activity. Dietary factors that increase the risk include red meat, processed meat, and alcohol. Another risk factor is inflammatory bowel disease, which includes Crohns disease and ulcerative colitis. Some of the inherited genetic disorders that can cause colorectal cancer include familial adenomatous polyposis and hereditary non-polyposis colon cancer; however, these represent less than 5% of cases. It typically starts as a benign tumor, often in the form of a polyp, which over time becomes cancerous.','{\"pat_doc\": 5148.0, \"pub_alt\": 7747.0, \"pub_doc\": 59511.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2456.0, \"clinic_alt\": 699.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3804.0, \"grant_fund\": 1021268537.0, \"pat_granted\": 1378.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 91.4, \"pub_doc\": 499.3, \"clinic_doc\": 542.0, \"grant_fund\": -69281414.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ac4f296080acc99b4e1a0b6e3e7de9c3','12dcedeb603ee2f3832d8525115bfc64','4893d9f6d48ce8d1001500525173bb9e','2023-09-07 23:56:32','2023-10-28 16:51:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Lipid Nanoparticles',24,'Lipid nanoparticles are nanoparticles composed of lipids. They are a novel pharmaceutical drug delivery system, and a novel pharmaceutical formulation. LNPs as a drug delivery vehicle were first approved in 2018 for the siRNA drug Onpattro. LNPs became more widely known in late 2020, as some COVID-19 vaccines that use RNA vaccine technology coat the fragile mRNA strands with PEGylated lipid nanoparticles as their delivery vehicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 1349.0, \"pub_alt\": 16312.0, \"pub_doc\": 2352.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 145.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1578.0, \"clinic_doc\": 15.0, \"grant_fund\": 75329244.0, \"pat_granted\": 144.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 197.2, \"pub_doc\": 208.7, \"clinic_doc\": 3.7, \"grant_fund\": 10362532.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ac8f66bf67f65ae3d5775ee348f37cbe','8837382ad71ea14d648e72dffa07f350','a10d686867f23b1f3c14742bdf7326cc','2023-09-05 19:11:33','2023-10-29 05:16:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Biomaterial',12,'A biomaterial is a substance that has been engineered to interact with biological systems for a medical purpose, either a therapeutic or a diagnostic one. The corresponding field of study, called biomaterials science or biomaterials engineering, is about fifty years old. It has experienced steady and strong growth over its history, with many companies investing large amounts of money into the development of new products. Biomaterials science encompasses elements of medicine, biology, chemistry, tissue engineering and materials science. Note that a biomaterial is different from a biological material, such as bone, that is produced by a biological system. Additionally, care should be exercised in defining a biomaterial as biocompatible, since it is application-specific. A biomaterial that is biocompatible or suitable for one application may not be biocompatible in another.','{\"pat_doc\": 988.0, \"pub_alt\": 907.0, \"pub_doc\": 8756.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 526.0, \"clinic_alt\": 260.0, \"clinic_doc\": 207.0, \"grant_fund\": 266542824.0, \"pat_granted\": 280.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -44.8, \"pub_doc\": 588.5, \"clinic_doc\": 50.9, \"grant_fund\": -91915477.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('acc262e7149b09a4e2d6b37bae3487fe','00f5350f80c16146d1f1e5be0746e46e','e910bc33478f3cb83e3ef258c7d92a6c','2023-09-08 02:32:48','2023-10-28 14:21:12','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel Drug Delivery','Gonadotropin-Releasing-Hormone Agonist',48,'A gonadotropin-releasing hormone agonist is a type of medication which affects gonadotropins and sex hormones. They are used for a variety of indications including in fertility medicine and to lower sex hormone levels in the treatment of hormone-sensitive cancers such as prostate cancer and breast cancer, certain gynecological disorders like heavy periods and endometriosis, high testosterone levels in women, early puberty in children, as a part of transgender hormone therapy, and to delay puberty in transgender youth among other uses. It is also used in the suppression of spontaneous ovulation as part of controlled ovarian hyperstimulation, an essential component in in IVF. GnRH agonists are given by injections into fat, as implants placed into fat, and as nasal sprays.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 21.0, \"pub_doc\": 1.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ad2b79bf143f0bb6e1890bb5db7bd74a','666869b3162af8fad5a5b7d07b2312c9','f268e5ab79c5a1d38ab08daccf7ee951','2023-09-08 01:48:42','2023-10-28 11:10:33','Electronics','Components','Processing Devices','Neuromorphic Hardware',36,'Neuromorphic hardware is a type of computer hardware that is inspired by the workings of the human brain. Unlike traditional hardware that uses a Von Neumann architecture where the processing and memory are separate, neuromorphic hardware combines both processing and memory in a single unit. This results in a more efficient way of computing, where information is processed in parallel, similar to how neurons work in the brain. Neuromorphic hardware is often used in applications that require low power consumption and real-time processing, such as robotics and autonomous vehicles. The technology has the potential to create highly advanced and intelligent systems, but there are still challenges to overcome, such as developing effective programming models and scaling up the hardware for larger applications. Nonetheless, neuromorphic hardware is an exciting and promising area of research that has the potential to revolutionize computing as we know it.','{\"pat_doc\": 65.0, \"pub_alt\": 645.0, \"pub_doc\": 807.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 45.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 43084432.0, \"pat_granted\": 24.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.9, \"pub_doc\": 33.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -50956752.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ad3604117ed8b58320923e9af135c3ae','3c51150cb4d6d0c2bbf77b25519de393','6de0c721cf3eb4c836d007670b4c702d','2023-09-08 00:28:32','2023-10-29 01:36:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Live Cell Imaging',24,'Live cell imaging is the study of living cells using time-lapse microscopy. It is used by scientists to obtain a better understanding of biological function through the study of cellular dynamics. Live cell imaging was pioneered in first decade of the 21th century. One of the first time-lapse microcinematographic films of cells ever made was made by Julius Ries, showing the fertilization and development of the sea urchin egg. Since then, several microscopy methods have been developed which allow researchers to study living cells in greater detail with less effort. A newer type of imaging utilizing quantum dots have been used as they are shown to be more stable. The development of holotomographic microscopy has disregarded phototoxicity and other staining-derived disadvantages by implementing digital staining based on cells refractive index.','{\"pat_doc\": 41.0, \"pub_alt\": 195.0, \"pub_doc\": 773.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 172.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 79913014.0, \"pat_granted\": 11.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.4, \"pub_doc\": -16.3, \"clinic_doc\": -0.2, \"grant_fund\": -12558862.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('aeb450cf206b915c2a91ffecd4b6366c','3e296fb8632883059f895163006d1ec4','47c2be7d4757b7a89106ea7e007a13dc','2023-09-08 00:02:21','2023-10-29 02:11:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Fluorescence In Situ Hybridization',48,'Fluorescence in situ hybridization is a molecular cytogenetic technique that uses fluorescent probes that bind to only particular parts of a nucleic acid sequence with a high degree of sequence complementarity. It was developed by biomedical researchers in the early 1980s to detect and localize the presence or absence of specific DNA sequences on chromosomes. Fluorescence microscopy can be used to find out where the fluorescent probe is bound to the chromosomes. FISH is often used for finding specific features in DNA for use in genetic counseling, medicine, and species identification. FISH can also be used to detect and localize specific RNA targets in cells, circulating tumor cells, and tissue samples. In this context, it can help define the spatial-temporal patterns of gene expression within cells and tissues.','{\"pat_doc\": 231.0, \"pub_alt\": 1177.0, \"pub_doc\": 5484.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 160.0, \"clinic_alt\": 50.0, \"clinic_doc\": 94.0, \"grant_fund\": 82930427.0, \"pat_granted\": 69.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.1, \"pub_doc\": -35.6, \"clinic_doc\": 12.4, \"grant_fund\": -136298.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('aec054cbb1e41feea87680401ee3445b','d4fdd9a1f4aa53cc01e7cbb316b38d68','a0401cb7a291257d3685c0a77fb2d841','2023-09-08 01:02:41','2023-10-28 15:51:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Retrovirus',12,'A retrovirus is a type of virus that inserts a DNA copy of its RNA genome into the DNA of a host cell that it invades, thus changing the genome of that cell. Once inside the host cells cytoplasm, the virus uses its own reverse transcriptase enzyme to produce DNA from its RNA genome, the reverse of the usual pattern, thus retro. The new DNA is then incorporated into the host cell genome by an integrase enzyme, at which point the retroviral DNA is referred to as a provirus. The host cell then treats the viral DNA as part of its own genome, transcribing and translating the viral genes along with the cells own genes, producing the proteins required to assemble new copies of the virus. Many retroviruses cause serious diseases in humans, other mammals, and birds. Retroviruses have many subfamilies in three basic groups. â€¢ Oncoretroviruses include human T-lymphotropic virus causing a type of leukemia in humans, and murine leukemia viruses in mice.','{\"pat_doc\": 123.0, \"pub_alt\": 947.0, \"pub_doc\": 769.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 42.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1310.0, \"clinic_doc\": 58.0, \"grant_fund\": 12646095.0, \"pat_granted\": 28.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.8, \"pub_doc\": 7.1, \"clinic_doc\": 15.6, \"grant_fund\": -9492771.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('aef2a4310d375321bae729326d5c6bd9','ee1ceea70d26f9efca309b5f07a6e479','77e5f6785bd7c9d4f3610b4ac830ad4e','2023-09-08 00:22:21','2023-10-29 01:51:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Electroporation',48,'Electroporation, or electropermeabilization, is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing chemicals, drugs, electrode arrays or DNA to be introduced into the cell. In microbiology, the process of electroporation is often used to transform bacteria, yeast, or plant protoplasts by introducing new coding DNA. If bacteria and plasmids are mixed together, the plasmids can be transferred into the bacteria after electroporation, though depending on what is being transferred, cell-penetrating peptides or CellSqueeze could also be used. Electroporation works by passing thousands of volts across suspended cells in an electroporation cuvette. Afterwards, the cells have to be handled carefully until they have had a chance to divide, producing new cells that contain reproduced plasmids.','{\"pat_doc\": 2334.0, \"pub_alt\": 1984.0, \"pub_doc\": 3802.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 351.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1151.0, \"clinic_doc\": 186.0, \"grant_fund\": 136514334.0, \"pat_granted\": 635.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 72.4, \"pub_doc\": -22.4, \"clinic_doc\": 21.4, \"grant_fund\": -13946036.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('af14f0ad4d5cc31a2a3dad2c67244834','eb2ca5cdbf466432efa3cad3dd594f1a','6725d42f932d0e446e761f0968e0172f','2023-09-08 02:04:06','2023-10-28 23:16:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','Cell Characterization',12,'Cell Characterization is the process of understanding the physical, chemical, and biological properties of a specific type of cell. It involves analyzing various aspects of the cell, such as morphology, size, and structure, as well as its function and behavior. Through this process, scientists can gain a deeper understanding of how cells function, how they interact with other cells, and how they respond to different environments or stimuli. Cell Characterization is an essential tool for researchers and scientists in a variety of fields, including cell biology, genetics, and immunology, as it allows for the development of new treatments and therapies for diseases and the discovery of new biological mechanisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 13.0, \"pub_alt\": 496.0, \"pub_doc\": 139.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 13.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 9088644.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 13.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -513209.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('af6a63129b94f09d7318057f602d5d5a','629f564fa930d422fbfc8405c3bae6c0','72a385b9d786832dcc2c823f54ed4998','2023-09-05 20:39:21','2023-10-28 12:40:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Digital Twin',12,'A digital twin is a digital representation of an intended or actual real-world physical product, system, or process that serves as the effectively indistinguishable digital counterpart of it for practical purposes, such as simulation, integration, testing, monitoring, and maintenance. The digital twin has been intended from its initial introduction to be the underlying premise for Product Lifecycle Management and exists throughout the entire lifecycle of the physical entity it represents. Since information is granular, the digital twin representation is determined by the value-based use cases it is created to implement. The digital twin can and does often exist before there is a physical entity. The use of a digital twin in the creation phase allows the intended entitys entire lifecycle to be modeled and simulated. A digital twin of an existing entity may be used in real-time and regularly synchronized with the corresponding physical system.','{\"pat_doc\": 4545.0, \"pub_alt\": 346.0, \"pub_doc\": 6652.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 631.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.0, \"grant_fund\": 1047538229.0, \"pat_granted\": 991.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1361.7, \"pub_doc\": 1705.1, \"clinic_doc\": 4.4, \"grant_fund\": 206480656.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('af90741587ee48309cdd2995c502e3c9','6e9cf23bacc0f67b8c70385963421414','75c037afe780bd09b9ce614027c7464a','2023-09-08 01:52:03','2023-10-28 23:51:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Cell-Free System',36,'A cell-free system is an in vitro tool widely used to study biological reactions that happen within cells apart from a full cell system, thus reducing the complex interactions typically found when working in a whole cell. Subcellular fractions can be isolated by ultracentrifugation to provide molecular machinery that can be used in reactions in the absence of many of the other cellular components. Eukaryotic and prokaryotic cell internals have been used for creation of these simplified environments. These systems have enabled cell-free synthetic biology to emerge, providing control over what reaction is being examined, as well as its yield, and lessening the considerations otherwise invoked when working with more sensitive live cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 152.0, \"pub_alt\": 1312.0, \"pub_doc\": 532.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 55.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 28874866.0, \"pat_granted\": 34.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.4, \"pub_doc\": 1.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 604452.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b01b073cd2dc938a483c06d3f2e8552e','ce48dd19951bc72e32788762866aa8ba','9f4de602c8b4dc324f5081159f81d1f9','2023-09-08 10:02:32','2023-10-28 19:21:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Loss on Drying',48,'Loss on Drying (LOD) is a common analysis performed in the pharmaceutical, food, and cosmetics industries to quantify the amount of moisture content in a sample. It is a gravimetric analysis method that measures the weight lost by a sample when it is heated at a specific temperature. The difference between the initial weight of the sample and the weight after heating is recorded as LOD. This technique is useful in determining the stability and shelf life of products, as high moisture content can lead to microbial growth, chemical degradation, and decreased product quality. LOD is a critical parameter in product manufacturing, as it can affect the products physical and chemical properties, efficacy, and safety. Controlling the moisture content of a product is essential to ensure its stability and prevent spoilage, making LOD an important tool for quality control and assurance.','{\"pat_doc\": 41.0, \"pub_alt\": 10.0, \"pub_doc\": 296.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": 35506.0, \"pat_granted\": 10.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 1.4, \"clinic_doc\": -0.8, \"grant_fund\": -10651.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b05e1c14d1dbd00fde5406c4627c97a9','f1df325e8a923b7c94ec1f46acdb203e','67ae7824162271af981ae2c6a606ee4e','2023-09-05 22:59:40','2023-10-28 12:00:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Memristor',12,'A memristor is a non-linear two-terminal electrical component relating electric charge and magnetic flux linkage. It was described and named in 1971 by Leon Chua, completing a theoretical quartet of fundamental electrical components which comprises also the resistor, capacitor and inductor. Chua and Kang later generalized the concept to memristive systems. Such a system comprises a circuit, of multiple conventional components, which mimics key properties of the ideal memristor component and is also commonly referred to as a memristor. Several such memristor system technologies have been developed, notably ReRAM. The identification of memristive properties in electronic devices has attracted controversy. Experimentally, the ideal memristor has yet to be demonstrated.','{\"pat_doc\": 757.0, \"pub_alt\": 160.0, \"pub_doc\": 1940.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 27.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 13013787.0, \"pat_granted\": 275.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 108.5, \"pub_doc\": 242.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2583132.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b0c11f165faf3a7763bb16e01e8a0478','12312c1c49930d5087ae7dcb6859710b','49f53d4e41fb1f785aeb36bddad58488','2023-09-08 10:40:37','2023-10-28 19:06:13','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Natural Language Processing',48,'Natural language processing is an interdisciplinary subfield of computer science and linguistics. It is primarily concerned with giving computers the ability to support and manipulate speech. It involves processing natural language datasets, such as text corpora or speech corpora, using either rule-based or probabilistic machine learning approaches. The goal is a computer capable of \"understanding\" the contents of documents, including the contextual nuances of the language within them. The technology can then accurately extract information and insights contained in the documents as well as categorize and organize the documents themselves. Challenges in natural language processing frequently involve speech recognition, natural-language understanding, and natural-language generation.','{\"pat_doc\": 13171.0, \"pub_alt\": 1330.0, \"pub_doc\": 33523.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2068.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 81.0, \"grant_fund\": 1009554618.0, \"pat_granted\": 3650.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 771.9, \"pub_doc\": 1863.9, \"clinic_doc\": 17.1, \"grant_fund\": -13379287.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b0cff9e4763b0a8c4a458929020c4038','3dd87ec4606ad304f7e661f044278af7','3fb1f33d12215e256dd98a72f66b746e','2023-09-08 01:32:52','2023-10-28 15:16:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Viral vector (gene) therapies','Oncolytic viruses',24,'An oncolytic virus is a virus that preferentially infects and kills cancer cells. As the infected cancer cells are destroyed by oncolysis, they release new infectious virus particles or virions to help destroy the remaining tumour. Oncolytic viruses are thought not only to cause direct destruction of the tumour cells, but also to stimulate host anti-tumour immune system responses. Oncolytic viruses also have the ability to affect the tumor micro-environment in multiple ways. The potential of viruses as anti-cancer agents was first realised in the early twentieth century, although coordinated research efforts did not begin until the 1960s. A number of viruses including adenovirus, reovirus, measles, herpes simplex, Newcastle disease virus, and vaccinia have been clinically tested as oncolytic agents. Most current oncolytic viruses are engineered for tumour selectivity, although there are naturally occurring examples such as reovirus and the senecavirus, resulting in clinical trials.','{\"pat_doc\": 405.0, \"pub_alt\": 756.0, \"pub_doc\": 635.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 42.0, \"clinic_alt\": 130.0, \"clinic_doc\": 15.0, \"grant_fund\": 9122709.0, \"pat_granted\": 48.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 26.2, \"pub_doc\": 4.4, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": -7924828.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b0dce776f3a1459d4bfe58ba1b7b4886','4efee97660391cd588fa5f748e6f0600','eaf48f12d2f6d964781bc23663490cdb','2023-09-08 10:49:43','2023-10-28 19:01:11','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Image Analysis',48,'Image analysis or imagery analysis is the extraction of meaningful information from images; mainly from digital images by means of digital image processing techniques. Image analysis tasks can be as simple as reading bar coded tags or as sophisticated as identifying a person from their face. Computers are indispensable for the analysis of large amounts of data, for tasks that require complex computation, or for the extraction of quantitative information. On the other hand, the human visual cortex is an excellent image analysis apparatus, especially for extracting higher-level information, and for many applications â€” including medicine, security, and remote sensing â€” human analysts still cannot be replaced by computers. For this reason, many important image analysis tools such as edge detectors and neural networks are inspired by human visual perception models.','{\"pat_doc\": 14904.0, \"pub_alt\": 1138.0, \"pub_doc\": 26953.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2252.0, \"clinic_alt\": 18.0, \"clinic_doc\": 364.0, \"grant_fund\": 822750935.0, \"pat_granted\": 4687.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 297.4, \"pub_doc\": 418.9, \"clinic_doc\": 55.6, \"grant_fund\": -41339384.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b10aa38275f4953739fd3a7aa4353307','0a067dac7f4a167516bf9ae7db80387b','05ecfec6f6dadbdbb84f6f314d1e344e','2023-09-08 09:06:23','2023-10-28 13:31:15','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Non-small cell lung cancer',36,'Non-small-cell lung carcinoma is any type of epithelial lung cancer other than small-cell lung carcinoma. NSCLC accounts for about 85% of all lung cancers. As a class, NSCLCs are relatively insensitive to chemotherapy, compared to small-cell carcinoma. When possible, they are primarily treated by surgical resection with curative intent, although chemotherapy has been used increasingly both preoperatively and postoperatively.','{\"pat_doc\": 1897.0, \"pub_alt\": 1405.0, \"pub_doc\": 24055.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 435.0, \"clinic_alt\": 822.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3300.0, \"grant_fund\": 196375019.0, \"pat_granted\": 498.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 34.7, \"pub_doc\": 157.7, \"clinic_doc\": 620.8, \"grant_fund\": -18325526.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b13ed954555f0846dc9a8da50c2eb0d4','b663e797baa447591490dab433b724b6','e5dc1ab9b95fd144580ba449bdb1f286','2023-09-05 22:04:26','2023-10-28 17:31:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Gene therapies (Non-viral)','CRISPR-Cas9',24,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 528.0, \"pub_alt\": 993.0, \"pub_doc\": 3786.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 460.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 20.0, \"grant_fund\": 192523840.0, \"pat_granted\": 151.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.8, \"pub_doc\": 114.2, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -29971557.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b18bdcdc35ea1c38121bedf056d362ce','6de9464f8e368a19a89261dd71c09017','641ccd99a014845dc487b6f5a217f8ff','2023-09-08 00:19:27','2023-10-29 01:56:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Nuclear Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy',36,'Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy, most commonly known as NMR spectroscopy or magnetic resonance spectroscopy, is a spectroscopic technique to observe local magnetic fields around atomic nuclei. This spectroscopy is based on the measurement of absorption of electromagnetic radiations in the radio frequency region from roughly 4 to 900 MHz. Absorption of radio waves in the presence of magnetic field is accompanied by a special type of nuclear transition, and for this reason, such type of spectroscopy is known as Nuclear Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy. The sample is placed in a magnetic field and the NMR signal is produced by excitation of the nuclei sample with radio waves into nuclear magnetic resonance, which is detected with sensitive radio receivers. The intramolecular magnetic field around an atom in a molecule changes the resonance frequency, thus giving access to details of the electronic structure of a molecule and its individual functional groups.','{\"pat_doc\": 110.0, \"pub_alt\": 745.0, \"pub_doc\": 3505.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 155.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": 103316063.0, \"pat_granted\": 35.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.8, \"pub_doc\": 7.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.9, \"grant_fund\": -2653145.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b1946ffc215b0d45b4b450e20dd662b1','b663e797baa447591490dab433b724b6','e5dc1ab9b95fd144580ba449bdb1f286','2023-09-05 22:04:26','2023-10-28 17:31:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Gene therapies (Non-viral)','CRISPR-Cas9',12,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 275.0, \"pub_alt\": 993.0, \"pub_doc\": 1854.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 177.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 17.0, \"grant_fund\": 72055014.0, \"pat_granted\": 92.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.8, \"pub_doc\": 114.2, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -29971557.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b1e27538ab6272e425b54869d80808cc','dd3b10037cd066e53410e9747f800fec','9bd82f68388cbaa629adeec1747d02c9','2023-09-04 19:22:50','2023-10-28 12:55:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','5g',48,'5G refers to the fifth generation of mobile networks and is the successor to 4G. It represents a significant improvement in terms of speed, latency, and capacity, enabling faster download and upload speeds, quicker response times, and the ability to connect more devices to the network simultaneously. The new network technology uses higher frequency radio waves and advanced antenna technology to transmit and receive data more efficiently. The increased bandwidth of 5G networks will enhance the capabilities of emerging technologies such as virtual and augmented reality, driverless vehicles, and Internet of Things (IoT) devices. The deployment of 5G networks is currently underway worldwide, and it is expected to have a significant impact on the way we communicate and access information in the years to come.','{\"pat_doc\": 76485.0, \"pub_alt\": 2908.0, \"pub_doc\": 64231.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3171.0, \"clinic_alt\": 61.0, \"clinic_doc\": 985.0, \"grant_fund\": 9761399630.0, \"pat_granted\": 28617.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1603.5, \"pub_doc\": 859.7, \"clinic_doc\": 107.3, \"grant_fund\": -2206973786.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b271ba81c4678759e37bf120ade44702','014a9a76a066045b2a9bf86aedfb7d7c','9b98ef926c70dcba53c5447a923e9d23','2023-09-08 02:30:56','2023-10-28 22:06:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Sequencing',12,'Protein sequencing is the practical process of determining the amino acid sequence of all or part of a protein or peptide. This may serve to identify the protein or characterize its post-translational modifications. Typically, partial sequencing of a protein provides sufficient information to identify it with reference to databases of protein sequences derived from the conceptual translation of genes. The two major direct methods of protein sequencing are mass spectrometry and Edman degradation using a protein sequenator. Mass spectrometry methods are now the most widely used for protein sequencing and identification but Edman degradation remains a valuable tool for characterizing a proteins N-terminus.','{\"pat_doc\": 39.0, \"pub_alt\": 374.0, \"pub_doc\": 77.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 19.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 8614471.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.9, \"pub_doc\": 7.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": 2760440.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b2833a2dc26891d539175be07bbd0d9c','d4fdd9a1f4aa53cc01e7cbb316b38d68','a0401cb7a291257d3685c0a77fb2d841','2023-09-08 01:02:41','2023-10-28 15:51:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Retrovirus',24,'A retrovirus is a type of virus that inserts a DNA copy of its RNA genome into the DNA of a host cell that it invades, thus changing the genome of that cell. Once inside the host cells cytoplasm, the virus uses its own reverse transcriptase enzyme to produce DNA from its RNA genome, the reverse of the usual pattern, thus retro. The new DNA is then incorporated into the host cell genome by an integrase enzyme, at which point the retroviral DNA is referred to as a provirus. The host cell then treats the viral DNA as part of its own genome, transcribing and translating the viral genes along with the cells own genes, producing the proteins required to assemble new copies of the virus. Many retroviruses cause serious diseases in humans, other mammals, and birds. Retroviruses have many subfamilies in three basic groups. â€¢ Oncoretroviruses include human T-lymphotropic virus causing a type of leukemia in humans, and murine leukemia viruses in mice.','{\"pat_doc\": 270.0, \"pub_alt\": 3897.0, \"pub_doc\": 1601.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 122.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1310.0, \"clinic_doc\": 63.0, \"grant_fund\": 57087363.0, \"pat_granted\": 62.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.8, \"pub_doc\": 7.1, \"clinic_doc\": 15.6, \"grant_fund\": -9492771.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b29624585655c214b20b22423c1d6c6f','848c570f631dc66b6c71249b5532b80c','f53620dbd4935249cccf6fdb7d35b8cf','2023-09-04 19:36:20','2023-10-29 05:56:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Immunofluorescence',24,'Immunofluorescence is a technique used for light microscopy with a fluorescence microscope and is used primarily on biological samples. This technique uses the specificity of antibodies to their antigen to target fluorescent dyes to specific biomolecule targets within a cell, and therefore allows visualization of the distribution of the target molecule through the sample. The specific region an antibody recognizes on an antigen is called an epitope. There have been efforts in epitope mapping since many antibodies can bind the same epitope and levels of binding between antibodies that recognize the same epitope can vary. Additionally, the binding of the fluorophore to the antibody itself cannot interfere with the immunological specificity of the antibody or the binding capacity of its antigen. Immunofluorescence is a widely used example of immunostaining and is a specific example of immunohistochemistry.','{\"pat_doc\": 771.0, \"pub_alt\": 4560.0, \"pub_doc\": 21314.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 432.0, \"clinic_alt\": 392.0, \"clinic_doc\": 122.0, \"grant_fund\": 207932568.0, \"pat_granted\": 293.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 29.2, \"pub_doc\": 619.2, \"clinic_doc\": 22.2, \"grant_fund\": -6312911.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b40800317bdb043bcca7bf15aa03bbe1','989e334c32437caa317127b884df7c33','704edc6299a6c2e6515a45403d655e47','2023-09-08 02:32:40','2023-10-28 10:55:31','Electronics','Components','Interface & Display Devices','MicroLED',24,'MicroLED is an emerging display technology that is similar to traditional LED displays, but with much smaller individual LEDs, or \"micro LEDs.\" The small size of these LEDs allows for higher resolution displays with better contrast and brightness compared to other types of displays like LCD or OLED. MicroLED is also more energy-efficient and can provide longer lifetimes than other technologies. While MicroLED displays have been around for a few years, they are still in the early stages of development with only a few consumer products in the market. However, it is expected that the technology will become more widely adopted in the coming years due to its many advantages over other display technologies.','{\"pat_doc\": 375.0, \"pub_alt\": 235.0, \"pub_doc\": 161.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 17.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 11706078.0, \"pat_granted\": 83.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 39.8, \"pub_doc\": 12.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 656986.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b4a7b315dafd4db76e2e1e7901a1dda7','938382e729311744061a6779d6023f38','41fcc042c592c420a4959d0a8d491f70','2023-09-08 01:56:00','2023-10-28 23:36:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Purification',48,'Protein purification is a series of processes intended to isolate one or a few proteins from a complex mixture, usually cells, tissues or whole organisms. Protein purification is vital for the specification of the function, structure and interactions of the protein of interest. The purification process may separate the protein and non-protein parts of the mixture, and finally separate the desired protein from all other proteins. Ideally, to study a protein of interest, it must be separated from other components of the cell so that contaminants wont interfere in the examination of the protein of interests structure and function. Separation of one protein from all others is typically the most laborious aspect of protein purification. Separation steps usually exploit differences in protein size, physico-chemical properties, binding affinity and biological activity. The pure result may be termed protein isolate.','{\"pat_doc\": 1162.0, \"pub_alt\": 430.0, \"pub_doc\": 760.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 115.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 45458750.0, \"pat_granted\": 504.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 5.2, \"pub_doc\": -6.6, \"clinic_doc\": -0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2889090.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b538802259704d6ea2a278ec98d324c4','ecb5eb0e681dab97bb1d5c09a929aa00','ad11810122ec68f63273a505f81c6d11','2023-09-08 00:01:07','2023-10-28 16:46:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Adeno-associated virus',48,'Adeno-associated viruses are small viruses that infect humans and some other primate species. They belong to the genus Dependoparvovirus, which in turn belongs to the family Parvoviridae. They are small replication-defective, nonenveloped viruses and have linear single-stranded DNA genome of approximately 4.8 kilobases. Several features make AAV an attractive candidate for creating viral vectors for gene therapy, and for the creation of isogenic human disease models. Gene therapy vectors using AAV can infect both dividing and quiescent cells and persist in an extrachromosomal state without integrating into the genome of the host cell. In the native virus, however, integration of virally carried genes into the host genome does occur. Integration can be important for certain applications, but can also have unwanted consequences. Recent human clinical trials using AAV for gene therapy in the retina have shown promise.','{\"pat_doc\": 5520.0, \"pub_alt\": 2540.0, \"pub_doc\": 4841.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 571.0, \"clinic_alt\": 500.0, \"clinic_doc\": 116.0, \"grant_fund\": 303484206.0, \"pat_granted\": 774.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 245.2, \"pub_doc\": 179.9, \"clinic_doc\": 23.4, \"grant_fund\": -12947659.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b5cfacb302522bdd65265028287ad36f','9cb1fcb17b688427ac67a33166effbb2','5ed796512ab4425cf98a4d2c7cdf5653','2023-09-05 20:27:46','2023-10-28 18:01:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Hematopoietic Stem Cells',24,'Hematopoietic stem cells are the stem cells that give rise to other blood cells. This process is called haematopoiesis. In vertebrates, the very first definitive HSCs arise from the ventral endothelial wall of the embryonic aorta within the aorta-gonad-mesonephros region, through a process known as endothelial-to-hematopoietic transition. In adults, haematopoiesis occurs in the red bone marrow, in the core of most bones. The red bone marrow is derived from the layer of the embryo called the mesoderm. Haematopoiesis is the process by which all mature blood cells are produced. It must balance enormous production needs with the need to regulate the number of each blood cell type in the circulation. In vertebrates, the vast majority of hematopoiesis occurs in the bone marrow and is derived from a limited number of hematopoietic stem cells that are multipotent and capable of extensive self-renewal.','{\"pat_doc\": 848.0, \"pub_alt\": 1334.0, \"pub_doc\": 2710.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 308.0, \"clinic_alt\": 77.0, \"clinic_doc\": 226.0, \"grant_fund\": 170425830.0, \"pat_granted\": 196.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -13.9, \"pub_doc\": -37.5, \"clinic_doc\": 48.6, \"grant_fund\": -17355143.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b5dcca3852ebfe3d90e914330395de74','a0128a060f00fc2880c25d9fe5536900','beb557d6f3a8f418565f2d30cdebe10e','2023-09-08 01:20:42','2023-10-28 15:21:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','natural killer T cells',12,'Natural Killer T cells are a type of lymphocytes that bridge the adaptive and innate immune systems. They have the ability to recognize and respond to a broad range of antigens presented on the surface of many different cell types, including cancer cells, and are important in regulating immune responses. These cells differentiate from the thymus and are characterized by the co-expression of T cell receptors and NK cell receptors. The interaction of these receptors allows them to respond quickly to pathogens and induces the rapid secretion of cytokines and other effector molecules. Natural Killer T cells play a vital role in controlling immune responses and have been implicated in various autoimmune diseases. Recent studies on the modulation of Natural Killer T cell responses provide new insights into the development of immunotherapeutic strategies for infectious and inflammatory diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_alt\": 282.0, \"pub_doc\": 116.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 37.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 1191656.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.0, \"pub_doc\": -0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.9, \"grant_fund\": -984070.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b60c836da00e0013ff458aaf3c3caf80','7f22a30b9d31980762db19938046f3e9','5762d74cf97f0e57d03def69845fe3e1','2023-09-08 02:43:41','2023-10-28 21:46:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Enzyme Technology',12,'Enzyme Technology involves the use of enzymes to carry out specific chemical reactions, useful in various industries such as food, pharmaceuticals, and the environment. Enzymes are biocatalysts that facilitate chemical reactions without being consumed in the process. They are highly specific and can work under mild conditions, making them eco-friendly and efficient. Enzyme Technology includes the optimization of enzyme-catalyzed reactions, engineering of new enzymes, and production of enzymes through fermentation processes. The applications of enzyme technology are vast, including the production of biofuels, detergents, food additives, and medications. The use of enzyme technology can also lead to more sustainable processes, reduced waste, and decreased environmental impact in industries.','{\"pat_doc\": 22.0, \"pub_alt\": 26.0, \"pub_doc\": 44.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4687623.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -7.1, \"pub_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -310772.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b6e7978d7e6d3f6befbd18cd0326272d','f1d991da1c3d1f34a90384e385b676a5','4101f5b584ffd5355154925e914aabcc','2023-09-08 00:58:18','2023-10-29 00:46:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Mass Cytometry',48,'Mass cytometry is a mass spectrometry technique based on inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry and time of flight mass spectrometry used for the determination of the properties of cells. In this approach, antibodies are conjugated with isotopically pure elements, and these antibodies are used to label cellular proteins. Cells are nebulized and sent through an argon plasma, which ionizes the metal-conjugated antibodies. The metal signals are then analyzed by a time-of-flight mass spectrometer. The approach overcomes limitations of spectral overlap in flow cytometry by utilizing discrete isotopes as a reporter system instead of traditional fluorophores which have broad emission spectra.','{\"pat_doc\": 125.0, \"pub_alt\": 6207.0, \"pub_doc\": 2291.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 423.0, \"clinic_alt\": 53.0, \"clinic_doc\": 61.0, \"grant_fund\": 260596829.0, \"pat_granted\": 20.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.1, \"pub_doc\": 21.7, \"clinic_doc\": 15.1, \"grant_fund\": -21158977.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b718c2df399c45ad9d81d2cee5eef012','de565fc9dd512d5b484b35f776f4545e','5428f4cb6631add28ed91160f184e3d2','2023-09-04 18:50:59','2023-10-29 06:46:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Polymerase Chain Reaction',24,'The polymerase chain reaction is a method widely used to make millions to billions of copies of a specific DNA sample rapidly, allowing scientists amplify a very small sample of DNA sufficiently to enable detailed study. PCR was invented in 1983 by American biochemist Kary Mullis at Cetus Corporation; Mullis and biochemist Michael Smith, who had developed other essential ways of manipulating DNA, were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1993. PCR is fundamental to many of the procedures used in genetic testing and research, including analysis of ancient samples of DNA and identification of infectious agents. Using PCR, copies of very small amounts of DNA sequences are exponentially amplified in a series of cycles of temperature changes. PCR is now a common and often indispensable technique used in medical laboratory research for a broad variety of applications including biomedical research and criminal forensics. The majority of PCR methods rely on thermal cycling.','{\"pat_doc\": 2061.0, \"pub_alt\": 7175.0, \"pub_doc\": 35601.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 179.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1692.0, \"clinic_doc\": 711.0, \"grant_fund\": 29343864.0, \"pat_granted\": 691.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 25.6, \"pub_doc\": -1022.4, \"clinic_doc\": 80.3, \"grant_fund\": -12358489.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b734a3e5479c32086414f0d17ff6ba0f','7d9363772a465cde721c0298e8b025e2','7bdb69262d8e22c117d34100c1831a78','2023-09-08 02:12:10','2023-10-28 23:01:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Organotypic Culture',24,'Organotypic culture is a method of growing cells in a three-dimensional structure that mimics the natural organization of tissues and organs. This type of culture system creates an environment that more closely resembles the in vivo conditions of the cells being examined, allowing for more accurate experimental results. In an organotypic culture, the cells are grown on a natural or synthetic scaffold that enables them to self-assemble into tissue-like structures. This provides an opportunity to study cell-to-cell interactions and analyze the development and behavior of tissue-specific functions. Organotypic cultures have been used in various fields, including cancer research, drug development, and regenerative medicine. They are a valuable tool for investigating complex biological processes and identifying potential therapeutic targets.','{\"pat_doc\": 7.0, \"pub_alt\": 225.0, \"pub_doc\": 228.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 30.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 15017696.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 5.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -1146973.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b74e24d20eaaa50e858eea4144a1c47c','5a0a5b9065b639feb58f1b4e34dc9f7c','9c4ba206250041cf1644bb291a643634','2023-09-05 18:59:35','2023-10-29 05:21:13','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Next-Generation Sequencing',36,'Massive parallel sequencing or massively parallel sequencing is any of several high-throughput approaches to DNA sequencing using the concept of massively parallel processing; it is also called next-generation sequencing or second-generation sequencing. Some of these technologies emerged between 1993 and 1998 and have been commercially available since 2005. These technologies use miniaturized and parallelized platforms for sequencing of 1 million to 43 billion short reads per instrument run. Many NGS platforms differ in engineering configurations and sequencing chemistry. They share the technical paradigm of massive parallel sequencing via spatially separated, clonally amplified DNA templates or single DNA molecules in a flow cell. This design is very different from that of Sanger sequencingâ€”also known as capillary sequencing or first-generation sequencingâ€”which is based on electrophoretic separation of chain-termination products produced in individual sequencing reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 426.0, \"pub_alt\": 5565.0, \"pub_doc\": 20329.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 763.0, \"clinic_alt\": 58.0, \"clinic_doc\": 394.0, \"grant_fund\": 239240246.0, \"pat_granted\": 101.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.9, \"pub_doc\": 170.9, \"clinic_doc\": 72.6, \"grant_fund\": -38192044.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b7e0be6d2916ade3f53108070f87bc74','68a4129044821c3a1d6386321b0e0003','71b92f66f40436e1ab511b3f211c9bd0','2023-09-08 02:35:10','2023-10-28 10:50:30','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Photonic Computing',48,'Optical computing or photonic computing uses light waves produced by lasers or incoherent sources for data processing, data storage or data communication for computing. For decades, photons have shown promise to enable a higher bandwidth than the electrons used in conventional computers. Most research projects focus on replacing current computer components with optical equivalents, resulting in an optical digital computer system processing binary data. This approach appears to offer the best short-term prospects for commercial optical computing, since optical components could be integrated into traditional computers to produce an optical-electronic hybrid. However, optoelectronic devices consume 30% of their energy converting electronic energy into photons and back; this conversion also slows the transmission of messages. All-optical computers eliminate the need for optical-electrical-optical conversions, thus reducing electrical power consumption.','{\"pat_doc\": 59.0, \"pub_alt\": 134.0, \"pub_doc\": 174.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 21.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 26157707.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.5, \"pub_doc\": 21.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2638715.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b7e2191e8c13a2f5ba86f98dbc3cc8e7','0a067dac7f4a167516bf9ae7db80387b','05ecfec6f6dadbdbb84f6f314d1e344e','2023-09-08 09:06:23','2023-10-28 13:31:15','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Non-small cell lung cancer',12,'Non-small-cell lung carcinoma is any type of epithelial lung cancer other than small-cell lung carcinoma. NSCLC accounts for about 85% of all lung cancers. As a class, NSCLCs are relatively insensitive to chemotherapy, compared to small-cell carcinoma. When possible, they are primarily treated by surgical resection with curative intent, although chemotherapy has been used increasingly both preoperatively and postoperatively.','{\"pat_doc\": 655.0, \"pub_alt\": 1352.0, \"pub_doc\": 7855.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 106.0, \"clinic_alt\": 822.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2409.0, \"grant_fund\": 44681891.0, \"pat_granted\": 172.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 34.7, \"pub_doc\": 157.7, \"clinic_doc\": 620.8, \"grant_fund\": -18325526.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b83ccc201659e46e484a7a47d2e43882','b973f9a55a74403c41f6bfdbc9121654','b347f7200b8aff24464a347c263147e9','2023-09-04 19:13:14','2023-10-29 06:11:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Filtration',24,'Filtration is a physical separation process that separates solid matter and fluid from a mixture using a filter medium that has a complex structure through which only the fluid can pass. Solid particles that cannot pass through the filter medium are described as oversize and the fluid that passes through is called the filtrate. Oversize particles may form a filter cake on top of the filter and may also block the filter lattice, preventing the fluid phase from crossing the filter, known as blinding. The size of the largest particles that can successfully pass through a filter is called the effective pore size of that filter. The separation of solid and fluid is imperfect; solids will be contaminated with some fluid and filtrate will contain fine particles. Filtration occurs both in nature and in engineered systems; there are biological, geological, and industrial forms.','{\"pat_doc\": 120490.0, \"pub_alt\": 26339.0, \"pub_doc\": 84428.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1969.0, \"clinic_alt\": 592.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2505.0, \"grant_fund\": 662536664.0, \"pat_granted\": 84436.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 315.7, \"pub_doc\": 2992.9, \"clinic_doc\": 373.4, \"grant_fund\": -100208796.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b85916b4ecaefc894517806a080d63f3','116c9f3326973bf53316f607199f9944','09c8640e20ae09de463871c1529a6589','2023-09-05 22:07:59','2023-10-29 03:36:14','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Fluorescence Microscopy',24,'A fluorescence microscope is an optical microscope that uses fluorescence instead of, or in addition to, scattering, reflection, and attenuation or absorption, to study the properties of organic or inorganic substances. \"Fluorescence microscope\" refers to any microscope that uses fluorescence to generate an image, whether it is a simple set up like an epifluorescence microscope or a more complicated design such as a confocal microscope, which uses optical sectioning to get better resolution of the fluorescence image.','{\"pat_doc\": 242.0, \"pub_alt\": 623.0, \"pub_doc\": 6016.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 508.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 24.0, \"grant_fund\": 187529376.0, \"pat_granted\": 76.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.7, \"pub_doc\": -63.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.8, \"grant_fund\": -17544989.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b8906ab6e39c7a9acda68b65804dabfd','b78f1ff4779c63394e7882c5ca767bf9','5f9f631521aff2090e15184e37181d22','2023-09-04 19:03:15','2023-10-29 06:20:05','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Immunohistochemistry',36,'Immunohistochemistry is the most common application of immunostaining. It involves the process of selectively identifying antigens in cells of a tissue section by exploiting the principle of antibodies binding specifically to antigens in biological tissues. IHC takes its name from the roots \"immuno\", in reference to antibodies used in the procedure, and \"histo\", meaning tissue. Albert Coons conceptualized and first implemented the procedure in 1941. Visualising an antibody-antigen interaction can be accomplished in a number of ways, mainly either of the following: â€¢ Chromogenic immunohistochemistry, wherein an antibody is conjugated to an enzyme, such as peroxidase, that can catalyse a colour-producing reaction. â€¢ Immunofluorescence, where the antibody is tagged to a fluorophore, such as fluorescein or rhodamine. Immunohistochemical staining is widely used in the diagnosis of abnormal cells such as those found in cancerous tumors.','{\"pat_doc\": 533.0, \"pub_alt\": 28733.0, \"pub_doc\": 47184.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1120.0, \"clinic_alt\": 553.0, \"clinic_doc\": 777.0, \"grant_fund\": 319645373.0, \"pat_granted\": 184.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.1, \"pub_doc\": -408.2, \"clinic_doc\": 134.5, \"grant_fund\": -28858320.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b8a05f4ae8453f1b23a1badf11b3d371','5421c4aba6fdcb923ad6893affebb649','ad96306f7a3e23d74408bb23ac8e0e9a','2023-09-08 09:55:35','2023-10-28 19:56:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Near-infrared imaging',48,'Near-infrared (NIR) imaging refers to a technique in which light in the near-infrared spectrum is used to create images of biological specimens. This technique is popular in the medical field, especially in cancer diagnosis and treatment. NIR light penetrates deeper into biological tissues than visible light and is absorbed by various molecules, including water, lipids, and proteins. By measuring the reflected or absorbed light, NIR imaging allows for the detection of abnormalities such as tumors. NIR imaging is non-invasive, fast, and does not require ionizing radiation, making it a safer alternative to other imaging techniques. It also has potential applications in areas such as agriculture, food, and environmental monitoring.','{\"pat_doc\": 140.0, \"pub_alt\": 876.0, \"pub_doc\": 518.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 28.0, \"grant_fund\": 5447651.0, \"pat_granted\": 51.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.8, \"pub_doc\": 0.6, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": -73702.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b8fa87ab1b6666fcdfad43556af846f4','8b12860860c34fa4f49e9fadc6bbab1d','d471ba9d05b4186943ade5d1a2ae30dc','2023-09-04 18:21:24','2023-10-29 07:10:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Mass Spectrometry',12,'Mass Spectrometry is a powerful analytical technique used in chemistry, biochemistry, and other scientific fields to identify molecules based on their mass-to-charge ratio (m/z). The process involves ionizing a sample, then separating the resulting ions based on their mass-to-charge ratio using electromagnetic fields. The ions are then detected and analyzed to determine their individual masses and concentrations. Mass spectrometry is used in many applications, including characterizing the structure of unknown compounds, identifying proteins and peptides, and tracking the movement of isotopes within molecules. It has become a standard tool in many areas of research, including drug discovery, environmental analysis, and forensic science.','{\"pat_doc\": 3936.0, \"pub_alt\": 3571.0, \"pub_doc\": 32260.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 943.0, \"clinic_alt\": 146.0, \"clinic_doc\": 435.0, \"grant_fund\": 418515424.0, \"pat_granted\": 1337.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 210.2, \"pub_doc\": 879.4, \"clinic_doc\": 100.8, \"grant_fund\": -169513024.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b9033f462562726b82a507d77f32ba37','3cf46267ec47fde029e918d250b335a1','c26c7529dcbe3665be368505da21babe','2023-09-08 02:53:34','2023-10-28 13:56:10','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Nanobots',48,'Nanoid robotics, or for short, nanorobotics or nanobotics, is an emerging technology field creating machines or robots whose components are at or near the scale of a nanometer. More specifically, nanorobotics refers to the nanotechnology engineering discipline of designing and building nanorobots with devices ranging in size from 0.1 to 10 micrometres and constructed of nanoscale or molecular components. The terms nanobot, nanoid, nanite, nanomachine and nanomite have also been used to describe such devices currently under research and development. Nanomachines are largely in the research and development phase, but some primitive molecular machines and nanomotors have been tested. An example is a sensor having a switch approximately 1.5 nanometers across, able to count specific molecules in the chemical sample. The first useful applications of nanomachines may be in nanomedicine. For example, biological machines could be used to identify and destroy cancer cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 10.0, \"pub_alt\": 265.0, \"pub_doc\": 135.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4944669.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 11.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -619816.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b90348fb5a042819d0142d4e0524ea74','3c24254d6c0d4e4249ab4b441e17dc83','abbcb6a1638f63a5747e204b798f4ec2','2023-09-08 00:41:06','2023-10-29 01:11:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','DNA Synthesis',12,'DNA synthesis is the natural or artificial creation of deoxyribonucleic acid molecules. DNA is a macromolecule made up of nucleotide units, which are linked by covalent bonds and hydrogen bonds, in a repeating structure. DNA synthesis occurs when these nucleotide units are joined to form DNA; this can occur artificially or naturally. Nucleotide units are made up of a nitrogenous base, pentose sugar and phosphate group. Each unit is joined when a covalent bond forms between its phosphate group and the pentose sugar of the next nucleotide, forming a sugar-phosphate backbone. DNA is a complementary, double stranded structure as specific base pairing occurs naturally when hydrogen bonds form between the nucleotide bases. There are several different definitions for DNA synthesis: it can refer to DNA replication - DNA biosynthesis, polymerase chain reaction - enzymatic DNA synthesis or gene synthesis - physically creating artificial gene sequences.','{\"pat_doc\": 155.0, \"pub_alt\": 590.0, \"pub_doc\": 797.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_alt\": 55.0, \"clinic_doc\": 41.0, \"grant_fund\": 14287741.0, \"pat_granted\": 45.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.0, \"pub_doc\": -7.9, \"clinic_doc\": 8.6, \"grant_fund\": -10466344.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b90e7af7c494e5ca5b283c817fac355f','3ac2ba09e7b52bbe721ad2f6f07c0d4c','efc072896d951f3550e7d73c38f3d42e','2023-09-08 09:56:42','2023-10-28 19:51:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Microscale thermophoresis',36,'Microscale thermophoresis is a technology for the interaction analysis of biomolecules. Microscale thermophoresis is the directed movement of particles in a microscopic temperature gradient. Any change of the hydration shell of biomolecules due to changes in their structure/conformation results in a relative change of the movement along the temperature gradient and is used to determine binding affinities. MST allows measurement of interactions directly in solution without the need of immobilization to a surface.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 361.0, \"pub_doc\": 548.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 25.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4171445.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -485048.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('b999ebb1b180f6561a517445d781b105','94a11929f6fb7d9d93e190ab5230cb23','2874f833fd4f69190438aa7cb5f052b5','2023-09-05 20:19:29','2023-10-29 04:41:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Blockchain technology',24,'Blockchain technology is a distributed ledger technology that allows for secure, transparent and irreversible peer-to-peer transactions without the need for intermediaries. It is based on a decentralized network of nodes that validate transactions and add them to the blockchain, a public ledger of all transactions. Blockchain technology is essentially a digital ledger that records and stores data in a secure and transparent way. This makes it useful for a variety of applications, such as cryptocurrency, supply chain management, voting systems, and more. The technologys key features include decentralization, transparency, immutability, and security. Overall, blockchain technology has the potential to revolutionize multiple industries and enable new business models.','{\"pat_doc\": 2458.0, \"pub_alt\": 1120.0, \"pub_doc\": 12034.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 100.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\"