l factors to restore, maintain, improve, or replace different types of biological tissues. Tissue engineering often involves the use of cells placed on tissue scaffolds in the formation of new viable tissue for a medical purpose but is not limited to applications involving cells and tissue scaffolds. While it was once categorized as a sub-field of biomaterials, having grown in scope and importance it can be considered as a field of its own. While most definitions of tissue engineering cover a broad range of applications, in practice the term is closely associated with applications that repair or replace portions of or whole tissues. Often, the tissues involved require certain mechanical and structural properties for proper functioning.','{\"pat_doc\": 2009.0, \"pub_alt\": 641.0, \"pub_doc\": 13513.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 698.0, \"clinic_alt\": 16.0, \"clinic_doc\": 61.0, \"grant_fund\": 242322849.0, \"pat_granted\": 780.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.9, \"pub_doc\": 306.5, \"clinic_doc\": 10.5, \"grant_fund\": -54494104.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c1c15b9c34468d2bf1513101746a5b89','eee0d94d36c42e167a1a4be01f14392d','8c7694fa0bfc9847929f37bd7f31bd59','2023-09-04 19:48:49','2023-10-29 05:51:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','3D printing',48,'3D printing or additive manufacturing is the construction of a three-dimensional object from a CAD model or a digital 3D model. It can be done in a variety of processes in which material is deposited, joined or solidified under computer control, with the material being added together, typically layer by layer. In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping. As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology, whereby the term additive manufacturing can be used synonymously with 3D printing.','{\"pat_doc\": 37442.0, \"pub_alt\": 2627.0, \"pub_doc\": 30445.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2691.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 240.0, \"grant_fund\": 1023150755.0, \"pat_granted\": 16184.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 434.0, \"pub_doc\": 1197.3, \"clinic_doc\": 23.8, \"grant_fund\": -8565739.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c1d74d7d0ec02eec7906c1cc32f1b0b3','665bbf50f9c0e74f93301c0a8c98acec','f7f9ce80272ab55a46f45831f319f87c','2023-09-08 10:01:20','2023-10-28 19:26:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Turbidimetry',12,'Turbidimetry is the process of measuring the loss of intensity of transmitted light due to the scattering effect of particles suspended in it. Light is passed through a filter creating a light of known wavelength which is then passed through a cuvette containing a solution. A photoelectric cell collects the light which passes through the cuvette. A measurement is then given for the amount of absorbed light. Turbidimetry can be used in biology to find the number of cells in a solution. Turbidity-is an expression of optical look of a solution caused by radiation to the scattered and absorbed wavelength. Scattering of light is elastic so both incident and scattered radiation have same wavelength. A turbidometer measures the amount of radiation that passes through a fluid in forward direction,analogous to absorption spectrphotoometry.','{\"pat_doc\": 85.0, \"pub_alt\": 52.0, \"pub_doc\": 156.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 149735.0, \"pat_granted\": 33.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -10.5, \"pub_doc\": -8.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": -47175.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c206fe1dca71da0f07cc378fd047d7ef','4823e60bd764349fc024f2fba11838f0','30640b686e5be896faa3d14ed6691346','2023-09-05 18:49:44','2023-10-29 05:35:06','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Biosensor',48,'A biosensor is an analytical device, used for the detection of a chemical substance, that combines a biological component with a physicochemical detector. The sensitive biological element, e.g. tissue, microorganisms, organelles, cell receptors, enzymes, antibodies, nucleic acids, etc., is a biologically derived material or biomimetic component that interacts with, binds with, or recognizes the analyte under study. The biologically sensitive elements can also be created by biological engineering. The transducer or the detector element, which transforms one signal into another one, works in a physicochemical way: optical, piezoelectric, electrochemical, electrochemiluminescence etc., resulting from the interaction of the analyte with the biological element, to easily measure and quantify. The biosensor reader device connects with the associated electronics or signal processors that are primarily responsible for the display of the results in a user-friendly way.','{\"pat_doc\": 9808.0, \"pub_alt\": 3920.0, \"pub_doc\": 33303.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2318.0, \"clinic_alt\": 108.0, \"clinic_doc\": 162.0, \"grant_fund\": 989358162.0, \"pat_granted\": 3181.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 137.4, \"pub_doc\": 867.1, \"clinic_doc\": 19.0, \"grant_fund\": -13437491.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c29c55633c1bdd10fad33af0d19fbe98','074a886190f8a82396d29ea68958db61','e9ee3da8c5950eddf30d7e6a8d175388','2023-09-08 00:39:05','2023-10-29 01:16:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Protein Engineering',36,'Protein engineering is the process of developing useful or valuable proteins through the design and production of unnatural polypeptides, often by altering amino acid sequences found in nature. It is a young discipline, with much research taking place into the understanding of protein folding and recognition for protein design principles. It has been used to improve the function of many enzymes for industrial catalysis. It is also a product and services market, with an estimated value of $168 billion by 2017. There are two general strategies for protein engineering: rational protein design and directed evolution. These methods are not mutually exclusive; researchers will often apply both. In the future, more detailed knowledge of protein structure and function, and advances in high-throughput screening, may greatly expand the abilities of protein engineering.','{\"pat_doc\": 429.0, \"pub_alt\": 1312.0, \"pub_doc\": 1996.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 432.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 254484564.0, \"pat_granted\": 135.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.1, \"pub_doc\": 48.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -16048598.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c3366c4c96aceae883566fa4c963277b','f1d991da1c3d1f34a90384e385b676a5','4101f5b584ffd5355154925e914aabcc','2023-09-08 00:58:18','2023-10-29 00:46:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Mass Cytometry',12,'Mass cytometry is a mass spectrometry technique based on inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry and time of flight mass spectrometry used for the determination of the properties of cells. In this approach, antibodies are conjugated with isotopically pure elements, and these antibodies are used to label cellular proteins. Cells are nebulized and sent through an argon plasma, which ionizes the metal-conjugated antibodies. The metal signals are then analyzed by a time-of-flight mass spectrometer. The approach overcomes limitations of spectral overlap in flow cytometry by utilizing discrete isotopes as a reporter system instead of traditional fluorophores which have broad emission spectra.','{\"pat_doc\": 31.0, \"pub_alt\": 619.0, \"pub_doc\": 583.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 61.0, \"clinic_alt\": 53.0, \"clinic_doc\": 51.0, \"grant_fund\": 25830554.0, \"pat_granted\": 5.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.1, \"pub_doc\": 21.7, \"clinic_doc\": 15.1, \"grant_fund\": -21158977.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c3a333e2082afd446d65c2b31dbc5c2a','dc11d80fc0114b8dfe9fa719a1d68ad7','a0ec7ffe04c046d0f8469b5de966ddfa','2023-09-04 18:54:26','2023-10-29 06:35:05','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Flow Cytometry',36,'Flow cytometry is a technique used to detect and measure physical and chemical characteristics of a population of cells or particles. In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument. The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components. Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths. Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer. Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials. Uses for flow cytometry include: â€¢ Cell counting â€¢ Cell sorting â€¢ Determining cell characteristics and function â€¢ Detecting microorganisms â€¢ Biomarker detection â€¢ Protein engineering detection â€¢ Diagnosis of health disorders such as blood cancers â€¢ Measuring genome size.','{\"pat_doc\": 1558.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 50469.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1677.0, \"clinic_alt\": 590.0, \"clinic_doc\": 766.0, \"grant_fund\": 478554038.0, \"pat_granted\": 510.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.1, \"pub_doc\": -433.8, \"clinic_doc\": 137.2, \"grant_fund\": -49967547.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c438643c3786d04d6e4a7d4eed69d65b','a822340ed295802f1550f5d13064ed80','26d358ca64d0c56aa9745ea1401e4d59','2023-09-05 22:53:22','2023-10-28 12:05:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Holography',12,'Holography is a technique that uses light to create three-dimensional images referred to as holograms. It was first developed in the mid-20th century and has since found numerous applications in fields such as art, security, and medicine. A hologram is created by splitting a laser beam into two and directing one toward an object while the other heads straight onto a photographic plate or film. When the two beams meet, an interference pattern is formed that captures the objects unique features. This pattern can then be viewed, illuminating a hologram of the object that appears lifelike, with depth and dimension. Holography plays a significant role in virtual reality, data storage, and scientific research, among others.','{\"pat_doc\": 195.0, \"pub_alt\": 1635.0, \"pub_doc\": 1561.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 56.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 68484541.0, \"pat_granted\": 65.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -18.4, \"pub_doc\": 93.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": 8559104.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c44f5c1f33d870c47407627fd1f21a00','99c7079af458b7e10d0e17de306286cf','7ec492ea6e0e56c5b381d422684157c5','2023-09-08 01:01:12','2023-09-08 01:01:12','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Cushing\'s Syndrome',48,'Cushing\'s syndrome is a collection of signs and symptoms due to prolonged exposure to glucocorticoids such as cortisol. Signs and symptoms may include high blood pressure, abdominal obesity but with thin arms and legs, reddish stretch marks, a round red face due to facial plethora, a fat lump between the shoulders, weak muscles, weak bones, acne, and fragile skin that heals poorly. Women may have more hair and irregular menstruation. Occasionally there may be changes in mood, headaches, and a chronic feeling of tiredness. Cushing\'s syndrome is caused by either excessive cortisol-like medication, such as prednisone, or a tumor that either produces or results in the production of excessive cortisol by the adrenal glands. Cases due to a pituitary adenoma are known as Cushing\'s disease, which is the second most common cause of Cushing\'s syndrome after medication. A number of other tumors, often referred to as ectopic due to their placement outside the pituitary, may also cause Cushing\'s.','{\"pat_doc\": 209.0, \"pub_alt\": 563.0, \"pub_doc\": 1050.0, \"deals_num\": 6.0, \"grant_doc\": 17.0, \"clinic_alt\": 32.0, \"clinic_doc\": 79.0, \"grant_fund\": 2294510.0, \"pat_granted\": 69.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 4.0, \"capital_raised\": 2154.86746457}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.3, \"pub_doc\": 41.6, \"clinic_doc\": 8.9, \"grant_fund\": -229023.8, \"capital_raised\": 215.348}'),('c4666c164b5f688c790646d852c085a8','60518e711e4b43d56a5bbd7732ffd16e','9d4e5b197da5f47c35976f2bf01251b9','2023-09-05 22:10:54','2023-10-29 03:31:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Personal Protective Equipment',36,'Personal protective equipment is protective clothing, helmets, goggles, or other garments or equipment designed to protect the wearers body from injury or infection. The hazards addressed by protective equipment include physical, electrical, heat, chemicals, biohazards, and airborne particulate matter. Protective equipment may be worn for job-related occupational safety and health purposes, as well as for sports and other recreational activities. Protective clothing is applied to traditional categories of clothing, and protective gear applies to items such as pads, guards, shields, or masks, and others. PPE suits can be similar in appearance to a cleanroom suit. The purpose of personal protective equipment is to reduce employee exposure to hazards when engineering controls and administrative controls are not feasible or effective to reduce these risks to acceptable levels. PPE is needed when there are hazards present.','{\"pat_doc\": 1067.0, \"pub_alt\": 6351.0, \"pub_doc\": 9700.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 237.0, \"clinic_alt\": 200.0, \"clinic_doc\": 206.0, \"grant_fund\": 99636973.0, \"pat_granted\": 184.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.6, \"pub_doc\": -446.8, \"clinic_doc\": -1.4, \"grant_fund\": -24125078.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c52c08056044fac72c30ddba823fcce5','1728b9cb87efc77cfd614e3c4311a042','ee2727bc78203418d56b7f3bacf8d4dc','2023-09-08 01:47:28','2023-10-28 11:15:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Web 3.0',24,'Web 3.0, also known as the Semantic Web, refers to the evolution of the internet that aims to provide a more seamless and intelligent user experience. It is based on the idea of improving the way data is accessed and used, by creating a universal language for machines to understand and communicate with each other. This means that information on the web will be more interconnected, accessible, and easier to find. Web 3.0 aims to enable decentralization, personalization, and improved security on the internet. It has the potential to transform industries such as healthcare, finance, and education, by improving data sharing, privacy, and efficiency.','{\"pat_doc\": 15.0, \"pub_alt\": 338.0, \"pub_doc\": 491.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 16.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 3055384.0, \"pat_granted\": 5.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.3, \"pub_doc\": 89.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 613675.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c543d50c4c2f2d20cc6a826ca2445f6a','42ee32d5802de92090c858e3452a50cf','d7426f446b19a6b58ca2ef44eac3e4b3','2023-09-08 01:12:46','2023-10-29 00:31:27','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','3D Cell Culture',24,'A 3D cell culture is an artificially created environment in which biological cells are permitted to grow or interact with their surroundings in all three dimensions. Unlike 2D environments, a 3D cell culture allows cells in vitro to grow in all directions, similar to how they would in vivo. These three-dimensional cultures are usually grown in bioreactors, small capsules in which the cells can grow into spheroids, or 3D cell colonies. Approximately 300 spheroids are usually cultured per bioreactor. 3D cell cultures can also be performed on microfluidic devices such as the OrganoplateÂ® to generate perfusable 3D tissues, and hanging drop devices to generate 3D spheroids.','{\"pat_doc\": 134.0, \"pub_alt\": 255.0, \"pub_doc\": 824.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 93.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 27274797.0, \"pat_granted\": 39.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 5.8, \"pub_doc\": 19.4, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -5741441.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c584c2ed6595f926fc52a35446899599','9ae996f0d6bbaff7b400a3648677eeaf','f79d0c4233733c41a41b0769be4ec44f','2023-09-08 01:43:31','2023-10-28 11:25:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Heterogeneous Integration',36,'Heterogeneous Integration refers to the process of combining different types of materials, devices, components, or functions into a single system or package. It involves the use of various technologies to create complex systems that can perform multiple functions using different components integrated together. This process enables the creation of new products, systems, and services with improved features, performance, and flexibility. The main benefits of heterogeneous integration include reduced cost, improved system performance, and increased connectivity and functionality. This approach is widely used in the development of advanced microprocessors, wireless communication devices, sensors and actuators, and other high-tech products. By integrating various components with different functionalities, manufacturers can achieve compact, high-performance systems that meet the demands of modern applications.','{\"pat_doc\": 317.0, \"pub_alt\": 288.0, \"pub_doc\": 978.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 133.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 118642137.0, \"pat_granted\": 89.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 24.9, \"pub_doc\": 44.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 9542163.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c64e3bf031f231505da967c5a2771de0','2815d363c4afb5dbd132a1ef2ad77edd','6476dd0e621a6ae9d97f588345914b91','2023-09-08 02:29:21','2023-10-28 14:26:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','McCune-Albright Syndrome',48,'McCuneâ€“Albright syndrome is a complex genetic disorder affecting the bone, skin and endocrine systems. It is a mosaic disease arising from somatic activating mutations in GNAS, which encodes the alpha-subunit of the Gâ‚› heterotrimeric G protein. It was first described in 1937 by American pediatrician Donovan James McCune and American endocrinologist Fuller Albright.','{\"pat_doc\": 2.0, \"pub_alt\": 70.0, \"pub_doc\": 218.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 3863032.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": -0.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": 27877.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c6a85567096c15d909097852042b1bf7','adc255a75abbc6dc9e8c5d454e86dad3','da6fc92b2753b0e9a72b21f2c514a42d','2023-09-08 00:04:14','2023-10-29 02:06:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Smart material',24,'Smart materials, also called intelligent or responsive materials, are designed materials that have one or more properties that can be significantly changed in a controlled fashion by external stimuli, such as stress, moisture, electric or magnetic fields, light, temperature, pH, or chemical compounds. Smart materials are the basis of many applications, including sensors and actuators, or artificial muscles, particularly as electroactive polymers. Terms used to describe smart materials include shape memory material and shape memory technology.','{\"pat_doc\": 93.0, \"pub_alt\": 227.0, \"pub_doc\": 9754.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 137.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 63134854.0, \"pat_granted\": 36.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -2.5, \"pub_doc\": 844.3, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -20872158.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c6ed0f4bcb4e98673c8af9d412bed45e','f82670ab57400d3e832f9efb4a5573a4','2e3f377d891e03c5b7a4ddf257a19dc5','2023-09-08 01:35:27','2023-10-28 15:11:17','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','DNA origami',48,'DNA origami is the nanoscale folding of DNA to create arbitrary two- and three-dimensional shapes at the nanoscale. The specificity of the interactions between complementary base pairs make DNA a useful construction material, through design of its base sequences. DNA is a well-understood material that is suitable for creating scaffolds that hold other molecules in place or to create structures all on its own. DNA origami was the cover story of Nature on March 16, 2006. Since then, DNA origami has progressed past an art form and has found a number of applications from drug delivery systems to uses as circuitry in plasmonic devices; however, most commercial applications remain in a concept or testing phase.','{\"pat_doc\": 131.0, \"pub_alt\": 581.0, \"pub_doc\": 1170.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 167.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 134350876.0, \"pat_granted\": 35.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.1, \"pub_doc\": 26.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1724661.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c6fd02d9154ea6e5ec0ddc3b5a41fa97','b5180881c0acd170e35e7e2628346b44','6f23015b34810fffb37ea505c3bdbd67','2023-09-05 19:31:51','2023-10-29 05:01:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Culture',36,'Cell culture or tissue culture is the process by which cells are grown under controlled conditions, generally outside of their natural environment. The term \"tissue culture\" was coined by American pathologist Montrose Thomas Burrows. This technique is also called micropropagation. After the cells of interest have been isolated from living tissue, they can subsequently be maintained under carefully controlled conditions. They need to be kept at body temperature in an incubator. These conditions vary for each cell type, but generally consist of a suitable vessel with a substrate or rich medium that supplies the essential nutrients, growth factors, hormones, and gases, and regulates the physio-chemical environment. Most cells require a surface or an artificial substrate to form an adherent culture as a monolayer, whereas others can be grown free floating in a medium as a suspension culture.','{\"pat_doc\": 18237.0, \"pub_alt\": 6747.0, \"pub_doc\": 22215.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2742.0, \"clinic_alt\": 504.0, \"clinic_doc\": 283.0, \"grant_fund\": 948145231.0, \"pat_granted\": 7048.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 342.7, \"pub_doc\": -154.3, \"clinic_doc\": 41.7, \"grant_fund\": -133904294.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c7554229a07c9453103337fcc6bd12e4','fa64bf855faf8c0f2191aab2fb8e889c','1eb03b411e805213588194c37797ec5c','2023-09-05 21:42:31','2023-10-28 17:41:11','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Hypothyroidism',48,'Hypothyroidism is a disorder of the endocrine system in which the thyroid gland does not produce enough thyroid hormone. It can cause a number of symptoms, such as poor ability to tolerate cold, a feeling of tiredness, constipation, slow heart rate, depression, and weight gain. Occasionally there may be swelling of the front part of the neck due to goitre. Untreated cases of hypothyroidism during pregnancy can lead to delays in growth and intellectual development in the baby or congenital iodine deficiency syndrome. Worldwide, too little iodine in the diet is the most common cause of hypothyroidism. Hashimotos thyroiditis is the most common cause of hypothyroidism in countries with sufficient dietary iodine. Less common causes include previous treatment with radioactive iodine, injury to the hypothalamus or the anterior pituitary gland, certain medications, a lack of a functioning thyroid at birth, or previous thyroid surgery.','{\"pat_doc\": 220.0, \"pub_alt\": 1214.0, \"pub_doc\": 13431.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 142.0, \"clinic_alt\": 28.0, \"clinic_doc\": 717.0, \"grant_fund\": 22102571.0, \"pat_granted\": 29.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.4, \"pub_doc\": 201.3, \"clinic_doc\": 62.3, \"grant_fund\": -98143.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c7967f24bdf31831f5aedffe8ae8648e','2f412f6d08233ef2ee97b503f7c210fd','bc432a22793de3677b1dacfb29fc2326','2023-09-08 09:49:36','2023-10-28 20:21:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','SDS-PAGE',48,'SDS-PAGE is a discontinuous electrophoretic system developed by Ulrich K. Laemmli which is commonly used as a method to separate proteins with molecular masses between 5 and 250 kDa. The combined use of sodium dodecyl sulfate and polyacrylamide gel eliminates the influence of structure and charge, and proteins are separated by differences in their size. At least up to 2012, the publication describing it was the most frequently cited paper by a single author, and the second most cited overall.','{\"pat_doc\": 291.0, \"pub_alt\": 606.0, \"pub_doc\": 5650.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 111.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 13.0, \"grant_fund\": 11546790.0, \"pat_granted\": 110.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.7, \"pub_doc\": -42.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": -1973486.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c7b51c00cef51236c9403bcbdf355a0b','30ab92573d44ab7bfab530de0c6c2f3b','834e427876f8944f329691ead9f0d4a1','2023-09-04 19:50:57','2023-10-28 18:06:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Coronary artery diseases',36,'Coronary artery diseases are a group of conditions that affect the blood vessels that supply the heart muscle with oxygen and nutrients. These diseases occur when there is a buildup of plaque, or fatty deposits, in the coronary arteries, which can narrow or block these vessels altogether. This can result in reduced blood flow to the heart, leading to chest pain (angina), shortness of breath, and even heart attacks. Risk factors for coronary artery disease include high blood pressure, high cholesterol, smoking, obesity, and an unhealthy diet. Treatment options for coronary artery disease include lifestyle changes such as exercise and diet modifications, medications, and in severe cases, surgery.','{\"pat_doc\": 33.0, \"pub_alt\": 339.0, \"pub_doc\": 626.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 14.0, \"clinic_alt\": 187.0, \"clinic_doc\": 61.0, \"grant_fund\": 2915667.0, \"pat_granted\": 9.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.7, \"pub_doc\": -4.9, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 134481.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c7c5b40b46c062590b71ad8c3db9c714','400032bc6a390bdea6fc89bda66806fe','5ca1ea433f162c5e837f4ddcc3c02253','2023-09-04 18:36:28','2023-10-29 06:56:10','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Chromatography',12,'In chemical analysis, chromatography is a laboratory technique for the separation of a mixture into its components. The mixture is dissolved in a fluid solvent (gas or liquid) called the mobile phase, which carries it through a system (a column, a capillary tube, a plate, or a sheet) on which a material called the stationary phase is fixed.','{\"pat_doc\": 11228.0, \"pub_alt\": 2957.0, \"pub_doc\": 31147.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 349.0, \"clinic_alt\": 100.0, \"clinic_doc\": 359.0, \"grant_fund\": 96382698.0, \"pat_granted\": 4356.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 570.9, \"pub_doc\": 561.6, \"clinic_doc\": 78.4, \"grant_fund\": -32028130.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c7dad8b4f0d686bf5999b150033d18df','b052bba7b488d052b6c520140b9a95f7','0f0001c9173ff0ef27a841bf7334c0a3','2023-09-07 23:32:11','2023-10-29 02:41:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Synthetic biology',12,'Synthetic biology is a multidisciplinary field of science that focuses on living systems and organisms, and it applies engineering principles to develop new biological parts, devices, and systems or to redesign existing systems found in nature. It is a branch of science that encompasses a broad range of methodologies from various disciplines, such as biotechnology, biomaterials, material science/engineering, genetic engineering, molecular biology, molecular engineering, systems biology, membrane science, biophysics, chemical and biological engineering, electrical and computer engineering, control engineering and evolutionary biology. It includes designing and constructing biological modules, biological systems, and biological machines or, re-design of existing biological systems for useful purposes. Additionally, it is the branch of science that focuses on the new abilities of engineering into existing organisms to redesign them for useful purposes.','{\"pat_doc\": 263.0, \"pub_alt\": 1082.0, \"pub_doc\": 1643.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 311.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 210539618.0, \"pat_granted\": 68.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 62.9, \"pub_doc\": 64.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.7, \"grant_fund\": -38172745.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c7eddc5d27274cc1e2f7ae31079f5b43','70acbc1819a41cd643bd80877d3bc5a4','79f0607dd327b272b64831fef13948f0','2023-09-08 09:12:08','2023-10-28 13:11:13','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Oncogenic signalling',24,'Oncogenic signaling refers to the changes that occur within cells that lead to uncontrolled cell growth and proliferation, ultimately resulting in cancer. These changes are typically driven by mutations that occur in genes that are involved in regulating cell growth and division. When these mutations occur, the affected gene becomes altered in a way that enhances its ability to promote cell growth and proliferation. This can occur through various mechanisms, including the activation of signaling pathways that regulate cell growth and division, or the alteration of the proteins that control the cell cycle. Ultimately, oncogenic signaling is a complex and multifaceted phenomenon that involves multiple genetic and biochemical factors working together to promote the growth and spread of cancer cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 410.0, \"pub_doc\": 75.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 3535728.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 2.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 250205.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c801ece92cdf1112c173f7edac9883b2','b663e797baa447591490dab433b724b6','e5dc1ab9b95fd144580ba449bdb1f286','2023-09-05 22:04:26','2023-10-28 17:31:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Gene therapies (Non-viral)','CRISPR-Cas9',48,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 956.0, \"pub_alt\": 3610.0, \"pub_doc\": 7026.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1218.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 22.0, \"grant_fund\": 503974497.0, \"pat_granted\": 261.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.8, \"pub_doc\": 114.2, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -29971557.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c829667ecf28b2eecf12a12fe52411cf','b623d7ca57acae4c7c681109e883ff82','9b78c6ab99d1ce69ff59eddcd1444cfe','2023-09-04 18:43:50','2023-10-28 18:21:15','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Heart failure',36,'Heart failure, also known as congestive heart failure, is a syndrome, a group of signs and symptoms, caused by an impairment of the hearts blood pumping function. Symptoms typically include shortness of breath, excessive fatigue, and leg swelling. The shortness of breath may occur with exertion or while lying down, and may wake people up during the night. Chest pain, including angina, is not usually caused by heart failure, but may occur if the heart failure was caused by a heart attack. The severity of the heart failure is mainly decided based on ejection fraction and also measured by the severity of symptoms. Other conditions that may have symptoms similar to heart failure include obesity, kidney failure, liver disease, anemia, and thyroid disease. Common causes of heart failure include coronary artery disease, heart attack, high blood pressure, atrial fibrillation, valvular heart disease, excessive alcohol consumption, infection, and cardiomyopathy.','{\"pat_doc\": 4392.0, \"pub_alt\": 20133.0, \"pub_doc\": 69898.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2878.0, \"clinic_alt\": 886.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5059.0, \"grant_fund\": 1392316026.0, \"pat_granted\": 1222.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 60.6, \"pub_doc\": 1207.9, \"clinic_doc\": 749.7, \"grant_fund\": -131899850.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c8be99bab1321398f4086687d9482354','e1e4825f9e69d0bff75f7b5f1728fa6c','de90a1c4d8531674dd30ee9b71846822','2023-09-08 02:18:06','2023-10-28 22:36:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Aseptic Technique',12,'Aseptic techniques are procedures followed by individual working in a area which is highly controlled with respect to its level of microbial count. The level of microbial count is controlled to eliminate their contamination in product, while processing aseptically in the working place like laminar air flow bench, unidirectional flow bench mainly used in pharmaceutical manufacturing of sterile drug products, and microbial testing labs. Aseptic techniques include the sterilization method of microbiological culture handling wire loops, which are required to hold over flame on a gas burner, before use in order to sterilize it. The growing procedures are adapted inside a critical area while handling sterile products or microbial culture. The sequential movement of material in and out of the critical area, sequential man movement and their dexterity of handling of the sterile product and the intervention methods altogether are called aseptic techniques.','{\"pat_doc\": 37.0, \"pub_alt\": 98.0, \"pub_doc\": 116.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 46.0, \"grant_fund\": 395436.0, \"pat_granted\": 33.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -10.9, \"pub_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.6, \"grant_fund\": 112023.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c94c0fbe7182e1376da7178149008cf8','9cb1fcb17b688427ac67a33166effbb2','5ed796512ab4425cf98a4d2c7cdf5653','2023-09-05 20:27:46','2023-10-28 18:01:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Hematopoietic Stem Cells',36,'Hematopoietic stem cells are the stem cells that give rise to other blood cells. This process is called haematopoiesis. In vertebrates, the very first definitive HSCs arise from the ventral endothelial wall of the embryonic aorta within the aorta-gonad-mesonephros region, through a process known as endothelial-to-hematopoietic transition. In adults, haematopoiesis occurs in the red bone marrow, in the core of most bones. The red bone marrow is derived from the layer of the embryo called the mesoderm. Haematopoiesis is the process by which all mature blood cells are produced. It must balance enormous production needs with the need to regulate the number of each blood cell type in the circulation. In vertebrates, the vast majority of hematopoiesis occurs in the bone marrow and is derived from a limited number of hematopoietic stem cells that are multipotent and capable of extensive self-renewal.','{\"pat_doc\": 1344.0, \"pub_alt\": 1334.0, \"pub_doc\": 4196.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 520.0, \"clinic_alt\": 164.0, \"clinic_doc\": 263.0, \"grant_fund\": 252521608.0, \"pat_granted\": 323.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -13.9, \"pub_doc\": -37.5, \"clinic_doc\": 48.6, \"grant_fund\": -17355143.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c9697369852e66bd246697601fd198f4','5a0a5b9065b639feb58f1b4e34dc9f7c','9c4ba206250041cf1644bb291a643634','2023-09-05 18:59:35','2023-10-29 05:21:13','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Next-Generation Sequencing',48,'Massive parallel sequencing or massively parallel sequencing is any of several high-throughput approaches to DNA sequencing using the concept of massively parallel processing; it is also called next-generation sequencing or second-generation sequencing. Some of these technologies emerged between 1993 and 1998 and have been commercially available since 2005. These technologies use miniaturized and parallelized platforms for sequencing of 1 million to 43 billion short reads per instrument run. Many NGS platforms differ in engineering configurations and sequencing chemistry. They share the technical paradigm of massive parallel sequencing via spatially separated, clonally amplified DNA templates or single DNA molecules in a flow cell. This design is very different from that of Sanger sequencingâ€”also known as capillary sequencing or first-generation sequencingâ€”which is based on electrophoretic separation of chain-termination products produced in individual sequencing reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 543.0, \"pub_alt\": 14265.0, \"pub_doc\": 26405.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1198.0, \"clinic_alt\": 77.0, \"clinic_doc\": 436.0, \"grant_fund\": 400868839.0, \"pat_granted\": 126.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.9, \"pub_doc\": 170.9, \"clinic_doc\": 72.6, \"grant_fund\": -38192044.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c96efa9781e4b1e6be0cb4f70d5054c7','8c579df990726481d707857fe85bab54','f0c1b8c703203eb82e320beebf070142','2023-09-04 19:39:15','2023-10-28 18:11:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','CRISPR',36,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 8553.0, \"pub_alt\": 3610.0, \"pub_doc\": 29784.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4581.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 85.0, \"grant_fund\": 2336528857.0, \"pat_granted\": 1998.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 422.3, \"pub_doc\": 715.2, \"clinic_doc\": 17.3, \"grant_fund\": -192193900.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c9731c973fd711271ab10e446b35b19a','92b44ff8d1d0e8c4689c1026159f41bb','dd42ec1636f7ea17b4c2869a3e543827','2023-09-08 02:08:52','2023-10-28 11:00:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Quantum Internet',12,'Quantum networks form an important element of quantum computing and quantum communication systems. Quantum networks facilitate the transmission of information in the form of quantum bits, also called qubits, between physically separated quantum processors. A quantum processor is a small quantum computer being able to perform quantum logic gates on a certain number of qubits. Quantum networks work in a similar way to classical networks. The main difference is that quantum networking, like quantum computing, is better at solving certain problems, such as modeling quantum systems.','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_alt\": 37.0, \"pub_doc\": 147.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 19.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 11012664.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.5, \"pub_doc\": 18.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -4606738.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('c990ef88217b1800206c8bfb065dd41b','8a48608f902f6d6e18861f68c6c16aa1','afe94a7da70247bc6803357002649726','2023-09-08 11:13:41','2023-10-28 18:41:12','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Clinical Decision Support Systems',48,'Clinical decision support systems (CDSS) are computer programs designed to assist healthcare professionals in making clinical decisions by providing information and knowledge at the point of care. CDSS incorporate patient data and evidence-based guidelines to suggest potential diagnoses, recommend laboratory tests and treatment options, calculate medication doses and detect harmful drug interactions. CDSS can improve patient outcomes by enhancing the accuracy of diagnoses, preventing medical errors, and enabling clinicians to make more informed decisions based on relevant clinical evidence. Furthermore, CDSS can help reduce healthcare costs and improve efficiency by reducing unnecessary tests and treatments, and minimizing length of hospital stay. Overall, CDSS provide an important tool for healthcare professionals to provide high-quality patient care.','{\"pat_doc\": 22.0, \"pub_alt\": 543.0, \"pub_doc\": 1380.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 59.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 35.0, \"grant_fund\": 28430054.0, \"pat_granted\": 5.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 46.6, \"clinic_doc\": 6.5, \"grant_fund\": -372976.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ca47e146d3ef49c91eba3326a6346ba1','3ac2ba09e7b52bbe721ad2f6f07c0d4c','efc072896d951f3550e7d73c38f3d42e','2023-09-08 09:56:42','2023-10-28 19:51:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Microscale thermophoresis',12,'Microscale thermophoresis is a technology for the interaction analysis of biomolecules. Microscale thermophoresis is the directed movement of particles in a microscopic temperature gradient. Any change of the hydration shell of biomolecules due to changes in their structure/conformation results in a relative change of the movement along the temperature gradient and is used to determine binding affinities. MST allows measurement of interactions directly in solution without the need of immobilization to a surface.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 70.0, \"pub_doc\": 186.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 916486.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -485048.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cae60287d7092f92c077bc355a5033bd','73178bcae12bbd288347bb8d8e293d45','9b201e2ee1a601e1d33b326135e74c79','2023-09-08 08:26:31','2023-10-28 10:35:32','Electronics','Devices','Other','4D printing',24,'4-dimensional printing uses the same techniques of 3D printing through computer-programmed deposition of material in successive layers to create a three-dimensional object. However, in 4D printing, the resulting 3D shape is able to morph into different forms in response to environmental stimulus, with the 4th dimension being the time-dependent shape change after the printing. It is therefore a type of programmable matter, wherein after the fabrication process, the printed product reacts with parameters within the environment and changes its form accordingly.','{\"pat_doc\": 226.0, \"pub_alt\": 211.0, \"pub_doc\": 778.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 22.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 15805691.0, \"pat_granted\": 85.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 10.9, \"pub_doc\": 86.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 226691.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cb7feb9504cb85d4c90d20a18d932ca4','f1c040e063712c5005b473ffb13588a1','cdaeb54e11180a1df70eb5bc5267c9f8','2023-09-08 09:46:18','2023-10-28 20:36:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Centrifugation',48,'Centrifugation is a mechanical process which involves the use of the centrifugal force to separate particles from a solution according to their size, shape, density, medium viscosity and rotor speed. The denser components of the mixture migrate away from the axis of the centrifuge, while the less dense components of the mixture migrate towards the axis. Chemists and biologists may increase the effective gravitational force of the test tube so that the precipitate will travel quickly and fully to the bottom of the tube. The remaining liquid that lies above the precipitate is called a supernatant or supernate. There is a correlation between the size and density of a particle and the rate that the particle separates from a heterogeneous mixture, when the only force applied is that of gravity. The larger the size and the larger the density of the particles, the faster they separate from the mixture.','{\"pat_doc\": 16036.0, \"pub_alt\": 2169.0, \"pub_doc\": 11529.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 474.0, \"clinic_alt\": 45.0, \"clinic_doc\": 477.0, \"grant_fund\": 76507012.0, \"pat_granted\": 8161.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -24.6, \"pub_doc\": 42.5, \"clinic_doc\": 50.1, \"grant_fund\": -9080944.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cb997d6f3f2fbb76a0f363378fda935e','7d2130a3ffbe9bc530ccc4b006bedc33','a21d57b1520cb1a6af41c917959012e7','2023-09-05 20:52:48','2023-10-28 17:51:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','siRNA',24,'SiRNA (short interfering RNA) is a small double-stranded RNA molecule that can trigger the destruction of specific messenger RNA (mRNA) and thereby inhibit the expression of genes. SiRNA is involved in RNA interference, a natural process that regulates gene expression at the post-transcriptional level. Once inside the cell, siRNA is incorporated into the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), which separates the two strands of the siRNA molecule and guides the antisense strand to a complementary target mRNA. The RISC complex then cleaves the target mRNA, preventing its translation into proteins. SiRNA has become a powerful tool for investigating gene function and developing new therapeutics for various diseases. Its potential applications include treating viral infections, cancer, and genetic disorders, as well as controlling insect pests and enhancing crop yields.','{\"pat_doc\": 2232.0, \"pub_alt\": 481.0, \"pub_doc\": 10690.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 424.0, \"clinic_alt\": 109.0, \"clinic_doc\": 23.0, \"grant_fund\": 144667480.0, \"pat_granted\": 585.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 99.5, \"pub_doc\": -402.5, \"clinic_doc\": 4.8, \"grant_fund\": -26868531.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cc192d50416a5a3126364295175bab14','116c9f3326973bf53316f607199f9944','09c8640e20ae09de463871c1529a6589','2023-09-05 22:07:59','2023-10-29 03:36:14','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Fluorescence Microscopy',12,'A fluorescence microscope is an optical microscope that uses fluorescence instead of, or in addition to, scattering, reflection, and attenuation or absorption, to study the properties of organic or inorganic substances. \"Fluorescence microscope\" refers to any microscope that uses fluorescence to generate an image, whether it is a simple set up like an epifluorescence microscope or a more complicated design such as a confocal microscope, which uses optical sectioning to get better resolution of the fluorescence image.','{\"pat_doc\": 125.0, \"pub_alt\": 623.0, \"pub_doc\": 2929.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 194.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 18.0, \"grant_fund\": 70072701.0, \"pat_granted\": 46.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.7, \"pub_doc\": -63.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.8, \"grant_fund\": -17544989.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cc76d10a0bbdfd4f6b0f146eb4b78b32','c66db8e5795eca3126bf573522e8cf4e','e77dece162a0133e50d5b2357c40719f','2023-09-05 22:56:00','2023-10-29 02:51:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','RNA interference',24,'RNA interference is a biological process in which RNA molecules are involved in sequence-specific suppression of gene expression by double-stranded RNA, through translational or transcriptional repression. Historically, RNAi was known by other names, including co-suppression, post-transcriptional gene silencing, and quelling. The detailed study of each of these seemingly different processes elucidated that the identity of these phenomena were all actually RNAi. Andrew Fire and Craig C. Mello shared the 2006 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their work on RNAi in the nematode worm Caenorhabditis elegans, which they published in 1998. Since the discovery of RNAi and its regulatory potentials, it has become evident that RNAi has immense potential in suppression of desired genes. RNAi is now known as precise, efficient, stable and better than antisense therapy for gene suppression.','{\"pat_doc\": 754.0, \"pub_alt\": 991.0, \"pub_doc\": 3577.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 153.0, \"clinic_alt\": 18.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 39864264.0, \"pat_granted\": 219.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.6, \"pub_doc\": -43.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": -14470471.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ccb3e45d25d60797328cda4a972045f4','5e047db7e10164d6ec0e89c2fe69a4b9','589b84d604aa424bb142db78b62d89e3','2023-09-08 02:00:38','2023-10-28 23:26:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Electrophoresis',48,'Protein electrophoresis is a method for analysing the proteins in a fluid or an extract. The electrophoresis may be performed with a small volume of sample in a number of alternative ways with or without a supporting medium: SDS polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis, free-flow electrophoresis, electrofocusing, isotachophoresis, affinity electrophoresis, immunoelectrophoresis, counterelectrophoresis, and capillary electrophoresis. Each method has many variations with individual advantages and limitations. Gel electrophoresis is often performed in combination with electroblotting immunoblotting to give additional information about a specific protein. Because of practical limitations, protein electrophoresis is generally not suited as a preparative method.','{\"pat_doc\": 96.0, \"pub_alt\": 230.0, \"pub_doc\": 855.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_alt\": 43.0, \"clinic_doc\": 28.0, \"grant_fund\": 1473924.0, \"pat_granted\": 57.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 3.1, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -94204.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ccba1edd295485604534ccd893df4386','074a886190f8a82396d29ea68958db61','e9ee3da8c5950eddf30d7e6a8d175388','2023-09-08 00:39:05','2023-10-29 01:16:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Protein Engineering',12,'Protein engineering is the process of developing useful or valuable proteins through the design and production of unnatural polypeptides, often by altering amino acid sequences found in nature. It is a young discipline, with much research taking place into the understanding of protein folding and recognition for protein design principles. It has been used to improve the function of many enzymes for industrial catalysis. It is also a product and services market, with an estimated value of $168 billion by 2017. There are two general strategies for protein engineering: rational protein design and directed evolution. These methods are not mutually exclusive; researchers will often apply both. In the future, more detailed knowledge of protein structure and function, and advances in high-throughput screening, may greatly expand the abilities of protein engineering.','{\"pat_doc\": 163.0, \"pub_alt\": 1207.0, \"pub_doc\": 713.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 91.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 66491002.0, \"pat_granted\": 41.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.1, \"pub_doc\": 48.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -16048598.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ccc923030140a236b47224bc522caa63','e10a2a038e97b6bb75152e575137a4fb','77e5f6785bd7c9d4f3610b4ac830ad4e','2023-09-08 00:22:46','2023-10-28 16:26:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Electroporation',36,'Electroporation, or electropermeabilization, is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing chemicals, drugs, electrode arrays or DNA to be introduced into the cell. In microbiology, the process of electroporation is often used to transform bacteria, yeast, or plant protoplasts by introducing new coding DNA. If bacteria and plasmids are mixed together, the plasmids can be transferred into the bacteria after electroporation, though depending on what is being transferred, cell-penetrating peptides or CellSqueeze could also be used. Electroporation works by passing thousands of volts across suspended cells in an electroporation cuvette. Afterwards, the cells have to be handled carefully until they have had a chance to divide, producing new cells that contain reproduced plasmids.','{\"pat_doc\": 1921.0, \"pub_alt\": 1984.0, \"pub_doc\": 2828.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 218.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1151.0, \"clinic_doc\": 164.0, \"grant_fund\": 80965440.0, \"pat_granted\": 535.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 72.8, \"pub_doc\": -23.0, \"clinic_doc\": 21.4, \"grant_fund\": -13946036.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cccadbc03c9b881d963a82d6435d1e6c','c4e49c5cbafa19cbaf0a14bd5ddcb651','0b71467e6421c543859a81713b7406ad','2023-09-08 09:43:15','2023-10-28 20:41:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','sample preparation',36,'In analytical chemistry, sample preparation refers to the ways in which a sample is treated prior to its analyses. Preparation is a very important step in most analytical techniques, because the techniques are often not responsive to the analyte in its in-situ form, or the results are distorted by interfering species. Sample preparation may involve dissolution, extraction, reaction with some chemical species, pulverizing, treatment with a chelating agent, masking, filtering, dilution, sub-sampling or many other techniques. Treatment is done to prepare the sample into a form ready for analysis by specified analytical equipment. Sample preparation could involve: crushing and dissolution, chemical digestion with acid or alkali, sample extraction, sample clean up and sample pre-concentration.','{\"pat_doc\": 7421.0, \"pub_alt\": 3919.0, \"pub_doc\": 11146.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 752.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 61.0, \"grant_fund\": 259322966.0, \"pat_granted\": 3492.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 189.7, \"pub_doc\": 74.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.5, \"grant_fund\": -48834204.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ccf40b5c3bbc44cd528c21fe813ebb18','3e296fb8632883059f895163006d1ec4','47c2be7d4757b7a89106ea7e007a13dc','2023-09-08 00:02:21','2023-10-29 02:11:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Fluorescence In Situ Hybridization',24,'Fluorescence in situ hybridization is a molecular cytogenetic technique that uses fluorescent probes that bind to only particular parts of a nucleic acid sequence with a high degree of sequence complementarity. It was developed by biomedical researchers in the early 1980s to detect and localize the presence or absence of specific DNA sequences on chromosomes. Fluorescence microscopy can be used to find out where the fluorescent probe is bound to the chromosomes. FISH is often used for finding specific features in DNA for use in genetic counseling, medicine, and species identification. FISH can also be used to detect and localize specific RNA targets in cells, circulating tumor cells, and tissue samples. In this context, it can help define the spatial-temporal patterns of gene expression within cells and tissues.','{\"pat_doc\": 128.0, \"pub_alt\": 1177.0, \"pub_doc\": 2680.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 68.0, \"clinic_alt\": 50.0, \"clinic_doc\": 69.0, \"grant_fund\": 47044938.0, \"pat_granted\": 37.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.1, \"pub_doc\": -35.6, \"clinic_doc\": 12.4, \"grant_fund\": -136298.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cd1263fc552019e66835634698768458','848c570f631dc66b6c71249b5532b80c','f53620dbd4935249cccf6fdb7d35b8cf','2023-09-04 19:36:20','2023-10-29 05:56:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Immunofluorescence',36,'Immunofluorescence is a technique used for light microscopy with a fluorescence microscope and is used primarily on biological samples. This technique uses the specificity of antibodies to their antigen to target fluorescent dyes to specific biomolecule targets within a cell, and therefore allows visualization of the distribution of the target molecule through the sample. The specific region an antibody recognizes on an antigen is called an epitope. There have been efforts in epitope mapping since many antibodies can bind the same epitope and levels of binding between antibodies that recognize the same epitope can vary. Additionally, the binding of the fluorophore to the antibody itself cannot interfere with the immunological specificity of the antibody or the binding capacity of its antigen. Immunofluorescence is a widely used example of immunostaining and is a specific example of immunohistochemistry.','{\"pat_doc\": 1121.0, \"pub_alt\": 4560.0, \"pub_doc\": 31017.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 694.0, \"clinic_alt\": 392.0, \"clinic_doc\": 149.0, \"grant_fund\": 292068938.0, \"pat_granted\": 423.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 29.2, \"pub_doc\": 619.2, \"clinic_doc\": 22.2, \"grant_fund\": -6312911.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cd22a2122dcd3231370dac1c58733fe5','af4c9bfdfefe7c5c014015d91cb309a6','df80b2fb86114e734e7660ea92fdd1fc','2023-09-08 00:08:07','2023-10-29 02:01:16','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Viral Vectors',36,'Viral vectors are tools commonly used by molecular biologists to deliver genetic material into cells. This process can be performed inside a living organism or in cell culture. Viruses have evolved specialized molecular mechanisms to efficiently transport their genomes inside the cells they infect. Delivery of genes or other genetic material by a vector is termed transduction and the infected cells are described as transduced. Molecular biologists first harnessed this machinery in the 1970s. Paul Berg used a modified SV40 virus containing DNA from the bacteriophage Î» to infect monkey kidney cells maintained in culture. In addition to their use in molecular biology research, viral vectors are used for gene therapy and the development of vaccines. Vectors can either integrate into a cells genome or transiently express a gene with non-integrative vectors.','{\"pat_doc\": 2786.0, \"pub_alt\": 8518.0, \"pub_doc\": 2963.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 450.0, \"clinic_alt\": 75.0, \"clinic_doc\": 34.0, \"grant_fund\": 305098838.0, \"pat_granted\": 391.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 84.9, \"pub_doc\": -18.6, \"clinic_doc\": 4.4, \"grant_fund\": -2376931.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cd2a145529e81ef22de1ade9f6eab766','a966912b70494ff7ec5379fbffffe2e6','a3d7925fcedbb9a92b698d370be59c62','2023-09-08 00:18:16','2023-10-28 11:50:31','Electronics','Needs','Customer or Market Needs','Sustainable materials',36,'Sustainable materials are those that have been sourced and manufactured in a way that minimizes environmental impact, promotes social responsibility, and provides economic benefits to communities. These materials are typically renewable, recyclable, or biodegradable, and they ensure the longevity of our natural resources. Sustainable materials can include plant-based options like bamboo, organic cotton, and linen, as well as recycled materials such as plastic bottles or reclaimed wood. Using sustainable materials in various industries is an important step toward a more sustainable future, as it reduces waste, conserves energy, and supports a circular economy. As consumers, we can make a difference by choosing products made from sustainable materials and encouraging companies to prioritize sustainability in their sourcing and manufacturing practices.','{\"pat_doc\": 67.0, \"pub_alt\": 1001.0, \"pub_doc\": 2047.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 358.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 241721679.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_doc\": 189.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 19728859.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cdb94d547b15037e2af161cd98144afb','093421fa544b6541b1aa9445b0324876','c69cae5bf0730201ed4820a70e56cfc2','2023-09-08 09:08:02','2023-10-28 13:26:11','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Gastrointestinal Cancer',48,'Gastrointestinal cancer refers to malignant conditions of the gastrointestinal tract and accessory organs of digestion, including the esophagus, stomach, biliary system, pancreas, small intestine, large intestine, rectum and anus. The symptoms relate to the organ affected and can include obstruction, abnormal bleeding or other associated problems. The diagnosis often requires endoscopy, followed by biopsy of suspicious tissue. The treatment depends on the location of the tumor, as well as the type of cancer cell and whether it has invaded other tissues or spread elsewhere. These factors also determine the prognosis. Overall, the GI tract and the accessory organs of digestion are responsible for more cancers and more deaths from cancer than any other system in the body. There is significant geographic variation in the rates of different gastrointestinal cancers.','{\"pat_doc\": 245.0, \"pub_alt\": 1676.0, \"pub_doc\": 4230.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 242.0, \"clinic_alt\": 412.0, \"clinic_doc\": 355.0, \"grant_fund\": 60591536.0, \"pat_granted\": 47.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.9, \"pub_doc\": 83.2, \"clinic_doc\": 43.7, \"grant_fund\": -5165841.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cdbe5114910aa29a9dd3d949174379ef','e7461a8ad3be85a4a9927a05f09da738','74dfdb3be3d296db4e284e57c8999ab7','2023-09-08 02:05:14','2023-10-28 23:11:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Primary Cell Culture',12,'Primary cell culture is the ex vivo culture of cells freshly obtained from a multicellular organism, as opposed to the culture of immortalized cell lines. In general, primary cell cultures are considered more representative of in vivo tissues than cell lines, and this is recognized legally in some countries such as the UK. However, primary cells require adequate substrate and nutrient conditions to thrive and after a certain number of divisions they acquire a senescent phenotype, leading to irreversible cell cycle arrest. The generation of cell lines stems from these two reasons. Primary cells can become immortalized either spontaneously or by genetic modification, at which point they become cell lines which can be subcultured indefinitely. Because of their requirements for viability, primary cell cultures did not become widespread until the 2000s.','{\"pat_doc\": 57.0, \"pub_alt\": 67.0, \"pub_doc\": 152.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 19.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 6718283.0, \"pat_granted\": 18.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 9.5, \"pub_doc\": -8.7, \"clinic_doc\": 2.5, \"grant_fund\": -4026979.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cdd4d9be680b5b42e74a41a191fc21b6','bcec320c1d366012496fdc05b1162aad','3e072ff4f027f97184b7ecfb791122b7','2023-09-05 22:06:34','2023-10-28 17:26:11','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Bacteriophages',36,'A bacteriophage, also known informally as a phage, is a duplodnaviria virus that infects and replicates within bacteria and archaea. The term was derived from \"bacteria\" and the Greek Ï†Î±Î³Îµá¿–Î½, meaning \"to devour\". Bacteriophages are composed of proteins that encapsulate a DNA or RNA genome, and may have structures that are either simple or elaborate. Their genomes may encode as few as four genes and as many as hundreds of genes. Phages replicate within the bacterium following the injection of their genome into its cytoplasm. Bacteriophages are among the most common and diverse entities in the biosphere. Bacteriophages are ubiquitous viruses, found wherever bacteria exist. It is estimated there are more than 10Â³Â¹ bacteriophages on the planet, more than every other organism on Earth, including bacteria, combined.','{\"pat_doc\": 534.0, \"pub_alt\": 722.0, \"pub_doc\": 3997.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 338.0, \"clinic_alt\": 247.0, \"clinic_doc\": 28.0, \"grant_fund\": 106706934.0, \"pat_granted\": 92.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.4, \"pub_doc\": 69.6, \"clinic_doc\": 4.7, \"grant_fund\": -11975247.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ce1202f4f8f0220bcda06df8d0064870','f1d991da1c3d1f34a90384e385b676a5','4101f5b584ffd5355154925e914aabcc','2023-09-08 00:58:18','2023-10-29 00:46:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Mass Cytometry',36,'Mass cytometry is a mass spectrometry technique based on inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry and time of flight mass spectrometry used for the determination of the properties of cells. In this approach, antibodies are conjugated with isotopically pure elements, and these antibodies are used to label cellular proteins. Cells are nebulized and sent through an argon plasma, which ionizes the metal-conjugated antibodies. The metal signals are then analyzed by a time-of-flight mass spectrometer. The approach overcomes limitations of spectral overlap in flow cytometry by utilizing discrete isotopes as a reporter system instead of traditional fluorophores which have broad emission spectra.','{\"pat_doc\": 101.0, \"pub_alt\": 6207.0, \"pub_doc\": 1750.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 303.0, \"clinic_alt\": 53.0, \"clinic_doc\": 59.0, \"grant_fund\": 165043237.0, \"pat_granted\": 12.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.1, \"pub_doc\": 21.7, \"clinic_doc\": 15.1, \"grant_fund\": -21158977.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ce21d3b2e820df6fab256902a5378b03','8c579df990726481d707857fe85bab54','f0c1b8c703203eb82e320beebf070142','2023-09-04 19:39:15','2023-10-28 18:11:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','CRISPR',24,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 6104.0, \"pub_alt\": 1837.0, \"pub_doc\": 20652.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2706.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 75.0, \"grant_fund\": 1317672915.0, \"pat_granted\": 1473.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 422.3, \"pub_doc\": 715.2, \"clinic_doc\": 17.3, \"grant_fund\": -192193900.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ce30293751a432270ab63d58501b137f','8c13cdcd2f46fbd04ad49b8164252967','b347f7200b8aff24464a347c263147e9','2023-09-08 09:25:33','2023-10-28 21:06:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Filtration',12,'Filtration is a physical separation process that separates solid matter and fluid from a mixture using a filter medium that has a complex structure through which only the fluid can pass. Solid particles that cannot pass through the filter medium are described as oversize and the fluid that passes through is called the filtrate. Oversize particles may form a filter cake on top of the filter and may also block the filter lattice, preventing the fluid phase from crossing the filter, known as blinding. The size of the largest particles that can successfully pass through a filter is called the effective pore size of that filter. The separation of solid and fluid is imperfect; solids will be contaminated with some fluid and filtrate will contain fine particles. Filtration occurs both in nature and in engineered systems; there are biological, geological, and industrial forms.','{\"pat_doc\": 54641.0, \"pub_alt\": 14660.0, \"pub_doc\": 42138.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 663.0, \"clinic_alt\": 592.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1873.0, \"grant_fund\": 261795069.0, \"pat_granted\": 37443.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 616.9, \"pub_doc\": 2964.5, \"clinic_doc\": 373.4, \"grant_fund\": -100190796.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ce5ba892fd57319206f3428f2acfbcad','53dc292182499fa33b7eec431b8b30ff','a0ec7ffe04c046d0f8469b5de966ddfa','2023-09-04 18:55:37','2023-10-29 06:31:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Flow Cytometry',12,'Flow cytometry is a technique used to detect and measure physical and chemical characteristics of a population of cells or particles. In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument. The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components. Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths. Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer. Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials. Uses for flow cytometry include: â€¢ Cell counting â€¢ Cell sorting â€¢ Determining cell characteristics and function â€¢ Detecting microorganisms â€¢ Biomarker detection â€¢ Protein engineering detection â€¢ Diagnosis of health disorders such as blood cancers â€¢ Measuring genome size.','{\"pat_doc\": 564.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 15615.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 380.0, \"clinic_alt\": 590.0, \"clinic_doc\": 555.0, \"grant_fund\": 116938725.0, \"pat_granted\": 170.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.1, \"pub_doc\": -433.8, \"clinic_doc\": 137.2, \"grant_fund\": -49967547.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ce65c41af47d31dd0317937943daf742','d26eb2bd1f18468fd4cd16acbcfe71a0','0de5062bb6f653f85fa36c9feb30d5e1','2023-09-08 01:30:22','2023-10-29 00:11:22','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Robotic Process Automation',24,'Robotic process automation is a form of business process automation that is based on software robots or artificial intelligence agents. It is sometimes referred to as software robotics. In traditional workflow automation tools, a software developer produces a list of actions to automate a task and interface to the back end system using internal application programming interfaces or dedicated scripting language. In contrast, RPA systems develop the action list by watching the user perform that task in the applications graphical user interface, and then perform the automation by repeating those tasks directly in the GUI. This can lower the barrier to the use of automation in products that might not otherwise feature APIs for this purpose. RPA tools have strong technical similarities to graphical user interface testing tools. These tools also automate interactions with the GUI, and often do so by repeating a set of demonstration actions performed by a user.','{\"pat_doc\": 821.0, \"pub_alt\": 119.0, \"pub_doc\": 686.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 13.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2070435.0, \"pat_granted\": 180.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 111.3, \"pub_doc\": 68.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -911088.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ce9a7d1bce4796e1f1545a4b10f9e963','c2aa8e8ff53300b96a4cd521696cbdbb','ba652e04894d8ad7c796a0f64375c740','2023-09-08 01:49:52','2023-10-28 23:56:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Suspension Culture',24,'A cell suspension or suspension culture is a type of cell culture in which single cells or small aggregates of cells are allowed to function and multiply in an agitated growth medium, thus forming a suspension. Suspension culture is one of the two classical types of cell culture, the other being adherent culture. The history of suspension cell culture closely aligns with the history of cell culture overall, but differs in maintenance methods and commercial applications. The cells themselves can either be derived from homogenized tissue or from heterogenous cell solutions. Suspension cell culture is commonly used to culture nonadhesive cell lines like hematopoietic cells, plant cells, and insect cells. While some cell lines are cultured in suspension, the majority of commercially available mammalian cell lines are adherent. Suspension cell cultures must be agitated to maintain cells in suspension, and may require specialized equipment and flasks.','{\"pat_doc\": 615.0, \"pub_alt\": 278.0, \"pub_doc\": 593.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 17.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4112285.0, \"pat_granted\": 216.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.9, \"pub_doc\": -11.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -1405329.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ceaa22363a7452d4af9f56f42ad12a5c','2b6a132222106ddec0310c5473271c19','d16e559190b993e5f50fdc62d46eec9a','2023-09-08 09:58:57','2023-10-28 19:36:09','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Modification',12,'mRNA modification is a process that occurs after transcription but before translation. It refers to the chemical modifications of messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules in order to regulate their stability, localization, and translation efficiency. The most common type of mRNA modification is the addition of a 5â€™ cap, a modified guanine nucleotide, to the 5â€™ end of the mRNA molecule. This cap protects the mRNA from degradation and facilitates its translation. Another important mRNA modification is the addition of a poly(A) tail, a string of adenine nucleotides, to the 3â€™ end of the mRNA molecule. This tail also stabilizes the mRNA and enhances its translation. Other types of mRNA modifications include splicing, editing, and methylation, which can affect the sequence, structure, and function of the mRNA molecule. mRNA modification plays a critical role in gene expression regulation and is essential for cellular processes such as development, differentiation, and adaptation to environmental changes.','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_alt\": 80.0, \"pub_doc\": 132.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 11.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 3383680.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 16.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -6725984.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ced8d7e539eff89a331bbcdddc2e80e3','68a4129044821c3a1d6386321b0e0003','71b92f66f40436e1ab511b3f211c9bd0','2023-09-08 02:35:10','2023-10-28 10:50:30','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Photonic Computing',12,'Optical computing or photonic computing uses light waves produced by lasers or incoherent sources for data processing, data storage or data communication for computing. For decades, photons have shown promise to enable a higher bandwidth than the electrons used in conventional computers. Most research projects focus on replacing current computer components with optical equivalents, resulting in an optical digital computer system processing binary data. This approach appears to offer the best short-term prospects for commercial optical computing, since optical components could be integrated into traditional computers to produce an optical-electronic hybrid. However, optoelectronic devices consume 30% of their energy converting electronic energy into photons and back; this conversion also slows the transmission of messages. All-optical computers eliminate the need for optical-electrical-optical conversions, thus reducing electrical power consumption.','{\"pat_doc\": 20.0, \"pub_alt\": 110.0, \"pub_doc\": 83.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 5.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 10858005.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.5, \"pub_doc\": 21.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2638715.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cef7a19ac34daf4f4c43c370b0ee3548','0aa43655311231d22f19c9a7f97c3577','69904542b990c5c24086b0dfa8c698cf','2023-09-05 22:50:45','2023-10-29 03:05:06','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','High-Throughput Screening',48,'High-throughput screening is a method for scientific experimentation especially used in drug discovery and relevant to the fields of biology, materials science and chemistry. Using robotics, data processing/control software, liquid handling devices, and sensitive detectors, high-throughput screening allows a researcher to quickly conduct millions of chemical, genetic, or pharmacological tests. Through this process one can quickly recognize active compounds, antibodies, or genes that modulate a particular biomolecular pathway. The results of these experiments provide starting points for drug design and for understanding the noninteraction or role of a particular location.','{\"pat_doc\": 1072.0, \"pub_alt\": 1213.0, \"pub_doc\": 5758.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 713.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.0, \"grant_fund\": 734054113.0, \"pat_granted\": 340.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.8, \"pub_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -83628586.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cf15708fc7aed20b191457ee4195c29d','230eda4c55f24cadd07347f1a221f5ca','d9f345c5479253d7d74e62f81762d9a5','2023-09-05 21:57:22','2023-10-28 12:15:33','Electronics','Components','Storage Devices','Spintronics',12,'Spintronics, also known as spin electronics, is the study of the intrinsic spin of the electron and its associated magnetic moment, in addition to its fundamental electronic charge, in solid-state devices. The field of spintronics concerns spin-charge coupling in metallic systems; the analogous effects in insulators fall into the field of multiferroics. Spintronics fundamentally differs from traditional electronics in that, in addition to charge state, electron spins are used as a further degree of freedom, with implications in the efficiency of data storage and transfer. Spintronic systems are most often realised in dilute magnetic semiconductors and Heusler alloys and are of particular interest in the field of quantum computing and neuromorphic computing.','{\"pat_doc\": 51.0, \"pub_alt\": 335.0, \"pub_doc\": 2009.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 122.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 102735199.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.9, \"pub_doc\": 169.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5459749.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cf205c5816af5f628d077a721c818cf7','f82670ab57400d3e832f9efb4a5573a4','2e3f377d891e03c5b7a4ddf257a19dc5','2023-09-08 01:35:27','2023-10-28 15:11:17','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','DNA origami',12,'DNA origami is the nanoscale folding of DNA to create arbitrary two- and three-dimensional shapes at the nanoscale. The specificity of the interactions between complementary base pairs make DNA a useful construction material, through design of its base sequences. DNA is a well-understood material that is suitable for creating scaffolds that hold other molecules in place or to create structures all on its own. DNA origami was the cover story of Nature on March 16, 2006. Since then, DNA origami has progressed past an art form and has found a number of applications from drug delivery systems to uses as circuitry in plasmonic devices; however, most commercial applications remain in a concept or testing phase.','{\"pat_doc\": 28.0, \"pub_alt\": 535.0, \"pub_doc\": 326.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 28.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 17354538.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.1, \"pub_doc\": 26.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1724661.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cf406ff982dbe45257753499aebe5be2','7cdbaeda7c2e92f0a0d7bcfe3cd23472','e2d4dfcdd74fd300c5581dfc34bfe679','2023-09-05 22:19:07','2023-10-28 12:10:33','Electronics','Devices','Next Generation Computers','Brain-computer interfaces',48,'A brainâ€“computer interface, sometimes called a brainâ€“machine interface or smartbrain, is a direct communication pathway between the brains electrical activity and an external device, most commonly a computer or robotic limb. BCIs are often directed at researching, mapping, assisting, augmenting, or repairing human cognitive or sensory-motor functions. They are often conceptualized as a humanâ€“machine interface that skips the intermediary component of the physical movement of body parts, although they also raise the possibility of the erasure of the discreteness of brain and machine. Implementations of BCIs range from non-invasive and partially invasive to invasive, based on how close electrodes get to brain tissue.','{\"pat_doc\": 207.0, \"pub_alt\": 1256.0, \"pub_doc\": 2194.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 130.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 83249216.0, \"pat_granted\": 55.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 20.1, \"pub_doc\": 77.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -3687771.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cf5bb04b9d8e1923831d7f132fd5dc32','860562e383a8d17a8f172fa2f70cc8f9','aeef280b6e10fec919822406e149ebb2','2023-09-08 02:33:55','2023-10-28 14:16:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Lipid regulation',36,'Lipid regulation is the process of maintaining healthy levels of lipids in the body. Lipids are a type of molecule that includes fats, oils, and waxes. They are essential for many functions in the body, including providing energy and helping with the absorption of vitamins. However, too much or too little of certain types of lipids can lead to health problems. For example, high levels of cholesterol can increase the risk of heart disease, while low levels of essential fatty acids can lead to inflammation and other issues. Efficient lipid regulation requires a balanced diet and regular exercise, along with possible medication if needed.','{\"pat_doc\": 12.0, \"pub_alt\": 1137.0, \"pub_doc\": 199.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 25.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 9257835.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": 5.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.4, \"grant_fund\": 1008259.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cf6429e6f99ae551363f2799ab0e95a8','21d871363877cc98d16111d220b3c6ab','aa4364cfb922eeea74c84893f0cb9469','2023-09-08 09:40:12','2023-10-28 20:46:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Surface Plasmon Resonance',48,'Surface plasmon resonance is a phenomenon that occurs where electrons in a thin metal sheet become excited by light that is directed to the sheet with a particular angle of incidence, and then travel parallel to the sheet. Assuming a constant light source wavelength and that the metal sheet is thin, the angle of incidence that triggers SPR is related to the refractive index of the material and even a small change in the refractive index will cause SPR to not be observed. This makes SPR a possible technique for detecting particular substances and SPR biosensors have been developed to detect various important biomarkers.','{\"pat_doc\": 1541.0, \"pub_alt\": 2771.0, \"pub_doc\": 14474.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 443.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 164816339.0, \"pat_granted\": 497.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.7, \"pub_doc\": 132.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.9, \"grant_fund\": -19685515.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cf85b64278e81cf915ae4379070bce9b','01807d836d93ed1511a8b58c90b6d398','3fcb9a9c61a418e177e61e3951321f26','2023-09-08 02:15:42','2023-10-28 22:46:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Controlled-release system',48,'A controlled-release system is a technology used in drug delivery, agriculture and other fields to release active ingredients evenly over a period of time. It involves encapsulating the active ingredient in a matrix that controls its release rate. This can increase the effectiveness of the ingredient and reduce the frequency of application. In drug delivery, it can improve patient compliance, reduce side effects and increase efficacy. In agriculture, it can reduce waste and environmental impact. Controlled-release systems can be designed using a variety of materials, including polymers, liposomes and mesoporous materials. They are an important tool in modern science and technology, with numerous applications in various industries.','{\"pat_doc\": 35.0, \"pub_alt\": 14.0, \"pub_doc\": 76.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1352759.0, \"pat_granted\": 12.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -135275.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('cfa219f90b61c9b93cdb6dcb34f43e9f','bf8b4feb522a72f79560c81cf6dc8720','62899d4dc41a7b9eb6091bb110aca523','2023-09-05 19:55:00','2023-10-29 04:51:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','Tissue Engineering',24,'Tissue engineering is a biomedical engineering discipline that uses a combination of cells, engineering, materials methods, and suitable biochemical and physicochemical factors to restore, maintain, improve, or replace different types of biological tissues. Tissue engineering often involves the use of cells placed on tissue scaffolds in the formation of new viable tissue for a medical purpose but is not limited to applications involving cells and tissue scaffolds. While it was once categorized as a sub-field of biomaterials, having grown in scope and importance it can be considered as a field of its own. While most definitions of tissue engineering cover a broad range of applications, in practice the term is closely associated with applications that repair or replace portions of or whole tissues. Often, the tissues involved require certain mechanical and structural properties for proper functioning.','{\"pat_doc\": 2009.0, \"pub_alt\": 641.0, \"pub_doc\": 13513.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 698.0, \"clinic_alt\": 16.0, \"clinic_doc\": 61.0, \"grant_fund\": 242322849.0, \"pat_granted\": 780.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.9, \"pub_doc\": 306.5, \"clinic_doc\": 10.5, \"grant_fund\": -54494104.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d04b38bc22d3ef11a2273e28912b9c9c','b5180881c0acd170e35e7e2628346b44','6f23015b34810fffb37ea505c3bdbd67','2023-09-05 19:31:51','2023-10-29 05:01:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Culture',48,'Cell culture or tissue culture is the process by which cells are grown under controlled conditions, generally outside of their natural environment. The term \"tissue culture\" was coined by American pathologist Montrose Thomas Burrows. This technique is also called micropropagation. After the cells of interest have been isolated from living tissue, they can subsequently be maintained under carefully controlled conditions. They need to be kept at body temperature in an incubator. These conditions vary for each cell type, but generally consist of a suitable vessel with a substrate or rich medium that supplies the essential nutrients, growth factors, hormones, and gases, and regulates the physio-chemical environment. Most cells require a surface or an artificial substrate to form an adherent culture as a monolayer, whereas others can be grown free floating in a medium as a suspension culture.','{\"pat_doc\": 23119.0, \"pub_alt\": 6747.0, \"pub_doc\": 29583.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4111.0, \"clinic_alt\": 504.0, \"clinic_doc\": 327.0, \"grant_fund\": 1544671350.0, \"pat_granted\": 8758.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 342.7, \"pub_doc\": -154.3, \"clinic_doc\": 41.7, \"grant_fund\": -133904294.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d09ace5f367c5cf9c6e329a06ca427c1','0a08029fe04824e466d5980ec8cdbf8b','a0ec7ffe04c046d0f8469b5de966ddfa','2023-09-04 18:53:14','2023-10-29 06:40:05','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Flow Cytometry',12,'Flow cytometry is a technique used to detect and measure physical and chemical characteristics of a population of cells or particles. In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument. The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components. Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths. Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer. Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials. Uses for flow cytometry include: â€¢ Cell counting â€¢ Cell sorting â€¢ Determining cell characteristics and function â€¢ Detecting microorganisms â€¢ Biomarker detection â€¢ Protein engineering detection â€¢ Diagnosis of health disorders such as blood cancers â€¢ Measuring genome size.','{\"pat_doc\": 564.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 15615.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 380.0, \"clinic_alt\": 590.0, \"clinic_doc\": 555.0, \"grant_fund\": 116938725.0, \"pat_granted\": 170.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.1, \"pub_doc\": -433.8, \"clinic_doc\": 137.2, \"grant_fund\": -49967547.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d0ea1c5e735570d9c932e4c0d93faf9f','5790a7bed485dce7c0fd1fac61020f51','f1911fd26254d1cbfba1808fbf1f3025','2023-09-08 01:53:10','2023-10-28 23:46:12','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Organ-on chip',24,'An organ-on-a-chip is a multi-channel 3-D microfluidic cell culture, integrated circuit that simulates the activities, mechanics and physiological response of an entire organ or an organ system. It constitutes the subject matter of significant biomedical engineering research, more precisely in bio-MEMS. The convergence of labs-on-chips and cell biology has permitted the study of human physiology in an organ-specific context. By acting as a more sophisticated in vitro approximation of complex tissues than standard cell culture, they provide the potential as an alternative to animal models for drug development and toxin testing. Although multiple publications claim to have translated organ functions onto this interface, the development of these microfluidic applications is still in its infancy. Organs-on-chips vary in design and approach between different researchers.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": -0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d10caf41f1e2c2897caed20fc85a8260','8a48608f902f6d6e18861f68c6c16aa1','afe94a7da70247bc6803357002649726','2023-09-08 11:13:41','2023-10-28 18:41:12','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Clinical Decision Support Systems',36,'Clinical decision support systems (CDSS) are computer programs designed to assist healthcare professionals in making clinical decisions by providing information and knowledge at the point of care. CDSS incorporate patient data and evidence-based guidelines to suggest potential diagnoses, recommend laboratory tests and treatment options, calculate medication doses and detect harmful drug interactions. CDSS can improve patient outcomes by enhancing the accuracy of diagnoses, preventing medical errors, and enabling clinicians to make more informed decisions based on relevant clinical evidence. Furthermore, CDSS can help reduce healthcare costs and improve efficiency by reducing unnecessary tests and treatments, and minimizing length of hospital stay. Overall, CDSS provide an important tool for healthcare professionals to provide high-quality patient care.','{\"pat_doc\": 15.0, \"pub_alt\": 543.0, \"pub_doc\": 1101.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 42.0, \"clinic_alt\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 33.0, \"grant_fund\": 23781426.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 46.6, \"clinic_doc\": 6.5, \"grant_fund\": -372976.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d1eb1d71402a90848ea46b5c04afb799','8b12860860c34fa4f49e9fadc6bbab1d','d471ba9d05b4186943ade5d1a2ae30dc','2023-09-04 18:21:24','2023-10-29 07:10:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Mass Spectrometry',24,'Mass Spectrometry is a powerful analytical technique used in chemistry, biochemistry, and other scientific fields to identify molecules based on their mass-to-charge ratio (m/z). The process involves ionizing a sample, then separating the resulting ions based on their mass-to-charge ratio using electromagnetic fields. The ions are then detected and analyzed to determine their individual masses and concentrations. Mass spectrometry is used in many applications, including characterizing the structure of unknown compounds, identifying proteins and peptides, and tracking the movement of isotopes within molecules. It has become a standard tool in many areas of research, including drug discovery, environmental analysis, and forensic science.','{\"pat_doc\": 7976.0, \"pub_alt\": 13857.0, \"pub_doc\": 64182.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2590.0, \"clinic_alt\": 146.0, \"clinic_doc\": 554.0, \"grant_fund\": 1133704828.0, \"pat_granted\": 2610.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 210.2, \"pub_doc\": 879.4, \"clinic_doc\": 100.8, \"grant_fund\": -169513024.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d1f7dc8bbdc8784ab70f9d5cf5c8e4b3','047522bba3b34e3fc4e040441987ea79','f7fd5614f8eb7d0dc72ab27f1dc2ffa2','2023-09-08 01:19:33','2023-10-28 11:30:33','Electronics','Components','Transfer Devices','Optical interconnect',24,'In integrated circuits, optical interconnects refers to any system of transmitting signals from one part of an integrated circuit to another using light. Optical interconnects have been the topic of study due to the high latency and power consumption incurred by conventional metal interconnects in transmitting electrical signals over long distances, such as in interconnects classed as global interconnects. The International Technology Roadmap for Semiconductors has highlighted interconnect scaling as a problem for the semiconductor industry. In electrical interconnects, nonlinear signals are transmitted by copper wires conventionally, and these electrical wires all have resistance and capacitance which severely limits the rise time of signals when the dimension of the wires are scaled down. Optical solution are used to transmit signals through long distances to substitute interconnection between dies within the integrated circuit package.','{\"pat_doc\": 422.0, \"pub_alt\": 238.0, \"pub_doc\": 570.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 34.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 27687121.0, \"pat_granted\": 115.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 24.2, \"pub_doc\": -0.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -665738.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d1f963907fcd75fe2ec5dcd19e762ed9','402437da63ba33a83221799ab29cf95b','d511e8881547550871faef764cbfed18','2023-09-08 02:40:12','2023-10-28 21:56:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Sterilization Technique',24,'Sterilization technique involves the process of eliminating all forms of microorganisms and pathogens from a surface or object. This technique is used in medical facilities or laboratories to avoid the spread of infections or diseases. There are several sterilization methods, such as chemical sterilization, radiation sterilization, and physical sterilization. Chemical sterilization procedures involve the use of gases or liquids to get rid of bacteria or other microorganisms. Radiation sterilization involves the utilization of ionizing radiation to destroy pathogens, whereas physical sterilization involves the use of heat, pressure, or filtration to eliminate bacteria or other microorganisms. These sterilization techniques are essential in maintaining a sterile environment, which is crucial in medical facilities that perform surgeries or other sensitive procedures.','{\"pat_doc\": 33.0, \"pub_alt\": 506.0, \"pub_doc\": 128.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1583809.0, \"pat_granted\": 19.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -5.0, \"pub_doc\": 3.3, \"clinic_doc\": -0.7, \"grant_fund\": 247564.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d205ae9680f12556ad2a482c8dcac849','4efee97660391cd588fa5f748e6f0600','eaf48f12d2f6d964781bc23663490cdb','2023-09-08 10:49:43','2023-10-28 19:01:11','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Image Analysis',24,'Image analysis or imagery analysis is the extraction of meaningful information from images; mainly from digital images by means of digital image processing techniques. Image analysis tasks can be as simple as reading bar coded tags or as sophisticated as identifying a person from their face. Computers are indispensable for the analysis of large amounts of data, for tasks that require complex computation, or for the extraction of quantitative information. On the other hand, the human visual cortex is an excellent image analysis apparatus, especially for extracting higher-level information, and for many applications â€” including medicine, security, and remote sensing â€” human analysts still cannot be replaced by computers. For this reason, many important image analysis tools such as edge detectors and neural networks are inspired by human visual perception models.','{\"pat_doc\": 8049.0, \"pub_alt\": 808.0, \"pub_doc\": 14268.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 794.0, \"clinic_alt\": 18.0, \"clinic_doc\": 279.0, \"grant_fund\": 349780308.0, \"pat_granted\": 2568.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 297.4, \"pub_doc\": 418.9, \"clinic_doc\": 55.6, \"grant_fund\": -41339384.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d2d170a616ec3c8dca2b4244619d4e93','eb2ca5cdbf466432efa3cad3dd594f1a','6725d42f932d0e446e761f0968e0172f','2023-09-08 02:04:06','2023-10-28 23:16:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','Cell Characterization',24,'Cell Characterization is the process of understanding the physical, chemical, and biological properties of a specific type of cell. It involves analyzing various aspects of the cell, such as morphology, size, and structure, as well as its function and behavior. Through this process, scientists can gain a deeper understanding of how cells function, how they interact with other cells, and how they respond to different environments or stimuli. Cell Characterization is an essential tool for researchers and scientists in a variety of fields, including cell biology, genetics, and immunology, as it allows for the development of new treatments and therapies for diseases and the discovery of new biological mechanisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 33.0, \"pub_alt\": 496.0, \"pub_doc\": 281.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 37.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 27150440.0, \"pat_granted\": 7.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 13.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -513209.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d30eaaf823c8e30627a61f3d6cc58752','dd3b10037cd066e53410e9747f800fec','9bd82f68388cbaa629adeec1747d02c9','2023-09-04 19:22:50','2023-10-28 12:55:34','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','5g',36,'5G refers to the fifth generation of mobile networks and is the successor to 4G. It represents a significant improvement in terms of speed, latency, and capacity, enabling faster download and upload speeds, quicker response times, and the ability to connect more devices to the network simultaneously. The new network technology uses higher frequency radio waves and advanced antenna technology to transmit and receive data more efficiently. The increased bandwidth of 5G networks will enhance the capabilities of emerging technologies such as virtual and augmented reality, driverless vehicles, and Internet of Things (IoT) devices. The deployment of 5G networks is currently underway worldwide, and it is expected to have a significant impact on the way we communicate and access information in the years to come.','{\"pat_doc\": 62358.0, \"pub_alt\": 2709.0, \"pub_doc\": 50327.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2321.0, \"clinic_alt\": 61.0, \"clinic_doc\": 829.0, \"grant_fund\": 1761228622.0, \"pat_granted\": 24784.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1603.5, \"pub_doc\": 859.7, \"clinic_doc\": 107.3, \"grant_fund\": -2206973786.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d3366e0cab10c4b4670e74830b485d11','c42efb8fe2ca41dc7fd5d4dbb0848ed6','7e6689dbdfabd5b7cf95a105e9764132','2023-09-08 09:27:09','2023-10-28 21:01:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Gas Chromatography',36,'Gas chromatography is a common type of chromatography used in analytical chemistry for separating and analyzing compounds that can be vaporized without decomposition. Typical uses of GC include testing the purity of a particular substance, or separating the different components of a mixture. In preparative chromatography, GC can be used to prepare pure compounds from a mixture. Gas chromatography is also sometimes known as vapor-phase chromatography, or gasâ€“liquid partition chromatography. These alternative names, as well as their respective abbreviations, are frequently used in scientific literature. Gas chromatography is the process of separating compounds in a mixture by injecting a gaseous or liquid sample into a mobile phase, typically called the carrier gas, and passing the gas through a stationary phase. The mobile phase is usually an inert gas or an unreactive gas such as helium, argon, nitrogen or hydrogen.','{\"pat_doc\": 4221.0, \"pub_alt\": 4917.0, \"pub_doc\": 25905.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 422.0, \"clinic_alt\": 100.0, \"clinic_doc\": 104.0, \"grant_fund\": 70242852.0, \"pat_granted\": 1689.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 67.1, \"pub_doc\": 279.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.9, \"grant_fund\": -2716027.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d4061962533c28ed1dbb6697ef789b33','666869b3162af8fad5a5b7d07b2312c9','f268e5ab79c5a1d38ab08daccf7ee951','2023-09-08 01:48:42','2023-10-28 11:10:32','Electronics','Components','Processing Devices','Neuromorphic Hardware',12,'Neuromorphic hardware is a type of computer hardware that is inspired by the workings of the human brain. Unlike traditional hardware that uses a Von Neumann architecture where the processing and memory are separate, neuromorphic hardware combines both processing and memory in a single unit. This results in a more efficient way of computing, where information is processed in parallel, similar to how neurons work in the brain. Neuromorphic hardware is often used in applications that require low power consumption and real-time processing, such as robotics and autonomous vehicles. The technology has the potential to create highly advanced and intelligent systems, but there are still challenges to overcome, such as developing effective programming models and scaling up the hardware for larger applications. Nonetheless, neuromorphic hardware is an exciting and promising area of research that has the potential to revolutionize computing as we know it.','{\"pat_doc\": 26.0, \"pub_alt\": 218.0, \"pub_doc\": 296.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 16.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 15534451.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.9, \"pub_doc\": 33.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -50956752.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d49214819d764a132674ac3127dc1d82','238b58270bac60d5acf4e26cc123d5f1','61eadfbcdffdebf7c01d9aa685edd597','2023-09-08 01:05:56','2023-10-28 11:35:31','Electronics','Components','Processing Devices','RISC-V',48,'RISC-V is an open standard instruction set architecture based on established reduced instruction set computer principles. Unlike most other ISA designs, RISC-V is provided under royalty-free open-source licenses. A number of companies are offering or have announced RISC-V hardware; open source operating systems with RISC-V support are available, and the instruction set is supported in several popular software toolchains. As a RISC architecture, the RISC-V ISA is a loadâ€“store architecture. Its floating-point instructions use IEEE 754 floating-point. Notable features of the RISC-V ISA include: instruction bit field locations chosen to simplify the use of multiplexers in a CPU, a design that is architecturally neutral, and a fixed location for the sign bit of immediate values to speed up sign extension. The instruction set is designed for a wide range of uses.','{\"pat_doc\": 536.0, \"pub_alt\": 247.0, \"pub_doc\": 1869.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 135.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 142408826.0, \"pat_granted\": 134.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 62.4, \"pub_doc\": 105.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 15384814.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d4abca44b64dcd1f6e4fe227db40964b','917192d39f4afc517e0a5df9df580afd','e5dc1ab9b95fd144580ba449bdb1f286','2023-09-05 20:46:53','2023-10-29 04:25:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','CRISPR-Cas9',48,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 954.0, \"pub_alt\": 3609.0, \"pub_doc\": 7033.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1218.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 22.0, \"grant_fund\": 503974497.0, \"pat_granted\": 261.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.6, \"pub_doc\": 115.9, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -29971557.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d5430cdf5aa1966c60e3eb47ccab9316','a50b8ea9f2c997ee8ae5e1323c17ab97','8ff2c0d27eb80a1a00a05bdcbea821c2','2023-09-08 02:07:31','2023-10-28 14:46:14','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Achondroplasia',12,'Achondroplasia is a genetic disorder with an autosomal dominant pattern of inheritance whose primary feature is dwarfism. In those with the condition, the arms and legs are short, while the torso is typically of normal length. Those affected have an average adult height of 131 centimetres for males and 123 centimetres for females. Other features can include an enlarged head and prominent forehead. Complications can include sleep apnea or recurrent ear infections. Achondroplasia includes short-limb skeletal dysplasia with severe combined immunodeficiency. Achondroplasia is caused by a mutation in the fibroblast growth factor receptor 3 gene that results in its protein being overactive. Achondroplasia results in impaired endochondral bone growth. The disorder has an autosomal dominant mode of inheritance, meaning only one mutated copy of the gene is required for the condition to occur.','{\"pat_doc\": 27.0, \"pub_alt\": 68.0, \"pub_doc\": 161.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 125.0, \"clinic_doc\": 37.0, \"grant_fund\": 704643.0, \"pat_granted\": 7.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.9, \"pub_doc\": 10.3, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": -1057396.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d628d5968b6d7d767a0c6da0e7cea73e','c66db8e5795eca3126bf573522e8cf4e','e77dece162a0133e50d5b2357c40719f','2023-09-05 22:56:00','2023-10-29 02:51:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','RNA interference',12,'RNA interference is a biological process in which RNA molecules are involved in sequence-specific suppression of gene expression by double-stranded RNA, through translational or transcriptional repression. Historically, RNAi was known by other names, including co-suppression, post-transcriptional gene silencing, and quelling. The detailed study of each of these seemingly different processes elucidated that the identity of these phenomena were all actually RNAi. Andrew Fire and Craig C. Mello shared the 2006 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their work on RNAi in the nematode worm Caenorhabditis elegans, which they published in 1998. Since the discovery of RNAi and its regulatory potentials, it has become evident that RNAi has immense potential in suppression of desired genes. RNAi is now known as precise, efficient, stable and better than antisense therapy for gene suppression.','{\"pat_doc\": 362.0, \"pub_alt\": 991.0, \"pub_doc\": 1684.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 53.0, \"clinic_alt\": 18.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 11697587.0, \"pat_granted\": 103.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.6, \"pub_doc\": -43.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": -14470471.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d6312fc5b94320d6671668b53f606b48','c24a789d6d92253253ff9f90dc646a7a','774a346d62790e44d654b1f21ecba973','2023-09-07 23:48:38','2023-10-29 02:26:21','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Single-Cell Analysis',48,'In the field of cellular biology, single-cell analysis is the study of genomics, transcriptomics, proteomics, metabolomics and cellâ€“cell interactions at the single cell level. The concept of single-cell analysis originated in the 1970s. Before the discovery of heterogeneity, single-cell analysis mainly referred to the analysis or manipulation of an individual cell in a bulk population of cells at a particular condition using optical or electronic microscope. To date, due to the heterogeneity seen in both eukaryotic and prokaryotic cell populations, analyzing a single cell makes it possible to discover mechanisms not seen when studying a bulk population of cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 146.0, \"pub_alt\": 920.0, \"pub_doc\": 2433.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 423.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 166016350.0, \"pat_granted\": 16.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.4, \"pub_doc\": 102.1, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": -19310396.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d71a06cf253f54972d755b7d19a7e299','238b58270bac60d5acf4e26cc123d5f1','61eadfbcdffdebf7c01d9aa685edd597','2023-09-08 01:05:56','2023-10-28 11:35:31','Electronics','Components','Processing Devices','RISC-V',24,'RISC-V is an open standard instruction set architecture based on established reduced instruction set computer principles. Unlike most other ISA designs, RISC-V is provided under royalty-free open-source licenses. A number of companies are offering or have announced RISC-V hardware; open source operating systems with RISC-V support are available, and the instruction set is supported in several popular software toolchains. As a RISC architecture, the RISC-V ISA is a loadâ€“store architecture. Its floating-point instructions use IEEE 754 floating-point. Notable features of the RISC-V ISA include: instruction bit field locations chosen to simplify the use of multiplexers in a CPU, a design that is architecturally neutral, and a fixed location for the sign bit of immediate values to speed up sign extension. The instruction set is designed for a wide range of uses.','{\"pat_doc\": 407.0, \"pub_alt\": 247.0, \"pub_doc\": 1154.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 72.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 104063906.0, \"pat_granted\": 107.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 62.4, \"pub_doc\": 105.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 15384814.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d73832e29c902c1c043df36ea86a3232','7286b6dd5e6f51fb279c0a6a82e528d2','4cfacc6752b10fbede9acf0bca84032d','2023-09-08 02:52:18','2023-10-28 21:21:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Line Culture',12,'Cell line culture refers to the process of growing and propagating cells in vitro, outside the organism from which they were derived. The cells are typically obtained from tissues or organs and are cultured in a laboratory using specialized techniques and growth media. Cell line cultures are used extensively in research, drug development, and biomedical applications to study cell behavior, cell function, and disease processes, among other things. They are an important tool for understanding the mechanisms of diseases and for developing new drugs and therapies. In addition, they offer a reliable and reproducible model system that is easily manipulated, making them an attractive option for a wide range of applications. Overall, cell line culture has revolutionized scientific research and is a critical tool in advancing medical knowledge and treatments.','{\"pat_doc\": 7.0, \"pub_alt\": 10.0, \"pub_doc\": 40.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 5.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -149953.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d7c1cc6a97b354af15f4a6ccaa93601d','90f1f351860541863718a68f1e2fe5b6','7a49c80d1b80fc15aa79d84c9b4afdbb','2023-09-05 22:29:10','2023-10-28 17:21:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Natural killer cells',48,'Natural killer cells, also known as NK cells or large granular lymphocytes, are a type of cytotoxic lymphocyte critical to the innate immune system that belong to the rapidly expanding family of known innate lymphoid cells and represent 5â€“20% of all circulating lymphocytes in humans. The role of NK cells is analogous to that of cytotoxic T cells in the vertebrate adaptive immune response. NK cells provide rapid responses to virus-infected cell and other intracellular pathogens acting at around 3 days after infection, and respond to tumor formation. Typically, immune cells detect the antigen presented on major histocompatibility complex on infected cell surfaces, triggering cytokine release, causing the death of the infected cell by lysis or apoptosis. NK cells are unique, however, as they have the ability to recognize and kill stressed cells in the absence of antibodies and MHC, allowing for a much faster immune reaction.','{\"pat_doc\": 1576.0, \"pub_alt\": 3387.0, \"pub_doc\": 4574.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 210.0, \"clinic_alt\": 200.0, \"clinic_doc\": 230.0, \"grant_fund\": 63788720.0, \"pat_granted\": 257.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 32.0, \"pub_doc\": 58.8, \"clinic_doc\": 29.4, \"grant_fund\": -4654238.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d804837a0f427003e21a7574403ff7c9','97a64c193e09e440bbb1c8b928126797','4893d9f6d48ce8d1001500525173bb9e','2023-09-07 23:55:39','2023-10-29 02:21:16','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','Lipid Nanoparticles',24,'Lipid nanoparticles are nanoparticles composed of lipids. They are a novel pharmaceutical drug delivery system, and a novel pharmaceutical formulation. LNPs as a drug delivery vehicle were first approved in 2018 for the siRNA drug Onpattro. LNPs became more widely known in late 2020, as some COVID-19 vaccines that use RNA vaccine technology coat the fragile mRNA strands with PEGylated lipid nanoparticles as their delivery vehicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 1346.0, \"pub_alt\": 16312.0, \"pub_doc\": 2349.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 145.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1578.0, \"clinic_doc\": 15.0, \"grant_fund\": 75329244.0, \"pat_granted\": 143.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 197.5, \"pub_doc\": 208.3, \"clinic_doc\": 3.7, \"grant_fund\": 10362532.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d854dfd2a15a1c9f6406807fa0c4ffa4','40a0355ede62ff4272058fe5b25b12bf','eefb2660a8535eb1d304c9a60295324f','2023-09-05 21:19:43','2023-10-28 17:46:11','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Liposomes',12,'A liposome is a small artificial vesicle, spherical in shape, having at least one lipid bilayer. Due to their hydrophobicity and/or hydrophilicity, biocompatibility, particle size and many other properties, liposomes can be used as drug delivery vehicles for administration of pharmaceutical drugs and nutrients, such as lipid nanoparticles in mRNA vaccines, and DNA vaccines. Liposomes can be prepared by disrupting biological membranes. Liposomes are most often composed of phospholipids, especially phosphatidylcholine, and cholesterol, but may also include other lipids, such as those found in egg and phosphatidylethanolamine, as long as they are compatible with lipid bilayer structure. A liposome design may employ surface ligands for attaching to unhealthy tissue. The major types of liposomes are the multilamellar vesicle, the small unilamellar liposome vesicle, the large unilamellar vesicle, and the cochleate vesicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 778.0, \"pub_alt\": 501.0, \"pub_doc\": 3144.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 74.0, \"clinic_alt\": 108.0, \"clinic_doc\": 38.0, \"grant_fund\": 24093602.0, \"pat_granted\": 208.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 11.3, \"pub_doc\": 166.2, \"clinic_doc\": 8.1, \"grant_fund\": -13776868.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d8935dd50aa15a8d0f0504b188fed68b','d86696ef8204e2fe630e53d5acb96743','0df45be154a854c136cea54f3239586e','2023-09-08 01:15:35','2023-10-28 15:31:15','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Hypoparathyroidism',12,'Hypoparathyroidism is decreased function of the parathyroid glands with underproduction of parathyroid hormone. This can lead to low levels of calcium in the blood, often causing cramping and twitching of muscles or tetany, and several other symptoms. It is a very rare disease. The condition can be inherited, but it is also encountered after thyroid or parathyroid gland surgery, and it can be caused by immune system-related damage as well as a number of rarer causes. The diagnosis is made with blood tests, and other investigations such as genetic testing depending on the results. The primary treatment of hypoparathyroidism is calcium and vitamin D supplementation. Calcium replacement or vitamin D can ameliorate the symptoms but can increase the risk of kidney stones and chronic kidney disease. Additionally, medications such as recombinant human parathyroid hormone or teriparatide may be given by injection to replace the missing hormone.','{\"pat_doc\": 39.0, \"pub_alt\": 106.0, \"pub_doc\": 572.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 60.0, \"clinic_doc\": 71.0, \"grant_fund\": 1461746.0, \"pat_granted\": 10.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.5, \"pub_doc\": 2.7, \"clinic_doc\": 13.5, \"grant_fund\": -516093.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d8b6c18502bbb631927f76b4e8538c62','593e0b5980cd1f5c381a759416640c82','fac8fdaee075a0078ef0f1af1e190a56','2023-09-08 02:54:38','2023-10-28 10:40:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Neuromorphic Photonics',12,'Neuromorphic photonics is an area of research that seeks to combine the principles of neuroscience and photonics, a field of study that deals with light and its properties. Scientists working in the field aim to create artificial systems that can process information in a way that mimics the human brain, using light instead of electrical signals. By doing this, they hope to create more efficient and powerful computing systems that can tackle complex tasks such as image recognition and natural language processing with ease. Neuromorphic photonics is still in the early stages of development, but it has the potential to revolutionize the field of artificial intelligence and lead to a new generation of smart machines.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 6.0, \"pub_doc\": 26.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -51400.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d8e979c4bc34cb48a0a90a0d3a521310','e1e875f09f9ac3cb516d1a52affa7c20','9ca5a3bb1439526aa869b8ae1a850da8','2024-01-18 11:38:52','2024-01-18 11:38:52','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Chromatography Detector',36,'In chemical analysis, chromatography is a laboratory technique for the separation of a mixture into its components. The mixture is dissolved in a fluid solvent (gas or liquid) called the mobile phase, which carries it through a system (a column, a capillary tube, a plate, or a sheet) on which a material called the stationary phase is fixed.','{\"pat_doc\": 65.0, \"pub_alt\": 2.0, \"pub_doc\": 9.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 430882.0, \"pat_granted\": 37.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": -1.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 43088.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d8f9837882108fb7692d910191509aef','e44792deacd6cf8232ea590a59b65829','ebccb11a63ab2a40e9dc38470854a837','2023-09-05 18:41:05','2023-10-29 05:46:09','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Differentiation',24,'Mechanisms of Development is a peer-reviewed scientific journal covering all aspects of developmental biology. It is the official journal of the International Society of Developmental Biologists and is published by Elsevier. The journal was established in 1972 as Cell Differentiation and was renamed Cell Differentiation and Development in 1988. It acquired its current name in December 1990. The editor-in-chief is D. Wilkinson. A separate section of the journal, Gene Expression Patterns, covers research on cloning and gene expression. In 2020 the journal became Cells & Development with the subtitle: Cell and Developmental Biology and their Quantitative Approaches.','{\"pat_doc\": 815.0, \"pub_alt\": 1940.0, \"pub_doc\": 8145.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 797.0, \"clinic_alt\": 437.0, \"clinic_doc\": 113.0, \"grant_fund\": 288834647.0, \"pat_granted\": 254.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.6, \"pub_doc\": 33.4, \"clinic_doc\": 21.2, \"grant_fund\": -58438151.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d8fd39661f36dd7c09d4091166b16ee7','cef1c501111b2b4c4a7d99d59f4c45cc','61697279f5d40a0cf2ea206c3315fe94','2023-09-08 00:20:47','2023-10-28 16:31:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Chimeric antigen receptor T cells',24,'Chimeric antigen receptor (CAR) T cells, also known as CAR-T cells, are modified immune cells that are trained to seek and destroy cancer cells. CAR-T cells are created by extracting T cells, a type of white blood cell, from a patients blood and genetically engineering them to produce a special protein called a chimeric antigen receptor. This receptor allows the CAR-T cells to recognize and attack cancer cells that express specific markers on their surface. Once re-infused into the patients bloodstream, the CAR-T cells multiply and aggressively seek out and destroy cancer cells. CAR-T cell therapy has shown promising results in treating certain blood cancers, including leukemia and lymphoma, and is being studied for use in other types of cancer.','{\"pat_doc\": 191.0, \"pub_alt\": 341.0, \"pub_doc\": 455.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 16.0, \"clinic_alt\": 32.0, \"clinic_doc\": 120.0, \"grant_fund\": 10373679.0, \"pat_granted\": 38.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -18.9, \"pub_doc\": 3.4, \"clinic_doc\": 24.6, \"grant_fund\": -2849426.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d95ea89221e139b45a15f7db8910420d','402437da63ba33a83221799ab29cf95b','d511e8881547550871faef764cbfed18','2023-09-08 02:40:12','2023-10-28 21:56:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Sterilization Technique',12,'Sterilization technique involves the process of eliminating all forms of microorganisms and pathogens from a surface or object. This technique is used in medical facilities or laboratories to avoid the spread of infections or diseases. There are several sterilization methods, such as chemical sterilization, radiation sterilization, and physical sterilization. Chemical sterilization procedures involve the use of gases or liquids to get rid of bacteria or other microorganisms. Radiation sterilization involves the utilization of ionizing radiation to destroy pathogens, whereas physical sterilization involves the use of heat, pressure, or filtration to eliminate bacteria or other microorganisms. These sterilization techniques are essential in maintaining a sterile environment, which is crucial in medical facilities that perform surgeries or other sensitive procedures.','{\"pat_doc\": 14.0, \"pub_alt\": 7.0, \"pub_doc\": 61.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1493212.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -5.0, \"pub_doc\": 3.3, \"clinic_doc\": -0.7, \"grant_fund\": 247564.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d995cbf112848d39341e6271180769ee','7c86b2353e10d37f742b8e8282b894cd','87aeff98505d298c3f2a7150e8c8ae7d','2023-09-05 21:14:26','2023-10-29 04:11:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Mxene',12,'In materials science, MXenes are a class of two-dimensional inorganic compounds, that consist of atomically thin layers of transition metal carbides, nitrides, or carbonitrides. MXenes accept a variety of hydrophilic terminations. MXenes were first reported in 2012.','{\"pat_doc\": 1491.0, \"pub_alt\": 213.0, \"pub_doc\": 5036.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 41.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 22824841.0, \"pat_granted\": 492.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 348.8, \"pub_doc\": 1206.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 246192.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('d9f043adc2b906f0981e50c8789f02dc','b25c61978fbea0483d82d3d77115840d','13bed64c970494074ea74f12ff611354','2023-09-08 01:04:15','2023-10-28 15:46:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','PROTAC',24,'A proteolysis targeting chimera is a heterobifunctional molecule composed of two active domains and a linker, capable of removing specific unwanted proteins. Rather than acting as a conventional enzyme inhibitor, a PROTAC works by inducing selective intracellular proteolysis. PROTACs consist of two covalently linked protein-binding molecules: one capable of engaging an E3 ubiquitin ligase, and another that binds to a target protein meant for degradation. Recruitment of the E3 ligase to the target protein results in ubiquitination and subsequent degradation of the target protein via the proteasome. Because PROTACs need only to bind their targets with high selectivity, there are currently many efforts to retool previously ineffective inhibitor molecules as PROTACs for next-generation drugs.','{\"pat_doc\": 342.0, \"pub_alt\": 310.0, \"pub_doc\": 1298.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 146.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 44661810.0, \"pat_granted\": 49.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 50.7, \"pub_doc\": 127.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.5, \"grant_fund\": -9266726.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('da45563d0b843095a5e78b257747c394','30ab92573d44ab7bfab530de0c6c2f3b','834e427876f8944f329691ead9f0d4a1','2023-09-04 19:50:57','2023-10-28 18:06:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Coronary artery diseases',48,'Coronary artery diseases are a group of conditions that affect the blood vessels that supply the heart muscle with oxygen and nutrients. These diseases occur when there is a buildup of plaque, or fatty deposits, in the coronary arteries, which can narrow or block these vessels altogether. This can result in reduced blood flow to the heart, leading to chest pain (angina), shortness of breath, and even heart attacks. Risk factors for coronary artery disease include high blood pressure, high cholesterol, smoking, obesity, and an unhealthy diet. Treatment options for coronary artery disease include lifestyle changes such as exercise and diet modifications, medications, and in severe cases, surgery.','{\"pat_doc\": 37.0, \"pub_alt\": 339.0, \"pub_doc\": 829.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 18.0, \"clinic_alt\": 187.0, \"clinic_doc\": 70.0, \"grant_fund\": 4052136.0, \"pat_granted\": 12.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.7, \"pub_doc\": -4.9, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 134481.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('da5d1774de44e4ea5fe991a4e702e026','8c579df990726481d707857fe85bab54','f0c1b8c703203eb82e320beebf070142','2023-09-04 19:39:15','2023-10-28 18:11:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','CRISPR',12,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 3230.0, \"pub_alt\": 1837.0, \"pub_doc\": 10212.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1081.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 63.0, \"grant_fund\": 468979245.0, \"pat_granted\": 830.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 422.3, \"pub_doc\": 715.2, \"clinic_doc\": 17.3, \"grant_fund\": -192193900.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('daea0d1e94c00a230e2b91762175620c','a822340ed295802f1550f5d13064ed80','26d358ca64d0c56aa9745ea1401e4d59','2023-09-05 22:53:22','2023-10-28 12:05:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Holography',36,'Holography is a technique that uses light to create three-dimensional images referred to as holograms. It was first developed in the mid-20th century and has since found numerous applications in fields such as art, security, and medicine. A hologram is created by splitting a laser beam into two and directing one toward an object while the other heads straight onto a photographic plate or film. When the two beams meet, an interference pattern is formed that captures the objects unique features. This pattern can then be viewed, illuminating a hologram of the object that appears lifelike, with depth and dimension. Holography plays a significant role in virtual reality, data storage, and scientific research, among others.','{\"pat_doc\": 655.0, \"pub_alt\": 1635.0, \"pub_doc\": 4565.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 310.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 150124042.0, \"pat_granted\": 253.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -18.4, \"pub_doc\": 93.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": 8559104.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('db4ad6046d6169bc94731fe91f75c9cf','41d7ff0d462e6a3d557069a37ea17023','9c4ba206250041cf1644bb291a643634','2023-09-05 18:58:16','2023-10-29 05:25:05','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Next-Generation Sequencing',36,'Massive parallel sequencing or massively parallel sequencing is any of several high-throughput approaches to DNA sequencing using the concept of massively parallel processing; it is also called next-generation sequencing or second-generation sequencing. Some of these technologies emerged between 1993 and 1998 and have been commercially available since 2005. These technologies use miniaturized and parallelized platforms for sequencing of 1 million to 43 billion short reads per instrument run. Many NGS platforms differ in engineering configurations and sequencing chemistry. They share the technical paradigm of massive parallel sequencing via spatially separated, clonally amplified DNA templates or single DNA molecules in a flow cell. This design is very different from that of Sanger sequencingâ€”also known as capillary sequencing or first-generation sequencingâ€”which is based on electrophoretic separation of chain-termination products produced in individual sequencing reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 426.0, \"pub_alt\": 5565.0, \"pub_doc\": 20329.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 763.0, \"clinic_alt\": 58.0, \"clinic_doc\": 394.0, \"grant_fund\": 239240246.0, \"pat_granted\": 101.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.9, \"pub_doc\": 170.9, \"clinic_doc\": 72.6, \"grant_fund\": -38192044.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('db4c57ce8717f04d43d92f3013ed5f15','e1c03cd2dbe1db8089d68f8b8c8054b0','e21059dfa6307a406da37caf3abb3281','2023-09-08 09:10:54','2023-10-28 13:16:11','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Urothelial cancer',48,'Urothelial cancer is a type of cancer that develops in the urothelial cells, which line the urinary tract. It is also known as transitional cell carcinoma. This type of cancer can develop in the bladder, ureters, or renal pelvis. The majority of urothelial cancers are found in the bladder, and symptoms may include blood in the urine, painful urination, and frequent urination. Urothelial cancer can be treated with surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy, and the prognosis can vary depending on the stage of the cancer. Early detection and treatment can lead to a better outcome, so it is important to seek medical attention if any symptoms are present.','{\"pat_doc\": 260.0, \"pub_alt\": 762.0, \"pub_doc\": 1908.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 72.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1167.0, \"clinic_doc\": 278.0, \"grant_fund\": 16554029.0, \"pat_granted\": 48.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_doc\": -5.4, \"clinic_doc\": 57.4, \"grant_fund\": -606977.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('db623803d51f2ef253de56cde33ff953','7d9363772a465cde721c0298e8b025e2','7bdb69262d8e22c117d34100c1831a78','2023-09-08 02:12:10','2023-10-28 23:01:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Organotypic Culture',12,'Organotypic culture is a method of growing cells in a three-dimensional structure that mimics the natural organization of tissues and organs. This type of culture system creates an environment that more closely resembles the in vivo conditions of the cells being examined, allowing for more accurate experimental results. In an organotypic culture, the cells are grown on a natural or synthetic scaffold that enables them to self-assemble into tissue-like structures. This provides an opportunity to study cell-to-cell interactions and analyze the development and behavior of tissue-specific functions. Organotypic cultures have been used in various fields, including cancer research, drug development, and regenerative medicine. They are a valuable tool for investigating complex biological processes and identifying potential therapeutic targets.','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_alt\": 77.0, \"pub_doc\": 122.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 7874063.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 5.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -1146973.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('dbbcb3242d183ca33d4c833cc46aea2a','047522bba3b34e3fc4e040441987ea79','f7fd5614f8eb7d0dc72ab27f1dc2ffa2','2023-09-08 01:19:33','2023-10-28 11:30:33','Electronics','Components','Transfer Devices','Optical interconnect',48,'In integrated circuits, optical interconnects refers to any system of transmitting signals from one part of an integrated circuit to another using light. Optical interconnects have been the topic of study due to the high latency and power consumption incurred by conventional metal interconnects in transmitting electrical signals over long distances, such as in interconnects classed as global interconnects. The International Technology Roadmap for Semiconductors has highlighted interconnect scaling as a problem for the semiconductor industry. In electrical interconnects, nonlinear signals are transmitted by copper wires conventionally, and these electrical wires all have resistance and capacitance which severely limits the rise time of signals when the dimension of the wires are scaled down. Optical solution are used to transmit signals through long distances to substitute interconnection between dies within the integrated circuit package.','{\"pat_doc\": 716.0, \"pub_alt\": 238.0, \"pub_doc\": 1126.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 92.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 53715892.0, \"pat_granted\": 251.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 24.2, \"pub_doc\": -0.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -665738.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('dc02228de27d6a852415d950cc9fd74a','12dcedeb603ee2f3832d8525115bfc64','4893d9f6d48ce8d1001500525173bb9e','2023-09-07 23:56:32','2023-10-28 16:51:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Lipid Nanoparticles',12,'Lipid nanoparticles are nanoparticles composed of lipids. They are a novel pharmaceutical drug delivery system, and a novel pharmaceutical formulation. LNPs as a drug delivery vehicle were first approved in 2018 for the siRNA drug Onpattro. LNPs became more widely known in late 2020, as some COVID-19 vaccines that use RNA vaccine technology coat the fragile mRNA strands with PEGylated lipid nanoparticles as their delivery vehicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 757.0, \"pub_alt\": 6178.0, \"pub_doc\": 1285.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 78.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1578.0, \"clinic_doc\": 13.0, \"grant_fund\": 46614547.0, \"pat_granted\": 85.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 197.2, \"pub_doc\": 208.7, \"clinic_doc\": 3.7, \"grant_fund\": 10362532.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('dc6e373fc5336420397eb15a3c5b22fc','ad14e59d8d8e44865760de1a016459ca','15926313fb5354a8aa389bc294cbeab7','2023-09-05 20:43:37','2023-10-29 04:36:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein-Protein Interaction',12,'Proteinâ€“protein interactions are physical contacts of high specificity established between two or more protein molecules as a result of biochemical events steered by interactions that include electrostatic forces, hydrogen bonding and the hydrophobic effect. Many are physical contacts with molecular associations between chains that occur in a cell or in a living organism in a specific biomolecular context. Proteins rarely act alone as their functions tend to be regulated. Many molecular processes within a cell are carried out by molecular machines that are built from numerous protein components organized by their PPIs. These physiological interactions make up the so-called interactomics of the organism, while aberrant PPIs are the basis of multiple aggregation-related diseases, such as Creutzfeldtâ€“Jakob and Alzheimers diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 232.0, \"pub_alt\": 622.0, \"pub_doc\": 4990.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 185.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 12.0, \"grant_fund\": 64677695.0, \"pat_granted\": 51.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.7, \"pub_doc\": 265.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.4, \"grant_fund\": -40776859.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('dc70325088155b9f7ca6f83eed16c56e','400032bc6a390bdea6fc89bda66806fe','5ca1ea433f162c5e837f4ddcc3c02253','2023-09-04 18:36:28','2023-10-29 06:56:10','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Chromatography',36,'In chemical analysis, chromatography is a laboratory technique for the separation of a mixture into its components. The mixture is dissolved in a fluid solvent (gas or liquid) called the mobile phase, which carries it through a system (a column, a capillary tube, a plate, or a sheet) on which a material called the stationary phase is fixed.','{\"pat_doc\": 34333.0, \"pub_alt\": 4918.0, \"pub_doc\": 93829.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1904.0, \"clinic_alt\": 100.0, \"clinic_doc\": 548.0, \"grant_fund\": 420468912.0, \"pat_granted\": 13034.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 570.9, \"pub_doc\": 561.6, \"clinic_doc\": 78.4, \"grant_fund\": -32028130.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('dd2e5996a0e5e2db6bbac6b8a2266e4a','adc255a75abbc6dc9e8c5d454e86dad3','da6fc92b2753b0e9a72b21f2c514a42d','2023-09-08 00:04:14','2023-10-29 02:06:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Smart material',12,'Smart materials, also called intelligent or responsive materials, are designed materials that have one or more properties that can be significantly changed in a controlled fashion by external stimuli, such as stress, moisture, electric or magnetic fields, light, temperature, pH, or chemical compounds. Smart materials are the basis of many applications, including sensors and actuators, or artificial muscles, particularly as electroactive polymers. Terms used to describe smart materials include shape memory material and shape memory technology.','{\"pat_doc\": 35.0, \"pub_alt\": 227.0, \"pub_doc\": 1149.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 40.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 17564653.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -2.5, \"pub_doc\": 844.3, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -20872158.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ddd84d203fe96bfa866d75c06df40579','938382e729311744061a6779d6023f38','41fcc042c592c420a4959d0a8d491f70','2023-09-08 01:56:00','2023-10-28 23:36:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Purification',12,'Protein purification is a series of processes intended to isolate one or a few proteins from a complex mixture, usually cells, tissues or whole organisms. Protein purification is vital for the specification of the function, structure and interactions of the protein of interest. The purification process may separate the protein and non-protein parts of the mixture, and finally separate the desired protein from all other proteins. Ideally, to study a protein of interest, it must be separated from other components of the cell so that contaminants wont interfere in the examination of the protein of interests structure and function. Separation of one protein from all others is typically the most laborious aspect of protein purification. Separation steps usually exploit differences in protein size, physico-chemical properties, binding affinity and biological activity. The pure result may be termed protein isolate.','{\"pat_doc\": 285.0, \"pub_alt\": 155.0, \"pub_doc\": 178.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 4737759.0, \"pat_granted\": 133.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 5.2, \"pub_doc\": -6.6, \"clinic_doc\": -0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2889090.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('de5dab061dc21915d951e383d42c589d','ee19185ea91ee66a9b4ca70824b1b576','06752199a8f52b307494ef715b2504c5','2023-09-08 11:11:55','2023-10-28 18:46:09','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Biomarker Discovery',48,'Biomarker discovery is a medical term describing the process by which biomarkers are discovered. Many commonly used blood tests in medicine are biomarkers. There is interest in biomarker discovery on the part of the pharmaceutical industry; blood-test or other biomarkers could serve as intermediate markers of disease in clinical trials, and as possible drug targets.','{\"pat_doc\": 80.0, \"pub_alt\": 1311.0, \"pub_doc\": 2791.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 376.0, \"clinic_alt\": 309.0, \"clinic_doc\": 100.0, \"grant_fund\": 440443009.0, \"pat_granted\": 18.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": 37.9, \"clinic_doc\": 20.6, \"grant_fund\": -49263941.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('de5e77f1301076eef8c6c9e0856ea641','671b6a0797f6c4055d3d1b7f83353201','45aa22dbd0eeecd7a8f404b4dd4dc2cc','2023-09-08 02:41:52','2023-10-28 21:51:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Containment System',48,'A containment system is a structure or mechanism designed to isolate or control the spread of something potentially dangerous, such as disease, hazardous materials, or other substances. These systems come in various forms and sizes, depending on the nature of the threat and the environment they are used in. Examples can include sealed chambers, biosecurity measures, containment suits, or even something as simple as plastic barriers. The main goal of a containment system is to prevent the spread of the harmful agent to other areas or individuals, reducing the risk of harm and containing the situation until it can be properly addressed. They are particularly important in settings like laboratories, medical facilities, and industrial sites where potentially harmful materials or organisms may be present.','{\"pat_doc\": 1209.0, \"pub_alt\": 537.0, \"pub_doc\": 285.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 26.0, \"clinic_alt\": 11.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 23880117.0, \"pat_granted\": 500.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -9.9, \"pub_doc\": 1.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.5, \"grant_fund\": -3150370.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('debc067d6194275e019128fe37a64c83','21d871363877cc98d16111d220b3c6ab','aa4364cfb922eeea74c84893f0cb9469','2023-09-08 09:40:12','2023-10-28 20:46:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Surface Plasmon Resonance',24,'Surface plasmon resonance is a phenomenon that occurs where electrons in a thin metal sheet become excited by light that is directed to the sheet with a particular angle of incidence, and then travel parallel to the sheet. Assuming a constant light source wavelength and that the metal sheet is thin, the angle of incidence that triggers SPR is related to the refractive index of the material and even a small change in the refractive index will cause SPR to not be observed. This makes SPR a possible technique for detecting particular substances and SPR biosensors have been developed to detect various important biomarkers.','{\"pat_doc\": 764.0, \"pub_alt\": 2771.0, \"pub_doc\": 7466.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 138.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 41614041.0, \"pat_granted\": 259.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.7, \"pub_doc\": 132.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.9, \"grant_fund\": -19685515.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('dee61e82e86952842fd05c1e689d2021','21d871363877cc98d16111d220b3c6ab','aa4364cfb922eeea74c84893f0cb9469','2023-09-08 09:40:12','2023-10-28 20:46:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Surface Plasmon Resonance',12,'Surface plasmon resonance is a phenomenon that occurs where electrons in a thin metal sheet become excited by light that is directed to the sheet with a particular angle of incidence, and then travel parallel to the sheet. Assuming a constant light source wavelength and that the metal sheet is thin, the angle of incidence that triggers SPR is related to the refractive index of the material and even a small change in the refractive index will cause SPR to not be observed. This makes SPR a possible technique for detecting particular substances and SPR biosensors have been developed to detect various important biomarkers.','{\"pat_doc\": 374.0, \"pub_alt\": 448.0, \"pub_doc\": 3830.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 41.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 21248842.0, \"pat_granted\": 127.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.7, \"pub_doc\": 132.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.9, \"grant_fund\": -19685515.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('def5888f967c21dd35a08031b836360b','c808cb9a80255cfef7c8736a22f3fd7d','586771bdb6aa5a69c62ea062df64fb52','2023-09-07 21:05:13','2023-10-28 11:55:32','Electronics','Components','Other','2D Materials',48,'2-Dimensional materials are a class of nanomaterials defined by their property of being merely one or two atoms thick. Graphene is at this time the material most commonly associated with 2-D materials.','{\"pat_doc\": 187.0, \"pub_alt\": 668.0, \"pub_doc\": 9509.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 993.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 552454342.0, \"pat_granted\": 49.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.3, \"pub_doc\": 184.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5014990.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('df113dff3a5410cb8a544b8afa75c666','f6196df8d7ae9a4d7f729e93364e0bd8','f612c4461ae2b2296d600f221ca9683b','2023-09-08 00:23:58','2023-10-29 01:46:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Cryo-electron microscopy',24,'Cryo-electron microscopy (cryo-EM) is an imaging technique used to determine the three-dimensional structures of biological macromolecules at near-atomic resolution. It involves the rapid freezing of a sample and the use of an electron microscope to capture images of the frozen sample from multiple angles. These images are then combined and analyzed computationally to generate a high-resolution 3D model of the sample. Cryo-EM has revolutionized the field of structural biology, allowing researchers to study previously inaccessible proteins and complexes and providing new insights into biological processes such as protein folding, virus-host interactions, and drug binding. Its ability to work with relatively small samples, including single molecules, and its potential for automated imaging make cryo-EM a powerful tool for drug discovery and structural biology research.','{\"pat_doc\": 34.0, \"pub_alt\": 1845.0, \"pub_doc\": 2084.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 348.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 207218210.0, \"pat_granted\": 8.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_doc\": 58.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -19994930.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('dfa9be5b93d2168815fd0d4dd4c549c1','643c5418206cf3f26f9e4a26676606ed','9d0b9265fabb266bda4551314039c119','2023-09-04 18:47:48','2023-10-28 18:16:21','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Metabolism','Type 2 Diabetes',24,'Type 2 Diabetes is a chronic condition where the body becomes resistant to insulin or does not produce enough insulin to regulate blood sugar levels. Insulin is a hormone produced by the pancreas that helps the body to use glucose for energy. When glucose builds up in the blood, it can cause damage to organs and tissues over time. Risk factors for developing type 2 diabetes include obesity, physical inactivity, poor diet, and genetics. Symptoms of type 2 diabetes may include frequent urination, increased thirst, blurred vision, fatigue, and slow healing of wounds. Treatment typically involves lifestyle modifications, such as diet and exercise, as well as medications to help regulate blood sugar levels. Without proper management, type 2 diabetes can lead to complications such as heart disease, stroke, kidney disease, and nerve damage.','{\"pat_doc\": 1703.0, \"pub_alt\": 12883.0, \"pub_doc\": 41638.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1306.0, \"clinic_alt\": 649.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4294.0, \"grant_fund\": 551323407.0, \"pat_granted\": 373.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 9.1, \"pub_doc\": 681.3, \"clinic_doc\": 645.5, \"grant_fund\": -142425510.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('dfc9235181bf2f40d14005f45506f24c','b44ddb1f06c55c8a655b7e35627c4216','eb670a907e9a4e83aa692353515a741c','2023-09-05 19:20:24','2023-10-29 05:06:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Emulsion',48,'An emulsion is a mixture of two or more liquids that are normally immiscible owing to liquid-liquid phase separation. Emulsions are part of a more general class of two-phase systems of matter called colloids. Although the terms colloid and emulsion are sometimes used interchangeably, emulsion should be used when both phases, dispersed and continuous, are liquids. In an emulsion, one liquid is dispersed in the other. Examples of emulsions include vinaigrettes, homogenized milk, liquid biomolecular condensates, and some cutting fluids for metal working. Two liquids can form different types of emulsions. As an example, oil and water can form, first, an oil-in-water emulsion, in which the oil is the dispersed phase, and water is the continuous phase. Second, they can form a water-in-oil emulsion, in which water is the dispersed phase and oil is the continuous phase. Multiple emulsions are also possible, including a \"water-in-oil-in-water\" emulsion and an \"oil-in-water-in-oil\" emulsion.','{\"pat_doc\": 75126.0, \"pub_alt\": 16313.0, \"pub_doc\": 38180.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1150.0, \"clinic_alt\": 588.0, \"clinic_doc\": 292.0, \"grant_fund\": 248019585.0, \"pat_granted\": 28958.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_doc\": 587.2, \"clinic_doc\": 18.4, \"grant_fund\": -8503567.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('dff62e33ecf274d93680f996361fa897','164a36aa72f0d1ad31bba2a4ae14dad1','52e358453865c2f781ecea69256e441f','2023-09-08 02:22:34','2023-10-28 22:26:12','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Spectral Database',24,'A spectral database is a repository of spectral data that can be used for identification and characterization of chemical compounds. Spectral data includes information about the properties of light interacting with a sample, such as absorption, emission, and scattering. By comparing the spectral data of an unknown sample to that in a spectral database, researchers can identify the likely chemical composition of the sample. Spectral databases are crucial for many scientific fields, including chemistry, biology, and materials science. They are constantly being updated with new data and have become essential tools in modern research.','{\"pat_doc\": 46.0, \"pub_alt\": 96.0, \"pub_doc\": 186.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 18.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 3964524.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.1, \"pub_doc\": 3.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -1497510.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e02f93471d564b29be96143892973ad3','a50b8ea9f2c997ee8ae5e1323c17ab97','8ff2c0d27eb80a1a00a05bdcbea821c2','2023-09-08 02:07:31','2023-10-28 14:46:14','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Achondroplasia',24,'Achondroplasia is a genetic disorder with an autosomal dominant pattern of inheritance whose primary feature is dwarfism. In those with the condition, the arms and legs are short, while the torso is typically of normal length. Those affected have an average adult height of 131 centimetres for males and 123 centimetres for females. Other features can include an enlarged head and prominent forehead. Complications can include sleep apnea or recurrent ear infections. Achondroplasia includes short-limb skeletal dysplasia with severe combined immunodeficiency. Achondroplasia is caused by a mutation in the fibroblast growth factor receptor 3 gene that results in its protein being overactive. Achondroplasia results in impaired endochondral bone growth. The disorder has an autosomal dominant mode of inheritance, meaning only one mutated copy of the gene is required for the condition to occur.','{\"pat_doc\": 48.0, \"pub_alt\": 71.0, \"pub_doc\": 294.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 125.0, \"clinic_doc\": 40.0, \"grant_fund\": 2679456.0, \"pat_granted\": 11.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.9, \"pub_doc\": 10.3, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": -1057396.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e114dbbf09ee52c199c5fa69975cc4bd','e5cdaf0403574f617436eb3c34f77c60','3889385fdc1bbeadad2bf5c86cbbd89a','2023-09-08 00:29:50','2023-10-29 01:31:13','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Electrochemical Biosensor',48,'An electrochemical biosensor is a device that uses the principles of electrochemistry to detect the presence of biological molecules. These biosensors typically consist of two main components - a biological recognition element, such as an enzyme or antibody, and a transducer that converts the interaction between the biological molecule and the recognition element into an electrical signal. The transducer typically consists of a working electrode, a reference electrode, and a counter electrode, which allow the movement of electrons between the recognition element and the surface of the electrode. The resulting electrical signal can then be measured and correlated to the concentration of the biological molecule of interest. Electrochemical biosensors are widely used in medical diagnostics, environmental monitoring, and food safety testing due to their high sensitivity, specificity, and ease of use.','{\"pat_doc\": 791.0, \"pub_alt\": 618.0, \"pub_doc\": 3440.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 115.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 18947828.0, \"pat_granted\": 265.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 19.7, \"pub_doc\": 147.8, \"clinic_doc\": 1.1, \"grant_fund\": -552123.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e11e4a427bc2b7430f73042c1c1b1936','d9d824a70a843cb14f452ee5dfe90190','1c2b4adda3013a6c23af8f23b2fc3d3e','2023-09-08 00:45:08','2023-10-28 11:45:32','Electronics','Devices','Immersive Experience','head-mounted display',36,'A head-mounted display is a display device, worn on the head or as part of a helmet, that has a small display optic in front of one or each eye. An HMD has many uses including gaming, aviation, engineering, and medicine. Virtual reality headsets are HMDs combined with IMUs. There is also an optical head-mounted display, which is a wearable display that can reflect projected images and allows a user to see through it.','{\"pat_doc\": 6297.0, \"pub_alt\": 597.0, \"pub_doc\": 2150.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 81.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 75.0, \"grant_fund\": 20147375.0, \"pat_granted\": 2364.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 37.6, \"pub_doc\": 37.6, \"clinic_doc\": 11.9, \"grant_fund\": -2029094.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e12df925a5e8ee26e43d86c90b0abc37','c2aa8e8ff53300b96a4cd521696cbdbb','ba652e04894d8ad7c796a0f64375c740','2023-09-08 01:49:52','2023-10-28 23:56:10','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Suspension Culture',12,'A cell suspension or suspension culture is a type of cell culture in which single cells or small aggregates of cells are allowed to function and multiply in an agitated growth medium, thus forming a suspension. Suspension culture is one of the two classical types of cell culture, the other being adherent culture. The history of suspension cell culture closely aligns with the history of cell culture overall, but differs in maintenance methods and commercial applications. The cells themselves can either be derived from homogenized tissue or from heterogenous cell solutions. Suspension cell culture is commonly used to culture nonadhesive cell lines like hematopoietic cells, plant cells, and insect cells. While some cell lines are cultured in suspension, the majority of commercially available mammalian cell lines are adherent. Suspension cell cultures must be agitated to maintain cells in suspension, and may require specialized equipment and flasks.','{\"pat_doc\": 283.0, \"pub_alt\": 278.0, \"pub_doc\": 289.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1247306.0, \"pat_granted\": 101.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.9, \"pub_doc\": -11.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -1405329.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e1a0eec3a3eec3d05f919486623df820','8f5e65940c2b32c65f99c25d9fea77ca','e9ee3da8c5950eddf30d7e6a8d175388','2023-09-08 00:36:35','2023-10-29 01:20:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Engineering',24,'Protein engineering is the process of developing useful or valuable proteins through the design and production of unnatural polypeptides, often by altering amino acid sequences found in nature. It is a young discipline, with much research taking place into the understanding of protein folding and recognition for protein design principles. It has been used to improve the function of many enzymes for industrial catalysis. It is also a product and services market, with an estimated value of $168 billion by 2017. There are two general strategies for protein engineering: rational protein design and directed evolution. These methods are not mutually exclusive; researchers will often apply both. In the future, more detailed knowledge of protein structure and function, and advances in high-throughput screening, may greatly expand the abilities of protein engineering.','{\"pat_doc\": 312.0, \"pub_alt\": 1207.0, \"pub_doc\": 1386.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 243.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 128298618.0, \"pat_granted\": 99.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.1, \"pub_doc\": 48.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -16048598.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e231a578cc73ce4a828e2b7a80e14c33','c808cb9a80255cfef7c8736a22f3fd7d','586771bdb6aa5a69c62ea062df64fb52','2023-09-07 21:05:13','2023-10-28 11:55:31','Electronics','Components','Other','2D Materials',12,'2-Dimensional materials are a class of nanomaterials defined by their property of being merely one or two atoms thick. Graphene is at this time the material most commonly associated with 2-D materials.','{\"pat_doc\": 58.0, \"pub_alt\": 284.0, \"pub_doc\": 2597.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 160.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 121079545.0, \"pat_granted\": 12.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 4.3, \"pub_doc\": 184.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5014990.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e291a9f7194d9cc5d295b4efe20b9bb5','0130bb7e16467c607ae66d5d6b5fe5d1','69904542b990c5c24086b0dfa8c698cf','2023-09-05 22:51:40','2023-10-29 03:01:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','High-Throughput Screening',36,'High-throughput screening is a method for scientific experimentation especially used in drug discovery and relevant to the fields of biology, materials science and chemistry. Using robotics, data processing/control software, liquid handling devices, and sensitive detectors, high-throughput screening allows a researcher to quickly conduct millions of chemical, genetic, or pharmacological tests. Through this process one can quickly recognize active compounds, antibodies, or genes that modulate a particular biomolecular pathway. The results of these experiments provide starting points for drug design and for understanding the noninteraction or role of a particular location.','{\"pat_doc\": 878.0, \"pub_alt\": 447.0, \"pub_doc\": 4410.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 464.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 12.0, \"grant_fund\": 366400697.0, \"pat_granted\": 280.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.8, \"pub_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -83628586.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e29b245395b42755a2a13edb2ad30fae','4703ee189b43ed759604065a8ab8bcd0','38375efab29a9add974615a48ca4c5ab','2023-09-08 02:24:52','2023-10-28 22:21:09','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Crystallography',48,'Protein crystallography is a technique used to determine the precise three-dimensional structure of proteins. It involves growing crystals of a protein of interest and using X-rays to deduce the position of each atom within the crystal lattice. The resulting structure can provide valuable insights into the function of the protein, including its interactions with other molecules and potential drug targets. Protein crystallography has played a crucial role in the fields of biology, biochemistry, and drug discovery, and continues to be an important tool for understanding the molecular basis of disease.','{\"pat_doc\": 10.0, \"pub_alt\": 76.0, \"pub_doc\": 253.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 78.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 37050482.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 2.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -4868876.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e37ff2a0f5c952b6a7c8bc4034e785b2','f47c085ebbd53aee312f00db0891448f','a2144b71351e9696db283cb552418a4f','2023-09-04 19:34:56','2023-10-29 06:01:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Monitoring System',12,'A monitoring system is a tool used to continuously track the status and performance of a particular process, network, or system. It helps detect and alert users of any abnormalities, errors, or threats in real-time, allowing them to quickly respond before any significant damage is done. The system collects data from various sources, such as sensors, servers, and applications, before analyzing and communicating the results to the user interface. This process enables operators to identify trends, isolate problems, and make informed decisions about necessary actions. In short, a monitoring system provides visibility, control, and optimization over a systems performance and security.','{\"pat_doc\": 26742.0, \"pub_alt\": 919.0, \"pub_doc\": 10665.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 281.0, \"clinic_alt\": 428.0, \"clinic_doc\": 419.0, \"grant_fund\": 177784159.0, \"pat_granted\": 10290.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 794.4, \"pub_doc\": 681.4, \"clinic_doc\": 89.9, \"grant_fund\": -66984808.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e38f825a2c93bda87804971d3f8e402c','9ac2c447720a37348ec3adf931d10093','10ca8f5850cbd8a1f9e8a6552dd0293d','2023-09-08 02:56:51','2023-10-28 13:46:12','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel therapies','Gonadotropin Stimulation',48,'Gonadotropin stimulation is a medical procedure that is used to increase the production of hormones that are responsible for regulating the reproductive system. The process involves administering a hormone called gonadotropin to the patient. This hormone stimulates the ovaries and testes to produce more eggs and sperm, respectively. Gonadotropin stimulation is commonly used in the treatment of infertility, as it can increase the chances of conceiving a child. The procedure is usually performed in conjunction with in vitro fertilization (IVF) or intrauterine insemination (IUI) to increase the chances of a successful pregnancy. However, gonadotropin stimulation is not without its risks and complications, which can include multiple pregnancies, ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome, and ectopic pregnancy. Patients undergoing this procedure should be carefully monitored by their healthcare provider to ensure their safety and well-being.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 278.0, \"pub_doc\": 156.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 27.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": -2.8, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e39a772e2ea9bed4e003b710c394c133','53dc292182499fa33b7eec431b8b30ff','a0ec7ffe04c046d0f8469b5de966ddfa','2023-09-04 18:55:37','2023-10-29 06:31:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Flow Cytometry',24,'Flow cytometry is a technique used to detect and measure physical and chemical characteristics of a population of cells or particles. In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument. The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components. Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths. Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer. Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials. Uses for flow cytometry include: â€¢ Cell counting â€¢ Cell sorting â€¢ Determining cell characteristics and function â€¢ Detecting microorganisms â€¢ Biomarker detection â€¢ Protein engineering detection â€¢ Diagnosis of health disorders such as blood cancers â€¢ Measuring genome size.','{\"pat_doc\": 1084.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 33213.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 907.0, \"clinic_alt\": 590.0, \"clinic_doc\": 661.0, \"grant_fund\": 266196486.0, \"pat_granted\": 347.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.1, \"pub_doc\": -433.8, \"clinic_doc\": 137.2, \"grant_fund\": -49967547.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e3b6e4552dd71d18b6f9bfd4ad8f549a','2815d363c4afb5dbd132a1ef2ad77edd','6476dd0e621a6ae9d97f588345914b91','2023-09-08 02:29:21','2023-10-28 14:26:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','McCune-Albright Syndrome',12,'McCuneâ€“Albright syndrome is a complex genetic disorder affecting the bone, skin and endocrine systems. It is a mosaic disease arising from somatic activating mutations in GNAS, which encodes the alpha-subunit of the Gâ‚› heterotrimeric G protein. It was first described in 1937 by American pediatrician Donovan James McCune and American endocrinologist Fuller Albright.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 8.0, \"pub_doc\": 52.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 1089214.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": -0.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": 27877.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e3e001686ce8c04eab291dfe2d515b10','7a50af118adfe006fb057aba1683daea','5ae657e8e871e94265b41c651880e213','2023-09-08 01:40:52','2023-10-29 00:01:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Coating technology',36,'Coating technology refers to the various processes used to apply a thin layer of material onto a surface to enhance or modify its properties. Coatings can be applied to a wide range of materials including metals, plastics, ceramics, and glass. Coatings can improve the surface properties of a material such as corrosion resistance, wear resistance, and thermal resistance. They can also be used to provide a decorative finish. Coating technology is extensively used in industries such as automotive, aerospace, construction, and electronics. There are several types of coating processes including thermal spraying, chemical vapor deposition, and electroplating. Advances in coating technology have enabled the development of high-performance coatings that can withstand extreme temperatures and harsh environments. Coating technology is an important field that helps to extend the life of materials and improve their performance.','{\"pat_doc\": 1145.0, \"pub_alt\": 294.0, \"pub_doc\": 747.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 140.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 50359524.0, \"pat_granted\": 529.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.5, \"pub_doc\": 36.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.8, \"grant_fund\": 152974.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e46f45afdcd6fe112368ac81ada2420a','a0128a060f00fc2880c25d9fe5536900','beb557d6f3a8f418565f2d30cdebe10e','2023-09-08 01:20:42','2023-10-28 15:21:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','natural killer T cells',36,'Natural Killer T cells are a type of lymphocytes that bridge the adaptive and innate immune systems. They have the ability to recognize and respond to a broad range of antigens presented on the surface of many different cell types, including cancer cells, and are important in regulating immune responses. These cells differentiate from the thymus and are characterized by the co-expression of T cell receptors and NK cell receptors. The interaction of these receptors allows them to respond quickly to pathogens and induces the rapid secretion of cytokines and other effector molecules. Natural Killer T cells play a vital role in controlling immune responses and have been implicated in various autoimmune diseases. Recent studies on the modulation of Natural Killer T cell responses provide new insights into the development of immunotherapeutic strategies for infectious and inflammatory diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 38.0, \"pub_alt\": 282.0, \"pub_doc\": 345.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 17.0, \"clinic_alt\": 37.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 6496825.0, \"pat_granted\": 11.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.0, \"pub_doc\": -0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.9, \"grant_fund\": -984070.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e4be85b63ce40920fdbe28ee527c530e','9ac2c447720a37348ec3adf931d10093','10ca8f5850cbd8a1f9e8a6552dd0293d','2023-09-08 02:56:51','2023-10-28 13:46:12','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel therapies','Gonadotropin Stimulation',12,'Gonadotropin stimulation is a medical procedure that is used to increase the production of hormones that are responsible for regulating the reproductive system. The process involves administering a hormone called gonadotropin to the patient. This hormone stimulates the ovaries and testes to produce more eggs and sperm, respectively. Gonadotropin stimulation is commonly used in the treatment of infertility, as it can increase the chances of conceiving a child. The procedure is usually performed in conjunction with in vitro fertilization (IVF) or intrauterine insemination (IUI) to increase the chances of a successful pregnancy. However, gonadotropin stimulation is not without its risks and complications, which can include multiple pregnancies, ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome, and ectopic pregnancy. Patients undergoing this procedure should be carefully monitored by their healthcare provider to ensure their safety and well-being.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 278.0, \"pub_doc\": 34.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 11.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": -2.8, \"clinic_doc\": 1.5, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e4da598276da63c721a04c28b53726e6','8b34441cb6296c1404d0a6501ee553ff','eecaf00b18ce2e327917c5c42d883f43','2023-09-05 18:42:49','2023-10-29 05:41:10','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Raman Spectroscopy',12,'Raman spectroscopy is a spectroscopic technique typically used to determine vibrational modes of molecules, although rotational and other low-frequency modes of systems may also be observed. Raman spectroscopy is commonly used in chemistry to provide a structural fingerprint by which molecules can be identified. Raman spectroscopy relies upon inelastic scattering of photons, known as Raman scattering. A source of monochromatic light, usually from a laser in the visible, near infrared, or near ultraviolet range is used, although X-rays can also be used. The laser light interacts with molecular vibrations, phonons or other excitations in the system, resulting in the energy of the laser photons being shifted up or down. The shift in energy gives information about the vibrational modes in the system. Infrared spectroscopy typically yields similar yet complementary information. Typically, a sample is illuminated with a laser beam.','{\"pat_doc\": 586.0, \"pub_alt\": 1098.0, \"pub_doc\": 9838.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 169.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 53.0, \"grant_fund\": 55441974.0, \"pat_granted\": 161.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -8.3, \"pub_doc\": 257.9, \"clinic_doc\": 14.3, \"grant_fund\": -11262983.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e5ea44707589e293bce20d2db56864ee','96a98502ddc2632768ff7919ec246022','d471ba9d05b4186943ade5d1a2ae30dc','2023-09-04 18:23:33','2023-10-29 07:06:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Mass Spectrometry',24,'Mass Spectrometry is a powerful analytical technique used in chemistry, biochemistry, and other scientific fields to identify molecules based on their mass-to-charge ratio (m/z). The process involves ionizing a sample, then separating the resulting ions based on their mass-to-charge ratio using electromagnetic fields. The ions are then detected and analyzed to determine their individual masses and concentrations. Mass spectrometry is used in many applications, including characterizing the structure of unknown compounds, identifying proteins and peptides, and tracking the movement of isotopes within molecules. It has become a standard tool in many areas of research, including drug discovery, environmental analysis, and forensic science.','{\"pat_doc\": 7976.0, \"pub_alt\": 13857.0, \"pub_doc\": 64182.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2590.0, \"clinic_alt\": 146.0, \"clinic_doc\": 554.0, \"grant_fund\": 1133704828.0, \"pat_granted\": 2610.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 210.2, \"pub_doc\": 879.4, \"clinic_doc\": 100.8, \"grant_fund\": -169513024.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e604679c41a5d1fd1c0ef4ee300cdc03','2f412f6d08233ef2ee97b503f7c210fd','bc432a22793de3677b1dacfb29fc2326','2023-09-08 09:49:36','2023-10-28 20:21:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','SDS-PAGE',24,'SDS-PAGE is a discontinuous electrophoretic system developed by Ulrich K. Laemmli which is commonly used as a method to separate proteins with molecular masses between 5 and 250 kDa. The combined use of sodium dodecyl sulfate and polyacrylamide gel eliminates the influence of structure and charge, and proteins are separated by differences in their size. At least up to 2012, the publication describing it was the most frequently cited paper by a single author, and the second most cited overall.','{\"pat_doc\": 131.0, \"pub_alt\": 606.0, \"pub_doc\": 2765.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 20.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 1415683.0, \"pat_granted\": 55.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.7, \"pub_doc\": -42.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": -1973486.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e61bb496ffdb9251e10bc3aec70571f4','55794ad69e12330a0b6d80e9fdb0988d','e612e4b67f9789306cf3914a627ea83c','2023-09-07 23:58:23','2023-10-29 02:16:16','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Metabolic Engineering',12,'Metabolic engineering is the practice of optimizing genetic and regulatory processes within cells to increase the cells production of a certain substance. These processes are chemical networks that use a series of biochemical reactions and enzymes that allow cells to convert raw materials into molecules necessary for the cells survival. Metabolic engineering specifically seeks to mathematically model these networks, calculate a yield of useful products, and pin point parts of the network that constrain the production of these products. Genetic engineering techniques can then be used to modify the network in order to relieve these constraints. Once again this modified network can be modeled to calculate the new product yield. The ultimate goal of metabolic engineering is to be able to use these organisms to produce valuable substances on an industrial scale in a cost-effective manner.','{\"pat_doc\": 256.0, \"pub_alt\": 142.0, \"pub_doc\": 1142.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 43.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 13895075.0, \"pat_granted\": 81.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 34.9, \"pub_doc\": 16.6, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -6039306.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e6290e26f01e6520f14b924043e2f31e','d4fdd9a1f4aa53cc01e7cbb316b38d68','a0401cb7a291257d3685c0a77fb2d841','2023-09-08 01:02:41','2023-10-28 15:51:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Retrovirus',36,'A retrovirus is a type of virus that inserts a DNA copy of its RNA genome into the DNA of a host cell that it invades, thus changing the genome of that cell. Once inside the host cells cytoplasm, the virus uses its own reverse transcriptase enzyme to produce DNA from its RNA genome, the reverse of the usual pattern, thus retro. The new DNA is then incorporated into the host cell genome by an integrase enzyme, at which point the retroviral DNA is referred to as a provirus. The host cell then treats the viral DNA as part of its own genome, transcribing and translating the viral genes along with the cells own genes, producing the proteins required to assemble new copies of the virus. Many retroviruses cause serious diseases in humans, other mammals, and birds. Retroviruses have many subfamilies in three basic groups. â€¢ Oncoretroviruses include human T-lymphotropic virus causing a type of leukemia in humans, and murine leukemia viruses in mice.','{\"pat_doc\": 407.0, \"pub_alt\": 3897.0, \"pub_doc\": 2401.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 222.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1310.0, \"clinic_doc\": 68.0, \"grant_fund\": 118004783.0, \"pat_granted\": 96.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.8, \"pub_doc\": 7.1, \"clinic_doc\": 15.6, \"grant_fund\": -9492771.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e62e08459e0f81a82ef3399b26f3aa7e','aedf0c478e49c48a393feff1fdcfaa4b','5b55c48790bb4cf3b5dc24f790e7d5a2','2023-09-05 21:32:03','2023-10-28 12:25:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Metaverse',24,'The Metaverse is a virtual reality space that contains multiple interconnected virtual worlds and augmented reality environments. It is a digital universe that enables users to create, experience, and interact with each other in various virtual environments. In the Metaverse, users can have a digital representation of themselves, or an avatar, who can move from one world to another. The concept of Metaverse is increasingly becoming popular as advancements in technology allow for more immersive and seamless experiences. It is used in various areas, including gaming, education, socialization, commerce, and even politics, to name a few. The Metaverse holds immense potential for revolutionizing how we interact with technology and each other.','{\"pat_doc\": 960.0, \"pub_alt\": 695.0, \"pub_doc\": 5855.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 119.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 76259069.0, \"pat_granted\": 270.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 259.5, \"pub_doc\": 1393.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.3, \"grant_fund\": 20484735.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e639471bab2c68c5353523094fbc9508','02a38e6ea55a654be6d75d697c93ecfb','0af29b992be89a885d2b3986c5a61ac5','2023-09-08 10:03:52','2023-10-28 19:11:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Catalyst screening',36,'Catalyst screening can be defined as a process by which researchers test a large number of catalysts in order to identify the most effective one for a particular reaction. Catalysts are substances that speed up reactions without being consumed in the process. The screening process typically involves testing each catalyst under a variety of conditions such as temperature, pressure, and reaction time, to determine which catalyst is the most suitable for the reaction being studied. Catalyst screening is an important step in many research projects as it helps researchers to identify the catalysts that are most likely to be effective in a real-world scenario. It can also help to identify new catalysts that may be more effective than those that are currently being used in industry. By screening a large number of catalysts, researchers can quickly identify promising candidates for further study, ultimately leading to the development of more efficient catalysts for a wide range of applications.','{\"pat_doc\": 50.0, \"pub_alt\": 86.0, \"pub_doc\": 172.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 14.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 3831872.0, \"pat_granted\": 33.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 7.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 219625.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e64cd61f9d7f605502eec52a2f119c13','f82670ab57400d3e832f9efb4a5573a4','2e3f377d891e03c5b7a4ddf257a19dc5','2023-09-08 01:35:27','2023-10-28 15:11:17','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','DNA origami',24,'DNA origami is the nanoscale folding of DNA to create arbitrary two- and three-dimensional shapes at the nanoscale. The specificity of the interactions between complementary base pairs make DNA a useful construction material, through design of its base sequences. DNA is a well-understood material that is suitable for creating scaffolds that hold other molecules in place or to create structures all on its own. DNA origami was the cover story of Nature on March 16, 2006. Since then, DNA origami has progressed past an art form and has found a number of applications from drug delivery systems to uses as circuitry in plasmonic devices; however, most commercial applications remain in a concept or testing phase.','{\"pat_doc\": 61.0, \"pub_alt\": 581.0, \"pub_doc\": 636.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 56.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 76569392.0, \"pat_granted\": 14.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.1, \"pub_doc\": 26.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1724661.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e6f68a87ebbe2a10c6d59095e04ef8db','82841277cc54621d2d6071e3ec919414','0b9a93bcbf56042557d5a41dd3db0243','2023-09-20 17:31:16','2023-10-28 13:01:19','Healthcare','Discovery & Development Technologies','Other','Waldo',48,'Telemanipulator, or waldo, is a device which, through electronic, hydraulic, or mechanical linkages, allows a hand-like mechanism to be controlled by a human operator.','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_alt\": 1938.0, \"pub_doc\": 1431.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 152.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": 4205454.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.6, \"pub_doc\": 12.9, \"clinic_doc\": 2.4, \"grant_fund\": -590542.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e71073f7d84129f6645e84324a538ef7','68a4129044821c3a1d6386321b0e0003','71b92f66f40436e1ab511b3f211c9bd0','2023-09-08 02:35:10','2023-10-28 10:50:30','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Photonic Computing',24,'Optical computing or photonic computing uses light waves produced by lasers or incoherent sources for data processing, data storage or data communication for computing. For decades, photons have shown promise to enable a higher bandwidth than the electrons used in conventional computers. Most research projects focus on replacing current computer components with optical equivalents, resulting in an optical digital computer system processing binary data. This approach appears to offer the best short-term prospects for commercial optical computing, since optical components could be integrated into traditional computers to produce an optical-electronic hybrid. However, optoelectronic devices consume 30% of their energy converting electronic energy into photons and back; this conversion also slows the transmission of messages. All-optical computers eliminate the need for optical-electrical-optical conversions, thus reducing electrical power consumption.','{\"pat_doc\": 36.0, \"pub_alt\": 126.0, \"pub_doc\": 129.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 10.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 16589540.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.5, \"pub_doc\": 21.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2638715.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e7b6b369dd8406d5a6c714189628e2a7','0aa43655311231d22f19c9a7f97c3577','69904542b990c5c24086b0dfa8c698cf','2023-09-05 22:50:45','2023-10-29 03:05:06','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','High-Throughput Screening',36,'High-throughput screening is a method for scientific experimentation especially used in drug discovery and relevant to the fields of biology, materials science and chemistry. Using robotics, data processing/control software, liquid handling devices, and sensitive detectors, high-throughput screening allows a researcher to quickly conduct millions of chemical, genetic, or pharmacological tests. Through this process one can quickly recognize active compounds, antibodies, or genes that modulate a particular biomolecular pathway. The results of these experiments provide starting points for drug design and for understanding the noninteraction or role of a particular location.','{\"pat_doc\": 878.0, \"pub_alt\": 447.0, \"pub_doc\": 4410.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 464.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 12.0, \"grant_fund\": 366400697.0, \"pat_granted\": 280.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.8, \"pub_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -83628586.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e7c0e9b097e7d11b4a1fbf13644d57f1','fad21049eb39f44584479b92c65f1f69','1d60e7deb149c3b68658f6de8ff089a9','2023-09-20 20:26:19','2023-10-28 15:56:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Cushings Syndrome',12,'Cushings syndrome is a collection of signs and symptoms due to prolonged exposure to glucocorticoids such as cortisol. Signs and symptoms may include high blood pressure, abdominal obesity but with thin arms and legs, reddish stretch marks, a round red face due to facial plethora, a fat lump between the shoulders, weak muscles, weak bones, acne, and fragile skin that heals poorly. Women may have more hair and irregular menstruation. Occasionally there may be changes in mood, headaches, and a chronic feeling of tiredness. Cushings syndrome is caused by either excessive cortisol-like medication, such as prednisone, or a tumor that either produces or results in the production of excessive cortisol by the adrenal glands. Cases due to a pituitary adenoma are known as Cushings disease, which is the second most common cause of Cushings syndrome after medication. A number of other tumors, often referred to as ectopic due to their placement outside the pituitary, may also cause Cushings.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": -1.4, \"clinic_doc\": -0.9, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e7d5aa78ed492673abb9a561f955d11a','0b7aa8ee981ba0fe14ccf04dee81c1ad','62899d4dc41a7b9eb6091bb110aca523','2023-09-05 19:51:05','2023-10-29 04:55:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Tissue Engineering',36,'Tissue engineering is a biomedical engineering discipline that uses a combination of cells, engineering, materials methods, and suitable biochemical and physicochemical factors to restore, maintain, improve, or replace different types of biological tissues. Tissue engineering often involves the use of cells placed on tissue scaffolds in the formation of new viable tissue for a medical purpose but is not limited to applications involving cells and tissue scaffolds. While it was once categorized as a sub-field of biomaterials, having grown in scope and importance it can be considered as a field of its own. While most definitions of tissue engineering cover a broad range of applications, in practice the term is closely associated with applications that repair or replace portions of or whole tissues. Often, the tissues involved require certain mechanical and structural properties for proper functioning.','{\"pat_doc\": 3048.0, \"pub_alt\": 641.0, \"pub_doc\": 20034.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1194.0, \"clinic_alt\": 16.0, \"clinic_doc\": 66.0, \"grant_fund\": 462506532.0, \"pat_granted\": 1177.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.9, \"pub_doc\": 306.5, \"clinic_doc\": 10.5, \"grant_fund\": -54494104.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e7f1cd3bfea578512233f1eb48e00ca4','8fbcc1f9eedaac7f718565fe8c77f942','db8b9e3ac816571bb88d6adb6207c374','2023-09-08 10:03:44','2023-10-28 19:16:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Microbiological assay',24,'Microbiological assay is a type of analytical technique used in biochemistry and microbiology to determine the concentration of a particular substance by measuring the growth response of microorganisms to varying levels of the substance. In this assay, a known quantity of a microorganism is inoculated into a series of test tubes containing different concentrations of the substance being tested. The growth response of the microorganism is then measured and compared to a set of standard concentrations of the substance to determine the relative concentration in the sample being tested. Microbiological assays are widely used in the pharmaceutical industry to determine the potency of drugs and antibiotics, and in the food industry to measure the nutritional value of food products.','{\"pat_doc\": 25.0, \"pub_alt\": 80.0, \"pub_doc\": 141.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 12.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 3769175.0, \"pat_granted\": 17.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.0, \"pub_doc\": -7.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.4, \"grant_fund\": -3518570.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e834af4e11fd59a150a71118b54d42d5','d006191764fe7b11e9181190cc8abcbe','5f9f631521aff2090e15184e37181d22','2023-09-04 19:03:56','2023-10-29 06:16:11','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Immunohistochemistry',12,'Immunohistochemistry is the most common application of immunostaining. It involves the process of selectively identifying antigens in cells of a tissue section by exploiting the principle of antibodies binding specifically to antigens in biological tissues. IHC takes its name from the roots \"immuno\", in reference to antibodies used in the procedure, and \"histo\", meaning tissue. Albert Coons conceptualized and first implemented the procedure in 1941. Visualising an antibody-antigen interaction can be accomplished in a number of ways, mainly either of the following: â€¢ Chromogenic immunohistochemistry, wherein an antibody is conjugated to an enzyme, such as peroxidase, that can catalyse a colour-producing reaction. â€¢ Immunofluorescence, where the antibody is tagged to a fluorophore, such as fluorescein or rhodamine. Immunohistochemical staining is widely used in the diagnosis of abnormal cells such as those found in cancerous tumors.','{\"pat_doc\": 192.0, \"pub_alt\": 2918.0, \"pub_doc\": 14783.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 261.0, \"clinic_alt\": 553.0, \"clinic_doc\": 537.0, \"grant_fund\": 60411699.0, \"pat_granted\": 60.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.1, \"pub_doc\": -408.2, \"clinic_doc\": 134.5, \"grant_fund\": -28858320.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e8a4f710313aa0264a1205797b8928f9','3dc3dd5d2df2a0b127886fa91ef3f5d5','606edbb39b7dac4ec5ef367e4247cc8d','2023-09-08 09:54:26','2023-10-28 20:01:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Ion Chromatography',12,'Ion chromatography is a form of chromatography that separates ions and polar molecules based on their affinity to the ion exchanger. It works on almost any kind of charged moleculeâ€”including large proteins, small nucleotides, and amino acids. However, ion chromatography must be done in conditions that are one unit away from the isoelectric point of a protein. The two types of ion chromatography are anion-exchange and cation-exchange. Cation-exchange chromatography is used when the molecule of interest is positively charged. The molecule is positively charged because the pH for chromatography is less than the pI. In this type of chromatography, the stationary phase is negatively charged and positively charged molecules are loaded to be attracted to it. Anion-exchange chromatography is when the stationary phase is positively charged and negatively charged molecules are loaded to be attracted to it. It is often used in protein purification, water analysis, and quality control.','{\"pat_doc\": 969.0, \"pub_alt\": 473.0, \"pub_doc\": 2456.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 33.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.0, \"grant_fund\": 5850005.0, \"pat_granted\": 283.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.4, \"pub_doc\": -31.8, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": -6435445.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e925c36610eeee2f0ed77023d0a89ed9','1fccc88a9353a2b047cbe302f41187a4','e935f5dfeb3e4ae65d7860e4ea27b605','2023-09-05 20:23:19','2023-10-28 12:45:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Societal & Economic Disruptions','Post-COVID-19',36,'The concept of Post-COVID-19 refers to the scenario and circumstances following the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic. The world after COVID-19 is expected to be markedly different, with changes in the way people work, travel, socialize, and interact with each other. These changes may include a greater emphasis on remote work, increased use of technology for communication, more flexible working arrangements, significant shifts in consumer behavior, and a focus on public health and hygiene. The pandemic has also highlighted the importance of international cooperation and sustainable development, leading to the adoption of new policies aimed at creating a more resilient and equitable world. Ultimately, the post-COVID-19 era represents both an opportunity and a challenge for businesses, governments, and individuals to adapt and thrive in a rapidly changing world.','{\"pat_doc\": 32.0, \"pub_alt\": 24451.0, \"pub_doc\": 11393.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 286.0, \"clinic_alt\": 244.0, \"clinic_doc\": 287.0, \"grant_fund\": 65794333.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.4, \"pub_doc\": 1295.8, \"clinic_doc\": 64.2, \"grant_fund\": -5280894.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e93807b84c51cedde70315434c5ca92e','8837382ad71ea14d648e72dffa07f350','a10d686867f23b1f3c14742bdf7326cc','2023-09-05 19:11:33','2023-10-29 05:16:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Biomaterial',36,'A biomaterial is a substance that has been engineered to interact with biological systems for a medical purpose, either a therapeutic or a diagnostic one. The corresponding field of study, called biomaterials science or biomaterials engineering, is about fifty years old. It has experienced steady and strong growth over its history, with many companies investing large amounts of money into the development of new products. Biomaterials science encompasses elements of medicine, biology, chemistry, tissue engineering and materials science. Note that a biomaterial is different from a biological material, such as bone, that is produced by a biological system. Additionally, care should be exercised in defining a biomaterial as biocompatible, since it is application-specific. A biomaterial that is biocompatible or suitable for one application may not be biocompatible in another.','{\"pat_doc\": 3493.0, \"pub_alt\": 1940.0, \"pub_doc\": 25219.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2416.0, \"clinic_alt\": 260.0, \"clinic_doc\": 293.0, \"grant_fund\": 1044619930.0, \"pat_granted\": 1037.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -44.8, \"pub_doc\": 588.5, \"clinic_doc\": 50.9, \"grant_fund\": -91915477.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e9688ede7a5d236ae3530ee643f24c5d','dc11d80fc0114b8dfe9fa719a1d68ad7','a0ec7ffe04c046d0f8469b5de966ddfa','2023-09-04 18:54:26','2023-10-29 06:35:05','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Flow Cytometry',48,'Flow cytometry is a technique used to detect and measure physical and chemical characteristics of a population of cells or particles. In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument. The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components. Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths. Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer. Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials. Uses for flow cytometry include: â€¢ Cell counting â€¢ Cell sorting â€¢ Determining cell characteristics and function â€¢ Detecting microorganisms â€¢ Biomarker detection â€¢ Protein engineering detection â€¢ Diagnosis of health disorders such as blood cancers â€¢ Measuring genome size.','{\"pat_doc\": 2017.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 67644.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2556.0, \"clinic_alt\": 590.0, \"clinic_doc\": 864.0, \"grant_fund\": 741017990.0, \"pat_granted\": 652.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.1, \"pub_doc\": -433.8, \"clinic_doc\": 137.2, \"grant_fund\": -49967547.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e9831d11bbb6217469b18114682e2283','f75d09446940f86ed08ebd34eebf7374','aa6c75c69a90f2c711a2a5e31bb1c990','2023-09-08 01:34:12','2023-10-29 00:06:22','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','mRNA sequencing',36,'mRNA sequencing refers to the process of analyzing the transcriptome of an organism by sequencing the messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules that are expressed in a given sample. mRNA is synthesized from DNA and contains the information required to make proteins, which are the building blocks of the cell. By sequencing the mRNA, researchers can identify which genes are being expressed in a specific tissue or cell type, and can also measure the abundance of each transcript. This information can be used to gain insights into the biological processes that are occurring in the organism, and can also be used to identify genes that are dysregulated in diseases such as cancer. mRNA sequencing has become a widely used technique for studying gene expression, and new methods are continually being developed to improve the accuracy and speed of this process.','{\"pat_doc\": 24.0, \"pub_alt\": 8858.0, \"pub_doc\": 1001.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 54.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 15428540.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.5, \"pub_doc\": 43.3, \"clinic_doc\": 1.2, \"grant_fund\": -1315097.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e9dd1a44458c6b7ff4b90dfe43332c08','60518e711e4b43d56a5bbd7732ffd16e','9d4e5b197da5f47c35976f2bf01251b9','2023-09-05 22:10:54','2023-10-29 03:31:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Personal Protective Equipment',24,'Personal protective equipment is protective clothing, helmets, goggles, or other garments or equipment designed to protect the wearers body from injury or infection. The hazards addressed by protective equipment include physical, electrical, heat, chemicals, biohazards, and airborne particulate matter. Protective equipment may be worn for job-related occupational safety and health purposes, as well as for sports and other recreational activities. Protective clothing is applied to traditional categories of clothing, and protective gear applies to items such as pads, guards, shields, or masks, and others. PPE suits can be similar in appearance to a cleanroom suit. The purpose of personal protective equipment is to reduce employee exposure to hazards when engineering controls and administrative controls are not feasible or effective to reduce these risks to acceptable levels. PPE is needed when there are hazards present.','{\"pat_doc\": 743.0, \"pub_alt\": 2792.0, \"pub_doc\": 5426.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 113.0, \"clinic_alt\": 75.0, \"clinic_doc\": 114.0, \"grant_fund\": 34568380.0, \"pat_granted\": 113.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.6, \"pub_doc\": -446.8, \"clinic_doc\": -1.4, \"grant_fund\": -24125078.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('e9ef19c1d1b43e3c761f290ca59c4cde','69a17d20e0dd95936b11c342f374274e','21412fd8c571a6c3727e6a6906b7c1a8','2023-09-08 02:19:08','2023-10-28 22:31:10','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Synthesis',36,'mRNA synthesis, also known as transcription, is a process that occurs in the nucleus of a cell whereby DNA is copied into a single strand of messenger RNA (mRNA). This process involves the separation of the two strands of DNA and the synthesizing of an mRNA strand using one of the DNA strands as a template. The mRNA formed during transcription will carry a genetic message from the DNA to the ribosome, where it will be translated into a protein. This process is a critical step in gene expression and the regulation of cellular processes. Defects in mRNA synthesis can lead to genetic disorders, developmental abnormalities, and diseases, making it an important area of study for geneticists and molecular biologists.','{\"pat_doc\": 9.0, \"pub_alt\": 714.0, \"pub_doc\": 189.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 20.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 12242933.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.1, \"pub_doc\": 2.4, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -2023051.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ea25f70597a07c2c22dd23288fd519d3','7d2130a3ffbe9bc530ccc4b006bedc33','a21d57b1520cb1a6af41c917959012e7','2023-09-05 20:52:48','2023-10-28 17:51:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','siRNA',12,'SiRNA (short interfering RNA) is a small double-stranded RNA molecule that can trigger the destruction of specific messenger RNA (mRNA) and thereby inhibit the expression of genes. SiRNA is involved in RNA interference, a natural process that regulates gene expression at the post-transcriptional level. Once inside the cell, siRNA is incorporated into the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), which separates the two strands of the siRNA molecule and guides the antisense strand to a complementary target mRNA. The RISC complex then cleaves the target mRNA, preventing its translation into proteins. SiRNA has become a powerful tool for investigating gene function and developing new therapeutics for various diseases. Its potential applications include treating viral infections, cancer, and genetic disorders, as well as controlling insect pests and enhancing crop yields.','{\"pat_doc\": 1158.0, \"pub_alt\": 478.0, \"pub_doc\": 4867.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 156.0, \"clinic_alt\": 109.0, \"clinic_doc\": 19.0, \"grant_fund\": 57475632.0, \"pat_granted\": 280.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 99.5, \"pub_doc\": -402.5, \"clinic_doc\": 4.8, \"grant_fund\": -26868531.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ea47a6eef982948d91aab7f84396a113','0a067dac7f4a167516bf9ae7db80387b','05ecfec6f6dadbdbb84f6f314d1e344e','2023-09-08 09:06:23','2023-10-28 13:31:15','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Non-small cell lung cancer',24,'Non-small-cell lung carcinoma is any type of epithelial lung cancer other than small-cell lung carcinoma. NSCLC accounts for about 85% of all lung cancers. As a class, NSCLCs are relatively insensitive to chemotherapy, compared to small-cell carcinoma. When possible, they are primarily treated by surgical resection with curative intent, although chemotherapy has been used increasingly both preoperatively and postoperatively.','{\"pat_doc\": 1325.0, \"pub_alt\": 1352.0, \"pub_doc\": 15929.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 245.0, \"clinic_alt\": 822.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2912.0, \"grant_fund\": 120428641.0, \"pat_granted\": 336.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 34.7, \"pub_doc\": 157.7, \"clinic_doc\": 620.8, \"grant_fund\": -18325526.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('eaeb52230fc5e6cd5154c338d6941b2d','d702a8adc5dbea4b170f75415100b3b5','4aebb65d3ef171435ae3068e3a2c9f22','2023-09-04 18:33:18','2023-10-29 07:01:15','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Stem Cells',48,'Stem cells are undifferentiated cells that have the ability to differentiate into specialized cells and regenerate damaged tissues in the body. These cells have the potential to give rise to any cell type in the body, such as blood, bone, muscle, and nerve cells. Stem cells can be classified into embryonic, fetal, and adult stem cells based on their origin and potential to differentiate. Embryonic stem cells are obtained from early-stage embryos and can differentiate into any cell type, while fetal and adult stem cells are found in various tissues and have a more limited differentiation potential. Stem cell research shows promise for developing treatments for a range of diseases and conditions.','{\"pat_doc\": 25354.0, \"pub_alt\": 3957.0, \"pub_doc\": 81437.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 9041.0, \"clinic_alt\": 945.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2682.0, \"grant_fund\": 3834453138.0, \"pat_granted\": 7389.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 141.4, \"pub_doc\": -576.1, \"clinic_doc\": 354.8, \"grant_fund\": -242932791.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('eafd22cf2b8521873ca2fcb063d68461','3c51150cb4d6d0c2bbf77b25519de393','6de0c721cf3eb4c836d007670b4c702d','2023-09-08 00:28:32','2023-10-29 01:36:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Live Cell Imaging',48,'Live cell imaging is the study of living cells using time-lapse microscopy. It is used by scientists to obtain a better understanding of biological function through the study of cellular dynamics. Live cell imaging was pioneered in first decade of the 21th century. One of the first time-lapse microcinematographic films of cells ever made was made by Julius Ries, showing the fertilization and development of the sea urchin egg. Since then, several microscopy methods have been developed which allow researchers to study living cells in greater detail with less effort. A newer type of imaging utilizing quantum dots have been used as they are shown to be more stable. The development of holotomographic microscopy has disregarded phototoxicity and other staining-derived disadvantages by implementing digital staining based on cells refractive index.','{\"pat_doc\": 72.0, \"pub_alt\": 371.0, \"pub_doc\": 1617.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 419.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 208864443.0, \"pat_granted\": 15.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.4, \"pub_doc\": -16.3, \"clinic_doc\": -0.2, \"grant_fund\": -12558862.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('eb0241582b33c1f241f2bb4e19991220','7286b6dd5e6f51fb279c0a6a82e528d2','4cfacc6752b10fbede9acf0bca84032d','2023-09-08 02:52:18','2023-10-28 21:21:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Cell Line Culture',24,'Cell line culture refers to the process of growing and propagating cells in vitro, outside the organism from which they were derived. The cells are typically obtained from tissues or organs and are cultured in a laboratory using specialized techniques and growth media. Cell line cultures are used extensively in research, drug development, and biomedical applications to study cell behavior, cell function, and disease processes, among other things. They are an important tool for understanding the mechanisms of diseases and for developing new drugs and therapies. In addition, they offer a reliable and reproducible model system that is easily manipulated, making them an attractive option for a wide range of applications. Overall, cell line culture has revolutionized scientific research and is a critical tool in advancing medical knowledge and treatments.','{\"pat_doc\": 12.0, \"pub_alt\": 11.0, \"pub_doc\": 79.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 304243.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.1, \"pub_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -149953.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('eb141d42def5ac2691b2e2c1e0377548','4703ee189b43ed759604065a8ab8bcd0','38375efab29a9add974615a48ca4c5ab','2023-09-08 02:24:52','2023-10-28 22:21:09','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Crystallography',12,'Protein crystallography is a technique used to determine the precise three-dimensional structure of proteins. It involves growing crystals of a protein of interest and using X-rays to deduce the position of each atom within the crystal lattice. The resulting structure can provide valuable insights into the function of the protein, including its interactions with other molecules and potential drug targets. Protein crystallography has played a crucial role in the fields of biology, biochemistry, and drug discovery, and continues to be an important tool for understanding the molecular basis of disease.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 76.0, \"pub_doc\": 73.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 5751346.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 2.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -4868876.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('eb9d52fe49ccf9cd3b1e2a8026d97bf6','382772c54fc63869435b590e8d1111c4','43d3334d4623a18878a471a105e8c82e','2023-09-08 00:27:07','2023-10-28 16:21:14','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Pheochromocytoma',12,'Pheochromocytoma is a rare tumor of the adrenal medulla composed of chromaffin cells, also known as pheochromocytes. When a tumor composed of the same cells as a pheochromocytoma develops outside the adrenal gland, it is referred to as a paraganglioma. These neuroendocrine tumors typically release massive amounts of catecholamines, metanephrines, or methoxytyramine, which result in the most common symptoms, including hypertension, tachycardia, and diaphoresis. Rarely, some tumors may secrete little to no catecholamines, making diagnosis difficult. While tumors of the head and neck are parasympathetic, their sympathetic counterparts are predominantly located in the abdomen and pelvis, particularly concentrated at the organ of Zuckerkandl.','{\"pat_doc\": 12.0, \"pub_alt\": 137.0, \"pub_doc\": 1029.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 312.0, \"clinic_doc\": 71.0, \"grant_fund\": 979405.0, \"pat_granted\": 5.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.4, \"pub_doc\": 22.8, \"clinic_doc\": 17.8, \"grant_fund\": -4557007.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ec118f7d126d81215c0b0acdb8da3049','69a17d20e0dd95936b11c342f374274e','21412fd8c571a6c3727e6a6906b7c1a8','2023-09-08 02:19:08','2023-10-28 22:31:10','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Synthesis',24,'mRNA synthesis, also known as transcription, is a process that occurs in the nucleus of a cell whereby DNA is copied into a single strand of messenger RNA (mRNA). This process involves the separation of the two strands of DNA and the synthesizing of an mRNA strand using one of the DNA strands as a template. The mRNA formed during transcription will carry a genetic message from the DNA to the ribosome, where it will be translated into a protein. This process is a critical step in gene expression and the regulation of cellular processes. Defects in mRNA synthesis can lead to genetic disorders, developmental abnormalities, and diseases, making it an important area of study for geneticists and molecular biologists.','{\"pat_doc\": 6.0, \"pub_alt\": 714.0, \"pub_doc\": 128.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 9.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2711838.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 1.1, \"pub_doc\": 2.4, \"clinic_doc\": -0.1, \"grant_fund\": -2023051.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ec7cef118a0e41fef57fc630bf8d4532','5c2546ad4bcf61666dc6e1c3462112a1','63620f5d0220fdda22b46d43a342534f','2023-09-08 01:14:21','2023-10-29 00:26:20','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Phage Display',24,'Phage display is a laboratory technique for the study of proteinâ€“protein, proteinâ€“peptide, and proteinâ€“DNA interactions that uses bacteriophages to connect proteins with the genetic information that encodes them. In this technique, a gene encoding a protein of interest is inserted into a phage coat protein gene, causing the phage to \"display\" the protein on its outside while containing the gene for the protein on its inside, resulting in a connection between genotype and phenotype. These displaying phages can then be screened against other proteins, peptides or DNA sequences, in order to detect interaction between the displayed protein and those other molecules. In this way, large libraries of proteins can be screened and amplified in a process called in vitro selection, which is analogous to natural selection. The most common bacteriophages used in phage display are M13 and fd filamentous phage, though T4, T7, and Î» phage have also been used.','{\"pat_doc\": 394.0, \"pub_alt\": 1051.0, \"pub_doc\": 966.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 83.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 26643025.0, \"pat_granted\": 142.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 23.5, \"pub_doc\": 24.6, \"clinic_doc\": -0.3, \"grant_fund\": -13328661.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ec98071e8dae2241cf6953283850d136','926bd332c30fbfe2631a0f1af6fd3501','a8f010b8551aa704497c66b481f56011','2023-09-08 02:21:24','2023-10-28 14:36:11','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Autologous chondrocytes',24,'Autologous chondrocytes refer to a type of cellular therapy that involves using the patients own cartilage cells to repair damaged or degenerated cartilage tissue. This procedure is typically used in cases of chondral defects or osteoarthritis. The process involves extracting a sample of the patients cartilage cells and growing them in a laboratory setting. The cells are then re-implanted into the patients damaged joint, where they can help to regenerate new cartilage tissue. Autologous chondrocyte therapy is considered a promising approach for the treatment of cartilage defects, as it enables the use of the patients own cells and can lead to improved outcomes compared to other treatment options.','{\"pat_doc\": 2.0, \"pub_alt\": 27.0, \"pub_doc\": 35.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 1687395.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": -2.4, \"clinic_doc\": 1.7, \"grant_fund\": 108408.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('eca4f233ddbb536bc8618f3e995641a3','233fd598fd0386ae12fee35e82334037','bd1c38b04e309caf5a996a81284254cb','2023-09-04 19:01:17','2023-10-29 06:26:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Nanomaterial',48,'Nanomaterials describe, in principle, materials of which a single unit is sized between 1 and 100 nm. Nanomaterials research takes a materials science-based approach to nanotechnology, leveraging advances in materials metrology and synthesis which have been developed in support of microfabrication research. Materials with structure at the nanoscale often have unique optical, electronic, thermo-physical or mechanical properties. Nanomaterials are slowly becoming commercialized and beginning to emerge as commodities.','{\"pat_doc\": 5638.0, \"pub_alt\": 1172.0, \"pub_doc\": 64144.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3732.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.0, \"grant_fund\": 1443841403.0, \"pat_granted\": 1698.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 290.2, \"pub_doc\": 1878.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.8, \"grant_fund\": -70327657.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ecfba2db22f58971eaba447df1ecb1ee','b2cee85dff870540c318cdc9d046cdcd','c3c3761ddee3a08a11545145a56cc763','2023-09-05 21:43:53','2023-10-29 03:56:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Co-culture',24,'Co-culture refers to the interaction and exchange between two or more distinct cultures. This can occur through direct contact or through mediated channels, such as media or trade. The concept of co-culture recognizes that cultures do not exist in isolation but are rather constantly interacting and influencing one another. It is important to understand co-culture in order to appreciate cultural diversity and to build bridges between cultures. Co-culture can lead to cultural fusion, which is the blending of elements from different cultures to create a new, hybrid culture. This can be seen in the arts, cuisine, and fashion, among other areas. However, co-culture can also lead to conflict and tension, particularly when different cultures have contrasting beliefs or values. By recognizing the role of co-culture, individuals and societies can foster greater understanding and appreciation for diverse cultural perspectives.','{\"pat_doc\": 1278.0, \"pub_alt\": 686.0, \"pub_doc\": 8683.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 659.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 61.0, \"grant_fund\": 234424692.0, \"pat_granted\": 446.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 54.4, \"pub_doc\": 183.5, \"clinic_doc\": 11.2, \"grant_fund\": -35120452.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ed01a6843eed7d91b9acf7e5d6c07dfa','3cf46267ec47fde029e918d250b335a1','c26c7529dcbe3665be368505da21babe','2023-09-08 02:53:34','2023-10-28 13:56:10','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Nanobots',24,'Nanoid robotics, or for short, nanorobotics or nanobotics, is an emerging technology field creating machines or robots whose components are at or near the scale of a nanometer. More specifically, nanorobotics refers to the nanotechnology engineering discipline of designing and building nanorobots with devices ranging in size from 0.1 to 10 micrometres and constructed of nanoscale or molecular components. The terms nanobot, nanoid, nanite, nanomachine and nanomite have also been used to describe such devices currently under research and development. Nanomachines are largely in the research and development phase, but some primitive molecular machines and nanomotors have been tested. An example is a sensor having a switch approximately 1.5 nanometers across, able to count specific molecules in the chemical sample. The first useful applications of nanomachines may be in nanomedicine. For example, biological machines could be used to identify and destroy cancer cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 6.0, \"pub_alt\": 265.0, \"pub_doc\": 88.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 1691458.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 11.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -619816.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ed2c1080f32d616a1488a2ea7fd01a2d','42a2ae4f376aa262cce85cebcfc87270','feda5fe0c35fb0034afb02626ac53d93','2023-09-08 02:11:05','2023-10-28 23:06:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','High-Content Screening',48,'High-content screening, also known as high-content analysis or cellomics, is a method that is used in biological research and drug discovery to identify substances such as small molecules, peptides, or RNAi that alter the phenotype of a cell in a desired manner. Hence high content screening is a type of phenotypic screen conducted in cells involving the analysis of whole cells or components of cells with simultaneous readout of several parameters. HCS is related to high-throughput screening, in which thousands of compounds are tested in parallel for their activity in one or more biological assays, but involves assays of more complex cellular phenotypes as outputs. Phenotypic changes may include increases or decreases in the production of cellular products such as proteins and/or changes in the morphology of the cell. Hence HCA typically involves automated microscopy and image analysis.','{\"pat_doc\": 5.0, \"pub_alt\": 343.0, \"pub_doc\": 366.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 44.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 20542413.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": -0.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2272629.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ed417e5c7aa025646342ace355e99b90','66370bcc1950b8300adc5378b5a9db5b','2cf8a6770a22256c603cf40927d188ef','2023-09-08 02:16:56','2023-10-28 22:41:13','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Non-viral Vector',12,'Non-viral vectors are genetic tools that aid in gene therapy that lack the viral genome and carry foreign genetic material that can be transferred into the cells. Instead of using an infectious pathogen, non-viral vectors use liposomes, nanoparticles, and chemical conjugates. Because non-viral vectors lack the viral genome, they are less immunogenic and safer than viral vectors. Non-viral vectors also allow the transfer of larger amounts of genetic material, providing possible benefits over the viral vector for genetic therapy applications. In addition, the simple design of non-viral vectors allows more economic and scalable production. Despite their advantages, non-viral vectors have lower transduction rates in cells than viral vectors.','{\"pat_doc\": 82.0, \"pub_alt\": 320.0, \"pub_doc\": 96.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_alt\": 29.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 2860602.0, \"pat_granted\": 10.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.8, \"pub_doc\": 0.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -408385.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ed67a738038bdc0b8d7a008e9a24bec5','05aa0de4a4917d54e102e40d1b76c9e1','fd6371fdffdf19bf1bf3ac9102b5acf9','2023-09-08 01:59:23','2023-10-28 23:31:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Autoclaving',12,'An autoclave is a machine used to carry out industrial and scientific processes requiring elevated temperature and pressure in relation to ambient pressure and/or temperature. Autoclaves are used before surgical procedures to perform sterilization and in the chemical industry to cure coatings and vulcanize rubber and for hydrothermal synthesis. Industrial autoclaves are used in industrial applications, especially in the manufacturing of composites. Many autoclaves are used to sterilize equipment and supplies by subjecting them to pressurized saturated steam at 121 Â°C for around 30-60 minutes at a pressure of 15 psi depending on the size of the load and the contents. The autoclave was invented by Charles Chamberland in 1879, although a precursor known as the steam digester was created by Denis Papin in 1679. The name comes from Greek auto-, ultimately meaning self, and Latin clavis meaning key, thus a self-locking device.','{\"pat_doc\": 134.0, \"pub_alt\": 12.0, \"pub_doc\": 248.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 799996.0, \"pat_granted\": 52.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -12.2, \"pub_doc\": -9.9, \"clinic_doc\": 1.2, \"grant_fund\": 113571.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('edee633a4d2239fdb290b4bc697ed193','00a65404eafa0410776576517426c1bf','c3708acc1ff6c957eeda159c8941d078','2023-09-08 02:55:47','2023-10-28 13:51:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Polymer-based Nanoparticles',12,'Polymer-based nanoparticles are tiny particles that are made from polymeric materials and have a diameter in the nanometer range. They are widely used in drug delivery, cancer therapy, imaging, and diagnostics, due to their unique and advantageous properties. Polymer-based nanoparticles offer several benefits, including controlled drug release, enhanced drug efficacy, and biocompatibility. They are also more stable and less toxic than traditional drug delivery vehicles such as liposomes. Polymer-based nanoparticles can be prepared using various fabrication methods such as emulsion polymerization, nanoprecipitation, and self-assembly. By manipulating the polymer chemistry and nanoparticle size, their properties can be tuned to optimize their performance for specific applications. Overall, polymer-based nanoparticles hold great promise for advancing medical technologies and improving patient outcomes.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 57.0, \"pub_doc\": 43.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.6, \"pub_doc\": 4.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -69931.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ee6845dcebe22e7b0c7b7abdf40c8fd1','6ad6b984db7a5bd574d38199653cd677','9e26cf59e38dc5ee0cf30259ac7c92ca','2023-09-05 20:05:34','2023-10-29 04:46:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Microfluidics',24,'Microfluidics refers to a system that manipulates a small amount of fluids using small channels with sizes ten to hundreds micrometres. It is a multidisciplinary field that involves molecular analysis, biodefence, molecular biology, and microelectronics. It has practical applications in the design of systems that process low volumes of fluids to achieve multiplexing, automation, and high-throughput screening. Microfluidics emerged in the beginning of the 1980s and is used in the development of inkjet printheads, DNA chips, lab-on-a-chip technology, micro-propulsion, and micro-thermal technologies. Typically, micro means one of the following features: â€¢ Small volumes â€¢ Small size â€¢ Low energy consumption â€¢ Microdomain effects. Typically microfluidic systems transport, mix, separate, or otherwise process fluids. Various applications rely on passive fluid control using capillary forces, in the form of capillary flow modifying elements, akin to flow resistors and flow accelerators.','{\"pat_doc\": 756.0, \"pub_alt\": 762.0, \"pub_doc\": 4401.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 552.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 14.0, \"grant_fund\": 258045855.0, \"pat_granted\": 241.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 28.6, \"pub_doc\": 144.5, \"clinic_doc\": 2.3, \"grant_fund\": -40950330.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ee6d880c5f7a34d6aa9fefdeace2c6bc','525ddc02deb579259414604666af7d2e','e910bc33478f3cb83e3ef258c7d92a6c','2023-09-08 02:02:55','2023-10-28 14:55:06','Healthcare','Fertility','Novel therapies','Gonadotropin-Releasing-Hormone Agonist',48,'A gonadotropin-releasing hormone agonist is a type of medication which affects gonadotropins and sex hormones. They are used for a variety of indications including in fertility medicine and to lower sex hormone levels in the treatment of hormone-sensitive cancers such as prostate cancer and breast cancer, certain gynecological disorders like heavy periods and endometriosis, high testosterone levels in women, early puberty in children, as a part of transgender hormone therapy, and to delay puberty in transgender youth among other uses. It is also used in the suppression of spontaneous ovulation as part of controlled ovarian hyperstimulation, an essential component in in IVF. GnRH agonists are given by injections into fat, as implants placed into fat, and as nasal sprays.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 21.0, \"pub_doc\": 1.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ee76165c0f509208bba0f37a9fd6991f','848c570f631dc66b6c71249b5532b80c','f53620dbd4935249cccf6fdb7d35b8cf','2023-09-04 19:36:20','2023-10-29 05:56:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Immunofluorescence',48,'Immunofluorescence is a technique used for light microscopy with a fluorescence microscope and is used primarily on biological samples. This technique uses the specificity of antibodies to their antigen to target fluorescent dyes to specific biomolecule targets within a cell, and therefore allows visualization of the distribution of the target molecule through the sample. The specific region an antibody recognizes on an antigen is called an epitope. There have been efforts in epitope mapping since many antibodies can bind the same epitope and levels of binding between antibodies that recognize the same epitope can vary. Additionally, the binding of the fluorophore to the antibody itself cannot interfere with the immunological specificity of the antibody or the binding capacity of its antigen. Immunofluorescence is a widely used example of immunostaining and is a specific example of immunohistochemistry.','{\"pat_doc\": 1436.0, \"pub_alt\": 4560.0, \"pub_doc\": 39956.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 995.0, \"clinic_alt\": 392.0, \"clinic_doc\": 170.0, \"grant_fund\": 384733226.0, \"pat_granted\": 520.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 29.2, \"pub_doc\": 619.2, \"clinic_doc\": 22.2, \"grant_fund\": -6312911.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ef1c4f4665cd36f65289a75ce1c23344','70acbc1819a41cd643bd80877d3bc5a4','79f0607dd327b272b64831fef13948f0','2023-09-08 09:12:08','2023-10-28 13:11:13','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Oncogenic signalling',36,'Oncogenic signaling refers to the changes that occur within cells that lead to uncontrolled cell growth and proliferation, ultimately resulting in cancer. These changes are typically driven by mutations that occur in genes that are involved in regulating cell growth and division. When these mutations occur, the affected gene becomes altered in a way that enhances its ability to promote cell growth and proliferation. This can occur through various mechanisms, including the activation of signaling pathways that regulate cell growth and division, or the alteration of the proteins that control the cell cycle. Ultimately, oncogenic signaling is a complex and multifaceted phenomenon that involves multiple genetic and biochemical factors working together to promote the growth and spread of cancer cells.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 410.0, \"pub_doc\": 110.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4385051.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 2.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 250205.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ef671919905657a0ac6462e1d38bace6','0aa43655311231d22f19c9a7f97c3577','69904542b990c5c24086b0dfa8c698cf','2023-09-05 22:50:45','2023-10-29 03:05:06','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','High-Throughput Screening',24,'High-throughput screening is a method for scientific experimentation especially used in drug discovery and relevant to the fields of biology, materials science and chemistry. Using robotics, data processing/control software, liquid handling devices, and sensitive detectors, high-throughput screening allows a researcher to quickly conduct millions of chemical, genetic, or pharmacological tests. Through this process one can quickly recognize active compounds, antibodies, or genes that modulate a particular biomolecular pathway. The results of these experiments provide starting points for drug design and for understanding the noninteraction or role of a particular location.','{\"pat_doc\": 611.0, \"pub_alt\": 447.0, \"pub_doc\": 2933.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 280.0, \"clinic_alt\": 17.0, \"clinic_doc\": 11.0, \"grant_fund\": 263917207.0, \"pat_granted\": 196.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.8, \"pub_doc\": 39.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.2, \"grant_fund\": -83628586.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('efbb87cba019a6f96061a936eb67a6db','f90e9c061ea63f3d762a3d1141314989','30640b686e5be896faa3d14ed6691346','2023-09-05 18:55:23','2023-10-29 05:31:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Biosensor',12,'A biosensor is an analytical device, used for the detection of a chemical substance, that combines a biological component with a physicochemical detector. The sensitive biological element, e.g. tissue, microorganisms, organelles, cell receptors, enzymes, antibodies, nucleic acids, etc., is a biologically derived material or biomimetic component that interacts with, binds with, or recognizes the analyte under study. The biologically sensitive elements can also be created by biological engineering. The transducer or the detector element, which transforms one signal into another one, works in a physicochemical way: optical, piezoelectric, electrochemical, electrochemiluminescence etc., resulting from the interaction of the analyte with the biological element, to easily measure and quantify. The biosensor reader device connects with the associated electronics or signal processors that are primarily responsible for the display of the results in a user-friendly way.','{\"pat_doc\": 2540.0, \"pub_alt\": 1506.0, \"pub_doc\": 9383.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 341.0, \"clinic_alt\": 12.0, \"clinic_doc\": 87.0, \"grant_fund\": 193119825.0, \"pat_granted\": 855.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 137.4, \"pub_doc\": 867.1, \"clinic_doc\": 19.0, \"grant_fund\": -13437491.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('efc0216d5e6407e67903fba6dbbaa455','18cad71c26158b8438ac86692a449576','7a95cc3a83815758eaf9c2eaa16704db','2023-09-05 21:55:52','2023-10-29 03:51:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Gene Therapy','Gene Editing',12,'Gene editing is the process of making specific changes to an organisms DNA using technologies such as CRISPR-Cas9. This technology allows scientists to make precise changes to DNA, including addition, deletion, or replacement of specific genes. It offers a powerful tool for disease research and treatment, as well as for increasing agricultural productivity and food security. Gene editing also raises ethical concerns, particularly in the area of human genome editing. While gene editing has enormous potential, it is important to consider the ethical implications and potential risks before using it in human clinical settings.','{\"pat_doc\": 1955.0, \"pub_alt\": 888.0, \"pub_doc\": 2321.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 292.0, \"clinic_alt\": 991.0, \"clinic_doc\": 20.0, \"grant_fund\": 187794572.0, \"pat_granted\": 506.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 332.4, \"pub_doc\": 204.6, \"clinic_doc\": 5.7, \"grant_fund\": -40539920.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('efd1a11be4175088173c02e3175a3850','62d3bf1b81cd240eca1b17ec53a45aed','9d56006f7b0bfb85db66d228f98a19d9','2023-09-08 00:57:05','2023-10-29 00:51:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Polymeric nanoparticles',36,'Polymeric nanoparticles are microscopic particles made up of polymers that have numerous applications, especially in the field of drug delivery and biomedical engineering. These particles, ranging from 1 to 1000 nanometers in size, can be designed in such a way that it can encapsulate drugs or other therapeutic agents and deliver them to the targeted site in a controlled manner. With characteristics such as their small size, large surface area, and the ability to protect the encapsulated content from degradation, they provide an excellent alternative to traditional drug delivery techniques. Polymeric nanoparticles have potential applications in cancer treatment, gene therapy, and imaging, among others. They have the potential to revolutionize the way we treat diseases and offer the possibility of more effective, less invasive therapeutic options.','{\"pat_doc\": 280.0, \"pub_alt\": 1000.0, \"pub_doc\": 2210.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 99.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 17574737.0, \"pat_granted\": 57.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.6, \"pub_doc\": 37.5, \"clinic_doc\": 0.2, \"grant_fund\": -3328898.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('efdd072a108683fb33ae572d2039f70d','92a972462fc449a3f071840dbe8b2742','392c6994beadcacc6139a1c22998f10f','2023-09-20 23:02:34','2023-10-28 18:26:13','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','spatial biology',48,'Spatial Biology is defined as the study of tissues within their own 2D or 3D context. It is the new frontier of molecular biology.\r\n\r\nConsider how GPS captures location coordinates within an area to create a map and track you within it. The same principle can be translated to spatial data on a cellular and molecular level.\r\n\r\nThrough this technology, we can help map the spatial architecture of a cell and how it talks to and interacts with its surroundings. Spatial biology is like being inside a tissue sample at a molecular level. It enables single-cell analysis. Through spatial biology tools, you are empowered to see things that are not possible by sequencing or any other technologies out there.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 407.0, \"pub_doc\": 137.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 22.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 16615786.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 26.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2600741.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f00718aa933ddeb81a9ffce93a1d17c6','123fff890be892fb84e8f950aecc8f54','e2436e9e1daec5dad6800e18965c31a2','2023-09-08 00:59:51','2023-10-28 16:01:19','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Monoclonal antibodies','Nanobodies',12,'Nanobodies are small antibody fragments with unique properties that offer promising potential for therapeutic and diagnostic applications. These fragments are derived from the immune system of camelids, such as camels and llamas, and consist of a single immunoglobulin domain that has a high affinity and specificity for its target. Nanobodies are much smaller and more stable than traditional antibodies, which allows them to penetrate deeper into tissues and reach difficult-to-access locations. Additionally, their small size and simplicity make it easier and cheaper to produce them at a large scale. Due to these advantages, nanobodies are being investigated for a variety of uses, including cancer therapy, imaging, and viral infections.','{\"pat_doc\": 172.0, \"pub_alt\": 780.0, \"pub_doc\": 461.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 51.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 17295324.0, \"pat_granted\": 35.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 40.8, \"pub_doc\": 70.3, \"clinic_doc\": 1.3, \"grant_fund\": -15354732.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f038b601303fe76d54ea583a41649ce1','68a4129044821c3a1d6386321b0e0003','71b92f66f40436e1ab511b3f211c9bd0','2023-09-08 02:35:10','2023-10-28 10:50:30','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Photonic Computing',36,'Optical computing or photonic computing uses light waves produced by lasers or incoherent sources for data processing, data storage or data communication for computing. For decades, photons have shown promise to enable a higher bandwidth than the electrons used in conventional computers. Most research projects focus on replacing current computer components with optical equivalents, resulting in an optical digital computer system processing binary data. This approach appears to offer the best short-term prospects for commercial optical computing, since optical components could be integrated into traditional computers to produce an optical-electronic hybrid. However, optoelectronic devices consume 30% of their energy converting electronic energy into photons and back; this conversion also slows the transmission of messages. All-optical computers eliminate the need for optical-electrical-optical conversions, thus reducing electrical power consumption.','{\"pat_doc\": 45.0, \"pub_alt\": 134.0, \"pub_doc\": 155.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 18.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 24982595.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 2.5, \"pub_doc\": 21.2, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 2638715.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f04dd1f99cd37cab7b9e509804b0883a','3c2d35cb47d7e664ff6a420c7371c3f4','13d8c275545d800af0151763656e07e5','2023-09-05 19:14:04','2023-10-29 05:11:15','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Quantum dot',24,'Quantum dots â€“ also called semiconductor nanocrystals, are semiconductor particles a few nanometres in size, having optical and electronic properties that differ from those of larger particles as a result of quantum mechanics. They are a central topic in nanotechnology and materials science. When the quantum dots are illuminated by UV light, an electron in the quantum dot can be excited to a state of higher energy. In the case of a semiconducting quantum dot, this process corresponds to the transition of an electron from the valence band to the conductance band. The excited electron can drop back into the valence band releasing its energy as light. This light emission is illustrated in the figure on the right.','{\"pat_doc\": 11620.0, \"pub_alt\": 568.0, \"pub_doc\": 16873.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 454.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 6.0, \"grant_fund\": 216995906.0, \"pat_granted\": 4611.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 59.8, \"pub_doc\": 330.7, \"clinic_doc\": 1.1, \"grant_fund\": -9612731.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f0c053daa3ec35257dc5e3f992fd9790','860562e383a8d17a8f172fa2f70cc8f9','aeef280b6e10fec919822406e149ebb2','2023-09-08 02:33:55','2023-10-28 14:16:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Lipid regulation',48,'Lipid regulation is the process of maintaining healthy levels of lipids in the body. Lipids are a type of molecule that includes fats, oils, and waxes. They are essential for many functions in the body, including providing energy and helping with the absorption of vitamins. However, too much or too little of certain types of lipids can lead to health problems. For example, high levels of cholesterol can increase the risk of heart disease, while low levels of essential fatty acids can lead to inflammation and other issues. Efficient lipid regulation requires a balanced diet and regular exercise, along with possible medication if needed.','{\"pat_doc\": 16.0, \"pub_alt\": 1137.0, \"pub_doc\": 244.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 32.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": 11044479.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": 5.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.4, \"grant_fund\": 1008259.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f1a163ce2f8ef595931963883b535778','ec9127faed503fab80aacc0c09e3bea4','1e154b56de35b3c06486dd7e904cade0','2023-09-05 22:15:33','2023-10-29 03:26:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','mRNA Therapy','mRNA Vaccines',36,'mRNA vaccines are a type of COVID-19 vaccine that provides immunity to the virus by introducing a small piece of messenger RNA (mRNA) into the body. This mRNA contains genetic instructions that direct cells to produce spike proteins, the same proteins that coat the surface of the coronavirus. Once the spike proteins are produced, the immune system recognizes them as foreign and develops antibodies to protect against future infections. mRNA vaccines are unique in that they do not contain weakened or dead virus particles, which makes them safer and easier to produce than traditional vaccines. They also have the potential to be rapidly developed and customized to address new variations of the virus. The two mRNA vaccines currently authorized for use in the United States are the Pfizer-BioNTech and Moderna vaccines.','{\"pat_doc\": 230.0, \"pub_alt\": 26339.0, \"pub_doc\": 3458.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 166.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1578.0, \"clinic_doc\": 82.0, \"grant_fund\": 126855178.0, \"pat_granted\": 19.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 39.4, \"pub_doc\": 427.8, \"clinic_doc\": 19.8, \"grant_fund\": 7035647.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f20ac6e294476eda8fe287685864e1a2','ee1ceea70d26f9efca309b5f07a6e479','77e5f6785bd7c9d4f3610b4ac830ad4e','2023-09-08 00:22:21','2023-10-29 01:51:11','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Electroporation',24,'Electroporation, or electropermeabilization, is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of the cell membrane, allowing chemicals, drugs, electrode arrays or DNA to be introduced into the cell. In microbiology, the process of electroporation is often used to transform bacteria, yeast, or plant protoplasts by introducing new coding DNA. If bacteria and plasmids are mixed together, the plasmids can be transferred into the bacteria after electroporation, though depending on what is being transferred, cell-penetrating peptides or CellSqueeze could also be used. Electroporation works by passing thousands of volts across suspended cells in an electroporation cuvette. Afterwards, the cells have to be handled carefully until they have had a chance to divide, producing new cells that contain reproduced plasmids.','{\"pat_doc\": 1332.0, \"pub_alt\": 688.0, \"pub_doc\": 1871.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 104.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1151.0, \"clinic_doc\": 125.0, \"grant_fund\": 39214481.0, \"pat_granted\": 369.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 72.4, \"pub_doc\": -22.4, \"clinic_doc\": 21.4, \"grant_fund\": -13946036.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f235c453716ac98324388388f3f6c82a','11ceddbe2884cfa304852a2ce17a1058','2483d5e44059b5dad528a46e9d77ee36','2023-09-08 00:49:58','2023-10-28 16:06:14','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Small molecules','antisense oligonucleotides',24,'Antisense oligonucleotides (ASOs) are short single-stranded pieces of DNA or RNA that bind to specific target mRNA molecules to regulate gene expression. ASOs are designed to silence a particular gene by preventing the translation of mRNA into protein, which can be useful in treating genetic disorders caused by overexpression or abnormal splicing of certain genes. ASOs are made up of a sequence complementary to the target mRNA, and once bound, they can recruit cellular machinery to degrade the mRNA or block its translation. ASOs are a promising therapeutic strategy for a variety of diseases, including cancer, viral infections, and genetic disorders.','{\"pat_doc\": 843.0, \"pub_alt\": 334.0, \"pub_doc\": 979.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 112.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 56686277.0, \"pat_granted\": 151.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 12.1, \"pub_doc\": 27.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -4641956.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f27c3cb611d90e9b5a8ca998b4157133','090feb32dfbba21cb999b8efda702d3f','2774276ce5bfae5027508a164fb2fcb7','2023-09-08 02:36:18','2023-10-28 22:01:17','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Gene delivery vector',48,'A gene delivery vector is a vehicle used to transfer genetic material into cells. These vectors are commonly used in gene therapy and biotechnology applications to alter the expression of genes in cells. The most commonly used gene delivery vectors are viruses, which can infect cells and insert genetic material into the host cells genome. Retroviruses, adenoviruses, and adeno-associated viruses are some examples of viral vectors. Non-viral vectors, such as liposomes and naked DNA, can also be used to deliver genes, but are generally less efficient than viral vectors. Gene delivery vectors have immense potential in the treatment of genetic disorders, cancer, and other diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 91.0, \"pub_alt\": 363.0, \"pub_doc\": 276.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 26.0, \"clinic_alt\": 12.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 14032008.0, \"pat_granted\": 21.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 5.7, \"pub_doc\": -4.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -650737.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f27c6d41e98fd8d06f5db1f88f74c28d','3be40ed2b8c2e8e952c0d1e6215ce7bc','d884de485418948cbb2562e1d885751d','2023-09-08 02:06:23','2023-09-08 02:06:23','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Addison\'s Disease',48,'Addison\'s disease, also known as primary adrenal insufficiency, is a rare long-term endocrine disorder characterized by inadequate production of the steroid hormones cortisol and aldosterone by the two outer layers of the cells of the adrenal glands, causing adrenal insufficiency. Symptoms generally come on slowly and insidiously and may include abdominal pain and gastrointestinal abnormalities, weakness, and weight loss. Darkening of the skin in certain areas may also occur. Under certain circumstances, an adrenal crisis may occur with low blood pressure, vomiting, lower back pain, and loss of consciousness. Mood changes may also occur. Rapid onset of symptoms indicates acute adrenal failure, which is a clinical emergency. An adrenal crisis can be triggered by stress, such as from an injury, surgery, or infection. Addison\'s disease arises from problems with the adrenal gland such that not enough of the steroid hormone cortisol and possibly aldosterone are produced.','{\"pat_doc\": 41.0, \"pub_alt\": 1437.0, \"pub_doc\": 259.0, \"deals_num\": 4.0, \"grant_doc\": 11.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 12.0, \"grant_fund\": 1591896.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 2.0, \"capital_raised\": 3.945}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": 1.5, \"clinic_doc\": 2.8, \"grant_fund\": -203023.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.806}'),('f29eaeff88834a1306e1214d26b84e80','8b3e02763472ad9cc815cfa5df7888cc','451ebb4679c1ff141207f279192eb1c8','2023-09-08 02:50:01','2023-10-28 21:26:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Bio-inspired material',48,'Bio-inspired materials refer to a class of materials inspired by natural designs and architectures found in living systems. These materials incorporate features such as self-assembly, hierarchical structure, and dynamic responsiveness. The idea behind bio-inspired materials is to take inspiration from nature to create advanced materials that have unique and valuable properties not found in conventional materials. Examples of such materials include self-healing polymers, super-strong spider silk-mimicking fibers, and high-performance ceramics based on the structure of seashells. Bio-inspired materials have the potential to lead to the development of new technologies and applications in fields such as medicine, construction, and robotics.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 189.0, \"pub_doc\": 179.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 51.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 39528457.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 4.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4564736.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f2d802cedf3f05269622d57c6c575907','41d7ff0d462e6a3d557069a37ea17023','9c4ba206250041cf1644bb291a643634','2023-09-05 18:58:16','2023-10-29 05:25:05','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Next-Generation Sequencing',12,'Massive parallel sequencing or massively parallel sequencing is any of several high-throughput approaches to DNA sequencing using the concept of massively parallel processing; it is also called next-generation sequencing or second-generation sequencing. Some of these technologies emerged between 1993 and 1998 and have been commercially available since 2005. These technologies use miniaturized and parallelized platforms for sequencing of 1 million to 43 billion short reads per instrument run. Many NGS platforms differ in engineering configurations and sequencing chemistry. They share the technical paradigm of massive parallel sequencing via spatially separated, clonally amplified DNA templates or single DNA molecules in a flow cell. This design is very different from that of Sanger sequencingâ€”also known as capillary sequencing or first-generation sequencingâ€”which is based on electrophoretic separation of chain-termination products produced in individual sequencing reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 107.0, \"pub_alt\": 809.0, \"pub_doc\": 6539.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 139.0, \"clinic_alt\": 58.0, \"clinic_doc\": 278.0, \"grant_fund\": 45013359.0, \"pat_granted\": 23.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.9, \"pub_doc\": 170.9, \"clinic_doc\": 72.6, \"grant_fund\": -38192044.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f332c9392ef2cebbd7f653fc3117ed50','fff9e1e5499bae01aa4fb0b484f21e1e','6a1c4a31986c97cfddf4de1bf91188d1','2023-09-05 21:08:55','2023-10-28 12:35:32','Electronics','Devices','Connectivity','Wearable devices',24,'Wearable technology is any technology that is designed to be used while worn. Common types of wearable technology include smartwatches and smartglasses. Wearable electronic devices are often close to or on the surface of the skin, where they detect, analyze, and transmit information such as vital signs, and/or ambient data and which allow in some cases immediate biofeedback to the wearer. Wearable devices such as activity trackers are an example of the Internet of Things, since \"things\" such as electronics, software, sensors, and connectivity are effectors that enable objects to exchange data through the internet with a manufacturer, operator, and/or other connected devices, without requiring human intervention. Wearable technology offers a wide range of possible uses, from communication and entertainment to improving health and fitness, however, there are worries about privacy and security because wearable devices have the ability to collect personal data.','{\"pat_doc\": 1636.0, \"pub_alt\": 4130.0, \"pub_doc\": 6973.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 263.0, \"clinic_alt\": 525.0, \"clinic_doc\": 261.0, \"grant_fund\": 160007323.0, \"pat_granted\": 587.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 43.4, \"pub_doc\": 482.3, \"clinic_doc\": 56.6, \"grant_fund\": 2342060.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f3606d11bac29dcd943d3490fabc39d5','bec6c7cf3a4a7344b41e74da4cea341b','2483d5e44059b5dad528a46e9d77ee36','2023-09-08 00:50:32','2023-10-29 01:06:12','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','antisense oligonucleotides',24,'Antisense oligonucleotides (ASOs) are short single-stranded pieces of DNA or RNA that bind to specific target mRNA molecules to regulate gene expression. ASOs are designed to silence a particular gene by preventing the translation of mRNA into protein, which can be useful in treating genetic disorders caused by overexpression or abnormal splicing of certain genes. ASOs are made up of a sequence complementary to the target mRNA, and once bound, they can recruit cellular machinery to degrade the mRNA or block its translation. ASOs are a promising therapeutic strategy for a variety of diseases, including cancer, viral infections, and genetic disorders.','{\"pat_doc\": 843.0, \"pub_alt\": 334.0, \"pub_doc\": 979.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 111.0, \"clinic_alt\": 2.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 56534000.0, \"pat_granted\": 151.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 12.5, \"pub_doc\": 28.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.6, \"grant_fund\": -4672412.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f3d2ac898a520f5cb27553e9f045d6e5','b2deca51e58703d27137669b972e2778','782fafb2d5b336b1996d7a1bfb56f465','2023-09-08 09:53:17','2023-10-28 20:06:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Mass spectrometry imaging',12,'Mass spectrometry imaging is a technique used in mass spectrometry to visualize the spatial distribution of molecules, as biomarkers, metabolites, peptides or proteins by their molecular masses. After collecting a mass spectrum at one spot, the sample is moved to reach another region, and so on, until the entire sample is scanned. By choosing a peak in the resulting spectra that corresponds to the compound of interest, the MS data is used to map its distribution across the sample. This results in pictures of the spatially resolved distribution of a compound pixel by pixel. Each data set contains a veritable gallery of pictures because any peak in each spectrum can be spatially mapped. Despite the fact that MSI has been generally considered a qualitative method, the signal generated by this technique is proportional to the relative abundance of the analyte. Therefore, quantification is possible, when its challenges are overcome.','{\"pat_doc\": 36.0, \"pub_alt\": 481.0, \"pub_doc\": 517.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 32.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 12739464.0, \"pat_granted\": 10.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 30.5, \"clinic_doc\": -0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2225201.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f470f3c25993d97c6d1a75ab1232277f','671b6a0797f6c4055d3d1b7f83353201','45aa22dbd0eeecd7a8f404b4dd4dc2cc','2023-09-08 02:41:52','2023-10-28 21:51:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Containment System',12,'A containment system is a structure or mechanism designed to isolate or control the spread of something potentially dangerous, such as disease, hazardous materials, or other substances. These systems come in various forms and sizes, depending on the nature of the threat and the environment they are used in. Examples can include sealed chambers, biosecurity measures, containment suits, or even something as simple as plastic barriers. The main goal of a containment system is to prevent the spread of the harmful agent to other areas or individuals, reducing the risk of harm and containing the situation until it can be properly addressed. They are particularly important in settings like laboratories, medical facilities, and industrial sites where potentially harmful materials or organisms may be present.','{\"pat_doc\": 279.0, \"pub_alt\": 22.0, \"pub_doc\": 68.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 3.0, \"grant_fund\": 116716.0, \"pat_granted\": 106.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -9.9, \"pub_doc\": 1.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.5, \"grant_fund\": -3150370.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f494adab1ff75af8830dd476efc2b6ed','fad21049eb39f44584479b92c65f1f69','1d60e7deb149c3b68658f6de8ff089a9','2023-09-20 20:26:19','2023-10-28 15:56:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Cushings Syndrome',48,'Cushings syndrome is a collection of signs and symptoms due to prolonged exposure to glucocorticoids such as cortisol. Signs and symptoms may include high blood pressure, abdominal obesity but with thin arms and legs, reddish stretch marks, a round red face due to facial plethora, a fat lump between the shoulders, weak muscles, weak bones, acne, and fragile skin that heals poorly. Women may have more hair and irregular menstruation. Occasionally there may be changes in mood, headaches, and a chronic feeling of tiredness. Cushings syndrome is caused by either excessive cortisol-like medication, such as prednisone, or a tumor that either produces or results in the production of excessive cortisol by the adrenal glands. Cases due to a pituitary adenoma are known as Cushings disease, which is the second most common cause of Cushings syndrome after medication. A number of other tumors, often referred to as ectopic due to their placement outside the pituitary, may also cause Cushings.','{\"pat_doc\": 5.0, \"pub_alt\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 18.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.1, \"pub_doc\": -1.4, \"clinic_doc\": -0.9, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f4ab3e03cbe5f8454c517e3920c1936f','5790a7bed485dce7c0fd1fac61020f51','f1911fd26254d1cbfba1808fbf1f3025','2023-09-08 01:53:10','2023-10-28 23:46:12','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Automated Systems, Control, & Data','Organ-on chip',48,'An organ-on-a-chip is a multi-channel 3-D microfluidic cell culture, integrated circuit that simulates the activities, mechanics and physiological response of an entire organ or an organ system. It constitutes the subject matter of significant biomedical engineering research, more precisely in bio-MEMS. The convergence of labs-on-chips and cell biology has permitted the study of human physiology in an organ-specific context. By acting as a more sophisticated in vitro approximation of complex tissues than standard cell culture, they provide the potential as an alternative to animal models for drug development and toxin testing. Although multiple publications claim to have translated organ functions onto this interface, the development of these microfluidic applications is still in its infancy. Organs-on-chips vary in design and approach between different researchers.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 1.0, \"pub_doc\": 1.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 0.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": -0.1, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f4dcf6fd5543d1cacc5a8650e4e38585','d893c2f2b521b2e83577694191a8eee4','8f14a9e350509c9aa1906cf48eaa7e87','2023-09-08 02:28:18','2023-10-28 22:11:09','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Water Purification System',48,'A water purification system is a device or process that removes impurities, contaminants, and other pollutants from water to make it safe for consumption. It typically involves several stages, such as sedimentation, filtration, disinfection, and sometimes reverse osmosis. These processes help to eliminate harmful bacteria, viruses, chemicals, and minerals while improving the taste and clarity of the water. Water purification systems may be utilized in households, hospitals, industries, and municipalities to ensure safe drinking water and maintain health and hygiene. The systems effectiveness depends on the quality of water being treated and the specific technology or technique used. Proper maintenance and regular monitoring are also critical to maintain its efficiency.','{\"pat_doc\": 2951.0, \"pub_alt\": 324.0, \"pub_doc\": 351.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 38.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 9915501.0, \"pat_granted\": 1681.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -46.1, \"pub_doc\": 9.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.4, \"grant_fund\": -471630.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f53dfc9e41881ef8bf42527671f19822','b6bd0e112ac4b84a4babc4781241a61c','eaab7bb973ab23e8de7a128f3cda6817','2023-09-08 00:05:29','2023-10-28 16:41:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Mesenchymal stromal cells',24,'Mesenchymal stem cells also known as mesenchymal stromal cells or medicinal signaling cells are multipotent stromal cells that can differentiate into a variety of cell types, including osteoblasts, chondrocytes, myocytes and adipocytes.','{\"pat_doc\": 141.0, \"pub_alt\": 452.0, \"pub_doc\": 2260.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 92.0, \"clinic_alt\": 190.0, \"clinic_doc\": 148.0, \"grant_fund\": 29233166.0, \"pat_granted\": 16.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": -47.2, \"clinic_doc\": 30.5, \"grant_fund\": -5473780.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f53f202003b6ed4417beb341b2d1f9d3','cef1c501111b2b4c4a7d99d59f4c45cc','61697279f5d40a0cf2ea206c3315fe94','2023-09-08 00:20:47','2023-10-28 16:31:16','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Chimeric antigen receptor T cells',48,'Chimeric antigen receptor (CAR) T cells, also known as CAR-T cells, are modified immune cells that are trained to seek and destroy cancer cells. CAR-T cells are created by extracting T cells, a type of white blood cell, from a patients blood and genetically engineering them to produce a special protein called a chimeric antigen receptor. This receptor allows the CAR-T cells to recognize and attack cancer cells that express specific markers on their surface. Once re-infused into the patients bloodstream, the CAR-T cells multiply and aggressively seek out and destroy cancer cells. CAR-T cell therapy has shown promising results in treating certain blood cancers, including leukemia and lymphoma, and is being studied for use in other types of cancer.','{\"pat_doc\": 469.0, \"pub_alt\": 451.0, \"pub_doc\": 876.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 43.0, \"clinic_alt\": 32.0, \"clinic_doc\": 160.0, \"grant_fund\": 43893057.0, \"pat_granted\": 62.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -18.9, \"pub_doc\": 3.4, \"clinic_doc\": 24.6, \"grant_fund\": -2849426.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f561fa64de39b22e2fd207cdddf706c6','f1c040e063712c5005b473ffb13588a1','cdaeb54e11180a1df70eb5bc5267c9f8','2023-09-08 09:46:18','2023-10-28 20:36:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Centrifugation',24,'Centrifugation is a mechanical process which involves the use of the centrifugal force to separate particles from a solution according to their size, shape, density, medium viscosity and rotor speed. The denser components of the mixture migrate away from the axis of the centrifuge, while the less dense components of the mixture migrate towards the axis. Chemists and biologists may increase the effective gravitational force of the test tube so that the precipitate will travel quickly and fully to the bottom of the tube. The remaining liquid that lies above the precipitate is called a supernatant or supernate. There is a correlation between the size and density of a particle and the rate that the particle separates from a heterogeneous mixture, when the only force applied is that of gravity. The larger the size and the larger the density of the particles, the faster they separate from the mixture.','{\"pat_doc\": 7999.0, \"pub_alt\": 488.0, \"pub_doc\": 5836.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 114.0, \"clinic_alt\": 29.0, \"clinic_doc\": 328.0, \"grant_fund\": 17072991.0, \"pat_granted\": 4082.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -24.6, \"pub_doc\": 42.5, \"clinic_doc\": 50.1, \"grant_fund\": -9080944.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f5b7e1d6002dc45c0b8e7c80dabacbf6','5a0a5b9065b639feb58f1b4e34dc9f7c','9c4ba206250041cf1644bb291a643634','2023-09-05 18:59:35','2023-10-29 05:21:13','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Next-Generation Sequencing',12,'Massive parallel sequencing or massively parallel sequencing is any of several high-throughput approaches to DNA sequencing using the concept of massively parallel processing; it is also called next-generation sequencing or second-generation sequencing. Some of these technologies emerged between 1993 and 1998 and have been commercially available since 2005. These technologies use miniaturized and parallelized platforms for sequencing of 1 million to 43 billion short reads per instrument run. Many NGS platforms differ in engineering configurations and sequencing chemistry. They share the technical paradigm of massive parallel sequencing via spatially separated, clonally amplified DNA templates or single DNA molecules in a flow cell. This design is very different from that of Sanger sequencingâ€”also known as capillary sequencing or first-generation sequencingâ€”which is based on electrophoretic separation of chain-termination products produced in individual sequencing reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 107.0, \"pub_alt\": 809.0, \"pub_doc\": 6539.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 139.0, \"clinic_alt\": 58.0, \"clinic_doc\": 278.0, \"grant_fund\": 45013359.0, \"pat_granted\": 23.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -1.9, \"pub_doc\": 170.9, \"clinic_doc\": 72.6, \"grant_fund\": -38192044.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f5c6480c9f9c5e8b6230157824820503','5e047db7e10164d6ec0e89c2fe69a4b9','589b84d604aa424bb142db78b62d89e3','2023-09-08 02:00:38','2023-10-28 23:26:14','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Electrophoresis',36,'Protein electrophoresis is a method for analysing the proteins in a fluid or an extract. The electrophoresis may be performed with a small volume of sample in a number of alternative ways with or without a supporting medium: SDS polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis, free-flow electrophoresis, electrofocusing, isotachophoresis, affinity electrophoresis, immunoelectrophoresis, counterelectrophoresis, and capillary electrophoresis. Each method has many variations with individual advantages and limitations. Gel electrophoresis is often performed in combination with electroblotting immunoblotting to give additional information about a specific protein. Because of practical limitations, protein electrophoresis is generally not suited as a preparative method.','{\"pat_doc\": 71.0, \"pub_alt\": 230.0, \"pub_doc\": 642.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 43.0, \"clinic_doc\": 25.0, \"grant_fund\": 869931.0, \"pat_granted\": 40.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 3.1, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -94204.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f5fd30ced9d9c35fc17913cf3d8d19d2','8c13cdcd2f46fbd04ad49b8164252967','b347f7200b8aff24464a347c263147e9','2023-09-08 09:25:33','2023-10-28 21:06:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Filtration',24,'Filtration is a physical separation process that separates solid matter and fluid from a mixture using a filter medium that has a complex structure through which only the fluid can pass. Solid particles that cannot pass through the filter medium are described as oversize and the fluid that passes through is called the filtrate. Oversize particles may form a filter cake on top of the filter and may also block the filter lattice, preventing the fluid phase from crossing the filter, known as blinding. The size of the largest particles that can successfully pass through a filter is called the effective pore size of that filter. The separation of solid and fluid is imperfect; solids will be contaminated with some fluid and filtrate will contain fine particles. Filtration occurs both in nature and in engineered systems; there are biological, geological, and industrial forms.','{\"pat_doc\": 121267.0, \"pub_alt\": 26339.0, \"pub_doc\": 84355.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1969.0, \"clinic_alt\": 592.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2505.0, \"grant_fund\": 662536664.0, \"pat_granted\": 85050.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 616.9, \"pub_doc\": 2964.5, \"clinic_doc\": 373.4, \"grant_fund\": -100190796.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f614006a353c5a7959afd9b8a1784db0','0b7aa8ee981ba0fe14ccf04dee81c1ad','62899d4dc41a7b9eb6091bb110aca523','2023-09-05 19:51:05','2023-10-29 04:55:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Tissue and Cell Culture','Tissue Engineering',12,'Tissue engineering is a biomedical engineering discipline that uses a combination of cells, engineering, materials methods, and suitable biochemical and physicochemical factors to restore, maintain, improve, or replace different types of biological tissues. Tissue engineering often involves the use of cells placed on tissue scaffolds in the formation of new viable tissue for a medical purpose but is not limited to applications involving cells and tissue scaffolds. While it was once categorized as a sub-field of biomaterials, having grown in scope and importance it can be considered as a field of its own. While most definitions of tissue engineering cover a broad range of applications, in practice the term is closely associated with applications that repair or replace portions of or whole tissues. Often, the tissues involved require certain mechanical and structural properties for proper functioning.','{\"pat_doc\": 973.0, \"pub_alt\": 641.0, \"pub_doc\": 6864.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 235.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 47.0, \"grant_fund\": 99913393.0, \"pat_granted\": 372.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.9, \"pub_doc\": 306.5, \"clinic_doc\": 10.5, \"grant_fund\": -54494104.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f6240fdc7cfc959e882eaa0f1892e6ee','b78f1ff4779c63394e7882c5ca767bf9','5f9f631521aff2090e15184e37181d22','2023-09-04 19:03:15','2023-10-29 06:20:05','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Immunohistochemistry',24,'Immunohistochemistry is the most common application of immunostaining. It involves the process of selectively identifying antigens in cells of a tissue section by exploiting the principle of antibodies binding specifically to antigens in biological tissues. IHC takes its name from the roots \"immuno\", in reference to antibodies used in the procedure, and \"histo\", meaning tissue. Albert Coons conceptualized and first implemented the procedure in 1941. Visualising an antibody-antigen interaction can be accomplished in a number of ways, mainly either of the following: â€¢ Chromogenic immunohistochemistry, wherein an antibody is conjugated to an enzyme, such as peroxidase, that can catalyse a colour-producing reaction. â€¢ Immunofluorescence, where the antibody is tagged to a fluorophore, such as fluorescein or rhodamine. Immunohistochemical staining is widely used in the diagnosis of abnormal cells such as those found in cancerous tumors.','{\"pat_doc\": 379.0, \"pub_alt\": 28733.0, \"pub_doc\": 30861.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 650.0, \"clinic_alt\": 553.0, \"clinic_doc\": 653.0, \"grant_fund\": 173900871.0, \"pat_granted\": 127.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 17.1, \"pub_doc\": -408.2, \"clinic_doc\": 134.5, \"grant_fund\": -28858320.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f64c3bc57c81631e8a2237e949057d17','b44ddb1f06c55c8a655b7e35627c4216','eb670a907e9a4e83aa692353515a741c','2023-09-05 19:20:24','2023-10-29 05:06:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Emulsion',36,'An emulsion is a mixture of two or more liquids that are normally immiscible owing to liquid-liquid phase separation. Emulsions are part of a more general class of two-phase systems of matter called colloids. Although the terms colloid and emulsion are sometimes used interchangeably, emulsion should be used when both phases, dispersed and continuous, are liquids. In an emulsion, one liquid is dispersed in the other. Examples of emulsions include vinaigrettes, homogenized milk, liquid biomolecular condensates, and some cutting fluids for metal working. Two liquids can form different types of emulsions. As an example, oil and water can form, first, an oil-in-water emulsion, in which the oil is the dispersed phase, and water is the continuous phase. Second, they can form a water-in-oil emulsion, in which water is the dispersed phase and oil is the continuous phase. Multiple emulsions are also possible, including a \"water-in-oil-in-water\" emulsion and an \"oil-in-water-in-oil\" emulsion.','{\"pat_doc\": 57375.0, \"pub_alt\": 16313.0, \"pub_doc\": 29608.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 749.0, \"clinic_alt\": 588.0, \"clinic_doc\": 235.0, \"grant_fund\": 179735574.0, \"pat_granted\": 22792.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 8.0, \"pub_doc\": 587.2, \"clinic_doc\": 18.4, \"grant_fund\": -8503567.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f6652fc4d5288e55febb7f8ad70e68c8','4d2d0b15ee17780893b8c9e0ae59e835','005e837817c21a0393b99843cbfee450','2023-09-08 01:10:59','2023-10-28 15:36:18','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Acromegaly',12,'Acromegaly is a disorder that results in excess growth of certain parts of the human body. It is caused by excess growth hormone after the growth plates have closed. The initial symptom is typically enlargement of the hands and feet. There may also be an enlargement of the forehead, jaw, and nose. Other symptoms may include joint pain, thicker skin, deepening of the voice, headaches, and problems with vision. Complications of the disease may include type 2 diabetes, sleep apnea, and high blood pressure.','{\"pat_doc\": 18.0, \"pub_alt\": 49.0, \"pub_doc\": 587.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 21.0, \"clinic_doc\": 52.0, \"grant_fund\": 1104020.0, \"pat_granted\": 6.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.2, \"pub_doc\": -4.4, \"clinic_doc\": 10.7, \"grant_fund\": 169355.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f68581b3437535d9dbb3d5228cb6b1a4','2f412f6d08233ef2ee97b503f7c210fd','bc432a22793de3677b1dacfb29fc2326','2023-09-08 09:49:36','2023-10-28 20:21:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','SDS-PAGE',36,'SDS-PAGE is a discontinuous electrophoretic system developed by Ulrich K. Laemmli which is commonly used as a method to separate proteins with molecular masses between 5 and 250 kDa. The combined use of sodium dodecyl sulfate and polyacrylamide gel eliminates the influence of structure and charge, and proteins are separated by differences in their size. At least up to 2012, the publication describing it was the most frequently cited paper by a single author, and the second most cited overall.','{\"pat_doc\": 215.0, \"pub_alt\": 606.0, \"pub_doc\": 4160.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 67.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": 5442242.0, \"pat_granted\": 88.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -3.7, \"pub_doc\": -42.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.1, \"grant_fund\": -1973486.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f6bd86ff430eed52e077694e7556ae16','c4e49c5cbafa19cbaf0a14bd5ddcb651','0b71467e6421c543859a81713b7406ad','2023-09-08 09:43:15','2023-10-28 20:41:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','sample preparation',24,'In analytical chemistry, sample preparation refers to the ways in which a sample is treated prior to its analyses. Preparation is a very important step in most analytical techniques, because the techniques are often not responsive to the analyte in its in-situ form, or the results are distorted by interfering species. Sample preparation may involve dissolution, extraction, reaction with some chemical species, pulverizing, treatment with a chelating agent, masking, filtering, dilution, sub-sampling or many other techniques. Treatment is done to prepare the sample into a form ready for analysis by specified analytical equipment. Sample preparation could involve: crushing and dissolution, chemical digestion with acid or alkali, sample extraction, sample clean up and sample pre-concentration.','{\"pat_doc\": 5126.0, \"pub_alt\": 2092.0, \"pub_doc\": 7411.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 376.0, \"clinic_alt\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 48.0, \"grant_fund\": 131397289.0, \"pat_granted\": 2432.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 189.7, \"pub_doc\": 74.0, \"clinic_doc\": 8.5, \"grant_fund\": -48834204.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f71cf7f77926b6342fdf23d797744a8e','d3549b81bb39a9ac922f45ac120eb0cc','3da09264ab4cd2d03a36df24f5f30506','2023-09-08 09:48:28','2023-10-28 20:26:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry',24,'Inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry is a type of mass spectrometry that uses an inductively coupled plasma to ionize the sample. It atomizes the sample and creates atomic and small polyatomic ions, which are then detected. It is known and used for its ability to detect metals and several non-metals in liquid samples at very low concentrations. It can detect different isotopes of the same element, which makes it a versatile tool in isotopic labeling. Compared to atomic absorption spectroscopy, ICP-MS has greater speed, precision, and sensitivity. However, compared with other types of mass spectrometry, such as thermal ionization mass spectrometry and glow discharge mass spectrometry, ICP-MS introduces many interfering species: argon from the plasma, component gases of air that leak through the cone orifices, and contamination from glassware and the cones.','{\"pat_doc\": 216.0, \"pub_alt\": 1281.0, \"pub_doc\": 2834.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 57.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 10.0, \"grant_fund\": 14435599.0, \"pat_granted\": 57.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 10.7, \"pub_doc\": 21.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.6, \"grant_fund\": -270284.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f73facbe0d740aafffd952cb2350b54d','8445e498b5c8e24b28f8fe85d68e76af','33b4678f6b096b9a11757bc96a56f980','2023-09-08 01:16:53','2023-10-29 00:21:18','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','Directed Evolution',24,'Directed evolution is a method used in protein engineering that mimics the process of natural selection to steer proteins or nucleic acids toward a user-defined goal. It consists of subjecting a gene to iterative rounds of mutagenesis, selection and amplification. It can be performed in vivo, or in vitro. Directed evolution is used both for protein engineering as an alternative to rationally designing modified proteins, as well as for experimental evolution studies of fundamental evolutionary principles in a controlled, laboratory environment.','{\"pat_doc\": 322.0, \"pub_alt\": 720.0, \"pub_doc\": 940.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 181.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 78473185.0, \"pat_granted\": 106.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 25.3, \"pub_doc\": 7.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -10443235.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f7756e4c1a6def7852a08d5c413367fa','3c51150cb4d6d0c2bbf77b25519de393','6de0c721cf3eb4c836d007670b4c702d','2023-09-08 00:28:32','2023-10-29 01:36:15','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Cell Detection and Analysis','Live Cell Imaging',12,'Live cell imaging is the study of living cells using time-lapse microscopy. It is used by scientists to obtain a better understanding of biological function through the study of cellular dynamics. Live cell imaging was pioneered in first decade of the 21th century. One of the first time-lapse microcinematographic films of cells ever made was made by Julius Ries, showing the fertilization and development of the sea urchin egg. Since then, several microscopy methods have been developed which allow researchers to study living cells in greater detail with less effort. A newer type of imaging utilizing quantum dots have been used as they are shown to be more stable. The development of holotomographic microscopy has disregarded phototoxicity and other staining-derived disadvantages by implementing digital staining based on cells refractive index.','{\"pat_doc\": 15.0, \"pub_alt\": 61.0, \"pub_doc\": 406.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 64.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 35489581.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.4, \"pub_doc\": -16.3, \"clinic_doc\": -0.2, \"grant_fund\": -12558862.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f797a6f5d7101eb750943be63702466d','3ac2ba09e7b52bbe721ad2f6f07c0d4c','efc072896d951f3550e7d73c38f3d42e','2023-09-08 09:56:42','2023-10-28 19:51:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Microscale thermophoresis',48,'Microscale thermophoresis is a technology for the interaction analysis of biomolecules. Microscale thermophoresis is the directed movement of particles in a microscopic temperature gradient. Any change of the hydration shell of biomolecules due to changes in their structure/conformation results in a relative change of the movement along the temperature gradient and is used to determine binding affinities. MST allows measurement of interactions directly in solution without the need of immobilization to a surface.','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_alt\": 361.0, \"pub_doc\": 708.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 36.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 6562007.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.0, \"pub_doc\": 10.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -485048.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f7cbaf20283d08cea3391d16a49c9537','86bfc1d6ea6ada0972bb4ebd56d88ad7','8f2884ac2f89f569ae690ad0aa820ccc','2023-09-08 01:08:24','2023-10-28 15:41:15','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Tumor-associated antigens',36,'Tumor-associated antigens (TAAs) are proteins that are present in cancer cells but not in normal cells or are expressed at higher levels in tumors than in healthy tissues. These antigens may be recognized by the immune system as foreign and trigger an immune response against the cancer cells. TAAs are being studied for their potential use in cancer vaccines and immunotherapy. However, many TAAs are also present in normal tissues, which can lead to side effects when targeted by cancer treatments. Therefore, the specificity of TAAs and their potential impact on healthy tissues must be carefully evaluated before their use in clinical settings.','{\"pat_doc\": 270.0, \"pub_alt\": 289.0, \"pub_doc\": 818.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 43.0, \"clinic_alt\": 504.0, \"clinic_doc\": 30.0, \"grant_fund\": 35651181.0, \"pat_granted\": 41.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -4.6, \"pub_doc\": 27.2, \"clinic_doc\": 6.4, \"grant_fund\": -3038596.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f84582eaabb2c06ace8cb26e502c0f47','5c2546ad4bcf61666dc6e1c3462112a1','63620f5d0220fdda22b46d43a342534f','2023-09-08 01:14:21','2023-10-29 00:26:20','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','Phage Display',12,'Phage display is a laboratory technique for the study of proteinâ€“protein, proteinâ€“peptide, and proteinâ€“DNA interactions that uses bacteriophages to connect proteins with the genetic information that encodes them. In this technique, a gene encoding a protein of interest is inserted into a phage coat protein gene, causing the phage to \"display\" the protein on its outside while containing the gene for the protein on its inside, resulting in a connection between genotype and phenotype. These displaying phages can then be screened against other proteins, peptides or DNA sequences, in order to detect interaction between the displayed protein and those other molecules. In this way, large libraries of proteins can be screened and amplified in a process called in vitro selection, which is analogous to natural selection. The most common bacteriophages used in phage display are M13 and fd filamentous phage, though T4, T7, and Î» phage have also been used.','{\"pat_doc\": 204.0, \"pub_alt\": 308.0, \"pub_doc\": 488.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 40.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 11921029.0, \"pat_granted\": 65.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 23.5, \"pub_doc\": 24.6, \"clinic_doc\": -0.3, \"grant_fund\": -13328661.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f84d5d81d9bc1930b650858b2cba0b24','dc11d80fc0114b8dfe9fa719a1d68ad7','a0ec7ffe04c046d0f8469b5de966ddfa','2023-09-04 18:54:26','2023-10-29 06:35:05','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Flow Cytometry',12,'Flow cytometry is a technique used to detect and measure physical and chemical characteristics of a population of cells or particles. In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument. The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components. Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths. Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer. Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials. Uses for flow cytometry include: â€¢ Cell counting â€¢ Cell sorting â€¢ Determining cell characteristics and function â€¢ Detecting microorganisms â€¢ Biomarker detection â€¢ Protein engineering detection â€¢ Diagnosis of health disorders such as blood cancers â€¢ Measuring genome size.','{\"pat_doc\": 564.0, \"pub_alt\": 7800.0, \"pub_doc\": 15615.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 380.0, \"clinic_alt\": 590.0, \"clinic_doc\": 555.0, \"grant_fund\": 116938725.0, \"pat_granted\": 170.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.1, \"pub_doc\": -433.8, \"clinic_doc\": 137.2, \"grant_fund\": -49967547.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f8762bebc04565a057488c976cf16de1','bf8b4feb522a72f79560c81cf6dc8720','62899d4dc41a7b9eb6091bb110aca523','2023-09-05 19:55:00','2023-10-29 04:51:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','Tissue Engineering',36,'Tissue engineering is a biomedical engineering discipline that uses a combination of cells, engineering, materials methods, and suitable biochemical and physicochemical factors to restore, maintain, improve, or replace different types of biological tissues. Tissue engineering often involves the use of cells placed on tissue scaffolds in the formation of new viable tissue for a medical purpose but is not limited to applications involving cells and tissue scaffolds. While it was once categorized as a sub-field of biomaterials, having grown in scope and importance it can be considered as a field of its own. While most definitions of tissue engineering cover a broad range of applications, in practice the term is closely associated with applications that repair or replace portions of or whole tissues. Often, the tissues involved require certain mechanical and structural properties for proper functioning.','{\"pat_doc\": 3048.0, \"pub_alt\": 641.0, \"pub_doc\": 20034.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1194.0, \"clinic_alt\": 16.0, \"clinic_doc\": 66.0, \"grant_fund\": 462506532.0, \"pat_granted\": 1177.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.9, \"pub_doc\": 306.5, \"clinic_doc\": 10.5, \"grant_fund\": -54494104.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f8abc9e7f1a2e81de601d5becf6c7f5a','bfef6514b60e4c25c2f8497aa216e34c','075f3ab037592e82b84202abe07674ba','2023-09-08 02:51:12','2023-10-28 10:45:32','Electronics','Devices','Next Generation Computers','Universal Quantum computer',12,'A quantum Turing machine or universal quantum computer is an abstract machine used to model the effects of a quantum computer. It provides a simple model that captures all of the power of quantum computationâ€”that is, any quantum algorithm can be expressed formally as a particular quantum Turing machine. However, the computationally equivalent quantum circuit is a more common model. Quantum Turing machines can be related to classical and probabilistic Turing machines in a framework based on transition matrices. That is, a matrix can be specified whose product with the matrix representing a classical or probabilistic machine provides the quantum probability matrix representing the quantum machine. This was shown by Lance Fortnow.','{\"pat_doc\": 1.0, \"pub_alt\": 134.0, \"pub_doc\": 47.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4738626.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.5, \"pub_doc\": 2.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -8025713.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f8bb74b11a5f790f16a651f6503aa718','7f22a30b9d31980762db19938046f3e9','5762d74cf97f0e57d03def69845fe3e1','2023-09-08 02:43:41','2023-10-28 21:46:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Enzyme Technology',24,'Enzyme Technology involves the use of enzymes to carry out specific chemical reactions, useful in various industries such as food, pharmaceuticals, and the environment. Enzymes are biocatalysts that facilitate chemical reactions without being consumed in the process. They are highly specific and can work under mild conditions, making them eco-friendly and efficient. Enzyme Technology includes the optimization of enzyme-catalyzed reactions, engineering of new enzymes, and production of enzymes through fermentation processes. The applications of enzyme technology are vast, including the production of biofuels, detergents, food additives, and medications. The use of enzyme technology can also lead to more sustainable processes, reduced waste, and decreased environmental impact in industries.','{\"pat_doc\": 54.0, \"pub_alt\": 26.0, \"pub_doc\": 93.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 4945715.0, \"pat_granted\": 13.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -7.1, \"pub_doc\": 7.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -310772.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f8f40ecc826a1bb06b38bb2320f5097b','bf8b4feb522a72f79560c81cf6dc8720','62899d4dc41a7b9eb6091bb110aca523','2023-09-05 19:55:00','2023-10-29 04:51:12','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','Tissue Engineering',12,'Tissue engineering is a biomedical engineering discipline that uses a combination of cells, engineering, materials methods, and suitable biochemical and physicochemical factors to restore, maintain, improve, or replace different types of biological tissues. Tissue engineering often involves the use of cells placed on tissue scaffolds in the formation of new viable tissue for a medical purpose but is not limited to applications involving cells and tissue scaffolds. While it was once categorized as a sub-field of biomaterials, having grown in scope and importance it can be considered as a field of its own. While most definitions of tissue engineering cover a broad range of applications, in practice the term is closely associated with applications that repair or replace portions of or whole tissues. Often, the tissues involved require certain mechanical and structural properties for proper functioning.','{\"pat_doc\": 973.0, \"pub_alt\": 641.0, \"pub_doc\": 6864.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 235.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 47.0, \"grant_fund\": 99913393.0, \"pat_granted\": 372.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 36.9, \"pub_doc\": 306.5, \"clinic_doc\": 10.5, \"grant_fund\": -54494104.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f91e13a4971d6734005b9cc6c8af77cd','cb426d718331f51011984ab644408b3c','b10c3992ebb8f463a7fad145792de043','2023-09-08 09:16:19','2023-10-28 21:11:12','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Liquid Chromatography',36,'Liquid chromatography (LC) is a widely used separation technique to isolate, identify, and quantify various components within a mixture. It works on the principle of differential partitioning of sample components between a mobile phase (liquid) and stationary phase (solid or liquid). The sample is introduced into the mobile phase, which is pumped through the stationary phase packed inside a column. The interaction between sample components and stationary phase determines the retention time and separation of individual components. Various types of liquid chromatography, such as high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC), ultra-high-performance liquid chromatography (UHPLC), and size exclusion chromatography (SEC), are available to separate different types of analytes based on their physicochemical properties. LC is widely used in the pharmaceutical, biotechnology, food, and environmental testing industries due to its high resolution, accuracy, and sensitivity.','{\"pat_doc\": 12183.0, \"pub_alt\": 1833.0, \"pub_doc\": 49343.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 901.0, \"clinic_alt\": 68.0, \"clinic_doc\": 402.0, \"grant_fund\": 188159531.0, \"pat_granted\": 4374.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 443.5, \"pub_doc\": 370.3, \"clinic_doc\": 60.7, \"grant_fund\": -16962097.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f920b5ac8cedab7064f3ac3820238d2f','e1fcd3b18c69467f559b50097886167b','a2b94a39823e51d1e7bb659a1415d3c3','2023-09-08 00:31:20','2023-10-29 01:26:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Biocatalysis',48,'Biocatalysis refers to the use of living systems or their parts to speed up chemical reactions. In biocatalytic processes, natural catalysts, such as enzymes, perform chemical transformations on organic compounds. Both enzymes that have been more or less isolated and enzymes still residing inside living cells are employed for this task. Modern biotechnology, specifically directed evolution, has made the production of modified or non-natural enzymes possible. This has enabled the development of enzymes that can catalyze novel small molecule transformations that may be difficult or impossible using classical synthetic organic chemistry. Utilizing natural or modified enzymes to perform organic synthesis is termed chemoenzymatic synthesis; the reactions performed by the enzyme are classified as chemoenzymatic reactions.','{\"pat_doc\": 574.0, \"pub_alt\": 743.0, \"pub_doc\": 2621.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 321.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 145898224.0, \"pat_granted\": 200.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 32.8, \"pub_doc\": 44.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 8603575.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f93760e70ce64c8e5f7d900fd5ee9d4e','3c24254d6c0d4e4249ab4b441e17dc83','abbcb6a1638f63a5747e204b798f4ec2','2023-09-08 00:41:06','2023-10-29 01:11:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Synthetic Biology','DNA Synthesis',36,'DNA synthesis is the natural or artificial creation of deoxyribonucleic acid molecules. DNA is a macromolecule made up of nucleotide units, which are linked by covalent bonds and hydrogen bonds, in a repeating structure. DNA synthesis occurs when these nucleotide units are joined to form DNA; this can occur artificially or naturally. Nucleotide units are made up of a nitrogenous base, pentose sugar and phosphate group. Each unit is joined when a covalent bond forms between its phosphate group and the pentose sugar of the next nucleotide, forming a sugar-phosphate backbone. DNA is a complementary, double stranded structure as specific base pairing occurs naturally when hydrogen bonds form between the nucleotide bases. There are several different definitions for DNA synthesis: it can refer to DNA replication - DNA biosynthesis, polymerase chain reaction - enzymatic DNA synthesis or gene synthesis - physically creating artificial gene sequences.','{\"pat_doc\": 496.0, \"pub_alt\": 860.0, \"pub_doc\": 2660.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 204.0, \"clinic_alt\": 55.0, \"clinic_doc\": 60.0, \"grant_fund\": 112797775.0, \"pat_granted\": 130.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.0, \"pub_doc\": -7.9, \"clinic_doc\": 8.6, \"grant_fund\": -10466344.6, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f9425726b5a6fbee4cda7e5c542c1ba4','8f5e65940c2b32c65f99c25d9fea77ca','e9ee3da8c5950eddf30d7e6a8d175388','2023-09-08 00:36:35','2023-10-29 01:20:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Engineering',48,'Protein engineering is the process of developing useful or valuable proteins through the design and production of unnatural polypeptides, often by altering amino acid sequences found in nature. It is a young discipline, with much research taking place into the understanding of protein folding and recognition for protein design principles. It has been used to improve the function of many enzymes for industrial catalysis. It is also a product and services market, with an estimated value of $168 billion by 2017. There are two general strategies for protein engineering: rational protein design and directed evolution. These methods are not mutually exclusive; researchers will often apply both. In the future, more detailed knowledge of protein structure and function, and advances in high-throughput screening, may greatly expand the abilities of protein engineering.','{\"pat_doc\": 529.0, \"pub_alt\": 1312.0, \"pub_doc\": 2569.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 600.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 353011452.0, \"pat_granted\": 169.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.1, \"pub_doc\": 48.3, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -16048598.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f9436f38f83eb6a1575c734088ed1530','3cd9bdd88ba7ae8b9d89cbab89c2b25b','461ca981d4ebaba8ec09f7fd419f33b2','2023-09-08 01:09:47','2023-10-29 00:36:23','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Formulation','Solid dispersion',24,'Solid dispersion is a technique used in the pharmaceutical industry to improve the solubility and bioavailability of poorly water-soluble drugs. It involves the preparation of a solid mixture of a drug with a hydrophilic carrier, such as a polymer or a surfactant, where the drug is dispersed in a molecularly or colloidal form in the carrier matrix. The resulting system exhibits an increased surface area of the drug particles and facilitates the formation of supersaturated solutions upon dissolution in aqueous media, leading to enhanced drug absorption and better therapeutic efficacy. Solid dispersion offers several advantages over traditional formulations, including reduced drug doses, improved patient compliance, and lowered production costs. Despite its potential benefits, the design and optimization of solid dispersions require careful consideration of various factors, such as drug-carrier interactions, drug loading, and stability.','{\"pat_doc\": 1218.0, \"pub_alt\": 347.0, \"pub_doc\": 1051.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 9.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 9.0, \"grant_fund\": 2043835.0, \"pat_granted\": 282.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 29.1, \"pub_doc\": 19.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.9, \"grant_fund\": -1206355.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f95b465f5ea16996da113d9e00ec950d','7c86b2353e10d37f742b8e8282b894cd','87aeff98505d298c3f2a7150e8c8ae7d','2023-09-05 21:14:26','2023-10-29 04:11:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Mxene',36,'In materials science, MXenes are a class of two-dimensional inorganic compounds, that consist of atomically thin layers of transition metal carbides, nitrides, or carbonitrides. MXenes accept a variety of hydrophilic terminations. MXenes were first reported in 2012.','{\"pat_doc\": 3630.0, \"pub_alt\": 224.0, \"pub_doc\": 11459.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 137.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 49363914.0, \"pat_granted\": 1125.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 348.8, \"pub_doc\": 1206.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 246192.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f96cda8c6ee2cadaa0b3950da960b72b','00a65404eafa0410776576517426c1bf','c3708acc1ff6c957eeda159c8941d078','2023-09-08 02:55:47','2023-10-28 13:51:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Polymer-based Nanoparticles',24,'Polymer-based nanoparticles are tiny particles that are made from polymeric materials and have a diameter in the nanometer range. They are widely used in drug delivery, cancer therapy, imaging, and diagnostics, due to their unique and advantageous properties. Polymer-based nanoparticles offer several benefits, including controlled drug release, enhanced drug efficacy, and biocompatibility. They are also more stable and less toxic than traditional drug delivery vehicles such as liposomes. Polymer-based nanoparticles can be prepared using various fabrication methods such as emulsion polymerization, nanoprecipitation, and self-assembly. By manipulating the polymer chemistry and nanoparticle size, their properties can be tuned to optimize their performance for specific applications. Overall, polymer-based nanoparticles hold great promise for advancing medical technologies and improving patient outcomes.','{\"pat_doc\": 6.0, \"pub_alt\": 57.0, \"pub_doc\": 88.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 0.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.6, \"pub_doc\": 4.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -69931.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f99e881d6304c002cfccbbaa4497ff9d','b3a328f05ef6249fe823d3c8f5701aaf','301cad2a0f77cdfc28e4f33b693d4618','2023-09-04 16:29:35','2023-10-29 07:16:15','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Magnetic Resonance Imaging',24,'Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) is a medical imaging technique that uses a strong magnetic field and radio waves to generate detailed images of the bodys internal structures. The process involves placing the patient in a machine that uses a powerful magnet to align the hydrogen atoms in their body. A short pulse of radio waves is then used to disrupt this alignment, causing the atoms to release energy that is detected by a scanner. The data collected is processed by a computer to produce detailed images of the target area. MRI is a non-invasive and highly precise diagnostic tool that can provide information about various conditions including tumors, infections, injuries, and abnormalities in organs and tissues. It is used in a wide range of medical applications, including neurology, cardiology, orthopedics, and oncology.','{\"pat_doc\": 5473.0, \"pub_alt\": 18424.0, \"pub_doc\": 53426.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1593.0, \"clinic_alt\": 632.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4261.0, \"grant_fund\": 869478349.0, \"pat_granted\": 2106.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -32.4, \"pub_doc\": 760.2, \"clinic_doc\": 884.6, \"grant_fund\": -78449677.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f9f54660ac2509cfcb121193cbc8077f','917192d39f4afc517e0a5df9df580afd','e5dc1ab9b95fd144580ba449bdb1f286','2023-09-05 20:46:53','2023-10-29 04:25:06','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Molecular Technologies','CRISPR-Cas9',24,'CRISPR is a family of DNA sequences found in the genomes of prokaryotic organisms such as bacteria and archaea. These sequences are derived from DNA fragments of bacteriophages that had previously infected the prokaryote. They are used to detect and destroy DNA from similar bacteriophages during subsequent infections. Hence these sequences play a key role in the antiviral defense system of prokaryotes and provide a form of acquired immunity. CRISPR is found in approximately 50% of sequenced bacterial genomes and nearly 90% of sequenced archaea. Cas9 is an enzyme that uses CRISPR sequences as a guide to recognize and cleave specific strands of DNA that are complementary to the CRISPR sequence. Cas9 enzymes together with CRISPR sequences form the basis of a technology known as CRISPR-Cas9 that can be used to edit genes within organisms.','{\"pat_doc\": 528.0, \"pub_alt\": 993.0, \"pub_doc\": 3792.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 460.0, \"clinic_alt\": 773.0, \"clinic_doc\": 20.0, \"grant_fund\": 192523840.0, \"pat_granted\": 151.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 22.6, \"pub_doc\": 115.9, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": -29971557.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('f9fb0849cde67613b1206db40386aa97','e1e4825f9e69d0bff75f7b5f1728fa6c','de90a1c4d8531674dd30ee9b71846822','2023-09-08 02:18:06','2023-10-28 22:36:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Bio-contaminant control','Aseptic Technique',36,'Aseptic techniques are procedures followed by individual working in a area which is highly controlled with respect to its level of microbial count. The level of microbial count is controlled to eliminate their contamination in product, while processing aseptically in the working place like laminar air flow bench, unidirectional flow bench mainly used in pharmaceutical manufacturing of sterile drug products, and microbial testing labs. Aseptic techniques include the sterilization method of microbiological culture handling wire loops, which are required to hold over flame on a gas burner, before use in order to sterilize it. The growing procedures are adapted inside a critical area while handling sterile products or microbial culture. The sequential movement of material in and out of the critical area, sequential man movement and their dexterity of handling of the sterile product and the intervention methods altogether are called aseptic techniques.','{\"pat_doc\": 216.0, \"pub_alt\": 98.0, \"pub_doc\": 356.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 4.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 82.0, \"grant_fund\": 1045435.0, \"pat_granted\": 184.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -10.9, \"pub_doc\": 8.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.6, \"grant_fund\": 112023.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fa09f12ad9c72c8abd05983d8ab220fc','92b44ff8d1d0e8c4689c1026159f41bb','dd42ec1636f7ea17b4c2869a3e543827','2023-09-08 02:08:52','2023-10-28 11:00:33','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Quantum Internet',48,'Quantum networks form an important element of quantum computing and quantum communication systems. Quantum networks facilitate the transmission of information in the form of quantum bits, also called qubits, between physically separated quantum processors. A quantum processor is a small quantum computer being able to perform quantum logic gates on a certain number of qubits. Quantum networks work in a similar way to classical networks. The main difference is that quantum networking, like quantum computing, is better at solving certain problems, such as modeling quantum systems.','{\"pat_doc\": 13.0, \"pub_alt\": 652.0, \"pub_doc\": 499.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 147.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 130836992.0, \"pat_granted\": 4.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.5, \"pub_doc\": 18.7, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": -4606738.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fa1bb3a690bb63e240145d5b2bda7970','5ca1037faccf16f0f31845755f697cb1','a9ac8b399c3d26dbcd46f8f3ee6f5ae2','2023-09-08 09:09:41','2023-10-28 13:21:11','Healthcare','Oncology & Immunocology','Other','Gynecologic Cancers',24,'Gynecologic oncology is a specialized field of medicine that focuses on cancers of the female reproductive system, including ovarian cancer, uterine cancer, vaginal cancer, cervical cancer, and vulvar cancer. As specialists, they have extensive training in the diagnosis and treatment of these cancers. In the United States, 82,000 women are diagnosed with gynecologic cancer annually. In 2013, an estimated 91,730 were diagnosed. There is low quality evidence which demonstrates women with gynaecological cancer receiving treatment from specialized centres benefit from longer survival than those managed in standard care. A meta analysis of three studies combining over 9000 women, suggested that specialist gynaecological cancer treatment centres may prolong the lives of women with ovarian cancer compared with general or community hospitals.','{\"pat_doc\": 5.0, \"pub_alt\": 146.0, \"pub_doc\": 509.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 19.0, \"clinic_alt\": 339.0, \"clinic_doc\": 58.0, \"grant_fund\": 7683915.0, \"pat_granted\": 1.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.0, \"pub_doc\": 5.4, \"clinic_doc\": 12.6, \"grant_fund\": -1132384.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fa663a0083c72d405cbbff5817e1d7d4','9bb760bba4bbf8524e3eb2a7e4d37392','5bad126b4b19ef48ed380a8bafb56304','2023-09-08 09:50:54','2023-10-28 20:16:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Capillary Electrophoresis',48,'Capillary electrophoresis is a family of electrokinetic separation methods performed in submillimeter diameter capillaries and in micro- and nanofluidic channels. Very often, CE refers to capillary zone electrophoresis, but other electrophoretic techniques including capillary gel electrophoresis, capillary isoelectric focusing, capillary isotachophoresis and micellar electrokinetic chromatography belong also to this class of methods. In CE methods, analytes migrate through electrolyte solutions under the influence of an electric field. Analytes can be separated according to ionic mobility and/or partitioning into an alternate phase via non-covalent interactions. Additionally, analytes may be concentrated or \"focused\" by means of gradients in conductivity and pH.','{\"pat_doc\": 1126.0, \"pub_alt\": 324.0, \"pub_doc\": 3623.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 148.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 18.0, \"grant_fund\": 39742289.0, \"pat_granted\": 400.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.4, \"pub_doc\": -61.5, \"clinic_doc\": 3.8, \"grant_fund\": -1132051.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fa6c0f5a8640d056b1057ed84a3043de','12dcedeb603ee2f3832d8525115bfc64','4893d9f6d48ce8d1001500525173bb9e','2023-09-07 23:56:32','2023-10-28 16:51:13','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Lipid Nanoparticles',48,'Lipid nanoparticles are nanoparticles composed of lipids. They are a novel pharmaceutical drug delivery system, and a novel pharmaceutical formulation. LNPs as a drug delivery vehicle were first approved in 2018 for the siRNA drug Onpattro. LNPs became more widely known in late 2020, as some COVID-19 vaccines that use RNA vaccine technology coat the fragile mRNA strands with PEGylated lipid nanoparticles as their delivery vehicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 1842.0, \"pub_alt\": 16312.0, \"pub_doc\": 3907.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 273.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1578.0, \"clinic_doc\": 17.0, \"grant_fund\": 107603694.0, \"pat_granted\": 219.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 197.2, \"pub_doc\": 208.7, \"clinic_doc\": 3.7, \"grant_fund\": 10362532.8, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fa90b8465ef5e4732142ffbcf942b1a6','1e66ed53f01f8188292c5c3609da476b','a58988e9b10205f335d6db1eeecb2311','2023-09-08 02:46:05','2023-10-28 21:36:11','Life Science','Next Generation Biology','Protein Technologies','Protein Expression System',36,'A Protein Expression System is a method used to produce proteins for scientific research, pharmaceutical development, and other applications. The system involves introducing DNA fragments encoding the desired protein sequence into a host cell, which then uses its own cellular machinery to produce the protein. Common hosts for protein expression include bacteria, yeast, and mammalian cells, with each system offering its own advantages and limitations. This method allows for the production of large quantities of a specific protein, aiding in the study of its function and potential therapeutic properties.','{\"pat_doc\": 169.0, \"pub_alt\": 300.0, \"pub_doc\": 165.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 47.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 2.0, \"grant_fund\": 18138840.0, \"pat_granted\": 44.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.7, \"pub_doc\": 3.2, \"clinic_doc\": -0.2, \"grant_fund\": -14107859.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('faa596f3589260a9f620eb24b4f1b1a1','090feb32dfbba21cb999b8efda702d3f','2774276ce5bfae5027508a164fb2fcb7','2023-09-08 02:36:18','2023-10-28 22:01:16','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Gene delivery vector',36,'A gene delivery vector is a vehicle used to transfer genetic material into cells. These vectors are commonly used in gene therapy and biotechnology applications to alter the expression of genes in cells. The most commonly used gene delivery vectors are viruses, which can infect cells and insert genetic material into the host cells genome. Retroviruses, adenoviruses, and adeno-associated viruses are some examples of viral vectors. Non-viral vectors, such as liposomes and naked DNA, can also be used to deliver genes, but are generally less efficient than viral vectors. Gene delivery vectors have immense potential in the treatment of genetic disorders, cancer, and other diseases.','{\"pat_doc\": 81.0, \"pub_alt\": 363.0, \"pub_doc\": 205.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 15.0, \"clinic_alt\": 12.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 8502048.0, \"pat_granted\": 18.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 5.7, \"pub_doc\": -4.6, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": -650737.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('faf774a73c59868fb242aa0c42db4b2c','8b34441cb6296c1404d0a6501ee553ff','eecaf00b18ce2e327917c5c42d883f43','2023-09-05 18:42:49','2023-10-29 05:41:10','Life Science','Lab & Future of the Factory','Sensors, Detection & Analysis','Raman Spectroscopy',36,'Raman spectroscopy is a spectroscopic technique typically used to determine vibrational modes of molecules, although rotational and other low-frequency modes of systems may also be observed. Raman spectroscopy is commonly used in chemistry to provide a structural fingerprint by which molecules can be identified. Raman spectroscopy relies upon inelastic scattering of photons, known as Raman scattering. A source of monochromatic light, usually from a laser in the visible, near infrared, or near ultraviolet range is used, although X-rays can also be used. The laser light interacts with molecular vibrations, phonons or other excitations in the system, resulting in the energy of the laser photons being shifted up or down. The shift in energy gives information about the vibrational modes in the system. Infrared spectroscopy typically yields similar yet complementary information. Typically, a sample is illuminated with a laser beam.','{\"pat_doc\": 1994.0, \"pub_alt\": 1807.0, \"pub_doc\": 28494.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 884.0, \"clinic_alt\": 3.0, \"clinic_doc\": 74.0, \"grant_fund\": 218761989.0, \"pat_granted\": 574.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -8.3, \"pub_doc\": 257.9, \"clinic_doc\": 14.3, \"grant_fund\": -11262983.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fb1c4b96535a5dbf5bcdd1cc090667aa','c9c8d2e4c7e139d539bc510be3e5f7ac','e9be6c0a64d57a69a37703624e73b1fd','2023-09-08 01:22:43','2023-10-29 00:16:22','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Cell Therapy','Cell Isolation',36,'Cell isolation is the process of separating individual living cells from a solid block of tissue or cell suspension. While some types of cell naturally exist in a separated form, other cell types that are found in solid tissue require specific techniques to separate them into individual cells. This may be performed by using enzymes to digest the proteins that binds these cells together within the extracellular matrix. After the matrix proteins have been digested, cells remain loosely bound together but can be gently separated mechanically. Following isolation, experiments can be performed on these single isolated cells including patch clamp electrophysiology, calcium fluorescence imaging, and immunocytochemistry.','{\"pat_doc\": 221.0, \"pub_alt\": 217.0, \"pub_doc\": 780.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 103.0, \"clinic_alt\": 5.0, \"clinic_doc\": 32.0, \"grant_fund\": 41813152.0, \"pat_granted\": 64.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -2.2, \"pub_doc\": 0.4, \"clinic_doc\": 4.9, \"grant_fund\": -1507208.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fb79f854e52b72692688e5e3741637e4','40a0355ede62ff4272058fe5b25b12bf','eefb2660a8535eb1d304c9a60295324f','2023-09-05 21:19:43','2023-10-28 17:46:11','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Liposomes',48,'A liposome is a small artificial vesicle, spherical in shape, having at least one lipid bilayer. Due to their hydrophobicity and/or hydrophilicity, biocompatibility, particle size and many other properties, liposomes can be used as drug delivery vehicles for administration of pharmaceutical drugs and nutrients, such as lipid nanoparticles in mRNA vaccines, and DNA vaccines. Liposomes can be prepared by disrupting biological membranes. Liposomes are most often composed of phospholipids, especially phosphatidylcholine, and cholesterol, but may also include other lipids, such as those found in egg and phosphatidylethanolamine, as long as they are compatible with lipid bilayer structure. A liposome design may employ surface ligands for attaching to unhealthy tissue. The major types of liposomes are the multilamellar vesicle, the small unilamellar liposome vesicle, the large unilamellar vesicle, and the cochleate vesicle.','{\"pat_doc\": 3101.0, \"pub_alt\": 590.0, \"pub_doc\": 11942.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 611.0, \"clinic_alt\": 108.0, \"clinic_doc\": 67.0, \"grant_fund\": 172975550.0, \"pat_granted\": 795.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 11.3, \"pub_doc\": 166.2, \"clinic_doc\": 8.1, \"grant_fund\": -13776868.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fc78bbfd247ddd19dbd327abc924b242','9bb760bba4bbf8524e3eb2a7e4d37392','5bad126b4b19ef48ed380a8bafb56304','2023-09-08 09:50:54','2023-10-28 20:16:13','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Capillary Electrophoresis',24,'Capillary electrophoresis is a family of electrokinetic separation methods performed in submillimeter diameter capillaries and in micro- and nanofluidic channels. Very often, CE refers to capillary zone electrophoresis, but other electrophoretic techniques including capillary gel electrophoresis, capillary isoelectric focusing, capillary isotachophoresis and micellar electrokinetic chromatography belong also to this class of methods. In CE methods, analytes migrate through electrolyte solutions under the influence of an electric field. Analytes can be separated according to ionic mobility and/or partitioning into an alternate phase via non-covalent interactions. Additionally, analytes may be concentrated or \"focused\" by means of gradients in conductivity and pH.','{\"pat_doc\": 582.0, \"pub_alt\": 324.0, \"pub_doc\": 1693.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 46.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 16.0, \"grant_fund\": 17203836.0, \"pat_granted\": 226.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.4, \"pub_doc\": -61.5, \"clinic_doc\": 3.8, \"grant_fund\": -1132051.5, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fcc3597207385936fcdfb4e1dd137169','dfe596d300e59da2f75df75fd3120d54','a73d74823ba2a6c69ad94ff6d93ed919','2023-09-08 01:42:12','2023-10-28 15:06:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Thyroids & Endocrinology','Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia',12,'Congenital adrenal hyperplasia is a group of autosomal recessive disorders characterized by impaired cortisol synthesis. It results from the deficiency of one of the five enzymes required for the synthesis of cortisol in the adrenal cortex. Most of these disorders involve excessive or deficient production of hormones such as glucocorticoids, mineralocorticoids, or sex steroids, and can alter development of primary or secondary sex characteristics in some affected infants, children, or adults. It is one of the most common autosomal recessive disorders in humans.','{\"pat_doc\": 48.0, \"pub_alt\": 74.0, \"pub_doc\": 406.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 2.0, \"clinic_alt\": 700.0, \"clinic_doc\": 33.0, \"grant_fund\": 1001994.0, \"pat_granted\": 3.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 6.4, \"pub_doc\": 1.7, \"clinic_doc\": 5.2, \"grant_fund\": -549349.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fd0e56ed9f8a2ede17f6d78bbfc3113c','926bd332c30fbfe2631a0f1af6fd3501','a8f010b8551aa704497c66b481f56011','2023-09-08 02:21:24','2023-10-28 14:36:11','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Cell therapies','Autologous chondrocytes',48,'Autologous chondrocytes refer to a type of cellular therapy that involves using the patients own cartilage cells to repair damaged or degenerated cartilage tissue. This procedure is typically used in cases of chondral defects or osteoarthritis. The process involves extracting a sample of the patients cartilage cells and growing them in a laboratory setting. The cells are then re-implanted into the patients damaged joint, where they can help to regenerate new cartilage tissue. Autologous chondrocyte therapy is considered a promising approach for the treatment of cartilage defects, as it enables the use of the patients own cells and can lead to improved outcomes compared to other treatment options.','{\"pat_doc\": 4.0, \"pub_alt\": 408.0, \"pub_doc\": 80.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 6.0, \"clinic_alt\": 1.0, \"clinic_doc\": 7.0, \"grant_fund\": 2370963.0, \"pat_granted\": 2.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -0.4, \"pub_doc\": -2.4, \"clinic_doc\": 1.7, \"grant_fund\": 108408.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fd4e1d99a5f2c57c04c4a539f2d41c77','9ae996f0d6bbaff7b400a3648677eeaf','f79d0c4233733c41a41b0769be4ec44f','2023-09-08 01:43:30','2023-10-28 11:25:31','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Heterogeneous Integration',12,'Heterogeneous Integration refers to the process of combining different types of materials, devices, components, or functions into a single system or package. It involves the use of various technologies to create complex systems that can perform multiple functions using different components integrated together. This process enables the creation of new products, systems, and services with improved features, performance, and flexibility. The main benefits of heterogeneous integration include reduced cost, improved system performance, and increased connectivity and functionality. This approach is widely used in the development of advanced microprocessors, wireless communication devices, sensors and actuators, and other high-tech products. By integrating various components with different functionalities, manufacturers can achieve compact, high-performance systems that meet the demands of modern applications.','{\"pat_doc\": 118.0, \"pub_alt\": 112.0, \"pub_doc\": 361.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 65.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 70079254.0, \"pat_granted\": 34.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 24.9, \"pub_doc\": 44.8, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 9542163.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fda7fe203dee83b1bf67ccb3750238d5','b2deca51e58703d27137669b972e2778','782fafb2d5b336b1996d7a1bfb56f465','2023-09-08 09:53:17','2023-10-28 20:06:11','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Mass spectrometry imaging',48,'Mass spectrometry imaging is a technique used in mass spectrometry to visualize the spatial distribution of molecules, as biomarkers, metabolites, peptides or proteins by their molecular masses. After collecting a mass spectrum at one spot, the sample is moved to reach another region, and so on, until the entire sample is scanned. By choosing a peak in the resulting spectra that corresponds to the compound of interest, the MS data is used to map its distribution across the sample. This results in pictures of the spatially resolved distribution of a compound pixel by pixel. Each data set contains a veritable gallery of pictures because any peak in each spectrum can be spatially mapped. Despite the fact that MSI has been generally considered a qualitative method, the signal generated by this technique is proportional to the relative abundance of the analyte. Therefore, quantification is possible, when its challenges are overcome.','{\"pat_doc\": 166.0, \"pub_alt\": 481.0, \"pub_doc\": 1905.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 155.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 4.0, \"grant_fund\": 70904389.0, \"pat_granted\": 52.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 0.2, \"pub_doc\": 30.5, \"clinic_doc\": -0.0, \"grant_fund\": -2225201.9, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fdb6cbfaa3803034a8451e6b62ca5e70','2531f8a177fbfd014f79f1851c094d65','6dae4310435505307085d7f2c73a1787','2023-09-08 00:48:13','2023-10-28 11:40:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Bioelectronics',12,'Bioelectronics is a field of research in the convergence of biology and electronics.','{\"pat_doc\": 23.0, \"pub_alt\": 1022.0, \"pub_doc\": 548.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 50.0, \"clinic_alt\": 8.0, \"clinic_doc\": 1.0, \"grant_fund\": 44975529.0, \"pat_granted\": 0.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 3.0, \"pub_doc\": 59.4, \"clinic_doc\": 0.3, \"grant_fund\": 7394410.3, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fdb8d52bf9a89ad3092a2f096de60ce9','4efee97660391cd588fa5f748e6f0600','eaf48f12d2f6d964781bc23663490cdb','2023-09-08 10:49:43','2023-10-28 19:01:11','Life Science','AI & Digital','AI/ML','Image Analysis',36,'Image analysis or imagery analysis is the extraction of meaningful information from images; mainly from digital images by means of digital image processing techniques. Image analysis tasks can be as simple as reading bar coded tags or as sophisticated as identifying a person from their face. Computers are indispensable for the analysis of large amounts of data, for tasks that require complex computation, or for the extraction of quantitative information. On the other hand, the human visual cortex is an excellent image analysis apparatus, especially for extracting higher-level information, and for many applications â€” including medicine, security, and remote sensing â€” human analysts still cannot be replaced by computers. For this reason, many important image analysis tools such as edge detectors and neural networks are inspired by human visual perception models.','{\"pat_doc\": 11752.0, \"pub_alt\": 1138.0, \"pub_doc\": 21027.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1513.0, \"clinic_alt\": 18.0, \"clinic_doc\": 322.0, \"grant_fund\": 570076459.0, \"pat_granted\": 3766.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 297.4, \"pub_doc\": 418.9, \"clinic_doc\": 55.6, \"grant_fund\": -41339384.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fe53bdc974c2003b969ab74f76b1af2f','511fe46a46ed4b151dc1fca695ee35f6','3351a35ba591fc4123a3314384741e66','2023-09-08 01:54:20','2023-10-28 23:41:13','Life Science','Novel Modalities','Non-Viral Gene Delivery','Cationic polymers',36,'In chemistry, cationic polymerization is a type of chain growth polymerization in which a cationic initiator transfers charge to a monomer which then becomes reactive. This reactive monomer goes on to react similarly with other monomers to form a polymer. The types of monomers necessary for cationic polymerization are limited to alkenes with electron-donating substituents and heterocycles. Similar to anionic polymerization reactions, cationic polymerization reactions are very sensitive to the type of solvent used. Specifically, the ability of a solvent to form free ions will dictate the reactivity of the propagating cationic chain. Cationic polymerization is used in the production of polyisobutylene and poly.','{\"pat_doc\": 584.0, \"pub_alt\": 68.0, \"pub_doc\": 351.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 26.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 6491741.0, \"pat_granted\": 192.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -10.9, \"pub_doc\": -2.9, \"clinic_doc\": 0.0, \"grant_fund\": 44316.1, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fe901b335a46baa3bbf45c508f3ca55e','d3549b81bb39a9ac922f45ac120eb0cc','3da09264ab4cd2d03a36df24f5f30506','2023-09-08 09:48:28','2023-10-28 20:26:10','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','Separations','Inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry',36,'Inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry is a type of mass spectrometry that uses an inductively coupled plasma to ionize the sample. It atomizes the sample and creates atomic and small polyatomic ions, which are then detected. It is known and used for its ability to detect metals and several non-metals in liquid samples at very low concentrations. It can detect different isotopes of the same element, which makes it a versatile tool in isotopic labeling. Compared to atomic absorption spectroscopy, ICP-MS has greater speed, precision, and sensitivity. However, compared with other types of mass spectrometry, such as thermal ionization mass spectrometry and glow discharge mass spectrometry, ICP-MS introduces many interfering species: argon from the plasma, component gases of air that leak through the cone orifices, and contamination from glassware and the cones.','{\"pat_doc\": 306.0, \"pub_alt\": 1281.0, \"pub_doc\": 4289.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 96.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 12.0, \"grant_fund\": 24610436.0, \"pat_granted\": 72.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 10.7, \"pub_doc\": 21.2, \"clinic_doc\": 1.6, \"grant_fund\": -270284.2, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ff4229a6c4fb631008f194f770dc9210','aedf0c478e49c48a393feff1fdcfaa4b','5b55c48790bb4cf3b5dc24f790e7d5a2','2023-09-05 21:32:03','2023-10-28 12:25:32','Electronics','Disruptions','Technology Disruptions','Metaverse',12,'The Metaverse is a virtual reality space that contains multiple interconnected virtual worlds and augmented reality environments. It is a digital universe that enables users to create, experience, and interact with each other in various virtual environments. In the Metaverse, users can have a digital representation of themselves, or an avatar, who can move from one world to another. The concept of Metaverse is increasingly becoming popular as advancements in technology allow for more immersive and seamless experiences. It is used in various areas, including gaming, education, socialization, commerce, and even politics, to name a few. The Metaverse holds immense potential for revolutionizing how we interact with technology and each other.','{\"pat_doc\": 833.0, \"pub_alt\": 341.0, \"pub_doc\": 4117.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 66.0, \"clinic_alt\": 0.0, \"clinic_doc\": 5.0, \"grant_fund\": 64906508.0, \"pat_granted\": 187.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 259.5, \"pub_doc\": 1393.6, \"clinic_doc\": 1.3, \"grant_fund\": 20484735.7, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ff5731bc18d53175846f9f4e524801eb','33e3b46112ca032f374d6e6e96ae9ab3','96ff1b7975967b788c2beb91534beb0f','2023-09-05 20:50:48','2023-10-28 17:56:12','Healthcare','Future therapeutic modalities','Delivery methods','Exosomes',48,'Exosomes are small membrane vesicles, typically with a diameter of 30-150 nm, that are secreted by many types of mammalian cells and are found in a variety of body fluids such as blood, urine, and breast milk. They are thought to play a role in intercellular communication and in some cases can transfer proteins, lipids, and genetic material between cells. Exosomes originate from the endosomal compartment of the cell and are formed by the inward budding of the membrane to create intraluminal vesicles. Once formed, the exosomes are released from the cell through fusion with the plasma membrane or phagocytosis by other cells. The content of exosomes can vary depending on the cell type and physiological conditions, and there is growing interest in their use as biomarkers for disease diagnosis and as potential therapeutic agents.','{\"pat_doc\": 5782.0, \"pub_alt\": 18945.0, \"pub_doc\": 17402.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 1778.0, \"clinic_alt\": 219.0, \"clinic_doc\": 366.0, \"grant_fund\": 443182354.0, \"pat_granted\": 1303.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 265.2, \"pub_doc\": 279.4, \"clinic_doc\": 55.8, \"grant_fund\": -46753820.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('ffe7450c6285fc9f8d3d71f27529f3c9','51aee0cb27f70c84f894c07b0faada65','05f0a405c035c7fc807679b69158e068','2023-09-07 23:36:05','2023-10-28 17:11:13','Healthcare','Cardio-metabolic diseases','Cardiovascular','Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy',36,'Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is a condition in which muscle tissues of the heart become thickened without an obvious cause. The parts of the heart most commonly affected are the interventricular septum and the ventricles. This results in the heart being less able to pump blood effectively and also may cause electrical conduction problems. People who have HCM may have a range of symptoms. People may be asymptomatic, or may have fatigue, leg swelling, and shortness of breath. It may also result in chest pain or fainting. Symptoms may be worse when the person is dehydrated. Complications may include heart failure, an irregular heartbeat, and sudden cardiac death. HCM is most commonly inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern. It is often due to mutations in certain genes involved with making heart muscle proteins. Other inherited causes of left ventricular hypertrophy may include Fabry disease, Friedreichs ataxia, and certain medications such as tacrolimus.','{\"pat_doc\": 236.0, \"pub_alt\": 668.0, \"pub_doc\": 4767.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 141.0, \"clinic_alt\": 83.0, \"clinic_doc\": 158.0, \"grant_fund\": 48303250.0, \"pat_granted\": 47.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": 14.4, \"pub_doc\": 133.8, \"clinic_doc\": 28.7, \"grant_fund\": -3954781.4, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}'),('fff95b478e51840f08935ae864b782d2','8837382ad71ea14d648e72dffa07f350','a10d686867f23b1f3c14742bdf7326cc','2023-09-05 19:11:33','2023-10-29 05:16:14','Life Science','Sustainability/Core','New Materials','Biomaterial',48,'A biomaterial is a substance that has been engineered to interact with biological systems for a medical purpose, either a therapeutic or a diagnostic one. The corresponding field of study, called biomaterials science or biomaterials engineering, is about fifty years old. It has experienced steady and strong growth over its history, with many companies investing large amounts of money into the development of new products. Biomaterials science encompasses elements of medicine, biology, chemistry, tissue engineering and materials science. Note that a biomaterial is different from a biological material, such as bone, that is produced by a biological system. Additionally, care should be exercised in defining a biomaterial as biocompatible, since it is application-specific. A biomaterial that is biocompatible or suitable for one application may not be biocompatible in another.','{\"pat_doc\": 4636.0, \"pub_alt\": 1940.0, \"pub_doc\": 32157.0, \"deals_num\": 0.0, \"grant_doc\": 3423.0, \"clinic_alt\": 260.0, \"clinic_doc\": 335.0, \"grant_fund\": 1585238532.0, \"pat_granted\": 1378.0, \"companies_num\": 0.0, \"investors_num\": 0.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}','{\"pat_doc\": -44.8, \"pub_doc\": 588.5, \"clinic_doc\": 50.9, \"grant_fund\": -91915477.0, \"capital_raised\": 0.0}');
